<!-- body="start" -->
Headlines of stories which follow:<br>
1.  Press Conference with Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov and Tansu Ciller,<br>
Turkish Prime Minister and Foreign Minister - December 18, 1996<br>
2.  President Nazarbayev unveils independence monument <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Press Conference with Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov and Tansu<br>
Ciller, Turkish Prime Minister and Foreign Minister - December 18, 1996<br>
SOURCE:  Official Kremlin Int'l News Broadcast, December 18, 1996 <br>
<p>
Moderator: A memorandum is being signed between the government the Russian<br>
Federation and the government of the Turkish Republic on cooperation in<br>
combating terrorism. The memorandum is being signed by the Foreign Affairs<br>
Minister of the Russian Federation Yevgeny Maximovich Primakov and<br>
Vice-Premier and Foreign Minister of the Turkish Republic Tansu Ciller. <br>
<p>
Tarasov: Good afternoon, ladies and gentlemen. The negotiations have ended<br>
between the Russian Foreign vc Minister Yevgeny Primakov and the Vice-Premier<br>
and the Foreign Minister of the Turkish Republic Mrs. Tansu Ciller. Mr.<br>
Ciller is in Moscow on an official visit. At the start of the press<br>
conference with your permission I will give her the floor. <br>
<p>
Ciller: The Turkish delegation are deeply moved by the affection and the warm<br>
atmosphere we have encountered in the friendly country of Russia. We felt all<br>
this during the talks with Mr. Primakov and in the talks earlier with mayor<br>
of Moscow and with the Chairman of the Government, Chernomyrdin. And I think<br>
the relationship between the peoples of our countries is the same, and for<br>
this we are grateful to the Russian Federation. I also believe that I am<br>
entitled to conveying to you similar feelings from the Turkish people. <br>
<p>
The relations between our two countries located in a large region which is<br>
living through radical change are based on cooperation and partnership and I<br>
am convinced that after our Moscow contacts, after this visit, we will open a<br>
new door in our relations and pass to a new level in our cooperation. We note<br>
with much satisfaction the extent to which our points of view come close on<br>
regional affairs. This is an excellent earnest for our future cooperation.<br>
Also, both sides confirmed at the talks their adherence to the principles of<br>
territorial integrity and declared for preserving the territorial integrity<br>
both of Russia and Turkey. Along with this we also signed a memorandum, as it<br>
was already announced, on cooperation between the governments of the two<br>
countries in the area of combating terrorism. <br>
<p>
We also are satisfied that the settlement of the Chechen problem in the<br>
Russian Federation is based on precisely these principles and is being<br>
implemented precisely within this framework. <br>
<p>
Also, we achieved unity of views in the question of the need to preserve the<br>
territorial integrity of absolutely all countries of the region and also the<br>
settlement of regional conflicts precisely on the basis of this principle,<br>
and this includes the preservation of the integrity of Azerbaijan. Now we can<br>
step up the dialogue between the two countries on the broadest range of<br>
issues, we will be able to extend the areas of cooperation and at the level<br>
of the two ministries we will be able to discuss specific issues and start<br>
resolving the outstanding problems between us immediately. The similarity of<br>
opinions between the two parties on regional problems and on conflict<br>
situations in our sensitive region provide an excellent foundation for<br>
partnership which we are seeking in our relations together. Such a foundation<br>
for our relations and our cooperation is also provided by the atmosphere of<br>
confidence that prevailed during our negotiations today. Both parties noted<br>
in the course of the negotiations that the two countries have enormous<br>
potential for trade and economic cooperation and a large trade. Turkey is the<br>
second largest trade and economic partner for Russia and similarly, Russia is<br>
Turkey's second trading partner after Germany. The advanced character of our<br>
cooperation will lead to partnership in our relations if we continue to work<br>
in the same way. <br>
<p>
Today we worked well in the course of our contacts on specific projects. We<br>
touched upon the question of encouraging the activities of small and medium<br>
businesses and of course, we discussed major projects in the field of energy<br>
and other sectors. And in the course of these contacts we have identified<br>
many areas for joint effort. But, of course, it will take great effort and<br>
much labor to further realize these projects. <br>
Within this framework we also discussed issues that were formerly touched<br>
upon by the Chernomyrdin government -- issues pertaining to cooperation in<br>
the energy and industry sectors. In this context, we decided to urgently<br>
convene working groups and step up their activity in respective fields, in<br>
particular, as early as tomorrow our energy group will hold a meeting -- I<br>
have taken a decision to this effect. <br>
<p>
We proceed from the need for cooperation and partnership with Russia on such<br>
issues as stepping up gas supplies from Russia to Turkey, oil supplies from<br>
the Caspian basin. At any rate, we will continue to work and the first<br>
concrete step will be made tomorrow.  Of course, the friendly and sincere<br>
dialogue between our countries will be continued on all issues, including the<br>
most sensitive ones for our country. <br>
<p>
I would like to take advantage of this opportunity to thank on behalf of all<br>
the members of our delegation Moscow's mayor Luzhkov and Chairman of the<br>
Government Chernomyrdin, and my dear colleague Primakov for the cordial<br>
reception we met here and for the warm attitude we all felt here, and also I<br>
would like you to express my best regards to the Russian people. <br>
<p>
Primakov: Thank you very much. The visit by Madam Ciller to Russia is not yet<br>
over, but it can already be said that it has produced many results, that it<br>
has been a very useful visit. It may become a very important visit in terms<br>
of the development of relations between our two countries. <br>
<p>
Combining here are both objective and subjective moments. The objective<br>
moments are that we are two closely located countries, two bordering<br>
countries that should live in peace, that should cooperate in the<br>
strengthening of regional stability, in the development of bilateral ties in<br>
the political and economic spheres. The subjective moment, I will not conceal<br>
that, is that it is very pleasant, greatly pleasant to do business with such<br>
a partner who clearly sets questions, who clearly provides answers to them,<br>
who conducts many conversations in a very trusting manner. <br>
<p>
We have arrived at the conclusion that a substantial economic foundation has<br>
been created for our relations. Madam Ciller is very correctly raising the<br>
question of the need to expand and strengthen this foundation. But now we are<br>
also saying that it is necessary to build a political superstructure, and by<br>
saying this I mean political consultations on a whole number of questions<br>
where our positions either coincide or are close. Today we, so to say, took<br>
stock of these problems. In the regional aspect this includes, of course, the<br>
liquidation of existing conflicts. We arrived at the conclusion that our<br>
positions are very close in respect of the liquidation, settlement of the<br>
Nagorny Karabakh conflict. The way out is in the self-determination of<br>
Nagorny Karabakh in conditions of recognition of the territorial integrity of<br>
Azerbaijan. We have agreed to act in parallel in this area but the goal is<br>
one -- settlement. Our views coincide in many ways on the situation in and<br>
around Iraq. We come out for the territorial integrity of Iraq with<br>
autonomous rights for the population in the north. Russia supports the desire<br>
of Turkey to resolve the issues in the relations with Syria. <br>
<p>
Finally, we discussed our bilateral relations at length. Perhaps, I should<br>
have started with this. Among the specific issues were the document on<br>
cooperation in combating terrorism which has already been mentioned by my<br>
colleague. An agreement in principle was reached on opening Russian General<br>
Consulate in Ismir and a Turkish Consulate in Novorosiisk. We will continue<br>
negotiations on dispensing with visas for those who travel under diplomatic<br>
and service passports and on abandoning quotas for the number of personnel in<br>
the diplomatic and consular offices. <br>
<p>
We have exchanged opinions on the situation in Europe, on the architecture of<br>
European security. Despite the continued existence of a certain difference in<br>
approaches here, despite the continuation of the differences that are seen in<br>
our positions, we are unanimous in that it is necessary to leave Europe<br>
without lines of division. <br>
<p>
The talks with Madam Ciller were very useful and pleasant ones. Like Turkey,<br>
and Madam Ciller has just said this, we will work to raise our relations to<br>
the level of a partnership relationship. Thank you. <br>
<p>
Moderator: Thank you, we will have questions now. As always, please introduce<br>
yourself and use the microphone that is in the center of the hall. <br>
<p>
Q: ORT. When you told us about your negotiations, you kept saying "despite<br>
certain differences, despite some differences in views". Can you, please,<br>
specify what these differences are? <br>
<p>
Primakov: Excuse me, but you must have not listened attentively enough. We<br>
emphasized more the identity or closeness of approaches to various questions.<br>
<p>
<p>
If we are to speak about different approaches, I mentioned only questions<br>
connected with the expansion of NATO. But I would also like to stress that<br>
both Russia and Turkey agree that no actions should disrupt the unity of<br>
Europe and bring about the appearance of some new divisive lines. <br>
<p>
I am sorry, but I cannot give anything of a sensational nature to ORT<br>
television. (Laughter.) <br>
<p>
Q: Could you provide any stuff for a sensation to Radio 1 on the role of<br>
personality in history and on how well you felt speaking with Mrs. Ciller? <br>
<p>
Primakov: In this respect I stick to Plekhanov's view, who believed that a<br>
personality can play a tremendous role in history. These today's negotiations<br>
came as another confirmation of this idea. <br>
<p>
Q: Interfax. I have a question both to Mrs. Ciller and Minister Primakov. My<br>
question to Mrs. Ciller is as follows: could NATO expansion proceed without<br>
Turkey's consent, in light of the close Turkey-Russia relationship? And a<br>
question to Yevgeny Maximovich: taking into account this very special<br>
relationship, could Turkey play the role of a go-between or a liaison officer<br>
in the forthcoming negotiations between Russia and NATO about drafting an<br>
agreement on special relationship? <br>
<p>
Ciller: We are certain that NATO expansion should proceed very carefully. And<br>
we flatly oppose the emergence of any new dividing lines in Europe. We oppose<br>
the emergence of any new dividing lines in Europe, and naturally, we are<br>
naturally aware of this and we know how sensitive Russia is to the plans of<br>
NATO enlargement. In the course of the negotiations the Russian Federation<br>
brought this concern to us in great detail. We are aware of all the details<br>
of Russian position and we have the respect for this position. Based on this<br>
information, we will continue dialogue with the Russian Federation which we<br>
hope will assume the form of cooperation in this field as well. In any case,<br>
we will never allow NATO to pose a threat to the Russian Federation. I am<br>
stating this clearly and with all responsibility. Processes of transformation<br>
cannot take place without the consent of Russia and without taking into<br>
account its interests. <br>
<p>
Primakov: Thank you. I will answer my part of the question. We have good<br>
experience of interacting with Turkey in addressing a number of specific<br>
issues, but issues that are very important. For example, we held very<br>
fruitful negotiations on flank limitations under the Conventional Forces in<br>
Europe Treaty. <br>
<p>
We will continue cooperation in this area in the future. As for consultations<br>
with NATO, we have been offered to conduct them with the Secretary General<br>
and with the persons who represent NATO as an organization. And while<br>
preserving our negative stand on the expansion of NATO, we have accepted the<br>
offer. <br>
<p>
Q: With the signing of the agreement on cooperation on combating terrorism,<br>
can it be said that from now on, the Workers' Party of Kurdistan will no<br>
longer be able to act on the territory of the Russian Federation? It's a<br>
question for Mr. Primakov. <br>
<p>
Primakov: Although I am not responsible for the activities of Workers' Party<br>
of Kurdistan, I will answer that question. We are against terrorist activity<br>
and we repeatedly stated this. There can be no support for terrorist<br>
activities on the part of democratic Russia. And you can rest assured that<br>
our territory cannot be made available as a base for any forms of terrorist<br>
activities. <br>
<p>
Q: NTV. Alexander Israyelyan. To further the theme raised by the Turkish<br>
colleague, fighting terrorism was discussed here, but both Turkey and Russia<br>
have two hot spots they try to bring tranquility to, I mean -- (inaudible) --<br>
Chechnya. On the other hand, there is the problem of the Kurds in Turkey. --<br>
(Inaudible) -- Mrs. Ciller, could you tell us: have you met with support from<br>
the Russian leadership for your activities against the Kurds in Turkey? <br>
<p>
Primakov: This question was asked in continuation of the Turkish journalist's<br>
question. <br>
<p>
Ciller: This is a case of journalists' solidarity. -- (Laughter) -- I have<br>
already stated that as regards Russia's territorial integrity, during our<br>
talks we have repeatedly stated our commitment to this principle. While<br>
discussing Chechnya-related matters, we stated that we stand for settling<br>
this problem within the framework of Russia's territorial integrity and that<br>
we consider this to be Russia's internal matter. Mr. Primakov has also<br>
expressed similar views on the activities of the Workers' Party of Kurdistan<br>
and the events in northern Iraq. I think that this similarity of views will<br>
play an important role in strengthening the atmosphere of confidence between<br>
the two countries. <br>
<p>
Moderator: Two final questions. <br>
<p>
Q: Mr. Primakov, I would like to show solidarity for my fellow journalists<br>
and ask you whether you found satisfactory the explanations of the Turkish<br>
side on Chechnya and whether you are satisfied with the position of the<br>
Turkish Republic on Chechnya? Did it dispel the doubts and fears that the<br>
Russian side had on that score? And a small question. Russia as a member of<br>
the U.N. Security Council and an active participant in the Cyprus settlement,<br>
how does this square with the supply of offensive weapons to the southern<br>
part of the island? These reports have brought a mixed reaction of the<br>
Turkish public opinion? <br>
<p>
Primakov: On the first question, we are certainly very satisfied with the<br>
position formulated by Turkey on Chechnya.  Certainly, there are some<br>
organizations of a public nature on the territory of Turkey which take a<br>
different stand. But we are very pleased with the official position of Turkey<br>
on the Chechen issue. <br>
<p>
On your second question, I would say that I do not consider the air defense<br>
systems whose shipments are contemplated to be offensive weapons. <br>
<p>
Q: A question for Mr. Primakov. You have mentioned Karabakh settlement and<br>
the need for the self-determination of Karabakh, so that the citizens of<br>
Karabakh should themselves decide the fate of that area. Should the Azeris<br>
who had to leave Karabakh earlier be involved in the process of such<br>
self-determination, that is, those who are in fact refugees? And the second<br>
question. You mentioned the territorial integrity of Iraq. The need of<br>
preserving this integrity is recognized by all. You also mentioned the<br>
certain autonomy that should be granted in the north of Iraq to the peoples<br>
that live there. When you mentioned autonomy, did you refer only to Kurds or<br>
you meant also other peoples, including Turkmen? <br>
<p>
Primakov: I will answer your questions. A separate document was issued in<br>
Lisbon on behalf of the current chairman of the OSCE, a document on Nagorny<br>
Karabakh, on the conflict in the Nagorny Karabakh. This document contained<br>
three provisions that were agreed upon by the members of the Minsk Group. The<br>
first is the recognition of the territorial integrity of both Azerbaijan and<br>
Armenia. The second -- self-determination of the people of Nagorny Karabakh<br>
on the basis of an agreement and within the framework of Azerbaijan. The<br>
third moment -- security, security ensured for all sides in the conflict. I<br>
believe that this is the basis for the settlement. <br>
<p>
Concerning the second question. We are against a situation, in the event of<br>
the formation of an autonomy in the north of Iraq, in which rights would not<br>
be enjoyed by the other peoples living in the north of Iraq, not only Kurds,<br>
but also Arabs, Turkomans, Assyrians, etc. <br>
<p>
This means that it is necessary to find such a decision that would ensure<br>
observance of human rights, ensure observance of the right to<br>
self-determination, which does not necessarily has to express itself in the<br>
form of cessation. In this case, as it was stressed by Madam Ciller, we come<br>
out for the solution of all these questions within the framework of Iraq.<br>
Thank you. <br>
<p>
Moderator: Thank you, the press conference is over, good-bye. <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: President Nazarbayev unveils independence monument <br>
SOURCE: Kazakh Television first channel, Alma-Ata, in Kazakh 1330 gmt 16 Dec<br>
96 <br>
<p>
The fifth anniversary of Kazakhstan's independence was marked when President<br>
Nursultan Nazarbayev unveiled a monument to Kazakh independence in Alma-Ata's<br>
central Square of the Republic on 16th December, Kazakh TV reported. <br>
<p>
Speaking at the ceremony, Nazarbayev said the legacy of those who have fought<br>
for Kazakh independence since the days of the Kazakh khans must be realized<br>
in the form of a law-governed state. " Kazakhstan's people and the Kazakhs<br>
have been fighting for this independence for vc many years. Now we are<br>
building a new law-based state based on equality of rights. We must not turn<br>
away from this road," he said <br>
<p>
He also said that reforms need time to bear fruit: "None of the world' s<br>
states has managed to carry out such huge reforms as Kazakhstan has achieved<br>
over the past five years [since independence]. We need patience and<br>
solidarity." He attributed problems with paying wages and pensions on time to<br>
the Soviet legacy of bad debts between enterprises, and noted that they are<br>
common to all former Soviet states. <br>
<p>
Nazarbayev also praised the absence of interethnic or religious strife in the<br>
country: "Thank God we have no Karabakh, Tajikistan or Chechnya here. We must<br>
preserve these kindly relations in this way." <br>
<p>
Among the freedom fighters of the past he singled out the Kazakh khans'fight<br>
for Kazakh statehood in the 14th-15th centuries and their struggle against<br>
the Dzhungarian-Kalmyk Mongol invaders, and the Kazakh nationalist and<br>
peasant victims of the Stalinist purges and farm collectivization in the<br>
1930s. He also spoke about the damage wrought by the Soviet Union to the soil<br>
of Kazakhstan through nuclear tests and the destruction of the Aral Sea, but<br>
expressed confidence in the ability of the people of the Kazakhstan to<br>
overcome this. <br>
<p>
Nazarbayev thanked those responsible for the monument, which is a 28-metre<br>
high gold-coloured column crowned with a Kazakh legendary warrior figure atop<br>
a winged snow leopard. <br>
<p>
Nazarbayev and Turkish President Suleyman Demirel, who arrived in Kazakhstan<br>
on 15th December, laid wreaths at the foot of the monument, the television<br>
said. <br>
