<!-- inreplyto="" -->
<title>Groong Network: Caspian oil: routes, plans, Karabakh, Kurdistan</title>
<h1>Caspian oil: routes, plans, Karabakh, Kurdistan</h1>
Arthur Martirosyan (<i>martiros@hulaw1.harvard.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 19 Dec 1996 14:05:37 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#172">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#172">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#172">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#172">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0173.html">Asbed Bedrossian: "Common Declaration of Pope John Paul II and Catholicos Karekin I"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0171.html">arpi@aaainc.org: "ORANGE COUNTY REGISTER HIGHLIGHTS ARMENIA"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Kommersant=FF-DAILY     =20<br>
<p>
Thursday, December 19, 1996<br>
<p>
Press-conference of Terry Adams<br>
<p>
Caspian Oil Consortium: =93it is like running the UN=94<br>
<p>
By Georgii Dvali and Andrei Smirnov<br>
<p>
Recent intensive consultations among participants of the Caspian Oil<br>
Consortium indicate that a final decision on the main oil route is not far.<br>
At a briefing for a close group of journalists (your =FF correspondent was<br>
among them) during his recent visit to Tbilisi the chief of the operations<br>
committee of the consortium, Terry Adams presented a detailed commercial<br>
feasibility study of various proposed routes for oil transportation.  But<br>
the problems that the =93project of the century=94 is facing are not only<br>
commercial ones.=20<br>
<p>
=93project of the century=94 that was the name that President of Azerbaijan<br>
Heidar Aliyev gave to the plan to develop oil resources of the Caspian shelf<br>
two years ago. Then it sounded pretentious. But now, according to Adams, it<br>
is clear that the project is truly turning into one of the largest projects<br>
of the century. =93I have always a feeling that I am running at least a UN,=<br>
=94<br>
said the chief of the consortium. Two years ago everything was different.<br>
=93We were assigned to develop a relatively simple project and to conclude=<br>
 all<br>
necessary contracts in two and a half years.=94 The budget was planned to be<br>
$600 million. Now everything has changed. Initially, Adams claims,<br>
participants of the consortium did not plan to finance the construction of<br>
northern route (via Russia) and Western route (via Georgia) pipelines. Now<br>
investments exceed $2 billion. The program of financing until 1998 envisions<br>
spending of: $220 million for infrastructure $630 million for a terminal in<br>
Sangachal, $40 million for restoration of the northern pipeline, $300<br>
million for the terminal in Supsa (Adjaria, Georgia), $60 million for<br>
pipeline service,  $26 million for the construction of the second platform. =<br>
 =20<br>
<p>
This project will provide access to new oil deposit which, according to<br>
Adams, are of =93super-gigantic scale.=94  The confirmed deposits amount to=<br>
 17.5<br>
billion barrels. These deposits are equal to all deposits in the Northern<br>
Sea. Deposits that are not yet confirmed but are based on some solid<br>
geological surveys indicate that Caspian deposits are twice as large as<br>
those of the Northern Sea.=20<br>
<p>
Adams reminded us that the length of the northern route is 1,400 km and only<br>
167 km are on the territory of Azerbaijan. The rest of the pipeline will go<br>
via Russian territory, including Chechnya, to Novorossiisk. Adams=92s<br>
statement that despite the recent war in Chechnya and tensions in the region<br>
the Russian section of the pipeline has been fully restored is sensational.<br>
The pipeline was cleaned of water and dirt and its first section was tested.<br>
The Azeri side has claimed that the first supplies of oil can begin in the<br>
end of first quarter of 1997.  The capacity of that pipeline is 5 million<br>
tons of oil per year and it shall be sufficient for the oil extracted from<br>
the first platform.=20<br>
<p>
The length of the second route is 930 km (to Batumi where terminal Supsa is<br>
under construction). In two months spending for this pipeline will be<br>
confirmed. Restoration works will begin in the second quarter of 1997. A<br>
significant volume of restoration works needs to be carried out on the<br>
section on the territory of Azerbaijan and a new pipeline from Akstafa to<br>
Tbilisi shall be built from scratch. A tender was announced for companies<br>
willing to participate in the reconstruction and restoration of the pipeline<br>
Baku-Batumi. The deadline is January 6. So far 53 companies had announced<br>
intentions to participate and   over 40 were rejected in the screening.  The<br>
first oil shall be delivered via the Western pipeline in the end of 1998.=20<br>
<p>
Adams said that the answer to the question which route the main oil from the<br>
Caspian will go will be given in the middle of next year. The choice of the<br>
main route will be pre-determined by technical and commercial factors.  The<br>
same two routes are under consideration: first -- existing northern route<br>
from Baku to Novorossiisk; second Western via Georgia to Eastern Turkey and<br>
Mediterranean port of Ceyhan. There are other scenarios which entail oil<br>
delivery by tankers through the straits or by pipelines bypassing the<br>
straits via Bulgaria and Greece in case Turkey closes the straits.  =20<br>
<p>
Adams did not make a secret that the choice of the route will also be<br>
determined by political factors. In Georgia, for example, a big row was<br>
caused by a statement of President of self-proclaimed Nagorno-Karabakh<br>
Republic, Robert Kocharyan, that consortium=92s activities were damaging<br>
security interests of Nagorno Karabakh since the implementation of the<br>
=93project of century=94 may increase the economic and first of all military<br>
potential of Azerbaijan.  Some military experts do not rule out that<br>
military formations of Karabakh may attempt to cut the Western pipeline by<br>
advancing to Gyandzha, the second largest city of Azerbaijan. The unresolved<br>
Armenian-Azerbaijani conflict may restart again in serious.  Another<br>
indication for this are Heidar Aliyev=92s words at his press-conference=<br>
 after<br>
Lisbon OSCE Summit when he called authorities of Azerbaijan =93occupants.=94=<br>
   =20<br>
 This situation is complicated by contradictions among states represented by<br>
companies in the consortium. Relations between Moscow and Baku cannot be<br>
called partnership. Moscow suspects that Azerbaijan secretly supports<br>
Chechen separatists. Baku accuses Moscow in conspiracy for not extraditing<br>
persons charged with plotting against Azerbaijan. Baku would want to see<br>
Turkey, not Russia as partner, and condemns the presence of the Russian<br>
military in Transcaucasus.  =20<br>
<p>
The problem of straits has not been resolved yet. Turkey (in violation of<br>
international maritime agreements, Montre) is trying to impose limits for<br>
oil tankers. As a response Moscow quite unambiguously hints that the project<br>
Baku-Tbilisi-Supsa-Ceyhan will never take off as it will have to cross areas<br>
of Kurdistan where PKK fighters have been waging a guerrilla war against<br>
Turkish authorities  for 12 years.  Answering a question of your =FF<br>
correspondent on the attitude of the Kurdish leadership to this project, a<br>
representative of the Front of national Liberation of Kurdistan in the CIS<br>
countries and Eastern Europe, Makhir Valat, stated that for the pipeline to<br>
pass areas controlled by PKK one would need to exterminate PKK and that<br>
won=92t be easy to achieve since they have a 30,000 strong army.=20<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;From the other hand side the end of war in Chechnya is strengthening chances</i><br>
of the northern route, of course, if Chechen leaders do not rush to use that<br>
trump card for getting a de jure independence.=20<br>
<p>
This knot of contradictions can be resolved peacefully only as a result of<br>
consent among all major players in the region and first of all among Moscow,<br>
Washington, and Ankara.  That is hard to imagine as their interests are<br>
often quite contradictory.  This is one of the cases where confrontation<br>
will reveal the loser who will have to step aside.  (end)=20<br>
<p>
(Translated by AM, name transliterations from Russian)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
