<title>Groong Network: ORANGE COUNTY REGISTER HIGHLIGHTS ARMENIA</title>
<h1>ORANGE COUNTY REGISTER HIGHLIGHTS ARMENIA</h1>
<i>arpi@aaainc.org</i><br>
<i>Thu, 19 Dec 96 14:01:56 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#171">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#171">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#171">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#171">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0172.html">Arthur Martirosyan: "Caspian oil: routes, plans, Karabakh, Kurdistan"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0170.html">Arthur Martirosyan: "Izvestia: Who was interested in this?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
     <br>
     Armenian Assembly of America<br>
     122 C Street, NW  Suite 350<br>
     Washington, D.C.  20001<br>
     tel: (202) 393-3434<br>
     fax: (202) 638-4904<br>
     email: arpi@aaainc.org<br>
     Contact: Arpi Vartanian<br>
     <br>
     <br>
     INFORMATION NOTICE<br>
     <br>
     December 19, 1996<br>
     <br>
     ORANGE COUNTY REGISTER HIGHLIGHTS ARMENIA<br>
     <br>
     The Orange County Register, published in Orange County, California, <br>
     ran a cover story on Armenia in its travel section on November 17, <br>
     entitled Armenia -- A People of Hope, A Land of Challenge. The article <br>
     introduced descriptions of tourist attractions, encounters with <br>
     Armenians, and history and current events including the Genocide, the <br>
     earthquake, blockades, and Nagorno Karabagh.<br>
     <br>
     On December 8, the Register also ran a feature story in the Accent <br>
     Section, The Eyes of Armenia, about Dr. Roger Ohanesian and Dr. Rick <br>
     Hill, local area eye surgeons who travel twice yearly to Armenia to <br>
     perform eye surgery, examinations, teach new techniques to Armenian <br>
     doctors, and provide the gift of vision of to patients. <br>
     <br>
     The Orange County Register sent reporter John Hughes and photographer <br>
     Bruce Strong to cover the work of these physicians and offer their <br>
     perspectives on what Armenia has to offer the traveler. The Armenian <br>
     Assembly's Western Region Office Director, Peter Abajian, and <br>
     Assistant Director, Lena Kaimian, met extensively with Hughes and <br>
     Strong prior to their first trip to Armenia to provide briefings, <br>
     background, and information. Hughes movingly captured the resilient <br>
     spirit of the Armenian people in his articles, while Strong's <br>
     outstanding photographs captured the beauty, pain and never-ending <br>
     hope of the Armenian people.<br>
     <br>
     ACTION:<br>
      Contact the Orange County Register (OCR) and commend them for <br>
     running two major and well-written articles on Armenia.<br>
     <br>
      Commend the OCR for sending reporter J. Hughes and photographer B. <br>
     Strong to Armenia.<br>
     <br>
      Commend the OCR for maintaining references to the Genocide in its <br>
     second story despite outrage from the Turkish community concerning <br>
     references to the Genocide in the first story.<br>
     <br>
      Urge the Orange County Register and other newspapers to continue <br>
     covering stories about Armenia and the one-half million Armenians in <br>
     California.<br>
     <br>
      Contact the Orange County Register to request back copies.<br>
     <br>
      Please share your letters and responses with us.<br>
     <br>
      For further information on work done by Drs. Ohanesian and Hill in <br>
     Armenia, or if you have any other questions, contact Peter Abajian or <br>
     Lena Kaimian at the Assembly in Los Angeles at: <br>
     <br>
     Tel: 310-360-0091    <br>
     Fax: 310-360-0094<br>
     E-mail: aaawr@mail.idt.net<br>
     <br>
     Armenian Assembly of America<br>
     50 North La Cienega Boulevard <br>
     Suite 202  <br>
     Beverly Hills, CA   90211<br>
     <br>
     You can contact the Orange County Register at: <br>
     <br>
     The Orange County Register<br>
     Ms. Tonnie Katz, Editor     OR      Ms. Robin Doussard, Accent Editor<br>
     625 North Grand Avenue<br>
     Santa Ana, CA   92701 <br>
     <br>
     Tel: 714-835-1234<br>
     Fax: 714-565-5052<br>
     E-mail: <a href="http://www/ocregister.com">http://www/ocregister.com</a><br>
     <br>
     Due to many requests, the Orange County Register no longer has copies <br>
     of the November 17 article about travel to Armenia. However, copies of <br>
     the December 8 article about Drs. Ohanesian and Hill are still <br>
     available.<br>
     <br>
     <br>
     <br>
     <br>
     The Armenian-American Action Committee (ARAMAC) -- the grassroots arm <br>
     of the Armenian Assembly of America -- supports grassroots activism <br>
     and anti-defamation. Providing accurate information regarding Armenian <br>
     issues as well as responding to inaccurate information is critical <br>
     today given that greater attention is being given to Armenian issues <br>
     in Congress. Mobilizing, encouraging, and supporting the one million <br>
     Armenians throughout the United States in disseminating information <br>
     and impacting legislation concerning Armenian-American issues is an <br>
     integral part of improved U.S.-Armenia relations and improved <br>
     conditions in Armenia and Nagorno Karabagh.<br>
