<!-- body="start" -->
Izvestia, 19/12/96 N 238 (24845) <br>
<p>
WHO WAS INTERESTED IN THIS? <br>
<p>
By Boris Vinogradov<br>
<p>
Most analysts who are looking into motives of the crime in Novye Atagi<br>
instead of the question "Who did that?" are asking the question "Who want to<br>
upset elections?"  This question immediately assigns political motives to<br>
this crime.  Moreover, a conclusion is implied that murderers shall be<br>
sought among those groups in Chechnya which have no chances to win elections<br>
but would want to preserve the status quo of post-war authority and<br>
influence in Chechnya.  This scenario is most popular among those who<br>
observe Chechnya from outside and try to make prognosis about outcome of<br>
elections.  With this approach quite a few groups in Chechnya, if not all,<br>
can be held under suspicion as none of them feels quite confident about<br>
results and the closer the date (January 27) the stronger tensions among<br>
them and the stronger chances for new provocations.  There is a wide-spread<br>
opinion that upsetting elections and introduction of a special regime<br>
similar to an extraordinary one would be in the interests both field<br>
commanders who are reluctant to say farewell to arms and such leading<br>
figures as Shamil Basayev and Zelimkhan Yandarbiyev.  From the other hand<br>
side postponement of elections may provoke open clashes among various<br>
Chechen groupings and channel developments to a river bed which is against<br>
interests of current leaders of Ichkeria and federal authorities.   <br>
<p>
Some other experts on Chechnya maintain a different view. They see the main<br>
reason for the crime in Novye Atagi in the fact that the balk of Chechen<br>
population is well armed. Emil Payin, Advisor to the President, does not<br>
rule out recurrence of similar actions in the foreseeable future. Moreover,<br>
this problem will become even more acute in future.  Even if elections are<br>
held, the legitimacy of elected power will always be challenged by<br>
legitimacy of arms. Emil Pain dismissed the version on political nature of<br>
this crime. He thinks that elections cannot be canceled due to any<br>
provocations. However, one cannot help note that these murders were<br>
committed right after Raduyev's band took Russian policemen hostages on<br>
Dagestani border. Raduyev tried to present this incident as a provocation of<br>
Russian special services. It is not by accident, says Payin, that some<br>
people in Grozny are implying that Moscow was involved in the blood-bath at<br>
international hospital. <br>
<p>
Meanwhile, reports from Grozny state that Interior Ministry bodies and the<br>
Offices of Prosecutor and National Security have developed their own version<br>
of the crime, but it is not clear what that version is.  Some light on this<br>
event is shed by eye-witness accounts. Thus, one of hospital guards stated<br>
that there were 10 terrorists, they intruded to hospital area through the<br>
fence and they had special arms with silencers.  (end) <br>
<p>
(Translated by AM) <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
