<!-- body="start" -->
Izvestia, 20/12/96<br>
<p>
TURKEY CONSIDERS CHECHNYA PART OF RUSSIA<br>
<p>
By Boris Pilyatskin<br>
<p>
The three day visit of Turkish Vice Prime Minister and Foreign Affairs<br>
Minister, Tansu Ciller, to Moscow ended yesterday with a signing of a<br>
Memorandum on cooperation between Russia and Turkey against terrorism.<br>
Among practical results of her visit are agreements on opening Russian and<br>
Turkish consulates in Izmir and Novorossiisk respectively and creation of a<br>
working group on energy issues this week. <br>
<p>
The Turkish guest evaluated the political importance of negotiations with<br>
the head of the Russian Federation MFA, Evgenii Primakov, and talks with<br>
Prime Minister Chernomyrdin and Moscow mayor Yurii Luzhkov as "opening of<br>
doors" to a new stage in the relations of two countries -- partnership.  Her<br>
Russian colleague completely agreed with her. At a joint press-conference<br>
Evgenii Primakov and Tansu Ciller expressed their satisfaction with the<br>
results of this visit and emphasized common approaches to a number of issues<br>
in international regional politics.  <br>
<p>
Moscow seems to be particularly pleased with the official position of Turkey<br>
which in the context of the resolution of the Chechen crisis. Turkish<br>
Foreign Affairs Minister reiterated her country's adherence to the principle<br>
of territorial integrity of the Russian Federation. The sides agreed that the<br>
same principle shall be applied to Turkey and other countries of the region.   <br>
<p>
Trying to identify areas of tensions between the sides, journalists asked<br>
the Russian Minister what he thought about supplies of "offensive weapon<br>
systems" to Cyprus. <br>
<p>
-- I do not think that anti-aircraft systems are offensive weapons,<br>
responded Primakov.<br>
<p>
Ciller kept silent and only smiled.  (end) (Translated from Russian by AM)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
