<title>Groong Network: Ciller's visit to Moscow</title>
<h1>Ciller's visit to Moscow</h1>
Arthur Martirosyan (<i>martiros@hulaw1.harvard.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 18 Dec 1996 22:34:15 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#166">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#166">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#166">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#166">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0167.html">vahe@arminco.com: "Aragil Headlines, 12/19/96"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0165.html">erac@ican.net: "DEDICATION OF NEW EMBASSY BUILDING IN OTTAWA"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
SEGODNIA: No. 235, 12/18/96<br>
<p>
Ankara is concerned with Russian military supplies to Cyprus<br>
Moscow accuses Turkey of "incorrect" activities on the territory of the RF<br>
<p>
The two day visit of Vice Prime Minister and Foreign Affairs Minister of<br>
Turkey Tansu Ciller to Moscow which began yesterday is held in the time of<br>
appreciable aggravation of bilateral relations. Interfax was told by a high<br>
ranking anonymous source in the Russian government on the eve of the visit<br>
that the Russian side was going to discuss the new Black Sea straits regime,<br>
unilaterally imposed by Ankara as well as attempts of Turkish officials to<br>
establish "special" relations with Turkic peoples of the Russian Federation<br>
which Moscow views as "incorrect."  According to the same source, Moscow is<br>
concerned with the activities of Islamic organizations in Turkey which<br>
financially support "separatist trends in Chechnya."  <br>
<p>
Ankara in its turn is extremely concerned with prospects of sales to Cyprus<br>
of Russian anti-aircraft systems S-300. Russia has already sold 41 T80-U<br>
tanks which impressed everybody at a military parade on October 1.  Along<br>
with 52 AMX-32B2 tanks provided by Greece and 52 French tanks already at the<br>
disposal of Cyprus, the Republic of Cyprus may soon reach parity  in terms<br>
of armor with the Turkish expeditionary corps which has 265 tanks on the<br>
island.  Meanwhile as Minister of Defense of Greece Akis Tsokhadzopulos<br>
stated last month during his trip to Moscow the south of the island badly<br>
needed protection against possible air strikes.  Recently S-300 systems have<br>
been examined by the Chief of Staff of Air Force of Greece, Georgios<br>
Antonetsis at one of Moscow test fields.  <br>
<p>
Mutual accusations can mar otherwise quite good potential of RussianTurkish<br>
military-technical copperation. Moscow hopes to bring sales of military<br>
equipment to Turkey to 300 million (currently 121 million) dollars. Turkey<br>
has an ambitious re-armament program (as well as Greece).  In the next 30<br>
years Turkey is planning to spend  150 billion dollars for defense purposes.<br>
However, it is not clear at all that Russia will play any significant role<br>
in that program. <br>
<p>
The political intrigue is that Turkey disappointed by yet another rejection<br>
to be accepted to EU has allegedly threatened to block expansion of NATO.<br>
The leak of this information was obviously sanctioned on the eve of Ciller's<br>
visit to Moscow. Most probably the threat will turn out to be a bluff (after<br>
all Greece, too, has the right of veto in the alliance). Moscow knows only<br>
too well the Turkey's inclinations to self-aggrandizement. <br>
<p>
Today the most feasible and the largest project  is the construction of the<br>
second natural gas pipeline which is in Ankara's utmost interest. The 1,160<br>
km long pipeline will cost 1.1 billion dollars and will increase Russian<br>
export of natural gas to Turkey from 8 to 14 billion cubic meters. (end) <br>
<p>
(Translated by AM from Russian)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
