<!-- body="start" -->
--=====================_850926236==_<br>
Content-Type: text/plain; charset="us-ascii"<br>
<p>
<p>
<p>
--=====================_850926236==_<br>
Content-Type: text/plain; charset="us-ascii"<br>
Content-Disposition: attachment; filename="OTTAWA.TXT"<br>
<p>
NOTES FOR AN ADDRESS BY HIS EXCELLENCY GARNIK NANAGOULIAN ON THE<br>
OCCASION OF THE TRIBUTE BANQUET MARKING THE DEDICATION CEREMONY OF THE<br>
PERMANENT PREMISES OF THE EMBASSY OF THE REPUBLIC OF ARMENIA IN OTTAWA<br>
OTTAWA, SUNDAY DECEMBER 7, 1996<br>
<p>
	It is very symbolic that December 7, the day of the tragic<br>
earthquake in Armenia, we chose to inaugurate the new Embassy building<br>
of the Republic of Armenia in Canada. There are many ways of marking<br>
this anniversary. Personally, I feel that we don't have the luxury to<br>
continue our grieving. We must take positive and constructive steps to<br>
re-build not only our homes, but, more critical to our future, to<br>
build our Nation. That would be the best monument to the memory of the<br>
victims of the earthquake. In Armenia today, the process of nation<br>
building is developing slowly but steadily. We are facing enormous<br>
challenges and problems but our goals are focused and our vision is<br>
clear and it is obvious that we are moving nearer to our target.<br>
<p>
	We are to create a country where fundamental human rights and<br>
the rule of law will be the essence of governing, and where every<br>
Armenian will be proud of not only a rich history and a fabulous past,<br>
but more importantly, of its current deeds. I have been privileged to<br>
become a member of the new government in Armenia, to join a team of<br>
those outstanding Armenians headed by the President of republic, Levon<br>
Ter-Petrossian , who are committed to fulfill this goal. But the<br>
important guarantee that this goal will come to fruition is the People<br>
of Armenia. Our people are the true safeguard for democratic reforms<br>
and socio-economic progress. It is not a secret that we have to rely<br>
on your support, the Armenians all over the world. To those who are<br>
still hesitating regarding the future of Armenia my best advice to you<br>
is to help us by taking a positive approach to the issues and work<br>
with us for solutions.<br>
<p>
	I have said that we are building in Armenia, but we build<br>
outside of Armenia as well. Thanks to the assistance of our friends,<br>
we erected "Hay Doons - Armenian Embassies" in a number of countries<br>
worldwide. In North America we have launched embassies in New York and<br>
Washington. I would like to take this opportunity to salute Mr. and<br>
Mrs. Hrair Hovanian for their extraordinary support which made it<br>
possible to have an Embassy building in Washington DC. Today, we have<br>
inaugurated another splendid Hay Doon, the Armenian Embassy in<br>
Ottawa. I think that it is a fitting monument to our fellow citizens<br>
who tragically died on 7 December 1988. Today it is also fitting that<br>
we pay a tribute to a man, an Armenian, whose contributions to the<br>
independent Armenia are hard to overestimate. It is a unique<br>
opportunity because he prefers to be a silent benefactor, a silent<br>
supporter and a silent soldier dedicated to his motherland. This man<br>
is Mr. Sarkis Acopian.<br>
<p>
	Owing to Mr. Acopian's generosity, the Embassy building in<br>
Canada became a reality. The magnitude of Mr. Acopian's generosity<br>
reaches well beyond the building in Ottawa. Through his support for<br>
many projects in Armenia, he has demonstrated a depth of commitment to<br>
our country well beyond what many can imagine. Respecting his modesty,<br>
I am in no position to elaborate on his contribution and involvement<br>
in a number of projects for Armenia. More than the gift, however, it<br>
is the manner in which the Acopian Family chooses to contribute that<br>
makes it so appreciated -- it is given with modesty, without fanfare<br>
and with extreme sincerity.<br>
<p>
	I met him several years ago and I got to know him better<br>
through our occasional meetings in Pennsylvania or Washington or<br>
Boston, I truly felt that my life was enriched. I felt very encouraged<br>
by the support for Armenia of an individual with these high moral<br>
values and philosophy of life. I, as an Armenian, felt more secure and<br>
more confident with this caliber of commitment; that we, as a nation,<br>
would prevail and we, as a nation, will once again claim our proper<br>
place in the world.<br>
<p>
	Mr. Acopian is a truly unique individual with wide range of<br>
activities and interests. He is involved in the sophisticated<br>
high-tech engineering that has created marvels for the defense<br>
capabilities of his country. But, at the same time, he is the driving<br>
force and an initiator of delicate projects such as the first<br>
Encyclopedia on the Feathered World of Armenia. Whatever he is<br>
involved in becomes enlightening and useful to human life.<br>
<p>
	After Armenia became independent, many people in the Diaspora<br>
felt lost and confused. They did not know what to do with this newborn<br>
and how to deal with it. Not for Mr. Acopian. His choice was<br>
immediately made and he started even before his corporate plane with<br>
the sign "Acopian" landed in Armenia. Independent Armenia was the<br>
incarnation of his and his parents' dream and regardless of the fact<br>
that who is in the government and what kind of political forces are<br>
there, he is committed to contribute to the process of making Armenia<br>
a modern nation. He is a man who has faced many challenges during his<br>
life and prevailed. He values professionalism, commitment and human<br>
decency. I wish I could spend more time with him. It is unfortunate<br>
that the full measure of Sarkis Acopian's good works are not known, as<br>
they would serve as an outstanding example for many to emulate.<br>
<p>
	Sarkis Acopian and his family fulfilled an enormous commitment<br>
with regards to their share to the new embassy building in Canada. The<br>
Canadian-Armenian Community also contributed to our new Embassy with<br>
its share. Today, I must mention in recognition for outstanding<br>
contributions to these efforts, Mr. John Adjeleian, the project<br>
manager, one of the most renowned structural engineers in Canada whose<br>
achievements include the famous Toronto Skydome, Mr. Haig Madjarian<br>
who provided all the lighting for the Embassy, actually, enlightened<br>
the Embassy, Mrs. Sylvia Toukhmanian, Mr. Mitchell Davey, Mr. and<br>
Mrs. Harry and Magda Yaghjian and others from the community whose<br>
daily contributions made this project come to fruition. And, of<br>
course, we have always felt the support from the Friends of Armenia,<br>
headed by Mr. Haig Misakyan, Mr. Mego Malkhassian and Mr. Garo<br>
Nichanian. A particular mention is due to the Primate of the Armenian<br>
Church in Canada, His Eminence Archbishop Hovnan Derd!  erian whose<br>
participation and guidance could hardly be exaggerated. He is an<br>
outstanding personality and a real leader of this Community.<br>
<p>
	So, the Home is built and now we have to fill it with the soul<br>
and essence. This must become a place where important initiatives<br>
strengthening Canadian-Armenian and Diasporan-Armenian relations<br>
should be executed. We should all join together to make this<br>
happen. The relations between our two countries have real<br>
perspectives. During the past one and a half years in Canada, we<br>
planted the seeds from which we are now just beginning to see the<br>
fruits of our labor. But it has only just begun. There are many more<br>
buds on the tree that will soon bloom, but with your attentiveness and<br>
cooperation. It so happens that I have to leave Canada. I will be<br>
frank with you, I will miss this country, I will miss the people, and<br>
I will miss you. During my stay here I met many wonderful people who<br>
were very supportive. I also experienced the sadness of losing close<br>
friends. Today I have to remember Dr. Ara Mouradian who held an<br>
instrumental role at the very beginning of our programs with regards!<br>
to the Armenian Nuclear Power Plant. His contribution and support are<br>
invaluable. I will not forget another good friend of the Armenian<br>
people, a decent Armenian man, Mr. Varoujean Boyadjian whose thoughts<br>
and support were so important at the initial stages of our Embassy.<br>
<p>
	But life goes on and there are many things to be done. Our<br>
people in Armenia deserve better living conditions. Let's not forget<br>
the fact that a significant number of them still live below the<br>
poverty line. We must continue to make ourselves stronger and to do<br>
everything possible to alleviate these burdensome problems. We are<br>
counting on your continued vigilance, your sensitive response, your<br>
caring support. I also rely on you, my friends, to support our Embassy<br>
staff here Mr. Ashot Grigorian, Mrs. Karine Afrikian and Mr. Hrach<br>
Kaspar.<br>
<p>
--=====================_850926236==_--<br>
