<title>Groong Network: ASBAREZ-ON-LINE [12-18-96]</title>
<h1>ASBAREZ-ON-LINE [12-18-96]</h1>
ASBAREZ-ON-LINE (<i>76635.2505@CompuServe.COM</i>)<br>
<i>18 Dec 96 19:46:55 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#164">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#164">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#164">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#164">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0165.html">erac@ican.net: "DEDICATION OF NEW EMBASSY BUILDING IN OTTAWA"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0163.html">Chavoush@aol.com: "Armenian News 12/18/96"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
ASBAREZ ON LINE <br>
12/18/1996<br>
<p>
<p>
1. POST-ELECTION ARREST CASE TO BE REVIEWED BY SUPREME COURT<br>
2. AYJM NEWSPAPER CONSIDCATED<br>
3. EUROCOURT DEALS DOUBLE BLOW TO TURKEY<br>
4. AEF NAMES PETROSSIAN EDUCATOR OF YEAR<br>
<p>
<p>
1. POST-ELECTION ARREST CASE TO BE REVIEWED BY SUPREME COURT<br>
<p>
YEREVAN-The preliminary investigation into criminal charges for a <br>
number of individuals arrested as a result of the Sept. 25 post-<br>
election crackdown in Armenia has concluded and the results have <br>
been submitted to the Supreme Court, National Democratic Union <br>
executive member and chairman of its lawyers association, Vova <br>
Hakhverdian said Wednesday.<br>
	According to Hakhverdian, none of the charges can be proven <br>
because the events that led to those individuals arrests-storming <br>
of the National Assembly building where the Central Electoral <br>
Commission was headquartered, the kidnapping of National Assembly <br>
Speaker Babken Ararktsian and the beating of Deputy Speaker Ara <br>
Sahakian-were carried out by Armenias leadership and not the <br>
opposition as is claimed.<br>
	The trials are scheduled to begin at the end of January and <br>
all of the defendants have retained attorneys to prepare their <br>
defenses, Hakhverdian said.<br>
	Armenian authorities have expedited the hearings to show the <br>
international community that the parliament building was stormed, <br>
laws were broken and that the responsible parties will be held <br>
accountable, Hakhverdian added.<br>
	Hakhverdian was convinced that the events of Sept. 25 were <br>
orchestrated entirely by Armenias leadership to cover up what <br>
truly happened. "Otherwise, they would not have any excuses," <br>
Hakhverdian said.<br>
	Criminal charges against Armenian Revolutionary Federation <br>
Executive Council member Kim Balayan will be heard separately. <br>
Balayan has been charged with leaving a victim unaided (Article <br>
128 of Armenias Criminal Code); inciting mass disorder (Article <br>
74); and illegal possession of weapons (Article 232).<br>
	Mkrtich Meghavorian, Vahe Beknazarian, Seyran Masoyan, Habet <br>
Petrossian and Argishti Kivirian have all been charged with <br>
violating Article 74 of the Criminal Code.<br>
	The families of the defendants issued a statement Wednesday <br>
in an effort to focus attention on the plight of their relatives. <br>
The statement, sent to Armenias public-political organizations <br>
and the mass media, calls attention to the fact that those <br>
individuals, who were all active in national alliance candidate <br>
Vazgen Manoukians presidential campaign, have been detained for <br>
their political convictions and participation in opposition <br>
politics.<br>
	"They are innocent, unless being a supporter of Vazgen <br>
Manoukian is a crime," the statement said.<br>
	"In his televised appearance following the declaration of <br>
his presidency, Levon Ter-Petrosyan promised that he would not <br>
carry out witch-hunts, but the trumped up charges against our <br>
relatives demonstrate that Armenias leadership is conducting a <br>
sweep of opposition forces," the statement said.<br>
	The statement harshly criticized the massive human rights <br>
violations by Armenias authorities, especially their relatives <br>
three-month detention without formal charges. The statement was <br>
also highly critical of Prosecutor-General Artavazd Gevorkian for <br>
carrying out the orders of the leadership and "detaining, without <br>
any evidence, innocent individuals." Gevorkians actions remain <br>
unchecked, the group said, calling on others to join their <br>
struggle for justice and to hold Gevorkian accountable.<br>
<p>
<p>
2. AYJM NEWSPAPER CONSIDCATED<br>
<p>
YEREVAN-The Dec. 18 issue of Ayjm newspaper, the official <br>
publication of the National Democratic Union, was confiscated by <br>
the state distributing agency.<br>
	The issue was published but never  reached readers, since, <br>
NDU officials said, the distributing agency Haimamoul, using its <br>
monopoly on newspaper distribution has halted the dissemination of <br>
Ayjm.<br>
	In the current issue, Ayjm had published a critical report <br>
on Haimamoul, which, in turn, decided to not distribute the <br>
newspaper.<br>
<p>
<p>
3. EUROCOURT DEALS DOUBLE BLOW TO TURKEY<br>
<p>
STRASBOURG, France (Reuter)-The European Court of Human Rights <br>
dealt a double blow to Turkey Wednesday, ruling that Ankara had <br>
violated the rights of a Greek Cypriot with land in northern <br>
Cyprus and tortured a suspected Kurdish fighter. <br>
	Turkish authorities had no immediate comment, but the <br>
rulings in widely-watched cases seemed bound to bolster already <br>
widespread criticism of Ankaras human rights record.<br>
	In a landmark finding, the court rejected Turkeys argument <br>
that the European human rights convention did not apply to its <br>
occupation of the north of Cyprus since it occurred before Ankara <br>
accepted its jurisdiction.<br>
	Cypriot lawyers said the ruling was significant because it <br>
made Turkey responsible for the situation on the island rather <br>
than the breakaway Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus declared in <br>
1983 and recognized only by Ankara.<br>
	"I believe its effects can be enormous," Cypriot President <br>
Glafcos Clerides told reporters following the judgment. "If we <br>
take into account those who were forced to leave their homes then <br>
the effects can be greater."<br>
	About 200,000 Greek Cypriots were displaced when Turkish <br>
troops took control of the northern third of Cyprus in 1974 after <br>
a brief coup engineered by a military junta then ruling Greece.<br>
	The court upheld a complaint by tourist guide Titina <br>
Loizidou that Turkey violated her property rights by denying her <br>
access to land she owned in Kyrenia, northern Cyprus.<br>
	It found by a vote of 11-6 that the Turkish army "exercised <br>
effective overall control" in Cyprus.<br>
	Loizidou told reporters she was sure the judgment would help <br>
the search for a solution to the Cyprus problem.<br>
	"This is an historic decision. It is the first time an <br>
international court has taken a legal decision on Turkeys <br>
responsibility in northern Cyprus and found Turkey guilty for <br>
denying people the right to enjoy their property," she said. <br>
	In the second case, the court, an arm of the 40-nation <br>
Council of Europe that promotes human rights and democracy, ruled <br>
that Turkish police tortured a Kurd, Zeki Aksoy, in 1992 after <br>
arresting him as a suspected terrorist.<br>
	Ankara was ordered to pay 4.3 billion Turkish lire ($41,000) <br>
in damages plus legal fees of 20,710 pounds sterling ($34,586). <br>
	But the court found no evidence that Aksoy was murdered by <br>
the state after complaining to Strasbourg about his treatment <br>
while he was held incommunicado for at least two weeks at the <br>
Kiziltepe security prison in southeast Turkey in late 1992. <br>
	Aksoy, who complained to the European authorities in May <br>
1993, was found murdered in April 1994. Two days before his death, <br>
he received a telephoned warning that he would be killed unless he <br>
withdrew his complaint, according to his lawyers. <br>
	Turkey told the court a member of the Kurdistan Workers <br>
Party (PKK) had been charged with the murder.<br>
	Though never charged, Askoy said he was subjected to a form <br>
of torture known as "Palestinian hanging" in which he was stripped <br>
naked and hung by his arms, causing him to lose the use of his <br>
arms and hands.<br>
	He was also given electric shocks to his genitals, kicked, <br>
slapped and verbally abused, he said.<br>
<p>
<p>
4. AEF NAMES PETROSSIAN EDUCATOR OF YEAR<br>
<p>
BY GARO MOUMDJIAN<br>
<p>
GLENDALE-More than 350 people were gathered at the Brandview <br>
Collection Hall at noon, on December 8, to honor one of Glendales <br>
outspoken, most energetic, and esteemed educators Alice <br>
Petrossian, who was named "Educator of the Year" during Armenian <br>
Educational Foundation's annual Poinsettia Brunch.<br>
	Present at the gathering were the Glendale Unified School <br>
District Superintendent James R. Brown, Assistant Superintendent <br>
Dr. Joanne Myrick, Glendale Unified School District Board member <br>
Linda Rocamora, Judge Alice Altoon, holder of AEF Chair in <br>
Armenian Studies Prof. Richard Hovanissian, former President of <br>
the American University of Armenia Dr. Mihran Aghbabian, as well <br>
as principals and vice-principals of Armenian schools, educators, <br>
professionals, journalists, and scores of relatives, associates <br>
and friends, who had come to honor Petrossian for her decades long <br>
services to the cause of education and the betterment of future <br>
generations.<br>
	AEF vice-president Nora Sahagian delivered the welcoming <br>
remarks, underlining the importance of education in the Armenian <br>
psyche and stressed that Alice Petrossian is the personification <br>
of that psyche, because she endured many hardships in her quest to <br>
excel and was able to accomplish the goals she set for herself.<br>
	Ralph Tufenkian, a benefactor and AEF Board member, <br>
delivered the opening remarks. He was followed by AEF president <br>
Shahen Nazarian who explained the reasons behind choosing <br>
Petrossian as the recipient of the organizations "Educator of the <br>
Year Award." <br>
	He stressed that it was a well-deserved award, since <br>
Petrossian was-by nature-an advocate of education and a civic <br>
leader who makes her voice heard in matters pertaining to the <br>
education, because she firmly believes that the youth are our <br>
future assets and, as such, much should be devoted to their proper <br>
upbringing and development. <br>
	Nazarian cited Petrossians own family as an example, saying <br>
that she, together with her husband, Vahik, attended to the needs <br>
of their two sons, Chris and Shant, who are university graduates <br>
and who devote their time to causes beneficial to their community.<br>
	Nazarian then called upon AEF member Berdj Karapetian to <br>
present the award. Karapetian highlighted several aspects of <br>
Petrossians accomplishments in the fields of education and <br>
Armenian community affairs. With tears in her eyes, Petrossian <br>
walked to the stage as attendees gave her a standing ovation. <br>
	"I would have not been able to do all this if it was not for <br>
you, my friends and associates, who encouraged me at all times," <br>
Petrossian said, as she thanked the AEF for honoring her. <br>
	She also expressed gratitude to her parents and her closest <br>
relatives for their encouragement, but most of all to the <br>
unequivocal support of her family, her husband and two sons, who <br>
endured her frequent absences on the path of advocacy for <br>
educational matters.<br>
	An appearance by the Valley View Elementary School choir was <br>
a part of a surprise organized by the brunch committee. The <br>
children entertained the guests with renditions of several popular <br>
Armenian songs, under the direction of their principal, Jackie <br>
Kurkdjian, a close friend of Petrossian.<br>
	Musical entertainment for the event was also provided by <br>
flutist Salpi Kerkonian with Sossi Carian (harp), and Missak <br>
Alexanian (cello).<br>
<p>
