<title>Groong Network: Armenian News 12/18/96</title>
<h1>Armenian News 12/18/96</h1>
<i>Chavoush@aol.com</i><br>
<i>Wed, 18 Dec 96 15:37:52 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#163">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#163">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#163">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#163">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0164.html">ASBAREZ-ON-LINE: "ASBAREZ-ON-LINE [12-18-96]"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0162.html">Armen Martirossyan: "Snark News"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Headlines of stories which follow:<br>
1.  President Aliyev says new oil project improves ties with USA <br>
2.  Azeris want new look at Tashkent accord <br>
3.  British Firm Harrison &amp; Sons to Print New Banknotes for Armenia<br>
4.  Azeri Oil Will Be Routed Across Russian Territory From The March Of 1997 <br>
5.  Agent in cassock spied on pontiff <br>
<p>
Chavoush's note on #5 - A Scottish newspaper claims that Mehmet Ali Agca, the<br>
man that shot the Pope, was an "Armenian Turk".  It is mentioned in the<br>
paragraph seventh from the end.  That is news to me!<br>
<p>
HEADLINE: President Aliyev says new oil project improves ties with USA <br>
SOURCE: Interfax news agency, Moscow, in English 1443 gmt and 1544 gmt 14 Dec<br>
96 <br>
<p>
Azerbaijani President Heydar Aliyev has described the signing of a 2bn-dollar<br>
deal with a consortium of international oil companies to develop two oil<br>
deposits in the Caspian as "a remarkable event" in the life of Azerbaijan and<br>
of significance for the development of relations between his country and the<br>
United States, ITAR-TASS news agency reported on 14th December. <br>
<p>
"The signing of this contract is of great importance for the development of<br>
the entire economy of my country, which is confidently showing to the world<br>
its openness and readiness for cooperation, and makes confident steps along<br>
the path leading to international integration," the agency quoted Aliyev as<br>
saying after the signing ceremony on 14th December. <br>
<p>
Noting the contract's significance in terms of promoting Azerbaijan's<br>
relations with the USA, Aliyev said the participation vc of the two US<br>
companies, Amoco and Unocal, in the project "meets the strategic interests of<br>
the two countries" , the agency reported. <br>
<p>
Interfax news agency quoted Aliyev as saying on the same occasion that Baku<br>
had no intention of changing its strategic policy for the development of<br>
offshore Caspian oil and gas fields "despite interference from some circles<br>
outside the country" . <br>
<p>
"The unsettled status of the Caspian Sea cannot influence the implementation<br>
of the contract signed," the agency quoted the Azerbaijan president as<br>
saying. Aliyev said US Vice President Al Gore had called him on 13th December<br>
"expressing US support for Azerbaijan' s strategy for the development of<br>
energy resources" . <br>
<p>
There are five companies involved in the project to develop the Dan Ulduzu<br>
and Ashrafi offshore oil and gas fields. They are Amoco, which has a<br>
30-per-cent stake; the Azerbaijani State Oil Company SOCAR and Japan's<br>
Itochu, which have 20 per cent each; and the USA's UNOCAL and Saudi Arabia's<br>
Delta acting in tandem with 30 per cent, divided into 25.5 and 4.5 per cent<br>
respectively, Interfax reported. <br>
<p>
In a separate report the same day, Interfax quoted SOCAR Vice President Ilham<br>
Aliyev as saying that the exclusion of Russian oil companies from the deal<br>
should not be viewed as a political move. In particular, the absence of<br>
Lukoil, which has a stake in Azerbaijan's three other oil deals, "is not<br>
linked in any way to Russia's political interests" , he was quoted as saying.<br>
<p>
<p>
"The two fields in question are adjacent to the Karabakh deposit, in which<br>
Lukoil has a 32.5-per-cent development stake, and the present contract could<br>
in the future be merged with the Karabakh one. That would give Lukoil an<br>
indirect stake," he added, as quoted by Interfax . <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Azeris want new look at Tashkent accord <br>
SOURCE:  Jane's Defence Weekly,   December 18, 1996<br>
<p>
Azerbaijan remains nervous about its neighbours, especially Armenia where the<br>
ceasefire over Nagorno Karabakh is fractious.  Meanwhile, Russia's intentions<br>
may pose a threat. <br>
<p>
Azerbaijan's armed forces would like to renegotiate the Tashkent Agreement<br>
for the sharing vc of former Soviet weaponry, but not at the expense of<br>
Russia gaining more materiel, a senior army officer told Jane's Defence<br>
Weekly. <br>
<p>
The source, who wished to remain anonymous, pointed out that Azerbaijan has<br>
longer borders and more citizens than Armenia and Georgia - something not<br>
considered when the agreement was signed. He complained that weapons continue<br>
to reach Armenian forces, which, despite the May 1994 ceasefire, are still in<br>
a state of war with Azerbaijan over the disputed region of Nagorno Karabakh.<br>
The officer said small arms fire is exchanged daily between Azeri and<br>
Armenian forces despite reports that the ceasefire is holding. <br>
<p>
Azerbaijan disputes independently published reports on Armenian force<br>
strengths and official Armenian-declared strengths in Nagorno Karabakh and<br>
offers its own estimates: <br>
<p>
- Personnel: Published: 12, 000,  Armenian claims: -, Azeri claims: 40, 000+;<br>
<p>
<p>
- MBTs: Published: 13, Armenian claims: 100, Azeri claims: 150+; <br>
<p>
- AFVs: Published: -, Armenian claims: 100, Azeri claims: 200+; <br>
<p>
- Artillery (100 mm+): Published: 16, Armenian claims: 200, Azeri claims:<br>
200+. <br>
<p>
He said: "The problem in verifying the estimates is the failure of inspection<br>
teams under the CFE [Conventional Forces in Europe] Treaty and Vienna<br>
Document-94 to make inspections where they really matter." <br>
<p>
Illegal arms transfers from Armenia to Nagorno Karabakh take place along<br>
three major access routes: Dilijan to Kelbajar in the northern sector; Megri<br>
to Zangelan in the south; and Sisian to Shusha in the central sector, which<br>
"have never been inspected". <br>
<p>
Armenia and foreign military forces there also hold more equipment than<br>
allowed under CFE treaty limitations, he claimed: 177 main battle tanks<br>
(MBTs), 435 other armoured combat vehicles (ACVs), 220 artillery pieces and<br>
12 attack helicopters. The officer also accused Iran of sending arms to<br>
Armenia. French, Lebanese, Libyan and Syrian mercenaries are based in Nagorno<br>
Karabakh, he claimed. <br>
<p>
One of the main difficulties in implementing the CFE Treaty, he said, is the<br>
problem of non-recoverable losses of Treaty-limited equipment in the course<br>
of military operations against Armenia. He says Azerbaijan has lost 186 MBTs,<br>
119 ACVs and 57 artillery pieces of 100 mm-plus. <br>
<p>
Under the terms of the CFE treaty, Azerbaijan has also retired 15 MBTs, 174<br>
ACVs and 40 artillery pieces above 100 mm and cascaded a further 100 to<br>
border troops in the Azeri enclave of Nakhchivan. <br>
<p>
A lot of the equipment received by Azerbaijan was "in very poor technical<br>
condition", and maintenance and spare parts are a serious problem. <br>
<p>
He said that Armenia has failed to implement UN resolutions in the area and<br>
that NATO, under the terms of Partnership for Peace, should recognise this<br>
and take action against Armenia. <br>
<p>
"We hope to find a peaceful solution to this problem," he said, but according<br>
to Western diplomats in Baku, no Azeri politician would be able to hold<br>
office without declaring his intention to recover captured areas by force,<br>
should negotiations fail. <br>
<p>
This, however, appears to be rhetoric rather than reality. Azerbaijan has<br>
signed major contracts with Western consortia for the exploitation of its oil<br>
wealth and it fears any renewed large-scale fighting would, at the very<br>
least, delay pumping and much needed foreign income. <br>
<p>
Azerbaijan's own frail internal political system and fears for the future of<br>
Russian President Boris Yeltsin are also cause for concern in Azerbaijan.<br>
Since gaining independence in 1991, Azerbaijan has faced coups, revolts,<br>
mutinies, states of emergencies and separatist threats as well as joining,<br>
leaving and rejoining the Commonwealth of Independent States. <br>
<p>
The country is held together by President Heydar Aliev, but he is ageing and<br>
appears to have no suitable successor. An internal power struggle is likely<br>
and the popular policy of retaking Nagorno Karabakh by force may swing the<br>
balance in any leadership struggle. <br>
<p>
Although Azeris downplay the possibility, they fear that an expansionist<br>
Russian leader may replace Yeltsin. First on the list for "reintegration" may<br>
be Azerbaijan and its oil fields, some Azeris believe, but not before the<br>
wells and pipelines are pumping. <br>
<p>
Russia continues to back ousted President Ayaz Mutalibov, who is in exile in<br>
Moscow and has attempted to regain power in Azerbaijan. Senior Azeri military<br>
officials point to reports that Gen Alexander Lebed, Russia's ousted national<br>
security chief, was attempting to establish a 'foreign legion', comprising<br>
mainly Armenian and Serbian personnel. They believe Russia could try to<br>
re-enter Azerbaijan by supporting a full-scale invasion via Armenia, using<br>
the Armenians as a proxy force. <br>
<p>
Azerbaijani forces continue to operate under the old Soviet force structure<br>
and doctrine "but now with greater co-operation with NATO and with frequent<br>
military exchanges, we are able to make new decisions on the best way to<br>
operate." Azerbaijan is restructuring its forces. <br>
<p>
As well as weapons acquisitions from Russia, Azerbaijan also buys equipment<br>
<i>&gt;from Israel, Turkey and China. Modernisation and standardisation are the main</i><br>
priorities of the armed forces. <br>
<p>
Azerbaijan publicly declared its support for NATO's moves to expand the<br>
alliance eastward at the latest meeting of the council of ministers of<br>
defence in Moscow. <br>
<p>
While the country has no immediate plans to make any of its forces available<br>
for peacekeeping operations, a special unit has been set up to study and<br>
train for peacekeeping, but now, "we need all our troops for any crises in<br>
Nagorno Karabakh", said the officer. <br>
<p>
Azerbaijan acknowledges only four terrorist attacks in the country - all in<br>
1994 - and no group claimed responsibility. Azerbaijan's foreign ethnic<br>
community comprises  around 300,000 Russian nationals of Azeri citizenship; a<br>
similar number of Armenians; and a smaller number of Daghestanis. <br>
<p>
Because these claim discrimination against them internal unrest and  renewed<br>
terrorist activity are possible. <br>
<p>
Around 90 per cent of Azeris are Shi'ite Muslims, although there is little<br>
 religious activity. Turkey appears to be leaning to a more fundamentalist<br>
way of life and may influence its Azeri neighbours in bordering Nakhchivan,<br>
while Iran regularly broadcasts religious radio and television programmes to<br>
Azerbaijan. <br>
<p>
One theory to try to explain why Iran supported Armenia over Nagorno Karabakh<br>
is that Azerbaijan would need Iran to support or mediate any future conflict<br>
between Armenia and Azerbaijan. Iran would then have the leverage to demand a<br>
more religious life in Azerbaijan and less Azeri involvement with the West,<br>
especially NATO. <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: British Firm Harrison &amp; Sons to Print New Banknotes for Armenia<br>
SOURCE:  Novecon, December 17, 1996<br>
<p>
The British firm Harrison &amp; Sons has won a tender to make new banknotes for<br>
Armenia, announced Armen Valesyan, head of the Armenian Central Bank's press<br>
service. <br>
<p>
The British firm's competitive edge was in that it had already printed new<br>
banknotes for Germany, Kazakhstan and Uzbekistan. The firm will begin<br>
printing the new money vc from mid-1997. Valesyan said that the old money<br>
will remain legal tender along with the new banknotes. <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Azeri Oil Will Be Routed Across Russian Territory From The March Of<br>
1997 <br>
SOURCE:  RusData DiaLine- BizEkon News (Segdonya, No 234, p. 5), December 17,<br>
1996<br>
<p>
The Baku-to-Novorossiisk northern route will have the first 30,000 tons of<br>
Azeri oil flowing in February, 1997. <br>
<p>
According to president of the Azerbaijan international operations company<br>
Terry Adams, the initial 30,000 tons of Azeri oil are to be carried to world<br>
markets via Russia in February, 1997. <br>
<p>
Those shipments are supposed to be followed up by deliveries of another<br>
40,000 tons of oil by the northern route vc from Baku to Novorossiisk, a<br>
Russian port on the Black Sea. No figures are yet finalized for such supplies<br>
in the following months, though relevant feasibility studies submitted to the<br>
government of Azerbaijan specify annual exports of 1 million tons. <br>
<p>
Mr Adams, for his part, sees no problems with transporting Azeri oil across<br>
Russian territory. <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Agent in cassock spied on pontiff <br>
SOURCE:  Scotland on Sunday, December 15, 1996<br>
<p>
Secret Police Files In Berlin Show That Someone Was Watching Over Polish Pope<br>
John Paul Ii In The Holy See - And It Wasn'T Just God, Writes Gabriel Ronay <br>
<p>
A communist spy infiltrated the Vatican in the guise of a high-ranking<br>
Catholic cleric to keep an eye on Pope John Paul II at the height of the Cold<br>
War. <br>
<p>
John Paul was the first non-Italian in four centuries to be elected to the<br>
Papacy, and the Kremlin believed his Eastern European roots as the former<br>
Bishop of Kracow vc in Poland made him an active spiritual opponent of<br>
atheistic communism. A fellow Pole within the church was recruited to watch<br>
over him. <br>
<p>
Stalin had previously regarded the Vatican as irrelevant to power politics,<br>
asking dismissively: "How many divisions has the Pope got?" But spying became<br>
an absolute imperative with the Pope's financial support for the Solidarity<br>
trade union in his native country and in view of the 'holy alliance' forged<br>
between the Vatican and US president Ronald Reagan in their drive against the<br>
influence of the 'evil empire' of the Soviet Union. <br>
<p>
The mysterious figure of an East European 'James Bond in a cassock' has only<br>
now emerged from previously unexamined files of the East German Stasi secret<br>
police archives in Berlin which include copies of Polish security service<br>
reports dating back to the early 1970s. They contain more than 300 pages of<br>
startling revelations ranging from Pope Paul VI's secret discussions with the<br>
late West German Chancellor Willy Brandt about his Ostpolitik vision, and<br>
also top secret CIA briefings for the current Pope that were given during the<br>
1980s. <br>
<p>
The Soviet bloc's Vatican spy, it appears, passed on all the information he<br>
gleaned from the Pope's entourage to the KGB who then distributed it to the<br>
other Warsaw Pact secret services. <br>
<p>
Vatican spokesman Monsignor Joaquin Navarro-Valls at first dismissed the<br>
newly-discovered Berlin spy files, claiming that these were "pure<br>
fabrications intended to show how well informed the Polish secret service had<br>
been." Warsaw's main daily newspaper, Gazeta Wyborcza, which has close<br>
connections with Solidarity and the Catholic Church in Poland, also tried to<br>
play down the story. <br>
<p>
But Rome is now taking the revelations much more seriously and German church<br>
historian Erwin Gatz has been entrusted with the delicate task of comparing<br>
the Stasi files to the Vatican originals. <br>
<p>
Now Henryk Bosak, a former high-ranking Polish secret service officer, has<br>
revealed that his country's Catholic credentials made possible the<br>
penetration of the Holy See, and he confirmed that his service had spied on<br>
the Vatican during the Cold War. <br>
<p>
In his recently published book, An Officer from the Centre, he states: "The<br>
Polish secret service had its sources within the walls of the Vatican,<br>
including one very highly placed one, who told us all about the Pope's<br>
dialogues and conversations." <br>
<p>
Unfortunately, the positive identification of the traitor at the Pope's side<br>
has been made more difficult by the shrewd decision of General Czeslaw<br>
Kiszczak, the last communist interior minister of Poland, to shred all secret<br>
service files on the Catholic Church in 1989. <br>
<p>
Jerzy Urban, the former communist government spokesman and present editor of<br>
the popular Warsaw satirical weekly Nie, noted in his journal that "since<br>
some 1,800 Polish priests had collaborated with the secret services up to the<br>
change-over to democracy, these shredded documents could have cast<br>
interesting light on the totally unknown face of the church". <br>
<p>
But the popular interest generated by the spy story has been such that, with<br>
the eager help of former secret service officer Bosak, the media have managed<br>
to narrow down the list of potential suspects to three. They are: Father<br>
Tadeusz Pieronek, the secretary of the Polish Bishops Conference, who had a<br>
very cordial relationship with the highest echelons of the Vatican; Father<br>
Tadeusz Rakoczi who served 14 years in an influential position at the Holy<br>
See, and Monsignor Juliusz Paetz, the bishop of Poznan, who served in Rome as<br>
the official go-between between the communist Polish government and the<br>
Vatican for 15 crucial years. <br>
<p>
The evidence is purely circumstantial in each case. <br>
<p>
Certainly, it would not produce a guilty verdict in a Scottish court of law.<br>
Therefore, the unmasking of the Polish mystery man with a double life and the<br>
key to all the secrets of the Vatican must await the final report of the<br>
Gauck Commission, which is sifting through the Stasi files. <br>
<p>
There is, as yet, no known connection between the Polish spy and Mehmet Ali<br>
Agca, the Armenian Turk who attempted to assassinate the Pope in 1981. <br>
<p>
The blame for that has been put on the Bulgarians. <br>
<p>
Unfortunately for the Vatican, the Polish 'James Bond in a cassock' was not<br>
the only cleric to betray the Vicar of Rome. It recently came to light in<br>
Romania that Monsignor Luigi Vitoria Blassuti, the Vicar-General of<br>
Bucharest, had spied on Vatican officials for Romania's secret police, the<br>
Securitate, for 30 years. <br>
<p>
It has now been established that the Romanian cleric was paid by the<br>
Securitate to influence the Vatican's East European appointments, to<br>
discredit dissidents and opponents of the Ceausescu regime, and to mislead<br>
the Vatican about Romania's true intentions towards its Catholic communities.<br>
<p>
<p>
The treacherous Vicar-General of Bucharest would never have been suspected of<br>
such nefarious activities had the Romanians been as efficient as the Poles in<br>
destroying the church files when the murderous Ceausescu regime was toppled. <br>
<p>
But the Securitate's successor, the Romanian Intelligence Service, simply<br>
buried tonnes of old Securitate dossiers in a forest. <br>
<p>
These were dug up by villagers and sold to the press. Thus, the brilliant<br>
career of Monsignor Blassuti - secret police code name Iacobescu - has come<br>
to light. <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
