<title>Groong Network: Russian perspective on Chechen "oil appetite"</title>
<h1>Russian perspective on Chechen "oil appetite"</h1>
Arthur Martirosyan (<i>martiros@hulaw1.harvard.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 18 Dec 1996 11:53:22 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#158">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#158">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#158">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#158">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0159.html">nt-send@nt.arminco.com: "Noyan Tapan News (December 17)"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0157.html">Arthur Martirosyan: "Some items of interest from Russian presss"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
KOMMERSANT-DAILY 18 December 1996 pages 1, 3<br>
<p>
   Report by Georgiy Bovt:  "For Terrorists, 'Druzhba' [Friendship] Comes<br>
First" <br>
<p>
  Yesterday, more bloody news came from Chechnya:  Six employees of the<br>
International Red Cross Committee were killed in the village of Novyye<br>
Atagi.  All of them were foreigners working at a hospital.  Meanwhile, the<br>
controversy around the captured policemen continued:  Security Council<br>
Secretary Ivan Rybkin yesterday arrived in Groznyy to clarify the situation<br>
as Dagestan Security Council Secretary Magomed Talbeyev earlier in the<br>
morning went to the Gudermes district of Chechnya to negotiate with Salman<br>
Raduyev who had captured the policemen.  The reign of terror in Chechnya,<br>
however, will not prevent its leaders from holding negotiations on<br>
international cooperation in, of all places, Japan. <br>
   While Rybkin and Talbeyev try to reason with the kidnappers [preceding<br>
word an English borrow in Cyrillic]  the separatist leaders went to the<br>
Japanese Islands to discuss vast foreign economic plans.  At their press<br>
conference in Tokyo, Khozh-Akhmed Nukhayev, first deputy premier of the<br>
Chechen government; and Ruslan Chimayev, head of the Ichkerian Foreign<br>
Ministry, declared the intention of the Chechen leadership to create an<br>
international consortium with the participation of Ukraine and Poland to<br>
transport oil via Chechnya to Georgia.  The new consortium is, in<br>
particular, to build a pipeline through Ukraine to Poland and is to be<br>
subsequently linked to the Druzhba [Friendship]  oil export pipeline in<br>
order to pump oil going through Chechnya and the Georgian port of Poti.<br>
Mansur Yakhimchik, chief foreign policy adviser in the Chechen government,<br>
told ITAR-TASS that the ambitious idea has already received support "at the<br>
level of Polish and Ukrainian presidents."  It is quite natural considering<br>
that this idea fits well into plans hatched, in particular, in Baku and Kiev.<br>
   The intention is to organize the so-called Eurasian transport corridor,<br>
bypassing Russia.  In the current Chechen interpretation (which is, to all<br>
appearances, shared not only in Groznyy), bypassing Russia means going via<br>
Chechnya.  In the separatists' estimate, their option for transporting, say,<br>
Azerbaijani oil will be some 20 percent cheaper than "a purely Russian<br>
option" (by sea via Novorossiysk and then by pipeline via Bulgaria and<br>
Greece).  Groznyy is also pinning great hopes on a pipeline that could be<br>
extended to the republic's borders from the Tengiz field in Kazakhstan. <br>
   So, the separatists have big plans for oil transit, primarily with<br>
respect to the Caspian International Consortium.  According to Terry Adams,<br>
head of the consortium's action committee, a preliminary route for the<br>
export of "primary" oil from the Azerbaijani sea deposits of Azeri, Chirag,<br>
and Gyuneshli will be approved in May 1997.  As is known, two routes have<br>
been defined for "early" oil: via Russia (Novorossiysk) and Georgia (Poti).<br>
Adams, however, said that at present "two to three route options" are being<br>
discussed: Along with the Baku-Jeihan (Turkey) and Baku-Novorossiysk routes<br>
there is also the possibility (it is also promoted by Moscow) of "bypassing<br>
the Bosphorous" via Burgas (Bulgaria) and Alexandropoulos (Greece).<br>
Earlier, Baku was quite unequivocal in supporting the idea of the Turkish<br>
route.  Ilgam Aliyev, vice president of the State Oil Company of Azerbaijan,<br>
even now indicates that Baku still gives preference to the export of<br>
"primary" oil via Turkey because "the problems involved in accessing Black<br>
Sea ports are well known." Turkey, according to him, fully guarantees the<br>
security of the transportation. <br>
   And still Baku's position is no longer as intransigent as is used to be.<br>
Its readiness to discuss other route options (from the purely commercial<br>
point of view, it is more advantageous to have multiple market accesses --<br>
in particular, in order to knock down transit charges) has become more<br>
conspicuous in connection with at least two circumstances:  The end of the<br>
war in Chechnya and the shuttle diplomacy of Boris Berezovskiy who, among<br>
other things, discussed in Baku Russian oil transit routes.<br>
   The separatists back up their vast plans in the oil transit sphere by<br>
purely bandit-like actions: murders, kidnappings, and other acts of<br>
terrorism.  In this context, for instance, the recent attempts to export the<br>
"Chechen green revolution" to Dagestan should be attributed not only to the<br>
slogans of such outlaws as Raduyev concerning the "reunification of all<br>
Chechen lands," but also this purely pragmatic calculation:  a wish to<br>
scuttle all attempts by Russia to create a transport network and<br>
infrastructure in Dagestan that could make up for the loss of Chechnya.<br>
   The principal novelty of the current "oil" situation is also that the<br>
field commanders, having done the fighting, aspire to roles as active<br>
players in the big-time oil game in the region, seeking to create the<br>
impression that they are open to negotiation.  They have developed certain<br>
contacts, justifying such hopes, back during the war with Azerbaijan and<br>
Turkey.  In principle -- through certain circles -- such contacts could even<br>
be established with Moscow.  From the purely objective point of view, the<br>
Chechen route could even become a compromise between the key players: for<br>
instance, Moscow and Ankara.  Although each of them would in principle like<br>
to have full control.  There is good reason to believe that Turkish Prime<br>
Minister Tansu Ciller, who was yesterday in Moscow, in fact conducted a<br>
delicate conversation on the relations within the Moscow-Groznyy-Ankara<br>
triangle.<br>
   And still, it is rather difficult to ponder objectively and impartially<br>
on Chechnya and its current rulers.  Meanwhile, those who are building<br>
speculative schemes on oil pipelines, transport corridors, and linkages<br>
based on generous infusions from the Russian budget (in the hope that the<br>
Chechen black hole would prove highly lucrative) could be in for a nasty<br>
surprise that will come when these players learn from their own experience:<br>
It is very difficult to come to terms with people who kill doctors from the<br>
Red Cross, and for whom kidnapping and gangsterism have already become a way<br>
of life -- be it Ankara, Moscow, or faraway Tokyo.<br>
(end)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
