<title>Groong Network: Some items of interest from Russian presss</title>
<h1>Some items of interest from Russian presss</h1>
Arthur Martirosyan (<i>martiros@hulaw1.harvard.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 18 Dec 1996 11:45:13 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#157">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#157">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#157">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#157">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0158.html">Arthur Martirosyan: "Russian perspective on Chechen "oil appetite""</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0156.html">Arthur Martirosyan: "From Monitor 18/12/96"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
1. Interview with Magomed Tolboyev, secretary of the Dagestani Security<br>
Council on recent hostage crisis<br>
<p>
2. Interview with Foreign Intelligence Service [SVR] Director Vyacheslav<br>
Trubnikov  <br>
<p>
NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA 18 December 1996 page 3<br>
<p>
   Interview with Magomed Tolboyev, secretary of the Dagestani Security<br>
Council, by Igor Rotar:  "The Execution of Six Doctors Has Become a Crime<br>
Against Humanity.  This Action Is Aimed To Scuttle the Peace Settlement"<br>
<p>
  At the negotiations on the release of the 22 Penza special purpose militia<br>
[OMON] troopers, Dagestan is represented by Security Council Secretary<br>
Magomed Tolboyev.  Your correspondent got in touch with him on the phone.<br>
 [Rotar]  What impression did Raduyev produce on you?<br>
 [Tolboyev]  It is very difficult to negotiate with him.  He has, in effect,<br>
all trumps in his hands, and we have to tread very cautiously, even though<br>
his demands are inadequate, to it mildly.  This person has no doubts about<br>
his force whatsoever.  His confidence stems from, among other things, his<br>
firm belief in the early comeback of Dudayev.  But still, I am sure that we<br>
shall manage to resolve this problem, and all the hostages will be released,<br>
safe and sound. <br>
 [Rotar]  Will Raduyev lay down arms?<br>
 [Tolboyev]  Oh no.  Certainly not.  It is no use even trying to raise this<br>
question with him.<br>
 [Rotar]  Do Raduyev's fighters constitute a serious military force?<br>
 [Tolboyev]  They certainly do.  In Chechnya, familial (like in Dagestan)<br>
and clannish ties are very important.  So, in the Gudermes district, from<br>
which he hails, Raduyev is king and god; he commands an unquestionable<br>
authority.  Whatever might be said, this man has made a name for himself.  <br>
 [Rotar]  Are clashes between Raduyev's fighters and Chechen-Ichkerian armed<br>
forces possible?<br>
 [Tolboyev]  The Chechen-Ichkerian leadership will not do that -- at least<br>
not before elections. <br>
 [Rotar]  Do you think that this latest hostage taking was accidental or<br>
inevitable?   <br>
 [Tolboyev]  There is no question that this particular excess could have<br>
been avoided.  As is known, Raduyev was going to Khasavyurt to take part in<br>
a festival with our Dagestani Checheno-Akkins.  The leaders of Dagestan's<br>
Chechen community knew about that.  Had they warned me, there would have<br>
been no problem.  Now they are themselves upset that they did not do that.<br>
It is another matter that such excesses are also possible in the future.<br>
Especially given that the Gudermes district borders Chechnya.<br>
 [Rotar]  What preventive measures are the Dagestani authorities going to take?<br>
 [Tolboyev]  First of all, of course, the Dagestani border should be beefed<br>
up.  It is another matter that this should have been done much earlier, not<br>
now.  I, for one, spoke about that six years ago.  There is no hope that we<br>
can establish full border control in six months.  Gaps will certainly<br>
remain.  But we are trying to do what is in our power.  Thus, we have made<br>
sure that one regiment from both the 101st and the 205th Russian Brigades<br>
currently being withdrawn from Chechnya stay in Dagestan.  Unfortunately, we<br>
are simply in no position to accommodate more Russian troops.  It is also<br>
very important that Dagestanis do their military service in their republic.<br>
We should like all Russian military units deployed in the republic to be 50<br>
percent manned with Dagestanis.  Self-defense detachments should be formed<br>
in areas bordering Chechnya -- of course, without violating any Russian laws.<br>
(end)<br>
<p>
&lt;=&gt;<br>
NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA 18 December 1996 pages 1, 2<br>
<p>
   Interview with Foreign Intelligence Service [SVR] Director Vyacheslav<br>
Trubnikov by Andrey Poleshchuk under the "Special Services" rubric:  "The<br>
Russian Foreign Intelligence Service Is Second To None in the World.  This<br>
Is the View of SVR Director Vyacheslav Trubnikov, Who Is Planning To<br>
Congratulate the New CIA Director On Assuming Office"<br>
<p>
  [Poleshchuk]  Vyacheslav Ivanovich, a year has passed since you were<br>
appointed to the post of SVR director.  Have you had more grounds for joy<br>
over your successes or disappointment at failures during this period of time?<br>
   [Trubnikov]  There is the following logic to an intelligence service:<br>
The more it knows, the more additional questions arise.  For this reason it<br>
is on rare occasions that an intelligence officer has the feeling of<br>
satisfaction with the results of his work.  As for joys and disappointments,<br>
I would rather speak about life's being saturated with both instead of<br>
trying to assess their proportions.<br>
   Intelligence is a fairly conservative thing, and so it finds evolutionary<br>
measures preferable to drastic ones.  Generally speaking, one should not<br>
forget the old maxim:  God gives one the strength to change what can be<br>
changed; patience, to put up with what cannot be changed; and intelligence,<br>
to distinguish one from the other.  By the way, not so long ago I saw this<br>
maxim pinned to the office wall of one of my Western colleagues -- a prayer<br>
of sorts for every day's work.<br>
   To sum up the results of the SVR's evolution, it has undergone serious<br>
restructuring, its staff has been trimmed, it has become leaner, more<br>
efficient -- I hope not to the detriment of the quality of its work.  We<br>
have relinquished globalism in the way we set our objectives, concentrating<br>
our efforts in the most crucial areas.  The legal framework of our activity<br>
continues to improve -- the federal law "On Foreign Intelligence" was<br>
approved a year ago.  Much has been done to open up the SVR to Russian<br>
society, although the specifics of intelligence operation inevitably place<br>
certain restrictions on our contacts with the press.<br>
   [Poleshchuk]  How do you assess the results of the Russian intelligence<br>
service's performance in 1996?<br>
   [Trubnikov]  The SVR examines the results of its activity every year,<br>
like any state agency or a private firm, checking the realization of its<br>
plans, setting the effort and funds spent against the results achieved.  To<br>
assess the quality of our work in the most general outlines, I can only note<br>
that we are competitive at the international level -- something that far<br>
from all Russian enterprises can boast.  Seriously speaking, what is<br>
important for us is the generally positive assessment of our work by the<br>
country's leadership.  It will be noted for the taxpayer that his money was<br>
not frittered away by the intelligence service for nothing in 1996.<br>
   [Poleshchuk]  It is well known that intelligence successes are classified<br>
as top secret information.  For this reason let me ask you only how many<br>
Yasenevo [SVR seat in Moscow] officers were decorated with state awards<br>
during this passing year?<br>
   [Trubnikov]  I can give you the combined figure -- about 80.  Yet edicts<br>
on giving awards to specific SVR officers who are still in service are, as a<br>
rule, secret in nature and currently we cannot give you this information<br>
without violating the law.  You will have to wait, maybe, for several dozen<br>
years.  I can recall with pride, however, that in the summer of this year as<br>
many as five foreign intelligence veterans were awarded the title of Hero of<br>
Russia by presidential edict for their outstanding contribution to ensuring<br>
our country's security.  Three of them -- Leonid Romanovich Kvasnikov,<br>
Anatoliy Antonovich Yatskov, and Leontina Vladislavovna Cohen (also known as<br>
Helen Kroger), unfortunately, were given this high award only posthumously.<br>
As for Vladimir Borisovich Barkovskiy and Aleksandr Semenovich Feklisov,<br>
although currently in retirement, they are still actively taking part in the<br>
training of young intelligence officers, are engaged in research and<br>
publicist activities.<br>
   Thanks to the efforts of these outstanding intelligence officers -- and<br>
very good and modest people at that -- our country obtained the most crucial<br>
materials on the military use of nuclear energy during the years of World<br>
War II, which enabled it within the shortest possible time to break the<br>
United States' monopoly in the area of nuclear weapons.  This might have<br>
been done later than it should have, but the country finally gave them due<br>
credit for their work.  Our thanks for the restoration of justice go to<br>
Russia and its president, Boris Nikolayevich Yeltsin.<br>
   [Poleshchuk]  When did you last meet with the president?  And who<br>
received reports of the SVR director during his forced absence from the Kremlin?<br>
   [Trubnikov]  I saw him last in July, when I delivered a report personally<br>
to the president.  After that I have not reported personally to anyone, but<br>
information from the SVR has been sent to the prime minister and government<br>
members.  The intelligence service knows very well who needs it and what he<br>
needs from it, and it fully meets the state agencies' requirements.<br>
   [Poleshchuk]  The end of the year was marked by two noisy scandals that<br>
appear to have added a considerable degree of tension to Russian-American<br>
relations, particularly, in the relations between the SVR and the CIA.  I<br>
mean the case of former SVR Colonel Vladimir Galkin and the arrest of Harold<br>
Nicholson, a Langley officer accused of spying for Russia.  First, a ritual<br>
question:  Does the SVR recognize having ever recruited Nicholson?  Second,<br>
what would you say about the theory whereby freedom for Galkin was paid for<br>
by the surrender of Nicholson?  Generally speaking, do you think there is<br>
any connection between these two developments?  Third, what did you think<br>
about the words of John Deutsch, now a former CIA director, who emphasized<br>
at his news conference he gave jointly with his FBI counterpart, Louis<br>
Freeh:  "We should display vigilance with regard to attempts by Russia and<br>
other hostile intelligence services to infiltrate into the structure of<br>
agencies dealing with matters of U.S. national security."  Fourth, how do<br>
you assess the work of the domestic media and the SVR press bureau during<br>
these conflict situations?<br>
   [Trubnikov]  First of all, let me remind you that in keeping with the<br>
practice of all intelligence services around the world the SVR  does not<br>
discuss publicly -- therefore, neither confirms nor denies -- reports<br>
alleging that one Russian citizen or another or citizens of other countries<br>
may have been involved in its operations.<br>
   In the case of former SVR officer Vladimir Galkin, we had to make an<br>
exception from that iron rule, struck as we were by so blatant a<br>
provocation.  The actions of the U.S. special services created a dangerous<br>
precedent for the future, but most important not one Russian citizen should<br>
be left to his own devices without his state's assistance.  The<br>
circumstances of Galkin' release are currently well known all over the<br>
world, and there are no grounds whatsoever for any speculation on that<br>
score.  Galkin's release was the result of concerted actions by Russian<br>
state agencies -- the SVR, Federal Security Service [FSB], and the Foreign<br>
Ministry -- at several levels at that, and, finally, personal intervention<br>
by Viktor Chernomyrdin, chairman of the Russian government, who gave a call<br>
to U.S. Vice President Albert Gore.  We cannot but point out the dignified<br>
and courageous line of conduct in that situation by Galkin himself -- he<br>
flatly rejected all FBI attempts to cajole him into cooperation, thus laying<br>
the firm foundation for measures aimed at securing his release to succeed.<br>
   Calls by the CIA director on American state agencies to step up their<br>
vigilance are a fully normal and understandable phenomenon.  For its part,<br>
the SVR has always called for greater vigilance at Russian state agencies,<br>
where, by the way, things in this regard stand much worse than in the United<br>
States.<br>
   As for assessing the actions of the Russian media, I would like to<br>
express yet another time our heartfelt thanks on behalf of all our<br>
employees.  Support of the official stance by the Russian press, television<br>
and radio, their impartial and competent comments on the gist of the problem<br>
expedited the positive outcome of this case.  We are also pleased with the<br>
way the SVR press bureau was operating during those days.<br>
   [Poleshchuk]  It is an open secret how much money the U.S. government<br>
appropriated to the U.S. intelligence community and, separately, to the CIA<br>
for 1997.  If I am not mistaken, the CIA got more than $3 billion.  As a<br>
taxpayer, I would like to learn the size of the SVR's annual budget, on<br>
which no information has ever been disclosed.  Could you lift this veil of<br>
secrecy over this subject?  And give at least an approximate number of<br>
foreign intelligence officers into the bargain?<br>
   [Trubnikov]  It is not the intelligence service that passed the law on<br>
state secrets, so it is not up to us to disclose the size of our annual<br>
budget or the number of intelligence officers.  As far as we know, the CIA<br>
itself has never officially revealed data relating to its budget or its<br>
payroll.  Yet, knowing the state of our two countries' economies you can<br>
yourself guess the approximate ratio of the Russian special service's<br>
financial, material, and personnel resources to those of its American<br>
counterpart.<br>
   [Poleshchuk]  Who exercises control over the SVR's activity, in what<br>
form, and how often?  How many times have you delivered reports to<br>
Federation Council members and State Duma deputies?<br>
   [Trubnikov]  The current legislation set clear-cut rules of control over<br>
intelligence activity.  This function falls under the jurisdiction of the<br>
president and the parliament of the Russian Federation.  Supervision over<br>
the way the foreign intelligence service complies with federal laws is<br>
exercised by the general prosecutor of the Russian Federation and the<br>
prosecutors he assigns.<br>
   The intelligence service tries to maintain the closest possible contacts<br>
with the Federal Assembly at the most diverse levels.  My deputies and I<br>
meet regularly with representatives of the legislative branch.  Recently we<br>
were audited by the Comptroller's Office.<br>
   [Poleshchuk]  Did the comptrollers find any shortfall?<br>
   [Trubnikov]  There was certain criticism -- not for misappropriations,<br>
but for some mistakes unrelated to the financing of our main activity.  We<br>
have constructive relations with all controlling agencies.  Absolutely all<br>
of them.<br>
   [Poleshchuk]  I would like to dwell on the subject of the SVR's<br>
relationship with non-government organizations.  It is obvious that in<br>
Russia the state authorities have merged with powerful financial groups.<br>
The consequences of this process probably cannot but affect the domestic<br>
special services, including the foreign intelligence service.  It is no<br>
secret that the so-called information-analysis services, administration,<br>
departments, and so forth, which operate within large banks, groups, and<br>
corporations are essentially but intelligence and counterintelligence<br>
agencies.  Highly professional ones at that, because they are for the most<br>
part staffed with former officers of Russian special services.  Many of them<br>
have not only retained their ties with their former colleagues at the FSB,<br>
Federal Government Communications and Information Agency [FAPSI], Main<br>
Intelligence Directorate [GRU], the Internal Affairs Ministry, and so forth,<br>
but they try to engage them in cooperation.  Do you make provision for this<br>
circumstance when organizing work to ensure your own security?<br>
   [Trubnikov]  Yes, of course, the SVR leadership takes into account the<br>
threat of unauthorized information leaks outside the intelligence service.<br>
There are temptations that are based on the very inadequate pay we get for<br>
our work.  This is our headache, something with which the intelligence<br>
service leadership has always fought and will always fight.  We proceed from<br>
the assumption that foreign intelligence services cannot participate in<br>
domestic competitive struggles.  We shall not help one bank make money at<br>
the expense of another.  This is not our business.  It is another matter if<br>
the interests of our Central Bank are at stake when it seeks more profitable<br>
terms of investing capital abroad -- here we do have our say.<br>
   [Poleshchuk]  Some time ago the press actively discussed the possibility<br>
of creating a Russian intelligence community, whose operation, modeled on<br>
U.S. experience, should be coordinated and guided by the foreign<br>
intelligence director.  At the time we learned your skeptical attitude to<br>
this idea.  Have you not changed your views?<br>
   [Trubnikov]  The idea of setting up the Russian intelligence community<br>
has been periodically put forward by the political and government circles of<br>
our country; in so doing various advocates of this idea sometimes pursue<br>
diametrically opposed objectives, which often have nothing to do with<br>
intelligence itself.  In the end, it is always not the appearance, but the<br>
essence that matters.  At present the objectives of intelligence activity<br>
are set by the president of the Russian Federation.  The SVR is represented<br>
on the Security Council and the Defense Council, it participates in the work<br>
of various interagency groups and commissions.  The coordination of<br>
operations by various intelligence services of the country is carried out on<br>
the basis of bilateral agreements and existing working contacts.<br>
Definitely, this system can and should be improved, but this should be done<br>
in a thought-out manner, putting above anything else the objective of<br>
improving its effectiveness and saving human and material resources.  As for<br>
yet another state bureaucratic structure modeled on foreign patterns, we do<br>
not need it.  In the meantime, the existence of an intelligence community in<br>
the United States is, in my view, predetermined first and foremost by the<br>
aggressive orientation of U.S. special services, which concentrated<br>
three-fourths of their efforts on the territory of the USSR.<br>
   [Poleshchuk]  Did Aleksandr Korzhakov, former chief of the Presidential<br>
Security Service, try, if not to bring the SVR under his control, then at<br>
least engage its assistance in order to realize what was reportedly his<br>
overriding idea of creating an intelligence super-service?<br>
   [Trubnikov]  As for Aleksandr Vasilyevich Korzhakov in person, my answer<br>
will be unequivocal and short:  He did not.  Yet this idea has periodically<br>
resurfaced, coming from the entrails of the Russian state apparatus.<br>
Undoubtedly, both the joint and separate existence of intelligence and<br>
counterintelligence services has its pros and cons.  In 1991, however, a<br>
crucial choice was made in favor of the SVR's independent existence, and<br>
currently we think that, on the whole, taking account of all these pros and<br>
cons, everyone -- both the intelligence service and the Russian state<br>
apparatus -- have benefited from that.  The main thing is that for the first<br>
time since our inception we were given the opportunity of direct access to<br>
the country's leadership, to whom we can report information without the<br>
filters or censorship of our superiors within a joint agency.<br>
   When such questions are discussed, one should also not forget the fact<br>
that any large-scale reorganization will automatically disrupt the normal<br>
operation of all special services participating in it for a long period of time.<br>
  [Polishchuk]  At all times in various countries there have always been<br>
certain contradictions between the intelligence and counterintelligence<br>
services.  Do tensions arise between the SVR and the FSB?<br>
   [Trubnikov]  We do have certain contradictions and tensions with the<br>
counterintelligence services of other countries.  As for the FSB, we<br>
maintain good, close working and personal contacts with our<br>
counterintelligence officers.  We are not just colleagues, we are comrades.<br>
All problems that might arise are resolved within the framework of<br>
agreements our agencies sign.  As has already been noted, the FSB's stance<br>
largely expedited Galkin's release, and we are sincerely grateful for that.<br>
   [Polishchuk]  What has happened to the series of the so-called open SVR<br>
reports on the most urgent problems of our time?<br>
   [Trubnikov]  This series will be continued.  Given the interest our<br>
previous reports have generated in this country and abroad we do not want to<br>
spend our efforts on trifles, and for this reason we are now particularly<br>
careful in selecting subjects for further publication.<br>
   [Polishchuk]  One of the reports that has already been published set<br>
forth the SVR's fairly tough stance on NATO expansion.  Has it changed?<br>
   [Trubnikov]  No, it has remained just as tough and it fully corresponds<br>
to that of the Foreign Ministry.  We are categorically opposed to NATO<br>
expansion.  This does not and cannot suit us!  Such is the presidential<br>
directive.<br>
   [Polishchuk]  It is considered inappropriate to report the SVR director's<br>
meetings and talks as well as his foreign trips.  Could you violate this<br>
taboo today and give us a brief account of the work you have done in this area?<br>
   [Trubnikov]  To maintain contacts with various intelligence and<br>
counterintelligence services of foreign states is one of the new and fastest<br>
growing areas in our activity.  It is a matter of collaboration on the basis<br>
of the strict accounting of Russian national interests -- naturally, our<br>
partners, too, proceed exclusively from the interests of their countries.<br>
Priority issues during such contacts are the problems of combating such<br>
international threats as the threat of the proliferation of weapons of mass<br>
destruction, international terrorism, drug trafficking and illicit arms<br>
trade, and the search for and release of hostages as well as citizens of<br>
Russia and CIS countries who are reported missing.  Meetings of intelligence<br>
service chiefs are undoubtedly useful, if only because they enable us to<br>
become better acquainted with one another and to avoid unnecessary<br>
complications in the future due to the absence of the right understanding of<br>
the other party's intentions, since we have by no means ceased our main<br>
activity.  As for me, I have visited eight countries during this past year.<br>
   [Polishchuk]  Anthony Lake was appointed the new CIS director.  Is it<br>
appropriate for intelligence service chiefs to congratulate each other on<br>
the occasion of assuming office or to send best wishes when they resign?<br>
   [Trubnikov]  Yes, it is.  When Mr. Lake officially assumes office, I will<br>
undoubtedly send him a congratulatory telegram.  Even if the previous CIA<br>
director, Mr. Deutsch, did not think it necessary to congratulate me on my<br>
new appointment.<br>
   [Polishchuk]  Who do you think forms the club of the world's top<br>
intelligence services?<br>
   [Trubnikov]  The Russian Foreign Intelligence Service is second to none!<br>
Next comes Britain's SIS and Israel's Mossad.<br>
   [Polishchuk]  The dream of any intelligence service of the world is to<br>
infiltrate its mole into the central staff of its opposite numbers.  To all<br>
appearances, the Russian intelligence service, the SVR in particular, has<br>
been quite successful in that.  Your opponents are surely not sitting on<br>
their hands either.  How does the SVR currently ensure its own security?<br>
   [Trubnikov]  This is a very serious problem, and one can never say that<br>
everything possible has been done to ensure security or that we are secured<br>
against emergencies in this regard.  I can only emphasize that the SVR<br>
leadership keeps this aspect of our activity under its unremitting control.<br>
For understandable reasons I cannot go into detail.<br>
   [Polishchuk]  From time to time journalists return to the fate of Aldrich<br>
Ames, a former CIA officer and one of the most valuable "moles" in the<br>
history of international espionage.  It is well known that the U.S. court<br>
sentenced Ames to life imprisonment without the right of pardon for his ties<br>
with Moscow.  The U.S. Congress passed the law called "Debt of Honor" ["Dolg<br>
chesti"], which guarantees comprehensive assistance to the families of KGB<br>
and GRU officers who were executed by firing-squad according to Ames' leads.<br>
Has the SVR done anything to ameliorate his fate?  Does it give any<br>
assistance to the Ames family?  Can there arise a realistic situation where<br>
talks on exchanging Aldrich Ames could begin?<br>
   [Trubnikov]  You have finally forced me to quote our press bureau's<br>
formula:  The SVR does not discuss such matters.  We get information on the<br>
situation in which Ames and his wife, who is also in jail, have found<br>
themselves from Western media, because Russian journalists have not yet<br>
spoken to Ames.<br>
   Americans have a penchant for affectation and posturing, for this reason<br>
they pass laws without taking into consideration whether or not members of<br>
the families of KGB and GRU officers who were found guilty of espionage want<br>
this assistance.  We think that all factors should be taken into account in<br>
so sensitive a case.<br>
   [Polishchuk]  Some time ago a statement was made to the effect that the<br>
SVR will no longer use the journalistic profession as a cover for its<br>
officers.  Is this really so?<br>
   [Trubnikov]  I'd rather not tell you something that is untrue.<br>
(end)<br>
<p>
