<title>Groong Network: NeGa interview with Vazgen Manukian</title>
<h1>NeGa interview with Vazgen Manukian</h1>
Arthur Martirosyan (<i>martiros@hulaw1.harvard.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 18 Dec 1996 01:36:59 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#154">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#154">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#154">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#154">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0155.html">vahe@arminco.com: "Aragil Headlines, 12/18/96"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0153.html">Arthur Martirosyan: "Turkey and Russia: is a deal on Kurdish problem possible?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
            NEZAVISIMAIA GAZETA: No.236 12/17/96<br>
<p>
OPPOSITION OFFERS NEW ELECTIONS<br>
<p>
By Yekaterina Sytaya<br>
<p>
_Armenia_=20<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;From NG=92s folder:</i><br>
<p>
Vazgen Manukian was born in 1946. In 1963 he was admitted to Yerevan State<br>
University. In 1966 he was transferred to Moscow State University but after<br>
he participated in a demonstration of protest at the embassy of Turkey in<br>
Moscow he was forced to go back. Manukian graduated from Yerevan State and<br>
got his Ph.D. in mathematics and physics from the Novosibirsk branch of the<br>
USSR Academy of Sciences. In July 1988 he became the coordinator of the<br>
Karabakh Committee. On December 10, 1988 he along with other Karabakh<br>
Committee activists was arrested and spent six months in the Matrosskaya<br>
tishina (Sailors=92 Silence) prison. In 1989 he was elected an honorable<br>
citizen of the city of Grenoble, France. He was the first Chairman if the<br>
Board of the ANM.  In 1990 he was elected to the Supreme Soviet of Armenia.<br>
In 1991 Manukian was Prime Minister, In 1992-1993 acting Minister of<br>
Defense. Today he is the leader of one of the major opposition parties NDU<br>
(National Democratic Union).   =20<br>
<p>
__ On the eve of presidential elections five opposition parties of Armenia<br>
united and supported you as the candidate for elections. Are there any<br>
chances that the electoral coalition will become a political bloc?  =20<br>
<p>
__ We united for the term of elections and six months after elections. We<br>
hoped to conduct new fair and free elections to the National Assembly and a<br>
referendum on the new Basic Law of Armenia. New Constitution  would balance<br>
branches of power in Armenia by limiting the executive, presidential power,<br>
and reinforcing the legislative power, the parliament. Upon resolving these<br>
problems, each party of the electoral coalition would go back to individual<br>
political  activity according to economic and political program. Truly<br>
democratic countries have a bright palette of political colors. In<br>
pseudo-democracies colors are black and white. In the events of September 25<br>
it was not only the opposition and its supporters who gathered near the<br>
parliament but also those who voted  for Levon Ter-Petrosyan.  They, too,<br>
demanded that the results of elections be verified.  When authorities and<br>
nation form antagonistic relations opposition easily unites.   Elements that<br>
differentiate opposition parties become insignificant before  common tasks.<br>
<p>
On September 25-26, formally,  no changes took place in Armenia but the<br>
nation came to realize that it lives not in a democratic country. The only<br>
mechanism which can change this situation is new elections. It is hard even<br>
to utter words like "uprising" today, but, as many see it in Armenia, all<br>
democratic methods of struggle have been exhausted.  =20<br>
<p>
__ You have returned to your party=92s office which was sealed after=<br>
 September<br>
events. Does not this mean that the authorities have made the first step<br>
towards a dialogue and democracy?=20<br>
<p>
__ The process of transition to democracy in Armenia as in the entire Soviet<br>
Union began in 1988 and then Armenia was ahead of all other Republics. The<br>
problem of Karabakh forced our society to concentrate attention on political<br>
issues. As early as in 1988 we had elected to the Supreme Soviet four<br>
members of the opposition movement. The ANM came to power in Armenia in 1990<br>
as a result of democratic elections. In 1991 the election of Levon<br>
Ter-Petrosyan became a further step towards democracy.=20<br>
Now Armenia is sliding back. In 1995 elections to the National Assembly were<br>
falsified. The majority of the nation was reluctant about participation in<br>
presidential elections as authorities were imposing the view that the<br>
results were pre-determined. Many parties wanted to boycott elections. I<br>
took the responsibility of calling on others to try to change things once<br>
again by a democratic procedure.  In my opinion, Levon Ter-Petrosyan<br>
suffered an excruciating defeat in the elections. After the defeat he and<br>
his entourage did everything in their capacity to cling to power. We are in<br>
a dead alley of some kind now =96 the mechanism of elections is not trusted=<br>
 by<br>
the people. Under the circumstances the choices are wither to become<br>
enslaved by the regime or to rise against it. Both choices are unacceptable.<br>
That=92s why we are discussing another option. We think that the story is=<br>
 not<br>
over yet and we offer new presidential elections. If we can achieve that,<br>
then the concession of authorities will open a possibility for negotiations<br>
to find new gentlemen rules of the game and get back to the road towards<br>
democracy.=20<br>
<p>
__How realistic is that the power holders will ever agree to new elections?=<br>
=20<br>
<p>
__They will be forced to. That depends not only on us, but also on external<br>
conditions =96 what will they be for Armenia? Currently, there is an erosion<br>
of power in Armenia. Everybody understands that  Levon Ter-Petrosyan was not<br>
elected and as a result the gradually it becomes more difficult to run the<br>
country.  This can force authorities to start a dialogue on new elections.<br>
But a dialogue on sharing power we consider absurd. =20<br>
Had the view of Europarliament been expressed by one country or a group of<br>
countries, one could have concluded that the view was biased by ulterior<br>
interests in the region (NeGa: The resolution of Europarliament from<br>
November 14 put under suspicion results of elections and demanded runoffs in<br>
the precincts where violations of electoral law were registered.)  However,<br>
the resolution of Europarliament is general. European deputies do want to<br>
see Armenia democratic. Unfortunately, their opinions were not taken<br>
seriously in Armenia.  It was clear that the Constitutional Court under this<br>
regime could not arrive at a fair ruling but we still decided to apply as we<br>
were pursuing three goals: this gave Ter-Petrosyan and his entourage a<br>
face-saving opportunity to find an honorable exit from this situation since<br>
the illegitimacy of power is limiting Armenia=92s capabilities; it was an<br>
opportunity for us to present our views to the nation and to demonstrate how<br>
elections were falsified; and we had to try all democratic methods available<br>
despite their limitations.  =20<br>
<p>
--When did a discord begin between you and Ter-Petrosyan? After all you were<br>
so close both in Karabakh movement and in the ANM?=20<br>
<p>
__In 1988 I led the Karabakh Committee and started to invite new people.<br>
Among them was Ter-Petrosyan whom I did not know well before that. When in<br>
two years we came to power Armenia was not a presidential republic.<br>
Ter-Petrosyan was the Chairman of the parliament and I headed the<br>
government.  We did not have any political or economic bones of contention<br>
(he did not know anything in economics, anyway). Eventually I  walked out<br>
against my own team which had as a goal clinging to power at any cost. I<br>
could not but resign. In a sense we had a bourgeois revolution in Armenia<br>
and advanced ideas and concepts of private property but many of our friends<br>
gradually became interested only in personal wealth.  To the date by and<br>
large only members of that same team continue to get wealthier  in Armenia<br>
by using levers of power which they obtained only accidentally. =20<br>
<p>
-- In the post-Soviet space generally proponents of market economy are<br>
opposed to by people of less democratic political inclinations. In Armenia<br>
the situation seems to be unique. Why then confrontation resulted in<br>
introduction of troops after elections?<br>
<p>
In the US Democrats and Republicans are both for private property and free<br>
market. Their ideas too coincide by and large. In Russia, the "Gorbachev<br>
revolution" touche only two-three major cities whereas the heartland<br>
remained Communist in structure and in mentality. In Armenia the struggle<br>
for power is not between Communists and democrats but between democrats and<br>
pseudo-democrats.   The role of Communists in Armenia is really marginal =96<br>
their leader got only 6% of votes. As an ideology Communism was always weak<br>
in Armenia and since 1988 it broke beyond repair against Karabakh movement.<br>
Certainly, people feel nostalgic about the past but that is only because<br>
people want the state to play a larger role in protecting their social<br>
rights.  Armenian Communists today are speaking about restoration of the<br>
USSR. But that is against economic and political interests of Russia.=20<br>
<p>
__ There are however some other forms of cooperation. What is your take on<br>
Armenia=92s participation in integration processes. =20<br>
<p>
__To restore the Armenian industry we need economic levers. We can restore<br>
our economic potential to 20-30% by entering the common economic space but<br>
remaining an independent country. CIS integrational processes are extremely<br>
important for us. I think not a single former Soviet country can re-build<br>
its economic capacity without that integration.  But integration shall not<br>
be a result of some short-term  political interests when leaders of CIS<br>
countries exploiting the feeling of nostalgia of their respective<br>
populations sign meaningless documents.  Besides, to restore the economy<br>
Armenia needs large scale investments. Today we do not really know what<br>
happens to the IMF credits. Armenian economic progress is possible only<br>
under conditions of political democracy. If we find common economic<br>
interests with other CIS countries in developing our economies and creating<br>
jobs, we shall pursue such cooperation which will ultimately improve<br>
standards of living.   (Yerevan-Moscow) (end)=20<br>
(Translated by AM)<br>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
"The most common form of human stupidity is=20<br>
forgetting what one is trying to do."=20<br>
<p>
Friedrich Nietzsche<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
