<title>Groong Network: Turkey and Russia: is a deal on Kurdish problem possible?</title>
<h1>Turkey and Russia: is a deal on Kurdish problem possible?</h1>
Arthur Martirosyan (<i>martiros@hulaw1.harvard.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 17 Dec 1996 23:44:49 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#153">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#153">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#153">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#153">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0154.html">Arthur Martirosyan: "NeGa interview with Vazgen Manukian"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0152.html">ASBAREZ-ON-LINE: "ASBAREZ-ON-LINE [12-17-96]"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
            NEZAVISIMAIA GAZETA: No.236 12/17/96<br>
<p>
<p>
TURKEY MAY OFFER A POLITICAL DEAL TO RUSSIA<br>
<p>
By Dmitrii Chernogorskii<br>
<p>
_Diplomacy_<br>
<p>
Today Vice Prime Minister and Foreign Affairs Minister of Turkey, Ms. Tansu<br>
Ciller is arriving in Russia. She was invited to visit Moscow by her<br>
opposite number, Evgenii Primakov. However, taking into consideration the<br>
experience of her previous numerous meetings with Prime  Minister<br>
Chernomyrdin in the capacity of Turkish Prime Minister, one may suggest that<br>
this time, too, conversations won=92t be limited by the protocol -- several<br>
Russian-Turkish agreements have been prepared for signing. =20<br>
<p>
Despite statements of the Turkish side that the bulk of the time will be<br>
devoted to economic issues, it is clear that some political problems in<br>
relations with Moscow of a serious concern to Ankara will be discussed.<br>
Among these problems one of the acute ones is the Kurdish problem. As<br>
previously, Tansu Ciller may try to secure the support of the Turkish<br>
position by the Russian Federation.  It is most probable that in exchange<br>
Moscow may ask assistance of Turkey in the dialogue with NATO against<br>
expansion plans of the alliance. This data was provided to NG shortly before<br>
the visit by well informed sources close to the PKK leadership which is<br>
fighting against the Turkish authorities.  The biased and highly negative<br>
attitude of these sources to the Turkish government is obvious. But it is<br>
quite logical to assume that such a scenario cannot be ruled out, the more<br>
so because Turkey and Russia are irreconcilable competitors, if not<br>
opponents, for spheres of influence in southern Russian border areas =96<br>
Transcaucasia and Central Asia. The competition has been increasingly tense<br>
in the recent years. =20<br>
<p>
Lately Turkey has been a target of harsh criticism from the USA and a number<br>
of European countries as well as international organizations for its abysmal<br>
human rights record in the areas of compact Kurdish settlements. The<br>
European Parliament has suspended $450 million credit line to Ankara and the<br>
decision on acceptance of Turkey to EU has been postponed to the year 2000.<br>
The military campaign of the Turkish government  against Kurdish separatist<br>
fighters has a negative impact on the economy of Turkey which in its turn<br>
scares foreign investors.=20<br>
<p>
Under the circumstances, Turkey may try to play the Russian card. Firstly,<br>
natural gas supplies from Russia may somewhat improve economic conditions.<br>
Secondly, the Western attention may be again attracted to the Turkish<br>
position on the Kurdish problem. =20<br>
<p>
Meanwhile Ciller=92s assurances that Turkey is opposed to NATO=92s expansion=<br>
 can<br>
hardly be sincere.  Lobbying Russian interests in Brussels is only a<br>
tactical step of the Turkish leadership albeit Ankara may even make some<br>
public statements on that issue. However, Russia=92s rejection of contacts<br>
with Kurds and recognition of their struggle as a terrorist activity may<br>
only result in the loss of Moscow=92s influence on a rather large Kurdish<br>
nation. It will not reinforce positions of Moscow in the dialogue with NATO<br>
but will deprive Moscow of maneuvering space against Ankara.=20<br>
<p>
Certainly, the importance of a country like Turkey and the need in a<br>
constructive cooperation with that country shall not be mollified. But it<br>
would not be expedient to make concessions on Russia=92s long-term interests<br>
even if those interests  are contrary to the positions of the partner in a<br>
dialogue. (end)  (Translated by AM)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
