<!-- body="start" -->
ASBAREZ ON LINE <br>
12/17/1996<br>
<p>
<p>
1. COURT TRANSCRIPT ISSUING DELAYS "DRO" APPEAL PROCESS<br>
2. ARMS HANDED OVER VOLUTARILY, DEFENDANT TESTIFIES<br>
3. UNEMPLOYMENT RISES IN ARMENIA<br>
4. ARMENIAN ARTISTS EXHIBIT IN CAIRO FESTIVAL<br>
5. NEGOTIATIONS TO RESUME AFTER ELECTION OF MINSK CO-CHAIRMAN<br>
6. NAYIRIT PLANT HEAD OPPOSED TO SALE THROUGH AUCTION<br>
7. ARMENIANS ARRESTED ON POLAND-GERMANY BORDER<br>
8. SCOUTING LEADERSHIP SEMINAR CONVENES IN AUSTRALIA<br>
9. HEANEY HEADLINES READING IN SUPPORT OF ARMENIAN POETS<br>
<p>
<p>
1. COURT TRANSCRIPT ISSUING DELAYS "DRO" APPEAL PROCESS<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Combined Sources)-Delays in processing the official court <br>
transcripts raised concerns over the deadline to file an appeal <br>
regarding the so-called "Dro" trial.<br>
	Upon handing down the maximum allowable sentences, presiding <br>
Judge Edward Manoukian announced last Tuesday that defense <br>
attorneys had one week to appeal the decision. <br>
	However, according to an Armenpress correspondent, the <br>
defense attorneys received the court transcripts of the sentencing <br>
phase  Tuesday, one day before the Wednesday  deadline set by the <br>
court.<br>
	According to Armenpress, the delay in transcribing and <br>
distributing the court records was due to a lack of modern <br>
technology. Supreme Court clerks still use manual typewriters for <br>
transcription, Armenpress said.<br>
	Three defendants received death sentences, while others in <br>
the so-called "Dro" group trial were sentenced to three to 15-year <br>
prison terms, as the trial ended last Tuesday with Armenias <br>
Supreme Court determining that the alleged clandestine terrorist <br>
group had no links to the Armenian Revolutionary Federation.<br>
	The court handed down death sentences to defendants Arsen <br>
Ardzrouni, Armen Grigorian and Armenak Munjoyan. The remaining <br>
defendants were sentenced in the following manner: Armen Zakarian, <br>
15 years; Hovik Mkrtchian, 10 years; Ara Harmandarian, six years; <br>
Edik Simonian, five years; Tatul Gabrielian and Gevork <br>
Alahverdian, three years each.<br>
	The court found that a group involved with so-called <br>
"banditism" engaged in drug trafficking and planned and executed <br>
the assassinations known as "Top 1" and "Kerop" operations, as a <br>
result of which Gagik Sahakian, Ashot Nercissian and his wife were <br>
murdered.<br>
	The court also found that ARF leader and Karabakh liberation <br>
movement organizer Hrand Markarian was in no way tied to the so-<br>
called "Dro" group, and thus was cleared of those charges. <br>
However, Markarian was sentenced to five years in prison on <br>
illegal weapons possession and forged documentation charges.<br>
	Co-defendant Gegham Manoukian was sentenced to three years <br>
in jail as an accessory.<br>
	The court found no direct links between Markarian and the <br>
so-called "Dro" group, thus absolving any alleged ties between the <br>
ARF and the purported clandestine group, although, according to <br>
initial charges the ARF-"Dro" relations  were conducted solely by <br>
Markarian. <br>
<p>
<p>
2. ARMS HANDED OVER VOLUTARILY, DEFENDANT TESTIFIES<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-Co-defendants Gevork Gazarian, Ofik Assikian <br>
and Gagik Assikian, who had been charged with illegal possession <br>
of weapons in the "Trial of 31," said they had voluntarily handed <br>
over their weapons to the military police.<br>
	According to the court documents, these weapons were stored <br>
in Karapet Gazarians house during the meeting on the eve of the <br>
alleged coup. After the arrest of Manvel Yeghiazarian, commander <br>
of "Arapo" detachment, the weapons were reportedly taken to  Ofik <br>
Assikian-an acquaintance of one of the participants of the <br>
meeting.<br>
	Her co-defendants said Ofik Assikian voluntarily handed over <br>
the weapons to the military police, and Arthur Gazarian, another <br>
defendant, had also intended to do the same. It was revealed in <br>
court that Gazarian had never talked to the other defendants about <br>
a military coup.<br>
	According to the evidence, the defendants were detained and <br>
taken to a Mashtots regional police station. Gevork Gazarian and <br>
Gagik Assikian were in police custody for 72 hours without being <br>
formally charged.<br>
	According to Ofik Assikian, Vladik Karapetian, "was beaten <br>
and disfigured." Assikian and her son Gagik spent four months in <br>
custody, while Gevork Gazarian spent three months in custody. They <br>
were later released and advised not to leave the country.<br>
	The defendants said they had no information regarding the <br>
missing machine guns.<br>
<p>
<p>
3. UNEMPLOYMENT RISES IN ARMENIA<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-As of Dec. 1, 1996, 156,909 people were <br>
unemployed in Armenia, of whom 48,237 live in Yerevan. Deputy <br>
Minister of Social Security Stepan Hayrapetian said that women <br>
make up 72 percent of the unemployed.<br>
	There were 131,705 unemployed people in Armenia on Jan. 1, <br>
1996. According to Hayrapetian, if compared to the previous year, <br>
the rise in unemployment was insignificant. The unemployment rate <br>
is currently 9.2 percent.<br>
	People between the ages of 30-50 make up the largest sector <br>
of the unemployed (71,625).<br>
<p>
<p>
4. ARMENIAN ARTISTS EXHIBIT IN CAIRO FESTIVAL<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-Armenian artists Aram Issabekian, Samvel <br>
Hambartsoumian and Ara Hayatsian and sculptor Albert Avetissian <br>
took part in the sixth international art festival in Cairo, Egypt.<br>
	Since Sunday, each of the artists have exhibited three of <br>
their works-paintings and sculptures-in the halls of the Cairo <br>
National Arts Center.<br>
<p>
<p>
5. NEGOTIATIONS TO RESUME AFTER ELECTION OF MINSK CO-CHAIRMAN<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Respublica Armenia)-The next round of negotiations for <br>
the resolution of the Karabakh conflict will be delayed until a <br>
new candidate for the position of co-chairman of the Organization <br>
for Security and Cooperation in Europe Minsk Group is found, <br>
Russian mediator to the Group Yuri Yukalov said.<br>
	According to Yukalov, the problem will probably be resolved <br>
before the new year. He did not say whether military operations <br>
will resume under the current situation.<br>
	"I dont believe that the situation will last much longer," <br>
he said, and added that the opposition in Azerbaijan has called <br>
for a military/political resolution of the conflict. "We are <br>
interested in the official opinion of Azerbaijan, which is in <br>
favor of the continuation of negotiations," Yukalov concluded.<br>
<p>
<p>
6. NAYIRIT PLANT HEAD OPPOSED TO SALE THROUGH AUCTION<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Azg/Fact)-According to a new privatization program, the <br>
Armenian government plans to sell 16 large companies, including <br>
the Nayirit Rubber Plant, a joint stock company, through an <br>
international auction.<br>
	Selling the plant through an international auction would be <br>
a great mistake, and the government is making the wrong decision, <br>
since the largest companies in the world will do their best to buy <br>
Nayirit and shut it down, Gevork Nersissian, head of the plant, <br>
said.<br>
	According to Nersissian, Nayirit is a national wealth, and <br>
it is not right to sell it for a small amount of money which may <br>
have significant negative results for the whole country in the <br>
future.<br>
<p>
<p>
7. ARMENIANS ARRESTED ON POLAND-GERMANY BORDER<br>
<p>
WARSAW (Azg, Fact)-Sixteen Armenian citizens, including six <br>
children, were arrested by Polish authorities in an attempt to <br>
illegally cross the German border.<br>
	Polish sources reported that the 16 Armenians were traveling <br>
in a Volkswagen bus. The driver was also arrested.<br>
<p>
<p>
8. SCOUTING LEADERSHIP SEMINAR CONVENES IN AUSTRALIA<br>
<p>
SYDNEY-Homenetmen scout leaders from throughout the Diaspora <br>
gathered in Australia Saturday for the third Pan-Homenetmen <br>
Scouting Leadership Conference at Sydneys Payton Paul <br>
campgrounds.<br>
	Twenty-eight participants from the United States, Canada, <br>
Lebanon, Syria, Argentina, England, Jordan, Iran and Australia <br>
were present at the conference organized by the Homenetmen Central <br>
Executive, which was represented by four members.<br>
	The organization of the camp was entrusted to the Homenetmen <br>
Australia Regional Executive and Garbis Kabasakalian was named <br>
director of the 10-day seminar.<br>
	The official opening ceremonies of the camp took place at 3 <br>
p.m. local time with a flag ceremony, and opening remarks were <br>
made by Kabasakalian and Homenetmen Central Executive vice-<br>
president Varoujan Seropian.<br>
	At the onset of the seminar, each region presented a <br>
synopsis of its regional activities and a background on the <br>
Homenetmen organization in each region. The participants were then <br>
taken to the Armenian Cultural Centre for a reception, which was <br>
attended by Australian Prelate Archbishop Aghan Baliozian, <br>
chairman of Australias Minority Council Stepan Kirkyasharian, <br>
representative of New South Whales governor parliamentarian John <br>
Watkins, Armenian Revolutionary Federation At-Large Committee <br>
chairmen Panos Manjian, Australian Scouting Council <br>
representatives Kate Stringfellow and Row Pate, as well as <br>
Homenetmen Australian Regional Executive chairman Berdj Momdjian <br>
and Scout leader Levon Balkabanian.<br>
	All praised the role of the Homenetmen in the international <br>
scouting movement and emphasized the importance of its activities <br>
for the enhancement and longevity of the Armenian nation.<br>
	In his remarks, Seropian emphasized the Homenetmens role in <br>
the process of including Armenias Scouting Association by the <br>
International Scouting Association. He also thanked the Australian <br>
Scouting Organization and the Homenetmen Regional Executive.<br>
	The conference is scheduled to conclude on Dec. 23.<br>
	Participating from the Homenetmen Western USA were Vartug <br>
Yaghmourian, Harut Madenian, Shogher Kassardjian, Aline Aghababian <br>
and Armine Mendzikian.<br>
	The Homenetmen has been an active entity in the <br>
international athletic and scouting movements and has represented <br>
Armenia internationally.<br>
<p>
<p>
9. HEANEY HEADLINES READING IN SUPPORT OF ARMENIAN POETS<br>
<p>
CAMBRIDGE, Mass.-Making a statement for increased support and <br>
backing of Armenian poets and writers currently living abroad, <br>
some 500 people gathered at Harvard University Dec. 2 on the <br>
occasion of a Benefit Reading for the Armenian Writers Union <br>
Publication Fund. <br>
	The event was sponsored by the New England Poetry Club and <br>
the Harvard Advocate. The guest readers of the evening were James <br>
Tate, Pulitzer Prize winner, and Seamus Heaney, Nobel Prize <br>
laureate in Literature in 1995.<br>
	The evening began with a welcome by Diana Der-Hovanessian, <br>
poet and president of the New England Poetry Club, and an <br>
introduction by Christopher Lydon, radio talk show host on WBUR in <br>
Boston, who connected the founding of the New England Poetry Club <br>
in 1915 to the beginning of the Armenian Genocide, when in April <br>
of the same year 200 Armenian poets were assembled and murdered in <br>
Istanbul. <br>
	He stressed the importance for the support of poets in <br>
Armenia, and read several poems written by modern Armenian poets <br>
and translated into English by Der-Hovanessian.<br>
	Carolyn Mugar, president of the Armenian Assembly, read <br>
modern poetry by women Armenian poets which were also translated <br>
by Diana Der-Hovanessian.<br>
	Lydon then introduced the first guest speaker, James Tate, <br>
Professor of English at the University of Massachusetts. Tate read <br>
many poems from his repertoire, including "A Knock on the Door," <br>
"Where Babies Come From," "Days of Pie and Coffee," "The <br>
Definition of Gardening," and "Dream On." His poetry, touched with <br>
a flair of humor and, at times, surrealism, was well received by <br>
the audience. <br>
	Tates books of poetry include Selected Poems published in <br>
1991, for which he was awarded the Pulitzer Prize and the William <br>
Carlos Williams Award, and most recently, Worshipful Company of <br>
Fletchers.<br>
	Seamus Heaney, Professor of Rhetoric at Harvard University, <br>
followed as the last reader of the evening. <br>
	He began first by explaining his inspiration from an <br>
Armenian poet who wrote the poem "Journey to Armenia," dealing <br>
with the return to the senses and the overcoming of writers block <br>
while living in the Soviet Union during the 1920s. <br>
	The poet traveled to Armenia in order to conquer the <br>
repression of his instincts and conscience, and wrote the poem <br>
thereafter. Heaney was first introduced to Armenian poetry and the <br>
plight of the Armenians by his friend, Professor and poet Peter <br>
Balakian.<br>
	Heaney read many of his poems including "Two Lauries," "The <br>
Lupines," "The Key," "The Guttural Muse," and his own translation <br>
from Old English of the last 50 lines from the epic poem <br>
"Beowulf." <br>
	His readings evoked a sense of loneliness, and an attachment <br>
to nature with bold phrases and thought-provoking schemes.<br>
	Heaneys works include Selected Poems, 1966-1987 and The <br>
Spirit Level.<br>
<p>
