<p>
PRESS RELEASE<br>
<p>
For Immediate Release<br>
Contact: Elizabeth S. Chouldjian<br>
December 17, 1996<br>
Tel: (202) 775-1918<br>
<p>
CLINTON NOMINEE FOR U.N. AMBASSADOR A PROPONENT OF ARMENIAN <br>
AMERICAN ISSUES IN CONGRESS<br>
<p>
New Mexico Congressman Bill Richardson Has Backed Aid to Armenia, <br>
Peace in Nagorno Karabagh, the Azeri Aid Ban, and Commemoration of <br>
the Genocide<br>
<p>
WASHINGTON, DC - President Clinton's nominee to serve as U.S. <br>
Ambassador to the United Nations, New Mexico Congressman Bill <br>
Richardson, has a record of supporting a range of issues of concern <br>
to Armenian Americans, including aid to Armenia, the equitable <br>
resolution of the Nagorno Karabagh conflict, sanctions on Turkey <br>
due to its blockade of Armenia, and the commemoration of the <br>
Armenian Genocide, reported the Armenian National Committee of <br>
America (ANCA).<br>
<p>
In June of this year, Congressman Richardson voted in favor of the <br>
Visclosky Amendment, which stregthened the Humanitarian Aid <br>
Corridor Act sanction on Turkey for obstructing U.S. humanitarian <br>
supplies to Armenia.  The Amendment, which limited the President's <br>
authority to waive the Corridor Act, was designed to cut off all <br>
U.S. economic assistance to Turkey until it had ceased to block the <br>
delivery of relief assistance to Armenia.  In June, 1995,  Rep. <br>
Richardson voted in favor of the Porter Amendment to the FY 1996 <br>
foreign aid bill, sharply reducing U.S. aid levels to Turkey <br>
because of that nation's continued blockade of Armenia, occupation <br>
of Cyprus, mistreatment of the Kurds, and worsening human rights <br>
record.  He has also supported a number of other issues of concern <br>
to Greek and Kurdish Americans.<br>
<p>
During the 103rd Congress, Rep. Richardson cosponsored H.Res. 86, <br>
introduced by House Democratic Whip David Bonior, which presented a <br>
six-point guideline for U.S. involvement in the Nagorno Karabagh <br>
Peace process.  The resolution 1) Called for continued humanitarian <br>
aid for Armenia; 2) Promoted a "lasting and equitable resolution to <br>
the conflict within the U.N. and CSCE;" 3) Called for the "full <br>
participation of the representatives of Nagorno Karabagh in all <br>
negotiations," 4) Encouraged "Turkey, which has provided military, <br>
economic and diplomatic support for Azerbaijan, to play a neutral <br>
role," 5) Condemned the "blockades of Armenia and Nagorno Karabagh <br>
and demanded "the immediate lifting of the blockades and the <br>
opening of humanitarian corridors to facilitate the delivery of <br>
humanitarian goods to Armenia; and 6) Supported the continuation of <br>
the ban on U.S. aid to Azerbaijan until its ceases its aggression <br>
against and blockades of Armenia and Nagorno Karabagh.<br>
<p>
Congressman Richardson voted for the Armenian Genocide resolution <br>
both times that it came before the House during his term of office, <br>
in 1987 (H.J.Res.132), and 1985 (H.J.Res.192).  He did not, <br>
however, support the Radanovich-Bonior Amendment to the FY 1997 <br>
foreign aid bill.<br>
<p>
