<!-- body="start" -->
        AT THE PRESIDENT'S OFFICE<br>
<p>
 YEREVAN, DECEMBER 17, ARMENPRESS.<br>
 Yesterday, the President of the Republic of Armenia Levon<br>
 Ter-Petrossian met with the President of the National Academy of<br>
 Sciences of the Republic of Armenia Fadey Sargissian. During the<br>
 meeting the sides discussed the current problems of the National<br>
 Academy, as well as the issues of financing science in 1997.<br>
 On the same day, President Ter-Petrossian signed the Law of the<br>
 Republic Armenia "On Insurance," passed by the National Assembly of<br>
 the Republic of Armenia on November 19.<br>
<p>
        ARMENIAN ARTISTS PARTICIPATE IN THE 6TH INTERNATIONAL<br>
        EXHIBITION IN CAIRO<br>
<p>
 YEREVAN, DECEMBER 17, ARMENPRESS.<br>
 4 painters from Armenia arrived in Cairo to participate in the 6th<br>
 international exhibition. The exhibition opened on December 15, in<br>
 the Cairo National Arts Center. This is a great opportunity to show<br>
 modern Armenian art to the international community.<br>
<p>
INTERVIEW WITH THE CHAIRMAN OF THE BOARD OF JUDGES OF<br>
CRIMINAL CASES OF THE SUPREME COURT OF THE REPUBLIC OF<br>
ARMENIA, THE PRESIDING PERSON AT THE "DRO" TRIAL, EDUARD<br>
MANUKIAN<br>
<p>
 YEREVAN, DECEMBER 17, ARMENPRESS.<br>
 More than 1.5 year-long trial of the "Dro" case, which followed a six<br>
 month investigation, indicates that the Board of Judges of Criminal<br>
 Cases of the Supreme Court of the Republic of Armenia has examined<br>
 the case in great detail. For months, this case was and still remains<br>
 in the center of attention of the press and the public. For months,<br>
 certain forces tried to attach political reasons to the trial,<br>
 despite a series of serious crimes, including 5 murders.<br>
 Mr. Eduard Manukian, who presided at the trial, always refused to<br>
 meet with the press in order to avoid giving any premature statements<br>
 and opinions. However, now, when the verdict is reached and the trial<br>
 is over, Mr. Manukian gave an interview to Armenpress.<br>
<p>
 Question.- Mr. Manukian, since a certain political atmosphere was<br>
forming<br>
 around this criminal case throughout the trial, I would like you to<br>
 address this issue first. Very often the Court was blamed for<br>
 carrying out certain "political order."<br>
<p>
 Answer.- I think the whole content of the trial itself shows that it<br>
 was conducted in the conditions of complete independence of judicial<br>
 power. I think that these people would like to find the opposite<br>
 meaning in the verdict. But the vedict was passed only by the firm<br>
 believes and opinions of the members of the Board of Judges, and<br>
 there was no outside pressure whatsoever on them.<br>
<p>
 Q.- The politization of the case was reflected in the "Dro"-ARF<br>
 (Armenian Revolutionary Federation, Dashnak Party) link suggested by<br>
 the preliminary investigation, one of the sections of which was the<br>
 Artsruni-Margarian link.<br>
<p>
 A.- There is no clearly stated opinion in the verdict that "Dro" had<br>
 no connection with the Dashnak Party. This conlusion can be reached<br>
 by the sentence for Hrant Margarian and Gegham Manukian, which can<br>
 cause wrong interpretations.<br>
 Arsen Artsruni was not the kind of person who could independently<br>
 establish such an organization. He was a member of the ARF who came<br>
 from Lebanon and continued his party activities and carried out party<br>
 orders. Artsruni's economic activity was also not his own initiative.<br>
 It pursued the goals of improving financial and economic means of the<br>
 party. The economic intelligence unit was also not his initiative. As<br>
 stated in the verdict and in various documents prepared by Artsruni<br>
 himself, it was established by the decision of the Supreme Body of<br>
 the ARF, which is stated in the veridict. From the point of view of<br>
 grounded proofs, the Artsruni-Margarian link was unsatisfactory.<br>
 However, this does not mean that Artsruni-ARF link is impossible.<br>
<p>
 Q.- In any case, in the verdict Hrant Margarian was not recognized as<br>
 a leader of "Dro".<br>
<p>
 A.- It should be taken into consideration that, according to the<br>
 Article 299 of the Code of Criminal Laws of the Republic of Armenia,<br>
 the verdict of "not guilty" may be reached if the proofs of guilt are<br>
 not sufficient. In case of Margarian, the Board of Judges was<br>
 governed by this.<br>
 The Board of Judges considered the proofs of establishing the "Dro"<br>
 organization within the security council as insufficient. The fact<br>
 that "Dro" was a part of ARF is indicated by Artsruni's testimony, as<br>
 well as other documents in the case and the testimony of other<br>
 accused, while there are no other evidence about the security council<br>
 than Artsruni's testimony. In the document which was accepted by the<br>
 investigating authorities as a basis, there are the names of 8 more<br>
 security council members, other than Margarian. In these<br>
 circumstances, the proofs have been treated arbitrarily. If<br>
 Artsruni's testimony and the document were used as basis, then other<br>
 members of the security council should have been called to Court.<br>
<p>
 Q.- The Board of Judges didn't address the appeal of the Prosecutor<br>
 General, who asked to decide on the issue of responsibility of ARF,<br>
 and pass the case to the Constitutional Court.<br>
<p>
 A.- This issue was not a subject of discussion by the Board of<br>
 Judges. The Board of Judges only examines the evidence in the case.<br>
 It is not in the power of the Board to appeal to the Constitutional<br>
 Court. That is why the Board of Judges didn't address this issue.<br>
<p>
 Q.- What evidence was the verdict based on: evidence of the<br>
 preliminary investigation or the trial?<br>
<p>
 A.- It is our principle to base our decisions on the evnidence which<br>
 has been proven by the investigation. Whether the evidence was<br>
 acquired by the preliminary investigation or the trial, does not<br>
 matter to us. All the evidence is evaluated. The main criteria is the<br>
 validity of the evidence. This is how all the examined and<br>
 established facts are taken as proofs in the case.<br>
 Sometimes it happens that the facts accepted by the investigation as<br>
 sufficient evidence are not considered as such by the court in the<br>
 process of trial. Then, the court can not use them as valid evidence.<br>
<p>
 Q.- The members of the group were sentenced from 3 years in prison to<br>
 the capital punishment. Compared to the suggestions of the Prosecutor<br>
 General, this punishement is much milder. However, three people are<br>
 sentenced to death.<br>
<p>
 A.- During the investigation, it was established that the "Dro"<br>
 organization was a criminal organization and it functioned. The<br>
 results of the group's activities are well known. From the point of<br>
 view of human rights the capital punishment has a different flavor to<br>
 it, but it is strange that the victims of the criminals are not<br>
 considered from the same point of view. We should not forget the<br>
 tragic consequences of the these crimes. No one in the Board of<br>
 Judges could sign the death sentence if he or she had even the least<br>
 doubts about the rightness of this decision. The evidence stated in<br>
 the verdict are a clear indication of this. I think that whoever<br>
 reads the evaluation of the evidence, can have no doubts that the<br>
 murders have been committed by these people.<br>
 Another issue is the degree of participation of various people in the<br>
 group. The Board of Judges carefully examined the degree of<br>
 participation of each person. The Board was very strict toward the<br>
 organizers and the activists of the group and the murders. I mean<br>
 Arsen Artsruni, Armenak Mnjoyan, Armen Grigorian, Armen Zakarian,<br>
 Hovnaness Mkrtchian.<br>
<p>
 Q.- It is stated in the verdict that a separate decision will be<br>
 passed on the violations which took place during the preliminary<br>
 investigation.<br>
<p>
 A.- Taking into consideration that there have been some violations in<br>
 gathering documents, arresting some people, and other actions during<br>
 the preliminary investigation, the Board of Judges thought it<br>
 necessary to pass a separate decision about this issue.<br>
<p>
 Q.- When does the verdict become effective?<br>
<p>
 A.- The verdict can be appealed within 7 days. If within this period<br>
 of time the plaintiff or the defendant sides do not file any formal<br>
 appeals, then the verdict automatically becomes effective. If appeal<br>
 is filed, the verdict will be reconsidered by the Arbitration Court<br>
 of the Supreme Court of the Republic of Armenia.<br>
<p>
 Q.- Do you think the appeals will be filed?<br>
<p>
 A.- I think both sides will not miss this opportunity.<br>
<p>
        INTERNATIONAL MONETARY FUND'S ACTIVITIES IN ARMENIA TO<br>
        CONTINUE NEXT YEAR<br>
<p>
 YEREVAN, DECEMBER 17, ARMENPRESS.<br>
 According to Mr. Tanos Cacambas, head of the International Monetary<br>
 Fund's Mission in Armenia, in the last months there have been<br>
 deviations from the government's and Central Bank's program of<br>
 economic reforms. During his 12-day visit to Armenia, the IMF<br>
 official negotiated the possibilities of correcting these deviations<br>
 and getting back into the program's framework.<br>
 Yesterday, during a press conference, the IMF official announced that<br>
 certain preliminary agreements have been reached, which (if passed)<br>
 will allow to return to the previously agreed program before the end<br>
 of January.<br>
 Mr. Cacambas said that the main deviations took place in two areas:<br>
 fiscal policies and structural reforms. Thus, in the area of fiscal<br>
 policies, the process of collecting the revenue has slowed down, and<br>
 the expenses were not adjusted accordingly. The amount of the actual<br>
 loan from the Central Bank have been exceeded. Pressure was put on<br>
 the exchange rate, which resulted in decrease of the Central Bank's<br>
 reserves. After low inflation in the previous 10 months, the<br>
 inflation in November was 2.4%. It is expected that in December the<br>
 inflation rate will be even higher.<br>
 As for the stuctural reforms, Mr. Cacambas thinks that reforms in the<br>
 banking and energy sectors have slowed down. According to prior<br>
 agreements, those banks which "could not be saved" should have been<br>
 closed or merged with more powerful banks, which has not been done.<br>
 The IMF official expressed a hope that the Committee headed by the<br>
 President of the Central Bank of the Republic of Armenia Bagrat<br>
 Asatrian will develop a program of recovery of the bank system.<br>
 Mr. Cacambas informed that it was suggested to the Government of the<br>
 Republic of Armenia to cut down the expenses. It was also suggested<br>
 to determine the expenses in accordance with the revenues and to<br>
 speed up the banking reforms and to strengthen the achievements in<br>
 the evergy sector.<br>
 The ESAF loan program of the IMF is scheduled for three years,<br>
 starting in 1996. Under this program Armenia is to receive $50 mln<br>
 per year.<br>
 The 1997 program will be discussed during the IMF delegation's visit<br>
 in February. Mr. Cacambas informed that the IMF, in particular, does<br>
 not agree with the 14% inflation rate expected by the Armenian<br>
 government. He said, if the inflation rate at the end of this year<br>
 will be 10% (instead of expected 18%) and at the same time the gross<br>
 domestic product will grow by 6% (as expected), than there is no<br>
 reason to expect a 14% inflation in 1997.<br>
