<title>Groong Network: Moving article in Montreal Gazette</title>
<h1>Moving article in Montreal Gazette</h1>
Terjanian, Antoine (<i>Antoine.Terjanian@geocan.emr.ca</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 17 Dec 96 11:31:13 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#147">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#147">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#147">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#147">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0148.html">Armen Martirossyan: "From Armenpress homepage"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0146.html">vahe@arminco.com: "Aragil Headlines, 12/17/96"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
The following article appeared on page A2 in the Friday, Dec. 6 edition of<br>
the Montreal Gazette.  It is reproduced here with permission from the author,<br>
who is also copied this message.  Mr. Fiorito is publishing 3 more articles<br>
on the same subject starting Dec. 28.<br>
<p>
I have noted that the article was not carried by other newspapers.  I have<br>
written to our local paper (the citizen), who belongs to the same chain<br>
(Southam), to draw their attention to the excellent quality of the reporting.<br>
 If you want to be able to read the remaining articles of the series, you may<br>
wish to draw this article to the attention of your own papers.<br>
===============================<br>
<p>
In Yerevan, they pray the lights will not go out*<br>
<p>
By Joe Fiorito<br>
<p>
Yerevan, Armenia- The alley is dusty and narrow and cuts an oblique path<br>
between two rows of stone buildings near Republic Square. The buildings are<br>
low and gray, their sides rubbed smooth by years of weather. <br>
<p>
The alley that runs between the buildings is lined with market stalls. Each<br>
stall is piled with boxes. The boxes spill a bright disorder of plastic toys<br>
and bars of laundry soap; smoked fish, pencils and dried beans; bottled<br>
water, soda, vodka; Russian cigarettes and stationery. <br>
<p>
And two kinds of candles. <br>
<p>
The white ones are for use at home; electricity is uncertain here. The skinny<br>
yellow ones are for use in church; people still pray in Yerevan. They pray<br>
the lights will not go out. <br>
<p>
The alley is choked with people who weigh each purchase carefully. They<br>
pause. they look, they move on. There s not a lot of laughter here, but there<br>
is music in the air, Celine Dion s voice, a love song aching from a boom-box<br>
on a shelf behind some plastic bags. <br>
<p>
There are two lines of people in this alley, heading in opposite directions;<br>
shoppers entering with empty bags, and shoppers leaving, not will full bags,<br>
but with less-empty ones. <br>
<p>
Nobody has much money to spend. <br>
<p>
Any dumb foreigner can see that much, just as any dumb foreigner knows their<br>
isn t room enough to linger for more than a moment; you move along on your<br>
own, in one line or the other, or you re moved along by the crowd. <br>
<p>
Most people here have little more than the clothes on their backs, and a bit<br>
of money for a candle or a fish. Many are refugees, dispossessed by a nasty<br>
little war. It was a war that took place along one of the bloody fault lines<br>
between Christianity and Islam. A war with ethnic underpinnings. <br>
<p>
You may remember: <br>
<p>
Nagorno-Karabagh, landlocked inside Azerbaijan, fighting to rejoin its<br>
neighbor and ethnic relative, Armenia; there were sharp battles, thousands<br>
dead, a catalogue of blistering atrocities. <br>
<p>
Armenians were killed, were beaten or kicked out of Azerbaijan simply for<br>
being Armenian: and Azeris were booted out of Armenia and Nagorno-Karabagh.<br>
One million refugees, all told. <br>
<p>
The first and worst of the atrocities were committed in Azerbaijan in 1988<br>
when, in the cities of Sumgait, Kirovabad and Baku, women were raped, men<br>
were thrown into bonfires on the streets, and people were beaten to death<br>
simply for being Armenian. <br>
<p>
Yes, Azeris died, too. <br>
<p>
The war has been quiet in recent years. Nagorno-Karabagh has achieved its<br>
primary objective, a physical link to nearby Armenia. That link, a<br>
seven-kilometer stretch of narrow mountain road, is maintained with the<br>
threat of blood and bullets. <br>
<p>
I spent a week there recently to observe the aftermath of the war, and the<br>
would-be republic s first democratic presidential elections. <br>
<p>
People are breathing clear air because, for the moment, their guns are<br>
silent, there are no fresh reasons to mourn, and because they view the<br>
election as a step toward achieving recognition as a country. <br>
<p>
Then I spent a week in the ancient city of Yerevan, where there were<br>
widespread allegations of fraud during the Armenian election last September.<br>
Seventy years of Soviet rule have ingrained blunt habits in certain of its<br>
politicians. <br>
<p>
But political fiddles may be the least of their problems; there was an<br>
earthquake in Armenia in 1988. The toll: 25,000 dead and 500,000 homeless. To<br>
make matters worse, Armenia has taken in some 300,000 refugees since the war<br>
began, and it remains cut off from the rest of the world by an Azerbaijani<br>
trade blockade. <br>
<p>
Some goods trickle northward from Iran, but poverty is so widespread in<br>
Armenia that ordinary suffering does not stand out unless you are a<br>
westerner, and easily shocked. <br>
<p>
That afternoon, in the alley market near Republic Square, I watched a woman<br>
not much older than I am wandering between the lines of shoppers. She was<br>
talking to herself. She had a coffee pot in her hand. Now and then she d<br>
reach for someone s sleeve. She d praise the value of the coffee pot. It was<br>
for sale at a good price. You couldn t find a better one anywhere. She didn t<br>
want to sell it, but she needed the money for food. The pot was all she had.<br>
Please. <br>
<p>
No takers. <br>
<p>
She looked at me, once. She didn t touch my arm. No point. She knew I<br>
wouldn t buy her pot. She knew I wouldn t understand its value. <br>
<p>
Perhaps I don t. <br>
<p>
But I understand its worth. <br>
<p>
If there were any goodness in the world, her pot would be worth a fortune and<br>
there would be no end buyers for it in this market. <br>
<p>
No, that s not right. <br>
<p>
If there were any goodness in the world, no one would be forced to sell a<br>
coffee pot to buy a little food. <br>
<p>
Joe Fiorito's e-mail address is fiorito@vir.com. His three part series about<br>
Armenia and Nagorno-Karabakh will be published in The Gazette starting Dec.<br>
28. <br>
<p>
                                                        The Gazette,         <br>
                                     Friday, December 6, 1996 <br>
<p>
* In the early edition of The Gazette, the same article was entitled "For the<br>
moment, the guns are silent in Yerevan". The correction was made in the final<br>
edition. <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
