<title>Groong Network: Turkey/CenAsia Highlights 12/13/96</title>
<h1>Turkey/CenAsia Highlights 12/13/96</h1>
Mher Sassouni (<i>as080@lafn.org</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 16 Dec 96 16:48:41 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#145">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#145">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#145">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#145">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0146.html">vahe@arminco.com: "Aragil Headlines, 12/17/96"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0144.html">Asbed Bedrossian: "AP/Reuters headlines to 12/16/96"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
  	  				 <br>
	+&gt; Yemen LNG, Turkey's Botas sign deal  <br>
	+&gt; Turkey's Ciller ordered to pay damages  <br>
	+&gt; Turkish police move against ex-minister  <br>
                               ======	 <br>
 Yemen LNG, Turkey's Botas sign deal<br>
	The Yemen Liquefied Natural Gas Co. Thursday signed a<br>
memorandum of understanding with the Turkish group Botas<br>
covering long-term LNG sales to Turkey, the French oil company<br>
Total announced. It said the deal covers the supply to Turkey of<br>
the entire production of one of the two trains of Yemen LNG's<br>
gas liquefaction plant, or about 2.6 million tonnes of LNG per<br>
year. The supply would last for a period of 25 years &gt;from the<br>
train's start-up. The terms of the sales contract are to be<br>
neogiated over the coming months, Total said. Total is the main<br>
shareholder in the Yemen Liquefied Natural Gas Co., which was<br>
set up last year to produce around 5 million tonnes of LNG a<br>
year from the year 2001, for an estimated inward investment of<br>
around $2.5 billion. A memorandum of understanding on the deal<br>
was signed in the Yemeni capital Sanaa in the presence of senior<br>
government officials from Turkey and Yemen.<br>
                               ======<br>
 Turkey's Ciller ordered to pay damages<br>
	A Turkish civil court Thursday ordered Deputy Prime<br>
Minister Tansu Ciller to pay $20,000 for insulting Justice<br>
Minister Sevket Kazan, the Anatolian News Agency said. The court<br>
ruled that Ciller had insulted Kazan for saying in the National<br>
Assembly that he "lacked honor and national pride." A court<br>
last month ordered Ciller, now in the same Cabinet with Kazan,<br>
to pay $40,000 damages for falsely accusing Prime Minister<br>
Necmettin Erbakan last year of misappropriating money collected<br>
for Bosnian Muslims. Erbakan is the leader and Kazan a member of<br>
the hard-line Muslim Welfare Party, while Ciller leads the<br>
center-right True Party Party. Erbakan and Ciller in July formed<br>
a coalition government, in which she also serves as foreign<br>
minister.<br>
                               ======<br>
 Turkish police move against ex-minister<br>
	Turkey's prime minister planned late Thursday to speak<br>
to reporters about allegations of government-underworld ties, as<br>
the Justice Ministry considered a move to lift a former<br>
minister's parliamentary immunity.  "After I meet with<br>
President Suleyman Demirel tonight, I will answer questions from<br>
the press," Necmettin Erbakan said Thursday. A prosecutor asked<br>
the Justice Ministry on Wednesday to lift the immunity of Mehmet<br>
Agar, who was Interior Minister until last month. The<br>
prosecutor's request was based on a police report that accused<br>
Agar of "malpractice," Turkey's Anatolian News Agency<br>
said. Allegations of corrupt government officials having links<br>
with criminals came to a head after a security chief, a gangster<br>
wanted by Interpol and a parliamentarian were involved in a<br>
Nov. 3 vehicle collision. The security chief and the gangster<br>
were killed, but the parliamentarian -- Sedat Bucak of the True<br>
Path Party, the junior partner in the coalition government --<br>
survived to admit that a cache of weapons found in the car<br>
belonged to him. Agar initially passed the crash off as a<br>
"traffic accident," but was forced to resign when opposition<br>
parliamentarians accused him of trying to cover up<br>
government-underworld links. Turkey's newspapers continued to<br>
pursue every conceivable angle on the crash, speculating on the<br>
contents of a dossier on corruption allegations that the leader<br>
of the main opposition party, Mesut Yilmaz of Motherland, has<br>
delivered to President Demirel. Turkish news reports said<br>
Thursday that Demirel was expected to discuss the dossier at his<br>
meeting with Erbakan, who has so far kept a low profile on the<br>
scandal. Newspapers have said Bucak, a Kurdish tribal chief who<br>
supports the government against Kurdish separatists, receives<br>
$1.3 million a month for providing "village guards" in the<br>
war-racked southeast of Turkey. More than 21, 000 people have<br>
been killed since the Kurdistan Workers Party began its<br>
insurgency for an independent Kurdistan in 1984.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
