<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
ASBAREZ ON LINE <br>
12/16/1996<br>
<p>
<p>
1. KOCHARIAN IN FRANCE, SAYS KARABAKH IS A NATIONAL ISSUE<br>
2. AZERBAIJAN SIGNS $2 BILLION CASPIAN OIL DEAL<br>
3. GENOCIDE REFERENCES IN ARAB HISTORIOGRAPHY STUDIED<br>
4. COMPETITION FOR BEST ARMENIAN TEXTBOOK PUBLICATION<br>
5. SARKISSIAN VISITS LONDON<br>
6. SAMSUNG ELECTRONICS OPENS IN ARMENIA<br>
7. CONSTITUTIONAL COURT CANDIDATE POOL SHOULD EXPAND<br>
8. ARMENIAN WRESTLER WINS BRONZE<br>
9. UN OFFERS OSCE HELP IN KARABAKH SETTLEMENT<br>
10. EU ASK BELARUS TO ALLOW DEMOCRACY FACT FINDERS<br>
11. NEW ARMENIAN CENTER INAUGURATED IN EAST VALLEY<br>
<p>
<p>
1. KOCHARIAN IN FRANCE, SAYS KARABAKH IS A NATIONAL ISSUE<br>
<p>
PARIS (Gamk)-Nagorno-Karabakh Republic President Robert Kocharian <br>
arrived in France last Tuesday for meetings with governmental <br>
organizations and the Armenian community.<br>
	On Wednesday, Kocharian was welcomed at Alfortville city <br>
hall during a reception organized by French senator and chairman <br>
of the "France-Armenia" friendship organization Renee Rouquet. <br>
Community leaders and members attended the reception during which <br>
the French senator addressed the Karabakh question, emphasizing <br>
its importance in modern times.<br>
	Rouquet specifically praised the will of the Nagorno-<br>
Karabakh population, who, through their selfless determination, <br>
struggled for victory in Karabakh.<br>
	Rouquet, who is also the mayor of Alfortville, did not mince <br>
words in praising Karabakhs right to self-determination and said <br>
that the inalienable principle was more important than a nations <br>
territorial integrity, which has become a tool for world leaders <br>
to pursue their interests.<br>
	The senator called on the entire Diaspora to assist the <br>
heroic people of Karabakh, which today has its own <br>
president-Robert Kocharian.<br>
	In response, the Karabakh leader thanked Rouquet for his <br>
hospitality and support and stressed that today Karabakh had the <br>
strongest army in the region and was capable of defending the <br>
Karabakh territory and the fragile cease-fire.<br>
	Kocharian also stressed the pivotal role the Diaspora <br>
played-and will continue to play-in the fate of the Nagorno-<br>
Karabakh Republic.<br>
	At 8 p.m. local time, Kocharian, his wife, and the Karabakh <br>
delegation, which included Karabakhs representative to Armenia <br>
Alexander Harutunian, Karabakhs representative to France and the <br>
European Parliament Varoujan Grigorian and Evangelical pastor Rene <br>
Levonian, arrived at the Armenian Cultural Home of Paris where <br>
community leaders and members had gathered to greet the president.<br>
	ARF Central Committee chairperson Hagop Yenikomshian and ARF <br>
CC member Dikran Shirvanian were joined with the Regional <br>
Executive members of the Armenian Blue Cross of France (ARS) and <br>
the Homenetmen Scouts who greeted the president with a salute.<br>
	The president was then directed to the editorial offices of <br>
our sister publication Gamk newspaper where he was interviewed.<br>
	"As I stated during  my campaign, the fundamental issues for <br>
Karabakh today is its independence and peace. Today, it can be <br>
said, that Karabakh is independent and  has declared its <br>
independence through a referendum. However, if other states have <br>
not yet recognized Karabakhs independence then that is another <br>
question...," stated Kocharian during his interview, the <br>
translated text of which will be published in future editions of <br>
Asbarez.<br>
	Following the interview, a community gathering took place at <br>
the Armenian centers hall, during which on behalf of the ARF CC <br>
and the Gamk newspaper, Shirvanian welcomed Kocharian and the <br>
Karabakh delegation to France.<br>
	In his remarks, Shirvanian stressed that the ARF has <br>
remained  and will always remain in solidarity with the Karabakh <br>
cause and the people of Artsakh, once again, pledging the partys <br>
resources to the needs of the Nagorno-Karabakh Republic.<br>
	In response, Kocharian thanked the community representatives <br>
and stressed the importance of the Diaspora in the fundamental <br>
state-building processes in Karabakh. Kocharian said that it was <br>
the responsibility of Karabakhs leadership to work and cooperate <br>
with all facets of the community.<br>
	Kocharian also stressed that any fundamental decision <br>
regarding Karabakh could not be made unilaterally, and the input <br>
of all Armenians was necessary since any decision would have its <br>
effect on the entire Armenian nation and the world.<br>
	Kocharian also visited Lyons, Marseilles and Geneva, from <br>
where he is scheduled to return to Stepanakert Thursday.<br>
<p>
<p>
2. AZERBAIJAN SIGNS $2 BILLION CASPIAN OIL DEAL<br>
<p>
BAKU (Reuter)-Azerbaijan and a consortium of foreign oil companies <br>
led by Amoco Corp.s Amoco Eurasian Petroleum Company signed a $2 <br>
billion deal Saturday in Baku to develop the Ashrafi and Dan <br>
Ulduzu oil fields.<br>
	The 25-year contract is Azerbaijans fourth major deal with <br>
a consortium of Western companies in the Caucasus republics <br>
Caspian Sea reserves.<br>
	Amoco said it hopes to sign another exploration agreement <br>
with the former Soviet republic soon.<br>
	The Western consortium in Saturdays deal includes Amoco <br>
Eurasian, with a 30 percent stake, Unocal with 25.5 percent, <br>
Japans Itochu with 20 percent and Saudi Arabias Delta Nimir with <br>
4.5 percent.<br>
	The Azerbaijan state oil company SOCAR will have a 20 <br>
percent stake in the deal, and Azeri oil officials say 65 to 80 <br>
percent of profits from the development of the fields will go to <br>
the Azeri government.<br>
	The Ashrafi and Dan Ulduzu fields lie approximately 30 miles <br>
off the Apsheron peninsula. They are spread over 175 square miles <br>
at depths of 246 to 656 feet and are estimated to contain 150 <br>
million metric tons of crude. <br>
	First production is expected to come on line in 2003 and <br>
will reach seven million metric tons per year by 2007.<br>
	The deal requires an up-front bonus payment to the Azeri <br>
government of $75 million from consortium members and must be <br>
ratified by the Azeri parliament.<br>
	The deal brings total western investment in Azerbaijans <br>
promising oil sector to over $12 billion.<br>
	Azeri President Gaidar Aliyev said the agreement was <br>
evidence of the growing importance of the former Soviet republic <br>
for American companies.<br>
	"I am happy that the Clinton administration is finding <br>
cooperation with Azerbaijan," Aliyev said, adding that he had <br>
received a telephone call from Vice President Al Gore Friday.<br>
	"I consider the US and Azerbaijan as strategic partners... <br>
The Vice President said the administration supports cooperation <br>
with the Azeri oil sector and regards the contract as of the <br>
utmost importance," he said.<br>
	Azerbaijan, with its vast Caspian oil potential, has been <br>
the center of a tug-of-war between Russia, Iran, Turkey and <br>
Western countries since independence in 1991.<br>
	Tom Stacy, Chairman of Amoco Eurasian Petroleum Company, <br>
said the oil giant hoped to sign another Caspian contract with the <br>
Azeri government soon.<br>
	"We are happy to work in Azerbaijan and hope to sign another <br>
contract soon on exploration of the southern part of the Azeri <br>
sector of the Caspian basin," he told a news conference.<br>
<p>
<p>
3. GENOCIDE REFERENCES IN ARAB HISTORIOGRAPHY STUDIED<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-National Academy of Sciences member and <br>
director of the Institute of Oriental Studies, Nikolay Oganessian, <br>
recently published a monograph on the causes of the Armenian <br>
Genocide as documented in Arab historiography.<br>
	Arabs lived under Ottoman rule for more than 400 years <br>
(1516-1918) and went through many hardships under the Sultans <br>
rule, however, the cause of the religious stand-off was omitted in <br>
the works of the Arab historians, Oganessian said.<br>
	Arab historians used the word genocide to describe the <br>
deportation of Armenians in 1915 in an effort to create a "pure <br>
Turkish society" as part of Pan Turanism, Oganessian said.<br>
	In addition, Arab historians view Soghomon Tehlirian, <br>
Arshavir Shirakian, Petros Ter-Poghossian and Stepan Dzaghikian, <br>
who assasinated the organizers of the Genocide not as terrorists <br>
but as "national avengers," said Oganessian, citing 56 sources of <br>
Arab historiography.<br>
<p>
<p>
4. COMPETITION FOR BEST ARMENIAN TEXTBOOK PUBLICATION<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-Eighteen publishing houses will compete in a <br>
bid to win publication rights of Armenian language and literature <br>
textbooks for children, ages 5-10 years.<br>
	Samples of the proposed textbooks will be submitted to a <br>
special commission in February 1997.<br>
	In spring, a competition for the best publication of <br>
textbooks on the Russian and English languages, and also <br>
mathematics will be announced. The competition will be funded by <br>
the World Bank, which provides financing of 155 publications in <br>
Armenia and $3.5 million has been earmarked for the implementation <br>
of the project.<br>
	The Minister for Education of Armenia, Artashes Petrossian <br>
said the commission which will judge textbooks will consist of the <br>
authors of the 1994-96 year textbook projects, secondary school <br>
teachers, lecturers of higher education establishments, <br>
psychologists and researchers.<br>
	Petrossian said the given project provides no publication of <br>
textbooks for primary school. Students age one to four will be <br>
using the new textbooks. The rest of the pupils are to use the old <br>
textbooks kept in school libraries.<br>
<p>
<p>
5. SARKISSIAN VISITS LONDON<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-During his recent visit to London, Armenian <br>
Prime Minister Armen Sarkissian had several meetings with <br>
representatives of major companies, such as Siemens, Johnson &amp; <br>
Johnson, IMG bank, Microsoft, Inchcape and others.<br>
	Sarkissian asked those companies to invest in Armenia, <br>
assuring that the Armenian government would do its best to <br>
encourage and support foreign investments. Sarkisian was visiting <br>
London for the last time as ambassador from Armenia to the United <br>
Kingdom. He had held this position since 1992. British government <br>
and diplomatic officials held a ceremony in Sarkissians honor, <br>
which was attended by opera virtuoso Placido Domingo was also <br>
invited. Accepting Sarkissians invitation, Domingo agreed to <br>
perform in Yerevan in the near future.<br>
	On Dec. 10, Sarkissian met with representatives of the local <br>
Armenian community in St. Peters Church. He thanked the British <br>
community for supporting the Armenian embassy.<br>
	He underlined the importance of strengthening ties between <br>
Armenia  and the Diaspora, saying that it is the obligation of <br>
each Armenian to support his homeland.<br>
	Representatives of the British government, foreign <br>
diplomats, as well as President of the Armenian General Benevolent <br>
Union, Louise Manoogian-Simone and Primate of the Ararat Diocese, <br>
Archbishop Garegin Nersissian attended Sarkissians farewell <br>
party.<br>
<p>
<p>
6. SAMSUNG ELECTRONICS OPENS IN ARMENIA<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-The Korean electronics giant, Samsung <br>
Electronics, opened a store in Yerevan last Friday making it the <br>
first major electronics company to open for business in the <br>
Commonwealth of Independent States.<br>
	So far, Samsung is represented in Russia, Ukraine and <br>
Kazakhstan.<br>
 	Samsungs official dealer in Armenia is the joint Armenian-<br>
Russian enterprise "Mark International" with which Samsung has <br>
been working with since 1992. President of "Mark International" <br>
Armen Hayrapetian reported that until recently, Samsungs <br>
appliances were brought into Armenia and Transcaucasia by other <br>
firms at relatively higher prices.<br>
	Samsungs store of home appliances in Yerevan has <br>
approximately 70 types of appliances, including 22 types of TV <br>
sets. The store will put on sale new models of microwaves, which <br>
work on a specially-programmed menu.<br>
	Hayrapetian said that Samsung also planned to open stores in <br>
Giumri, Sevan and Etchmiadzin. <br>
	Samsung is the third largest producer of home appliances, <br>
(behind Sony and Panasonic) and the first largest producer of <br>
microwaves.<br>
	In 1996, Samsungs profits increased by 36 percent to $87 <br>
billion. Currently,  Samsung Electronics is manufacturing more <br>
than 500 items.<br>
<p>
<p>
7. CONSTITUTIONAL COURT CANDIDATE POOL SHOULD EXPAND<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-Chairman of the Constitutional Court of <br>
Armenia, Gagik Haroutunian, said that it is necessary to enlarge <br>
the number of agencies eligible to apply to the Constitutional <br>
Court.<br>
	Haroutunian emphasized that it is necessary that the <br>
parliament speaker, prime minister,  the prosecutor-general, <br>
courts, physical entities, local self-government bodies and <br>
churches have the right to apply to the Constitutional Court.<br>
	According to the Article 101  of the Armenian Constitution, <br>
presently that right is reserved by the president of Armenia, one-<br>
third parliamentarians and presidential and deputy candidates.<br>
	The Constitution can be amended through a referendum only. <br>
According to Haroutunian, it is necessary that the Constitutional <br>
Court review a number of  laws (especially those which regulate <br>
the work of the parliament) before they are signed by the <br>
president and published.<br>
<p>
<p>
8. ARMENIAN WRESTLER WINS BRONZE<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-Habetnak Kurghinian (82kg) won a bronze <br>
medal in the Student Wrestling Championship which was held in Iran <br>
on Dec. 9-12.<br>
	Two other Armenian wrestlers, Rudik Markarian (52kg) and <br>
Karen Simonian (90kg) took 5th and 10th places, respectively.<br>
<p>
<p>
9. UN OFFERS OSCE HELP IN KARABAKH SETTLEMENT<br>
<p>
BAKU (Noyan Tapan)-Azeri sources defined the adoption of a <br>
resolution by the UN General Assembly and Council of Foreign <br>
Ministers of the Islamic Conference Organization as another <br>
victory for Azeri diplomacy.<br>
	Despite Armenias protests, the UN General Assembly adopted <br>
a resolution last Thursday offering the cooperation of the <br>
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe. <br>
	The ninth article of the resolution again confirms <br>
Azerbaijans territorial integrity. Azeri diplomats insisted on <br>
the adoption of this point of the resolution, which also asks for <br>
cooperation by the UN and OSCE in the settlement of the Karabakh <br>
conflict.<br>
	According to ANS-Press, diplomats reported that "it was only <br>
representatives of Armenia, which earlier blocked the adoption of <br>
the decision on the principles of settlement of the Karabakh <br>
conflict at the Lisbon Summit, that did not take part in the <br>
voting."<br>
	ANS-Press also reports that ICOs resolution bans military <br>
assistance to Armenia on the part of ICO member states. Demanding <br>
unconditional pulling out of Armenias armed forces from the <br>
occupied Azeri territories, foreign ministers of Islamic countries <br>
backed OSCE managing chairmans statement on principles of <br>
solution to the Karabakh conflict.<br>
<p>
<p>
10. EU ASK BELARUS TO ALLOW DEMOCRACY FACT FINDERS<br>
<p>
DUBLIN (Reuter)-The European Union urged Belarus President <br>
Alexander Lukashenko Saturday to restore full respect for <br>
democracy and accept a fact-finding mission, warning relations <br>
would otherwise suffer.<br>
	In a statement adopted at a summit in Dublin, EU leaders <br>
said they were seriously concerned at developments in Belarus <br>
after last months disputed referendum adopted a constitution <br>
greatly widening Lukashenkos powers at parliaments expense. <br>
	"The European Council calls on the leadership of Belarus to <br>
re-establish full respect for internationally accepted democratic <br>
and constitutional principles and practices and hopes that the <br>
leadership will accept the Unions proposal for a fact-finding <br>
mission," the declaration said.<br>
	"The absence of progress in these areas would have a <br>
negative impact on relations between Belarus and the European <br>
Union, and on Union support for Belarus accession to the Council <br>
of Europe," it said.<br>
	The European Parliament urged the 15-nation Union on <br>
Thursday to stop financial aid to the former Soviet republic <br>
because of doubts over its commitment to democracy.<br>
	Irish Prime Minister John Bruton, as EU president, raised <br>
the idea of sending a fact-finding mission when he met Lukashenko <br>
at an Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) <br>
summit in Lisbon on December 3.<br>
	EU foreign ministers later endorsed the proposal but there <br>
has been no official answer from Minsk.<br>
	A senior opposition figure in Belarus has been sentenced to <br>
15 days in prison for organizing an unauthorized rally in Minsk <br>
earlier this month, a spokeswoman for his Social Democratic Party <br>
said Saturday.<br>
	"The leader of our party, Mikola Statkevich, got a 15-day <br>
prison term yesterday for the December 8 anti-presidential rally," <br>
Lyubov Arestovich told Reuters.<br>
	Up to 7,000 people marched in central Minsk to denounce <br>
President Alexander Lukashenko and a referendum on November 24 <br>
which gave him sweeping powers over rival institutions.<br>
	Arestovich said several people had been sentenced to shorter <br>
terms for taking part in the rally last Sunday.<br>
	Irma Tabushava, 60, the sister of Justice Minister Valentin <br>
Sukala, was sent home from prison on Friday suffering from <br>
"serious heart problems" after she was sentenced to 10 days for <br>
taking part in the rally, Belapan news agency said on Friday.<br>
	Lukashenko has taken a tough line on rallies, banning them <br>
during the harvest season. On several occasions police have been <br>
sent in to break them up.<br>
	Scores of people have been arrested, though most have been <br>
held for days rather than months.<br>
	Arestovich said 15 people, mostly students, had been fined <br>
between $2.50 and $25. The average monthly salary in the former <br>
Soviet republic of 10 million is about $50.<br>
	"The Social Democrats have started a collection to support <br>
victims of political repression in Belarus," Arestovich said. "We <br>
would like to collect money to pay lawyers and fines." <br>
<p>
<p>
11. NEW ARMENIAN CENTER INAUGURATED IN EAST VALLEY<br>
<p>
STUDIO CITY-The Armenian Revolutionary Federation "Papken Suni" <br>
Gomideh (North Hollywood, Studio City, Van Nuys East of the 405 <br>
fwy) inaugurated its new center Sunday during an official ceremony <br>
attended by more than 100 community representatives and city <br>
officials, including Los Angeles County Board of Supervisors <br>
member Zev Yaroslavsky.<br>
	The new center, located at 11719 Moorpark St., Studio City, <br>
will serve the burgeoning East Valley community. It is estimated <br>
that the Armenian-American population of East San Fernando Valley <br>
has doubled during the past six years and numbers more than <br>
40,000. Large numbers of Armenians who settled in the Hollywood <br>
area when they immigrated to the United States in the 1970s and <br>
1980s have relocated to the East San Fernando Valley.<br>
	Reverend Vicken Vassilian presided over the ribbon-cutting <br>
ceremony and blessed the new center on behalf of Western Prelate  <br>
Right Rev. Moushegh Mardirossian, who was on a visit to the Utah <br>
parish.<br>
	"Running an Armenian center is difficult and may encounter a <br>
number of obstacles in its effort to serve the community, but I am <br>
convinced that with hard work and determination it can be <br>
accomplished," Rev. Vassilian said, and added "I wish that this <br>
new center becomes a thriving bastion of activity full of young <br>
and old members of the community."<br>
	Berdj Karapetian, past chairman of the Armenian National <br>
Committee of America-Western Region Board of Directors, welcomed <br>
the gathering and recalled the humble beginnings of the recently <br>
transplanted East San Fernando Valley Armenian community. "Most of <br>
us grew up in the Hollywood area, and in the 1970s we began our <br>
work at the small center on Santa Monica Blvd., and some time <br>
later moved into a two-story center on Vermont Ave.," Karapetian <br>
said, adding that the Vermont center continues to serve the <br>
considerable Hollywood community and houses sister organizations.<br>
	"We hope that this small center will also be a starting <br>
point for an even larger one with which we may serve the <br>
community," Karapetian added, before introducing city and county <br>
officials.<br>
	Gomideh chairperson Charles Lousararian was presented with <br>
several proclamations from Los Angeles Mayor Richard Riordans <br>
representative Steve Parker, LA City Councilman Mike Feuers <br>
representative Undine Petanlis, as well as one from Supervisor <br>
Yaroslavsky.<br>
	Supervisor Zev Yaroslavsky congratulated the new centers <br>
opening. He advised the community to not disregard the potential <br>
of a new, yet small center and to look to the future in <br>
anticipation of the great things that will be accomplished there.<br>
	"This new center is a part of the mosaic of the Armenian <br>
community of Los Angeles County," Yaroslavsky said. The new center <br>
will help newly arrived immigrants to adapt to their respective <br>
communities as well as helping them become US citizens, <br>
Yaroslavsky said, in light of new and changing legislation.<br>
	In recalling the birth of the new Gomideh, Lousararian said <br>
that the somewhat hesitant steps taken toward the establishment of <br>
this center will be chronicled in the history of this regions <br>
Armenian community.<br>
	"The ARFs history is marked by service to the community. <br>
Incidentally, the ARF was born out of the need to defend the <br>
Armenian people and in order to provide physical and moral support <br>
at an important juncture in its history," Lousararian said.<br>
	"It is not a coincidence then that wherever an Armenian <br>
community undergoes expansion, the necessity to establish an <br>
Armenian center also arises and the ARF responds," he added.<br>
	According to Lousararian, the establishment of a new Gomideh <br>
was approved by the ARF Central Committee on March 20, 1996, and <br>
as it coincided with the 100th anniversary of the seizure of Bank <br>
Ottoman, it was called "Papken Suni" after the leader of that <br>
operation.<br>
	The center also houses the local ANC chapter, the ARF-Youth <br>
Organizations "Hrayr Tjokhk" Chapter , and will soon welcome the <br>
local ARS chapter.<br>
	ARF Central Committee member Ara Khanjian delineated the two <br>
functions that an Armenian center serves: to meet the needs of the <br>
local community and to serve as link between the Diaspora and <br>
Armenia and Karabakh.<br>
	The final speaker of the day was Koko Mgrdichian, <br>
representing the newest ARF-YO chapter, who presented a brief <br>
background of its namesake-Hrayr Tjokhk-and on behalf of the <br>
chapters other members pledged to uphold the legacy of the turn-<br>
of-the-century national hero who waged a national liberation <br>
struggle against the Ottoman Empire.<br>
<p>
