        PRIME MINISTER SARGISSIAN MEETS WITH THE PRESIDENT OF THE<br>
        CIS INTERSTATE BANK<br>
<p>
 YEREVAN, DECEMBER 16, ARMENPRESS.<br>
 On December 13, the Prime Minister of the Republic of Armenia Armen<br>
 Sargissian received the President of the CIS Interstate Bank Vladimir<br>
 Mashits. During the meeting, the sides discussed issues related to<br>
 the activities of the Interstate Bank, the establishement of the<br>
 Bank's branch in Armenia, and the expansion of cooperation.<br>
 The President of the Central Bank of the Republic of Armenia Bagrat<br>
 Asatrian was present at the meeting.<br>
<p>
        PRIME MINISTER SARGISSIAN MEETS WITH THE REPRESENTATIVE OF THE<br>
        INTERNATIONAL FINANCIAL COMPANY<br>
<p>
 YEREVAN, DECEMBER 16, ARMENPRESS.<br>
 The Prime Minister of the Republic of Armenia Armen Sargissian<br>
 Director of the General Financial Services of the International<br>
 Financial Company of the World Bank, Mr. Philip Litart.<br>
 During the meeting the sides discussed the possible investments of<br>
 the International Financial Company in Armenia, especially in the<br>
 private sector of Armenia's economy.<br>
 The Extraordinary and Plenipotentiary Representative of the World<br>
 Bank in Armenia Vahram Nersisiants was present at the meeting.<br>
<p>
        SAMSUNG OPENS ITS STORE IN YEREVAN<br>
<p>
 YEREVAN, DECEMBER 16, ARMENPRESS.<br>
 The internationally famous South Korean "Samsung Electronics" firm<br>
 has opened its first store in Yerevan. More than 80 types of<br>
 technical equipment is in stock: TV sets, video cameras, telephones,<br>
 fax machines, microwave ovens, etc.<br>
 On December 13, the presentation of the store took place in Yerevan<br>
 with participation of numerous representatives of mass media. During<br>
 the presentation a raffle took place. Many of those present won<br>
 various Samsung products as prizes.<br>
<p>
        SIMON OSBOURNE POSITIVELY EVALUATES THE ACTIVITIES OF THE<br>
        CONSTITUTIONAL COURT OF THE REPUBLIC OF ARMENIA<br>
<p>
 YEREVAN, DECEMBER 16, ARMENPRESS.<br>
 On December 6, the Coordinator of OSCE International Observers during<br>
 the presidential elections in Armenia Simon Osbourne participated in<br>
 the meeting called "Armenia: Transition to Democracy," organized by<br>
 the "Zorian Institute" in London. During that meeting, Mr. Osbourne<br>
 stated that in general the voting process was correct and in<br>
 accordance with the elections laws.<br>
 According to Mr. Osbourne, representatives of the presidential<br>
 candidates were present in 93.3% of the polling stations. The only<br>
 open questions are the voting of the military personnel and the<br>
 discrepance between the numbers submitted by the Central Electoral<br>
 Committee and the number of voting stubs. However, according to Mr.<br>
 Osbourne, no one can give an exhaustive answer to these questions.<br>
 Mr. Osbourne also doubted the numbers submitted by the opposition. he<br>
 said that the opposition often tends to exaggerate.<br>
 As for the decision of the Constitutional Court of the Republic of<br>
 Armenia, Mr. Osbourne said, "Despite the fact that many people in<br>
 Yerevan and around the world are not happy with the Constitutional<br>
 Court's decision, I can not deny that the Constitutional Court, as<br>
 well as the authorities, reacted positively to my statement and<br>
 announced that they will take our suggestions into consideration and<br>
 will re-examine the voting process, particularly, in Yerevan."<br>
 "I think, continued Ms. Osbourne, that Armenia is in the transitional<br>
 phase of the road to democracy, and this phase will take a long time.<br>
 Any little step towards improving the situation, the improvements in<br>
 the area of administration and electoral processes, is an important<br>
 step for establishment of democratic structures in the country.<br>
 Addressing some of these questions by the Constitutional Court's<br>
 decision is a positive step. And that is very important," concluded<br>
 Mr. Osbourne.<br>
<p>
        "DRO" ESTABLISHED BY THE ARMENIAN REVOLUTIONARY FEDERATION<br>
<p>
 YEREVAN, DECEMBER 16, ARMENPRESS.<br>
 Recently, the trial of the "Dro" case ended in Yerevan. The 11<br>
 accused persons were found guilty of their crimes sentenced to<br>
 various degrees of punishment. The question that interests a lot of<br>
 people after the trial is the connection between the Dro group and<br>
 the Armenian Revolutionary Federation (ARF) (Dashnak Party).<br>
 It is stated in the final verdict, that the Board of Judges of the<br>
 Supreme Court of the Republic of Armenia considers the following<br>
 facts as established and proven.<br>
 The accused A. Artsruni and A. Harmandayan (ARF members since 1981<br>
 and 1982) continued their activities as party members in Armenia and<br>
 carried out orders given by the party. In order to implement the<br>
 party's suggestions in the area of economy, in 1992-1993 prepared the<br>
 proposal and program of the "Dro" organization, and later, the<br>
 charter and all the necessary founding documents for the "Dro"<br>
 organization. Thus, violating the laws of the Republic of Armenia, a<br>
 secret intelligence organization (Dro) based on military discipline<br>
 has been established in Armenia. The purpose of this organization<br>
 was to uphold the principle of the ARF and at the same time to gather<br>
 political, military, economic, diplomantic and other information.<br>
 The economic branch of the Dro was also established. It engaged in<br>
 illegal economic activities. It also engaged in terrorist activities<br>
 against people who had ever said or done anything against any ARF<br>
 members.<br>
 The verdict is based on the "Dro" organization's charter and other<br>
 important documents, which clearly state that the economic<br>
 intelligence unit of the "Dro" was established by the decision of the<br>
 ARF's highest body and operated in conditions of absolute secrecy.<br>
 Thus, according to the Court, there are serious grouds which prove<br>
 the "Dro" organization was created by the Armenian Revolutionary<br>
 Federation.<br>
<p>
        MAIN TRENDS OF THE 1997 STATE BUDGET DISCUSSED<br>
<p>
 YEREVAN, DECEMBER 16, ARMENPRESS.<br>
 On December 14, the President of the Republic of Armenia Levon<br>
 Ter-Petrossian held a meeting-consultation to discussed the main<br>
 trends of the 1997 state budget.<br>
 The President of the National Assembly of the Republic of Armenia<br>
 Babken Ararktsian, the Prime Minister Armen Sargissian, the Minister<br>
 of Defense Vazgen Sargissian, the Minister of Internal Affairs and<br>
 National Security Serge Sargissian, the Minister of Finance Levon<br>
 Barkhudarian, the Minister of Foreign Affairs Alexander Arzumanian,<br>
 the Yerevan Mayor Vano Siradeghian, the President of the Central Bank<br>
 Bagrat Asatrian, and the Senior Advisor to the Armenian President<br>
 Jirair Libaridian were present at the meeting.<br>
<p>
        TWO CHURCHES REOPENED IN APARAN<br>
<p>
 APARAN, DECEMBER 16, ARMENPRESS.<br>
 There will be two more acting churches in the Aparan region next<br>
 year. After 60 years of closure, the Surb Khach (St. Cross) church<br>
 (5th century A.D.) was renovated and recently reopened in Aparan<br>
 (north-eastern Armenia). Another church will reopen in the Kuchak<br>
 village. This church was built in 1901 by the local community, but<br>
 was closed in 1930s by the Soviet authorities.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
