<title>Groong Network: The Eyes of Armenia - Part 2 of 2</title>
<h1>The Eyes of Armenia - Part 2 of 2</h1>
<i>Chavoush@aol.com</i><br>
<i>Mon, 16 Dec 96 14:30:43 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#140">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#140">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#140">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#140">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0141.html">Asbed Bedrossian: "OMRI Digest 12/16/96"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0139.html">Chavoush@aol.com: "The Eyes of Armenia - Part 1 of 2"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
HEADLINE:  The Eyes of Armenia  Vision: A land groping toward a brighter<br>
future gets help from Orange County doctors who bring hope, one clear eye at<br>
a time.<br>
SOURCE:  The Orange County Register, December 8, 1996<br>
<p>
Part 2 of 2<br>
<p>
On the night Hill is to return to the United States, he is to leave for the<br>
Yerevan airport at 12:30 a.m. At midnight, he finishes his last surgery, then<br>
hangs a lab coat with his name on it in the hallway of the little suite he<br>
shares with Ohanesian.  <br>
<p>
The two leave their coats hanging there after every trip. They want the<br>
people of this hospital to know they will be coming back.  <br>
<p>
Eyes make up one-five hundredth of the body, and if they are the window to<br>
the soul, the souls of Armenia have been blessed with acutely compelling<br>
windows. <br>
<p>
Like their dark, powerful coffee steaming in demi-cups, black eyes are a<br>
distinguishing trait that give a marked soberness to a people of uncommonly<br>
gracious humor. <br>
<p>
In a few days of medicine in Yerevan, it is as if all those eyes have seen<br>
trouble and have come for a cure. <br>
<p>
With news having spread that the Orbis team, as well as Ohanesian and Hill,<br>
are in town, bedlam reigns outside Republican Eye Hospital. Guards are called<br>
to maintain order. The Orbis director, a veteran observer of some of the<br>
world's most remote and extensive desperation, calls on hospital director<br>
Alex Malaian to appeal to the swelling crowd. <br>
<p>
Inside, the sound of knuckles knocking on windows frequently interrupts Roger<br>
Ohanesian's examinations in a room where the hospital cat patters quietly and<br>
freely about.  <br>
<p>
"You see cases here that you just don't see other places," Ohanesian says.  <br>
<p>
Particularly pronounced are diabetes-related cases and ailments found in the<br>
youth of Armenia that aren't usually manifested in Americans until their<br>
later years. <br>
<p>
Ohanesian is especially concerned about diabetes in the country and hopes to<br>
do a study to determine why it is so common.  <br>
<p>
Milton James, an Orbis doctor making his first visit to Armenia, says his<br>
group does not usually see the variety and severity of problems it has seen<br>
in Armenia. <br>
<p>
Some causes are sadly obvious.  <br>
<p>
On his first trip to Armenia, Ohanesian met Seyran Hasratian, brought to him<br>
straight out of combat in Karabakh.  <br>
<p>
Hasratian's battalion had been pinned down by an Azerbaijan tank. The soldier<br>
charged the enemy tank and lobbed an explosive down its hatch. <br>
<p>
An ill-intentioned vehicle of war was the last thing Hasratian saw clearly<br>
four years ago. The explosion that freed his comrades from enemy fire took so<br>
much of his sight that the gallant soldier now has to be led through crowded<br>
halls of Republican Eye Hospital, with his large, powerful hand gripping his<br>
sister's elbow. <br>
<p>
In 1992, Ohanesian operated from 10 p.m. until sunrise removing shrapnel from<br>
the 32-year-old soldier's eyes. <br>
<p>
Later, he arranged to have Hasratian brought to New York, where a specialist<br>
repaired a detached retina.<br>
<p>
He also had a corneal transplant _ usually a procedure in which only a<br>
portion of the cornea has to be replaced, typically no more than 8<br>
millimeters. In Hasratian's, however, shell fragments so badly damaged his<br>
eye that 11 millimeters _ surgeons call it a "wall to wall" transplant _ had<br>
to be restored. <br>
<p>
Now the soldier is back, his dramatically thick glasses of little use, as the<br>
patched cornea has clouded over. As always, his sister attends to his care<br>
and cries when she hears that no help is available at the moment. <br>
<p>
He needs a fresh cornea. When Ohanesian returns next spring, he will take one<br>
with him and do another corneal transplant inside the already repaired one. <br>
<p>
If Ohanesian's efforts are successful, patients such as Hasratian someday<br>
will not have to look to America for corneas.  <br>
<p>
Legislation, inspired by Ohanesian and written by American doctors, is on the<br>
table in the young republic to create a cornea bank for Armenia.  <br>
<p>
Self-reliance is a tough lesson in a country where the outsides of homes<br>
often go unrepaired because residents accustomed to Soviet ways say, "That's<br>
the state's job." <br>
<p>
But American eye doctors whose mission is not only to heal but to train are<br>
making their own progress in Armenia. <br>
<p>
The medical school now uses a curriculum drafted by Ohanesian. And, through<br>
Hill, Ohanesian and Kupperman's efforts, Armen Vartanian, from the Republican<br>
Eye Hospital, is at UCI this winter on a medical fellowship. <br>
<p>
The hospital that has become Ohanesian and Hill's distant annex of sorts is a<br>
five-story, 500-bed, distinctly Soviet facility of proletarian design. It<br>
sits in an unremarkable section of Yerevan, and for several days this October<br>
the sidewalks leading through its stout iron gates are a path toward promise.<br>
 <br>
<p>
They take buses as far as they go, from distant parts of the city and even<br>
<i>&gt;from hours away in Georgia, and then walk as needed _ these Armenians with</i><br>
storybook images of America and its doctors.  <br>
<p>
And even late at night on unlighted streets, if the doctors venture onto<br>
those same sidewalks, they will be stopped by patients wanting examinations<br>
curbside.<br>
<p>
On the fourth floor of Republican Eye Hospital, three mementos hang behind<br>
the desk of director Alex Malaian.  <br>
<p>
There is a stone bust of his grandfather, the first generation of Malaian<br>
doctors. There is a portrait of his father, who started this hospital 40<br>
years ago, a man who died at 42 but not before establishing a precedent of<br>
health care that his son proudly continues. <br>
<p>
Between those family icons is a photo of Roger Ohanesian and his family.  <br>
<p>
If an explanation for such prominence is needed, it can be found down the<br>
hall on a wall next to an operating room, where a copper plaque says: <br>
<p>
"Operating Room named for Roger Ohanesian. Token of gradidute."  <br>
<p>
Since 1992, the goodwill of American medical companies and doctors who know<br>
little of Armenia but much of its unofficial ambassador, Ohanesian, has sent<br>
$3.5 million worth of medicine, equipment and supplies to Armenia. <br>
<p>
Microscopes and lamps throughout Republican Eye Hospital are from American<br>
companies solicited by Ohanesian. Surgical scrubs carry the stenciled names<br>
of distant American hospitals. Eyedrops, antibiotics, anti-inflammatories and<br>
lens implants are from American medical suppliers. <br>
<p>
The American doctors work for free, pay for their own travel and rearrange<br>
their own clinic schedules to accommodate their two-week, semiannual visits<br>
to Armenia. <br>
<p>
"I think (the trips to Armenia) appeal to something very basic in any<br>
physician," Ohanesian says. "It is the basic instinct to want to do something<br>
charitable." <br>
<p>
If he were Ross Perot or a Forbes, Ohanesian says, he would simply buy<br>
Armenia whatever it needs. But:  <br>
<p>
"I don't have those kind of resources," he says. "But I do have my talents. I<br>
know that I'm a good teacher and a capable ophthalmic surgeon. <br>
<p>
"I would feel badly if I didn't do something."<br>
<p>
It is a conviction first evident in Ohanesian's grandfather, who, after<br>
immigrating to the United States in the early 1900s, returned to Armenia to<br>
join the war against the Turks.  <br>
<p>
Ohanesian, 57, was raised in Waterford, Mass., and learned early about the<br>
hardships of his ancestral home.  <br>
<p>
As a pre-teen boy, Roger Ohanesian had a playmate named Lilly.    <br>
<p>
Shortly after World War II, Lilly's father announced he was returning to<br>
Armenia to re-establish life there. He would send for his family once he got<br>
settled. Meanwhile, he would write and report how things were there.  <br>
<p>
"I will send back a photograph," Lilly's father said. "If we are standing in<br>
the photograph, you will know things are good. If we are sitting, it means<br>
things are not good." <br>
<p>
Weeks later, a photo came to Lilly's mailbox. It was of Lilly's father and<br>
his family and they were lying on the floor.<br>
<p>
In 22 years in Orange County, Roger Ohanesian has made a comfortable life for<br>
his family after moving here for the weather and to use his Harvard-trained<br>
skills in a growing medical market.  <br>
<p>
("When I left Boston," he says, "my uncle said to me, 'Roger, why would you<br>
leave Boston? It is the hub of medicine.' And I said to him: 'But remember,<br>
it is near the hub that the wheel moves the slowest.' ") <br>
<p>
Now, with the memory of a playmate's family pictured prostrate, the doctor's<br>
passion is to help a struggling country pull itself up.  <br>
<p>
"He is an angel," says Osheen Keshishian, editor of the Armenian Observer<br>
newspaper in Los Angeles. "He is considered a miracle worker in Armenia." <br>
<p>
All he wanted to be was a doctor. <br>
<p>
As a child, someone teased Roger Ohanesian with the "rich man, poor man,"<br>
game in which the buttons of a shirt are tapped to a nursery rhyme: <br>
<p>
"Rich man, poor man, beggar man, thief. Doctor, lawyer, Indian chief," the<br>
game went. <br>
<p>
Ohanesian remembers tearing off the buttons from his shirt that didn't<br>
represent "doctor." <br>
<p>
In high school his aspirations were more narrowly defined. Beside his photo<br>
in a yearbook, he wrote that he wanted to be an ophthalmologist. <br>
<p>
His grandmother was a reason why.  <br>
<p>
Her name was Nevart Roupenian, but Roger and his sister called her "Rocko,"<br>
because she used to sit in her window and rock.  <br>
<p>
As a little boy he felt her warm embrace with deep hugs. As a teen-ager, he<br>
saw Rocko watch television an inch from her face.  <br>
<p>
Cataracts took his grandmother's sight and inspired Roger Ohanesian's vision.<br>
<p>
<p>
The Boy Scouts helped, too. <br>
<p>
"I remember reading Boy's Life," Ohanesian says, "and there would always be<br>
some true-life story about a Boy Scout saving someone's life. I went around<br>
looking for people in trouble."  <br>
<p>
Thirty years after earning Eagle Scout status, Ohanesian did, in fact, help<br>
save a life, as he and another motorist pulled a passenger from a burning<br>
vehicle on a freeway.) <br>
<p>
He was not his family's first doctor, nor its most recognized.  That would be<br>
Varastade Kazajian. <br>
<p>
In a South Boston movie theater during World War I, Flora Kazajian, future<br>
mother of Roger Ohanesian, was watching a newsreel and translating it for her<br>
Armenian-speaking mother.  The newsreel was about a young doctor who had<br>
developed methods for reconstructing war-damaged faces of soldiers in Europe.<br>
 <br>
<p>
"That's my brother! That's my brother," Roger Ohanesian's grandmother<br>
shouted.  <br>
<p>
It was, in fact, Kazajian, one of this country's first reconstructive<br>
surgeons, and the newsreel was of him being knighted by Britain's King George<br>
VI for his medical service during wartime.  <br>
<p>
When he first came to this country, Ohanesian's uncle worked at Worcester<br>
Wire near Boston. Later he became a dentist. Using a combination of skills,<br>
Kazajian used wire to connect the mouth and the eyebrows of a soldier whose<br>
jawbone had been destroyed _ and launched his career in reconstructive<br>
surgery.  <br>
<p>
By raising his eyebrows, the soldier was able to open and close his mouth.  <br>
<p>
Ingenuity, the Armenian way: Use what you have if you don't have what you<br>
need.    <br>
<p>
In Stepanakert, the capital of Karabakh, the great-nephew of the knighted<br>
dentist-turned-reconstructive surgeon uses a utility knife when tweezers<br>
aren't available.  <br>
<p>
Here, there is a need for a "miracle worker."<br>
<p>
It would take, it seems, at least a miracle to restore this region of only<br>
150,000 to the reasonable living conditions it enjoyed before successfully<br>
resisting Azerbaijan's invasion, at a terrible cost.  <br>
<p>
Major buildings are without roofs, gutted by missiles and turned to great<br>
stone sieves by artillery fire.  <br>
<p>
Soldiers are as prevalent as civilians, and the very air is a shawl of unrest<br>
around the burdened shoulders of these, the most beseiged Armenians. <br>
<p>
When Ohanesian speaks to various Armenian civic groups in the United States,<br>
one question, he says, is always asked:  <br>
<p>
"And what of Karabakh?"<br>
<p>
Two years into a cease-fire, the partial answer comes from a 19-year-old<br>
soldier too wary of persecution to have his name appear even in a foreign<br>
newspaper. <br>
<p>
"I lost four brothers and four cousins in the war," he says.<br>
<p>
"There is no one in Karabakh who did not lose a family member or a friend."<br>
<p>
There is a prosthetics factory in Stepanakert. War created that need.    <br>
<p>
There are, says Melic Agopjanian, Karabakh's minister of culture, 7,000-8,000<br>
invalids of war.  <br>
<p>
"We are allowed to have problems," the minister says, "and allowed to fight<br>
to not have them tomorrow. But when you see peace, it is hard to go back to<br>
war. It is like a bad dream that is past." <br>
<p>
Then, at lunch welcoming the American doctor, the minister raises a cordial<br>
glass of Petrov vodka and says:  <br>
<p>
"Let us drink to all doctors, to those who do not cause injury, but to those<br>
who heal wounds caused by others."  <br>
<p>
On a Sunday after examining 100 or more citizens of Karabakh in a clinic<br>
without so much as tweezers, Ohanesian's answer to "what of Karabakh" is on a<br>
folded piece of brown paper he has tucked in his shirt pocket. <br>
<p>
Antibiotics. Anti-inflammatories. Dilators. Anesthetics. Glaucoma meds.<br>
Reichart tonometer. Functioning slit lamp. Keratonometer . . . <br>
<p>
"For less than $10,000 Karabakh could be fully equipped (for eye care),"<br>
Ohanesian says. "I am concerned, because supplies are running out and<br>
equipment is falling apart."  <br>
<p>
And demand to save the beautiful eyes of Armenia does not lessen.  <br>
<p>
In the antiquated operating room of Republican Eye Hospital, stooped over his<br>
teen-age patient,  Roger Ohanesian sees only a single need: to rescue the<br>
vision of one child, whose letter three years ago was a prayer. <br>
<p>
"I want to believe you haven't forgotten me ..."<br>
<p>
Ohanesian does not speak the mother language, except in broken attempts close<br>
enough to lead to eventual understanding.  <br>
<p>
But he tries, nicknaming Christine, "aghvor aghchik."    He knows little<br>
about her, except that she is his son's age and her face reminds him of old<br>
pictures of his grandmother. <br>
<p>
So he calls her "beautiful girl." <br>
<p>
Upon returning to Laguna Beach, the doctor checks records to find out more<br>
about her. <br>
<p>
Her name, he learns, is Christine Ohanesian. <br>
<p>
NAME: Roger Ohanesian<br>
AGE: 57<br>
HOME: Laguna Beach<br>
OCCUPATION: Eye surgeon<br>
FAMILY: Wife, Eileen; son, Andrew<br>
ETC.: Likes toy electric trains and has one that passes through<br>
the walls of his game room. Has three dogs: Mulligan (Labrador<br>
retriever), Max (German shepherd), Maggie (English bulldog).<br>
<p>
NAME: Richard Hill<br>
AGE: 41<br>
HOME: Irvine<br>
OCCUPATION: Eye surgeon, professor UCI<br>
FAMILY: Wife, Melissa; sons, Travis and Ricky<br>
ETC.: Makes jewelry from cut stones, including his and Melissa's<br>
wedding bands. Is working to establish an international chair in<br>
ophthalmology at UCI.<br>
<p>
CHART: ABOUT THE ORGANIZATION<br>
<p>
Orbis International is a nonprofit organization that travels<br>
year-round to regions where eye care is acutely needed.<br>
<p>
At local hospitals, patients are examined and screened for surgery aboard the<br>
Orbis DC-10, equipped with a state-of-the-art operating room in the rear of<br>
the plane and a lecture room in the front, where native doctors are taught<br>
modern medical procedures.  <br>
<p>
In 14 years, Orbis has traveled to 74 countries, treated nearly 22,000<br>
patients and trained almost 35,000 doctors, nurses and healthcare workers. <br>
<p>
For more information about Orbis International, call (800) ORBISUS.<br>
 <br>
For more information about the work of Southern California eye<br>
doctors in Armenia, call (714) 493-5412.<br>
