<title>Groong Network: The Eyes of Armenia - Part 1 of 2</title>
<h1>The Eyes of Armenia - Part 1 of 2</h1>
<i>Chavoush@aol.com</i><br>
<i>Mon, 16 Dec 96 14:30:36 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#139">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#139">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#139">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#139">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0140.html">Chavoush@aol.com: "The Eyes of Armenia - Part 2 of 2"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0138.html">Chavoush@aol.com: "Armenian News 12/16/96"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
HEADLINE:  The Eyes of Armenia  Vision: A land groping toward a brighter<br>
future gets help from Orange County doctors who bring hope, one clear eye at<br>
a time.<br>
SOURCE:  The Orange County Register, December 8, 1996<br>
<p>
The snowy, ancient head of Mount Ararat catches the first sun and sprays a<br>
soft, rosy light toward the windows of this operating room, where a child<br>
sleeps in  anesthetized peace.<br>
<p>
Noah's ark, it's said, landed on that mountain, and the first rainbow was<br>
God's contract that nature would never again destroy itself.<br>
<p>
This close to holy ground, hope is an instinct, an extra sense that mercy<br>
follows long suffering; that peace follows war; that freedom follows<br>
oppression; that prosperity follows struggle.<br>
<p>
Hope that sight can be restored to clouded eyes.<br>
<p>
And so a sleeping Armenian child dreams of waking to a clear view of that<br>
mountain.<br>
<p>
But it is not the God of Noah she turns to for a miracle, but an American<br>
doctor.<br>
<p>
A teen-ager named Christine sleeps in guarded quiet while Roger Ohanesian of<br>
Laguna Beach slides the thinnest of scalpels across the exterior of her left<br>
eyeball, cutting away darkness for a child who said to him:<br>
<p>
"Do not abandon me."<br>
<p>
In 1993, Christine came to Republican Eye Hospital in Yerevan because she had<br>
heard an American doctor was there.<br>
<p>
Ohanesian treated her for uveitis glaucoma, a progressive disease that, like<br>
many disorders here, is seen more often in these children than those in<br>
America.<br>
<p>
She was 13 when he first operated to save her sight and to relieve the<br>
discomfort of the painful ailment. <br>
<p>
After Ohanesian returned to Laguna Beach, he received a letter addressed<br>
"Dear Mr. Roger" and signed "Christine" that said:<br>
<p>
"I want to believe you haven't forgotten me and my fate excites you as much<br>
as the fate of the American children who are under your treatment. I envy<br>
them, because I trust in you. I met you by chance and began to hope for the<br>
best.<br>
<p>
"After your leaving I began to see badly again. My parents' unhappy faces and<br>
the doctors' avoiding answers made me understand that they are unable to save<br>
me. Again I remembered you. If only you were here and helped me again. You<br>
are the only one who could help me ..."<br>
<p>
Complications from other procedures left Christine with hemorrhagic<br>
 choroidal detachment, a condition in which fluid is trapped behind the lens<br>
of the eye, causing severe pain.<br>
<p>
At Harvard Eye Associates, one of three offices he and partners started in<br>
south Orange County, the doctor would operate with ultramodern equipment in<br>
pristine surroundings.<br>
<p>
But this dank operating room in Yerevan is 6,000 miles and a world away from<br>
those facilities. The equipment is sufficient because most of it has been<br>
donated by American physicians, including the Armenian American Medical<br>
Society, who learned of Ohanesian's work in Armenia.<br>
<p>
Still, a look around this operating room is a vision of medicine as it used<br>
to be: tin pans (not stainless steel) hold instruments and assorted supplies.<br>
The patient rests not on a bed or table but on a gurney with wheels like the<br>
wayward coasters of a shopping cart.<br>
<p>
When Ohanesian operates at home, masks, gloves and gowns are used once, then<br>
discarded. Here, everything is recycled _ surgical gowns boiled so many times<br>
they are frayed and hold the scent of disinfectant.<br>
<p>
Here, cotton swabs are scarce but ingenuity is plentiful, so this hospital<br>
uses filters it gets from a cigarette company to serve the same purpose. The<br>
nurses even refer to the sponges as "cigarettes."<br>
<p>
But in these conditions, primitive by U.S. standards, eye surgeries take<br>
place daily that are sophisticated decades beyond the facilities in which<br>
they are performed.<br>
<p>
And not just by American doctors but by the staff members of this hospital,<br>
who, thanks to twice-yearly visits here, have been trained and tutored by<br>
Ohanesian, by Rick Hill of the University of California, Irvine, who just<br>
completed his sixth trip, and by other Southern California doctors who have<br>
donated time and skills.<br>
<p>
Hill has a favorite saying about the country to which he, without Ohanesian's<br>
roots, has attached himself by donating time, money and services:  <br>
<p>
"Don't go to Armenia if you can't take a joke," Hill says _ a reference<br>
applicable to the Armenians' remarkable delight in humor but also meaning<br>
that good-natured tolerance is a necessity.<br>
<p>
Even when electricity is regular, microscope bulbs burn out, with no<br>
replacements. And in winter, before the local doctors can sterilize<br>
themselves for surgery, ice must be broken from the water pans in the frosty<br>
operating room. <br>
<p>
In the absence of a sclerol depressor, a common accessory for American<br>
doctors, Ohanesian uses a cap from a ballpoint pen. And when simple tweezers<br>
were not available in one clinic, he used a Swiss Army knife to extract an<br>
errant suture that had caused inflammation. <br>
<p>
With 10 trips to his ancestral homeland as lessons, Ohanesian has learned to<br>
do the best he can with whatever is available.    <br>
<p>
It is a theme here.<br>
<p>
Since the day Noah landed on Ararat the people of Armenia have invoked inner<br>
resources when war, earthquakes, genocide or political oppression turned<br>
prosperity to dearth. <br>
<p>
Before World War I, Armenia included land now occupied by Turkey. (The<br>
 boundaries, like many Armenian assertions about the history of the region,<br>
are disputed by Turkey and its supporters.) <br>
<p>
<i>&gt;From about 1915 to 1920, Armenia suffered a defining tragedy. In what some</i><br>
call "war" and others "genocide," the Armenian population was devastated.  <br>
<p>
Many nations have recognized the action as a holocaust, which Turkey<br>
disputes. The estimate of the number of Armenians who died ranges 600,000-1.8<br>
million; Turkey's estimate is 300,000. <br>
<p>
Death established a familiarity with suffering _ and a reference point<br>
against which future Armenians could gauge the harshness of life _ a twisted<br>
parable reminding that horror, at least, isn't eternal.  <br>
<p>
"The ghastly procession of the dead marches on," wrote a Presbyterian<br>
missionary from Urmia (in modern Iran) in 1915. "A great many are able to get<br>
plain wooden coffins for their dead now, but the great mass are just dropped<br>
into the great trench of<br>
rotting humanity. As I stand at my window in the morning I see one after<br>
another of the little bodies carried by, wrapped mostly in a ragged piece of<br>
patch-work; and the condition of the living is more pitiful ...<br>
<p>
"A dozen times a day I pray: 'Oh, Lord, how long?' "<br>
<p>
It is a question not quickly answered.<br>
<p>
Armenia survived massacre only to be shrunk under Josef Stalin, whose system<br>
of divide and conquer gave a part of Armenia to Azerbaijan, under Soviet rule<br>
that extended from 1920 to 1991.    A portion of that land remains disputed,<br>
and an uneasy cease-fire exists with Azerbaijan over Nagorno-Karabakh, a spit<br>
of land for which thousands (neither Azerbaijan nor Armenia have released<br>
official figures) died in 1988-94. <br>
<p>
Modern Armenia borders Turkey, Azerbaijan, Iran and Georgia and is smaller<br>
than Maryland. In 1988 a portion of the tiny republic suffered destruction by<br>
an earthquake that killed more than 25,000 and from which many people are<br>
still recovering.  <br>
<p>
When the Soviet Union collapsed, Armenia was left to create a new republic,<br>
gladly freed, but unsteady as a toddler taking first steps toward democracy. <br>
<p>
At the beginning of this decade, the well-being of Armenia was tenuous, a<br>
whole nation loosed like lifelong captives, suddenly dangerously alone. <br>
<p>
Because of its strained relations with Turkey and Azerbaijan, and because of<br>
inner conflict in Georgia, the landlocked country's need for oil became so<br>
great that it relied on the ridiculous but necessary means of getting fuel<br>
into the country via airplanes.  <br>
<p>
Then came earthquake, war and some of the harshest winters in modern times,<br>
when even the relatively well-off of Armenia reduced their homes to one room<br>
and burned furniture for fuel.   <br>
<p>
Armenia, which once had one of the highest standards of living of all Soviet<br>
states, saw its national income fall by 75 percent in 1991-93, when the<br>
annual inflation rate averaged 3,730 percent.  <br>
<p>
Now, with trade routes opened through Georgia and improving political<br>
relations with Turkey, Armenia is a country eager to earn its place in the<br>
world market: By the end of last year the inflation rate was only 2 percent,<br>
and agricultural production increased 101.4 percent in 1995-96. <br>
<p>
More than 40 American companies are doing business in Armenia, where a<br>
British bank recently opened an office, responding to the new need for<br>
international financing. <br>
<p>
It is a country of great contrasts, where a link to the Internet is more<br>
accessible than good paper products; where former "state" artists whose<br>
commissioned work was rewarded with resort vacations during communist times<br>
now sell their own creations in the market for the price of art supplies. <br>
<p>
Here, there is evidence that communism was, for some, a shelter from<br>
self-reliance. Here, too, are signs of a new government's struggles to keep<br>
freedom's leash from becoming a noose.  <br>
<p>
Recent presidential elections led to street protests and charges of ballot<br>
tampering, which were met Soviet style by calling in tanks and soldiers to<br>
discourage public assembly. <br>
<p>
Here, taxi drivers are learning capitalism by gouging foreigners, while 70<br>
percent of the country (according to U.N. figures) is umemployed. Those with<br>
jobs had an official annual income of about $360 per capita in 1995.  <br>
<p>
Freedom has not broken the grip of hardship: Winters remain brutal, and<br>
electricity is a rationed blessing.  <br>
<p>
"We don't know what is happiness," says Marina Yedigarian, a medical student.<br>
"Our people have a very big struggle for new life. It isn't a good one, but<br>
it is better than the one before."<br>
<p>
It is a struggle shared by Armenians who have relocated to the United States<br>
_ the diaspora.  <br>
<p>
Armenia's population is about 3.5 million. There are nearly one-third that<br>
number of Armenians now in the United States. Of the estimated 1 million<br>
Armenian Americans, half are in California, with about 400,000 in Los Angeles<br>
and Orange counties. (In Yerevan, the country's capital, taxi drivers refer<br>
to Los Angeles as "Los Armenias.") <br>
<p>
Various support groups say $10 million-$25 million a month goes to Armenia<br>
<i>&gt;from family and friends in the United States and France.  </i><br>
<p>
Officially, the U.S. government has budgeted $95 million for Armenian relief<br>
next year _ second only to the amount set aside for Israel in per capita<br>
foreign aid. <br>
<p>
"During Communism (Armenians in America) were connected to Armenia in a<br>
limited sense," says Lena Kaimian, assistant director of the Armenian<br>
Assembly of America, a lobbying group in Los Angeles. "We were displaced<br>
after the genocide; now there is the opportunity for us to reconnect with our<br>
brethren in Armenia and Nagorno-Karabakh." <br>
<p>
In Armenia and Karabakh, the history of conflict is written in scars and<br>
crippled limbs and powder burns on the men who earned their country's<br>
reputation as fierce warriors, and in hard lines on the faces of women who<br>
waited and hoped. <br>
<p>
And too often, signs of struggle _ whether punctures from the thousands of<br>
land mines that still terrorize Karabakh, or disease resulting from poor<br>
health care _ are first evident in the dark eyes of Armenians whose<br>
bloodlines cross with Roger Ohanesian, who has come here for certain but<br>
unexplored reasons. <br>
<p>
It is an October Thursday that began at 8 a.m. It is now 2:30 p.m., and the<br>
doctor takes his only break for a lunch of fried eggplant, boiled eggs and<br>
grilled kabob at an airport medical-clinic lunchroom. <br>
<p>
Leaving the examination room, he ducked his way through a hallway full of<br>
needy patients desperate to see the American doctor.  <br>
<p>
The morning's patients included a 5-year-old boy who, one month ago, was<br>
struck by shrapnel from a latent land mine.  The boy's parents look to the<br>
American prayerfully, but, having traveled here twice a year for the past<br>
five years, Ohanesian has seen enough of these cases to know that the boy's<br>
vision will not improve. <br>
<p>
"What about surgery?" the mother asks. <br>
<p>
"No," the American says.<br>
<p>
"Medical help?"<br>
<p>
"No."<br>
<p>
"What about pupil surgery?"<br>
<p>
"No."<br>
<p>
"At this point we have to believe in God?" asks the mother, crying.<br>
<p>
"Yes," says the doctor, who wishes his reputation as a god were true.<br>
<p>
Another patient is an old woman who has heard the doctor would be in town,<br>
and has traveled many hours from an outlying city to see him.<br>
<p>
"I need your surgery," she pleads through a translator. "I know you can help<br>
me."<br>
<p>
And then she says words Ohanesian will hear too many times:<br>
<p>
"Touk eem vercheen hooses ek."<br>
<p>
They are the words that keep a lab coat with his name on it hanging<br>
year-round in a Yerevan hospital:<br>
<p>
"You are my last hope."<br>
<p>
The words stay with the doctor, but they do not define why he is here.<br>
<p>
"I haven't really examined my motives about why I'm doing this," Ohanesian<br>
says. "Maybe I'm just one of those guys who doesn't look at things too<br>
closely. <br>
<p>
"I wish I could tell you it was totally satisfying and I enjoyed every single<br>
aspect of it, but I don't. <br>
<p>
"But you don't get many chances in your life to do something altruistic. This<br>
is something that, because several things came together and because of my<br>
ancestral nationality, it presented itself. <br>
<p>
"I don't like to miss an opportunity."<br>
<p>
It is an opportunity created by war and sustained by Ohanesian's intent to<br>
ease war's effects. <br>
<p>
In 1992, a day before Ohanesian, his wife, Eileen, and son, Andrew, were to<br>
travel to London, the doctor received a fax from the minister of health in<br>
Armenia, who knew of Ohanesian through an Armenian medical association.<br>
<p>
The war, the minister said, was creating an overload of eye injuries.<br>
<p>
London was canceled, with his family's blessing, and Ohanesian was booked to<br>
Yerevan.<br>
<p>
Since that first trip, other American doctors have joined Ohanesian's trips<br>
to save the eyes of Armenia. <br>
<p>
Howard Conn, an ophthalmic plastic surgeon from Irvine, operated and lectured<br>
there in September last year.  <br>
<p>
In September 1994, Santa Ana retinal surgeon Sanford Chen saw 53 patients and<br>
performed nine surgeries in Yerevan.  <br>
<p>
In May 1995, Barry Kupperman of Irvine and Mary Davidian (formerly of Irvine,<br>
since relocated to New York) saw 320 cases and did 21 surgeries. <br>
<p>
Others have helped, this side of Armenia: John Lean, Ed Kim and Keane Ganan<br>
of Laguna Hills and Robert Ruper of Orange have operated on patients brought<br>
here by Ohanesian. <br>
<p>
In all, Southern California doctors led by Ohanesian have trained about 200<br>
eye doctors in Armenia, including about 75 surgeons. <br>
<p>
They have seen several thousand patients, about 40 percent of whom were<br>
children.  <br>
<p>
On their latest trip, Hill and Ohanesian together saw more than 1,000<br>
patients in 10 days.  <br>
<p>
Besides Ohanesian, no American has been more devoted to Armenia than Rick<br>
Hill, a glaucoma specialist from UCI. <br>
<p>
In 1994, Ohanesian told Hill he had a patient he'd like him to see and, by<br>
the way, she's in Armenia. <br>
<p>
With a week's notice, Hill joined Ohanesian's next trip, knowing little of<br>
Armenia except its great need. <br>
<p>
Now the two are so well-known in Armenia, doing follow-up checks every six<br>
months, they joke about having an international practice.<br>
<p>
For Ohanesian, devotion to the cause can be traced by bloodlines. Hill says<br>
his commitment is as easily explained. <br>
<p>
"When I see these kids who I operated on two years ago, who would be blind if<br>
I hadn't seem them, well, the answer to why I'm here is real easy," Hill<br>
says. "A lot of things are universal. Going blind means just about the same<br>
thing in any country.  <br>
<p>
"I wouldn't have much respect for someone who could help but wouldn't." <br>
<p>
On this trip to Armenia, Orbis, the New York-based international eye-care<br>
charity with a DC-10 equipped for surgery and teaching, is also in Armenia<br>
and has asked Ohanesian and Hill to be guest faculty.  <br>
<p>
Orbis' work is tightly scheduled, starting at 8 a.m., ending at 4 p.m.  <br>
<p>
But after that, Hill and Ohanesian begin second days in which crowds line up<br>
outside Republican Eye Hospital and wait long into the night, shoving to<br>
squeeze, one at a time, through the guarded hospital door. <br>
<p>
At 1:05 a.m., Hill's eyes look as if they've been under a diamond blade,<br>
rather than gazing from the other end of one.  <br>
<p>
These are the hours of his trips when Hill's inspired description of Armenia<br>
is "a severe pleasure."  <br>
<p>
He has been up since 7:30 the previous morning, doing exams, lectures and<br>
surgeries.  <br>
<p>
A surgery he could have done alone in 30 minutes has taken two hours because<br>
Hill insisted that one of Republican's staff doctors do the procedure while<br>
he assisted, so that the Armenian doctor will know how the work is done for<br>
future cases.  <br>
<p>
The doors finally swing shut behind him, and Hill leaves the operating room,<br>
on his way, he thinks, to rest.  <br>
<p>
But before he reaches his quarters _ a hospital room converted for his and<br>
Ohanesian's visits _ an old man catches Hill in the hallway. He has been<br>
waiting since the afternoon.  <br>
<p>
Hill takes the man to an examination room. He remembers having seen the<br>
patient before, a World War II veteran of the Russian Army who said to Hill:<br>
"I can't see who's responsible for this."  <br>
<p>
The old man has waited most of the day, and at 1:15 a.m. the doctor has a<br>
suggestion. <br>
<p>
On a brief visit to an inner-city market, Hill, a coin collector, saw a booth<br>
that sold magnifying glasses.  <br>
<p>
"Go to the market and get a magnifying glass," he tells the man who has<br>
waited intolerable hours to learn that nothing can be done for his condition.<br>
<p>
<p>
But he has heard the news from an American, and that seems to make a<br>
difference.  <br>
<p>
Cases like his, Hill says, "are why you sit for a couple of hours and let<br>
these doctors do the work. Because eventually they'll find a guy like this<br>
early enough that they can help."  <br>
<p>
And such cases are why Hill is working to establish an international chair in<br>
ophthalmology at UCI.  <br>
<p>
&lt;&lt;Continued&gt;&gt;<br>
