<title>Groong Network: Armenian News 12/16/96</title>
<h1>Armenian News 12/16/96</h1>
<i>Chavoush@aol.com</i><br>
<i>Mon, 16 Dec 96 14:30:29 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#138">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#138">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#138">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#138">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0139.html">Chavoush@aol.com: "The Eyes of Armenia - Part 1 of 2"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0137.html">Sanentz@aol.com: "NY/NJ/CT area netters"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Headlines of stories which follow:<br>
1.  North Osetian strip of Georgian-Russian border remains sealed off <br>
2.  Nagornyy Karabakh MPs criticize conclusion of Lisbon OSCE summit <br>
3.  Nagornyy Karabakh leader against Azerbaijan-Georgia oil pipeline <br>
4.  Salonika to show off Byzantine legacy in 1997 <br>
5.  Studio City Armenians to Open Community Center<br>
6.  Armenian Prelate Visits Salt Lake City<br>
<p>
HEADLINE: North Osetian strip of Georgian-Russian border remains sealed off <br>
SOURCE: Iberia news agency, Tbilisi, in Georgian 1320 gmt 12 Dec 96 <br>
<p>
The situation remains critical at the Larsi checkpoint in Dariali gorge on<br>
the Georgian-Russian border [linking Georgia with North Osetia], an Iberia<br>
correspondent was told at the Georgian Border Service Department. Russian<br>
border guards do not let either individuals or goods through the border from<br>
or into Georgia.   They say they are acting on the order of the director of<br>
the Russian Border Service, Gen Andrey Nikolayev. Nikolayev himself said that<br>
the decision had been taken in accordance with the December 1994 decree by<br>
Russian Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin. The decree declared a moratorium<br>
on the functioning of the border because of events in Chechnya. Nikolayev<br>
also said that the decree had not been implemented in respect of the border<br>
with Georgia until now and that it was being implemented now because the<br>
Russian government deemed it necessary. <br>
<p>
A senior official of the Georgian Border Service Department told the Iberia<br>
correspondent that Russia had virtually imposed an economic blockade on<br>
Georgia. The Russian as well as Georgian border guards permit the passage of<br>
individuals and goods from Armenia in both directions. <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Nagornyy Karabakh MPs criticize conclusion of Lisbon OSCE summit <br>
SOURCE: Interfax news agency, Moscow, in English 1650 gmt 12 Dec 96 (<br>
ITAR-TASS news agency (World Service) Moscow, in English 1941 gmt 3 Dec 96)<br>
<p>
The parliament of the self-proclaimed Nagornyy Karabakh Republic has<br>
criticized the recent Lisbon summit meeting of the Organization for Security<br>
and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) for supporting Azerbaijan's position and has<br>
questioned the wisdom of continuing to participate in the OSCE-sponsored<br>
Minsk peace process, Interfax news agency reported on 12th December. <br>
<p>
It said the parliament issued a statement that day expressing regret that the<br>
Lisbon summit failed "to denounce the Azerbaijani delegation' s position on<br>
the Karabakh-Azerbaijani conflict" . <br>
<p>
The statement described remarks made by the current chairman of the OSCE,<br>
Flavio Cotti, on the principles underlying a resolution of the Karabakh<br>
problem as "an attempt at dictating the status of Nagornyy Karabakh in total<br>
disregard of the people's right to self-determination and other OSCE<br>
principles" , the agency said. They also criticized Cotti for adopting "a<br>
biased position which reflects only Azerbaijani interests and is inconsistent<br>
with the essence of international cooperation" , the agency said. <br>
<p>
It called on Azerbaijan "to abandon the policy of annexation" and start<br>
bilateral talks with Karabakh representatives. "We are convinced that this is<br>
the shortest and most constructive road to accord and peace between Nagornyy<br>
Karabakh and Azerbaijan," the MPs said. <br>
<p>
The statement on Nagornyy Karabakh issued at the end of the Lisbon summit on<br>
3rd December recommended three settlement principles: " Territorial integrity<br>
of the Azerbaijani Republic and the Republic of Armenia; a legal status for<br>
Nagornyy Karabakh, outlined in an agreement on the basis of<br>
self-determination, which would give Nagornyy Karabakh the highest degree of<br>
self-government within Azerbaijan; guaranteed security for Nagornyy Karabakh<br>
and its whole population, including mutual obligations to abide by settlement<br>
provisions," ITAR-TASS news agency reported at the time. <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Nagornyy Karabakh leader against Azerbaijan-Georgia oil pipeline <br>
SOURCE: Sakinform news agency, Tbilisi, in Georgian 1230 gmt 13 Dec 96 <br>
<p>
According to the [Georgian] 'Akhali Taoba' newspaper published in Tbilisi,<br>
the newly-elected president of Nagornyy Karabakh, Robert Kocharyan, has<br>
expressed concern over plans to build an oil pipeline for transporting<br>
Caspian oil from Azerbaijan via Georgia. This will help the Azerbaijani<br>
economy to grow, which is undesirable for Nagornyy Karabakh, he said.<br>
Kocharyan also said that he had sent his representatives to Abkhazia, South<br>
Osetia [breakaway regions of Georgia] and the Dnestr republic [a breakaway<br>
region of Moldova] to study their experience in shaping statehood. <br>
<p>
<p>
HEADLINE: Salonika to show off Byzantine legacy in 1997 <br>
SOURCE:  Reuters World Service, December 15, 1996<br>
<p>
Greece's second city has been delving into its rich cultural history,<br>
spanning more than 2,000 years, to come up with some rare gems for its year<br>
as Europe's cultural capital in 1997. <br>
<p>
An unprecedented exhibition of Byzantine art from the nearby all-male<br>
monastic community of Mount Athos, where women are forbidden, is expected to<br>
draw more than a million visitors. <br>
<p>
"After two years of preparation, the treasures of our Byzantine tradition,<br>
which has been kept alive for centuries, will be displayed for the first time<br>
outside Mount Athos," Salonika Mayor Constantine Kosmopoulos told reporters. <br>
<p>
A total of 589 items, ranging from gold-leaf icons to rare manuscripts, will<br>
be sent from the Byzantine monasteries dotting the Athos peninsula to be<br>
shown at the new Byzantine museum from June. <br>
<p>
Salonika, founded in 316 BC and named after Alexander the Great's sister<br>
Thessalonikeia, is determined to show off both its unique roots and its new<br>
air as a vibrant university city. <br>
<p>
"We want to project Greek culture as continuing to the present, not a relic<br>
of the past," said Culture Minister Evangelos Venizelos while hosting a tour<br>
of the city. <br>
<p>
Events will range from ancient Greek drama to plays by Jean Cocteau and<br>
Samuel Beckett; from modern jazz to Puccini's La Boheme and Verdi's Il<br>
Trovatore. <br>
<p>
Exhibitions span the work of Caravaggio to sculptures by the surrealist Max<br>
Ernst and a retrospective of Hans Arp; from engravings by Goya to<br>
contemporary Yugoslav art. <br>
<p>
"We want to promote Greece through a festival of ideas, not by projecting a<br>
silly chauvinism," Panos Theodoridis, the cultural capital's artistic<br>
director, told reporters. <br>
<p>
ROWS BEHIND THE SCENES <br>
<p>
The fourth director since 1992, when Salonika was chosen to succeed<br>
Copenhagen, he took over in April only to face chronic delays, public<br>
indifference and his predecessors' conflicting visions -- which he quickly<br>
overturned. <br>
<p>
The initial idea was to promote the legacies of Christian Orthodoxy,<br>
Byzantium and Alexander the Great, the Macedonian king who spread the Greek<br>
language and ideas as far east as India. <br>
<p>
Salonika's intellectual elite decried the concept as nationalist hysteria and<br>
said it was wrong to give the top job to Athenians who knew nothing of the<br>
city's international past. <br>
<p>
They also accused the government in Athens, which earmarked 80 billion<br>
drachmas ($328 million) for the cultural capital, of not pushing through the<br>
construction needed to make it a success. <br>
<p>
"Surely some works have been delayed," Venizelos admitted. "The Cultural<br>
Capital Organisation has management problems. It has become a giant; it<br>
should be smaller and more agile." <br>
<p>
Theodoridis, a Salonika native, quickly decided it was never too late and the<br>
city's existing facilities would have to do. <br>
<p>
"The space is enough and more than enough. What I care about is for the<br>
public to come to watch the events," he said. <br>
<p>
HISTORIC COMMUNITIES LEAVE MARK <br>
<p>
Theodoridis's vision pays tribute to the medley of religions and ethnic<br>
groups that have left their mark on the waterfront city, where St Paul<br>
preached in 50 AD. <br>
<p>
"We remember and pay tribute to the historic communities of the Armenians and<br>
the Jews, who, along with the traditional communities of the Moslems and<br>
Christians, helped the city reach its peak," he said. <br>
<p>
Dotted with Byzantine churches, Ottoman mosques and bath houses, the city<br>
became part of Greece in 1913 during the Balkan Wars. Its streets combine the<br>
charm of an eastern marketplace with the grey solemnity of a western<br>
industrial hub. <br>
<p>
Part of the Roman and Byzantine empires, Salonika was ruled at times by<br>
Saracens, crusaders and Venetians until it fell to the Ottoman Turks. <br>
<p>
It is the birthplace of Cyril and Methodius, who converted the Slavs to<br>
Christianity in the 800s as well as Kemal Ataturk, the founder of modern<br>
Turkey. <br>
<p>
Salonika got its major economic and cultural boost after the settlement of<br>
20,000 Jews expelled from Spain and Portugal in 1492. The Nazis sent 50,000<br>
Jews from the city known as the Second Jerusalem to the death camps. About<br>
2,000 Jews live here today. <br>
<p>
By the 16th century Salonika was a bustling international port city where<br>
Jews, Turks, Christians, Armenians and Slavs co-existed and flourished. <br>
<p>
About 30 European and Middle East countries are sending artists to perform<br>
next year. The United States, Canada, Australia and Japan are also<br>
participating. <br>
<p>
Salonika fears the year might be such a success that it could have difficulty<br>
putting up a huge numbers of visitors. <br>
<p>
"Salonika does have a problem with hotels," Venizelos said. "That's why we<br>
made arrangements to have cruise ships docked at the port to cover any such<br>
needs." <br>
<p>
($1-243.9 Drachma) <br>
<p>
HEADLINE:  Studio City Armenians to Open Community Center<br>
SOURCE:  Los Angeles Times, December 14, 1996<br>
<p>
Aimed at a growing San Fernando Valley population of Armenian Americans<br>
estimated at 100,000, the Armenian Cultural Foundation will open a new<br>
community center Sunday. <br>
<p>
Rep.-elect Brad Sherman (D-Sherman Oaks) is scheduled to attend an opening<br>
 ceremony at 5 p.m., along with state Assemblyman Bob Hertzberg (D-Sherman<br>
Oaks) and other dignitaries. The center, located in an office complex at the<br>
corner of Moorpark Street and Colfax Avenue, will be open from 4 to 6 p.m.<br>
Sunday.<br>
<p>
"It's kind of a humble beginning," said Berdj Karapetian, who represents<br>
Armenian organizations that will have offices at the center. "Eventually we<br>
hope to purchase our own building and have athletic facilities and so forth."<br>
<p>
The center is the foundation's ninth in Southern California and will<br>
primarily serve Studio City, Sherman Oaks, North Hollywood and Van Nuys.<br>
Groups with offices there will include the Armenian Youth Federation,<br>
Armenian Athletic Union and Scouts, Armenian Relief Society, Armenian<br>
Cultural Assn., Armenian National<br>
Committee and the ARF-Dashnagtsutiun, a political party. <br>
<p>
Most of the large numbers of Armenians who came to America during the 1970s<br>
and '80s settled in Hollywood because of its affordable housing, Karapetian<br>
said. But in the past decade as the Valley became more affordable, many<br>
Armenian Americans began moving to the Valley.<br>
<p>
Karapetian said the number of Armenians living in the East Valley is<br>
estimated at about 40,000--a figure that has doubled in the last six years.<br>
<p>
"Businesses here have responded to the trend," he added. "You don't have to<br>
be in Hollywood now to get an Armenian doctor or an Armenian grocery store."<br>
<p>
HEADLINE:  Armenian Prelate Visits Salt Lake City<br>
SOURCE:  The Salt Lake Tribune, December 14, 1996<br>
<p>
The Right Rev. Moushegh Mardirossian, prelate of the Los Angeles-based<br>
Western Prelacy of the Armenian Apostolic Church of America, is visiting Salt<br>
Lake City's Armenian community this weekend.<br>
<p>
Salt Lake City's Hamaspure Chapter of the Armenian Relief Society of the<br>
Western USA will recognize him tonight  at a 7 p.m. dinner at the Airport<br>
Holiday Inn. The Society is a nonprofit organization that was known as the<br>
Armenian Red Cross until a name change 25 years ago.<br>
<p>
On Sunday, Mardirossian will celebrate Mass at 1 p.m. in Salt Lake City's<br>
Cathedral of the Madeleine. <br>
<p>
Asdghig Shahinian, one of the Salt Lake City chapter's 32 members, said there<br>
are 500 to 750 Armenians in Utah, mostly in the Salt Lake Valley.  <br>
<p>
"We have no central place of worship," Shahinian said. "Our organization gets<br>
priests or fathers from Los Angeles to visit two or three times a year. They<br>
do baptisms, blessings, weddings." <br>
<p>
In addition to the infrequent visits from Armenian clergy, she said, Armenian<br>
 Christians often worship in Salt Lake City's Greek Orthodox parish and at<br>
St. Jude's parish in Murray. <br>
<p>
While affiliated with Utah's Roman Catholic diocese, St. Jude's is a Maronite<br>
Rite parish. Maronite Christians, primarily from Lebanon, have their own<br>
liturgy but are in union with the pope. <br>
<p>
Armenian Christianity is among the oldest forms of the religion in the world.<br>
Cappadocian bishop and missionary Gregory the Illuminator brought<br>
Christianity to Armenia in the late 3rd century, according to The<br>
HarperCollins Dictionary of Religion. <br>
<p>
The Armenian liturgical tradition blends Cappadocian, Syrian and Byzantine<br>
elements. Today, the dictionary states, there are both Orthodox Armenian<br>
Christians, who sometimes are known as Gregorian Armenians, and Eastern-rite<br>
Catholic Armenians, not only in Armenia but in communities in the Near East,<br>
Europe, North and South America. <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
