<title>Groong Network: Armenian News 12/15/96</title>
<h1>Armenian News 12/15/96</h1>
<i>Chavoush@aol.com</i><br>
<i>Sun, 15 Dec 96 22:55:35 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#134">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#134">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#134">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#134">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0135.html">Kevork K. Oskanian: "Yerevan,Baku exchange accusations....."</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0133.html">KEVORK: "second messege-NEW ARMENIAN WWW SITE(GREECE)"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Headlines of stories which follow:<br>
1.  Chess (by Raymond Keene)<br>
2.  Azeris, Oil Firms Sign $2 Bln Caspian Sea Deal <br>
3.  Pope signs partial reconciliation agreement with Armenian church <br>
<p>
HEADLINE:  Chess (by Raymond Keene)<br>
SOURCE:  The Times, December 14, 1996<br>
<p>
Perhaps the event of the year for British chess was Matthew Sadler's gold<br>
medal in the Erevan Olympiad in the autumn. In the November issue of the<br>
British Chess Magazine , he recounts his extraordinarily detailed<br>
preparation, which was not just confined to the analysis of chess moves. <br>
<p>
"I decided that it might be useful to get a small feel of Armenia before I<br>
went, and my preparation was meticulous. I bought CDs of Armenian classical<br>
and choral music, I learnt the Armenian alphabet. I even bought a Russian<br>
cookbook and made my poor mother slave over the cooker producing Armenian<br>
stews and Kazhakstan dried fruit tarts. So I was ready: I could eat Armenian,<br>
read Armenian, sing Armenian..." <br>
<p>
The English team performance was good, if not brilliant. Seeded second,<br>
England came in joint third, but missed the bronze medals on tie-break. <br>
<p>
As so often in the past, the English team was generously supported by the<br>
merchant bank Duncan Lawrie, which helped to ensure that the strongest<br>
possible side turned out. <br>
<p>
English Olympiad Results The chart below shows the English individual scores<br>
in the Erevan Olympiad. In any round, four of the six players are involved. 1<br>
indicates a win, 1/2 is a draw and 0 a loss. If a player did not play in any<br>
particular round, that is indicated by *. There were fourteen rounds, each of<br>
them indicated by a number at the top of the chart. For purposes of<br>
cross-reference, England played against Indonesia in round 1, Denmark in<br>
round 2, Latvia in round 3, then against Romania, Holland, Georgia, Spain,<br>
Croatia, Vietnam, Armenia 1, Sweden, China, Israel and Hungary. <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Azeris, Oil Firms Sign $2 Bln Caspian Sea Deal <br>
SOURCE:  The Reuter European Business Report,  December 14, 1996<br>
<p>
Azerbaijan and a consortium of foreign oil companies led by Amoco Corp's<br>
Amoco Eurasian Petroleum Company signed a $ 2 billion deal on Saturday in<br>
Baku to develop the Ashrafi and Dan Ulduzu oil fields. <br>
<p>
The 25-year contract is Azerbaijan's fourth major deal with a consortium of<br>
Western companies, in the Caucasus republic's Caspian Sea reserves. <br>
<p>
Amoco said it hopes to sign another exploration agreement with the former<br>
Soviet republic soon. <br>
<p>
The Western consortium in Saturday's deal includes Amoco Eurasian, with a 30<br>
percent stake, Unocal with 25.5 percent, Japan's Itochu with 20 percent and<br>
Saudi Arabia's Delta Nimir with 4.5 percent. <br>
<p>
The Azerbaijan state oil company SOCAR will have a 20 percent stake in the<br>
deal and Azeri oil officials say 65 to 80 percent of profits from the<br>
development of the fields will go to the Azeri government. <br>
<p>
The Ashrafi and Dan Ulduzu fields lie appoximately 30 miles off the Apsheron<br>
peninsula. They are spread over 453 square km (175 sq miles) at depths of 75<br>
to 200 metres (246 to 656 feet) and are estimated to contain 150 million<br>
tonnes of crude. <br>
<p>
First production is expected to come on line in 2003 and will reach seven<br>
million tonnes per year by 2007. <br>
<p>
The deal requires an up-front bonus payment to the Azeri government of $ 75<br>
million from consortium members and must be ratified by the Azeri parliament.<br>
<p>
<p>
The deal brings total western investment in Azerbaijan's promising oil sector<br>
to over $ 12 billion. <br>
<p>
Azeri President Haydar Aliyev said the agreement was evidence of the growing<br>
importance of the former Soviet republic for American companies. <br>
<p>
"I am happy that the Clinton administration is finding cooperation with<br>
Azerbaijan," Aliyev said, adding that he had received a telephone call from<br>
U.S. Vice President Al Gore on Friday. <br>
<p>
"I consider that the U.S. and Azerbaijan are strategic partners... The Vice<br>
President said the administration supports cooperation with the Azeri oil<br>
sector and regards the contract as of the utmost importance," he said. <br>
<p>
Azerbaijan, with its vast Capsian oil potential, has been the centre of a<br>
tug-of-war between Russia, Iran, Trukey and Western countries since<br>
independence in 1991. <br>
<p>
Tom Stacy, Chairman of Amoco Eurasian Petroleum Company, said the oil giant<br>
hoped to sign another Caspian contract with the Azeri government soon. <br>
<p>
"We are happy to work in Azerbaijan and hope to sign another contract soon on<br>
exploration of the southern part of the Azeri sector of the Caspian basin,"<br>
he told a news conference. <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Pope signs partial reconciliation agreement with Armenian church <br>
SOURCE:  Deutsche Presse-Agentur,  December 13, 1996<br>
<p>
Pope John Paul II and the head of the Apostolic Armenian Church, Patriarch<br>
Karekin I, signed an agreement Friday which moves their churches closer to<br>
reconciliation. <br>
<p>
The agreement - a development in the ecumenical relationship and in<br>
theological discussion - cleared up "many misunderstandings", the two leaders<br>
said.   The agreement was reached after 25 hours of talks between the pope<br>
and Catholics. <br>
<p>
After 1,500 years, the Catholic church and the Armenian Church agreed to end<br>
their dispute about the nature of Christ. They broke in their beliefs during<br>
the Council of Chalcedon in 451. <br>
<p>
The joint statement expresses Christ's double nature - his godly and human<br>
sides. Until now, the Armenian church had only recognized Christ's godly<br>
side. <br>
<p>
"The squabbles and the deplorable discord (between the denominations) should<br>
no longer have negative effects on the life and testimony of the church,"<br>
both leaders said in the agreement. <br>
<p>
The biggest problem for furthering the two churches' relationship is the<br>
primacy of the pope, which is not recognized by the Armenian church. <br>
<p>
Karekin, who comes from Syria, represents about six million believers around<br>
the world. He arrived Tuesday at the Vatican for a five-day visit.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
