<title>Groong Network: Turkish complicity in March 1995 coup attempt in Baku</title>
<h1>Turkish complicity in March 1995 coup attempt in Baku</h1>
Arthur Martirosyan (<i>martiros@hulaw1.harvard.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 15 Dec 1996 22:30:05 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#131">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#131">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#131">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#131">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0132.html">Arthur Martirosyan: "Evaluation of Lisbon Summit results by political parties in"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0130.html">Armen Martirossyan: "From Aragil News"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
 SEGODNIA: No. 232, 12/15/96<br>
<p>
By Arif Husseinov<br>
<p>
Turkish special services participated in an anti-Aliyev conspiracy<br>
Baku and Ankara conduct parallel investigations<br>
<p>
The scandal which began with a publication of facts on complicity of Turkish<br>
special services in the organization of a state coup in Azerbaijan in March<br>
1995 (see: Segodnya from 11/22) in a Turkish newspaper Hurriyet  continues. <br>
<p>
Investigation in Azerbaijan has established that some high ranking Turkish<br>
diplomats were involved in the organization of the coup. Among others is<br>
named citizen of Turkey Farman Demirgol who then was an advisor to the<br>
juridical department of the Milli Mejlis and, according to some sources, the<br>
former resident of the Turkish special services in Azerbaijan. 34 members of<br>
the parliament and some leaders of political parties of Azerbaijan were<br>
involved in the "conspiracy of diplomats."  <br>
<p>
At a press-conference last week President of Azerbaijan, Heidar Aliyev,<br>
stated that Farman Demirgol's guilt was proved beyond any doubt and he<br>
himself did not deny that he had participated in the organization of the<br>
coup. Moreover, in a televised speech the other day Demirgol "sincerely<br>
apologized" to the Azerbaijani nation. <br>
<p>
Answering numerous questions of journalists, Heidar Aliyev confirmed that<br>
Suleyman Demirel was the first to warn him about  the coup. It is not clear<br>
how special services of "the brotherly country"  dared to prepare a coup<br>
involving high ranking diplomats without sanctions from the top political<br>
leadership.  <br>
<p>
According to some information, the official Ankara is conducting a parallel<br>
investigation.  (end) (Translated by AM. Names transliterated from Russian.) <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
