<title>Groong Network: Armenian News 12/14/96</title>
<h1>Armenian News 12/14/96</h1>
<i>Chavoush@aol.com</i><br>
<i>Sat, 14 Dec 96 18:31:24 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#128">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#128">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#128">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#128">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0129.html">vahe@arminco.com: "Aragil Headlines, 12/16/96"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0127.html">Bruce Becker: "job opportunity in armenia"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Headlines of stories which follow:<br>
1.  Azeri Parliament Approves 1997 Budget <br>
2.  Maneri/Morris/Maneri Three Men Walking <br>
3.  Black Sea Has Truckers Blue but Wheels are in Motion to Ease Customs<br>
Headaches in the Region <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Azeri Parliament Approves 1997 Budget <br>
SOURCE:  Reuters Financial Service, December 13, 1996<br>
<p>
Azerbaijan's parliament on Friday approved a $ 758 million budget for 1997<br>
which includes a $ 163 million deficit, a significant increase over 1996. <br>
<p>
The Milli Mejlis, or parliament, approved spending of 3.18 trillion manats<br>
and revenues of 2.5 trillion manats.   The 680 billion manat deficit is<br>
significantly more than in 1996 which it was 516 billion manats ($ 117<br>
million at the then exchange rate). <br>
<p>
The deficit is to be covered mainly by issuing treasury bills and "bonuses"<br>
paid into state coffers by western oil companies signing new offshore Caspian<br>
Sea drilling contracts with the government. <br>
<p>
The government expects gross domestic product to rise two percent over 1996<br>
levels to 17.2 trillion manats. <br>
<p>
Education accounts for 648 billion manats, the biggest slice of government<br>
spending, while 357 billion go to defence, 278 billion for social security<br>
and 250 billion for health care. <br>
<p>
Servicing the government debt will take 413 billion manats. <br>
<p>
Some Milli Mejlis deputies complained about what they see as the relatively<br>
low level of military spending at a time when the country is still in<br>
conflict with neighbouring Armenia over the disputed territory of<br>
Nagorno-Karabakh. <br>
<p>
Finance Minister Fikret Usifov said the government had collected nearly 100<br>
percent of expected tax revenues for 1996. <br>
<p>
($ 1 US = 4250 manat) <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: The 1996 Jazz CD Guide - Maneri/Morris/Maneri Three Men Walking <br>
SOURCE:  The Guardian, December 13, 1996<br>
<p>
Maneri/Morris/Maneri Three Men Walking (ECM CD 531-023-2) pounds 15.49 <br>
<p>
One of the best free-improvising discs of the year. Sixty-nine-year-old Joe<br>
Maneri plays clarinet, alto and tenor on this set, in the company of his son<br>
Mat on six-string electric violin, and Joe Morris on electric guitar (the<br>
latter's work has been described as sounding like 'Albert Ayler as played by<br>
Grant Green' or 'the missing link between Jimi Hendrix and Ornette Coleman').<br>
Maneri Senior has long sought to combine structural notions drawn from<br>
Schoenberg, Berg and Bartok with free-jazz and world music (he has<br>
particularly studied Turkish, Greek and Armenian forms) and has developed a<br>
form of microtonal music of his own - and though this is a long way from<br>
straight-ahead jazz, or straight-ahead anything, it's played with passion and<br>
skill, and they listen to each other like hawks. The British improv trio<br>
called Hession, Wilkinson and Fell, which toured during 1996, revealed many<br>
similar qualities, though the idiomatic references were narrower. <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Black Sea Has Truckers Blue but Wheels are in Motion to Ease<br>
Customs Headaches in the Region <br>
SOURCE:  Journal of Commerce, December 6, 1996<br>
<p>
For Ahmed Sohn, director of Beyazit Exporters, a trucking company moving<br>
goods across the border of Balkan and Caucasian republics, times have never<br>
been tougher.  He fends off the angry calls of customers waiting for delayed<br>
goods. He bargains for the release of trucks stuck at remote border posts<br>
where bribes are common. And he navigates routes through ever-changing<br>
customs regulations. <br>
<p>
But soon Mr. Sohn's worries may be over. <br>
<p>
The Black Sea Economic Cooperation Council is planning to form a customs task<br>
force. The special unit, made up of officials from the 11-member-nation<br>
BSECC, will begin efforts to standardize customs procedures at international<br>
borders to allow the free passage of commercial goods. <br>
<p>
''What we are trying to do here is to streamline the procedure of moving<br>
commercial goods,'' said Mustafa Aksin, Turkish representative to the BSECC.<br>
''It's a small step, but it should do a lot, in time, to reduce the cost of<br>
transportation by unifying border-crossing procedures of all nations.'' <br>
<p>
Much of the problem, according to BSECC officials, has to do with instability<br>
throughout the region, particularly in the Russian Federation, the Balkans<br>
and the Caucasian republics. <br>
<p>
Because those nations are newly formed, and because they are facing stiff<br>
financial restraints, customs personnel, police and equipment are either not<br>
well trained or not present. <br>
<p>
''Crossing these borders is a joke, quite frankly,'' said Mr. Sohn. ''Some of<br>
my guys have been delayed for days while their cargoes are examined and<br>
searched, sometimes looted and the only way to get out alive is to pay.''<br>
Indeed, the region loses millions of dollars worth of trade, according to<br>
Turkish Customs officials, because of customs delays and deliveries gone<br>
wrong while crossing international borders. <br>
<p>
In Baku, Azerbaijan, a manager of Bertling Caspian Ltd. has similar<br>
complaints. But he says that he is comforted by the fact that his company<br>
hired him because of logistical experience in other difficult working<br>
environments. <br>
<p>
''There are bandits on the highways at night which makes delivery north,<br>
south and west of Azerbaijan difficult and sometimes time-consuming,'' said<br>
Greg Clemmons, Bertling's general manager in Baku. <br>
<p>
''Then there's the on-again-off-again war in Azerbaijan and Armenia which<br>
forces us to skirt around Armenia and into Georgia to make deliveries to and<br>
<i>&gt;from Turkey - it'd be great if everyone could agree that free trade is better</i><br>
for a nation's health than war.'' <br>
<p>
And while many had hoped that the fall of the Soviet Union would bring a new<br>
era of free trade to the Black Sea region, they are being confronted instead<br>
by disorganized and often corrupt customs officials. <br>
<p>
''If nations simply agreed and enforced worldwide customs conventions then we<br>
would not have any problems,'' said Peter Krausz, a manager with the<br>
Switzerland-based International Road Transport Union. ''There is clearly room<br>
for improvement, especially in the area of monitoring customs procedures.''<br>
The 11-nation body, formed in 1992, includes customs and trade officials, as<br>
well as business leaders from Albania, Armenia, Azerbaijan, Bulgaria,<br>
Georgia, Greece, Moldova, Rumania, the Russian Federation, Turkey and<br>
Ukraine. And while no date has been set for their first meeting, BSECC<br>
officials say the new task force will meet once each quarter beginning in<br>
January 1997. <br>
<p>
"It's a dream, of course, to formalize all the various customs and<br>
border-crossing procedures - but it's a dream that I think is attainable,''<br>
said Mr. Aksin.  ''But it's the first step toward bringing a healthy economy<br>
to the region - the world must wish us luck.'' <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
