<title>Groong Network: Samsung Electronics opens outlet in Yerevan.</title>
<h1>Samsung Electronics opens outlet in Yerevan.</h1>
Kevork K. Oskanian (<i>100436.3410@compuserve.com</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 13 Dec 96 15:15:56 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#121">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#121">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#121">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#121">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0122.html">Asbed Bedrossian: "OMRI Digest 12/13/96"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0120.html">Kevork K. Oskanian: "Catholic, Armenian Churches end 1,500-year rift"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
  YEREVAN, December 13 (Itar-Tass) - The South Korean Samsung <br>
Electronics company opened an outlet in Yerevan on Friday. This is the <br>
only shop of Samsung Electronics in Transcaucasia. The 100 square metre <br>
shop offers a wide range of goods -- from video recorders to vacuum <br>
cleaners. The supplies will be made from Finland via Moscow. <br>
   The shop idea was put forward by the Mark International Russian-Armenian<br>
<p>
joint venture, the official and only dealer of Samsung Electronics in <br>
Armenia and Transcaucasia. In the words of venture head Armen Airapetyan, <br>
it is much better to buy video, audio and other appliances in the <br>
outlet -- prices are low and service is good. <br>
   Samsung offices in Moscow and Dubai, the United Arab Emirates, are <br>
competing for the Transcaucasian market. <br>
   "We accepted the proposal of our partners with satisfaction, studied <br>
their abilities and granted them dealer powers," the general manager and <br>
head of the Samsung Electronics Moscow office told Itar-Tass. He said <br>
the company will expand its presence in Transcaucasia. <br>
   yer/yur <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
