<title>Groong Network: Armenian News 12/13/96</title>
<h1>Armenian News 12/13/96</h1>
<i>Chavoush@aol.com</i><br>
<i>Fri, 13 Dec 96 14:56:39 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#116">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#116">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#116">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#116">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0117.html">Armen Martirossyan: "From Armenpress Homepage"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0115.html">ASBAREZ-ON-LINE: "ASBAREZ-ON-LINE [12-13-96]"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Headlines of stories which follow:<br>
1.  Spokesman links Karabakh issue resolution with opening Armenia border <br>
2.  Turkish Officials' Links to Crime Lords are Probed <br>
3.  Former Soviet republics form news agency alliance <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Spokesman links Karabakh issue resolution with opening Armenia<br>
border <br>
SOURCE: TRT TV, Ankara, in Turkish 1800 gmt 11 Dec 96 <br>
<p>
[Announcer] Turkey has said that it is not considering opening its border<br>
with Armenia until a substantive agreement on principles is reached between<br>
Armenia and Azerbaijan . <br>
<p>
Foreign Ministry deputy spokesman Sermet Atacanli, speaking at his weekly<br>
news conference, said that there had been no positive developments with<br>
regard to the solution of the Nagorno-Karabakh problem since the decision [by<br>
Turkey] to close the Turkish-Armenian border on 3rd April, 1993.   He<br>
recalled that Armenia did not accept the principles on a solution to the<br>
problem contained in the joint communique issued at the end of the OSCE<br>
summit Lisbon at the beginning of this month. <br>
<p>
[Atacanli] Above all, Turkey believes that Azerbaijan and Armenia should<br>
reach a substantive agreement on principles for a solution to the<br>
Nagorno-Karabakh problem in line with Azerbaijan's territorial integrity, the<br>
evacuation of the occupied territories and the return of refugees to their<br>
homes. Until such an agreement is reached, Turkey will not consider reviewing<br>
its decision regarding its border with Armenia. <br>
<p>
[Announcer] In reply to a question, Atacanli said that Armenia had on various<br>
occasions expressed the desire to develop its relations with Turkey and that<br>
Turkey was , in principle, not opposed to that. <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Turkish Officials' Links to Crime Lords are Probed <br>
SOURCE: Associated Press, December 12, 1996<br>
<p>
A traffic accident that revealed links between the Turkish government and the<br>
underworld has forced President Suleyman Demirel to step in and demand an<br>
accounting. <br>
<p>
Demirel met Tuesday with the main opposition leader, Mesut Yilmaz, who has<br>
played a key role in disclosing secret ties between the police and crime<br>
bosses. <br>
<p>
There also have been allegations of government-backed death squads to<br>
suppress dissidents and Kurdish rebels. <br>
<p>
Demirel is summoning other opposition leaders and is to meet with Prime<br>
Minister Necmettin Erbakan on Thursday. <br>
<p>
"Nothing will remain secret under the sky. You cannot hide anything," Demirel<br>
told the newspaper Hurriyet. "Whoever tries to hide it gets buried under it."<br>
<p>
<p>
The scandal surfaced after a Mercedes-Benz and a tractor-trailer collided on<br>
a highway 90 miles south of Istanbul last month. <br>
<p>
A Parliament deputy, a fugitive criminal and a police official were in the<br>
Mercedes; only the deputy survived. The criminal, Abdullah Catli, reputedly<br>
had links to the Turk who shot Pope John Paul II and was wanted in<br>
Switzerland, where he was convicted of drug smuggling and escaped from prison<br>
in 1990. <br>
<p>
The connections between the three men immediately appeared suspicious.  Sedat<br>
Bucak, the deputy who survived the crash and who is also a powerful official<br>
in Turkey's Kurdish-dominated southeast, could not provide any reasonable<br>
explanation. <br>
<p>
After the accident, Interior Minister Mehmet Agar, who had close ties to the<br>
police chief, was forced to resign under pressure from opposition parties. <br>
<p>
The scandal grew when Yilmaz said Catli organized the killing of a casino<br>
operator, Omer Lutfi Topal, with three police officers in July to help Bucak<br>
seize his assets. Three police officers who were briefly detained after the<br>
killing assigned were later to guard Bucak. <br>
<p>
Yilmaz said he had tapes of phone calls between the three officers talking<br>
about their murder of Topal. <br>
<p>
Bucak runs a 2,000-man army in southeastern Turkey to fight Kurdish rebels<br>
and reportedly receives more than $1 million a month from the government for<br>
it. <br>
<p>
Newspaper reports say his men allegedly were members of death squads that<br>
killed hundreds of supporters of the Kurdish rebel movement and have smuggled<br>
drugs and weapons. <br>
<p>
The government's handling of the scandal has led to suspicions that Foreign<br>
Minister Tansu Ciller knew about the alleged ties between the state and<br>
underworld leaders during her three years as prime minister. <br>
<p>
Ciller said in a recent speech that Catli deserved being honored for fighting<br>
for Turkey. She also accused Yilmaz of supporting the Kurdish rebel groups<br>
and Armenian terrorists by getting tough on Catli. <br>
<p>
But on Monday, Ciller told reporters after being summoned by Demirel that the<br>
state's mission is to fight criminals. "The state does not form gangs," she<br>
said. <br>
<p>
The government took its first action last week in the unfolding scandal,<br>
removing Istanbul's well-respected police chief and the three officers linked<br>
to Topal's killing. But the move against the police chief caused an uproar. <br>
<p>
News reports said the police chief, Kemal Yazicioglu, was being punished for<br>
leaking the link between the three officers and Topal's slaying. <br>
<p>
The truck driver who crashed into the Mercedes received a "most respected<br>
citizen honor" from a small leftist party for his role in exposing the<br>
scandal. <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Former Soviet republics form news agency alliance <br>
SOURCE:  Kyodo News Service, December 12, 1996<br>
<p>
News agencies from nine former Soviet republics established the Association<br>
of National Information Agencies on Wednesday, according to reports from<br>
Moscow monitored in Tokyo on Thursday. <br>
<p>
The members of the news agency alliance are Russia, Belarus, Azerbaijan,<br>
Armenia, Tajikistan, Ukraine, Kyrgyzstan, Moldova and Kazakstan, all members<br>
of the Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS) formed after the collapse of<br>
the Soviet Union, the report said. <br>
<p>
The news alliance was formed in a bid to facilitate cooperation among member<br>
countries and the directors of the national news agencies elected Vitaly<br>
Ignatenko, Russia's deputy prime minister and president of Itar-Tass, to head<br>
the new organization, the report said. <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
