<title>Groong Network: ASBAREZ-ON-LINE [12-13-96]</title>
<h1>ASBAREZ-ON-LINE [12-13-96]</h1>
ASBAREZ-ON-LINE (<i>76635.2505@CompuServe.COM</i>)<br>
<i>13 Dec 96 17:29:30 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#115">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#115">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#115">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#115">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0116.html">Chavoush@aol.com: "Armenian News 12/13/96"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0114.html">Antranik Ashdjian: "WWW page with Cyprus Armenians info"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
ASBAREZ ON LINE <br>
12/13/1996<br>
<p>
<p>
1. SARKISSIAN MEETS WITH ARF EXECUTIVE COUNCIL<br>
2. SOCIALIST YOUTH VOICE CONCERN OVER BREAKDOWN OF DEMOCRACY<br>
3. POPE, CATHOLICOS AGREE TO END 1500-YEAR RIFT<br>
4. "TRIAL OF 31" DEFENDANT HAS NERVOUS BREAKDOWN<br>
5. EUROPARLIAMENT FREEZES TURKISH AID<br>
6. NEW ARS CHAPTER ESTABLISHED IN RIVERSIDE<br>
7. PRELATE MARDIROSSIAN HONORED IN ORANGE COUNTY<br>
8. EIGHTH HOMENETMEN PAN-ARMENIAN GAMES CONCLUDE<br>
<p>
<p>
1. SARKISSIAN MEETS WITH ARF EXECUTIVE COUNCIL<br>
<p>
YEREVAN-Armenias Prime Minister Armen Sarkissian met with <br>
representatives of the Armenian Revolutionary Federation Executive <br>
Council of Armenia, Rouben Hakobian, Hrayr Karapetian and Gagik <br>
Mkrtchian on Friday to discuss his new program of development for <br>
Armenia.<br>
	The delegation congratulated the newly-appointed prime <br>
minister and stressed the importance of involving political <br>
parties in resolving the current internal political crisis during <br>
the hour-long meeting.<br>
<p>
<p>
2. SOCIALIST YOUTH VOICE CONCERN OVER BREAKDOWN OF DEMOCRACY<br>
<p>
KATHMANDU, Nepal-A delegation of the Armenian Revolutionary <br>
Federation Youth Organization took part in the annual conference <br>
of the International Union of Socialist Youth in Kathmandu, Nepal <br>
from December 6-8.<br>
	The ARF-YO delegation focused the participants attention on <br>
the breakdown of democracy in the Republic of Armenia and the <br>
grave human rights violations following the Sept. 22 presidential <br>
elections.<br>
	The IUSY conference unanimously adopted a resolution on the <br>
democratic process in Armenia.<br>
	Below is the complete text of the resolution:<br>
<p>
	Resolution on the Democratic Process in Armenia<br>
<p>
	Since her independence from the Soviet Union in 1991 and the <br>
formation of the 2nd Republic (the first being that of 1918 right <br>
after WWI), Armenia has undergone a series of rough political <br>
processes on the road to becoming a genuine democratic state.<br>
	That has yet to be accomplished not because post-Soviet <br>
political and economic trends have disallowed such a <br>
development-on the contrary, most Western countries, as well as <br>
Russia, have shown keen interest toward the achievement of <br>
democracy in all CIS countries-but due to the emergence to power <br>
of a group of opportunistic individuals who have formed a self-<br>
centered and dictatorial government, working under the guise of <br>
democracy.<br>
	The recent Armenian presidential elections of September 22, <br>
1996 have shown in effect that a democratic Republic of Armenia <br>
cannot become a reality unless the ruling government either <br>
acknowledges the fundamental rights of the Armenian populous to <br>
speak, think and act freely through open political expression or <br>
gives way to the mounting popular opposition, which has shown <br>
indisputable clarity that it is time for change.<br>
	Already, the European Parliament with its Resolution (Oct. <br>
1996) of condemnation on irregularities and illegitimacy of recent <br>
Armenian presidential elections, along with the attestation to <br>
that effect by the European Electoral Monitoring Commission, have <br>
expressed serious political concern over the lack of progress in <br>
the democratic process in Armenia.<br>
	It is time for the Armenian people to show its capability to <br>
create a democratically sound state.<br>
	In light of the aforementioned, IUSY and the World Council <br>
meeting, giving top priority to democracy, economic development <br>
and human rights for all nations, addresses the issue of the <br>
democratic process in Armenia with the following:<br>
<p>
1. Expresses deep concern in the lack of democracy in Armenia.<br>
2. Calls on the current Armenian government to lift all <br>
restrictions on banned political parties in Armenia and to return <br>
all confiscated property to their rightful owners.<br>
3. Joins in solidarity to the call of the Armenian people to move <br>
towards democracy.<br>
4. Calls on the Armenian government currently in power to be <br>
accountable to the International Community on any fraud or <br>
illegitimacy taken place during the presidential elections of <br>
September 22, 1996.<br>
<p>
<p>
3. POPE, CATHOLICOS AGREE TO END 1500-YEAR RIFT<br>
<p>
VATICAN CITY (Reuter)-The Roman Catholic and Armenian Churches <br>
Friday formally buried a theological controversy that had divided <br>
them for 1,500 years.<br>
	Pope John Paul II and Karekin I, Catholicos of All <br>
Armenians, issued a common declaration officially ending the <br>
controversy over the nature of Christ.<br>
	The controversy dates back to the 6th century when the <br>
Council of Chalcedon condemned those, including Armenian <br>
Christians, who asserted that Christ had only a divine and not <br>
also a human nature.<br>
	Thursdays declaration spoke of the dual nature of Christ <br>
and said both sides agreed that past controversies "should not <br>
continue to influence the life and witness of the Church today."<br>
	The declaration, signed at the end of Karekins official <br>
visit to the Vatican, said past disputes were due to "linguistic, <br>
cultural and political factors."<br>
	It capped renewed contacts and theological dialogue between <br>
the two Churches in the past three decades. In the declaration, <br>
both the Pope and Karekin said they were committed to eventual <br>
unity between their two Churches.<br>
	The Armenian Church is one of the so-called Ancient Churches <br>
of the East which split away from Byzantine Christianity before <br>
the Great Schism of 1054, which divided the Eastern and Western <br>
Churches.<br>
	The Armenian Church is an independent Christian Church <br>
introduced to Armenia by the apostles Thaddeus and Bartholomew. In <br>
AD 301 Armenia became the first nation to adopt Christianity as a <br>
state religion.<br>
	The Armenian Church has various patriarchates around the <br>
world and has members in the countries of the former Soviet Union, <br>
North and South America, the Middle East, Europe and Asia.<br>
<p>
<p>
4. "TRIAL OF 31" DEFENDANT HAS NERVOUS BREAKDOWN<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-Co-defendant in the so-called "Trial of 31" <br>
Arthur Kazarian had a nervous breakdown Thursday in court as he <br>
learned about the pressure and insults incurred by his father.<br>
	Kazarian lost self-control, jumped on the bench and started <br>
to violently shake the holding cage and shout, sources close to <br>
the case said. The other defendants, who were in the same cage, <br>
tried to restrain Kazarian and calm him down.<br>
	Court was adjourned until Monday, Dec. 16.<br>
	Prior to the breakdown, Kazarian had said that during the <br>
preliminary investigation, he had given "false" testimony under <br>
duress for fear of his familys safety. He said that he had <br>
planned to tell the truth in court. Kazarian described the charges <br>
against him as "nonsense, lies and slander."<br>
	Also on Thursday, the judicial board ordered prison <br>
officials to submit a medical report on Kazarians condition, in <br>
response to the defendants complaint that his hand had been <br>
broken and his vision and hearing were deteriorating. Kazarians <br>
attorneys also asked the court to order the Military Police, for <br>
which Kazarian worked, to also submit their clients medical <br>
records.<br>
	Kazarians father, Gevork Kazarian, also testified Thursday <br>
to repeatedly being arrested although he was in no way connected <br>
to the alleged arms delivery. Kazarian is accused of delivering <br>
arms, allegedly stored in co-defendant Ofik Asikians garage, to <br>
the Military Police. Gevork Kazarian said following his <br>
intermittent arrests and questioning, he was subjected to "moral <br>
humiliation" in August.<br>
<p>
<p>
5. EUROPARLIAMENT FREEZES TURKISH AID<br>
<p>
STRASBOURG, France (Reuter)-The European Parliament voted to <br>
freeze EU funds worth 53 million Ecus ($66 million) promised to <br>
Turkey for 1997 to help set up an EU-Turkey customs union.<br>
	Turkish Foreign Minister Tansu Ciller blasted the European <br>
Union Friday, saying it had failed to honor a bilateral customs <br>
union and was unfairly shutting Ankara out of its plans to admit <br>
new members. <br>
	Ciller, who will dine with the blocs leaders Saturday at <br>
the Dublin summit, said the one-year-old customs union had fallen <br>
short of expectations, as associated aid had not been released.<br>
	"This first year, I have to say, has been a bit of a <br>
disappointment on the part of Turkey," Ciller told a news <br>
conference. "Its only fair that we would expect the conditions to <br>
be met by the European side."<br>
	She said that Turkey-which on account of its poor human <br>
rights record has been left out of the EUs plans to expand <br>
eastward-should be the first country to be admitted, rather than <br>
being excluded.<br>
	"We have protected Europe against the threat of communism. <br>
We have protected it for a long time as an ally of NATO. All <br>
this... makes us only a fair partner in this enlargement," she <br>
said, pointing to the fact that the customs union gave Ankara the <br>
most sophisticated trade links with the EU.<br>
	She hinted that Turkey could block the planned expansion of <br>
NATO, of which it is a member, unless the EU changes its attitude.<br>
	"You can not look at the enlargement of this institution as <br>
a separate issue-these are interlocked institutions," she said.<br>
	Greece, which is constantly at odds with its eastern <br>
neighbor over territorial and minority rights issues, has vowed to <br>
block any moves by the EU presidency Ireland at the Dublin summit <br>
to advance relations with Ankara.<br>
	Ciller said that Greece and Turkey should sit down and hold <br>
a dialogue in a bid to sort out their many problems.<br>
	"Its about time that  Greece and Turkey sit down and talk <br>
about their differences and see which we can resolve and what we <br>
can not," she said.<br>
	The two countries, despite being NATO allies, almost came to <br>
war earlier in the year over uninhabited islets in the Aegean Sea. <br>
The United States stepped in to broker a compromise. <br>
	Under the customs union, Ciller said, Turkeys imports from <br>
the EU have increased by more than 40 percent while its exports to <br>
the rest of the Union had increased by only seven percent. <br>
	She said that Turkey was honoring its promise to improve on <br>
human rights.<br>
	"On the human rights front we are going to work in all <br>
directions," she said, adding: "This is our dedication. This is <br>
something we are doing for our people.... Its not something we <br>
are doing for our integration process."<br>
	The European Parliament said on Thursday it was concerned <br>
that the Turkish authorities were trying to muzzle the press, <br>
warning this would damage relations between the European Union and <br>
Ankara.<br>
	"The European Parliament expresses its strong opposition to <br>
attempts to restrict freedom of the press in Turkey," the EUs <br>
directly elected assembly said in a resolution, which charged that <br>
journalists have been imprisoned, abducted and assassinated.<br>
	Euro-parliamentarians called on the government in Ankara "to <br>
abandon its plans to adopt a new law to restrict freedom of the <br>
press, which would damage relations between the EU and Turkey."<br>
	Parliament said it was shocked to learn the Turkish police <br>
had detained, fined and expelled from Turkey a member of the <br>
Danish Parliament, sent there to observe the trial of Kemal Koc. <br>
	Koc, a naturalized Dane, was arrested and jailed by Turkish <br>
authorities in Ankara on July 9 while attending his brothers <br>
funeral and charged with giving economic assistance to the Kurdish <br>
Workers Party (PKK) from Denmark.<br>
	The Euro-deputies also condemned Ankara for compiling a <br>
black list of "undesirable" EU politicians and urged the EU <br>
Council of Ministers to take steps to ensure it was scrapped. <br>
	Turkey protested  Denmark in March for allowing the <br>
convention of a session of the Brussels-based Kurdish Parliament-<br>
in- Exile in the Danish legislature.<br>
<p>
<p>
6. NEW ARS CHAPTER ESTABLISHED IN RIVERSIDE<br>
<p>
CORONA-Responding to a formal request by the Armenian community of <br>
the San Bernardino County, the Western Regional Executive of the <br>
Armenian Relief Society established the ARS "Getashen" Chapter of <br>
Riverside on Dec.8.<br>
	Seventeen new members pledged to carry on the mission of the <br>
ARS in a special ceremony at the Corona home of Hasmig Dabaghian, <br>
one of the members of the charitable organizations 27th chapter <br>
in the Western United States. Representatives of the ARS Regional <br>
Executive and members of the Diamond Bar "Arpi" and Orange County <br>
"Sevan" chapters attended the gathering. <br>
	Regional Executive chairperson Alice Madenlian congratulated <br>
the 87-year old organizations newest members and wished them <br>
success in their endeavors to serve the Armenian people, <br>
specifically the growing community in San Bernardino County. <br>
Madenlian welcomed the novitiates, who had independently served <br>
their community before joining "the ARS family."<br>
	The official ceremony concluded with the singing of the ARS <br>
anthem and the patriotic song "Getashen," the city in Nagorno-<br>
Karabakh that witnessed heroic self-defense struggles and after <br>
which the chapter is named.<br>
	Newly-inducted members Hrip Dolmajian, Hasmig Dabaghian, <br>
Berjouhi Benyazian, Rosine Panjarjian, Kohar Zaher and Sona <br>
Demirjian were appointed to the chapters executive body.<br>
	During the past year and a half, members of the chapter have <br>
been operating a Saturday school to teach area children about <br>
their Armenian heritage.<br>
<p>
<p>
7. PRELATE MARDIROSSIAN HONORED IN ORANGE COUNTY<br>
<p>
SANTA ANA-The Armenian community of Orange County honored Right <br>
Rev. Moushegh Mardirossian, Prelate of the Western United States, <br>
for ten years of service to their community during a banquet in <br>
his honor on Dec. 1. The event also served to congratulate Right <br>
Rev. Mardirossian on his election as Prelate.<br>
	Prior to his election, Right Rev. Mardirossian, nee Sarkis, <br>
served as the spiritual leader of the Forty Martyrs Armenian <br>
Apostolic Church in Santa Ana.<br>
	Eastern United States Prelate Archbishop Mesrob Ashjian, <br>
Arch. Smpad Lapajian, Arch. Yeprem Tabakian and  Right Rev. Miuron <br>
Aznikian were on among the more than 400 people in attendance at <br>
the event.<br>
	A cultural program following the benediction by Rev. Nareg <br>
Pehlivanian featured the sixth grade students of Ari Guiragos <br>
Minassian Armenian School, who recited "The Armenian Language" <br>
poem and Sunday school students that made brief congratulatory <br>
statements to the Prelate.<br>
	Arpine and Elizabeth Pehlivanian performed duets by <br>
Ganachian and Kotoyan, followed by a solo performance by Arpine <br>
Pehlivanian, accompanied on the piano by Gloria Mikayelian. <br>
	Cellist Gasia Kaprielian, accompanied by Kevork Gulatian on <br>
the piano, performed selections from Tchaikovsky, Gomidas and <br>
Ayvazian.<br>
	Following the dinner, several community representatives and <br>
clergy reflected on the Prelates dedicated service to the <br>
Armenian Church and nation, his character  and beliefs and values.<br>
	Retired Rev. Ashod Kochian highly praised Mardirossians <br>
respect and devotion toward his people and his ability to preach <br>
and guide the community. Rev. Kochian described Mardirossian as <br>
"an exemplary clergyman with a stubborn will, unrelenting spirit <br>
and celestial talents and capabilities."<br>
	Right Rev. Miuron Aznikian of Fresnos Holy Trinity Church <br>
also had high words of praise for Mardirossian and his service. <br>
"As a member of the clergy, you directed your love and caring <br>
toward everyone, inspired people to understand one another and <br>
shared your faith, hope and spirit of self-sacrifice with all <br>
those that came to hear the kind sermons of the kind shepherd, " <br>
Aznikian said.<br>
	Chairman of the Prelacy Religious Council, Arch. Yeprem <br>
Tabakian voiced hope that similar events and occasions would draw <br>
the youth of the community toward serving the Armenian Church. <br>
Tabakian congratulated  Mardirossian on behalf of the Religious <br>
and Executive councils of the Prelacy and wished him success in <br>
fulfilling his duties as Prelate just as he did while in Orange <br>
County.<br>
	Eastern United States Prelate, Arch. Mesrob Ashjian, who had <br>
been Mardirossians first teacher at the Holy See of Cilicia <br>
Seminary in Antelias, Lebanon, expressed  confidence in his former <br>
students abilities. Because he did such a good job in Orange <br>
County, he was given a greater responsibility to lead the Western <br>
Prelacy, Ashjian said of Mardirossian.<br>
	His Holiness Aram I of the Holy See of Cilicia joined those <br>
honoring Mardirossian with a special message read by Rev. Papken <br>
Charian.<br>
	Chairman of the Forty Martyrs Church Board of Trustees, <br>
Baghdig Ohanian spoke of the Prelates days in Orange County. <br>
"With his enthusiasm and commitment, Right Rev. Mardirossian <br>
inspired and breathed new life into our community," Ohanian said, <br>
crediting Mardirossian with the expansion of  community <br>
organizations. Ohanian then presented Mardirossian with a  <br>
Bishops ring.<br>
	The guest of honor was humbled by the words of praise as he <br>
expressed his gratitude to Catholicos Aram I and thanked the <br>
members of the clergy for their kind words. "Their heartfelt <br>
praises were not for me, but for my service, and their words <br>
encouraged and inspired me to continue to serve, more dedicated <br>
and determined than ever," Mardirossian said.<br>
	Reflecting on his years in Orange County, Mardirossian was <br>
especially grateful to the Armenian community there  for its <br>
decade-long nurturing and support. He thanked them and wished them <br>
continued prosperity and growth. "Let growth and development of <br>
the community be your motivation for involvement," the Prelate <br>
advised.<br>
	The final speaker of the evening was the first Prelate of <br>
the Western US, Arch. Smpad Lapajian, who wished the new Prelate <br>
success and recalled the words of John the Baptist: "We have <br>
opened a door before you and that door will not close as long as <br>
you wish to serve God and your people with genuine faith, love and <br>
complete devotion."<br>
	The evening concluded with Arch. Lapajians closing prayers.<br>
<p>
<p>
8. EIGHTH HOMENETMEN PAN-ARMENIAN GAMES CONCLUDE<br>
<p>
PASADENA-The Eighth annual Pan Armenian Games of the Armenian <br>
General Athletic Association-Homenetmen-drew to a close Friday, <br>
Dec. 6 with a special banquet in  honor of the athletes, <br>
volunteers and organizers that made the games such a huge success.<br>
	With some 600 guests on hand and the Pasadena Armenian <br>
Center hall decorated with balls and other athletic paraphernalia <br>
to symbolize the evening, Armenian singers Harout Pamboukjian and <br>
Ashot did their part to create a festive and warm atmosphere as <br>
dinner was served, while countless guests danced to traditional <br>
Armenian music before the official program got underway.<br>
	Homenetmen Regional Executive member Siran Bosnoian acted as <br>
mistress of ceremonies, and on behalf of the Homenetmen Western <br>
Regional Executive and the Athletic Council, welcomed all in <br>
attendance and officially called the games to a close.<br>
	"Every weekend during the past two months, the games brought <br>
together athletes came together from various Armenian athletic <br>
organizations to showcase their talent in an environment of <br>
healthy competition," Bosnoian said.<br>
	Bosnoian introduced several prominent figures in attendance <br>
Friday, including Homenetmen Central Executive member Koko Balian, <br>
as well as newly-elected members Mher Tavitian (chairman), Jora <br>
Martirossian, Steve Artinian, Vartan Yaghmourian, Sako Garabedian, <br>
Raffi Ispendjian, Bosnoian, Oshin Peroomian and Shahik Aghbabian.<br>
	"In keeping with A healthy mind in a healthy body motto of <br>
Homenetmen, we believe that these games will serve as an example <br>
to other community groups to organize similar athletic events <br>
between our youth where unity and togetherness would be stressed," <br>
Bosnoian added.<br>
	Following the short program, championship trophies and <br>
medals were handed out to the winning teams and athletes.<br>
	In addition, the Regional Executive presented one male and <br>
one female participant with the Exemplary Athlete Award for <br>
his/her outstanding leadership, talent and sportsmanship during <br>
the course of the games. This years recipients were Montebellos <br>
Greg Khachikian and Glendale "Ararat" Chapters Yolanda Davitian.<br>
	Veteran members Mike Vartanian and Serko Ashikian were <br>
honored for the tireless efforts during the past two years, while <br>
longtime member Manuel Marselian was honored for his service to <br>
the organization and his efforts in bringing Homenetmen to the <br>
forefront of the community.<br>
	The games began Saturday, Sept. 28 and lasted until Sunday, <br>
Nov. 24, and involved 156 teams from virtually every Homenetmen <br>
chapter in the area, as well as the Glendale, Pasadena and San <br>
Fernando Valley chapters of the Armenian General Benevolent Union, <br>
the Armenian Youth Athletic Association and the "Nareg" Cultural <br>
Union.<br>
	AGBU representative Hagop Sepedjian was presented with the <br>
championship trophies for basketball and volleyball (AA and A <br>
Divisions) by Regional Executive chairman Mher Tavidian and <br>
Regional Executive representative to the Athletic Council, Raffi <br>
Ispendjian.<br>
