        MEETINGS WITH PRESIDENT TER-PETROSSIAN<br>
<p>
 YEREVAN, DECEMBER 11, ARMENPRESS.<br>
 Yesterday, the President of the Republic of Armenia, Levon<br>
 Ter-Petrossian held a meeting-consultation with the Chairman of the<br>
 Central Bank of the Republic of Armenia, Bagrat Asatrian, the<br>
 Minister of Finance of the Republic of Armenia, Levon Barkhudarian,<br>
 and the Head of the Taxation Department of the Republic of Armenia<br>
 Pavel Safarian. During the meeting the sides discussed issues related<br>
 to the realization of the 1996 state budget and the taxation system.<br>
 On the same day, President Ter-Petrossian met with the Minister of<br>
 Energy of the Republic of Armenia, Gagik Martirossian, to discuss the<br>
 issues related to the electricity supply in Yerevan and other cities<br>
 during the winter.<br>
<p>
        ARMENIAN AND RUSSIAN FOREIGN MINISTERS MEET IN MOSCOW<br>
<p>
 MOSCOW, DECEMBER 11, ARMENPRESS.<br>
 After the meeting with the Minister of Foreign Affairs of the<br>
 Republic of Armenia Alexander Arzumanian, the Russian Foreign<br>
Minister<br>
 Evgeni Primakov stated that Russia is interested in the stabilisation<br>
 of the situation in Nagorny Karabagh and the quick resolution of the<br>
 conflict based on mutual compromise.<br>
 "The solution of the problem must be found in the recognition of the<br>
 Nagorny Karabagh's right to self-determination, while respecting the<br>
 territorial integrity of Azerbaijan," continued Mr. Primakov.<br>
 During the meetings, the Armenian and Russian Foreign Ministers<br>
 reached mutual understranding in various economic and political<br>
 issues. However, the sides maintained different attitudes toward the<br>
 recent presidential elections in Nagorny Karabagh. Mr. Primakov said<br>
 that the Russian side opposed the fact of holding presidential<br>
 elections in Nagorny Karabagh before finding a solution to the<br>
 problem.<br>
 The Armenian Foreign Minister Alexander Arzumanian pointed out that<br>
 the Armenian side does not consider the elections as an extraordinary<br>
 phenomenon outside the logical limits of the negotiation process. He<br>
 reminded that in 1992, the Minsk Group had decided that the elected<br>
 authorities of Armenia, Azerbaijan and Nagorny Karabagh should<br>
 participate in the negotiations. "Thus, the elections do not break<br>
 the harmony of the negotiation process," added the Armenian Foreign<br>
 Minister.<br>
 As for the Russian military presence in Armenia, Mr. Primakov<br>
 informed that the appropriate documents have been sent to the State<br>
 Duma (parliament) for ratification. Meanwhile, Mr. Primakov asked<br>
 the Armenian side to speed up the passage of corresponsing documents<br>
 in the Armenian parliament.<br>
<p>
        61.9 PERCENT OF PRIVATIZATION CERTIFICATES USED<br>
<p>
 YEREVAN, DECEMBER 11, ARMENPRESS.<br>
 As of December 1,982,988 privatization certificates distributed to<br>
 the population of the Republic of Armenia have been used. This is<br>
 61.9 percent of the total number of certificates distributed. New<br>
 privatization certificates will be distributed only after 90 percent<br>
 of the old ones will be used.<br>
<p>
<p>
        NEW WORLD BANK LOAN TO SUPPORT PRIVATE SECTOR<br>
<p>
 YEREVAN, DECEMBER 11, ARMENPRESS.<br>
 As was reported earlier, recently the Republic of Armenia and the<br>
 World Bank have signed a loan agreement, according to which the World<br>
 Bank will extend a 17 million dollar loan to Armenia.<br>
 According to the Deputy Minister of Economy of the Republic of<br>
 Armenia Vardan Movsisian, unlike other loans, which were used to<br>
 cover the state budget deficit or for the reconstruction of the<br>
 industrial insfrastructure, the new loan will be used for the support<br>
 of the private sector in the Armenian economy.<br>
<p>
    SURVEY OF TECHNICAL CONDITION OF BUILDINGS IN THE EARTHQUAKE ZONE<br>
<p>
 YEREVAN, DECEMBER 11, ARMENPRESS.<br>
 The Armenian Institute of Seismically Resistant Constructions has<br>
 conducted a survey of the technical condition of buildings in the<br>
 earthquake zone.<br>
 15 cities and town (not including Yerevan and Gyumri) were surveyed.<br>
 Out of 1167 buildings, 105 have damages of the first degree, and need<br>
 slight repair. 798 buildings have damages of the second degree.<br>
 234 buildings have damages of the third degree. Their fundamental<br>
 constructions have serious damages, and this building will have to<br>
 be strengthened.<br>
 It is financially and technically not viable to reconstruct the<br>
 buildings with the fourth degree of damages. 30 out of 162 buildings<br>
 in this category will be demolished.<br>
<p>
   ARMENIA TO COOPERATE WITH THE EUROPEAN UNION IN THE AREA OF TRADE<br>
<p>
 YEREVAN, DECEMBER 11, ARMENPRESS.<br>
 According to the Press Service of the President of the Republic of<br>
 Armenia, yesterday, in Brussels, the Head of the Armenian Mission in<br>
 the European Union, Ambassador Gagik Shahbazian, signed a temporary<br>
 agreement with the European Union on trade and commercial issues.<br>
 This agreement will allow Armenia to cooperate with the European<br>
 Union and its member-countries in the area of trade and commerce.<br>
<p>
        FOREIGN INVESTMENTS TO INCREASE NEXT YEAR<br>
<p>
 YEREVAN, DECEMBER 11, ARMENPRESS.<br>
 As of December 10, the total founding capital of Armenian enterprises<br>
 with foreign investments is 50.5 million US dollars (since 1988).<br>
 According to Head of the Foreign Investments Department of the<br>
 Ministry of Economy of the Republic of Armenia, Ms. Narine Sahakian,<br>
 the main form of organizing foreign investments in Armenia remains<br>
 the establishement of enterprises with foreign investments.<br>
 There are 675 such enterprises in Armenia today. 374 of them are<br>
 joint ventures. The main investors are the United States, Iran, and<br>
 Russia.<br>
 Out of the expected 33.8 million dollars as foreign investments in<br>
 1996, 24 million have already been invested. According to Ms.<br>
 Sahakian, 75 million dollars are expected to be invested in Armenia's<br>
 economy in 1997.<br>
<p>
<p>
        PRESIDENT TER-PETROSSIAN MEETS WITH THE LEADERS OF THE<br>
        HANRAPETUTYUN BLOC<br>
<p>
 YEREVAN, DECEMBER 12, ARMENPRESS.<br>
 Yesterday, the President of the Republic of Armenia Levon<br>
 Ter-Petrossian met with the leaders of the political parties which<br>
 form the Hanrapetutyun [Republic] bloc: Ter Husik Lazarian (Armenian<br>
 National Movement), Ashot Navasardian (Republican Party), Hovhanness<br>
 Tokmadjian (Intellectual Armenia party), Eghia Najarian (Social<br>
 Democratic Henchak Party), Vigen Khachatrian (Ramkavar Azatakan<br>
 (Liberal Democratic) party), and Azat Arshakian (Christian Democratic<br>
 Union).<br>
 During the meeting the sides discussed issues related to the results<br>
 of the recent local government elections, the relations between the<br>
 newly formed local government bodies and the National Assembly, the<br>
 internal political situation in Armenia, and the Hanrapetutyun Bloc's<br>
 future activities.<br>
<p>
        PRESIDENT OF THE NATIONAL ASSEMBLY BABKEN ARARKTSIAN MEETS<br>
        WITH THE GEORGIAN PRESIDENT<br>
<p>
 YEREVAN, DECEMBER 12, ARMENPRESS.<br>
 Yesterday, the President of the National Assembly of the Republic of<br>
 Armenia Babken Ararktsian met with the President of Georgia Eduard<br>
 Chevardnadze, in Tbilisi.<br>
 During the meeting the sides discussed the Armenian-Georgian<br>
 relations, the social situation in both countries, and some regional<br>
 problems. They also discussed the processes of peaceful settlement of<br>
 conflicts in Abkhazia and Nagorny Karabagh.<br>
 The Georgian President welcomed the idea of his Armenian counterpart<br>
 Levon Ter-Petrosyan to establish direct dialogue between the<br>
 Transcaucasian countries.<br>
<p>
        REPRESENTATIVE OF THE ACTING CHAIRMAN OF THE OSCE VISITS<br>
        NAGORNY KARABAGH<br>
<p>
 STEPANAKERT, DECEMBER 12, ARMENPRESS.<br>
 The representative of the OSCE Acting Chairman, Ambassador Anjey<br>
 Casprcik has arrived in Stepanakert. There, he was received by the<br>
 Minister of Foreign Affairs of Nagonro-Karabagh Republic Arkadi<br>
 Ghukassian. During the meeting the sides discussed various points of<br>
 view on the Karabagh conflict resolution,  as well as some issues<br>
 related to the OSCE's activities in Karabagh.<br>
 The Ambassador also met with the First Deputy Minister of Defense,<br>
 Major-General Seiran Ohanian.<br>
<p>
<p>
        ARMENIAN-AMERICAN COOPERATION IN THE AREA OF AGRICULTURE<br>
<p>
 YEREVAN, DECEMBER 12, ARMENPRESS.<br>
 According to the Deputy Minister of Agriculture of the Republic of<br>
 Armenia Ishkhan Martirossian, the country cooperates in the area of<br>
 agriculture with several foreign organizations, mostly American.<br>
 Thus, the United States Department of Agriculture (USDA) has a<br>
 training program, where each year ten agricultural specialists<br>
 undergo special training in the United States. Within four years,<br>
 about 50 people went through this training. The USDA also has a<br>
 humanitarian aid program which generates income from the sale of<br>
 wheat to finance the "Gitaspyur" program.<br>
 Many American organizations (UMCOR, CARE, US Peace Corps, etc) make<br>
 direct investments in various villages of the country, thus providing<br>
 much needed financial assistance to the newly emerging farmers.<br>
<p>
        CENTRAL BANK CLARIFIES...<br>
<p>
 YEREVAN, DECEMBER 12, ARMENPRESS.<br>
 Recently, the Central Bank of the Republic of Armenia passed a<br>
 decision, according to which physical persons can apply through the<br>
 Central Bank to participate in the first distribution auction of the<br>
 short term state bonds. Some experts think that such a decision will<br>
 hamper the development of the secondary securities market in Armenia.<br>
 The Central Bank will become a dealer for physical persons, which is<br>
 an unusual function for the Central Bank.<br>
 According to the Head of the Financial Transactions of the Central<br>
 Bank of the Republic of Armenia Tigran Davtian, the purpose of this<br>
 decision is to facilitate the process of buying securities for the<br>
 people. There is a lot of money in private hands right now, and<br>
 people do not trust commercial banks. But, according to Mr. Davtian,<br>
 people trust the Central Bank. Mr. Davtian also added, that this is s<br>
 temporary measure, which will help to increase people's confidence in<br>
 the securities.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
