AASBAREZ ON LINE <br>
12/12/1996<br>
<p>
<p>
1. KARABAKH PARLIAMENT THREATENS TO REVIEW OSCE PARTICIPATION<br>
2. APPEALS FILED IN "DRO" CASE<br>
3. SCIENTISTS MARK ANNIVERSARY OF FOUNDER OF SPACE BIOLOGY <br>
4. DEFENDANT KAZARIAN DENIES PRELIMINARY TESTIMONY<br>
6. BABAJANIANS 75TH BIRTHDAY TO BE MARKED IN MOSCOW<br>
5. CENTRAL BANK OF AZERBAIJAN MAY JOIN BASEL COMMITTEE<br>
7. MAFIA SCANDAL EMBROILS POLITICS IN SCANDAL<br>
8. EUROPARLIAMENT URGES BELARUS AID FREEZE<br>
9. JOHN &amp; ASTGHIK PETROSSIAN DONATE $15,000 TO PRELACY<br>
<p>
<p>
1. KARABAKH PARLIAMENT THREATENS TO REVIEW OSCE PARTICIPATION<br>
<p>
STEPANAKERT (Noyan Tapan)-"The National Assembly of Nagorno-<br>
Karabakh expresses its regret that during the Lisbon Summit of the <br>
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe member states, <br>
the Azeri delegations provocative stance over the settlement of <br>
the Karabakh conflict did not find a proper denouncement," <br>
according to a statement released by the National Assembly of <br>
Nagorno-Karabakh Tuesday.<br>
	"The National Assembly of Karabakh views the statement by <br>
the  OSCE Chairman-in-Office about the principles of the Karabakh <br>
problem as an attempt to predetermine Karabakhs status by <br>
completly ignoring its the right to self-determination. We are <br>
also indignant by the fact that in searching for a settlement, the <br>
participants of the OSCE Minsk Group persistently renounced the <br>
international legal aspects of the problem, the current <br>
military/political situation and continued attempts at  self-<br>
preservation of the forcibly divided Armenian nation.<br>
	"We consider Azerbaijans stance voiced at the Lisbon Summit <br>
to be a continuation of the policy of annexation of Nagorno-<br>
Karabakh, which is finally aimed at forcible deportation of the <br>
native Armenian population from its historical homeland. People <br>
have a right to freedom and security. Our people paid too much to <br>
gain this right and will never agree to become a pawn in the <br>
[Caspian] oil game and to delegate the guarantee of its security <br>
to Azerbaijan, which has a criminal past.<br>
	"The National Assembly of Karabakh calls on the Azeri side <br>
to renounce the policy of annexation, blackmail, political <br>
speculation, manipulation and commence bilateral negotiations.<br>
	"We are convinced that it is the constitutional way to <br>
achieve peace between Nagorno-Karabakh and Azerbaijan. <br>
	"Assessing the OSCE chairmans statement as a unilateral <br>
stance, which reflects the interests of only Azerbaijan and <br>
contradicts the essence of international mediation, the Karabakh <br>
Parliament claims that such a stance by the OSCE makes us wonder <br>
if Karabakhs further participation in the Minsk process makes any <br>
sense. <br>
	"The Karabakh Parliament calls on the United Nations, the <br>
OSCE, the Commonwealth of Independent States and other <br>
international organizations to display support for our peoples <br>
aspiration to freedom and self-determination and actively <br>
contribute to the peaceful settlement of the conflict on the basis <br>
of a fair, wise and mutually admissible decisions."<br>
<p>
<p>
2. APPEALS FILED IN "DRO" CASE<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Shrjan)-The attorneys for Hrand Markarian, Ara <br>
Harmandarian and Armenak Mnjoyan announced plans Thursday to <br>
appeal the verdict and sentences in the case of the so-called <br>
"Dro" case, which concluded Tuesday more than a year later.<br>
	Rouben Rshdouni, who was not in the courtroom during <br>
Tuesdays sentencing, said he planned to file an appeal with <br>
Armenias Supreme Court. Rshdouni was not present due to another <br>
court appearance in Kapan Tuesday, sources close to the case said.<br>
	Armenian law on appeals allows ten days for attorneys to <br>
file with the Supreme Court. In the case of the "Dro" trial, the <br>
Supreme Court heard the original case. A new judicial board or a <br>
new judge may be assigned the case on appeal.<br>
	Sahakian said he will base his appeal on the fact that <br>
Markarian was never convicted of a crime, yet he received the <br>
maximum sentence for the crimes he was charged with. "[Judge] <br>
Edward Manoukian finally made his decision, but failed to outline <br>
the extenuating circumstances leading to the sentence," Sahakian <br>
said, adding that Manoukian also disregarded the testimony of <br>
character witnesses, especially a statement from General Arkady <br>
Tatevosian.<br>
	According to Sahakian, the judge was unable to establish a <br>
link between Hrand Markarian and the "Dro" group because in order <br>
do that he would have had to present evidence, which simply does <br>
not exist. "Manoukian, himself, acknowledged this fact and <br>
acquitted my client of those charges. I can only say that <br>
Armenias leadership does not want to see Markarian free," he <br>
said.<br>
	Ara Harmandarians verdict was also unfair, Sahakian noted.<br>
	Anahit Yessayan, co-counsel for Markarian, said that she <br>
expected acquittal of all charges, based on the fact that all the <br>
evidence presented in court had been compiled through questionable <br>
preliminary investigations and depositions. 	<br>
	"There was a document signed by the Defense Minister of <br>
Nagorno-Karabakh giving Markarian permission to carry and <br>
distribute weapons," Yessayan said, pointing to Markarians <br>
charges of illegal possession of weapons and forged documents.<br>
	"Those charges are also morally wrong if you take into <br>
consideration that he [Markarian] fought for the defense of <br>
Nagorno-Karabakh. And in that capacity, carrying forged documents <br>
oftentimes was imperative in securing the defense of a large <br>
portion of the Armenian population," Yessayan added.<br>
	In addition, Hrand Markarian reportedly affixed official <br>
Azeri stamps to the passports of the self-defense fighters in <br>
order to facilitate their travel throughout the region. "This <br>
charge was also unsubstantiated," Yessayan said.<br>
	Yessayan was convinced that the maximum sentence was given <br>
to her client based on unsubstantiated charges in order to free <br>
from responsibility those individuals that signed Markarians <br>
arrest orders.<br>
	"I think the appeal will bring about changes in the <br>
sentence," Yessayan said.<br>
<p>
<p>
3. SCIENTISTS MARK ANNIVERSARY OF FOUNDER OF SPACE BIOLOGY <br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-A scientific conference dedicated to the <br>
90th anniversary of the founder of space biology and member of the <br>
National Academy of Armenia, Norayr Sisakian, took place Thursday <br>
at the National Academy of Sciences in Armenia.<br>
	"Today we are paying tribute to the greatest son of Armenia <br>
who achieved worldwide success in the creation of a number of new <br>
trends in science," President of the National Academy of Sciences <br>
of Armenia, Fadey Sarkissian said as he greeted the participants <br>
of the conference. Sisakians son, Vice-Director of the United <br>
Institute of Nuclear Studies, (Dubna) Alexey Sisakian, also <br>
attended the conference.<br>
	Fellow scientist Armen Galoyan briefed those present on the <br>
wide range of scientific problems which were first surveyed by <br>
Sisakian. He especially pointed out the scientific research of <br>
1960-1962, which dealt with biological and medical research on the <br>
preparation of a human being for space mission.<br>
	The participants also hailed Sisakians great contribution <br>
to the development of science when he was the Soviet Union <br>
representative to UNESCO. <br>
	Sisakian who died at 59  was the receipient of a number of <br>
awards including  a title of  Bach and Mechnikov prizes, as well <br>
as medals from the Liege University (Belgium, 1956) and Pasteurs <br>
Institute (Paris, 1959). One of the moons craters was named after <br>
Sisakian.<br>
	In January 1997, an international symposium, "Problems of <br>
Biochemistry, Radiation and Space Biology," dedicated to Sisakian <br>
will be held in Moscow and Dubna and will be sponsored by UNESCO. <br>
The Russian Academy of Sciences, the National Academy of Sciences <br>
of Armenia and the Yerevan State University will take part in the <br>
organization of the symposium. The President of the National <br>
Academy of France, Professor Grunberg-Manago, Academicians from <br>
the Russian Academy of Sciences and NASA representatives have been <br>
invited to attend the symposium.<br>
<p>
<p>
4. DEFENDANT KAZARIAN DENIES PRELIMINARY TESTIMONY<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-At Wednesdays "Trial of 31" court session, <br>
defendant Arthur Kazarian pleaded not guilty to charges of <br>
plotting a coup detat and terrorist activity.<br>
	He noted that the preliminary evidence linking him to a coup <br>
detat and acts of terrorism were not true. The defendant said he <br>
had given these "false statements" to help his arrested father, <br>
relatives and neighbors. Kazarian refused to answer whether he had <br>
been tortured in the course of the preliminary investigation.<br>
	He said that he had been denied access to an attorney  from <br>
the onset of the trial. The court refused Kazarians request for a <br>
new attorney. Kazarian is the only defendant who does not have <br>
legal representation.<br>
	Kazarian also said that attempts to connect the "Dro" <br>
detachment which  fought  on the Armenian border  with the "Dro" <br>
case or the ARF Party had been early in the case.  Kazarian said <br>
the preliminary investigation was set up to connect these people <br>
with the "Trial of  31" case.<br>
	The defendant was bewildered over the fact that three hours <br>
after the policemen had been killed, he and co-defendant Gagik <br>
Karapetian were announced murderers and their photographs shown on <br>
numerous TV news broadcasts.<br>
	"This means that everything had been plotted including the <br>
murder of the policemen," said Kazarian.<br>
<p>
<p>
5. CENTRAL BANK OF AZERBAIJAN MAY JOIN BASEL COMMITTEE<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-Chairman of the Transcaucasian  Council, <br>
Rouben Valessian reported on Wednesday that the Central Bank of <br>
Azerbaijan would be joining the regional group of Trancaucasian <br>
and Central Asian countries of the International Basel Banking <br>
Control Committee.<br>
	The regional group of Transcaucasian and Central Asian <br>
countries of the International Basel Banking Control Committee was <br>
set up in Yerevan in 1995. Azerbaijan has never participated in <br>
the work of the Committee. <br>
	Valessian said that from now on all decisions on control <br>
standards would be taken by the International Basel Committee for <br>
banking control after they are agreed on with the regional groups.<br>
	The group's Ashkhabad conference dealt with problems of <br>
todays banking control methods and ways of controlling <br>
international banking systems. The next conference will be held in <br>
Tbilisi, in June 1997.<br>
	Valessian particularly stressed the importance of his <br>
meeting with representatives of Turkey. This was the first meeting <br>
at the Central Bank level. <br>
	Valessian said he planned to visit  Ankara to discuss <br>
problems with the  exchange of specialists and banking control.<br>
<p>
<p>
6. BABAJANIANS 75TH BIRTHDAY TO BE MARKED IN MOSCOW<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-A festival dedicated to the 75th birthday of <br>
prominent Armenian composer Arno Babajanian will be held in Moscow <br>
from  Dec. 15 to  20.<br>
	Ara Babajanian, the composers son and  chairman of the Arno <br>
Babajanian Fund, reported that a special committee led by Deputy <br>
Speaker of the Russian Duma Artur Chilingarov had been <br>
established, and included  Armenias Culture Minister Armen <br>
Smbatian, Chairman of the Union of Composers of Armenia Robert <br>
Amirkhanian, Deputy Culture Minister of Russia Mikhail Shvidkoy, <br>
singer Iosif Kobzon and  businessman Artem Tarasov.<br>
	An Armenian delegation led by Armen Smbatian has already <br>
arrived in Moscow. The delegation is made up of composers Edward <br>
Mirzoyan, Alexander Haroutiunian, Lazar Sarian, Adam Khoudoyan, <br>
Robert Amirkhanian and Yuri Erzinkian.<br>
	A solemn opening of the festival is to take place on Dec. 16 <br>
at the Concert  Hall of the Chaikovsky Conservatory in Moscow. The <br>
Russian Symphonic Orchestra directed by Ohan Dourian and Mikael <br>
Avetissian will perform Babajanians compositions.<br>
	A memorial table made by sculptor Aramian will be displayed <br>
at 13 Ogarev Street in Moscow. Famous script-writers and movie <br>
directors who have worked with Babajanian will take part in a <br>
special program  dedicated to Babajanians film scores. "My Heart <br>
in the Highlands" will also be screened during the party.<br>
	A final concert will take place in Kollony Hall during which <br>
Russian and Armenian artists will perform.   <br>
	On Dec. 17 Armenias delegation will meet with members of <br>
the Russian State Duma. A  reception in honor of participants of <br>
the festival will also take place on that day. <br>
<p>
<p>
7. MAFIA SCANDAL EMBROILS POLITICS IN SCANDAL<br>
<p>
ANKARA (Reuter)-A government parliamentarian Thursday faced <br>
possible prosecution in a security scandal that is drawing <br>
Turkeys politicians deeper into a twilight world of gangsters, <br>
mystery murders and heroin trafficking.<br>
	Justice ministry officials said a prosecutor had asked in a <br>
report for legal steps to be taken to lift deputy Mehmet Agars <br>
parliamentary immunity from legal censure.<br>
	"This report has reached our criminal affairs department. It <br>
is being studied," a ministry official told Reuters.<br>
	Agar, who quit as interior minister in November over the <br>
scandal, was accused this week of having signed a false police <br>
identity document for a fugitive gangster who was allegedly used <br>
by officials to kill Turkeys political opponents.<br>
	President Suleyman Demirel, who usually stays clear of day-<br>
to-day politics, has put his weight behind calls for five weeks of <br>
allegations to be cleared up.<br>
	"This is an important matter. It has to be brought to light. <br>
It has to go as far is it goes," he told Turkish television on <br>
Wednesday in a rare interview that was devoted to the scandal.<br>
	The media and opposition have alleged that leading officials <br>
directed hit squads to kill Kurdish rebel sympathizers and <br>
business rivals. More than 1,300 people have died since 1992 in <br>
unsolved political killings, human right activists say.<br>
	The scandal broke on November 3 when a car carrying a <br>
government parliamentarian who heads a Kurdish militia, a wanted <br>
gangster and a leading policeman crashed.<br>
	It has pushed problems like annual inflation of more than 80 <br>
percent, faltering revenue-raising plans and worsening relations <br>
with Europe almost off the political map.<br>
	Demirel said he feared the whole establishment could be <br>
tainted by the affair. "If the perpetrators are not found the <br>
state will get the blame. I am also uneasy about (the mystery <br>
killings)."<br>
	He said main opposition leader Mesut Yilmaz had given him <br>
names of "people in high places" involved in the scandal. <br>
	Demirel met Prime Minister Necmettin Erbakan on Thursday <br>
evening for talks on Yilmazs accusations that a network of up to <br>
120 people directed by senior policemen are involved in murders, <br>
extortion and drug smuggling.<br>
	"Whatever is necessary will be brought out into the open. <br>
The state is legal state. If there is within the state, a person <br>
or group acting against the law, none of us can accept this," <br>
Erbakan said after the meeting.<br>
	Erbakans coalition partner Tansu Ciller, linked by the <br>
media to the scandal, said the atmosphere of suspicion had dented <br>
public faith in the system.<br>
	"Turkey has been put under a cloud, from the office of the <br>
president to the police force and parliament," Foreign Minister <br>
Ciller told a meeting of her True Path Party.<br>
	Western diplomats say Ciller has lost much of her <br>
credibility for a speech she made last month in which she praised <br>
convicted heroin smuggler Abdullah Catli, who died in the crash, <br>
and suggested he had done political dirty work for the security <br>
apparatus.<br>
	Although Catli had been sought for murder for 18 years, a <br>
police identity document and a passport of a kind only issued to <br>
top officials were recovered in the car.<br>
<p>
<p>
8. EUROPARLIAMENT URGES BELARUS AID FREEZE<br>
<p>
STRASBOURG, France (Reuter)-The European Parliament on Thursday <br>
urged the 15-nation European Union to stop financial aid to <br>
Belarus because of doubts over its commitment to democracy.<br>
	Hard-line Belarus President Alexander Lukashenko has been <br>
criticized in the West for using a huge victory in a November 24 <br>
referendum to rewrite the constitution and secure sweeping powers <br>
for himself.<br>
	The EU assembly, said that only democracy-related aid under <br>
the so-called TACIS program, which includes measures to support a <br>
free and independent media, should be maintained. <br>
	The Parliament confirmed an earlier statement that it would <br>
go no further with a planned cooperation and partnership accord <br>
with the former Soviet republic until it had received "clear <br>
signals from the Belarus authorities of their intention fully to <br>
respect basic democratic and human rights."<br>
	The Parliament said in a statement that the EU should use <br>
its weight to put pressure on international organizations to <br>
freeze their own aid in a bid to force democracy in Belarus.<br>
<p>
<p>
9. JOHN &amp; ASTGHIK PETROSSIAN DONATE $15,000 TO PRELACY<br>
<p>
LOS ANGELES-Mr. &amp; Mrs. John and Astghik Petrossian of Encino <br>
recently donated $15,000 to the Western Prelacy on the occasion of <br>
the new year and Christmas holidays.<br>
	For years the Petrossians have been regular contributors to <br>
the Prelacy and through their financial and moral generosity have <br>
supported the religious, education and cultural activities <br>
undertaken by the Prelacy.<br>
	Through this donation, the Petrossians, once again, have <br>
sponsored the annual traditional Christmas banquet hosted by the <br>
Prelate.<br>
	The Petrossians also underwrote all costs for His Holiness <br>
Aram I, Catholicos of the Holy See of Cilicia during his first <br>
pontifical visit to the Western Region.<br>
	Western Prelate Right Rev. Moushegh Mardirossian and the <br>
Prelacy Religious and Executive councils expressed their gratitude <br>
to the Petrossians for their continued generosity.<br>
	John Petrossian is a National Representative Assembly <br>
Delegate from Encinos Holy Martyrs Armenian Church.<br>
<p>
