<title>Groong Network: Armenian News 12/12/96</title>
<h1>Armenian News 12/12/96</h1>
<i>Chavoush@aol.com</i><br>
<i>Thu, 12 Dec 96 10:35:33 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#103">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#103">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#103">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#103">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0104.html">nt-send@nt.arminco.com: "Noyan Tapan News (December 12)"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0102.html">Asbed Bedrossian: "OMRI Digest 12/12/96"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Headlines of stories which follow:<br>
1.  Armenians detained trying to cross Polish-German border illegally <br>
2.  Three members of "terrorist group" sentenced to death <br>
3.  Islamic foreign ministers ready to condemn Armenia over Karabakh <br>
4.  Turkey drops plan to open border gate with Armenia <br>
5.  Taiwan Buddhist group aids refugees in Azerbaijan <br>
6.  Armenian Church leader visits Pope <br>
7.  Defendory International exhibition <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Armenians detained trying to cross Polish-German border illegally <br>
SOURCE: PAP news agency, Warsaw, in English 0730 gmt 11 Dec 96 <br>
<p>
Some 16 Armenian citizens, including six children, were detained while trying<br>
to illegally cross the Polish-German border in Strzegow, Zielona Gora<br>
Province [western Poland], today, spokesman for the local Border Guard Piotr<br>
Zakowiak has reported. <br>
<p>
The Armenians were travelling in a large Volkswagen with Poznan registration<br>
plates. The driver of the car managed to escape but was seized later in the<br>
day. <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Three members of "terrorist group" sentenced to death <br>
SOURCE: ITAR-TASS news agency (World Service), Moscow, in Russian 1716 gmt 10<br>
Dec 96 <br>
<p>
Three members of the 'Dro'organization who were accused of terrorist<br>
activities, including political assassinations, have been sentenced to death.<br>
<p>
<p>
The Armenian Supreme Court's panel of criminal judges sentenced "the<br>
organizer and the head of the armed band" , a Lebanese citizen, Arsen<br>
Artsruni, and two other members of the group - Armen Grigoryan and Armenak<br>
Minjoyan.   The latter is a grandson of the famous Soviet pharmaceutical<br>
chemistry scientist, Academician Armenak Minjoyan [1904-1970], the founder<br>
and director of the Yerevan Research Institute of Pure Organic Chemistry<br>
which now bears his name. <br>
<p>
Other members of the group received prison sentences of varying length. Among<br>
them Ara Kharmandayan, a Lebanese citizen, was sentenced to six years<br>
imprisonment. <br>
<p>
It was not proved that Grant Markaryan, an Iranian citizen, and Gegam<br>
Manukyan were members of the 'Dro' organization. Nevertheless, the former was<br>
sentenced to five years imprisonment for using a forged USSR passport and for<br>
illegal possession of arms and the latter got a three-year prison sentence<br>
for not reporting the planned crimes. The verdict specifies that the men have<br>
a week to appeal. <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Islamic foreign ministers ready to condemn Armenia over Karabakh <br>
SOURCE: ITAR-TASS news agency (World Service), Moscow, in English 1502 gmt 10<br>
Dec 96 <br>
<p>
Foreign ministers from the countries of the Organization of the Islamic<br>
Conference (OIC) meeting in the Indonesian capital, Jakarta, on 10th December<br>
backed Azerbaijan in condemning "Armenian aggression" and calling for the<br>
liberation of occupied Azerbaijani territory, ITAR-TASS news agency reported,<br>
quoting Azerbaijani Foreign Minister Hasan Hasanov. <br>
<p>
Hasanov said that on the second day of the meeting many speakers "<br>
unequivocally supported Azerbaijan's righteous cause" and condemned Armenia.<br>
"My country's assessment of Yerevan's actions as 'Armenian aggression' was<br>
politically backed by the OIC members," Hasanov said. <br>
<p>
He said the calls by speakers at the meeting for the withdrawal of Armenian<br>
troops from occupied Azerbaijani territory would be reflected in the<br>
meeting's final resolution on this issue, which, judging by the tone of the<br>
speakers, would differ very little from the original draft. <br>
<p>
Hasanov also expressed his appreciation of Russia's "sufficiently objective"<br>
stand on Nagornyy Karabakh, saying that recently Moscow had taken "a whole<br>
line of serious steps to achieve a fair settlement of this problem" , the<br>
agency said. <br>
<p>
"We must have only friendly relations with Russia," Hasanov added. <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Turkey drops plan to open border gate with Armenia <br>
SOURCE:  Agence France Presse, December 11, 1996<br>
 <br>
Turkey said Wednesday that it would not open a border checkpoint with Armenia<br>
unless Yerevan moved to settle a territorial dispute over the disputed<br>
enclave of Nagorno-Karabakh in neighboring Azerbaijan. <br>
<p>
"As long as Armenia does not take steps toward an agreement with Azerbaijan,<br>
Turkey's earlier decision (to keep its border with Armenia closed) will<br>
remain in effect," foreign ministry spokesman Sermet Atacanli told reporters.<br>
<p>
<p>
Turkey closed its frontier with Yerevan in April 1993 amid an Armenian<br>
military campaign to capture Nagorno-Karabakh, an enclave mainly populated by<br>
Armenians but within Azerbaijan. <br>
<p>
Turkey gave signs of revising its decision this year, with Foreign Minister<br>
Tansu Ciller saying in October that Ankara was planning to open the border<br>
with Armenia at Akyaka. <br>
<p>
But diplomats said Armenia's recent refusal to acknowledge the need for a<br>
solution to the problem had forced Turkey to rethink. <br>
<p>
The Azeri-Armenian dispute threatened the publication of a final declaration<br>
at the end of the Organisation for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE)<br>
summit in Lisbon last week. <br>
<p>
In the Nagorno-Karabakh dispute which flared in 1988, local Armenians have<br>
captured the whole of the enclave and surrounding Azeri lands. <br>
<p>
Turkey has given full diplomatic support to Azerbaijan, with which it has<br>
ethnic, linguistic and religious links, throughout the dispute. <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Taiwan Buddhist group aids refugees in Azerbaijan <br>
SOURCE:  Deutsche Presse-Agentur, December 11, 1996<br>
<p>
A Taiwan Buddhist group will join London University in a<br>
3-million-U.S.-dollar aid programme for Azerbaijan refugees, the group said<br>
Wednesday. <br>
<p>
The Tzuchi International Relief Fund will donate 1.65 million dollars and<br>
London University will raise 1.35 million dollars. <br>
<p>
"One million Azerbeijans were made homeless by the territorial war with<br>
Armenia, which started after the collapse of the Soviet Union," Tzuchi<br>
spokesman Hsieh Ching-kuei said. <br>
<p>
The fund will be used to build new camps and to buy wheelchairs, blankets and<br>
clothing. <br>
<p>
The three-year project will start after the agreement is signed by Tzuchi<br>
founder Reverant Cheng Yen and Azerbaijan Deputy Prime Minister Izzat<br>
Rustamov. <br>
<p>
The international fund is part of the Tzuchi Buddhist Foundation, founded by<br>
Cheng Yen - hailed as Taiwan's Mother Teresa - in 1966 in Hualien county. <br>
<p>
Her fund has sent relief to China, Outer Mongolia, Ethiopia, Nepal, Cambodia<br>
and Rwanda. <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Armenian Church leader visits Pope <br>
SOURCE:  Reuters North American Wire, December 11, 1996<br>
<p>
Pope John Paul on Wednesday welcomed to the Vatican His Holiness Karekin I,<br>
spiritual leader of the world's some six million Armenian Christians, who is<br>
on a five-day official visit. <br>
<p>
Karekin's official title is His Holiness Karekin I Supreme Patriarch and<br>
Catholicos of All Armenians.   He resides in Etchmiadzin, near the Armenian<br>
capital Yerevan. <br>
<p>
The two- the Pope wearing his traditional white cassock and the bearded<br>
Karekin wearing a hooded black robe- sat side by side on identical thrones<br>
during the Pontiff's general audience. <br>
<p>
The Armenian Church is one of the so-called Ancient Churches of the East<br>
which split away from Byzantine Christianity before the Great Schism of 1054,<br>
which divided the Eastern and Western Churches. <br>
<p>
The Pope told the crowd in the Vatican's audience hall that he hoped the two<br>
Churches could eventually reach full unity. <br>
<p>
Karekin said he was praying for the 76-year-old Pope's good health, "not only<br>
for the good of the Roman Catholic Church but for that of all humanity." <br>
<p>
The Armenian Church is an independent Christian Church introduced to Armenia<br>
by the apostles Jude and Bartholomew. In 301 A.D. Armenia became the first<br>
nation to adopt Christianity as a state religion. <br>
<p>
The Armenian Church has various patriarchates around the world and members in<br>
the countries of the former Soviet Union, North and South America, the Middle<br>
East, Europe and Asia.<br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Defendory International exhibition <br>
SOURCE:  Jane's Defence Systems Modernisation,  December 1, 1996<br>
<p>
The ninth biennial Defendory International exhibition took place in Athens,<br>
Greece, from 1 to 5 October. Exhibitors from 28 countries took part,<br>
including, for the first time, Armenia (which introduced a new assault<br>
rifle), Iran and Slovakia. The Editor, with input from Christopher F. Foss,<br>
reports from Piraeus, Athens. <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
