<title>Groong Network: Armenian News 12/11/96</title>
<h1>Armenian News 12/11/96</h1>
<i>Chavoush@aol.com</i><br>
<i>Wed, 11 Dec 96 17:14:22 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#100">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#100">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#100">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#100">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0101.html">vahe@arminco.com: "Aragil Headlines, 12/12/96"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0099.html">ASBAREZ-ON-LINE: "ASBAREZ-ON-LINE [12-11-96]"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Headlines of stories which follow:<br>
1.  No serious problems separate Russia and Armenia - Foreign Minister<br>
Primakov <br>
2.  President Ter-Petrosyan, Russian border guard chief meet in Yerevan <br>
3.  Azerbaijan welcomes Lisbon summit declaration, but Armenia critical <br>
4.  Karabakh's self-proclaimed president appoints prime minister <br>
5.  Islamic ministers lay out views on Moslem issues <br>
6.  Activists say West encourages rights abuses in former USSR <br>
7.  Oil Deal Possible in Nagorny Karabakh <br>
8.  No Headline (Armenia; Volume XLVIII, No. 45; Pg. 18)<br>
9.  Presidential Inauguration Held - A Third of the New government's Members<br>
Were Not in the Old One<br>
<p>
HEADLINE: No serious problems separate Russia and Armenia - Foreign Minister<br>
Primakov <br>
SOURCE: Interfax news agency, Moscow, in English 1423 gmt 9 Dec 96 <br>
<p>
There are no serious problems which would separate Russia and Armenia,<br>
Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeniy Primakov told a news conference in Moscow<br>
on Monday [9th December] after meeting his Armenian counterpart, Aleksandr<br>
Arzumanyan. <br>
<p>
Moscow supports stabilizing the situation in Nagornyy Karabakh as soon as<br>
possible through a search for mutual compromises, Primakov said.   A<br>
compromise solution to a Nagornyy Karabakh settlement lies in Azerbaijan's<br>
territorial integrity and Nagornyy Karabakh's highest possible autonomy<br>
within Azerbaijan, Primakov said. <br>
<p>
In comment on the recent presidential elections in Nagornyy Karabakh and<br>
Russia's negative attitude to them, Primakov said: "If the elections had been<br>
held as local elections in a region of Azerbaijan, there would have been no<br>
questions. But their organizers proceeded from Nagornyy Karabakh's<br>
independence, which is not recognized by anyone, including Russia." <br>
<p>
Ratification of the Russian-Armenian treaty on the deployment of Russian<br>
military bases in Armenia was one of the main subjects of the discussion,<br>
Primakov said. "We informed the Armenian side that this document has been<br>
approved by Duma committees and submitted for ratification," he said. For its<br>
part, Armenia pledged to do its best to resolve this issue simultaneously.<br>
"We are satisfied with this pledge," Primakov said. "Mutual understanding was<br>
reached on all issues of bilateral relations discussed at the talks,"<br>
Arzumanyan concurred. <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: President Ter-Petrosyan, Russian border guard chief meet in Yerevan<br>
<p>
SOURCE: Interfax news agency, Moscow, in English 0709 gmt 7 Dec 96 <br>
<p>
Armenian President Levon Ter-Petrosyan and Russian Federal Border Service<br>
Director Andrey Nikolayev discussed a broad range of problems regarding<br>
Russia's and Armenia's security during their meeting in Yerevan on Friday<br>
[6th December]. <br>
<p>
The Armenian leadership has always supported a collective system for border<br>
defence, Nikolayev told a briefing in Yerevan later in the day .   Armenia<br>
sees bilateral relations with Russia and relations between Russia and other<br>
countries in the Transcaucasian region as the foundation of a collective<br>
security system, he said. The Armenian president is satisfied with border<br>
guards'activity, Nikolayev said. " In brief, the Armenian president supports<br>
Russia's presence on the Armenian borders with neighbouring countries." <br>
<p>
The Russian side at the talks set out the issues which should be settled in<br>
the interests of both countries and with which "the Armenian leadership<br>
expressed satisfaction" , Nikolayev said. Several agreements were reached<br>
which will be reflected in the protocols currently being prepared for<br>
signing, he said. The Russian and Armenian presidents believe that urgent<br>
measures are needed to settle the situation in trouble spots in the<br>
Transcaucasian region, Nikolayev said. "There is no firing there at present,<br>
but the core point is that the settlement process should be brought near a<br>
final political solution." <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Azerbaijan welcomes Lisbon summit declaration, but Armenia critical<br>
<p>
SOURCE: Interfax news agency, Moscow, in English 1041 gmt 6 Dec 96 <br>
<p>
Azerbaijani presidential aide Vafa Gulizade said on 6th December that the<br>
statement on the Armenian-Azerbaijani conflict made at the end of the Lisbon<br>
summit meeting of the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe<br>
(OSCE) on the 3rd was "a success scored by Azerbaijani diplomacy" because it<br>
confirmed the principle of Azerbaijan's territorial integrity, Interfax news<br>
agency reported. <br>
<p>
The statement "effectively contained the formula suggested by Azerbaijan" ,<br>
Gulizade said.   The three principles outlined in it include Azerbaijan's<br>
territorial integrity, broad autonomy for Nagornyy Karabakh and security<br>
guarantees for the Karabakh Armenians, he told Interfax, adding that the OSCE<br>
Minsk Group talks on resolving the Karabakh conflict would now be geared<br>
towards the realization of these principles. <br>
<p>
Gulizade said that Armenia had effectively isolated itself at the Lisbon<br>
summit by vetoing Paragraph 20 of the Lisbon OSCE declaration on the Karabakh<br>
conflict, while the United States, Russia and other countries supported<br>
Azerbaijan. <br>
<p>
However, Armenian presidential spokesman Levon Zurabyan told a Yerevan news<br>
conference on 5th December that "Azerbaijani posturing" had made it<br>
impossible to take a decision on Nagornyy Karabakh at the Lisbon meeting. <br>
<p>
He said that by demanding that the OSCE declaration include Azerbaijan's<br>
sovereignty, territorial integrity and the inviolability of its borders,<br>
Azerbaijan had "defied the logic of the negotiating process" , obstructed the<br>
search for a compromise and made it impossible for the OSCE to pass a<br>
decision on the Nagornyy Karabakh problem, the agency reported. <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Karabakh's self-proclaimed president appoints prime minister <br>
SOURCE: Snark news agency, Yerevan, in English 1700 gmt 7 Dec 96 <br>
<p>
The president of the self-proclaimed Nagornyy Karabakh republic, Robert<br>
Kocharyan, appointed Leonard Petrosyan as prime minister on 7th December,<br>
Snark news agency reported, quoting Kocharyan's press office. <br>
<p>
Petrosyan was instructed to select a new cabinet within 10 days, the agency<br>
said. <br>
<p>
Kocharyan was re-elected president on 24th November. <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Islamic ministers lay out views on Moslem issues <br>
SOURCE:  Reuters North American Wire, December 10, 1996<br>
<p>
Islamic countries laid out their views on issues affecting the Moslem world<br>
on Tuesday at the annual foreign ministerial meeting of the 54-member<br>
Organisation of the Islamic Conference (IOC). <br>
<p>
Conference sources said one of the most contentious issues was likely to<br>
arise in the political affairs committee, with Kuwait expected to propose a<br>
resolution hostile to Iraq, which Baghdad would strongly oppose. <br>
<p>
The conference was also expected to endorse a resolution condemning Aremenia<br>
for "aggression" against Azerbaijan and calling for the withdrawal of<br>
Armenian troops and the "liberation" of occupied Azerbaijani territory. <br>
<p>
The five-day conference opened on Monday with an attack on Israel over what<br>
speakers said was its "reneging" on agreements with the Palestinians, and<br>
calls for Moslem unity and economic cooperation and development. <br>
<p>
It is also seeking to dispel an image among some in the West equating Islam<br>
with violence and terrorism. <br>
<p>
The conference's Cultural and Islamic Affairs Committee is studying<br>
resolutions that include ways to unify Moslems in the defence of Islamic<br>
values. <br>
<p>
Ministers also met their counterparts for bilateral discussions on the<br>
sidelines of the conference. <br>
<p>
Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali Alatas had a session on Tuesday with<br>
Afghanistan's Rahim Gafoorazai, who is deputy foreign minister in the<br>
government of President Burhanuddin Rabbani. <br>
<p>
Rabbani was driven from Kabul in September by the purist Islamic Taleban<br>
militia, and is now allied with ethnic Uzbek leader Rashid Dostum in a bid to<br>
retake the capital. <br>
<p>
The OIC has left Afghanistan's seat vacant while urging the warring Afghan<br>
parties to form a government of national unity.REUTER <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Activists say West encourages rights abuses in former USSR <br>
SOURCE:  Reuters North American Wire, December 10, 1996<br>
 <br>
The United States and its Western allies put political and economic interests<br>
ahead of the protection of human rights in the former Soviet Union, a<br>
watchdog group charged Tuesday. <br>
<p>
"In 1996 human rights principles were subordinated to current political and<br>
economic interests," said Alexander Petrov, Moscow representative of the<br>
U.S.-based Human Rights Watch/Helsinki group. <br>
<p>
"This particularly concerned the United States and the countries of the<br>
European Union," he told a news conference to mark International Human Rights<br>
Day. <br>
<p>
"An example of this kind of policy was provided by Russia's accession to the<br>
Council of Europe despite the renewal and continuation of intense military<br>
activity in Chechnya involving colossal violations of humanitarian law," he<br>
said. <br>
<p>
The Council of Europe, which sees itself as an arbiter of human rights,<br>
accepted Russia in February after months of delay due to concerns over<br>
Moscow's campaign in the breakaway region. <br>
<p>
Council members said at the time that having Russia on board would help it to<br>
push forward human rights, but critics charged that it did nothing to stop<br>
the Chechnya fighting, which killed tens of thousands before a peace deal was<br>
signed in August. <br>
<p>
"Things were no better in other republics," Petrov said, citing aid given to<br>
Armenia and Georgia despite government crackdowns on opposition groups. <br>
<p>
Azerbaijan had also conducted a campaign to crush dissent, he said, but<br>
nevertheless won observer status in the Council of Europe. Kazakhstan and<br>
Kirgizia also got Western support. <br>
<p>
As far as the rights situation itself was concerned, Petrov said autocratic<br>
and arbitrary rule in Uzbekistan and Turkmenistan made them the biggest<br>
causes for alarm. <br>
<p>
In Russia, Petrov said the only significant improvement was the end to the<br>
conflict against separatist rebels in Chechnya, begun when President Boris<br>
Yeltsin sent in troops two years ago. <br>
<p>
"If you set this aside human rights stayed on the same level and in some<br>
cases worsened," he said. <br>
<p>
He said the situation in Russia's regions was worse than in Moscow and other<br>
big cities, citing direct threats and financial sanctions which he said were<br>
used to gag the media. "There is no progress, but a regression here." <br>
<p>
Petrov also pinpointed a growth in xenophobia in Russia, particularly against<br>
people of Caucasian origin beaten up and deported from big cities by the<br>
authorities. <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Oil Deal Possible in Nagorny Karabakh <br>
SOURCE:  Moscow News, December 5, 1996 (Ara Tatevosyan)<br>
<p>
The situation confronting the Lisbon talks is quite complicated. Russia and<br>
the U.S. have cast doubt on the legitimacy of the presidential elections held<br>
in the self-declared Republic of Nagorny Karabakh on November 24. For its<br>
part, Stepanakert has directed some tough comments at the Russian Foreign<br>
Affairs Ministry. <br>
<p>
On the eve of the meeting in Lisbon, Azerbaijan seemed to be enjoying an<br>
advantage. <br>
<p>
Baku seeks to raise the question of territorial integrity, which Yerevan<br>
intends to veto. However, Armenian President Levon Ter-Petrosian said:<br>
"Although I hope the matter doesn't come down to a veto, I assure you that<br>
our response will be adequate." <br>
<p>
In Lisbon at Azerbaijan's insistence the co-chairman of the Organization for<br>
Security and Co-operationing Europe "Minsk" group will be replaced. German,<br>
the U.S. and France are advancing candidates for the post. Sweden and Finland<br>
(former co-chairmen) have no interests in the region. The interests of the<br>
three who do are obvious - Baku oil. During a recent visit to the<br>
Transcaucasus region the German envoy at the "Minsk" group, Frank Lambach,<br>
said that he conceives of a resolution to the conflict only in the framework<br>
of Azerbaijan's territorial integrity. By saying that, Lambach violated the<br>
gentlemen's agreement reached in 1992 that Karabakh's future status would not<br>
be discussed by the mediators. As for the U.S., a candidate is understood to<br>
have been was advanced only in order to force Karabakh to choose the lesser<br>
evil - Germany. <br>
<p>
After years of negotiations, highly-placed Azerbaijani politicians are for<br>
the first time openly offering Armenia an "oil for Karabakh" formula.<br>
Azerbaijan's Foreign Affairs Minister Gasan Gasanov announced that, "If<br>
Armenia doesn't get linked up with the oil business now, it's not going to<br>
happen in the foreseeable future." The position of Armenia and Karabakh are<br>
unambiguous - linking the Karabakh and oil issues is unacceptable. <br>
<p>
Today it's clear that if 1997 doesn't see the beginning of a genuine peace<br>
settlement, there is a high probability that it will be a year of renewed<br>
fighting for Karabakh.  Armenia and Nagorny-Karabakh realize that thanks to<br>
oil, Azerbaijan's military and economic potential is growing. It was no<br>
accident that on the eve of the Lisbon summit, the commander of Turkey's<br>
ground forces, General Hikmet Geksal, announced that, if necessary, his<br>
country would give Azerbaijan necessary military aid, in accordance with an<br>
existing agreement on "bilateral military cooperation." Russia, which has an<br>
analogous agreement with Armenia, not to mention the C.I.S. agreement on<br>
collective security, is keeping silent. Perhaps Lisbon will raise the curtain<br>
on a Russian secret connected with the trip by the new Deputy Security<br>
Council Secretary, Boris Berezovsky, to the oil centers of Almaty and Baku.<br>
In that case, the new Russian position on Karabakh will become clear. <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: No Headline (Armenia; Volume XLVIII, No. 45; Pg. 18)<br>
SOURCE: Current Digest of the Post-Soviet Press,  December 4, 1996<br>
(Nezavisimaya gazeta, Nov. 6, p. 3. Condensed text)<br>
<p>
On the evening of Nov. 4, Armenia's Prime Minister Grant Bagratyan, who had<br>
held the position of head of government since February 1993, submitted his<br>
resignation.   President Levon Ter-Petrosyan accepted the resignation. On the<br>
same day, the President signed a decree appointing 42-year-old Doctor of<br>
Mathematics Armen Sarkisyan, who is now the Republic of Armenia's Ambassador<br>
Extraordinary and Plenipotentiary to Great Britain, to the position of Prime<br>
Minister of Armenia. <br>
<p>
In the opinion of local observers, Grant Bagratyan's departure marks the<br>
beginning of the major personnel reshuffles that President Levon<br>
Ter-Petrosyan promised after the Sept. 22 presidential election.<br>
<p>
According to local observers, efforts to solve social problems will become<br>
the main thrust of the government's activity. <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Presidential Inauguration Held - A Third of the New government's<br>
Members Were Not in the Old One (Armenia; Volume XLVIII, No. 45; Pg. 19)<br>
SOURCE: Current Digest of the Post-Soviet Press,  December 4, 1996 (By Annen<br>
Khanbabyan. Nezavisimaya gazeta, Nov. 12, p. 3. Excerpts)<br>
<p>
President Levon Ter-Petrosyan signed decrees Nov. 8 on the structure of the<br>
Armenian government and rules governing its work, the personnel makeup of the<br>
Cabinet, and a reform of the republic's judicial and legal system. . . . <br>
<p>
More than a third of the Cabinet was replaced: Personnel changes affected,<br>
among other officials, the heads of the Ministries of Foreign Affairs,<br>
Education and Science, Culture, Trade, and Social Security. In addition, the<br>
Ministry of Information was abolished, as were the posts of Minister for<br>
Liaison Between the Government and Parliament and Minister for Liaison<br>
Between Armenia and the CIS and European Union. On the other hand, a new<br>
Ministry of Privatization and Foreign Investment was established. . . . The<br>
decision to merge the Ministry of Internal Affairs and the Ministry of<br>
National Security into a single department headed by Minister of National<br>
Security Serzh Sarkisyan seems quite sensational. As for former Minister of<br>
Internal Affairs Vano Siradegyan, he has been appointed mayor-governor of<br>
Yerevan. To all appearances, the merger of the Internal Affairs Ministry and<br>
the National Security Ministry marks the start of a profound reform of the<br>
entire system of power-wielding departments. . . . <br>
<p>
The new Prime Minister, Armen Sarkisyan, has offered assurances that economic<br>
reform in general and privatization in particular will be not only continued<br>
but accelerated, However, they will acquire a new focus. The Prime Minister<br>
said that the priority for the next three years will be the development of<br>
industrial potential and agriculture. . . . The Prime Minister thinks that<br>
foreign investment could provide impetus for a spurt forward. . . . The head<br>
of government regards the development of education and science as a key<br>
objective. . . . <br>
<p>
Since his appointment as Prime Minister, Armen Sarkisyan has been holding<br>
intensive consultations with representatives of both pro-President and<br>
opposition parties, including the parties in the National Accord bloc. During<br>
these meetings, he has continually stressed that the attainment of domestic<br>
political stability is a key to economic growth. So far, only the<br>
parliamentary faction of the National Democratic Union, led by Vazgen<br>
Manukyan, has declined to meet with the Prime Minister. . . . <br>
<p>
President Levon Ter-Petrosyan was inaugurated on Nov. 11. . . . The ceremony<br>
marking the Armenian President's assumption of office was held despite the<br>
fact that the Constitutional Court has yet to hand down a ruling on the<br>
complaint filed by the leader of the united opposition, Vazgen Manukyan, who<br>
is asking that the official election results be declared invalid. . . . <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
