ASBAREZ ON LINE <br>
12/11/1996<br>
<p>
<p>
1. AMNESTY CALLS FOR COMMUTE OF "DRO" DEATH SENTENCES<br>
2. HELSINKI COMMITTEE URGES RELEASE OF PRISONERS<br>
3. KARABAKH INDEPENDENCE REFERENDUM DAY MARKED<br>
4. KOCHARIAN IN PARIS FOR CONFERENCE<br>
5. POPE GREETS KAREKIN I<br>
6. AN ANALYSIS OF THE "DRO" VERDICTS<br>
7. ARMENIA TO TAKE PART IN BLACK SEA CONFERENCE<br>
8. DEADLINE FOR PASSPORT EXCHANGE EXTENDED<br>
9. US AGRICULTURE GROUP IMPLEMENTS PROJECT <br>
10. TURKEY SEEKS DEFENSE COOPERATION WITH IRAN<br>
11. VATCHE MANOUGIAN ESTABLISHES SCHOLARSHIP FUND<br>
<p>
<p>
1. AMNESTY CALLS FOR COMMUTE OF "DRO" DEATH SENTENCES<br>
<p>
Levon Ter-Petrosyan of Armenia should immediately commute the <br>
death sentences of Arsen Ardzruni, Armen Grigorian and Armenak <br>
Munjoyan-three political prisoners who were sentenced to death <br>
Tuesday amid allegations that their year-long trial was unfair, <br>
Amnesty International said Wednesday.<br>
	"The President has stated that he is personally opposed to <br>
the death penalty. We ask him to show this commitment in a more <br>
concrete way-by not only refusing to sign execution warrants but <br>
also actually commuting all pending death sentences," the human <br>
rights organization said.<br>
	Amnesty International is calling for a thorough and <br>
impartial judicial review of the case.<br>
	"We are particularly concerned about allegations that <br>
several defendants were beaten or ill-treated in order to extract <br>
confessions, and that some had difficulties in getting access to a <br>
lawyer of their own choice," Amnesty International said.<br>
	The 11 defendants have been on trial in the so-called "Dro" <br>
case, accused of forming a clandestine terrorist group within the <br>
opposition Armenian Revolutionary Federation. Charges against them <br>
ranged from withholding information to illegal possession of <br>
weapons and premeditated murder. A 12th defendant, Ardavazd <br>
Manoukian, died in custody in May last year amid allegations that <br>
before his death he was denied adequate medical care for a range <br>
of health problems for several weeks.<br>
	The court found that the so-called "Dro" group had no links <br>
to the ARF.<br>
	Ter-Petrosyan has stated that he is personally opposed to <br>
the death penalty, and his office has assured Amnesty <br>
International that no executions have taken place, or will take <br>
place, during his term in office. It appears, however, thatTer-<br>
Petrosyan has not correspondingly used his authority to commute <br>
pending death sentences. This means that those currently on death <br>
row, believed to number 13 before this trial, may have been <br>
waiting years without knowing when they may expect their clemency <br>
appeals to be heard, or what the outcome may be.<br>
	Amnesty International opposes the death penalty in all <br>
cases, on the grounds that it is a violation of the right to life.<br>
<p>
<p>
2. HELSINKI COMMITTEE URGES RELEASE OF PRISONERS<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Fact)-The Yerevan-based Helsinki Committee of Armenia <br>
issued an announcement Monday calling for the release of all <br>
Armenian political prisoners. The announcement was issued to <br>
coincide with International Human Rights Day, Tuesday.<br>
	"Since 1993, Armenia has been moving toward a totalitarian <br>
regime and an intolerant struggle against opposing views," the <br>
statement read, specifically outlining the facts and events which <br>
have created political tension and have moved the nation to a <br>
crisis situation.<br>
	"We find that such undertakings by the leadership of Armenia <br>
are the continuation of violations of human and individual rights, <br>
a disregard for democratic principles and the establishment of a <br>
police state in Armenia," continued the statement.<br>
	"We urge the release of all political prisoners. We call on <br>
the leadership of Armenia to bring to justice all government <br>
officials before a court of law for violations of human rights, as <br>
is expected through international conventions to which Armenia has <br>
agreed," the statement asserted.<br>
	The Helsinki Committee also called for financial reparations <br>
to victims of inhumane acts by Armenias power ministries.<br>
	"We find that the only guarantee for human rights <br>
preservation is the punishment of the guilty and retribution for <br>
innocent victims," the statement said.<br>
	"We call on the leadership of Armenia to end state terrorism <br>
and their struggle against opposition views."<br>
<p>
<p>
3. KARABAKH INDEPENDENCE REFERENDUM DAY MARKED<br>
<p>
STEPANAKERT (ANIS)-The Armenia Revolutionary Federation Central <br>
Committee of Artsakh issued an announcement Tuesday on the <br>
occasion of the fifth anniversary of Karabakhs independence <br>
referendum.<br>
	Below is a translated text of that announcement:<br>
	Dear Compatriots,<br>
	Today, December 10, marks the fifth anniversary of the <br>
referendum for independence in Nagorno-Karabakh.<br>
	Heeding our inner call, we conducted a referendum under <br>
bullets and bombs, and under international laws declared the <br>
independent Nagorno-Karabakh Republic.<br>
	This was our peoples political victory before the fall of <br>
the Soviet Union.<br>
	The successes of our people during the past five <br>
years-liberated territories, rebuilding of villages, stabilization <br>
of economy-affirm that the self-determining people of Karabakh can <br>
become equals in the international arena, without giving into <br>
international pressures.<br>
	The people of Karabakh, once again, proved their <br>
independence by electing a president on Nov. 24 through public <br>
elections.<br>
	December 10 is also International Human Rights Day. It seems <br>
that this coincidence was necessary for the benefit of Karabakh. <br>
However, the fact that universal human rights are being granted to <br>
our people through hesitation, by certain international <br>
institutions, despite our right to self-determination, is <br>
unacceptable. This, however, does not mean that the people of <br>
Karabakh will regress.<br>
	Today, by congratulating all, we are confident in our <br>
collective unity and are certain that we are building Karabakh for <br>
future generations and righting historys mistakes.<br>
<p>
<p>
4. KOCHARIAN IN PARIS FOR CONFERENCE<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-Nagorno-Karabakh President Robert Kocharian <br>
left for France Tuesday to attend the 70th anniversary <br>
celebrations of the International Academy of Diplomacy.<br>
	Kocharian, who was invited by the Armenian community of <br>
France, also was scheduled to meet with members of the French <br>
National Assembly and other government officials.<br>
<p>
<p>
5. POPE GREETS KAREKIN I<br>
<p>
VATICAN CITY (Reuter)-Pope John Paul II Wednesday welcomed to the <br>
Vatican His Holiness Karekin I, Catholicos of All Armenians, who <br>
is on a five-day official visit.<br>
	The two-the Pope wearing his traditional white cassock and <br>
the bearded Karekin wearing a hooded black robe-sat side by side <br>
on identical thrones during the Pontiffs general audience.<br>
	The Armenian Church is one of the Ancient Churches of the <br>
East which split away from Byzantine Christianity before the Great <br>
Schism of 1054, which divided the Eastern and Western Churches.<br>
	The Pope told the crowd in the Vaticans audience hall that <br>
he hoped the two Churches could eventually reach full unity. <br>
	Karekin said he was praying for the 76-year-old Popes good <br>
health, "not only for the good of the Roman Catholic Church but <br>
for that of all humanity."<br>
	The Armenian Church is an independent Christian Church <br>
introduced to Armenia by the apostles Thaddeus and Bartholomew. In <br>
301 A.D., Armenia became the first nation to adopt Christianity as <br>
a state religion.<br>
	The Armenian Church has various patriarchates around the <br>
world and members in the countries of the former Soviet Union, <br>
North and South America, the Middle East, Europe and Asia.<br>
	Karekin I arrived in Rome aboard a private plane furnished <br>
by philanthropist Vatche Manougian and was accompanied by Bishop <br>
Barkev Mardirossian, Primate of the Artsakh Diocese; Archbishop <br>
Krikoris Buniatian, Primate of the Shirak Diocese and Archbishop <br>
Garegin Nercessian, Primate of the Ararat Valley  Diocese.<br>
	The pontiff was greeted at the Rome airport by the Patriarch <br>
of Istanbul Arch. Karekin Kazandjian and the Patriarch of <br>
Jerusalem Arch. Torkom Manougian, who were joined by Western <br>
Primate Arch. Vatche Hovsepian, Eastern US Primate Arch. Khajag <br>
Barsamian and the Paris Primate Bishop Kiud Nakkashian.<br>
	Karekin I and his delegation will remain Rome and the <br>
Vatican until Friday, where they will visit several Catholic <br>
leaders. <br>
	The visit will culminate with a private visit between the <br>
Catholicos and the Pope.<br>
	Karekin I is also scheduled to meet Italys president <br>
Saturday.<br>
<p>
<p>
6. AN ANALYSIS OF THE "DRO" VERDICTS<br>
<p>
BY INGA ZARAFIAN &amp;  SONA MASHOULIAN<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-The judicial board in the trial of the so-<br>
called "Dro" group rule Tuesday that charges linking the Armenian <br>
Revolutionary Federation with the so-called "Dro" group were <br>
groundless. The judicial board also acquitted co-defendant Hrand <br>
Markarian of charges of organizing the group and being an <br>
accomplice to murders and drug trafficking.<br>
	The courtroom was filled to capacity with friends, relatives <br>
and and foreign reporters during Tuesdays sentencing phase of the <br>
18-month trial.<br>
	The case drew international interest when the preliminary <br>
investigations were said to be politically motivated.<br>
	No reasons or explanations were offered in relation to the <br>
suspended ARF in the verdict despite prosecutor Mikayel <br>
Grigorians demands.<br>
	The court concluded that the "Dro" group was established by <br>
Arsen Ardzruni in 1990 when he moved to Armenia from Lebanon. In <br>
1992, according to the judicial board, Ardzruni proposed that the <br>
"Dro" group under the auspices of the ARF engage in intelligence <br>
and economic affairs. According to the groups by-laws, its aim <br>
would be to preserve the revolutionary principles of the party <br>
[ARF], repudiate principles of parliamentary activity as well as <br>
work on unveiling the "state mafia," the judicial board said, <br>
adding that if necessary, the group planned to use emergency <br>
measures against leaders of the mafia.<br>
	It was noted that the "Dro" groups by-laws differed from <br>
that of the ARF. The "Dro" groups by-laws reportedly call for <br>
stiff penalties for its members, including death. "Dro" members <br>
who wished to quit the organization would be subject to severe <br>
punishment, the court said.<br>
	According to Judge Edward Manoukian, these stiff penalties <br>
were what the "Dro" members were afraid of. <br>
	If one of the members was caught out of line, they were <br>
punished by not allowing them to carry a firearm. This punishment <br>
was handed down to Armenak Zakarian for being drunk while <br>
following Gagik Sahakian, who was later murdered by some of the <br>
group members, Manoukian said, but Zakarian did not take part in <br>
Sahakians murder because he was unarmed at the time. The judge <br>
noted that this punishment actually resulted in Zakarian not <br>
receiving the death penalty.<br>
	Co-defendants Armenak Mnjoyan and Armen Grigorian, were <br>
sentenced to death for the murder of Sahakian.<br>
	Zakarian, Mnjoyan and Grigorian were also found guilty of <br>
planning the murder of the Nersissian couple.<br>
	To ensure secrecy, Ardzruni gave members of the group codes <br>
and nicknames, the judge said, and secret information was conveyed <br>
to Mnjoyan and Ardzruni via messengers Rouzanna Gevorkian and <br>
Ovsanna Hovsepian. Lesser ranked members of the group kept in <br>
contact via Mnjoyan, according to the judge.<br>
	Ardzruni wanted to involve Gegham Manoukian in the <br>
organization and discussed his plans with him, which Manoukian <br>
later testified to in court. Markarian advised Manoukian to stay <br>
away from Ardzruni, the judge said.<br>
	The court sentenced Hrand Markarian to five years, Arsen <br>
Ardzruni, Armenak Mnjoyan and Armen Grigorian, death; Armenak <br>
Zakarian, 15 years; Hovaness Mkrtchian, 10 years; Ara <br>
Harmandarian, 6 years; Edik Simonian, five years; and Gevork <br>
Alaverdian, Tatul Gabrielian and Gegham Manoukian, three years.<br>
<p>
<p>
7. ARMENIA TO TAKE PART IN BLACK SEA CONFERENCE<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Azg)-A parliamentary delegation from the Republic of <br>
Armenia, headed by Speaker Babken Ararktsian, left for the <br>
Georgian capital Tbilisi Tuesday to participate in the eighth <br>
conference of Black Sea Economic Cooperation members.<br>
	The delegation also plans to meet with Georgian President <br>
Eduard Shevardnadze.<br>
<p>
<p>
8. DEADLINE FOR PASSPORT EXCHANGE EXTENDED<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Lragir)-The deadline to exchange old passports issued by <br>
the Soviet Union has been extended, the Passport and Visa <br>
Department of Armenias Foreign Ministry announced, but did not <br>
say what the new deadline was.<br>
	The Foreign Ministrys original deadline had been set for <br>
December 1996.<br>
<p>
<p>
9. US AGRICULTURE GROUP IMPLEMENTS PROJECT <br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-The American Volunteers Overseas Cooperative <br>
Assistance organization plans to implement projects on production, <br>
processing and sale of agricultural commodities, the improvement <br>
of veterinary services and irrigation systems in Armenia starting <br>
next year.<br>
	Since 1992, VOCA whose projects are financed by the United <br>
Stated Agency for International Development, has implemented 120 <br>
agricultural assistance projects in different regions of Armenia.<br>
	VOCAs regional representative Paul Sommers said that in <br>
1996, 30 volunteers of the organization were working in Armenia. <br>
The production of dried tomatoes, apricots and canned grape leaves <br>
has been established in the Vayots Dzor and Ararat regions with <br>
VOCAs help, in addition to four irrigation projects also in <br>
Vayots Dzor for previously unirrigated land.<br>
	Sommers reported that an Armenian subsidiary of VOCA, <br>
VISTAA, has been set up at the request of Armenias agricultural <br>
experts. Scientists working with VISTAA have designed new pumps <br>
which supply water to mountainous lands and foothills without the <br>
use of electricity.<br>
	The pumps will be sold to farmers at reasonable prices, <br>
Sommers said.<br>
<p>
<p>
10. TURKEY SEEKS DEFENSE COOPERATION WITH IRAN<br>
<p>
ANKARA (Reuter)-Turkey discussed defense industry cooperation with <br>
neighboring Iran, a Turkish Foreign Ministry spokesman said <br>
Wednesday.<br>
	"Various cooperation opportunities between Turkey and Iran <br>
were dealt with during Mr. Boroujerdis visit to our ministry. <br>
Defense industry cooperation...was only one of them," spokesman <br>
Sermet Atacanli told a news briefing.<br>
	Prime Minister Necmettin Erbakan on Tuesday met Irans <br>
deputy foreign minister, Alaeddin Boroujerdi, who came to Ankara <br>
ahead of a visit by Iranian President Ali Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani <br>
later this month.<br>
	Boroujerdi told reporters after the meeting that the two <br>
countries defense ministers had held talks in Tehran in August <br>
during a visit to Iran by Erbakan.<br>
	Spokesman Atacanli said defense cooperation might be <br>
discussed during Rafsanjanis visit but he gave no more details. <br>
Defense Ministry officials declined to comment on any defense <br>
cooperation with Iran.<br>
	Ankara sealed a military training deal with Israel in <br>
February which drew sharp criticism from Arab countries and Iran. <br>
Turkey also has a defense industry agreement with the Jewish state <br>
under which Israel is to modernize Turkish air force F-4 jets.<br>
	Erbakan, Turkeys first Islamist prime minister, has <br>
promised to improve relations with the countrys Moslem neighbors.<br>
	Turkey and Iran signed a $23 billion gas deal that angered <br>
Ankaras close ally the United States when Erbakan visited Tehran.<br>
<p>
<p>
11. VATCHE MANOUGIAN ESTABLISHES SCHOLARSHIP FUND<br>
<p>
ANTELIAS, Lebanon-Upon the request by His Holiness Aram I, <br>
Catholicos of the Holy See of Cilicia, philanthropist Vatche <br>
Manougian established a $1 million scholarship under the auspices <br>
of the Cilician Catholicosate, announced the Catholicosates <br>
executive.<br>
	The fund will be available to all college and university <br>
students. A by-laws for the scholarship fund is being prepared <br>
which will determine criteria through which the scholarship may be <br>
received.<br>
	Catholicos Aram I highly praised Manougian for his <br>
commitment to education of the youth and gratefully thanked the <br>
philanthropist for this generous undertaking.<br>
<p>
