Armenian Assembly of America<br>
122 C Street, NW  Suite 350<br>
Washington, D.C.  20001<br>
tel: (202) 393-3434<br>
fax: (202) 638-4904<br>
<p>
<p>
PRESS RELEASE<br>
<p>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE      <br>
     December 11, 1996<br>
     <br>
     CONTACT: <br>
     Elaine Merguerian<br>
     <br>
                <br>
     ARMENIAN ASSEMBLY OPENS STEPANAKERT OFFICE<br>
     STEPANAKERT, Nagorno Karabagh Republic _  "I want to congratulate all <br>
     of us for the opening of the Armenian Assembly of America's <br>
     Stepanakert Office," said N.K.R. Deputy Prime Minister Jirair <br>
     Boghosian to some 40 government officials and local NGO <br>
     (nongovernmental organization) representatives, who celebrated the <br>
     ribbon-cutting of the Assembly's new N.K.R. office November 7.  "We <br>
     are very familiar with the work the Armenian Assembly has accomplished <br>
     for Armenia and N.K.R., and I hope that with the opening of the <br>
     Stepanakert Office, the Armenian Assembly can [help to] support the <br>
     resolution of the Karabagh conflict and convey our concerns to the <br>
     international community."<br>
        N.K.R. Foreign Minister Arkady Ghukasian was among the government <br>
     officials attending the ceremony.  Representing the Armenian Assembly <br>
     at the event was Yerevan Office Director Edith Khachatourian, who has <br>
     been instrumental in the set-up of this newest Assembly venture.  "The <br>
     Armenian Assembly has offices in Washington, D.C., Los Angeles, <br>
     Yerevan, Gyumri and now I am proud to witness the opening of an office <br>
     in Stepanakert.  Today is an unforgettable day for the Armenian <br>
     Assembly and, especially, for me," she said.  Over the last several <br>
     months, Khachatourian has made several trips to N.K.R. for planning <br>
     and consultation with N.K.R. President Robert Kocharian and the <br>
     foreign minister.  She will oversee the office's activities and act as <br>
     a liaison between the Assembly's Stepanakert and Yerevan offices.  Her <br>
     work will be supported by that of Karabagh native Inna Gabrielian, who <br>
     will staff the office full-time.  <br>
        Following an earlier meeting with President Kocharian, Assembly <br>
     Board of Trustees Chairman Hirair Hovnanian noted the commitment <br>
     reflected in the Assembly's decision to open an office in Stepanakert. <br>
      "The presence of an Assembly office in N.K.R. will facilitate our <br>
     organization's continuing advocacy for that nation's <br>
     self-determination," he says.  "This office will be a vehicle for <br>
     substantially enhanced efforts in Washington to promote increased U.S. <br>
     engagement in the peace process and in the region.  It is imperative <br>
     that our government moves beyond its standard defense of the <br>
     territorial integrity of all states and takes into much greater <br>
     account Karabagh's de facto status as an independent entity."<br>
        The Armenian Assembly is a nationwide nonprofit organization which <br>
     promotes public understanding and awareness of Armenian issues.<br>
     X   X   X <br>
     NR#96-122<br>
     _ Photo sent to newspapers under separate cover.<br>
     <br>
     <br>
