<title>Groong Network: Turkey/CenAsia Highlights 12/11/96</title>
<h1>Turkey/CenAsia Highlights 12/11/96</h1>
Mher Sassouni (<i>as080@lafn.org</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 11 Dec 96 13:49:22 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#97">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#97">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#97">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#97">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0098.html">elaine@aaainc.org: "AAA Opens Stepanakert Office"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0096.html">Mher Sassouni: "Turkey/CenAsia Highlights 12/10/96"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
  	  				 <br>
	+&gt; Turkish exports increased  <br>
	+&gt; Turkish troops discharged over religion  <br>
	+&gt; Tajik rivals to continue dialogue  <br>
	+&gt; Turkey, Yemen sign gas deal  <br>
	+&gt; Turkey: Iraqi oil exports by Monday  <br>
                               ======	 <br>
 Turkish exports increased<br>
	Turkisk ecports increased to $21.333 billion (by 4.4 per<br>
cent) in the first 11 months of the year from $20.436 billion in<br>
the corresponding period in 1995, the Turkish Exportes Assembly<br>
, TIM, said in an statement. Turkey's November exports were up<br>
4.8 per cent to $2.261 billion from $2.158 billion recorded last<br>
year for the same month, the statement said.Iron, steel and<br>
metal industry exportss increased by 3.8 per cent to $2.57<br>
billion, textile and related raw materfial exports rose 8.3 per<br>
cent to $2.30 billion, electric -electronic exports increased 33<br>
per cent to $1.71 billion in January -November, compared to the<br>
same 1995 period, TIM said.<br>
                               ======<br>
 Turkish troops discharged over religion<br>
	Turkey discharged Tuesday 69 military commanders and<br>
noncommissioned officers for immoral behavior and<br>
``undisciplined acts,'' an armed forces council said. Turkish TV<br>
and radio reports said the Supreme Military Council ordered the<br>
dismissals at the second session of its two-day meeting in<br>
Ankara because those involved had engaged in hard- line Muslim<br>
activities. Extremist and illegal religious activities in the<br>
middle ranks had sparked increasing concern among higher levels<br>
of the strongly secular armed forces, military analysts told<br>
United Press International. Concern has been building since the<br>
election of Prime Minister Necmettin Erbakan, head of the<br>
hard-line Muslim Welfare Party, they said. Erbakan conducted<br>
Tuesday's defense meeting and approved the decision, as he had<br>
the dismissals of 18 officers and 32 other soldiers in August,<br>
also for religious activities prohibited in the armed forces.<br>
The prime minister is walking a tightrope with the military,<br>
which has risen three times since 1960 to depose governments<br>
opposed by its commanders. He signed Friday a deal heavily<br>
favored by the military for Israel to upgrade Turkish jet<br>
fighter trainers, even though he campaigned against close<br>
Turkish ties to Israel and Western nations.  When the council's<br>
first meeting Monday was conducted by the military chief of<br>
staff, Gen. Ismail Hakki Karadayi, Erbakan's absence was<br>
attacked by opponents. The prime minister heads the council,<br>
which meets twice a year. Turkey's military has prevented<br>
control by hard-line Muslims since being set up on a secular<br>
basis when the republic was formed in 1923. Furthermore, most<br>
mililtary leaders support Turkey's role in the North Atlantic<br>
Treaty Organization.<br>
                               ======<br>
 Tajik rivals to continue dialogue<br>
	Tajik President Emomali Rakhmonov and opposition leader<br>
Said Abdullo Nuri said Tuesday they will continue peace talks<br>
next week in Moscow and agreed on the need to form a bilateral<br>
commission to work toward reconciliation, reports<br>
said. Rakhmonov and Nuri met in northern Afghanistan in a bid to<br>
ease fighting in Tajikistan and approach a consensus on the<br>
future of the troubled Central Asian nation. The Russian news<br>
agency Itar-Tass said they were planning to continue discussions<br>
Wednesday. After their first day of talks in a village in the<br>
Takhar province, where the Tajik opposition has been based since<br>
being driven across the frontier in a 1992 civil war, they<br>
agreed to meet again in Moscow on Dec. 19 and hold a new round<br>
of U.N.-mediated peace negotiations a few weeks later. They also<br>
agreed in the need to form a bilateral commission charged with<br>
hammering out a long-term solution to their struggle, Itar-Tass<br>
reported. The schedule of the commission and details about its<br>
goals and makeup will be discussed at the U.N.-sponsored<br>
talks. Similar agreements in the past have disintegrated amid<br>
argument over the terms of reconciliation. The opposition wants<br>
a share of power to govern the nation of 5.7 million, but<br>
Rakhmonov and his administration have been unwilling to release<br>
their increasingly loose grip on the country. The meeting was<br>
the first between Rakhmonov and Nuri in more than a year and<br>
came amid heavy fighting between government and pro-Islamic<br>
opposition forces east of the capital Dushanbe.<br>
                               ======<br>
 Turkey, Yemen sign gas deal<br>
	A delegation led by Turkish Energy and Natural Resources<br>
Minister Racai Kutan and general director of the state-run<br>
pipeline company BOTAS, Mustafa Murathan, arrived to the Arab<br>
Republic of Yemen on Wednesday to sign a natural gas agreement,<br>
the Turkish officials reported. The Turkish delegation will<br>
return to Turkey on Friday.<br>
                               ======<br>
 Turkey: Iraqi oil exports by Monday<br>
	Commercial loading of Iraqi crude oil pumped to Turkey<br>
will begin after an official ceremony Dec. 16, officials said<br>
Tuesday. Iraqi President Saddam Hussein inaugurated Tuesday the<br>
start of oil pumping operations at Kirkuk in central Iraq. Tests<br>
on the 556-mile (890-km) twin pipeline were expected to continue<br>
through Sunday, oil industry officials said. An official<br>
ceremony attended by Prime Minister Necmettin Erbakan will mark<br>
the start of crude oil loading operations at Yurmurtalik in<br>
southeastern Turkey, the semi-official Anatolian News Agency<br>
said. The pipeline was reopened under an oil-for-food deal<br>
agreed with the United Nations. It was closed when the<br>
U.N. imposed sanctions on Iraq after it invaded Kuwait in<br>
1990. Under the U.N. deal aimed at alleviating the suffering of<br>
some 20 million Iraqis, Iraq plans to sell $2 billion worth of<br>
oil for a renewable six-month period. The proceeds from the oil<br>
sale would be deposited in a U.N. escrow account in New York for<br>
use by the United Nations to buy food and medicine for Iraqi<br>
civilians. The pumping of oil was interrupted Tuesday to allow<br>
for further tests. A Turkish oil industry official said the<br>
first vessel to be loaded would be nominated by the Turkish oil<br>
company Tupras. Iraqi officials said in remarks quoted by the<br>
official Iraqi News Agency that Baghdad had received new offers<br>
from international exporting companies to buy Iraqi oil.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
