<!-- body="start" -->
  	  				 <br>
	+&gt; Tajik rivals meet  <br>
	+&gt; Turkish Foreign Minister to visit Russia  <br>
	+&gt; Indian, Kazakh presidents met  <br>
                               ======	 <br>
 Tajik rivals meet<br>
	Tajik President Emomali Rakhmonov met Tuesday in<br>
northern Afghanistan with the leader of the pro-Islamic Tajik<br>
opposition, Said Abdullo Nuri, reports said. Russian news<br>
agencies said Rakhmonov and Nuri met behind closed doors in a<br>
village in the Takhar province, where the Tajik opposition has<br>
been based since being driven across the frontier in a 1992<br>
civil war. The meeting, the first between the rivals in the<br>
Central Asian nation in more than a year, came amid heavy<br>
fighting between government and pro-Islamic opposition forces<br>
east of the Tajik capital Dushanbe. The talks were aimed to ease<br>
hostilities that have wracked several regions east of Dushanbe<br>
for more than a week and set the stage for a new round of<br>
U.N.-sponsored negotiations scheduled to take place this month<br>
in Moscow. Since the war, which killed tens of thousands of<br>
people and plunged the former Soviet republic further into<br>
poverty, the opposition has battled government troops within<br>
Tajikistan and Russian forces on the Afghan border. The<br>
opposition has made gains in increased fighting this year,<br>
seizing several towns on a key road from Afghanistan through<br>
Tajikistan to Kyrgyzstan and pressing closer to Dushanbe. The<br>
opposition has been seeking a share of the power since its<br>
defeat in the civil war and in the wake of susequent<br>
presidential and parliamentary elections that cemented<br>
Rakhmonov's power but were criticized as unfair.  The government<br>
and opposition have signed cease-fires and peace deals during<br>
five rounds of talks under the aegis of the United Nations, but<br>
the agreements have been short-lived and ineffective.<br>
                               ======<br>
 Turkish Foreign Minister to visit Russia<br>
	Turkish Foreign Minister Tansu Ciller will visit Russia<br>
next week to discuss bilateral ties with special emphasis on<br>
trade and economy, a Foreign Ministry sources said Monday. Her<br>
talks with Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov will also<br>
include regional developments and political issues, the source<br>
said. Ciller, who is due in Moscow Dec. 17, is also the deputy<br>
Prime Minister in the Islamist-led coalition government. During<br>
her two-day visit she will also confer with Russian Prime<br>
Minister Victor Chernomyrdyn and other Cabinet ministers. Russia<br>
is the fourth largest importer of Turkish goods and sixth in<br>
terms of exports to Turkey. Turkey currently imports 6 billion<br>
cubic metres of natural gas annually from Russia. The two sides<br>
agreed in principle last month to increase the gas flow to 16<br>
billion cubic metres annually over the next 10 years.<br>
                               ======<br>
 Indian, Kazakh presidents met<br>
	Indian President Shankar Dayal Sharma and Kazakh<br>
President Nursultan Nazarbayev held a meeting in New Delhi<br>
Monday, the Russian Itar-Tass news agency said. ``India and<br>
Kazakhstan support the efforts being taken by the United Nations<br>
and the International Community to restore peace and stability<br>
in Afghanistan which remains to be an area of tension and<br>
bloodshed,'' Nazarbayev said. He also pointed out that his<br>
country is interested in developing closer interaction with<br>
India in order to prevent Islamic fundamentalists from<br>
increasing their influence in Asia, and to ward off new<br>
conflicts and tensions.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
