<title>Groong Network: Crime links probed in Turkey</title>
<h1>Crime links probed in Turkey</h1>
Kevork K. Oskanian (<i>100436.3410@compuserve.com</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 11 Dec 96 12:47:44 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#95">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#95">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#95">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#95">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0096.html">Mher Sassouni: "Turkey/CenAsia Highlights 12/10/96"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0094.html">Kevork K. Oskanian: "Armenian Church leader visits pope"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
By ZEYNEP ALEMDAR<br>
 Associated Press Writer<br>
   ANKARA, Turkey (AP) -- A traffic accident that revealed links<br>
between the government and the underworld has forced President<br>
Suleyman Demirel to step in and demand an accounting.<br>
   Demirel was meeting Tuesday with the main opposition leader<br>
Mesut Yilmaz, who has played a key role in disclosing secret ties<br>
between policemen and crime bosses.<br>
   There also have been allegations of government-backed death<br>
squads to suppress dissidents and Kurdish rebels.<br>
   Demirel will summon other opposition leaders this week and meet<br>
with Prime Minister Necmettin Erbakan on Thursday.<br>
   "Nothing will remain secret under the sky. You cannot hide<br>
anything," Demirel told the newspaper Hurriyet. "Whoever tries to<br>
hide it gets buried under it."<br>
   The scandal surfaced after a Mercedes and a tractor-trailer<br>
collided on a highway 90 miles south of Istanbul last month.<br>
   A Parliament deputy, a fugitive criminal and a police official<br>
were in the Mercedes. In the Mercedes, only the deputy survived.<br>
The criminal, Abdullah Catli, reputedly had links to the Turk who<br>
shot Pope John Paul II and was wanted in Switzerland, where he was<br>
convicted of drug smuggling and escaped from prison in 1990.<br>
   The connections between the three men immediately appeared<br>
suspicious. Sedat Bucak, the deputy who survived the crash and who<br>
is also a powerful official in the Turkey's Kurdish-dominated<br>
southeast, could not provide any reasonable explanation.<br>
   Interior Minister Mehmet Agar, who had close ties to the police<br>
chief, was forced to resign after the accident under pressure from<br>
opposition parties.<br>
   The scandal grew when Yilmaz claimed Catli organized the killing<br>
of a casino operator, Omer Lutfi Topal, with three policemen in<br>
July to help Bucak seize his assets. Three policemen who were<br>
briefly detained after the killing were later assigned to guard<br>
Bucak.<br>
   Yilmaz claimed he had tapes of phone calls between the three<br>
officers talking about their murder of Topal.<br>
   Bucak runs a 2,000-man army in southeastern Turkey to fight<br>
Kurdish rebels, and reportedly receives more than $1 million a<br>
month from the government for it.<br>
   Newspaper reports say his men allegedly were members of death<br>
squads that killed hundreds of supporters of the Kurdish rebel<br>
movement, and have smuggled drugs and weapons.<br>
   The government's handling of the scandal has led to suspicions<br>
that Foreign Minister Tansu Ciller knew about the alleged ties<br>
between the state and underworld leaders during her three years as<br>
prime minister.<br>
   Ciller said in a recent speech that Catli deserved being honored<br>
for fighting for Turkey. She also accused Yilmaz of supporting the<br>
Kurdish rebel groups and Armenian terrorists by getting tough on<br>
Catli.<br>
   But on Monday, Mrs. Ciller told reporters after being summoned<br>
by Demirel that the state's mission is to fight criminals. "The<br>
state does not form gangs," she said.<br>
   The government took its first action last week in connection<br>
with the unfolding scandal, removing Istanbul's well-respected<br>
police chief and the three officers linked to Topal's killing. But<br>
the move against the police chief caused an uproar.<br>
   News reports said the police chief, Kemal Yazicioglu, was being<br>
punished for leaking the link between the three officers and<br>
Topal's slaying.<br>
   The truck driver who crashed into the Mercedes received a "most<br>
respected citizen honor" from a small leftist party for his role<br>
in exposing the scandal.<br>
   "The accident unveiled the dark liaisons within the state.<br>
These facts now have to be further dug out," said opposition<br>
leader Bulent Ecevit.<br>
   <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
