<title>Groong Network: Two items of interest from the Russian press</title>
<h1>Two items of interest from the Russian press</h1>
Arthur Martirosyan (<i>martiros@hulaw1.harvard.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 11 Dec 1996 13:26:25 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#90">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#90">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#90">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#90">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0091.html">nt-send@nt.arminco.com: "Noyan Tapan News (December 11)"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0089.html">arpi@aaainc.org: "Aragil Headlines, 12/11/96"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
MOSKOVSKIY KOMSOMOLETS 11 Dec 1996 p 1<br>
<p>
   Report by Aleksandr Budberg:  "General Semenov's Secret Uncovered.  New<br>
Compromising Evidence Leak Expected This Week"<br>
<p>
   The scandal surrounding the dismissal of commander in chief of the Ground<br>
Forces Vladimir Semenov is gaining momentum.  Taking advantage of the<br>
non-too-clear stance of Defense Minister Igor Rodionov, the suspended<br>
general of the army began to gradually going on the offensive.<br>
   MOSKOVSKIY KOMSOMOLETS has come to learn from sufficiently informed<br>
sources in the Defense Ministry that Vladimir Magomedovich's [Semenov's]<br>
increased activity stirred the Defense Ministry leadership into more<br>
resolute actions.  One can expect the publication in a few next days of<br>
transcripts of Semenov's taped telephone conversations (which they did not<br>
want to leak before).<br>
   If one is to believe a source, it emerges from these conversations that<br>
General Semenov was rather effectively involved in business operations to<br>
buy food and grain for troops in his charge.  The source is also talking<br>
about $200,000 in commission money for lobbying the sale to a Turkish firm<br>
of two Russian helicopters.  The contract does not specify where these<br>
helicopters might get to from Turkey.  The source also alleges that the<br>
tapes deal with the reception of concrete money.<br>
   MOSKOVSKIY KOMSOMOLETS cannot claim that all the reports are absolutely<br>
true.  Especially because the tapes have not been examined by experts.<br>
However, this version is explains convincingly enough both the tough wording<br>
of the commander in chief's dismissal order -- for actions discrediting the<br>
honor and dignity, and the long silence of the defense minister who ended up<br>
in an amazingly stupid position.  Indeed, the eavesdropping on, perhaps, all<br>
high-ranking officials (one may think not only of Chubays but also the<br>
scandal involving Grachev's "plot") can in theory be carried out only with<br>
the prosecutor's permission.  Therefore, the data which were put on<br>
Rodionov's desk cannot be official proof even if they contained correct<br>
information.<br>
   Therefore, the scandal surrounding Semenov's dismissal -- no matter how<br>
the case involving the general and his wife ends -- may put into even<br>
sharper focus the question of morals among the top leadership of Russia.<br>
   It is perhaps realizing this that Rodionov, regarded as a sufficiently<br>
punctilious person, was for so long trying to prevent the news leak.  Had<br>
not the scandal been used in order to put the minister "in his place" and<br>
show who is the master in the house, the source in the Defense Ministry<br>
would not have spoken.<br>
(end)<br>
<p>
<p>
NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA 11 Dec 1996 p 3<br>
<p>
   NEGA untitled report<br>
<p>
   A statement of Georgia's foreign ministry underlines that the republic<br>
will never renounce its rights to part of the Black Sea Fleet which it will<br>
be able to maintain.<br>
   Ukraine has supported Tbilisi's demand.  The Kiev officials think that<br>
all the naval ships which were based in the ports of Batumi and Poti until<br>
1992 should be restored to Georgia.<br>
(end)<br>
