ASBAREZ ON LINE <br>
12/10/1996<br>
<p>
<p>
1. THREE SENTENCED TO DEATH, AS "DRO" CASE ENDS<br>
2. KAREKIN I ARRIVES IN ROME<br>
3. ACTIVISTS SAY WEST ENCOURAGES ABUSES IN CIS<br>
4. ULTRASENSITIVE SEISMIC STATIONS BEING INSTALLED IN ARMENIA<br>
5. ARTUR KAZARIAN TESTIFIES AT "TRIAL OF 31"<br>
6. LEONARD PETROSSIAN TO REMAIN KARABAKH PRIME MINISTER<br>
7. NEW YEREVAN MAYOR TAKES BACK LAND ALLOCATED BY PREDECESSOR<br>
8. 500 CASES OF SYPHILIS REPORTED IN ARMENIA<br>
9. NEW SAFETY PANEL DEVELOPED FOR NUCLEAR REACTORS<br>
<p>
<p>
1. THREE SENTENCED TO DEATH, AS "DRO" CASE ENDS<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Combined Sources)-Three defendants received death <br>
sentences, while others in the so-called "Dro" group trial were <br>
sentenced to three to 15-year prison terms, as the trial ended <br>
Tuesday with Armenias Supreme Court determining that the alleged <br>
clandestine terrorist group had no links to the Armenian <br>
Revolutionary Federation.<br>
	The court, presided over by Judge Eduard Manoukian, handed <br>
down death sentences to defendants Arsen Ardzrouni, Armen <br>
Grigorian and Armenak Munjoyan. The remaining defendants were <br>
sentenced in the following manner: Armen Zakarian, 15 years; Hovik <br>
Mkrtchian, 10 years; Ara Harmandarian, six years; Edik Simonian, <br>
five years; Tatul Gabrielian and Gevork Alahverdian three years <br>
each.<br>
	The court found that a group involved with so-called <br>
"banditism" engaged in drug trafficking and planned and executed <br>
the assassinations known as "Top 1" and "Kerop" operations, as <br>
result of which Gagik Sahakian, Ashot Nercissian and his wife were <br>
murdered.<br>
	The court also found that ARF leader and Karabakh liberation <br>
movement organizer Hrand Markarian was in no way tied to the so-<br>
called "Dro" group, and thus was cleared of those charges. <br>
However, Markarian was sentenced to five years in prison on <br>
illegal weapons possession and forged documentation charges.<br>
	Co-defendant Gegham Manoukian was sentenced to three years <br>
in jail as an accessory.<br>
	On December 28, 1994 then president Levon Ter-Petrosyan <br>
issued a decree suspending the ARF activities in Armenia, alleging <br>
that the party was involved in the operation of the so-called <br>
"Dro" group. The ARF has been suspended since that time, despite <br>
numerous appeals by the party to Armenias Justice Ministry. The <br>
government purge against the ARF was also extended in July 1995 <br>
when then ARF Bureau member Vahan Hovanessian and 31 others were <br>
arrested on charges of supporting the forcible overthrow of the <br>
government.<br>
	Several questions still remain. Markarian was found guilty <br>
of using forged documents, the same documents which he used to <br>
enter Karabakh which at that time was undergoing a self-<br>
determination war. Markarian was also found guilty of illegal arms <br>
possession, a license which was granted by commander of the <br>
Karabakh armed forces Samvel Babayan.<br>
	The court found no direct links between Markarian and the <br>
so-called "Dro" group, thus absolving any alleged ties between the <br>
ARF and the purported clandestine group, although, according to <br>
initial charges the ARF-"Dro" relations  were conducted solely by <br>
Markarian. <br>
	Defendants have 10 days to appeal the courts ruling.<br>
	Seven of the 12 defense attorneys were in the courtroom <br>
during the sentencing, coincidentally on the day that the world <br>
marks Human Rights Day.<br>
	Immediately following the sentencing, a number of the <br>
defendants relatives commented on the case and the sentences.<br>
	"This is unlawfulness, but the verdict is in. Here is the <br>
decision of the judge. The only positive thing is that certain <br>
realities were taken into consideration. Of course there were <br>
faults with the case, and those were connected with the <br>
preliminary investigation. This was an oversight on the part of <br>
the judge who failed to interpreted them correctly. According to <br>
the judge, those are also realities," said Azad Manoukian, the <br>
father of Gegham Manoukian.<br>
	Seryozha Mkrtchian, the father of Hovaness Mkrtchian said, <br>
"As a matter of fact, the verdict was a carbon copy of the <br>
December 28, 1994 televised address of Levon Ter-Petrosyan. <br>
Earlier this year, so-called Prosecutor-General [Ardavazt] <br>
Gevorkian made the same statement during an appearance on March 1. <br>
The Armenian leaderships order was basically realized."<br>
	Vehanoush Markarian, Hrand Markarians wife, said that the <br>
term of the sentence was unimportant, stating  that the crucial <br>
aspect was  at the end the judge ruled that neither her husband <br>
nor the ARF were linked with the so-called "Dro" group.<br>
	Marine Galabian, Hovaness Mkrtchians defense attorney said, <br>
"As far as the verdict, it was a verdict, but as far as the <br>
sentences are concerned, I believe the sentences were incoherent. <br>
My client was permitted to carry a weapon in Karabakh. Even if he <br>
had not received similar permission in Armenia, that does not <br>
merit such a harsh sentence. I, of course, presumed he would be <br>
found not guilty, but the prosecutor asked for a 15-year sentence, <br>
yet the judge reduced it to ten. In this regard, I have no <br>
complaints based on the evidence presented in the case. However, <br>
the judge should have explained his reasons for giving him the <br>
maximum sentence. A harsher sentence could have been handed down <br>
in the absence of special circumstances and other issues that <br>
otherwise called for a reduced sentence. In this regard, the judge <br>
did not provide any explanations and handed down the maximum <br>
sentence."<br>
	Responding to whether the verdict and sentence would have <br>
been different had his client been tried separately, Hrand <br>
Markarians defense attorney Rouben Sahakian said, "In that case <br>
the preliminary investigation and the trial would have been over <br>
in a month, and I do not believe my client would have received the <br>
maximum sentence for the crimes he is charged with. That [maximum <br>
sentence] simply escapes any logic, any the only explanation is <br>
that the authorities do not wish to see Hrand Markarian free. What <br>
is criminal is giving a person the maximum sentence when that <br>
person was charged with that crime for the first time. The reasons <br>
for giving Hrand Markarian the maximum sentence should have been <br>
explained."<br>
	Laura Munjoyan, mother of Armenak Munjoyan said, "They tried <br>
innocent people."<br>
	Judge Edward Manoukian said at the end of the sentencing <br>
phase that  the courts decision may be appealed within seven <br>
days. Defense attorney Marine Galabian said that only after <br>
reviewing the case with her client will she take the next step. <br>
	Rouben Sahakian said that he was planning to file an appeal <br>
on behalf of his client, Hrand Markarian.<br>
<p>
<p>
2. KAREKIN I ARRIVES IN ROME<br>
<p>
ROME-His Holiness Karekin I, Catholicos of All Armenians arrived <br>
at the Vatican Tuesday for an official visit with Pope John Paul <br>
II.<br>
	Karekin I arrived in Rome aboard a private plane furnished <br>
by philanthropist Vatche Manougian and was accompanied by Bishop <br>
Barkev Mardirossian, Primate of the Artsakh Diocese; Archbishop <br>
Krikoris Buniatian, Primate of the Shirak Diocese and Archbishop <br>
Garegin Nercessian, Primate of the Araratian Diocese.<br>
	The pontiff was greeted at the Rome airport by the Patriarch <br>
of Istanbul Arch. Karekin Kazandjian and the Patriarch of <br>
Jerusalem Arch. Torkom Manougian, who were joined by Western <br>
Primate Arch. Vatche Hovsepian, Eastern US Primate Arch. Khajag <br>
Barsamian and the Paris Primate Bishop Kiut Nakkashian.<br>
	The Catholicos was scheduled to meet with the Pope at 6 p.m. <br>
local time.<br>
	Karekin I and his delegation will remain Rome and the <br>
Vatican until Friday, where they will visit several Catholic <br>
leaders. The visit will culminate with a private visit between the <br>
Catholicos and the Pope.<br>
	The purpose of the visit is to discuss developing relations <br>
between the Armenian and Catholic churches.<br>
	Karekin I is also scheduled to meet Italys president <br>
Saturday.<br>
<p>
<p>
3. ACTIVISTS SAY WEST ENCOURAGES ABUSES IN CIS<br>
<p>
MOSCOW (Reuter)-Human rights activists Tuesday accused the West of <br>
not doing enough to protect human rights in ex-Soviet states, <br>
saying Western countries should not support governments <br>
responsible for abuses.<br>
	"In 1996 human rights principles were subordinated to <br>
current political and economic interests," said Alexander Petrov, <br>
Moscow representative of the US-based rights monitor Human Rights <br>
Watch/Helsinki.<br>
	"This particularly concerned the United States and the <br>
countries of the European Union," he told a news conference to <br>
mark International Human Rights Day.<br>
	"An example of this kind of policy was provided by Russias <br>
accession to the Council of Europe despite the renewal and <br>
continuation of intense military activity in Chechnya involving <br>
colossal violations of humanitarian law," he said.<br>
	The Council of Europe, which sees itself as an arbiter of <br>
human rights, accepted Russia in February after months of delay <br>
due to concerns over Moscows campaign in the breakaway region. <br>
	Council members said at the time that having Russia on board <br>
would help it to push forward human rights, but critics charged <br>
that it did nothing to stop the Chechnya fighting, which killed <br>
tens of thousands before a peace deal was signed in August. <br>
	"Things were no better in other republics," Petrov said, <br>
citing aid given to Armenia and Georgia despite government <br>
crackdowns on opposition groups.<br>
	Azerbaijan had also conducted a campaign to crush dissent, <br>
he said, but nevertheless won observer status in the Council of <br>
Europe. Kazakhstan and Kirgizia also got Western support.<br>
	As far as the rights situation itself was concerned, Petrov <br>
said autocratic and arbitrary rule in Uzbekistan and Turkmenistan <br>
made them the biggest causes for alarm.<br>
	In Russia, Petrov said the only significant improvement was <br>
the end to the conflict against separatist rebels in Chechnya, <br>
begun when President Boris Yeltsin sent in troops two years ago. <br>
	"If you set this aside human rights stayed on the same level <br>
and in some cases worsened," he said.<br>
	He said the situation in Russias regions was worse than in <br>
Moscow and other big towns, citing direct threats and financial <br>
sanctions which he said were used to gag the media. "There is no <br>
progress, but a regression here."<br>
	Petrov also pinpointed a growth in xenophobia in Russia, <br>
particularly against people of Caucasian origin beaten up and <br>
deported from big towns by the authorities.<br>
	Lyudmila Alekseyeva, president of the Moscow Helsinki Group, <br>
which fought for human rights under communism, said the group had <br>
previously been concerned mainly with political rights, but was <br>
now turning its attention to the economy.<br>
	"After the end of the war in Chechnya the biggest violations <br>
of human rights are delays in wage payments and pensions."<br>
	She said that despite repeated promises, the government had <br>
shown itself unable to guarantee wage payments and so should give <br>
people the power to claim their pay from the directors of their <br>
enterprises via the courts.<br>
	"We will fight until it is resolved," she said. "Im afraid <br>
it will take a long time."<br>
<p>
<p>
4. ULTRASENSITIVE SEISMIC STATIONS BEING INSTALLED IN ARMENIA<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-Armenia, being one of the most seismically <br>
active regions, had built structures with very low seismic <br>
resistance, head of the National Seismic Protection Service, <br>
Sergey Balassanian, said at a news conference Saturday on the <br>
occasion of  the eighth anniversary of the earthquake in <br>
northeastern Armenia.<br>
	The establishment of the NSPS in 1991 was a serious step <br>
toward the formation of a seismic protection program in Armenia, <br>
Balassanian said.<br>
	The program, aimed at lowering seismic risks in Armenia, <br>
will enable the NSPS to outline seismic danger; to raise the <br>
seismic resistance of existing buildings and buildings which are <br>
still under construction; and to prepare the population for <br>
another major earthquake.<br>
	The NSPS has many international points of observations and <br>
Armenia possesses about 150 of these observation points.<br>
	New stations are being established, Balassanian said. The <br>
first one is a global geodesic satellite station (GPS)-the only <br>
one in the Middle East. It was installed a month ago through the <br>
assistance of NASA and the University of Massachusetts.<br>
	The other station, IRIS, is being installed by the US <br>
Seismic Service. It is very sensitive to micro-tremors and even to <br>
the smallest fluctuations of the earths crust under the influence <br>
of gravitational waves of the moon and sun.<br>
	Balassanian said that the NSPS has compiled a new map of <br>
seismic zones for Armenia.<br>
	Mikael Melkoumian, director of the Center for Seismic <br>
Resistance Construction, stressed the importance of raising the <br>
seismic resistance of buildings. A new method for the <br>
reinforcement of buildings was devised and successfully tested <br>
which does not require the evacuation of people and is much less <br>
expensive than the old methods.<br>
<p>
<p>
5. ARTUR KAZARIAN TESTIFIES AT "TRIAL OF 31"<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-At Mondays court session of the so-called <br>
"Trial of 31," the judicial board presented letters written by <br>
defendant Artur Kazarian to Parliament Speaker Babken Ararktsian, <br>
Prosecutor-General Artavazd Gevorkian and National Security <br>
Minister Serge Sargssian.<br>
	In his letters to Armenias high-ranking officials, Kazarian <br>
reportedly wrote "the guilt should be laid on the Armenian <br>
Revolutionary Federation and its members" requesting that <br>
authorities "not let anybody involve the freedom fighters in the <br>
dirty party politics and to treat the disillusioned freedom <br>
fighters with kindness."<br>
	Kazarian said that evidence regarding the killing of the <br>
policemen was deliberately distorted. He reported that he had <br>
heard defendant Gagik Karapetian shout "Who are you shooting at?" <br>
and saw Tigran Avetissian fire a shot into the ground. He said he <br>
had heard three pistol shots (all the three shots were made by the <br>
policemen) and three or four shots fired from a machine-gun.<br>
	Kazarian highly doubted the experts findings which stated <br>
that no shots had been fired from the policemens guns. Kazarian <br>
said that he doesnt know who the killer or killers of the <br>
policemen were.<br>
	He also denied allegations that they had not followed the <br>
policemens orders, saying that they were willing to follow the <br>
policemen to the Internal Affairs office.<br>
	As for the murder of the police officers, Kazarian said he <br>
learned about it from a television news broadcast.<br>
	Kazarian also said that after they had escaped to the <br>
mountains in Sourenavan, "all the guys were surprised to learn the <br>
news about the policemens death," and Avetissian exclaimed: "I <br>
was shooting in another direction, I couldnt have hit them." <br>
Kazarian voiced hope that the questioning of the surviving <br>
policeman will shed light on these murders and there <br>
circumstances.<br>
<p>
<p>
6. LEONARD PETROSSIAN TO REMAIN KARABAKH PRIME MINISTER<br>
<p>
STEPANAKERT (Hayastani Hanrapetutyun)-Newly elected President <br>
Robert Kocharian re-appointed Leonard Petrossian as Prime Minister <br>
of the Nagorno-Karabakh Republic by presidential decree last <br>
Saturday.<br>
	Petrossian was asked to develop and present the structure of <br>
the new government within ten days.<br>
<p>
<p>
7. NEW YEREVAN MAYOR TAKES BACK LAND ALLOCATED BY PREDECESSOR<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Hayastani Hanrapetutyun)-The new mayor of Yerevan, former <br>
Interior Minister Vano Siradeghian announced Monday that he will <br>
be taking back 7.5 hectares of land allocated by the former mayor <br>
for the construction of parks and gardens, according to Yerevan <br>
City Council secretary Sergey Poghossian.<br>
<p>
<p>
8. 500 CASES OF SYPHILIS REPORTED IN ARMENIA<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Azg)-Armenias chief expert on skin and venereal <br>
diseases, Dr. Karen Babayan, said that more than 500 cases of <br>
syphilis have been reported in Armenia.<br>
	He said that another 100 unreported cases should be added to <br>
the official figures because some of the patients do not seek <br>
medical care.<br>
	According to Babayan, the number of cases has been <br>
increasing during the recent years, and the average age of the <br>
patients is getting younger. Most of the patients are 21-30 years <br>
old.<br>
	The majority of the patients are people who are currently <br>
unemployed and homeless. He said that the disease, which in the <br>
past would be cured in a year or two, can now be cured in less <br>
than a month with a single injection.<br>
	Babayan said that the print and broadcast media should be <br>
involved in educating the public about this and other venereal <br>
diseases.<br>
<p>
<p>
9. NEW SAFETY PANEL DEVELOPED FOR NUCLEAR REACTORS<br>
<p>
MOSCOW (Itar-Tass)-Russian and French specialists have developed a <br>
new panel for better data control of nuclear reactors. <br>
	Armen Abagyan, director of Russias main research institute <br>
for nuclear power plants, told Itar-Tass that such a panel would <br>
be connected to the second reactor of the Kalinin station and <br>
other Russian nuclear power plants with VVER-1000-type reactors <br>
(on light water).<br>
	The safety panel is an automated computer system. In case of <br>
an accident, an operator can find the problem easily with the help <br>
of the system, assess the situation and take prompt action. The <br>
panel was developed especially for VVER-1000-type reactors, which <br>
have replaced the old ones.<br>
	The development of the new panel was financed within the <br>
"Tasis" European program in which nuclear safety is the main goal. <br>
A total of $400 million has been allocated for the project since <br>
1991.<br>
<p>
