<title>Groong Network: Speech by LDPR Leader Vladimir Zhirinovsky</title>
<h1>Speech by LDPR Leader Vladimir Zhirinovsky</h1>
<i>Chavoush@aol.com</i><br>
<i>Tue, 10 Dec 96 16:17:58 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#85">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#85">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#85">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#85">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0086.html">ASBAREZ-ON-LINE: "ASBAREZ-ON-LINE [12-10-96]"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0084.html">Chavoush@aol.com: "Armenian News 12/10/96"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
In short, regarding Armenians, Zhirinovsky says:<br>
1.  Russian Communists didn't know the difference between Armenians and Turks<br>
2.  The Soviet policy on nationalities was all-wrong<br>
3.  Stunned that Armenians in USA voted for Clinton<br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Speech by LDPR Leader Vladimir Zhirinovsky at the Monthly Luncheon<br>
of the American Chamber of Commerce in Russia December 09, 1996 <br>
SOURCE:  Official Kremlin Int'l News Broadcast, December 9, 1996<br>
<p>
Zhirinovsky: Good afternoon, I apologize for being late. I had a meeting with<br>
television Channel II. I had to cut that meeting short out of respect for<br>
you. But I have a long running feud with the television people. I am glad to<br>
meet you and I know that you have previously met with Communist leaders. The<br>
main difference between us and them is that they are all former Communists. I<br>
am the only leader of a political party who has never been a member of the<br>
Communist Party. Perhaps, a mistake of the foreign policy of the United<br>
States and the embassy of the United States in Moscow that they took one part<br>
of the former CPSU for democrats, for new political forces. This accounts for<br>
many problems. <br>
<p>
Because you are in the business of trade I can put it this way, America has<br>
bought a false political commodity in Russia. That's why we now have problems<br>
of investments, trade and economics. The same mistake was made by Napoleon<br>
and Hitler in their time. Before they approached Russia they made no<br>
mistakes. And it seemed to them that Russia could be handled in the same way,<br>
that they could impose a French order or a German order. And the United<br>
States is making the same mistake today. <br>
<p>
A simple example. Havel in the Czech Republic is alive and he is President of<br>
the Czech Republic. He is the same democrat as Gamsakhurdia in Georgia whom<br>
the United States might as well have supported. He has been assassinated.<br>
Here is a difference between a democracy in the Czech Republic or Poland and<br>
a democracy further to the East. <br>
<p>
The political forces that we have here today are mainly the rump of the<br>
former Communist Party. They have immunity as it were, and a negative<br>
attitude to the private sector and to world trade and to the relations with<br>
the Western countries. <br>
Many years ago I proposed to American political leaders to place accents in<br>
their policy differently. If they heeded me five or six years ago not only<br>
Russia but America could have been spared their current problems. But as I<br>
said, you relaxed in your approach to Russia. You thought that it's the same<br>
model here. These are democrats and this is some other trend and you can move<br>
ahead in the country. But Russia turned out to be different. <br>
<p>
I want Russia to have the broadest links with the United States and with any<br>
Western country. I am for the broadest trade and for the creation of a real<br>
legal basis so that all business people could work comfortably in Russia.<br>
Judging from this hotel Penta, this is a Potyomkin village, a show-case for<br>
advanced capitalism and democracy. Beyond the Moscow ringroad you will find<br>
nothing like it. But in order to pursue business you need much larger space.<br>
The Communists used to think in the same way, they used to think that sitting<br>
in the Kremlin and at their dachas outside Moscow, in Sochi sanatoria, think<br>
that everything is alright with communism and with friendship of peoples, and<br>
we all saw how easy this way to break and degenerate. <br>
<p>
Perhaps, I could have been in the CPSU or with Zyuganov, or with Gaidar or<br>
Yavlinsky among the democrats, but I have a different life behind, that's why<br>
I have a different view, I have been through a different war. I come from a<br>
very poor family and I starved for many years at a time when everything<br>
seemed quite alright in our country. I started some petty business activity,<br>
raising and selling rabbits to buy a bicycle for myself, so I have passed<br>
this path of private enterprise. <br>
<p>
And the fact that private farming cannot get to its feet today, that private<br>
enterprise cannot work in the agricultural sector -- I felt myself how it<br>
feels. Khrushchov prohibited me to have a small rabbit-raising firm within<br>
city limits -- only outside the city. No one knew how it will work outside<br>
the city, and within the city it was forbidden, though it did not do harm to<br>
anybody. "Only in some other place" -- this is the abstract way it was put.<br>
The same is happening to us today. At that time there was no perestroika, we<br>
had a regime of a certain kind, but there has hardly been any improvement in<br>
the attitude towards producers over the 30 years, since 1966, the sixties. <br>
<p>
It's the wrong approach to the question of nationalities that has left the<br>
greatest imprint on business and life in general in Russia. On this issue, I<br>
also have my personal experience, since I have spent half of my life in<br>
non-Russian republics of Kazakhstan and Georgia. Present-day leaders cannot<br>
find these regions on the map, do not know the languages that are spoken<br>
there, the creed of those peoples. <br>
<p>
Yesterday we had the 8th anniversary of the earthquake in Armenia. At that<br>
time the leaders of our country travelled to Yerevan and discovered only<br>
there that Armenians are not Moslems, are Christians. How can one be the<br>
leader of a country not knowing that this is the main distinction and<br>
contradiction between Armenia and Turkey and present-day Azerbaijan.<br>
Therefore it was also during the communists that there was a wrong solution<br>
to the nationalities question. Just as at present under the democrats. There<br>
is no difference. But all this affects trade, business. <br>
<p>
Under the communists the private sector was in the shadow economy. That was<br>
the time when they worked at a state-owned enterprise during the day while<br>
underground production shops worked at night. They were located somewhere in<br>
the mountains. They used the raw materials that were supplied to the state<br>
enterprises. That was a good capitalism, but it was driven underground. But<br>
the same continues, in principle, today. Though in a somewhat different way.<br>
You are interested in the existence of a firm legal basis for any business<br>
activity. But this did not exist either in the past, under the old regime,<br>
or, regrettably, today. Former heads of communist parties continue to rule<br>
the former regions of the former USSR. Yeltsin is the former Party Secretary<br>
of Moscow, Nazarbayev in Alma- Ata is the former Secretary of the Communist<br>
Party of Kazakhstan, Karimov, Aliyev, Shevardnadze -- they are all members of<br>
the former Central Committee of the CPSU and some of them of the Politburo.<br>
They are not interested in the economy. They are concerned about staying in<br>
power, about avoiding being put on trial and about dying calmly and let<br>
others attend to the new economy and the new democracy. In other words, the<br>
party Mafia retains its positions in all the former Union republics. <br>
<p>
Therefore it is hard for you to engage in business activities in Russia<br>
because you are caught between the party Mafia above, redtape and bureaucracy<br>
and the criminal Mafia so that you don't feel safe. <br>
<p>
I am in favor of private initiative, of the private sector because when a<br>
person is his own master he works better, he feels better, he is free. But<br>
the others are like infants who are linked by an umbilical cord with the<br>
former regime. So they are not likely to introduce the changes that could<br>
create more favorable conditions.This is one of the reasons why they don't<br>
like me in your country and in my country. They don't like me in your country<br>
because they feel that I am one of those people who could make Russia more<br>
powerful which would again rival the United States. And they don't like me in<br>
my country because I have from birth adhered to an ideology which they can<br>
never understand, to an economy that they can never implement. And I indeed<br>
share to a greater extent than anyone on how to approach all the problems of<br>
the economy, the nationalities and foreign policy the way you do in your<br>
country. So, I cannot understand the alienation that political leaders of the<br>
United States feel toward me. If the US leadership wants further aggravation<br>
of the situation in our country, then they are right. All people they stake<br>
on will only deteriorate and weaken this country. They cannot do any good to<br>
it. But then your unhappiness over what has been going on in our country,<br>
including the lack of appropriate climate, for US business will remain as it<br>
is today. I stand for reforming the administrative system. There is no<br>
country in the world with internal administrative division along ethnic<br>
lines. This is exactly what causes ethnic hostility. <br>
<p>
And you can see that the democrats have not touched on this issue lying at<br>
the root. They have destroyed everything, but the root of Russia's weakness<br>
-- its territorial division system remain intact. We could have long ago<br>
launched joint projects, profitable both for us and you. We could have built<br>
a transcontinental road Hamburg-Berlin- Moscow-Vladivostok. Trucks with<br>
freight could have travelled this road spanning two continents, Europe and<br>
Asia, day and night. But there is no such road in existence and one will not<br>
appear in the coming 10-20 years. <br>
<p>
We have similar problems in the south. You may face dangers in the south and<br>
we have problems there. We could have come to each other's assistance but we<br>
are acting to the contrary so far. While struggling against Russia you have<br>
strengthened other regions of the world which are struggling against you,<br>
against the United States. This reminds me of the campaign that we had to<br>
exterminate wolves. The wolves were exterminated, but rodents appeared. A lot<br>
was spent on the extermination of wolves, but even more was required to cope<br>
with the rodents. Russia is a wolf and can be dealt with, but as a result,<br>
you will find yourself surrounded by a huge number of small rodents. You will<br>
find that this is a much more serious problem. You will find out that it<br>
would be better to have two wolves, America and Russia. It would be better<br>
for America to confront a weakened Russian wolf than to be at the receiving<br>
end of hundreds of rodents. <br>
<p>
So, at the front you are struggling with Russia, but in your rear your<br>
adversaries are stockpiling arms and this struggle against them will not be a<br>
successful one for you. I have no allergy, no negative attitude to Americans<br>
because we never were in face-to-face conflict. <br>
<p>
We fought with the Chinese, the Japanese, the Turks, the Germans, the Finns,<br>
with all our neighbors, and many times at that. The attitude to Americans<br>
should be the most well-wishing one. <br>
<p>
We have a fighter plane. The whole of Europe united and only with difficulty<br>
created an analogue. The whole of Europe, on the one hand, and Russia, on the<br>
other hand. Russia has its plane while they, having pooled their efforts,<br>
failed to create a plane of the same quality. Or take China. It has 1.5<br>
billion population, a lot of resources, but they don't have a plane like<br>
that. The Chinese engineer is incapable of building modern fighter plane.<br>
Russian can. We have achievements which we could share and we could help each<br>
other. The same is true of the United States. <br>
<p>
If Russia is destroyed in the south, the Muslim factor will be strengthen and<br>
it would threaten America too. Or the Chinese factor will strengthen which<br>
too will pose a greater threat to America than to Russia. So I think the US<br>
leadership today has lost a sense of expediency and profitability. It ceased<br>
to be beneficial for your country. <br>
Our own instincts too sometimes let us down. You invited me among the last.<br>
When you have run out of parties to invite. So, two or three years on you<br>
have decided to meet with me. And previously you mainly met with your<br>
enemies, who won't be able to help you in any way. And you have seen that in<br>
the last two or three years there has been no progress in business in our<br>
country. I can carry on, my record is speaking 12 hours non-stop. I believe a<br>
dialogue is better. I will answer your questions. I proposed more than once<br>
to seat all sorts of political leaders in front of millions of television<br>
viewers, in front of businessmen for a panel discussion, so that they could<br>
see who is healthier, who is more vigorous. They all would be carried away,<br>
while I would remain alone, but when I stand alone without any competitors, I<br>
feel bad. I need competition. <br>
<p>
I apologize again for being late. I wanted very much to be on time. <br>
<p>
Moderator: We will take questions now. <br>
<p>
Q: I represent the company Thompson. What is the role of foreign investments,<br>
in your opinion, in Russia's development? <br>
<p>
Zhirinovsky: I would like to recall your businessman who was recently<br>
murdered. He was a co-owner of Hotel Slavyanskaya. He asked me for assistance<br>
in his dispute. I did not expect such a tragic outcome. Otherwise, we would<br>
have tried to give him at least some assistance. I was gratified that an<br>
American businessman approached us, our faction for assistance. Alas, time<br>
had run out. Of course, I believe that there should be no restrictions in<br>
this field. We have a huge territory, huge wealth, we could have found the<br>
necessary conditions for investments, for cooperation. That would be very<br>
much to our advantage. But you are interested only in profits and in the<br>
possibility to dispose of them freely. In this country you will see not a<br>
single new industrial enterprise, new production facility. Lots of<br>
enterprises are standing idle. On sale you will matryoshka dolls that we<br>
produce. If we set up a joint venture to produce such dolls, it will bring<br>
little profit to you or to us. <br>
<p>
I stand for giving as much freedom as possible, but the problem lies in the<br>
absence of a ruling party and an opposition party. The situation which is<br>
unthinkable in any democratic country, where the will of the majority cannot<br>
be determined within a political formula. So, laws that would help you in<br>
this sphere have virtually not been adopted or implemented so far. And the<br>
main obstacle here is that, as you can see in regions, as you can see from<br>
the results of the past elections, the communists are regaining power. They<br>
are in the center, since the entire government is made up of former<br>
communists, the president's team is fully made up of former communists, and<br>
they are in regions, even where initially democratic-oriented administrations<br>
ruled. All recent elections show that the orthodox communists are coming<br>
back. If the US foreign policies are aimed at further destroying Russia, this<br>
should be viewed as a positive development. Then they can register this as a<br>
good result: let them completely destroy -- this time a lop-sided capitalism.<br>
But if they need real business, which is a sine qua non for the development,<br>
security and stability of America, this is a bad sign. But it's your embassy<br>
who is to blame, for it's not always that it makes correct assessments of the<br>
political situation in our country. <br>
<p>
A simple example is offered by Afghanistan, the offensive of the Taliban and<br>
the actions of that political structure plays into the hands of Pakistan and<br>
the US and into our hands too. We could find common ground there and achieve<br>
joint success in Central Asia, both in the political and business spheres.<br>
But Moscow doesn't act in this way. Again, we are opposing each other where<br>
we could united. Clinton embraces Yeltsin and Christopher embraces Primakov<br>
-- and now of course you have a new Secretary of State. In short there is a<br>
lack of understanding. Russia is not what the United States believes it to<br>
be. It is different.  <br>
<p>
Or take two more examples. Transcaucasia. If you need Turkey, you should not<br>
be supportive of Shevardnadze, the Georgian President. Moscow too would stand<br>
to gain more by not supporting Shevardnadze. We would do better to support<br>
Abkhazia, Adjaria and Southern Ossetia. So we two powers are pursuing the<br>
wrong policy with regard to Georgia. This is another mistake. And then there<br>
is a problem of Armenia. Clinton gained very many Armenian-American votes,<br>
but the policy in the Caucasus is anti- Armenian and this worsens the Caspian<br>
oil situation. <br>
<p>
The same is true of the Kurds. We too occupy a wrong kind of position. This<br>
lack of coordination between American and Russian policy affects American<br>
business in Russia and even more Russian business in America, lack of<br>
coordination of our activities in the Middle East, in the Caucasus and<br>
Central Asia. The reason is that new regions of the former USSR, the Caucasus<br>
and Central Asia are new to you. You have yet to study them. For Moscow, they<br>
are old and familiar. But the pattern is based on the former party structures<br>
because these regions are led by Shevardnadze, Aliyev, Petrosyan or Karimov.<br>
They are former Communists. So, we have not yet been able to put these<br>
regions in order to as to provide a good business environment that would<br>
favor Russia and America. <br>
<p>
Q: Good afternoon. I wonder if you could, please, let me know what your views<br>
are with regard to the current negotiations for the expansion of NATO toward<br>
the Russian borders and how far do you feel that the recent events in<br>
Byelorussia could perhaps assist Russia in NATO negotiations with regard to a<br>
possible buffer state toward the Eastern expansion? <br>
<p>
Zhirinovsky: The expansion of NATO? I do not see a military rationale for the<br>
expansion of NATO. If it expands then the future aim is to attack Russia. So,<br>
why do business in Russia, all this will burn up, will be looted and taken<br>
away. If this is a political act we have the Organization for Security and<br>
Cooperation in Europe, the Council of Europe. I don't see why the NATO<br>
military organization should come into it to intervene in the relations<br>
between this region and Western Europe. <br>
<p>
Byelorussia, should it so wish, and Russia could become even closer and find<br>
a form of setting up a united state. There is no danger to anybody in this.<br>
This is one and the same people. One people. If Wales were to secede from<br>
Britain for a number of years and then wish to restore closer relations with<br>
London, would this raise eyebrows, generate any contradictions? Britain has<br>
been a single state for many centuries already. To withdraw and then join<br>
again -- there is nothing dangerous in this. <br>
<p>
A wrong parallel is sometimes drawn, that of France and Algeria. Algeria was<br>
a colony that was conquered by France. But Russians came from Byelorussia. It<br>
is not that Byelorussia will be joining Russia, it will be Russia that will<br>
be returning to Kievan Rus. It will be Russia that will be rejoining<br>
Byelorussia and Ukraine. They are simply parts of a single Slavic state.<br>
Kievan Rus, we began with Kiev. It was from there that the princes advanced<br>
to the East, came to Moscow, went to the North, went to Minsk. That was the<br>
development of one and the same state. <br>
<p>
Q: Thank you for coming here. I would like to ask the following question.<br>
Your appearance here today in the American Chamber of Commerce means that you<br>
attach much importance to relations and cooperation between our two<br>
countries. What areas, in your opinion, are most promising for the<br>
development of bilateral relations in terms of technology, commerce, in the<br>
intellectual area, that would be most beneficial for the Russian Federation?<br>
What political changes, do you think, are necessary for creating the<br>
necessary basis for such a development of relations? <br>
<p>
Zhirinovsky: We are interested in such directions as roads, considering that<br>
the United States has achieved much in this area, we are interested in<br>
transport, especially in automobiles. In such areas as ship-building and the<br>
defense industry we could pool our efforts, we could even jointly appear on<br>
the world market. We could cooperate on the huge armaments market.<br>
Communications is a promising area. We have our own good chemical industry.<br>
We could have our own priorities here. We do not have a huge requirement in<br>
Pepsi-Cola, Coca-Cola, MacDonalds, in hamburgers. Russia has its Russian<br>
equivalents. Russians are irritated by this. Our national drinks -- the<br>
Russian vodka used to be the best in the world. So, piling goods on us which<br>
we had a lot before, this is irritating. We need the good and the new things<br>
that Americans have. But this we are not getting in our market. And there are<br>
very many such examples. We could cooperate in fighting AIDS. We have some<br>
powerful virusologists and cardiologists. Our doctors and American doctors<br>
got together and so far, as far as the President is concerned, this has been<br>
a success. And if he dies the American doctor will be to blame. <br>
<p>
So there are many different areas in which we could cooperate. But we have to<br>
see that we are getting real American products. But we do not see that. <br>
<p>
Q: Could you indicate your attitude to the fact that Mr. Clinton has been<br>
reelected President of the US and to how he is forming his government, in<br>
particular, the new appointment of Secretary of State? Will it contribute to<br>
Russian-American relations, and business? <br>
<p>
Zhirinovsky: Russia and America are similar, we have become more similar when<br>
it comes to elections. Whether it is Clinton or whether Clinton would have<br>
been elected doesn't make much difference. <br>
<p>
Look what happened when Clinton replaced George Bush.  Over here, Yeltsin has<br>
been reelected and nothing has changed. Although we need change more than you<br>
do. As to forming the team, the President himself decides. But you are<br>
different from us because you find new people and our President keeps<br>
shuffling the same old stack of cards. This is his mistake. He has brought<br>
back Chubais and Shakhrai to the Constitutional Court and Mityukov to the<br>
Security Council. So, it's the same group of people. There is no dynamism<br>
here. It's the same old communist style. They make appointments from their<br>
own midst, from amongst the people who are close to them. Yeltsin today is<br>
forming the team which will surround him at his death. In other words, he is<br>
concerned about himself, so that he could die in peace or in any case calmly<br>
retire in the year 2000 so that he shouldn't be kicked. Your presidents by<br>
contrast, are looking for specialists who may make mistakes, but they bring<br>
new blood, new dynamism. I like it more.<br>
 <br>
Q: I think for the people in this room probably two of the most important<br>
issues are the question of tax reform in the Russian Federation and also the<br>
question on the remaining laws which could bring into effect the regime for<br>
production sharing agreements in the oil and gas sector. What will be the<br>
position of the LDPR of the question of tax reform and specifically the draft<br>
tax code which has been submitted by the government to the Duma? And will you<br>
be supporting the law on amendments which is necessary to bring the<br>
production sharing regime into effect as well as the law lists of subsoil<br>
resources? <br>
<p>
Zhirinovsky: As regards taxes, we stand for fewer taxes, there should be no<br>
confusion, these taxes should necessarily be collected and used according to<br>
the purpose. And they should stimulate trade and production, rather than<br>
stifle them. <br>
Here again, there is one political point. The government has to raise some<br>
funds through taxation, but it is incapable to collect them in a normal way,<br>
because there exist non-Russian regions which pay nothing or pay lower taxes.<br>
Here again politics are put over economics. And this is not convenient for<br>
you, because you never know how great your taxes will be, where, at what<br>
point they will be charged, and whether you will be able to draw the profit<br>
you projected.  The same holds true for the production-sharing law. There is<br>
also one point related to the nationalities issue. It concerns those regions<br>
of Russia which are predominantly populated by non-Russian peoples or which<br>
administratively are within regions which are a non- Russian part of Russia.<br>
For example, Yakutia, which occupies vast spaces, it's communists who did it,<br>
for Yakutia had never before occupied them. They just drew a line on the map,<br>
and now it turns out that Yakutia occupies half of Siberia and controls all<br>
diamonds of Russia. Yakutia has seen no development, for there is a need for<br>
investments, there is a need for an international airport, railway. But the<br>
Yakuts, in order to keep Russians away, do nothing of that. They derive<br>
enough money from diamond sales through De Beers, but their region does not<br>
develop. So, here again we run into the nationalities issue. <br>
<p>
Here again, the blame must be on your embassy which looks only at the YABLOKO<br>
faction and tries to use that faction as a vehicle to lobby for the adoption<br>
of the law. It has not approached us and this is the trouble. This is the<br>
reason why the bill has not yet been passed. So, you should assess the<br>
political forces correctly. I can speak in parliament in such a way that the<br>
law will be passed and in a way that it will not be passed. Although we only<br>
have 11 percent of the seats in the Duma we can sway the vote. Including on<br>
the issue of production sharing. It is because of our faction that the law<br>
has not yet been passed. And those who wanted it passed did not reach us for<br>
some reason. This is your fault. <br>
<p>
Q: At least one region where the Communists were not elected again was I<br>
believe in the Pskov region where a member of your parliamentary faction was<br>
elected governor. What new or different initiatives can we perhaps expect<br>
<i>&gt;from the Pskov region, for instance, to attract foreign investment? What is</i><br>
going to be different? <br>
<p>
Zhirinovsky: The Kremlin's inability to correctly assess the situation leads<br>
it to defeat in local elections. They hate me so much -- I myself tried to<br>
save their candidates in five regions in Russia. But they refused television<br>
time and so even in the five regions where I have tried to help, the<br>
Communist candidate won by a small margin. <br>
<p>
And on the example of Pskov Gubernia, or Pskov State, which may sound more<br>
familiar to you, you will see that the greatest opportunities will be created<br>
for any investors and security climate, there will be no racketeering by<br>
officials; all issues will be solved promptly and in an effective manner.<br>
This is what the Kremlin is afraid of. Had my governors carried the day in 40<br>
gubernias, the LDPR would score a final victory in 1999, and I would become<br>
the nation's president. <br>
<p>
So, by fighting me, they fight you. They don't want me to be a counterbalance<br>
to Yeltsin, so they will go out of their way to impede your business<br>
throughout the country in order to avert a growth in my party's influence.<br>
They would rather agree to a communist comeback, and the communists are<br>
indeed coming back. So, this is a case of putting personal interests above<br>
Russia's national interests. They would rather agree to a comeback of their<br>
fellow party members, for they all used to be members of that party. I am a<br>
stranger for them. It's like your coming to America to create a new<br>
civilization. Like you, I am founding a new civilization on the vast lands of<br>
former Russia or the former Soviet Union. In this respect I may be closer to<br>
you. And today's meeting may be useful in this respect, it might help you<br>
assess the line-up of political forces before you embassy and your Secretary<br>
of State do this and better than they do. We are going to see another<br>
election race in the Volga region, there we also stand chances for a victory.<br>
And unless you had thwarted us -- in December 1993 your Vice-President Gore<br>
launched a crusade against me, declaring me a fascist. And for three years<br>
America has been maintaining this campaign. And for the three years Russia<br>
has lived fearing communism or fascism, though otherwise we could have long<br>
worked in a calm manner. So, this has to do with the leadership of your<br>
country. And the LDPR would long have become a ruling political party and the<br>
presidential election in June could have followed a different course but for<br>
the subjective mistakes. <br>
<p>
So, just another example. In June, when your vice president came over here,<br>
he prevailed over Yeltsin to have a comeback with Chubais into the<br>
government, so Chubais became the chief of staff. That was your doing.<br>
Chubais is hated throughout this country, he is hated by all. It is something<br>
that happens sometimes. This is psychological incompatibility. If you want to<br>
have a pro-American person somewhere high up, there is nothing wrong with<br>
that, but you should have chosen someone else. And Chubais should have been<br>
moved somewhere where he is not seen, because he is so much hated. This is<br>
something that is happening and that is working against your interests,<br>
against creating the appropriate climate for American business and investment<br>
in this country. <br>
<p>
Moderator: I think we should finish so that our visitor could at least have a<br>
cup of coffee before he leaves. Please join me in thanking him very much for<br>
coming. <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
