<title>Groong Network: Armenian News 12/10/96</title>
<h1>Armenian News 12/10/96</h1>
<i>Chavoush@aol.com</i><br>
<i>Tue, 10 Dec 96 16:17:47 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#84">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#84">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#84">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#84">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0085.html">Chavoush@aol.com: "Speech by LDPR Leader Vladimir Zhirinovsky"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0083.html">Kevork K. Oskanian: "Armenian High Court sentences party activists to death"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Headlines of stories which follow:<br>
<p>
1.  Iranian Armenians reject "negative propaganda" of foreign media<br>
2.  Armenia, Kazakhstan to return precious stones and metals to Russia<br>
3.  Nobel laureates call for solution to East Timor conflict <br>
4.  Armenian Minfin to Launch State Coupon Bonds for the First Time<br>
5.  Russia Urges Armenia, Azerbaijan to Compromise on Karabakh <br>
6.  Azerbaijan's Answer To Armenia's Call     <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Iranian Armenians reject "negative propaganda" of foreign media <br>
SOURCE: IRNA news agency, Tehran, in English 1935 gmt 8 Dec 96 <br>
<p>
Iranian Armenians on Sunday [8th December] condemned the disinformation and<br>
negative propaganda spread by foreign media and some so-called human rights<br>
organizations regarding their status. <br>
<p>
The National and Cultural Association of Armenians of Tehran said in its<br>
statement on the eve of the world human rights'day, that Iranian Armenians<br>
actively and freely pursue their social and cultural activities without any<br>
restrictions. <br>
<p>
"Iranian Armenians enjoy full freedom in their personal lives and religious<br>
affairs, as guaranteed by the constitution of the Islamic Republic of Iran,"<br>
read part of the statement. "This association, as a social entity, hereby<br>
condemns the idle prattle of global arrogance," concluded the statement. <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Armenia, Kazakhstan to return precious stones and metals to Russia <br>
SOURCE: ITAR-TASS news agency (World Service), Moscow, in Russian 0946 gmt 9<br>
Dec 96 <br>
<p>
Diamonds belonging to Russia are to be returned by Armenia in December this<br>
year, and gold and silver by the Republic of Kazakhstan in January 1997,<br>
Russia's minister for cooperation with CIS countries, Aman Tuleyev, said in<br>
an interview with ITAR-TASS. <br>
<p>
Two years ago the Russian state conglomerate Almazyuvelirexport [diamond<br>
jewellery export] dispatched rough diamonds to Armenia for cutting, but the<br>
cut diamonds - worth 6.5m dollars - produced from these by the Sapphire<br>
factory, have yet to reach Russia.   Moreover, almost a year has passed since<br>
a Siberian factory sent a consignment of complex ores to Chimkent plating<br>
works in Kazakhstan for processing. The ores yielded 380 kg of gold and 3.5 t<br>
of silver, which have also not been returned to Russia... <br>
<p>
We are not able to give such expensive presents at a time when strikes are<br>
taking place everywhere because of wage and pensions arrears. "We have an<br>
obligation to follow things through," the minister added. <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Nobel laureates call for solution to East Timor conflict <br>
SOURCE:  Agence France, December 9, 1996<br>
<p>
The 1996 Nobel Peace Prize co-laureates on Monday reiterated appeals -- in<br>
separate press conferences -- for a solution to the conflict in East Timor on<br>
the eve of the Nobel Peace Prize ceremony in Oslo. <br>
<p>
Carlos Filipe Ximenes Belo, bishop of the East Timor capital Dili, and Jose<br>
Ramos-Horta, spokesman in exile of the East Timorese resistance, held<br>
separate press conferences instead of a planned joint conference, following<br>
"obvious" pressure on Belo from Jakarta, according to Ramos-Horta. <br>
<p>
Jakarta has told Belo to limit his public appearances with Ramos-Horta, the<br>
latter said. <br>
<p>
The Norwegian Nobel Committee complied with the laureates' wishes, judging it<br>
wiser to hold two separate press conferences. <br>
<p>
"The two laureates are working for the same cause. They are on good personal<br>
terms, but Mr. Belo is a religious spiritual leader and Mr.  Ramos-Horta is a<br>
political leader," said the chairman of the Norwegian Nobel Committee, Geir<br>
Lundestad. <br>
<p>
East Timor was a Portuguese colony until 1975, when Indonesian forces<br>
occupied the territory. The United Nations has never recognised Indonesia's<br>
annexation of East Timor in 1976. <br>
<p>
At his press conference, Belo refused to discuss his political beliefs,<br>
instead limiting himself to his role as spiritual leader. <br>
<p>
He stressed that he "recognised the efforts of the Indonesian government to<br>
develop East Timor" and the efforts of "many other friendly countries," and<br>
underlined that he was prepared to cooperate at "national and international"<br>
levels to find a "fair, peaceful and dignified" solution to the conflict. <br>
<p>
"But these efforts cannot be appreciated when they are not carried out with<br>
the responsible participation of the local people," the bishop said, calling<br>
for "a free and sincere dialogue" to overcome "the cultural barriers and<br>
psychological incomprehension" which are "the results of the past." <br>
<p>
Belo stressed that he had full freedom to travel and confirmed that he would<br>
visit Stockholm, Bonn and the Vatican as planned after the awards ceremony in<br>
Oslo. <br>
<p>
"I came here freely and I will return freely," he said, adding that "it is<br>
not totally correct" that he is under pressure from Jakarta. <br>
<p>
Ramos-Horta took a more political stance, criticising the Indonesian regime<br>
as well as western governments and reiterating his appeal for "a dialogue<br>
without preceding conditions to be opened within the framework of the United<br>
Nations." <br>
<p>
But any solution must "take into account the East Timorese people's right to<br>
self-determination," he added. <br>
<p>
Ramos-Horta said he was "prepared to be flexible, creative" and "to move step<br>
by step to find a solution to enable Indonesia to disengage gradually" from<br>
East Timor, so that Indonesia can "save face." <br>
<p>
Such a solution would include close cooperation with Indonesia across all<br>
existing regional organisations, such as the Asia-Pacific Economic<br>
Cooperation (APEC) forum, he said. <br>
<p>
The activist noted that the conflict, which has claimed the lives of some<br>
200,000 people, had been "largely ignored" by the international community,<br>
governments and non-governmental organisations, and compared it to "the<br>
Jewish and Armenian holocausts." <br>
<p>
Ramos-Horta was confident that the Nobel prize would "in the long run,<br>
perhaps even within two to three months, bring a change in the perception and<br>
attitude" of the Indonesian government. <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Armenian Minfin to Launch State Coupon Bonds for the First Time <br>
SOURCE:  Novecon, December 9, 1996<br>
<p>
The Armenian Finance Ministry and the Central Bank have announced the issue<br>
of state coupon bonds. <br>
<p>
According to Ashot Salnazaryan, head of the Securities Market Department at<br>
the Finance Ministry, the funds raised from the issue should help the country<br>
cover its budget deficit and repay its external debt.   Through bond issues,<br>
the government hopes to draw in 500m drams from the population before the end<br>
of 1997. Bonds will be issued for terms of 3, 6 and 12 months and will be<br>
sold at 10,000 drams per share without any restrictions. Yields on the bonds<br>
are exempt from taxation and will be paid once a quarter at 50 to 55% annual<br>
interest rate. <br>
<p>
Both legal entities and individuals, residents and non-residents are entitled<br>
to acquire the bonds. The total issue will be placed as bearer bonds. No<br>
refund is envisaged in the event of the bonds being either lost or damaged. <br>
<p>
HEADLINE:  Russia Urges Armenia, Azerbaijan to Compromise on Karabakh <br>
SOURCE:  ITAR-TASS, December 9, 1996<br>
 <br>
"Russia is interested in stabilising the situation and resolving the problem<br>
of Nagorno-Karabakh on the basis of a compromise," Russian Foreign Minister<br>
Yevgeny Primakov said after talks with his Armenian counterpart Alexander<br>
Arzumanyan on Monday. <br>
<p>
"A solution should be found on the basis of recognition of Nagorno-Karabakh's<br>
right to self-determination and self- government,while preserving the<br>
territorial integrity of Azerbaijan.  Such a right can be laid down in a<br>
corresponding agreement," Primakov said. <br>
<p>
He also noted that further consultations on these issues should be<br>
accompanied by contacts with Nagorno-Karabakh. <br>
<p>
The Russian and Armenian ministers reached understanding on all economic and<br>
political issues they discussed and agreed to invigorate consultations<br>
between the foreign ministries of the two countries anddevelop fraternal and<br>
friendly relations between Russia and Armenia. <br>
<p>
At the same time, the ministers gave differing assessments of the<br>
parliamentary elections in Nagorno-Karabakh held in November 1996. <br>
<p>
"The Russian side was against them because it believed that they should not<br>
be held before a mechanism for resolving the Nagorno-Karabakh crisis is<br>
worked out," Primakov said. <br>
<p>
However, Arzumanyan noted that Armenia does not consider the polls as an<br>
"extraordinary event going beyond the logic of the negotiating process. " <br>
<p>
He recalled a decision reached within the framework of the OSCE Minsk group<br>
that the talks would involve Armenia, Azerbaijan and elected leaders of<br>
Nagorno-Karabakh. <br>
<p>
"Therefore, elections do not break the harmony of the negotiating process and<br>
go in line with its spirit and principles," he added. <br>
<p>
On Russian troops in Armenia, Primakov said a corresponding document has<br>
already been considered by State Duma committees and been submitted to the<br>
parliament for ratification. <br>
<p>
Russia has also asked the Armenian parliament to accelerate thepassage of a<br>
similar document and received assurances from Armenian lawmakers that they<br>
are doing their best to synchronise the adoption of the document with their<br>
Russian counterparts. <br>
<p>
Speaking of oil production in the Caspian Sea, Primakov recalled that Russia,<br>
being one of the major oil exporters in the world, does not participate in<br>
the Organisation of the Petroleum Exporting Countries which determines quotas<br>
for member countries. <br>
<p>
"At the same time, the expansion of oil production in the Caspian Sea creates<br>
a new situation which none of us can ignore," he said. <br>
<p>
This is Arzumanyan's first visit to Moscow since his appointment in November<br>
1996. <br>
<p>
Arzumanyan said he was pleased that he paid one of this first foreign visits<br>
to Russia which has "an exclusive place in Armenia's foreign policy. " <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Azerbaijan's Answer To Armenia's Call <br>
SOURCE: Moskovsky Komsomolets (Russian Press Digest), December 7, 1996<br>
(Marina Vartanyan)<br>
<p>
Azerbaijan responds with heavy gunfire to Armenia's decision on presence of<br>
Russian troops on Armenian soil. <br>
<p>
A few days ago, Armenia's Constitutional Court ruled that the presence of<br>
Russia's military base and troops in Armenia was fully in line with the<br>
republic's Constitution. Baku responded to this with a massive shelling of<br>
Armenian territory, Moskovsky Komsomolets reports. <br>
<p>
On the day the relevant decision of the Armenian Constitutional Court came<br>
into force, Azeri artillery delivered heavy fire on three Armenian districts<br>
situated on the Armenian-Azeri border. In fact, there is nothing new in the<br>
shelling of Armenian soil -- this happens every day. "Normally," Azeri guns<br>
concentrate fire on an individual district or village, therefore the shelling<br>
of three targets at once was "very unusual," the paper notes. <br>
<p>
Turkey has increased its military capability seven-fold over the past three<br>
years, exclusively at the expense of and from the arsenals of NATO. The plans<br>
of NATO's eastward expansion include the scenario of approaching Russia's<br>
borders also from the southern direction, that is, by moving the idea of a<br>
"Greater Turan" -- Azerbaijan, Abkhazia, Chechnya and the like, farther and<br>
farther to the north-west and east.  Specifically, the objective is to oust<br>
Russia higher and higher to the North Pole by using the territory of these<br>
countries as a bridgehead. <br>
<p>
Perhaps it was for this reason that Russia's border guards chief, General<br>
Andrei Nikolayev, arrived in Yerevan with a fact-finding visit right after<br>
the Armenian Constitutional Court had made its decision on Russia's military<br>
base and the presence of Russian troops in Armenia, Moskovsky Komsomolets<br>
speculates. <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
