<p>
            ------------- POLITICS ------------<br>
<p>
CC RESOLUTION REGARDING ELECTION RESULTS ADOPTED BY<br>
MAJORITY OF VOTES<br>
     YEREVAN, November  26   (Noyan  Tapan). "This was the first<br>
attempt  to  raise a  dispute   between  the  opposition and the<br>
authorities  onto  a   civilized   level,"   Chairman   of   the<br>
Constitutional Court (CC) of Armenia Gagik Haroutiunian  said at<br>
a Monday news conference.<br>
     Haroutiunian said that the Constitutional Court had  chosen<br>
the right way -- a search for a final decision  through thorough<br>
scritiny and analysis of all available documents.<br>
     Haroutiunian  reported  that the  Constitutional Court  had<br>
charged  lawenforcement    agencies   to   institute    criminal<br>
proceedings in connection with a number of violations and  carry<br>
out a probe into those cases. Haroutiunian was  astonished  over<br>
the fact   that  a  person who  had   stolen a ballot box from a<br>
polling station was sentenced to 10  days  in  jail.  Meanwhile,<br>
according to him, that was a serious crime.<br>
     CC Chairman said that the law on the  Constitutional  Court<br>
of the Republic  of Armenia bans publicising the results of  the<br>
discussions.  He only said  that  the resolution  was adopted by<br>
the majority of votes. Constitutional Court  Chairman noted that<br>
under  the  legislation in  effect, protocols of closed  meeting<br>
were immediately sealed and sent to  state  archives.  "Pethaps,<br>
in some years they will be accessible,  and everybody will  have<br>
an opportunity to know what had happened," he said.<br>
     Haroutiunian said  it   was  not right   to  form electoral<br>
commission by   party  representation principle, since, he said,<br>
the commissions should be made up  of professionals, whose  work<br>
must be supervised.<br>
     Haroutiunian highly appreciated a worthy  behavior  of  the<br>
aggrieved party representatives at  the Court.  He  said that it<br>
thanks to  them  that  the  proceedings  were held  on  a really<br>
civilized level. "Our  country  needs opposition as we have  the<br>
Parliament,  Government   and   the  Constitutional  Court,"  CC<br>
Chairman said.<br>
<p>
<p>
PRESIDENTIAL ELECTION IN KARABAKH AROUSED AZERBAIJAN'S<br>
ANGER<br>
     YEREVAN,  November 26   (Noyan Tapan).  The   November   24<br>
presidential election  in  the   Nagorno-Karabakh Republic  were<br>
held, despite statements from  a  number of countries that  they<br>
will not recognize the election results.<br>
     On the   same  day   rallies,   protesting   the   Karabakh<br>
presidential   election  were    staged   in  Azerbaijan.    The<br>
Instanbul-based  Armenian  "Marmara"  daily  reports  that Azeri<br>
Culture Minister Polad Bul-Bul ogly said, addressing  a rally in<br>
Baku,  that  the  elections  in Karabakh  were   nothing but  "a<br>
politcal irritator". He said that  Azerbaijan  was  against  any<br>
bloodshed, but,  if   necessary, they were ready  to  shed their<br>
blood to liberate the occupied Azeri territories.<br>
<p>
<p>
            --------------- ECONOMY ----------------<br>
<p>
<p>
ECONOMIC REVIEW (NOVEMBER 17-24)<br>
<p>
     YEREVAN, November 26 (Noyan Tapan).<br>
<p>
     NATIONAL CURRENCY<br>
     Dollar rate did not practically  change for the  week.  The<br>
average cost of 1 USD decreased by 1 point and was equal to  434<br>
drams during   the week.  At   the  same  time, the  margin (the<br>
difference between sale and purchase prices) is still very  low.<br>
Maximal sale  price   (433 drams against 1  dollar) dropped by 2<br>
points, and minimal purchase price (436  drams) decreased by the<br>
same two points.<br>
     In principle, the  margin size is to  a certain  extent  an<br>
indicator of the health of the national currency. The higher  is<br>
the margin, the more alarming is  the  condition  of  the  given<br>
currency, and vice versa. In our case, drop of the  margin  from<br>
10 drams (2.5%  of the  dollar)  in  early November to  3  drams<br>
(0.7%)  is a sign  of  healthening,  though  its causes are  not<br>
clear.  The Government  did   not take  any efficient  steps  to<br>
protect dram from devaluation , and did  not even  make a formal<br>
statement on it. The Central Bank did only  one  thing:  for the<br>
first time during  two months it  took part  in  tradings at the<br>
Yerevan and Giumri Stock Exchange and purchased a rather  modest<br>
sum of 200,000 dollars.<br>
     But this   circumstance  could  never able  to  relax   the<br>
tension on currency market. Here, we  have  probably  the result<br>
of other factors: restraint from  emission, the  fact  that  the<br>
government used only those sums that are  in circulation, delays<br>
in pension and salary payments, and hence,  low consumer  demand<br>
and  relatively  stable consumer prices.  Anyway,  it should  be<br>
noted that it is not only the dollar rate that  affects consumer<br>
prices, but  also consumer  prices cause changes  in the  dollar<br>
rate.<br>
     Exchange  rate  at the Moscow  Interbank Currency  Exchange<br>
was 5,489 ruble on November 22.<br>
<p>
     CONSUMER BUDGET<br>
     By  the end   of  the  week the  cost  of   the living wage<br>
consumer budget   was  12,900  drams (29.6 dollars). The cost of<br>
the overalkl budget constituted 19,800 drams (45.5 dollars).<br>
     So, the cost of the consumer budget dropped by  200  drams,<br>
and 0.5 dollars.<br>
<p>
     CONSUMER PRICES<br>
     NT-16  index calculated   of  16 staple   food products was<br>
equal  to 1,000,  i.e.  general level of consumer prices  had no<br>
relation to changes in dollar rate and remained unchanged.<br>
<p>
     INVESTMENT ACTIVITY<br>
     Following the "Hrant"  index,  the investment  activity was<br>
9.55 during the week.<br>
<p>
     TREASURY BILLS MARKET<br>
     "Sed  Marced"  index of   profitability of   treasury bills<br>
constituted 0.3996, which is  456 points  lower  if  compared to<br>
the previous   week. The profitability  was 39.96%. According to<br>
President of   the Sed   Marced Firm  Tigran  Jerbashian,   such<br>
decrease  is  conditioned by  the fact that  2,000,000,000-worth<br>
treasury  bills were   used  up by  foreign  investors  two week<br>
before.<br>
<p>
<p>
            ------------- KARABAKH NEWS -----------<br>
<p>
<p>
KARABAKH DISAPPOINTED WITH HELSINKI NEGOTIATIONS, FM SAYS<br>
     YEREVAN, November 26 (Noyan Tapan).  "We  are  disappointed<br>
with the results of this round of negotiations  on  the Karabakh<br>
conflict", Karabakh Foreign Minister Arkady  Ghoukassian said at<br>
a Nov. 26 news conference.<br>
     He  noted that results  of  a  half-and-a-year  work of the<br>
OSCE  Minsk  group  and  principles  of  the conflict settlement<br>
worked out by the Armenian party were left out  of  the  account<br>
at  the   Helsinki    negotiations.   Ghoukassian  said    that,<br>
unfortunately, at the last moment  representatives of Azerbaijan<br>
refused  to participate  in   the work,   insisting   that   the<br>
negotiations  must be  held from the initial position,  i.e. the<br>
principle of territorial integrity of Azerbaijan.<br>
     Ghoukassian  said  that  the Nagorno-Karabakh  Republic did<br>
not consider   itself to  be   a  part  of Azerbaijan,   and any<br>
decision must proceed from this position.  "We  are  against any<br>
attempts to   predetermine the  results   of  the  negotiations.<br>
Respecting the  territorial  integrity,   Karabakh is  ready  to<br>
discuss this issue only after both  contending sides  hold equal<br>
initial positions at the  negotiations  and the Nagorno-Karabakh<br>
Republic  is  viewed as   a subject  of the  international law,"<br>
Karabakh's FM said. He described  statements by  the Azeri  side<br>
as statements of the  lost party which  demands  capitulation of<br>
its enemy. "If Azerbaijan really viewed Nagorno Karabakh  as its<br>
integral part, it would have  decided this  problem  by  itself,<br>
without turning to international organizations," he noted.<br>
     According to Ghoukassian, Azerbaijan intends  to kick up  a<br>
row at   the  forthcoming  OSCE summit   in Lisbon.  He   voiced<br>
confidence  that if  Azerbaijan  insists  that  the  territorial<br>
integrity be a basic principle of the  conflict settlement, then<br>
Armenia will have to use its right to veto.<br>
     He stressed  that  the  issue of  territorial  integirty is<br>
directly connected with the problem of  Karabakh's  status. "The<br>
fact  that the  Nagorno-Karabakh  Republic  is   independent  is<br>
obvious  and the status of  Karabakh  must be  a  result  of the<br>
negotiations,  and not   a starting   point  for   the  latter,"<br>
Ghoukassian said.<br>
     He emphasized   that  the presidential  election in Nagorno<br>
Karabakh proved that the Karabakh people trusts its leadership.<br>
     Ghoukassian said that the internal political  situation  in<br>
Armenia had played a certain part in toughening of  position  of<br>
Azerbaijan. However, he voiced confidence that  this  would  not<br>
influence the positions of Karabakh and Armenia.<br>
<p>
CONFLICTING SIDES FAIL TO AGREE A COMMON DOCUMENT<br>
     YEREVAN, November  26  (Noyan   Tapan).  No document  to be<br>
submitted at   the forthcoming OSCE summit in  Lisbon  has  been<br>
adopted  at a recent  round of talks  over the Karabakh conflict<br>
held in Helsinki. The positions of the parties  to  the conflict<br>
remained unchanged,   President elect   of the  Nagorno-Karabakh<br>
Republic Robert   Kocharian  said   at  a  news   conference  in<br>
Stepanakert. He noted that no document had  been  adopted during<br>
Libaridian-Guluzade meeting as well.<br>
     Kocharian noted that there  is  still a  chance to  agree a<br>
common  document  in  Vienna, a   document,  which  will then be<br>
presented at   the  Lisbon summit.  But   he was skeptical about<br>
that. He  said Azerbaijan  would stick  to its  position  as  it<br>
hoped to   submit  its  own  document at   the   Lisbon  summit.<br>
According to   Kocharian, the   Azeri side   will be pushing for<br>
territorial integirty of Azerbaijan. Azerbaijan counts  that the<br>
document will be supported by all countries-participants of  the<br>
cummit, and if Armenia  uses its rights to  veto  and  does  not<br>
vote for  that  document, it will have  to  confront with  other<br>
OSCE-member  countries.  Azerbaijan   believes  that  this  will<br>
seriously affect Armenia's international image.<br>
     "This is the major  position on  which  Azerbaijan  stakes.<br>
Taking  this    position  Azerbaijan  torpedoes  any  compromise<br>
decision which  might   be  achieved before the Lisbon  summit,"<br>
Kocharian said.<br>
<p>
<p>
           -------- CRIMINAL AND JUDICIAL --------<br>
<p>
MANVEL EGHIAZARIAN REFUSES TO ATTEND HEARINGS ON CASE OF 31<br>
     YEREVAN, November 26 (Noyan Tapan). At a  Nov.  25  hearing<br>
on the case of 31  Manvel  Eghiazarian's nephew Gagik Vanian did<br>
not plead guilty to committing an attempt on policeman's life.<br>
     Vanian  confirmed testimonies  that  he   had  given during<br>
preliminary  probe.   He   said  that  on  the  day  of   arrest<br>
Eghiazarian's house was encircled  by  armed people in masks and<br>
heavy  military  vehicles (Vanian said the house  was surrounded<br>
by tanks).  Armed  people burst  into the yard of the house  and<br>
opened  fire.  Eghiazarian was   crying out: "Don't shoot, there<br>
are small children at the house." Vanian said  he  was  not with<br>
Eghiazarian   and  could   not    remember   precisely   whether<br>
Eghiazarian returned fire or not. Vanian  said he  did not  know<br>
whether the  assailants   were agents   of  the   lawenforcement<br>
bodies.<br>
     Vanian said that out of the arms  seized at his  apartment,<br>
only 15 cartridges really belonged to him. He said he  kept them<br>
as a memory about the Karabakh war. He said he did not  know how<br>
the rest of the arms appeared at his apartment. As to arms  that<br>
had been found at Eghiazarian's, Vanian  said  that  "Manvel has<br>
always kept   arms at  home  and   even   much  more   than  the<br>
lawenforcement agents have found."<br>
     Manvel   Eghiazarian  said  that   he  refuses  to   attend<br>
hearings, whereas   his  wife Mariam Khzyrjian will not  come to<br>
the court as a witness.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
