Headlines of stories which follow:<br>
<p>
1.  Russian Border Service Chief Completes Trip to Armenia <br>
2.  Outside Interests Winning Battle for Kasparov's Attention, Time<br>
3.  Where Are They Now? Korky still hangs out in the buff now?<br>
     (Korky Day (Tashjian) - Canadian-Armenian pioneer of political nudity)<br>
4.  Increase in sexual exploitation of children attributed to growth in<br>
tourism<br>
     (statement of Fikret M. Pashayev, representing Azerbaijan)<br>
5.  Once Enemies, Russians and American Troops New Partners in Bosnia <br>
     (quotes Gevork Isahanian, commander of Russian troops in Bosnia)<br>
<p>
HEADLINE:  Russian Border Service Chief Completes Trip to Armenia <br>
SOURCE:  ITAR-TASS, December 8, 1996 (Dicran Liloian)<br>
<p>
"The Armenian leadership backs Russia's presence on the republican borders,"<br>
said here on saturday Director of the Russian Federal Border Service (FBS)<br>
Andrei  Nikolayev, describing the level of Russian-Armenian cooperation in<br>
border protection. <br>
<p>
On completing his one-day working visit to Yerevan, the General expressed<br>
satisfaction with the results of talks with republican president Levon<br>
Ter-Petrosyan as well as meetings with the Armenian Foreign, Interior and<br>
National Security Ministers and the commander of republican border troops. <br>
<p>
"We discussed issues concerning security of Russia and Armenia," he added. <br>
<p>
The Armenian leadership traditionally abides by approaches connected with the<br>
collective system of ensuring security, Nikolayev continued.  Hestated that<br>
collective security for Yerevan is based on bilateralrelations with Russia<br>
and also between Russia and other Caucasian states. <br>
<p>
The Armenian president expressed satisfaction with the work done by Russian<br>
border guards, the FBS director reported.   <br>
<p>
"Ter-Petrosyan expresseda desire for additional measures to ensure our common<br>
security and to protect outside borders of the Commonwealth of Independent<br>
States," Nikolayev noted. <br>
<p>
According to the Russian border service chief, the Armenian leader believes<br>
it possible to take additional measures to improve material supplies and to<br>
reinforce personnel of Russian border troops. <br>
<p>
"Our side outlined questions which we are tackling in the interests of our<br>
common tasks, and they were met with approval by the Armenian side," the<br>
General  emphasised. <br>
<p>
Generals and officers who accompanied Nikolayev, worked at border detachments<br>
of the "Armenia" army group which protects the state border between Armenia<br>
and Turkey and Iran. <br>
<p>
In compliance with treaties and agreements, signed by the leaders of the two<br>
nations, Armenian citizens have an opportunity to service in Russian border<br>
troops, deployed in the republic. <br>
<p>
HEADLINE:  Outside Interests Winning Battle for Kasparov's Attention, Time<br>
SOURCE:  Chicago Tribune, December 8, 1996<br>
<p>
The good news is that Garry Kasparov hopes to play a world title match with<br>
Anatoly Karpov next autumn. The disappointing news is--with that one<br>
exception--he does not plan to otherwise compete against his fellow humans<br>
during the next 12 months. <br>
<p>
Hailed as the strongest player in history, Kasparov brings to the board a<br>
creative flair and warrior mentality unmatched by any other player today. The<br>
insightful logic and beauty of his play have an irresistable effect on fellow<br>
grandmasters and audiences alike. <br>
<p>
After the VSB Tournament in Amsterdam last May, co-winner Veselin Topalov<br>
paid a deserved tribute:  <br>
<p>
"We have the world champion to thank for the small number of draws in the<br>
 tournament. Kasparov's brilliant fighting chess set an example for all of<br>
us."  <br>
<p>
Ineluctably, Kasparov has been turning away from chess to business and<br>
politics. During Russia's presidential elections, he energetically stumped<br>
for Boris Yeltsin. He also found time to campaign for the re-election of the<br>
Armenian President Levon Petrosian while playing in the World Chess Olympics<br>
in Yerevan.  After the Armenian elections, thousands took to the streets of<br>
Yerevan to challenge the legitimacy of Petrosian's victory.  <br>
<p>
The political ambitions of the world champion of chess are apparently without<br>
bounds, but most chess players would probably prefer to see him remain the<br>
Russian king of chess than reincarnated as the president or king of Russia. <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Where Are They Now? Korky still hangs out in the buff now?<br>
SOURCE: Vancouver Sun,December 7, 1996<br>
<p>
If you're talking about nudism in Vancouver, you're talking about Korky Day.<br>
He was the guy who arranged the "Nude-in" at Wreck Beach in 1970 that helped<br>
establish Wreck as the premier nude beach in Canada. He was the guy who<br>
wanted to turn the giant 1983 peace march into a "nude walk for peace," until<br>
police detained him. He is the guy you see marching bare-chested alongside<br>
topless women in the "top free" marches of the '90s.<br>
<p>
Day is still a nude activist -- when the weather gets a little chilly to go<br>
to Wreck, he helps organize twice-a-month nude swimming parties at indoor<br>
pools (for details, call him at 877-1631).<br>
<p>
But he's got other irons in the fire. The 48-year-old native of Pasadena,<br>
Calif., who was born Kirk Reynold Stone and arrived in Canada as a war<br>
resister in 1968, is very active in the Green Party. He worked hard to get<br>
the proportional representation clause on Vancouver's referendum about wards<br>
and the at-large system. <br>
<p>
"It's a fair, neutral system," he says of proportional representation. "All<br>
the other systems are weighted in favor of some or another group, or in favor<br>
of forcing everybody into central parties." <br>
<p>
Day has been co-hosting the Armenian Variety Show on Co-Op Radio since 1984<br>
(his family name was Tashjian before it was anglicized). <br>
<p>
He publishes his own newspaper, Allies ("it's an alternative newspaper --<br>
what the Georgia Straight should have been, and would have been, had it not<br>
been taken over by the liberal Bolsheviks"). <br>
<p>
Most recently, the national Green Party adopted his resolution to take nudity<br>
out of the Criminal Code. "Nudity is not a crime," he says. "It may be<br>
annoying at times, or produce frostbite, but it's not a crime."  <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Increase in sexual exploitation of children attributed to growth in<br>
tourism<br>
SOURCE:  M2 Presswire, November 15, 1996<br>
<p>
Fikret M. Pashayev (Azerbaijan), said the report of the Secretary-General's<br>
expert had indicated that millions of children were caught up in armed<br>
conflict in which they were not merely bystanders but also victims of armed<br>
aggression and genocide. However, he could not agree with the report's<br>
statement that all major armed conflicts around the world in 1995 were<br>
internal and took place within States. Unfortunately, the report did not<br>
reflect the conditions of hundreds of thousands of children, refugees and<br>
displaced persons in Azerbaijan. As a result of the armed aggression by<br>
Armenia and its continuing occupation of 20 per cent of Azerbaijan's<br>
territory, there were one million refugees and displaced persons, many of<br>
them women and children. The Armenian army had destroyed 900 human<br>
settlements, as well homes, schools, mosques, social and cultural facilities,<br>
libraries and nurseries, all of which had a negative impact on children. <br>
<p>
He said when millions of children, including thousands in his country lived<br>
in refugee camps, suffering from starvation and malnutrition, and lack of<br>
medical services, the international community must take effective action to<br>
protect their rights. International humanitarian organizations played a<br>
leading role in that task. Taking into account their limited resources, there<br>
must be a more effective process of post-conflict settlement, which included<br>
speedy repatriation of refugees and displaced persons, as well as<br>
reconciliation, recovery and development. The Convention on the Rights of the<br>
Child must be ratified by all Governments, but more importantly, it must be<br>
implemented. The welfare of children depended on the welfare of their<br>
mothers, strong economies and good neighbourly relations. His Government<br>
supported the recommendations in the report.  <br>
<p>
HEADLINE:  Once Enemies, Russians and American Troops New Partners in Bosnia<br>
SOURCE: The Associated Press, October 12, 1996<br>
<p>
Russian Capt. Stanislav Mazurin studied the leaves turning to autumn red on<br>
the mountainside before him, and reckoned he'd learned a thing or two about<br>
Americans since coming to Bosnia last winter.<br>
<p>
"The devil is not so dangerous as we previously thought," Mazurin<br>
acknowledged, as he inspected his company's position on a winding road in a<br>
zone separating Bosnian Serbs from Muslims in northeast Bosnia. <br>
<p>
Many eyes are watching this experiment in Russia-NATO cooperation -  the<br>
first Russian-American military collaboration  -  in hopes it may lead to<br>
closer East-West security ties.  <br>
<p>
The 1,500-man Russian brigade, part of a force commanded by U.S. Army Maj.<br>
Gen. William Nash, has played a vital role in separating former combatants<br>
here.  <br>
<p>
Nash has nothing but the highest praise for the Russians  - although it would<br>
be surprising if he didn't, given the political sensitivity of the<br>
partnership. <br>
<p>
"The forces that they have provided here are extremely proficient," said<br>
Nash, proudly showing a photograph of himself and the Russian commander.<br>
"They are dedicated. They are disciplined. They have reacted quickly to<br>
incidents that required quick movement of forces."<br>
<p>
Lt. Col. Gevork Isahanian, chief of staff of the Russian brigade, is no less<br>
enthusiastic. <br>
<p>
"After so many strained years between East and West, we've got a real chance<br>
to see each other in a military operation, a chance to study each other," he<br>
said during a talk at brigade headquarters. <br>
<p>
"All these countries have had a chance to see the Russians are not so rude,<br>
not so strange, not so dangerous," Isahanian said. "We are normal people." <br>
<p>
Added Col. Vladimir Nakhoun, chief of the brigade's civil affairs unit: "Now,<br>
the image of a potential enemy has changed to a potential partner." <br>
<p>
Relations with the local people is another matter. While the Russians get<br>
along well with Serbs, Muslims suspect they are here only to protect their<br>
"Serbian brothers." <br>
<p>
Isahanian insisted the Russians were impartial, but admitted there had been<br>
problems with the Muslims. <br>
<p>
Among them is the village of Jusici, a smashed tumble of houses at the end of<br>
a twisting, muddy road in Serb-controlled territory east of Tuzla, site of<br>
the U.S. headquarters. Muslims driven from it during the 3 1/2-year war have<br>
come back to reclaim their homes. <br>
<p>
The return has been tense. A villager claimed he was beaten by Russians. The<br>
Russians claim villagers set a small explosive charge in one of their<br>
generators. Accusations still fly back and forth. <br>
<p>
Isahanian  -  an ornamental ashtray made from a Coke can decorating his desk<br>
 -  said there was no reason for Jusici Muslims to believe that the Russians<br>
favored the Serbs.  <br>
<p>
For his part, Nash believes the Russians have been treated badly by the<br>
Muslim side. <br>
<p>
"The biggest problem we've faced together is the attempt by the (Muslims) to<br>
split us," the American general said. <br>
<p>
"It has been unsuccessful," he said. "The Russian brigade is a member of my<br>
division, and an insult to them is an insult to me."  <br>
The only problems he has had with the Russian troops have been the usual ones<br>
that arise between commanders of divisions and their subordinates, he said.<br>
"The relationship has been amazingly normal." <br>
<p>
A year ago, NATO and Russian officials haggled at length over the command<br>
structure, working out a complicated chart of who would report to whom  -  in<br>
large part a face-saving document to avoid the impression that Russians were<br>
serving under NATO.  <br>
<p>
The arrangement also provided a mechanism allowing the Russians to go<br>
directly to their own hierarchy. <br>
<p>
Nash said neither he nor the Russian commander have ever even mentioned this<br>
chart. It simply hasn't been necessary. That is even more true at the bottom<br>
end of the scale where soldiers are soldiers -  and mud is mud. <br>
<p>
In Jusici, Russian and American enlisted men cook rations over the same fire<br>
 -  and when language isn't a barrier, grumble about the same things. <br>
<p>
The American troops have less to complain about, Mazurin said, marveling at<br>
the "luxury" with which U.S. forces are equipped.    Better the Russian way,<br>
he said, where equipment and supplies are simpler and easier to maintain. <br>
<p>
The Russian captain has been studying American military troops from afar<br>
since beginning his career in Cold War days. But seeing Americans up close in<br>
a real operation just once, he said, beats reading about them 100 times in<br>
training manuals. <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
