<title>Groong Network: Turkey/CenAsia Highlights 12/07/96</title>
<h1>Turkey/CenAsia Highlights 12/07/96</h1>
Mher Sassouni (<i>as080@lafn.org</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 9 Dec 96 16:45:56 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#73">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#73">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#73">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#73">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0074.html">Chavoush@aol.com: "Armenian News 12/9/96"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0072.html">ASBAREZ-ON-LINE: "ASBAREZ-ON-LINE [12-09-96]"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
  	  				 <br>
	+&gt; Kazakhstan oil pipeline deal signed  <br>
	+&gt; Police chief's sacking sparks Turkey row  <br>
	+&gt; Conference on Afganistan to be held  <br>
	+&gt; Turkey lifts veto on Israeli deal  <br>
	+&gt; Turkey fires Istanbul police chief  <br>
	+&gt; Armenia to discuss Karabakh issue  <br>
                               ======	 <br>
 Kazakhstan oil pipeline deal signed<br>
	Kazakhstan has signed agreements with Russia, Oman and a<br>
group of major oil companies to build a $2 billion pipeline<br>
transporting Kazakh crude oil to Europe through a Russian port<br>
on the Black Sea, the Interfax news agency said Saturday. The<br>
900-mile (1,500 km) pipeline would deliver oil from the Caspian<br>
Sea Tengiz field to the Russian Black Sea port of Novorossiysk,<br>
the agency said in a dispatch monitored in London. Construction<br>
s expected to begin early next year and scheduled to be<br>
completed by 1999. The new accords, which were signed Friday in<br>
Moscow, revise the structure of the Caspian Pipeline Consortium,<br>
originally formed in 1992 between the governments of Kazakhstan,<br>
Russia and Oman. The Financial Times newspaper said the nine oil<br>
companies would finance construction in exchange for 50 percent<br>
of the equity. U.  S. multinational Chevron's Senior<br>
Vice-President, Jeet Bindra, said the new accords meant earnings<br>
of about $40 billion over 40 years for Russian central and local<br>
government institutions. ``In addition, a considerable part of<br>
the pipeline capacity will be used for Russian exports,<br>
stimulating the development of Russian oilfields,'' said<br>
Bindra. The pipeline initially would carry each year about 28<br>
million tonnes of Kazakh crude oil, increasing the throughput to<br>
67 million tonnes at a later stage.<br>
                               ======<br>
 Police chief's sacking sparks Turkey row<br>
	Turkish opposition leaders cried cover-up Friday in<br>
reaction to the government's suspension of Istanbul's police<br>
chief and five officers.  Interior Minister Meral Aksener<br>
announced late Thursday that Chief Kemal Yazicioglu, his deputy,<br>
the head of the special operations department and three officers<br>
had been suspended and removed from an investigation into<br>
allegations of official links to drug killings. Yasar Dedelek,<br>
speaking for the opposition Motherland Party, called the<br>
decision ``a very serious attempt on the part of the government<br>
to try to cover up dirt. The government should review its<br>
decision.'' But Prime Minister Necmettin Erbakan promised<br>
President Suleyman Demirel in a letter Friday that the<br>
government would do everything it could to investigate the<br>
allegations. Newspapers and Mesut Yilmaz, Motherland's leader,<br>
had accused the suspended men of involvement in the July killing<br>
of Omer Lutfu Topal, a drug lord and casino owner, over division<br>
of gambling and smuggling profits. Yilmaz said he had documents<br>
proving such ties and proof that prominent politicians had<br>
underworld links. Yilmaz appealed to Demirel to intervene. The<br>
president responded by urging the prime minister to<br>
investigate. That was followed by Thursday night's<br>
suspensions. ``The state cannot be dirty. It is some of the<br>
people in the authoritative positions who are not clean,'' said<br>
Onur Kumbaracibasi, spokesman for the leftist opposition<br>
Republican People's Party. Former Interior Minister Ismet<br>
Sezgin, now an independent parliamentarian, accused Interior<br>
Minister Aksener of being an inexperienced functionary of the<br>
rightist True Path Party, the junior partner in the government<br>
coalition with Erbakan's arch-Muslim Welfare Party.<br>
                               ======<br>
 Conference on Afganistan to be held<br>
	An international conference on Afghanistan will be held<br>
in Ashkhabad from Jan. 21 to 22, Turkmen Foreign Minister Boris<br>
Shikhmuradov told the Russian Itar-Tass news agency<br>
Friday. Shikhmuradov said the decision had been adopted by the<br>
United Nations in New York. The U.N. has manifested its<br>
intention to use the political and international potential of<br>
Turkmenistan as a neutral state which has proved its adherence<br>
to the aims and targets of the U.N. Foreign ministers of<br>
Australia, Austria, Canada, Egypt, Germany, India, Indonesia,<br>
Iran, Japan, Malaysia, Pakistan, Russia, Saudi Arabia, South<br>
Korea, Spain, Switzerland, the U.  S. and other states are<br>
expected to participate. Political and Social leaders, as well<br>
as representatives of various international organizations, will<br>
also attend. They will held an exchange of opinions on the<br>
situation in Afghanistan in an attempt to provide the war-torn<br>
country with tangible humanitarian assistance. The political,<br>
economic, social and military issues will also be discussed, the<br>
agency said.<br>
                               ======<br>
 Turkey lifts veto on Israeli deal<br>
	Turkey's Prime Minister has reversed his opposition to<br>
an Israeli aircraft contract and given the go-ahead to the deal,<br>
a senior official said Friday. Prime Minister Necmettin<br>
Erbakan's defense advisor, Sedat Celikdogan, told United Press<br>
International that the contract would now go to President<br>
Suleyman Demirel for signing -- expected to be a formality. Last<br>
week Erbakan blocked the deal for Israel to modernise 54 Turkish<br>
Airforce F-4 Phantom fighters, saying that the interest payments<br>
on the $600 million contract were too high. In a move which<br>
threatened to provoke a showdown with the Turkish military,<br>
Erbakan said the interest rates had to be<br>
renegotiated. Celikdogan declined to explain why Erbakan had<br>
finally approved the deal. Analysts speculated that Erbakan had<br>
bowed to the military's insistence that the deal was vital to<br>
Turkey's armed forces. A senior member of the Turkish general<br>
staff said Friday he was pleased with Erbakan's decision. The<br>
Turkish military has overthrown unpopular governments three<br>
times since 1960 and Erbakan's coalition is currently weathering<br>
a storm of protests over alleged corruption.<br>
	Under the contract, Israeli Aircraft Industries is to<br>
fit the planes with advanced avionic systems.<br>
                               ======<br>
 Turkey fires Istanbul police chief<br>
	The Turkish government has fired Istanbul's police chief<br>
and five members of an elite police unit over allegations of<br>
links with drug killings, a London newspaper said Friday. Police<br>
Chief Kemal Yazicioglu, his deputy, the head of the special<br>
operations department and three officers were suspended<br>
Thursday, the Financial Times said. Opposition figures and media<br>
reports have accused the six of involvement in the July murder<br>
of Omer Lutfu Topal, a drug lord and casino owner, the newspaper<br>
said. Topal was killed in a dispute over dividing gambling and<br>
smuggling profits. The latest police-crime scandal came to light<br>
as Turkey continued to simmer over an unexplained episode in<br>
November, when a car carrying parliamentarian Sedat Bucak, a<br>
high-ranking police officer and a criminal wanted by Interpol<br>
crashed, killing all except Bucak. Bucak is a member of the<br>
rightist True Path Party, the junior partner in Turkey's<br>
government coalition. He has been recovering from crash injuries<br>
and was repeatedly interrogated this week by<br>
investigators. Bucak admitted that weapons found in the car were<br>
his and threatened to name top officials tied to the crash,<br>
raising the specter of government involvement in corruption and<br>
ties with organized crime.  The parliamentarian is a leader in a<br>
Kurdish tribe allied to the government and fighting Kurdish<br>
separatists in southeastern Turkey.  Then-Interior Minister<br>
Mehmet Agar of the True Path Party resigned after being accused<br>
of covering up facts about the crash.<br>
                               ======<br>
 Armenia to discuss Karabakh issue<br>
	Armenia is ready to continue negotiations on all aspects<br>
of the Karabakh settlement, Armenian Foreign Minister Alexander<br>
Arzumanyan told foreign ambassadors in Yerevan, the Russian<br>
Itar-Tass news agency said Friday. He said, ``There is the<br>
impression Azerbaijan is not ready to continue the<br>
negotiations. The OSCE leader's proposals on the Karabakh<br>
settlement principles are actually proposals of the Azerbaijani<br>
delegation and cannot be accepted by Armenia,'' he added.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
