<p>
<p>
1. "DRO" GROUP NOT LINKED WITH ARF, REITERATES BUREAU MEMBER<br>
<p>
MONTREAL-The 106th anniversary of the Armenian Revolutionary <br>
Federation was celebrated at the Montreal Armenian Center, during <br>
which ARF Bureau member Vicken Hovsepian once again unequivocally <br>
rejected any and all party ties with the so-called "Dro" group.<br>
	Given a recent announcement that the longwinded "Dro" trial <br>
was scheduled to conclude Tuesday, with the announcement of the <br>
verdicts, the Bureau member reiterated the partys position on the <br>
matter.<br>
	"The trial proceedings clearly showed that individual <br>
criminal wrongdoing were attempted to be tied to the ARF, solely <br>
for political purposes," stated Hovsepian adding that "the <br>
Armenian people saw that those attempts were futile and that there <br>
was no evidence, whatsoever, to legitimize those claims."<br>
	The ARF leader stated that the trial deviated from all <br>
judicial and human rights norms.<br>
	"As we have officially announced immediately following the <br>
arrests, and as the ARF 26th World Congress and the subsequent <br>
July Armenias Supreme Assembly announced, we also reiterate to <br>
the Armenian people that no ARF assembly or executive body has had <br>
links with the creation and activities of the `Dro group. In the <br>
event that criminal evidence is presented against individual <br>
members, the ARF, as always, will take necessary actions against <br>
those individuals who have violated the moral and ideological <br>
values and principles of  our organization," declared Hovsepian.<br>
	"Based on the aforementioned provisions, we, once again, <br>
announce from this podium that if criminal allegations are tied to <br>
the ARF through the verdicts, it would be proven  that the trial <br>
was staged based on political interests, and aimed at prohibiting <br>
the normal operations of the ARF in Armenia," concluded  <br>
Hovsepian.<br>
	At the beginning of his remarks, Hovsepian discussed the <br>
ARFs posturing toward the current political situation in Armenia, <br>
as well as the socio-economic conditions in the homeland.<br>
	Hovsepian specifically highlighted the plan presented to <br>
Armenias National Assembly by newly appointed Prime Minister <br>
Armen Sarkissian, discussing its positive aspects, and expressed <br>
hope that in coming months, through the realization of the plan, <br>
conditions in Armenia, as well as Armenia-Diaspora relations would <br>
improve.<br>
<p>
<p>
2. ARF 106TH ANNIVERSARY MARKED IN KARABAKH<br>
<p>
STEPANAKERT (ANIS)-The Armenian Revolutionary Federations 106th <br>
anniversary celebrations were held on Sunday at the "Nigol Douman" <br>
Center in Stepanakert.<br>
	The event was organized by the ARF "Artur Mkrtchian" <br>
Gomideh.<br>
	Central Committee chairperson Armen Sargssian delivered the <br>
keynote address, highlighting the 106-year-old organizations <br>
achievements and its work in Nagorno-Karabakh, which resulted in <br>
the free and independent Republic of Nagorno-Karabakh.<br>
	ARF Bureau representative to Nagorno-Karabakh, Serge <br>
Amirkhanian, also addressed Sundays gathering. "Marking the 106th <br>
anniversary of the ARF in Artsakh marks a rebirth of sorts. We <br>
consider today to be a day of accountability, as we look back at <br>
the past year and evaluate what we have given to the nation in <br>
terms of the ARFs general goals," Amirkhanian said.<br>
	"Today, each ARF member renews his pledge, which is an <br>
annual tradition. We are a lucky generation to be able to <br>
celebrate this anniversary in the free and independent Artsakh," <br>
he said.<br>
	The evenings celebration concluded with a dinner and <br>
patriotic songs. Throughout the night event organizers recalled <br>
episodes in the lives and activities of fallen heroes martyred in <br>
the defense of Karabakh.<br>
	Four new members joined the ARF ranks that evening.<br>
	"By becoming a member of this party, I will continue the <br>
work of my ancestors that was left undone. This party [the ARF] <br>
was considered to be sacred in my family," said Anna Assatrian, <br>
chairperson of the "Armenian Woman" organization of the Armenian <br>
Relief Society in Artsakh.<br>
	Emil Abrahamian, Executive Director of the Artsakh Fund, <br>
told an ANIS reporter, "We celebrate this day like a holiday, but <br>
this day is symbolically and spiritually different from other <br>
holidays. And that spirit is what strengthens us. That strength <br>
which encompasses the nation is called Dashnaktsutiun [Armenian <br>
Revolutionary Federation]."<br>
	"The ARF is not a prescription to be given to a patient. The <br>
ARF is a national way of thinking. I am convinced that the time <br>
will come when the ARF will be able to freely, and anywhere it <br>
chooses, serve the Armenian nation."<br>
<p>
<p>
3. PRIMAKOV CALLS FOR AUTONOMY FOR KARABAKH WITHIN AZERBAIJAN<br>
<p>
MOSCOW (Itar-Tass)-"Russia is interested in stabilizing the <br>
situation and resolving the Nagorno-Karabakh conflict," Russian <br>
Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov said after talks with Armenian <br>
Foreign Minister Alexander Arzoumanian on Monday.<br>
	"A solution should be found on the basis of recognition of <br>
Nagorno-Karabakhs right to self-determination and self-government <br>
while preserving the territorial integrity of Azerbaijan," <br>
Primakov said. <br>
	The Russian and Armenian ministers reached an understanding <br>
on all economic and political issues. They also agreed to <br>
invigorate consultations between the foreign ministries of the two <br>
countries and develop fraternal and friendly relations between <br>
Russia and Armenia.<br>
	This was Arzoumanians first visit to Moscow since his <br>
appointment in  November 1996.<br>
	At a meeting with Armenias foreign diplomatic corps <br>
Saturday, Arzoumanian he presented the Armenian governments <br>
viewpoint regarding the results of the OSCE Lisbon summit and <br>
voiced regret over the OSCE Chairmans proposal on the Karabakh <br>
conflict settlement being unacceptable for Armenia.<br>
	Arzoumanian said that Azerbaijans proposal was illogical, <br>
adding that Azerbaijans attempt to exert pressure on Armenia by <br>
blocking the entire declaration could create a very dangerous <br>
precedent in the future.<br>
	He assured that Armenia was ready to continue negotiations <br>
although Azerbaijan did not seem to be ready to proceed with the <br>
negotiations. <br>
<p>
<p>
4. ARMENIA'S DEBT TO WORLD BANK COULD REACH $500 MILLION<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-Armenia's debt to the World Bank could reach <br>
$500 million, stated Vahram Nercisissian the World Bank's <br>
plenipotentiary representative to Armenia during a recent seminar <br>
at the American University of Armenia.<br>
	Nercissian reported that Armenia currently owes the World <br>
Bank approximately $280 million and if more projects were <br>
undertaken through World Bank loans and credits that debt could <br>
reach more than $500 million.<br>
	The World Bank reportedly is planning a $16.75 million <br>
credit program to banks in Armenia which correspond to <br>
international norms.	<br>
	The World Bank announced that its has allocated $1,818,000 <br>
for the construction of homes and dwellings in Shirak.<br>
	According to Albert Markarian, Deputy Chief of Shiraks <br>
City-Planning Department, the money will be used for the <br>
construction of more than 300 apartments in the regions capital <br>
of Gumri, and 100 apartments in other areas of the region.<br>
	The construction of the dwellings and other facilities has <br>
been financed both through the budget funds and credits allocated <br>
by the World Bank.<br>
	The first stage of one of the World Bank projects on <br>
restoration of the earthquake area has been completed. This <br>
project included construction and reconstruction of residential <br>
buildings and communications. The World Bank agreed to provide an <br>
advance of $2 million for the implementation of the second stage <br>
of the project.<br>
	Another World Bank project reportedly aims at restoring <br>
social institutions, including schools, water pipelines, <br>
irrigation systems and telephone communications. <br>
	This project is being implemented by the Armenian Fund for <br>
Social Investments, which provided $1,500,000 worth of contracts <br>
to the Shirak region.<br>
	The Armenia Fund also plans to implement a $3.5 million in <br>
construction in the Shirak region in 1997. The Funds project <br>
includes reconstruction of schools and residential buildings. <br>
	Markarian noted that one of the largest schools in Gumri <br>
would begin operation in the near future. Its construction is <br>
being sponsored by the governments of France and Armenia, which <br>
have allocated  $1.7 million.<br>
	Among other projects Markarian also discussed the <br>
construction of schools, which are being conducted by the Armenian <br>
Assistance Fund and the Armenian Education Foundation.<br>
<p>
<p>
5. RUSSIA, ARMENIA COOPERATE IN SECURITY REALM<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-"I am satisfied with the results of the <br>
meetings I had with both Levon Ter-Petrosyan and National Security <br>
and Interior Minister Serge Sargsyan," Director of the Russian <br>
Federal Border Service, Andrey Nikolayev said upon his arrival in <br>
Yerevan.<br>
	Nikolayev said a wide range of problems concerning Russias <br>
and Armenias security had been discussed. <br>
	He said that the Armenian leadership traditionally adheres <br>
to a collective assurance of security.<br>
	According to Nikolayev, Ter-Petrosyan expressed his <br>
satisfaction with the work done by the frontier guards. Nikolayev <br>
pointed out that Ter-Petrosyan wants additional measures to be <br>
taken to help strengthen their material supplies and staff. <br>
	"In short, Ter-Petrosyan will back the presence of Russian <br>
troops on the Armenian borders," he said.<br>
	Nikolayev also pointed out that he has repeatedly told <br>
Russian President Boris Yeltsin about the necessity of helping in <br>
the settlement of regional conflicts.<br>
	In compliance with treaties and agreements signed by the <br>
leaders of the two nations, Armenian citizens have an opportunity <br>
to serve as Russian border troops on the Armenia, Turkey and Iran <br>
border. <br>
<p>
<p>
6. ARMENIA TO RETURN RUSSIAN DIAMONDS<br>
<p>
MOSCOW (Itar-Tass)-Russian Minister for Commonwealth of <br>
Independent States relations, Aman Tuleyev said that Russia will <br>
be getting its diamonds, gold and silver back from Armenia by <br>
January 1997.<br>
	The Russian state-run Almazyuvelir export company shipped a <br>
consignment of rough diamonds to Armenia two years ago to be cut <br>
and polished at the Sapfir diamond factory. The diamonds, worth <br>
$6,500,000, were never returned to Russia.<br>
	In addition, Siberian enterprises shipped a consignment of <br>
polymetallic ore for processing to the Chimkent lead plant in <br>
Kazakhstan almost a year ago.<br>
	Approximately 172 pounds of gold and 3.5 tons of silver were <br>
extracted from the ore. Russia has yet to retrieve the gold and <br>
silver.<br>
	Tuleyev said  Russia must get its property back. "We cannot <br>
afford to give presents at a time when strikes are breaking out <br>
throughout the country because of the governments failure to pay <br>
wages and pensions," he said.<br>
<p>
<p>
7. ARMENIA INTRODUCES COMPUTERIZED CUSTOMS SYSTEM<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-Armenia is the first Commonwealth of <br>
Independent States member to implement a computerized customs <br>
registration program, head of the Customs Department, Yerjanik <br>
Abgarian, said at a Friday news conference.<br>
	He said that some 70 countries started installing the <br>
program, but only one third of them, among them Armenia, completed <br>
it.<br>
	According to Abgarian, the program, known as "Asicuda," was <br>
fully operational by May 1996 in the Ararat region, and later in <br>
Shirak, Lori and Siunik regions.<br>
	Although the program is far from perfect, Abgarian said that <br>
it can be improved, with the help of a $1.3 million World Bank <br>
credit.<br>
	Abgarian said that two customs offices connecting Armenia <br>
with Turkey are also ready. However, we cannot say the same about <br>
those connecting Armenia and Georgia, where there was a lack of <br>
facilities and customs officers, he said.<br>
	There are plans to build customs offices in Gougark and <br>
Siunik regions, and three offices on the border with Georgia <br>
during the next year.<br>
	Responding to a question on international drug trafficking <br>
via Armenia, Abgarian said there is no danger for Armenia to <br>
become a transition zone for drug trafficking. Abgarian did not <br>
share the opinions expressed in a recent United Nations report, <br>
saying that Armenia can turn into a transition zone for the drugs <br>
going from Iran to Russia and to Europe.<br>
	Head of the Service for Efficiency in Trade and Development <br>
of Infrastructures, Jean Gurunlian said that Armenia will <br>
introduce a new system to prevent smuggling. Gurunlian noted that <br>
customs offices of the former Soviet Union are far from being <br>
perfect, which creates obstacles in realizing these programs.<br>
<p>
<p>
8. NATIONAL PROGRESS PARTY LEADER SOUGHT BY AUTHORITIES<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-Last Thursday at about 4:30 p.m. a group of <br>
ten armed National Security and Interior Ministry forces entered <br>
the home of Albert Bagdassarian, vice-chairman of the National <br>
Progress party, with the intention to take him to their <br>
headquarters, the National Progress party said in a statement <br>
Friday.<br>
	Bagdassarian, a former National Assembly member, was not <br>
home at the time, and the group told his wife that they wanted to <br>
take her husband for "a conversation with National Security and <br>
Interior Minister Serge Sargsyan." They also told Bagdassarians <br>
wife that Prosecutor-General Artavazd Gevorgian also wanted to see <br>
him, the statement said.<br>
	Two of the officers, ordered to stay at the apartment, <br>
waited until 11:30 p.m. not allowing anyone to leave or use the <br>
telephone, the statement said. Bagdassarians mother-in-law, <br>
sister-in-law and her baby were detained along with Bagdassarians <br>
wife and two children. In addition, the Interior Ministry officers <br>
also detained National Progress party chairman Vardan Zournachian <br>
and an administrative member, Ashot Ounanian, who had come to <br>
visit the Bagdassarians, according to the statement.<br>
	The party has filed a complaint with Armenias Prosecutor-<br>
General, demanding to know "who will be taking responsibility for <br>
violating the sanctity of Albert Bagdassarians home and the <br>
rights of his family;" and on what grounds and based on which laws <br>
did Sargsyan send ten armed officers to bring Bagdassarian to <br>
headquarters?"<br>
	The National Progress party called on Armenian authorities <br>
to "stop political persecutions in the republic and take relevant <br>
measures to restore legal power, order and democracy."<br>
<p>
<p>
9. OSKANIAN ASSESSES LISBON SUMMITT<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-"Armenia was pressured from the very first <br>
day of the Lisbon Summit to adopt paragraph 20 of the final <br>
declaration of the summit. At the last moment  Levon Ter-Petrosyan <br>
had to use his right to veto," Deputy Foreign Minister of Armenia <br>
Vardan Oskanian said at a recent news conference in Yerevan.<br>
	Oskanian said that the international community had always <br>
proposed three principles which were inadmissible for Armenia-the <br>
territorial integrity of Azerbaijan, international guarantees of <br>
wider autonomy and security for Nagorno-Karabakh. <br>
	Oskanian said Azerbaijan was pressured only after it had <br>
threatened to block the entire declaration. "I believe this will <br>
have negative consequences for Azerbaijan in the future."<br>
	Prior to the OSCE Lisbon Summit, Ter-Petrosyan said there <br>
would be no surprises at the summit, however, Oskanian explained <br>
that the talks were stable prior to the summit, and Armenia had <br>
succeeded in removing the passage referring to the aforementioned <br>
principles and replaced them with a more neutral paragraph.<br>
	Oskanian said that the OSCE clearly agreed with Armenias <br>
position on the settlement of the Karabakh conflict. He <br>
characterized as negative the discussion on the Karabakh conflict <br>
as a collective opinion. <br>
	The principle of national self-determination was clearly <br>
stated in a final Helsinki statement, which says that a nation has <br>
the right to determine its foreign and domestic political status. <br>
	"I see some positive signs in the fact that this principle <br>
is now accepted, although with several reservations. It seems to <br>
me that we must emphasize this very principle," he said.<br>
	Oskanian said that there is a distinct difference between <br>
the Karabakh conflict and the other regional disputes, explaining <br>
that the international community treats the Karabakh problem very <br>
cautiously. "They understand that the Karabakh conflict differs <br>
from the other conflicts and the approaches used with the other <br>
conflicts will not work here." <br>
	Oskanian said that Armenia would strongly oppose the Minsk <br>
Group negotiations if they were held within the limits of <br>
territorial integrity for Azerbaijan and wider autonomy for <br>
Nagorno-Karabakh.<br>
	"The Minsk Group must tackle a very clear-cut position-to <br>
coordinate a comprehensive political accord," Oskanian said, <br>
adding that the draft proposal does not include a reference to <br>
Karabakhs political status. "It seems to me that Azerbaijan will <br>
make such attempts, however, I think well be able to reject their <br>
discussion and emphasize the political accord," he stressed.<br>
	"These questions should have been specified during the <br>
bilateral negotiations which Nagorno-Karabakh should have also <br>
joined later. However, this never happened. Well continue <br>
negotiations on the political accord and political status, but we <br>
are not going to take these three principles as grounds for the <br>
negotiations," Oskanian said.<br>
	Oskanian also made a statement about the rotation of the <br>
OSCE co-chairmen. The present co-chairmen are likely to be <br>
replaced by the United States and France, he said. "We are <br>
entering a new phase. The process is taking on a new nature and <br>
our diplomacy will have to deal with a difficult task," he said.<br>
	He also noted that the position of Nagorno-Karabakh and its <br>
commentary and assessments would be of great significance and will <br>
depend on the course of further negotiations.<br>
	Oskanian said that Madeleine Albrights appointment as US <br>
Secretary of State would not influence the position held by the US <br>
on the Karabakh issue. Albright knows the problem very well. <br>
	She was the US Ambassador to the UN so she had constant <br>
contacts with Armenias Ambassador to the UN, Alexander <br>
Arzoumanian, who is currently Armenias Foreign Minister.<br>
<p>
<p>
10. HUMAN RIGHTS ORGANIZATION CELEBRATES FIRST YEAR<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-The UN Office in Armenia presented two <br>
books, "Human Rights and Legal Procedure" and "Human Rights and <br>
Elections" during the celebration of the first anniversary of the <br>
Armenian Center for Democracy and Human Rights.<br>
	The first book was published on the eve of the presidential <br>
election in Armenia and is a handbook of the UN Human Rights <br>
Center. The second book is a collection of all international <br>
documents on human rights and elections. The publication of the <br>
books was sponsored by the US Embassy in Armenia, the US <br>
Information Service office in Yerevan and the UN.<br>
<p>
<p>
11. TURKEY SIGNS WARPLANE ACCORD WITH ISRAEL<br>
<p>
ANKARA (Reuter)-Turkeys Islamist Prime Minister Necmettin Erbakan <br>
has signed a $600 million agreement with Israel for the <br>
modernization of Turkish F-4 fighter-bombers, the state-run <br>
Anatolian news agency reported Friday.<br>
	Erbakan, who reportedly signed the accord Thursday, had <br>
pledged to scrap an earlier military cooperation agreement between <br>
Turkey and Israel before taking office in June. He has not since <br>
acted on the pledge.<br>
	Turkish President Suleyman Demirel approved the deal Friday, <br>
the presidents office said in a statement.<br>
	Turkish officials were not available to comment on the <br>
signing of the latest accord, which was welcomed by Israels <br>
embassy in Ankara.<br>
	"We feel very pleased that the project in question has been <br>
signed by Prime Minister Erbakan after a long period of talks," an <br>
embassy spokesman was quoted as telling Anatolian.<br>
	"We want the project to be put into effect as soon as <br>
possible," the spokesman said.<br>
	The five-year modernization project covers 54 US-made F-4 <br>
planes and will be financed with Israeli credit.<br>
	Twenty-six of the Turkish Air Force planes will be <br>
modernized in Israel and 28 in the western Turkish town of <br>
Eskisehir.<br>
	Israeli commercial banks approved the $600 million credit <br>
package by Israel Aircraft Industries in October.<br>
	The five-year deal will involve the installation of advanced <br>
avionic systems including radar and electronic warfare and <br>
navigation systems.<br>
	Israeli officials said last weekend that they had renewed <br>
the military cooperation agreement with Turkey, which had drawn <br>
the ire of Syria, Iran and Islamists.<br>
<p>
<p>
12. EUROPEAN ORGANIZATION DENOUNCES TORTURE BY TURKISH POLICE<br>
<p>
STRASBOURG (Reuter)-The European Committee for the Prevention of <br>
Torture, in a rare public statement, Friday denounced Turkish <br>
police for physically torturing prison inmates.<br>
	The Committee, part of the Strasbourg-based Council of <br>
Europe which safeguards democracy and human rights, issued the <br>
statement after visiting police-run institutions in Adana, Bursa <br>
and Istanbul in September. The committee also met former inmates <br>
who were examined by police doctors.<br>
	"A considerable number of those examined had lesions or <br>
other medical signs compatible with their allegations of bad <br>
treatment...and in particular with blows on the soles of their <br>
feet, blows on the palms of their hands and with being suspended <br>
by their arms," the Committee said.<br>
	"Two of the people examined had lost the use of their two <br>
arms. These effects could prove irreversible," it said.<br>
	The team reported that it had found equipment for electric <br>
shocks and for suspending people by their arms in the offices of <br>
police headquarters in Istanbul.<br>
	According to the Committee, the Turkish government was <br>
informed of its findings and "failed to recognize the gravity of <br>
the situation." Notes and circulars issued by the Turkish <br>
authorities to improve the human rights situation were not <br>
enforced.<br>
	"It is up to the state to make sure it is obeyed," the <br>
Committee said, adding that in no circumstances could the fight <br>
against guerrilla violence justify torture or other ill-treatment <br>
by security forces.<br>
	The Committee issued a similar report four years ago. Turkey <br>
is the only member of the Council of Europe which has never <br>
published findings by the Committee. It decided to publish the <br>
latest report as the only way of putting pressure on Ankara.<br>
<p>
<p>
13. KERIANS, CAROLANS DONATE $25,000 TO PRELACY<br>
<p>
LOS ANGELES-Benefactors Tina Carolan and Mr. and Mrs. Vartan and <br>
Clara Kerian visited the Western Prelacy of the Armenian Apostolic <br>
Church and presented Prelate Right Rev. Moushegh Mardirossian with <br>
a generous holiday donation of $25,000.<br>
	Mr. and Mrs. Richard and Tina Carolan and the Kerians have <br>
been ardent supporters of the Prelacys religious, national and <br>
educational programs.<br>
	At the request of the benefactors, this recent donation will <br>
be earmarked for the Prelacys traditional New Years and <br>
Christmas dinner and the publishing house of the Holy See of <br>
Cilicia.<br>
	Earlier this year, the Carolans and the Kerians made a <br>
magnanimous donation of $100,000 to the Holy See of Cilicia <br>
monastery and the Western Prelacy building fund upon Catholicos <br>
Aram Is first pontifical visit to the Western Prelacy.<br>
<p>
