<title>Groong Network: Russia urges Armenia, Azerbaijan to compromise....</title>
<h1>Russia urges Armenia, Azerbaijan to compromise....</h1>
Kevork K. Oskanian (<i>100436.3410@CompuServe.COM</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 9 Dec 96 13:13:01 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#70">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#70">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#70">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#70">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0071.html">Asbed Bedrossian: "AP/Reuters headlines to 12/09/96"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0069.html">Armen Martirossyan: "From Armenpress homepage"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
 By Valery Sevryukov  <br>
MOSCOW, December 9 (Itar-Tass) - "Russia is <br>
interested in stabilising the situation and resolving the problem of <br>
Nagorno- Karabakh on the basis of a compromise," Russian Foreign <br>
Minister Yevgeny Primakov said after talks with his Armenian counterpart <br>
Alexander Arzumanyan on Monday. <br>
   "A solution should be found on the basis of recognition of <br>
Nagorno-Karabakh's right to self-determination and self- government, <br>
while preserving the territorial integrity of Azerbaijan. Such a right <br>
can be laid down in a corresponding agreement," Primakov said. <br>
   He also noted that further consultations on these issues should be <br>
accompanied by contacts with Nagorno-Karabakh. <br>
   The Russian and Armenian ministers reached understanding on all economic <br>
and political issues they discussed and agreed to invigorate <br>
consultations between the foreign ministries of the two countries and <br>
develop fraternal and friendly relations between Russia and Armenia. <br>
   At the same time, the ministers gave differing assessments of the <br>
parliamentary elections in Nagorno-Karabakh held in November 1996. <br>
   "The Russian side was against them because it believed that they should <br>
not be held before a mechanism for resolving the Nagorno-Karabakh crisis <br>
is worked out," Primakov said. <br>
   However, Arzumanyan noted that Armenia does not consider the polls as an <br>
"extraordinary event going beyond the logic of the negotiating <br>
process." <br>
   He recalled a decision reached within the framework of the OSCE Minsk <br>
Group that the talks would involve Armenia, Azerbaijan and elected <br>
leaders of Nagorno-Karabakh. <br>
   "Therefore, elections do not break the harmony of the negotiating <br>
process and go in line with its spirit and principles," he added. <br>
   On Russian troops in Armenia, Primakov said a corresponding document has <br>
already been considered by State Duma committees and been submitted to <br>
the parliament for ratification. <br>
   Russia has also asked the Armenian parliament to accelerate the passage <br>
of a similar document and received assurances from Armenian lawmakers <br>
that they are doing their best to synchronise the adoption of the <br>
document with their Russian counterparts. <br>
   Speaking of oil production in the Caspian sea, Primakov recalled that <br>
Russia, being one of the major oil exporters in the world, does not <br>
participate in the Organisation of the Petroleum Exporting Countries <br>
which determines quotas for member countries. <br>
   "At the same time, the expansion of oil production in the Caspian Sea <br>
creates a new situation which none of us can ignore," he said. <br>
   This is Arzumanyan's first visit to Moscow since his appointment in <br>
November 1996. <br>
   Arzumanyan said he was pleased that he paid one of this first foreign <br>
visits to Russia which has "an exclusive place in Armenia's foreign <br>
policy." <br>
   zak/ <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
