<!-- body="start" -->
        PRESIDENT TER-PETROSSIAN MEETS WITH THE DIRECTOR OF THE<br>
        RUSSIAN BORDER GUARDING TROOPS<br>
<p>
 YEREVAN, DECEMBER 9, ARMENPRESS.<br>
 On December 6, the President of the Republic of Armenia Levon<br>
 Ter-Petrossian received the Director of the Russian Federal Border<br>
 Guarding Troops, General Andrey Nikolaev.<br>
 During the meeting the sides discussed the material and technical<br>
 aspects of Armenian-Russian cooperation in the area of<br>
 border-guarding.<br>
 Immediately after the meeting, Mr. Nikolaev had a brief meeting with<br>
 journalists, during which he expressed his satisfaction with the<br>
 results of his meeting with the President, and the earlier meetings<br>
 with the Minister of Foreign Affairs and the Minister of Internal<br>
 Affairs and National Security of the Republic of Armenia.<br>
 Mr. Nikolaev said that the President and the Ministers consider the<br>
 effective Armenian-Russian cooperation, as well as Russia's<br>
 cooperation with other Transcaucasian countries, as a key for<br>
 effective security system.<br>
 According to Mr. Nikolaev, President Ter-Petrossian expressed his<br>
 satisfaction with the work of the border guards and supported the<br>
 presence of the Russian border guards on Armenian borders.<br>
<p>
        PRESIDENT TER-PETROSSIAN MEETS WITH A UN REPRESENTATIVE<br>
<p>
 YEREVAN, DECEMBER 9, ARMENPRESS.<br>
 On December 6, the President of the Republic of Armenia Levon<br>
 Ter-Petrossian met with the Chairman of the UN International Trade<br>
 Symposium and the Head of the Trade Development and Efficiency<br>
 Services Jean Gurunlian.<br>
 During the meeting the sides discussed issues related to the<br>
 cooperation between this organization and the Republic of Armenia, in<br>
 particular, in the area of modernization of the Armenian customs<br>
 system.<br>
<p>
        STATEMENT OF THE MINISTRY OF FOREIGN AFFAIRS OF THE<br>
        NAGORNO-KARABAGH REPUBLIC<br>
<p>
 STEPANAKERT, DECEMBER 9, ARMENPRESS.<br>
 On December 6, 1996, the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the<br>
 Nagorno-Karabagh Republic issued a statement, in which it expressed<br>
 the bewilderment with the statement of the OSCE Acting Chairman<br>
 during the Lisbon Summit.<br>
 According to Ministry of Foreign Affairs, that statement defies the<br>
 international legal and historical aspects of the Karabagh conflict.<br>
 The OSCE's Chairman's statement is considered as a defeat of justice<br>
 and common sense by the blackmail on the part of Azerbaijan, which is<br>
 abusing the oil interests of some countries.<br>
 The Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Nagorno-Karabagh Republic<br>
 pointed out that throughout the 20th century the Armenian people have<br>
 been the victim of geographic interests of the world's superpowers.<br>
 The Ministry classified the efforts to keep Karabagh within a<br>
 criminal country, who has been steadily conducting anti-Armenian<br>
 politics, as the continuation of the already familiar policies.<br>
 The Ministry once again voiced the preparedeness of Karabagh to keep<br>
 the ceasefire and to resolve the conflict in a peaceful manner.<br>
 It stated that the Karabagh should be represented in the<br>
 negotiations, because the proposals of the mediators are often based<br>
 on partial interpretations of internationally accepted rights and<br>
 reflect the interests of only one out of three sides of the conflict.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
