<!-- body="start" -->
Dear Readers:  The following is the latest version of the monthly<br>
publication, "TransCaucasus: A Chronology," published by the Washington<br>
office of the Armenian National Committee of America (ANCA), written<br>
by Richard Giragosian and edited by Christopher Hekimian.  This issue<br>
examines events in the region during November 1996.<br>
<p>
For more information, or to be added to the publication's email<br>
distribution list, please email the author, Richard Giragosian, at:<br>
giragosi@essential.org<br>
<p>
Richard Giragosian<br>
Washington, D.C.<br>
giragosi@essential.org<br>
<p>
<p>
****************************************************************<br>
<p>
                      TransCaucasus<br>
                      A Chronology<br>
                    (E-Mail Version)*<br>
<p>
****************************************************************<br>
Vol. 5                 December, 1996                      No.12<br>
<p>
<p>
The TransCaucasus: A Chronology is a chronological summary of the <br>
significant social, economic, and political events in the lower <br>
Caucasus, as reported by local and international media and selected <br>
sources in the region.  Full acknowledgement should be given to all <br>
material quoted from or based on this publication.<br>
<p>
Compiled and written by Richard Giragosian (giragosi@essential.org)<br>
Edited and designed by Christopher Hekimian<br>
<p>
ISSN 1078-3113<br>
<p>
A Publication Of The Armenian National Committee of America<br>
<p>
****************************************************************<br>
<p>
Republic of <br>
Armenia<br>
<p>
Total area:<br>
29,800 sq. km<br>
Slightly larger than Maryland<br>
<p>
Bordering states:<br>
Azerbaijan (east) 566 km<br>
Nakhichevan (south) 221 km<br>
Georgia 164 km<br>
Iran 35 km<br>
Turkey 268 km<br>
<p>
Population:<br>
3.6 million<br>
68% urban<br>
110.5 persons/sq. km<br>
<p>
Ethnic composition:<br>
93.3% Armenian<br>
1.5% Russian<br>
1.7% Kurdish<br>
3.5% Assyrian, Greek, other<br>
<p>
-------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<p>
Leadership:  Levon Ter Petrosian, President; Hrant Bagratian, Prime <br>
Minister; Vahan Papazian, Foreign Minister. <br>
<p>
Independence:  Armenia re-established its independence on September <br>
23, 1991, after more than 70 years of Soviet rule.  The first <br>
Armenian Republic was established on May 28, 1918.<br>
<p>
CIS membership status:  Armenia joined the CIS in March 1992 and <br>
CIS Defense Treaty in May 1992.<br>
<p>
Constitution:  A constitution was adopted by national referendum on <br>
July 5, 1995.<br>
<p>
Elections:  Elections were held for Parliament July 5, 1995 and for <br>
President September 22, 1996.<br>
<p>
Diplomatic representation:  The United States representative to <br>
Armenia is Ambassador Peter Tomsen. The Armenian representative to <br>
the United States is Ambassador Rouben Shugarian.  The Armenian <br>
representative to the United Nations is Ambassador Alexander <br>
Arzoumanian.<br>
<p>
-------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<p>
MONTHLY CHRONOLOGY<br>
<p>
2 November: The Armenian Constitutional Court begins consideration <br>
of the appeal filed by the opposition presidential candidates <br>
Vazgen Manukian and Ashot Manoucharian over alleged irregularities <br>
and fraud during the country's September 22nd presidential <br>
election.  The appeal seeks to have the election results <br>
invalidated due to the allegations of widespread, organized and <br>
systematic fraud by the government resulting in the president's <br>
reelection.  The contest has led to mass demonstrations in the <br>
capital, protests by the country's opposition parties and a <br>
crackdown by the state authorities introducing a temporary <br>
suspension of civil liberties and a ban on all public gatherings.  <br>
The Constitutional Court is comprised of nine members, four of whom <br>
are appointed by the President and the other five by the majority <br>
pro-government parliament.<br>
<p>
2 November: President Levon Ter Petrosian meets with a visiting <br>
official of the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe <br>
(OSCE) to review the situation regarding the Nagorno Karabagh <br>
conflict.  The OSCE official, Finnish Foreign Minister Tarja <br>
Halonen, reviews his plans for the mediation process of the OSCE's <br>
working group on the conflict, the so-called "Minsk Group," now <br>
chaired jointly by Finland and Russia.  During the visit to <br>
Armenia, the Finnish foreign minister also discusses the issue of <br>
bilateral relations between Finland and Armenia.  The OSCE is <br>
engaged in a renewed flurry of activity in preparation for its <br>
upcoming 54-nation, two-day summit to be held in Lisbon in early <br>
December. <br>
<p>
4 November: Armenian Prime Minister Hrant Bagratian resigns his <br>
post and is replaced by the Armenian Ambassador to the United <br>
Kingdom, Armen Sarkissian.  The appointment of the new prime <br>
minister, the fifth in the five years of the Ter Petrosian <br>
government, is interpreted as an attempt to ease the political <br>
tension overwhelming the country since the controversial reelection <br>
of Ter Petrosian.  The outgoing prime minister was initially <br>
appointed in February 1993 and had previously held the posts of <br>
deputy prime minister and economics minister.  Bagratian enjoyed <br>
the support and confidence of the international lending <br>
organizations engaged in supporting the economic market reforms in <br>
Armenia throughout his tenure in the government. <br>
<p>
5 November: Shavarsh Kocharian, who is representing Vazgen Manukian <br>
in his appeal to annul the presidential election results due to the <br>
voting fraud and irregularities, criticizes the court for <br>
"violating the principles of equality and transparency."<br>
<p>
5 November: In a show of solidarity with the jailed opposition <br>
Armenian Revolutionary Federation (ARF) leader Vahan Hovanessian, <br>
eight protesters begin a hunger strike in Yerevan's Liberty Square.  <br>
The hunger strikers demand an immediate end to the government-run <br>
political trials of the country's leading opposition political <br>
figures, the release of all political prisoners, and the lifting of <br>
the government's ban on the activities of the country's largest <br>
opposition party, the ARF.<br>
<p>
6 November: Newly appointed Prime Minister Armen Sarkissian issues <br>
a statement promising his commitment to continue the economic <br>
reforms of his predecessor with "a new impetus and to uphold the <br>
country's independence." The new prime minister further adds that <br>
his economic plan will endow Armenia with a truly competitive and <br>
modernized economy in order to prevent the country from being <br>
overtaken by "regional economic and political forces."  The <br>
statements are aimed at easing the internal political tension <br>
afflicting the country since the recent tainted presidential <br>
election and the external worries over the state of the economic <br>
reforms marshaled by former Prime Minister Bagratian.<br>
<p>
7 November: More changes in the new Ter Petrosian government are <br>
announced with the resignation of the interior and foreign affairs <br>
ministers.  Interior Minister Vano Siradeghian, notorious for his <br>
connections to organized crime in Armenia, is appointed mayor of <br>
Yerevan by presidential order and Foreign Affairs Minister Vahan <br>
Papazian is dismissed from his post.  Both figures are prominent <br>
members of the ruling Armenian National Movement (ANM) and are <br>
personally close to the president.  Defense Minister Vazgen <br>
Sarkisian is reportedly retaining his post in the new government.<br>
<p>
8 November: President Ter Petrosian announces the final changes in <br>
the new governmental structure.  The powerful interior and national <br>
security ministries are consolidated into one power ministry to be <br>
headed by security minister Serge Sarkisian.  While the influential <br>
defense minister, Vazgen Sarkisian, retains his post, three <br>
newcomers enter the cabinet.  The former Ambassador to the United <br>
Nations, Alexander Arzoumanian, is appointed foreign minister, <br>
former communist party leader Vladimir Movsisian is named minister <br>
of agriculture, and former communist youth official Hranush <br>
Hakobian becomes social welfare minister.<br>
<p>
8 November: A jailed leader of the banned opposition party the <br>
Armenian Revolutionary Federation (ARF), Vahan Hovanessian, ends <br>
his hunger strike that he initiated on October 29th to protest the <br>
continuous delays in the government's trial targeting him and other <br>
opposition figures.  The Hovanessian trial involves a group of 31 <br>
opposition members charged with treason, terrorism and assorted <br>
crimes against the state.  Since their arrest in July 1995, state <br>
authorities have violated the defendants' civil rights and rights <br>
to trial and have been accused of inhumane treatment and denying <br>
the prisoners the right to medical attention resulting into the <br>
mysterious death of one detainee from excessive blood loss.<br>
<p>
10 November: Armenian President Levon Ter Petrosian is formally <br>
inaugurated and his newly reconstituted government is officially <br>
installed.  The ceremony proceeds, marking the start of the <br>
president's second five-year term, despite the pending <br>
Constitutional Court's review of the opposition's appeal claiming <br>
fraud in the presidential election.  Of the country's main <br>
opposition parties, nearly all of whose activities are restricted <br>
or banned, the Communist Party is the only one in attendance.<br>
<p>
14 November: The European Parliament adopts a resolution condemning <br>
the election violations, the government's undemocratic treatment of <br>
the country's opposition parties and its leaders, and the state <br>
repression of the media.  The resolution calls on the Armenian <br>
government to hold new elections in the districts where the results <br>
were seriously questionable and to return to the international <br>
norms of democracy and freedom by guaranteeing the civil liberties <br>
of free speech, free press and assembly.<br>
<p>
17 November: Angrily denouncing the arbitrary decision of the <br>
Armenian Constitutional Court regarding the opposition's petition <br>
alleging voting fraud in the recent presidential election, <br>
opposition representatives hold a press conference in Yerevan.  The <br>
Constitutional Court announced that it will examine the documents <br>
and returns from several questionable electoral precincts for <br>
suspected fraud but will hear from only one of more sixty witnesses <br>
offered by the opposition.  Moreover, the Court ruled that it will <br>
continue to deny access to voting records and tabulations in <br>
military units and supported the actions of the government-<br>
controlled Central Election Commission in sealing all of its <br>
documents.  The Central Election Commission, in its explanation to <br>
the Court, also rejected a report by the international election <br>
observers of the Organization for Security and Cooperation in <br>
Europe (OSCE) critical of the election and documenting cases of <br>
fraud and voting irregularities as being "ill-informed" and a <br>
"reflection of private opinions only."<br>
<p>
22 November: The Armenian Constitutional Court formally rejects the <br>
opposition's appeal alleging voting fraud in the presidential <br>
election and certifies the election's results as valid and binding.  <br>
The Court decision, effective immediately, is final and without any <br>
avenue for appeal.  The country's opposition political parties <br>
respond with a uniform condemnation stressing that they have <br>
followed the legal avenues available for contesting the election <br>
and asserting that the court's verdict in no way legitimizes the <br>
election.<br>
<p>
25 November: Speaking at a press conference in Yerevan, Armenian <br>
presidential advisor Jirair Libaridian warns that Armenia will veto <br>
any document regarding Nagorno Karabagh submitted to the upcoming <br>
summit of the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe <br>
(OSCE) that has not been approved by Yerevan.  The Armenian <br>
official stresses that the summit is the only effective avenue for <br>
negotiating a draft document on the political status of Nagorno <br>
Karabagh and any draft plan must include a definitive diplomatic <br>
and legal status for Karabagh with firm security guarantees for the <br>
Nagorno Karabagh population.<br>
<p>
-------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<p>
Republic of Georgia<br>
<p>
Total area:<br>
69,700 sq. km<br>
Slightly larger than S. Carolina<br>
<p>
Bordering states:<br>
Armenia 164 km<br>
Azerbaijan 322 km<br>
Russia 723 km<br>
Turkey 252 km<br>
<p>
Population:<br>
<p>
5.57 million<br>
56% urban<br>
78 persons/sq. km<br>
<p>
Ethnic composition:<br>
69% Georgian<br>
9% Armenian<br>
6% Russian<br>
6% Ajarian<br>
5% Azerbaijani<br>
3% Ossetian<br>
2% Abkhazian<br>
<p>
Georgia includes the autonomous republics of Abkhazia and Ajaria<br>
and the South Ossetian Autonomous Region.<br>
________________________________________________________________<br>
<p>
Leadership:  Eduard Shevardnadze, President; Irakli Menagrashvili, <br>
Foreign Minister, Nickol Lekishvili, Secretary of State, Zurab <br>
Zhvania, Parliamentary Chairman.<br>
Independence:  Georgia established its independence on April 9, <br>
1991.<br>
<p>
CIS membership status:  The Georgian government joined the CIS on <br>
October 23, 1993.<br>
<p>
Constitution:  A new constitution was adopted in August, 1995, <br>
which reinstates a presidential form of government and provides for <br>
a strong executive branch and a unicameral 235-seat parliament.  A <br>
constitutional court is also created.  The constitution, however, <br>
does not address the status of Abkhazia, Ossetia or Ajaria.<br>
<p>
Elections:  Presidential and parliamentary elections were last held <br>
November 1995.<br>
<p>
Diplomatic representation:  The United States representative to <br>
Georgia is Ambassador Kent Brown. The Georgian representative to <br>
the United States, as well as Canada and Mexico, is Ambassador Tedo <br>
Japaridze.  The Georgian representative to the United Nations is <br>
Ambassador Peter Chkiedze.<br>
<p>
-------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<p>
MONTHLY CHRONOLOGY<br>
<p>
2-3 November: Abkhazian government officials report that armed <br>
Georgian groups have attacked Russian peacekeepers along the <br>
Abkhazian-Georgian border.  Artillery bombardments are also <br>
reported in the Abkhazian town of Gali.  Tensions are reportedly <br>
increasing as Abkhazia November 23 parliamentary elections near.<br>
<p>
4 November: The Georgian government denounces the Abkhazian <br>
elections as illegal and appeals to Russia to state their official <br>
position on the elections in an attempt to stop them through <br>
diplomatic intervention and pressure.  The United Nations, fearful <br>
of the election's effect on the stalled mediation talks over the <br>
conflict, has called on Abkhazia to postpone the elections pending <br>
the return of the several hundred thousand Georgian refugees.<br>
<p>
4-5 November: Ukrainian Prime Minister Pavlo Lazarenko meets with <br>
Shevardnadze and other Georgian officials in Tbilisi.  A series of <br>
bilateral agreements are signed including an important accord <br>
stipulating military cooperation between the two countries.  The <br>
Ukrainian delegation also discusses the strategic issue of the <br>
planned transport of oil from Azerbaijan to Georgia's Black Sea <br>
port facilities.  Given Kiev's significant dependence on energy <br>
imports from Russia, Ukraine is interested in importing Azerbaijani <br>
oil from Georgia and is seeking the possible creation of a regional <br>
transit network consisting of inter-state highways, railway lines <br>
and pipelines.<br>
<p>
5 November: A new committee comprising representatives of eighteen <br>
opposition parties is formed to advocate the complete withdrawal of <br>
all Russian military troops from Georgia.  These include troops <br>
deployed along the Abkhazian-Georgian border as peacekeepers and <br>
those stationed at the four military bases Russia leases from <br>
Georgia.  This new committee is similar to an earlier group, the <br>
"National Liberation Movement of Georgia," founded several months <br>
ago by members of fourteen opposition parties not represented in <br>
the current parliament.<br>
<p>
8 November: The deputy secretary of the newly reconstituted Russian <br>
Security Council, Boris Berezovsky, meets with Shevardnadze to <br>
discuss the latest situation in nearby Chechenya and to review <br>
bilateral relations between Moscow and Tbilisi.  Shevardnadze also <br>
reiterates his appeal for increased Russian pressure on the <br>
Abkhazian leadership as the negotiations between Sukhumi and <br>
Tbilisi have stalled in recent months.<br>
<p>
10 November: Results from presidential elections in the former <br>
Georgian autonomous "oblast," or region, of South Ossetia, show <br>
parliamentary chairman Lyudvig Chibirov winning with 65 percent of <br>
the vote.  Former Prime Minister Vladislav Gabarayev is second with <br>
a mere 20 percent.  Georgian officials, though characterizing the <br>
election as "unlawful," are pleased by the outcome due to <br>
Gabarayev's platform advocating secession from Georgia and <br>
unification with adjoining North Ossetia within the Russian <br>
Federation.  The low turnout for Gabarayev indicates a significant <br>
lessening of support for outright unification with North Ossetia <br>
and a favoring of the more gradualist position advanced by <br>
Chibirov. South Ossetia adopted two referendums advocating <br>
secession from Georgia in 1991 and 1992 and is currently engaged in <br>
negotiations with Tbilisi over its political status.  The Georgian <br>
government is offering greater autonomy for the independence-<br>
seeking region. <br>
<p>
11 November: Georgian Defense Minister Lt. General Vardiko <br>
Nadibaidze meets with his Russian counterpart, General Igor <br>
Rodionov, in Moscow to finalize the bilateral agreement providing <br>
for Russian military assistance to Georgia.  The agreement calls <br>
for the transfer of Russian armored personnel carriers, artillery <br>
and naval vessels to Georgia.  The Russian Defense Council has <br>
heralded this agreement as an important element in Russia's <br>
strategy to build a series of bilateral military and security <br>
accords throughout the Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS).<br>
<p>
24 November: Abkhazian officials announce that the first round of <br>
parliamentary elections have decided 30 of 35 seats and begin <br>
preparations for runoff elections for the five remaining seats.  <br>
Several hundred thousand Georgian refugees from the Abkhazian <br>
region are not able to participate in the elections, however.  This <br>
election represents a significant advance in the Abkhazian <br>
leadership's bid for independence, as it effectively replaces the <br>
previous Soviet-style legislature which split in 1993 into two <br>
rival camps, one favoring Abkhazian independence and the other <br>
supporting Tbilisi.  Georgian officials conduct a referendum for <br>
the Georgian refugees from Abkhazia resulting in a predictable <br>
majority voting to disregard any Abkhazian election held without <br>
their participation.<br>
<p>
-------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<p>
Republic of Azerbaijan<br>
<p>
Total area:<br>
81,800 sq. km<br>
Slightly smaller than Maine<br>
<p>
Bordering states:<br>
Armenia (West) 566 km<br>
Armenia (southwest) 221 km<br>
Georgia 332 km<br>
Iran (south) 432 km<br>
Iran (southwest) 179 km<br>
Russia 284 km<br>
Turkey 9 km<br>
<p>
Population:<br>
7.3 million<br>
54% urban<br>
89 persons/sq. km<br>
<p>
Ethnic composition:<br>
71% Azerbaijani<br>
11% Talish<br>
6% Russian<br>
4% Lezgi <br>
3% Daghestani<br>
3% Kurdish<br>
2% Avar<br>
<p>
The autonomous republic of Nakhichevan (pop. 350,000; 5,500 sq. km)<br>
was placed under Azerbaijani administration in 1921.<br>
-------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<p>
Leadership:  Geidar Aliyev, President; Artur Rasizade, Prime <br>
Minister; Hasan Hasanov, Foreign Minister; Shamshaddin Khanbabayev, <br>
Premier of Nakhichevan.<br>
<p>
Independence:  Azerbaijan established its independence on August <br>
30, 1991.<br>
<p>
CIS membership status:  Azerbaijan joined the CIS on September 24, <br>
1993.<br>
<p>
Constitution:  A new constitution was passed by referendum in <br>
November 1995.<br>
<p>
Elections: Parliamentary elections for a new 125-seat legislature <br>
were held November 1995.<br>
<p>
Diplomatic representation:  The United States representative to <br>
Azerbaijan is Ambassador Richard Kauzlarich.  The Azerbaijani <br>
representative to the United States is Ambassador Hafiz Pashayev.  <br>
The Azerbaijani representative to the United Nations is Yashar <br>
Aliyev.<br>
________________________________________________________________<br>
<p>
MONTHLY CHRONOLOGY<br>
<p>
2 November: The Canadian A &amp; B Geoscience Corporation (ABGV) <br>
announces that its subsidiary Commonwealth Oil and Gas has signed <br>
an agreement with the Azerbaijani State Oil Company (SOCAR) for the <br>
joint development of an offshore oil field in the Caspian Sea.  The <br>
project is set to begin exploratory work on an offshore field <br>
estimated to hold 151 million barrels of oil equivalent (with a <br>
ratio of roughly 66 percent oil to 34 percent natural gas).  The <br>
Canadian firm has signed a production-sharing agreement with SOCAR <br>
and is expected to launch the first stages of the exploration by <br>
the end of the year.  This is the first significant Canadian <br>
involvement in the promising energy sector of Azerbaijan.<br>
<p>
4 November: Azerbaijani President Geidar Aliyev meets with Finnish <br>
Foreign Minister Tarja Halonen, visiting the region as part of a <br>
mediation mission under the auspices of the Organization for <br>
Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE).  The OSCE officials <br>
reports that President Aliyev has offered a status of the "highest <br>
autonomy" for Nagorno Karabagh and pledges that Azerbaijan is ready <br>
to formally reach a political agreement with Armenia and is seeking <br>
to resolve the long-standing Nagorno Karabagh conflict.<br>
<p>
4 November: Azerbaijani presidential advisor Vafa Guluzade departs <br>
for an undisclosed European city for secret talks with his Armenian <br>
counterpart Jirair Libaridian.  The two officials have been <br>
conducting secret diplomacy through these types of meetings over <br>
the past few years.  The talks center on the latest developments in <br>
the international mediation efforts underway for the Nagorno <br>
Karabagh conflict.<br>
<p>
5 November: The chairman of the Parliamentary Assembly of the OSCE, <br>
Xavier Ruperes, holds a series of meetings with Azerbaijani <br>
officials during a visit to Baku.  The OSCE official meets with the <br>
Azerbaijani president and foreign minister, and with <br>
representatives of the main opposition parties, the Azeri Popular <br>
Front and the National Independence Party.  Ruperes is briefed on <br>
the Azerbaijani government's position regarding the upcoming <br>
presidential elections in Nagorno Karabagh which it condemns as <br>
illegitimate and a provocation threatening the mediation process.<br>
<p>
8 November: Russia announces a shift in its official position on <br>
the Caspian Sea to allow for a communal agreement among the <br>
littoral states.  Specifically, the Russian government is <br>
advocating the formation of a new exclusive zone forty miles from <br>
each country's shore with resources beyond that limit being legally <br>
shared by all five countries bordering the Caspian.  Iran, <br>
Turkmenistan and Russia are seeking this interpretation while <br>
Azerbaijan, whose extensive offshore reserves are well beyond the <br>
forty mile limit, strongly opposes it and Kazakhstan, with reserves <br>
within the exclusive zone, wavering in its position.  This new <br>
Russian position was first revealed last month but Russian <br>
officials have now intensified their bid to legalize this position.<br>
<p>
9-10 November: Officials of the French oil company Elf-Equitaine <br>
hold talks with officials of the Azerbaijani State Oil Company <br>
SOCAR in Baku.  The meeting seeks to accelerate the negotiations <br>
over the development of the offshore Lenkoran-Deniz oil field along <br>
the Caspian Sea shelf.  The project, for the development of an <br>
estimated 50-60 million tons of oil, is expected to be formalized <br>
with the signing of an official production-sharing agreement during <br>
the visit of President Aliyev to France in the next few months.  <br>
The French company is already active in the development of <br>
Azerbaijan's offshore reserves with a substantial stake in the <br>
exploration of the Shah-Deniz oil and natural gas fields.  Another <br>
deal between SOCAR and a consortium of international oil companies <br>
is finalized for the development of the offshore Dan-Ulduzu and <br>
Ashrafi oil fields, said to hold some 100-120 million tons of oil <br>
and 30-50 billion cubic meters of natural gas to be extracted over <br>
a 25-30 year period.  This deal consists of a thirty percent share <br>
for the U.S. companies AMOCO and UNOCAL and for the Saudi Arabian <br>
Delta company.  The Japanese Itochu company and SOCAR each hold <br>
another twenty percent in the project, with the consortium <br>
reportedly providing the financing for the SOCAR share. <br>
<p>
11-13 November: The Commander of the Turkish ground forces, General <br>
Hikmet Heksal, holds a series of meetings and briefings with <br>
Azerbaijani military personnel in Baku.  During the meetings, the <br>
Turkish military official states that Turkey is committed to <br>
defending Azerbaijan militarily in the event of any outside attack <br>
or aggression posed against Azerbaijan, as stipulated in the <br>
bilateral military cooperation and security in effect between the <br>
two countries.  The Turkish military is planning to provide <br>
assistance through joint training exercises and drills.  This visit <br>
follows a meeting between a delegation from the Turkish military <br>
general staff with Azerbaijani Defense Minister Safar Abiyev late <br>
last month.<br>
<p>
12 November: Convening a summit in Turkmenistan to discuss the <br>
legal status and definition of the Caspian Sea, the foreign <br>
ministers of Azerbaijan, Russia, Iran, Kazakhstan and Turkmenistan <br>
reach a consensus whereby all five states bordering the Caspian <br>
resolve to sign an international convention on the Caspian shortly.  <br>
The meeting decides to form a special task force empowered to <br>
negotiate the final details and will meet in the Kazakh capital <br>
Almati next month.  During the meeting, the Russian, Iranian and <br>
Turkmen officials agree to expand cooperation in the exploration of <br>
the mineral and fishery resources of the Caspian.<br>
<p>
15 November: Azerbaijani opposition leader Nemat Panahov, the head <br>
of the National Statehood Party, is detained by security forces <br>
just prior to the start of a press conference in Baku.  The <br>
opposition leader is a former advisor and confidant of President <br>
Aliyev but resigned his post several months ago in protest of the <br>
government's "widespread corruption." <br>
<p>
17 November: According to Azerbaijani officials, Russian Security <br>
Council deputy secretary Boris Berezovsky has assured them that <br>
Russia will guarantee the safe passage of the early oil expected <br>
<i>&gt;from the multi-billion dollar offshore energy project..  The oil is </i><br>
to be transported by pipeline through Chechenya to the Russian port <br>
facility at Novorossiisk on the Black Sea.  The security of this <br>
Baku-Novorossiisk pipeline has been a primary concern to Azerbaijan <br>
and the consortium of Western oil companies.  The need to secure an <br>
effective and reliable route for the transport of the oil from <br>
Azerbaijan remains a fundamental challenge to the long term <br>
viability of all energy projects underway.  Russian first deputy <br>
minister for oil and power, Anatoly Shatalov, has also promised <br>
that this pipeline route would be readied for the shipments of <br>
Azerbaijani oil by next year.  The pipeline through Chechenya, in <br>
need of an estimated (pre-conflict) $55 million in repair and <br>
modernization, is to transport 32 million tons of initial oil over <br>
a seven-year period starting in August 1997. <br>
<p>
20 November: U.S. State Department official James Collins meets <br>
with officials of the Azerbaijani foreign ministry during a visit <br>
to Baku.  Ambassador Collins states that the U.S. regards the <br>
development of Azerbaijan's economy and its energy sector, with <br>
significant U.S. investment, as a strategic concern for Washington.  <br>
The settlement of the Nagorno Karabagh conflict is also seen by the <br>
U.S. as a prerequisite for the establishment of Azerbaijan's <br>
security, according to Ambassador Collins. <br>
<p>
22 November: Speaking to reporters following a visit to Iran and <br>
Azerbaijan, President Mintimer Shaimiyev of Tartarstan, an <br>
autonomous region within the Russian Federation, reviews the recent <br>
bilateral accords reached calling for cooperation in the <br>
development of industry and trade with Tartarstan.  Both Iranian <br>
and Azerbaijani officials are interested in establishing new <br>
commercial ventures with Tartarstan, prominent for the production <br>
of Kamaz cargo planes and heavy trucks.  Tartarstan also has a <br>
growing petrochemical sector which is attracting significant <br>
foreign investment.<br>
<p>
23 November: Demonstrators gather in Baku to protest the <br>
presidential election in Nagorno Karabagh. The demonstration, <br>
seemingly organized and encouraged by the Azerbaijani government, <br>
consists of several thousand Azerbaijani refugees forced from their <br>
homes due to the fighting in Nagorno Karabagh.  The refugees <br>
denounce the election as illegal and as "disrespectful of <br>
Azerbaijani sovereignty and territorial integrity."<br>
<p>
24 November: An opposition demonstration is held in Baku to protest <br>
corruption within the Aliyev government. During the demonstration, <br>
plain clothes Azerbaijani security forces break up the rally and <br>
forcibly disperse the protesters from Baku's Freedom Square.  An <br>
Azerbaijani reporter is beaten by the police units after <br>
interviewing an opposition organizer of the demonstration.  <br>
Witnesses also report that the security forces assaulted several <br>
dozen participants and questioned some of the organizers.<br>
<p>
____________________________________________________<br>
<p>
Republic of Nagorno Karabagh<br>
<p>
Total area:<br>
4,800 sq. km<br>
Slightly smaller than Delaware<br>
<p>
Bordering states:<br>
Azerbaijan<br>
<p>
Population:<br>
150,000<br>
31 persons/sq. km<br>
<p>
Ethnic composition:<br>
95% Armenian<br>
5% Assyrian, Greek,<br>
Kurdish, other<br>
<p>
-------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<p>
Leadership:  Robert Kocharian, President (elected December 22, <br>
1994);  Leonard Petrossian, Prime Minister;  Arkady Gukasyan, <br>
Foreign Minister;  Samvel Babayan, Defense Minister.<br>
<p>
Independence:  The Republic of Nagorno Karabagh was established on <br>
September 2, 1991 and declared its independence on January 6, 1992.<br>
<p>
CIS membership status:  Nagorno Karabagh is not a member of the <br>
CIS.<br>
<p>
Constitution:  The Parliament, which approved a temporary <br>
constitution in June 1992, had been working on drafting a <br>
constitution for the republic.  This task will now be assumed by <br>
the new parliament.<br>
<p>
Elections:  Parliamentary elections were held April 30, 1995 for a <br>
new 33-seat parliament.  Presidential elections are scheduled for <br>
November 22, 1996.<br>
<p>
Diplomatic representation:  Nagorno Karabagh's representative to <br>
the United States is Ardem Haroutunian.  Varoujan Krikorian is the <br>
representative of Nagorno Karabagh to the European Community and <br>
the European Parliament.<br>
<p>
-------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<p>
MONTHLY CHRONOLOGY<br>
<p>
1 November: The Nagorno Karabagh Central Electoral Committee <br>
announces that three candidates have been formally registered for <br>
the upcoming presidential election.  The three candidates, the <br>
current President Robert Kocharian, communist party leader Hrant <br>
Melkoumian, and parliamentarian Boris Aroushanian, have met the <br>
requirement for signed petitions supporting their candidacy.  The <br>
Central Electoral Committee chairman, Moushegh Ohanjanian, also <br>
announces that potential candidate Albert Ghazarian has been <br>
disqualified due to discrepancies in his petitions.<br>
<p>
4 November: President Robert Kocharian initiates his campaign for <br>
reelection with a tour of the Askeran, Marduni and Mardakert <br>
districts.  The president also meets with various units of the <br>
Nagorno Karabagh military and the faculty of Stepanakert <br>
University.  During the tour, Kocharian stresses his government's <br>
achievements, including the development of Karabagh's energy and <br>
communications sectors and the expansion of agriculture from six <br>
hectares of harvesting to the current level of over 40,000 <br>
cultivated hectares.  Kocharian promises to continue the policies <br>
of providing tax and credit benefits to collective and private <br>
farms in order to foster agricultural self-sufficiency, and to <br>
expand small- and medium-sized enterprises to provide more <br>
employment.<br>
<p>
11 November: International representatives of non-governmental <br>
organizations attend a conference on conflict settlement and <br>
preventive diplomacy in Stepanakert.  Participants include <br>
delegates from the Helsinki Citizen Assemblies of Ukraine, Georgia, <br>
Armenia, and the Netherlands, the International Committee of the <br>
Red Cross, and other European non-governmental organizations.  <br>
<p>
15 November: Articulating last month's reports of possible Central <br>
Asian participation in a settlement of the Nagorno Karabagh <br>
conflict, Kyrgyzstan's Foreign Minister Roza Obumbayeva states that <br>
troops from the Central Asian states may participate in the <br>
deployment of international peacekeepers, but only on the <br>
precondition that a peace treaty is signed between Armenia and <br>
Azerbaijan first.<br>
<p>
16 November: Negotiations over the exchange of prisoners of war <br>
held by Azerbaijani and Karabagh forces break down after failing to <br>
reach an agreement on details of the exchange.  The head of the <br>
Nagorno Karabagh State Committee for War Prisoners and Hostages, <br>
Alexander Agasarian, accuses the Azerbaijani side of delaying the <br>
talks until the conclusion of the recent mediation talks brokered <br>
by the international mediators of the Organization for Security and <br>
Cooperation in Europe (OSCE).<br>
<p>
17 November: The non-governmental organization Helsinki Initiative-<br>
92 announces its official endorsement for the candidacy of <br>
President Robert Kocharian in his bid for reelection.  Helsinki <br>
Initiative-92 coordinator Karen Ohanjanian cites Kocharian's <br>
contribution to state-building and the strengthening of democracy <br>
and the rule of law in Nagorno Karabagh.<br>
<p>
18 November: A new round of mediation talks are held in Helsinki <br>
under the auspices of the Finnish co-chair of the Organization for <br>
Security and Cooperation in Europe's (OSCE) working group on <br>
Karabagh.  The talks attempt to build on the initial progress made <br>
during the visit to Armenia and Azerbaijan by the Finnish foreign <br>
minister, Tarja Halonen.<br>
<p>
19 November: The Armenian Revolutionary Federation (ARF), the <br>
largest opposition party in Armenia and long active in the defense <br>
of Nagorno Karabagh, issues an endorsement of President Robert <br>
Kocharian calling on its members and supporters to vote for him in <br>
the upcoming presidential election.<br>
<p>
20 November: Nagorno Karabagh officials begin preparing their <br>
diplomatic and political position for the upcoming 54-nation summit <br>
of the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE).  <br>
Azerbaijan has announced that it will work toward a solution to the <br>
conflict through the OSCE mediation process but only from a <br>
position based on the international recognition of Azerbaijan's <br>
territorial integrity and sovereignty.  Baku seems determined to <br>
limit its concessions to greater autonomy for Nagorno Karabagh and <br>
resolutely dismisses Stepanakert's concerns for the security of its <br>
population and its defense of its right to self-determination. <br>
<p>
24 November: Nagorno Karabagh President Robert Kocharian is <br>
reelected to a five-year presidential term, garnering 86 percent of <br>
the vote while defeating two other candidates.  Parliamentarian <br>
Boris Aroushanian came in second with just under seven percent of <br>
the vote and Communist Party figure Hrant Melkoumian received 3.7 <br>
percent. The election enjoyed voter turnout of 78 percent of the <br>
electorate.  International election observers from the European <br>
Parliament, the Russian State Duma (the lower house of parliament) <br>
and other European countries report that the election was free and <br>
fair and was without any violations in election procedure.  <br>
President Kocharian was first elected to a two-year term in 1994 <br>
during Nagorno Karabagh's transition from a Soviet-style <br>
governmental structure to a presidential system.  The presidential <br>
election has been criticized by international organizations and <br>
countries attempting to mediate the Nagorno Karabagh conflict and <br>
has been sharply condemned by Azerbaijan.<br>
<p>
25 November: Armenian Minister of Justice Marat Alexanian meets <br>
with President Kocharian in Stepanakert.  The justice minister <br>
reviews a plan to provide Nagorno Karabagh with assistance in the <br>
development of the republic's legislation and criminal code.<br>
<p>
26 November: Speaking at a press conference in Stepanakert, <br>
Kocharian reports that the latest round of talks with Azerbaijan on <br>
the Karabagh conflict have ended in a stalemate.  The talks, <br>
serving as a preliminary round prior to next month's major summit <br>
of the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE), <br>
comprised Armenian presidential advisor Jirair Libaridian and his <br>
Azerbaijani counterpart Vafa Guluzade.<br>
<p>
<p>
****************************************************************<br>
<p>
*The E-mail version of the TransCaucasus: A Chronology differs from <br>
the   official printed version in two ways:  (1) text formatting <br>
and (2) the   printed version includes maps of the Transcaucasus <br>
countries.<br>
