<title>Groong Network: Osborn speaks at Zoryan Institute event</title>
<h1>Osborn speaks at Zoryan Institute event</h1>
<i>H.TCHILINGIRIAN@lse.ac.uk</i><br>
<i>Mon, 9 Dec 96 12:59:23 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#66">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#66">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#66">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#66">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0067.html">Richard Giragosian: "TransCaucasus: A Chronology -- December 1996 (fwd)"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0065.html">H.TCHILINGIRIAN@lse.ac.uk: "Fire Damages Church Property in Istanbul"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
     SIMON OSBORN SPEAKS AT ZORYAN INSTITUTE EVENT<br>
     <br>
     LONDON (7/12/96)--Organized by the Zoryan Institute, on December 6, a <br>
     public presentation on "Armenia: Transition to Democracy" was held at <br>
     the London School of Economics.  Simon Osborn, OSCE on site <br>
     coordinator of the International Election Observation Mission for the <br>
     Armenian Presidential Elections, and Razmik Panossian, a Ph.D. <br>
     Candidate at the London School of Economics, spoke about the recent <br>
     presidential elections in Armenia and the subsequent controversies <br>
     that followed. <br>
     <br>
     In her introduction, the moderator and member of the Board of <br>
     Directors of the Zoryan Institute, Dr. Susan Pattie said, "The new CIS <br>
     and former Eastern Block countries face problems particular to their <br>
     histories and current geo-political relationships. Developing <br>
     democracies there are better understood in this context rather than in <br>
     a rough shod comparison with how they measure up to those established <br>
     on other continents in other centuries.  However, if we are to use the <br>
     word `democracy' for all these cases, we need to have some basic point <br>
     of comparison.  Is democracy an ideal which will never be truly <br>
     achieved on earth, as a sort of political utopia, or have we in the <br>
     West accepted the version we know best as the true democracy? <br>
     Democracy is most powerful as an idea. However, it exists in our <br>
     world, not as concept, but as a living process, one which we should <br>
     all be striving to improve in the countries in which we live as well <br>
     as those farther away." <br>
     <br>
     The first speaker, Razmik Panossian spent four months in Armenia doing <br>
     research on Armenian nationalism and politics.  He presented an <br>
     overview of the election issues and provided an analysis of the <br>
     election campaign before September 22, using a video clip and other <br>
     visual material. He pointed out that the Armenian National Movement <br>
     (ANM) was taken by surprise by the sudden popularity of  the <br>
     opposition after several parties formed the `National Accord' block." <br>
     In his conclusion, reflecting on the direction Armenia is going as a <br>
     state, Panossian said,  "Neither authoritarian nor democratic, Armenia <br>
     is caught in the twilight zone. Armenia is an open society, people <br>
     could speak their mind, organize rallies, and publish anti-government <br>
     editorials in newspapers, etc. But when the government sees any <br>
     organized opposition as a  serious concern then it employs indirect <br>
     pressures to suppress the threat." Commenting on the opposition's <br>
     role, Panossian concluded, "I certainly do not expect the opposition <br>
     to remain quiet for the sake of national interest. Political stability <br>
     is very important, but is also a very dangerous slogan."<br>
     <br>
     Following Panossian's presentation, Simon Osborn explained the role of <br>
     the OSCE observers, who were invited by the Central Election <br>
     Commission of Armenia, and gave details about what the observers did <br>
     before, during, and after the election.  He then presented statistics <br>
     collected by the observers and pointed out that, generally, the voting <br>
     process was conducted "correctly and according to the election laws." <br>
     He noted that there were candidates' proxies at 93.3% of the precincts <br>
     and added that "The only questionable issue in the voting process was <br>
     the military vote".  However, "things went wrong during the counting <br>
     of the ballots", Osborn said. <br>
     <br>
     Reflecting on the final results, Osborn commented: "The real problem <br>
     for me came when I saw the official results of the elections that came <br>
     from the Central Election Commission. When I looked at these results <br>
     something was very striking: there was a discrepancy of 22,013 <br>
     coupons_  What happened?  I do not know the answer to this question. I <br>
     do not think anyone else knows either." He also questioned the numbers <br>
     cited by the opposition. "I must say that the opposition tends to <br>
     exaggerate too much."<br>
     <br>
     Osborn then went over the recommendations made by the OSCE team and <br>
     commented on the decision of the Constitutional Court. He said, <br>
     "Although many people in Yerevan and elsewhere in the world will not <br>
     be happy with what the Constitutional Court said, I do recognize that <br>
     the Court and, officially, the government who responded to my report <br>
     very positively, said they would look into the recommendation that <br>
     were made and that they would do a review of the process, particularly <br>
     in Yerevan."<br>
     <br>
     Osborn concluded his presentation commenting on the democratic process <br>
     in Armenia. "I think", he said,  "Armenia is on a transition to <br>
     democracy and it is going to take a long, long time. I know this does <br>
     not make everyone particularly happy. I know Armenians' real desire to <br>
     have democracy and the desire to have a say in the way their country <br>
     is growing.  Every little step that is made to improve the situation, <br>
     to try to make improvements to the law, within the administration and <br>
     the election process are important steps on the way to building <br>
     democratic structures in the country.  The Constitutional Court's <br>
     decision to address some of the problems is a positive step. This is <br>
     very important."<br>
     <br>
     The presentations were followed by questions from the audience and <br>
     responses from the two speakers.<br>
     <br>
     The Zoryan Institute is a non-profit, independent research center <br>
     based in Cambridge, Mass., devoted to the study of contemporary <br>
     Armenian issues in the context of regional and global changes. <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
