<!-- body="start" -->
HEADLINE: Restoration of the Banusha bridge would allow to deliver up to 20 K<br>
tons of goods with railways to Armenia. <br>
SOURCE:  Delovoi Mir, November 14, 1996<br>
<p>
Restoration of the Banusha bridge in Georgia would allow to resume delivery<br>
of goods with railways to Armenia. The bridge is a part of the railroad<br>
connecting Turkey with Iran. Realization of the project was made possible due<br>
to assistance provided by governments of several 6 countries including Great<br>
Britain ($0.3 mil of aid), Switzerland ($0.17 mil), Georgia ($0.15 mil), and<br>
USAID ($0.2 mil). Restoration works were accomplished by Mostostroj<br>
(Georgia). Last year near 13,900 railway trucks were delivered to Armenia<br>
with use of the bridge before reconstruction was started. Capacity of the<br>
railroad after bridge restoration would allow delivery of up to 20 K tons of<br>
cargo daily. A significant attention is provided by international<br>
organizations to development of transport infrastructure in the region. World<br>
Bank is expected to spend $50 mil for reconstruction of automobile roads<br>
connecting sea ports in Georgia with Erevan, Armenia. <br>
<p>
HEADLINE:  Sapfir (Armenia) continues to support business relations with<br>
Russian partners in spite of a payment problem. <br>
SOURCE:  Izvestiia, November 10, 1996<br>
<p>
Sapfir (Sapphire) (Armenia) continues to support business relations with<br>
Russian partners in spite of certain problems created by customs regulation<br>
and payment problem. Russian diamonds were polished by Sapfir with a total<br>
value of $16 mil over the 1993-1994 period. Jewelry diamonds were sent back<br>
to Almazyuvelireksport (Moscow, Russia), a jewelry export/import enterprise,<br>
for a total sum of $11 mil. Diamonds for $5.1 mil are kept in Armenia because<br>
Sapfir still has not received $1.2 mil as a payment for polishing the<br>
diamonds. A delay with payment for delivered products is a common problem<br>
making financial situation at Sapfir very difficult. Debts of Russian<br>
consumers increased now to near $400 K. Nevertheless Sapfir continues to<br>
supply the Vtoroj Moskovskij Chasovoj Zavod (Moscow, Russia), a watch making<br>
enterprise in Moscow and the Zavod Tochmasha (Vladimir, Russia), a precise<br>
machinery enterprise. <br>
<p>
HEADLINE:  Armenian-USA company was created to determine presence of oil<br>
fields in Armenia. <br>
SOURCE:  Delovoi Mir, November 5, 1996<br>
<p>
Armenian-USA geological and prospecting company was created to determine<br>
presence of oil fields in Armenia. The company has intention to drill 3 wells<br>
in areas close to Erevan and to accomplish seismic studies of the region over<br>
the next 5 years. Near $10 mil will be spent for this purpose by the US side<br>
at the first stage. Future of the project depends on results to be obtained.<br>
If oil is found then the project will be continued. The previous study of the<br>
region was accomplished by the SPT consortium (UK) in cooperation with<br>
Parteko (Portugal). According to some experts, near 35 mil tons of oil and 80<br>
bil cubic meters of gas could be produced in Armenia.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
