        PRESS SECRETARY OF THE ARMENIAN PRESIDENT ON THE OSCE SUMMIT<br>
        IN LISBON<br>
<p>
 YEREVAN, DECEMBER 6, ARMENPRESS.<br>
 Yesterday, the Acting Press Secretary of the President of the<br>
 Republic of Armenia Levon Zurabian held a press conference to<br>
 announce the official Armenian position on the Nagorno-Karabagh issue<br>
 after the Lisbon Summit of OSCE.<br>
 No decision was passed in Lisbon due to Azerbaijan's behavior, and<br>
 that only complicated the course of negotiations.<br>
 As was reported earlier, Azerbaijan tried to force its point of view,<br>
 according to which the Nagorno-Karabagh conflict should be resolved<br>
 based on the principle of preservation of Azerbaijan's territorial<br>
 integrity. If this point of view was not accepted, Azerbaijan<br>
 threatened to veto the entire final document of the Summit in Lisbon.<br>
 Mr. Zurabian condemned such behavior, and said that it set a<br>
 dangerous precedent, when one country can practically take hostage<br>
 the entire results of work of so many different countries.<br>
 Mr. Zurabian stated the reasons why the Armenian side did not allow<br>
 to accept the suggestion of the Minsk Croup Co-Chairmen, which was<br>
 put forward to reach a concensus, despite the fact that this<br>
 suggestion contained the principle of self-determination and the need<br>
 for guaranteeing the security of people of Nagorny Karabagh.<br>
 They are as follows:<br>
 1. The Minsk Group was authorized to negotiate the elements of the<br>
 political agreement, but in reality discussed neither the Karabagh's<br>
 status, nor its elements.<br>
 2. The 1994 OSCE Summit in Budapest passed a decision, according to<br>
 which the direct dialogue is pointed out as the forum, where the<br>
 status and its elements must be discussed. However, this dialogue is<br>
 not over yet.<br>
 3. Such a wording preconditions the outcome of the Minsk conference.<br>
 But according to the 1992 decision of the Meeting of the OSCE<br>
 Ministers, the status of Nagorny Karabagh must be defined by the<br>
 Minsk conference.<br>
 Mr. Zurabian said that it will be more difficult to find compromises<br>
 in the negotiations, since the mutual trust atmosphere has been<br>
 broken. However, Mr. Zurabian said that he does not think that the<br>
 negotiations have not reached the deadlock.<br>
 Mr. Zurabian refuted the statements published in Turkish and Azeri<br>
 press that the Armenian diplomacy was defeated in Lisbon.<br>
<p>
        DELEGATION OF THE NATIONAL ASSEMBLY OF THE REPUBLIC OF ARMENIA<br>
        VISITS INDIA<br>
<p>
 YEREVAN, DECEMBER 6, ARMENPRESS.<br>
 On December 4 the delegation of the National Assembly of the Republic<br>
 of Armenia headed by the President of the National Assembly Babken<br>
 Ararktsian arrived in Delhi.<br>
 The Armenian delegation was received by the Prime Minister of India<br>
 Devi Gouda. The Prime Minister said that India is interested in<br>
 developing political, economic, and cultural ties with Armenia.<br>
 During the meeting the sides also discussed the issue of opening<br>
 Embassies of the two countries.<br>
 Then, the delegation met with the Minister of Tourism Srikant Jenai.<br>
 During the meeting the sides discussed the further development of<br>
 trade and tourism between Armenia and India.<br>
 Later on the Armenian delegation was received by the Vice President<br>
 of India Mr. Narayana. During the meeting the sides discussed various<br>
 issues of mutual interest, in particular, the possibilities of the<br>
 Armenia-Iran_India economic cooperation.<br>
 At the end of the visit the Armenian delegation was received by the<br>
 President of India Shankar Dajal Sharma. The President expressed his<br>
 preparedness to continue the implementation of the cooperation<br>
 agreement signed last year by the Presidents of Armenia and India.<br>
<p>
        THE CONSTITUTIONAL COURT REESTABLISHES THE CONFIDENCE IN THE<br>
        PRESIDENTIAL ELECTIONS, WHILE THE OPPOSITION IS DEFEATED<br>
<p>
 YEREVAN, DECEMBER 6, ARMENPRESS.<br>
 On November 22, the Constitutional Court of the Republic of Armenia<br>
 completed the hearing of the case about the results of the September<br>
 22 presidential elections in Armenia.<br>
 The Constitutional Court carefully studied all the materials in the<br>
 case. It checked 162 polling stations, including all the voting boxes<br>
 and the documents of all the polling stations pointed out by the<br>
 opposition. In fact, all the polling stations about which the<br>
 opposition had any doubts and complaints were checked.<br>
 An insiginficant discrepancy with the data of the Central Electoral<br>
 Commission, CEC, has been found. In 110 cases the numbers found fully<br>
 coincided with the numbers of the CEC, in 41 cases there was 3-5<br>
 votes difference, and in other cases there were some irregularities,<br>
 which were reflected in the Constitutional Court's decision.<br>
 During the hearing in the Constitutional Court, all the reports from<br>
 precincts, submitted by the opposition (1035 in total) were<br>
 compared with the reports of the CEC. During the comparison, it<br>
 became clear that there are some partial discrepancy in the reports<br>
 of only 9 precincts.<br>
 The CEC was asked to submit its data based on the reports of all the<br>
 930 districts and 1155 precincts (including 303 precincts in<br>
 Yerevan). Taking into consideration the fact that most districts<br>
 consist of one precinct, it turns out that out of 1598 precincts, the<br>
 Constitutional Court didn't check about 70 precincts, about which the<br>
 opposition didn't submit any complaints.<br>
 When checking the Yerevan marz and precinct reports, it turned out<br>
 that in reality the big numbers 21701 (difference between the<br>
 participants and the counterfoils) and 21128 (difference between the<br>
 number of participants and the bulletins), which were reflected in<br>
 the OSCE report, were a mere mistake made by the Yerevan marz<br>
 commission. The recalculation showed that these numbers in reality<br>
 are 919 and 1114.<br>
 During the hearing it turned out that the opposition has never<br>
 applied to any courts with any complaints about the elections, and<br>
 out of the 15 thousand people who worked as proxies of the opposition<br>
 candidate, only about 3 percent submited complaints about the process<br>
 of elections.<br>
<p>
        VISIT OF THE PRIME MINISTER OF THE REPUBLIC OF ARMENIA ARMEN<br>
        SARGISSIAN TO GREAT BRITAIN<br>
<p>
 YEREVAN, DECEMBER 6, ARMENPRESS.<br>
 The Prime Minister of the Republic of Armenia Armen Sargissian is now<br>
 on an official visit to Great Britain.<br>
 Yesterday, Mr. Sargissian met with the Minister of Foreign Affairs of<br>
 Great Britain Sir Nicolas Bonser. During the meeting the Armenian<br>
 Prime Minister breifly described the present socio-political<br>
 situation in Armenia, and talked about the future plans of the<br>
 Armenian Government. The sides also discussed the results of the<br>
 Lisbon Summit of the OSCE, and the present state of Armenian-British<br>
 relations.<br>
 On the same day, Prime Minister Sargissian met with the British<br>
 Minister of Trade and Manufacturing Anthony Nelson. Mr. Sargissian<br>
 briefly described the privatization process in Armenia, the reforms<br>
 in the banking system of the country, and other economic reforms.<br>
 During the meeting the sides discussed the possibilities of<br>
 Armenian-British economic cooperation.<br>
 Today, the Prime Minister is scheduled to meet with the President of<br>
 the European Bank of Reconstruction and Development.<br>
 Mr. Sargissian will also be received by Her Majesty Elizabeth II.<br>
<p>
        "HAYASTAN" ALL ARMENIAN FUND URGES ARMENIANS AROUND THE WORLD<br>
        TO HELP FINISH THE RECONSTRUCTION OF THE EARTHQUAKE ZONE<br>
<p>
 YEREVAN, DECEMBER 6, ARMENPRESS.<br>
 The Administration of the "Hayastan" All-Armenian Fund has sent an<br>
 open letter to the Armenian Diaspora on the occasion of the 8th<br>
 anniversary of the Spitak earthquake. In this letter it is written,<br>
 in particular, that according to some information, in the United<br>
 States alone about 40 million US dollars have been raised as<br>
 for the earthquake zone reconstruction. However, most of this sum has<br>
 not reached its destination yet. The Administration of the Fund urged<br>
 the Armenians abroad to continue their humanitarian efforts to help<br>
 overcome the tragic consequences of the earthquake.<br>
 It is also mentioned that since 1992 the Fund has allocated 3 million<br>
 815 thousand US dollars for the reconstruction of the earthquake<br>
 zone. This money was used to built 43 apartment buildings, 24 houses,<br>
 9 schools and other educational institutions, and 1 medical<br>
 institution. However, there is still a lot to be done in this area,<br>
 and the help of Armenians around the world would be greatly<br>
 appreciated.<br>
