<!-- body="start" -->
Headlines of stories which follow:<br>
<p>
1.  Parliament defers decision on 1997 budget until February <br>
2.  Constitutional Court recommends adoption of Russian military agreement<br>
3.  Armenia Ready to Discuss Karabakh Settlement - Minister   <br>
4.  Foreign Ministry Press Briefing<br>
5.  Yeltsin urges closer CIS integration <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Parliament defers decision on 1997 budget until February <br>
SOURCE: RIA news agency, Moscow, in English 1247 gmt 5 Dec 96 <br>
<p>
The third session of Armenia's National Assembly has wound up in Yerevan with<br>
the passing of a government report on the performance of the 1996 budget -<br>
its deficit amounts to 31m drams. <br>
<p>
Hearings on the 1997 draft budget have been postponed until next January<br>
because of a new government being in the making and the need to amend the<br>
budget draft. The parliamentary vacations will last until early February<br>
1997. <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Constitutional Court recommends adoption of Russian military<br>
agreement <br>
SOURCE: Russian Public TV, Moscow, in Russian 0600 gmt 6 Dec 96 <br>
<p>
[Presenter] The Armenian Constitutional Court has considered the presence of<br>
the Russian military base on its territory in light of the requirements of<br>
the country's constitution. <br>
<p>
[Correspondent] Armenia was one of the first members of the CIS to support<br>
the presence of the Russian armed forces on its territory.   In March 1995,<br>
the bilateral agreement on this issue acquired the status of an interstate<br>
treaty with a 25-year life span and the possibility of further extension. <br>
<p>
The Russian military base in Armenia is a reality. Men are serving there,<br>
exercises are taking place, including joint exercises with the republic's<br>
national army. However, all of this is not quite legal. Both the Armenian<br>
parliament and the Russian State Duma have yet to ratify the treaty signed in<br>
Moscow 18 months ago by the presidents of the two countries. This was the<br>
reason for [Armenian President] Levon Ter-Petrosyan's application to the<br>
republic's Constitutional Court. <br>
<p>
After considering all six intergovernmental treaties connected with the<br>
presence of Russian troops in Armenia, the court declared that they did not<br>
contravene the constitution and recommended that the Armenian National<br>
Assembly ratify the treaty. <br>
<p>
HEADLINE:  Armenia Ready to Discuss Karabakh Settlement - Minister <br>
SOURCE:  TASS December 6, 1996 (by Dicran Liloian, Yerevan)<br>
<p>
"Armenia is ready to continue negotiations on all aspects of the karabakh<br>
settlement," Armenian Foreign Minister Alexander Arzumanyan told foreign<br>
ambassadors in Yerevan on Friday. <br>
<p>
The minister told the ambassadors about Armenia's opinion of results of the<br>
OSCE Lisbon summit.  "There is the impression Azerbaijan is not ready to<br>
continue the negotiations" on Karabakh settlement, he said. <br>
<p>
The Minister lamented that the OSCE leader's proposals on the Karabakh<br>
settlement principles are actually proposals of the Azerbaijani delegation<br>
and cannot be accepted by Armenia. <br>
 <br>
HEADLINE: Foreign Ministry Press Briefing<br>
SOURCE: Official Kremlin Int'l News Broadcast, December 5, 1996<br>
 <br>
Andreyev: Good day, to preempt questions I will introduce myself. The more so<br>
that I appear here quite rarely. I am Vladimir Vadimovich Andreyev, I am head<br>
of the department of prompt information at the Information and Press<br>
Directorate of the Foreign Ministry. I am appearing here as an official<br>
spokesman of the Ministry. <br>
<p>
I will begin, as always, with materials that we have prepared for you on our<br>
own initiative. The first, naturally, concerns the Lisbon meeting of heads of<br>
state and government of OSCE member countries. <br>
<p>
The meeting of heads of state and government of OSCE member countries was<br>
held in Lisbon on December 2 and 3. The message of greetings sent by<br>
President Boris Nikolayevich Yeltsin to the leaders of more than 50 countries<br>
of Europe, Asia and North America who took part in the meeting stresses that<br>
Europe is on the threshold of crucial decisions. We should not allow a new<br>
division of our continent, the message says, the role of the OSCE in this<br>
context is invaluable. The assets of the OSCE include the detailed discussion<br>
of the model of European security in the 21st century, the universally<br>
recognized contribution to Bosnian affairs, to the settlement of a number of<br>
other regional conflicts. The OSCE also has a big field of activity in<br>
ensuring human rights and the rights of minorities, in particular, the<br>
Russian-speaking population. These ideas were spelled out in greater detail<br>
in the speech by Viktor Stepanovich Chernomyrdin, who headed the Russian<br>
delegation in Lisbon.  The main result of the summit is that our ideas of<br>
creating a new model of European security are getting growing support. The<br>
summit adopted as its main document a detailed declaration on the model of a<br>
general and comprehensive security for Europe of the 21st century. The<br>
provisions that are of great importance to us include the provisions on the<br>
impermissibility of attempts to strengthen one's own security at the expense<br>
of the security of others, on the cooperation of various international<br>
organizations and institutions in the strengthening of the OSCE. <br>
<p>
The declaration singles out the agreement on the working out in the future of<br>
a European security charter of comparable importance with the Helsinki Final<br>
Act. Another important result of the Lisbon meeting is the adoption of a<br>
document on the renewal of the treaty on conventional armed forces in Europe.<br>
Talks on this subject will begin already in January 1997. This makes it<br>
possible to press for material guarantees of ensuring our security, including<br>
by way of further limitations on the military possibilities of NATO. <br>
<p>
It is of fundamental importance that along with the decision on the<br>
adjustment of the treaty we secured an obligation of member states to show<br>
restraint in respect of their military efforts, including the present levels<br>
of armaments and deployment. <br>
<p>
Other documents were also adopted. They strengthened the role of arms control<br>
as an important instrument of ensuring stability in Europe. They make it<br>
possible to use the all-Europe format to identify and consider future<br>
confidence-building measures and military security that cause concern here. <br>
<p>
Given the important role played by the OSCE in the settlement of a number of<br>
regional conflicts, this was one of the main topics at the summit. On the<br>
whole, the preparation of the summit and its work showed that the fight for<br>
advancing the European idea is growing more fierce. Further implementation of<br>
this idea will encounter considerable difficulties connected with the desire<br>
of a number of countries to transform NATO into the axis of a future security<br>
system. <br>
<p>
The results of the Lisbon meeting are controversial, however, their general<br>
balance, including with regard to disarmament, is in favor of Russia. Despite<br>
everything, our vision of Europe of the 21st century -- at the core of which<br>
is a charter -- is making its way and we believe that the best instrument to<br>
continue this work would be the OSCE, where all countries have the same<br>
status and where the rule of consensus applies. This allows Russia to<br>
adequately reflect our interests in relevant documents and decisions. The<br>
Nagorno-Karabakh issue at the Lisbon summit. Unfortunately, the Lisbon summit<br>
revealed a serious gap in positions between Armenia and Azerbaijan on the<br>
provision concerning Nagorno-Karabakh in the summit final declaration. This<br>
endangered the adoption of the declaration itself. <br>
<p>
However, a consensus was reached and the declaration was approved after the<br>
issue had been discussed at the plenary meeting of the heads of state and<br>
government. <br>
<p>
Provision 20 on Nagorno-Karabakh was left outside the document. It was<br>
replaced with a statement by the OSCE chairman in office, Swiss Foreign<br>
Minister Flavio Cotti, which outlined the main principles of conflict<br>
settlement in Nagorno-Karabakh. The statement will be included in the Lisbon<br>
summit documents. Russia agrees with the statement as was confirmed by Prime<br>
Minister Viktor Stepanovich Chernomyrdin, who represented Russia at the<br>
Lisbon summit. We believe that these principles will make it possible to<br>
continue to work for the settlement of the conflict. <br>
<p>
This crisis is of special importance to Russia. We are not indifferent to it,<br>
considering our interest in stability in the Transcaucasus and the<br>
peacekeeping efforts that we have been taking there through shuttle<br>
diplomacy, as well as within the framework of the OSCE Minsk Group. <br>
<p>
Practically all delegations of the OSCE called for a speedy settlement of the<br>
situation and we hope that the leadership of both Armenia and Azerbaijan will<br>
use this opportunity to continue talks on the settlement of the conflict<br>
based on the views of the OSCE leaders. <br>
<p>
[REMAINING PORTION OF ARTICLE REMOVED]<br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Yeltsin urges closer CIS integration <br>
SOURCE: 'Trud' newspaper, Moscow, in Russian 6-13 Dec 96 <br>
<p>
President Yeltsin has called for speedier and closer integration of CIS<br>
member states. Interviewed on the eve of the fifth anniversary of the CIS, he<br>
said that the community of Russia and Belarus was an example of "the real<br>
results" of such integration. Yeltsin praised military cooperation within the<br>
CIS, saying that it was aimed at stability and conflict prevention. He<br>
reaffirmed his opposition to NATO enlargement and said that it would "harm<br>
Europe" . The following is the text of Yeltsin's interview published in the<br>
'Trud' newspaper; subheadings have been inserted editorially: <br>
<p>
No alternative to CIS <br>
<p>
[Interviewer] Boris Nikolayevich, the opposition continues to accuse you of<br>
breaking up the USSR. This is one of its main themes. What would you reply to<br>
your opponents today, five years after the creation of the CIS? <br>
<p>
[Yeltsin] It would not be out of place to ask this question too: what would<br>
have happened if we had all remained in the state in which we were during the<br>
last months of the union's existence? You will recall how things stood in the<br>
economy and in other spheres of life. <br>
<p>
By December 1991, the break-up of the former union had assumed the nature of<br>
a landslide. This was very dangerous. However hard it might be to admit it,<br>
the union had outlived itself. We had to save what could still be saved. The<br>
Commonwealth of Independent States - sovereign countries enjoying equal<br>
rights - was created. Each one assumed responsibility for its own affairs. <br>
<p>
At that time, the idea of the CIS was the only one on whose basis it was<br>
possible to reach agreement among the former republics, with the exception of<br>
the Baltic republics. I will repeat: five years ago no-one proposed a<br>
different model of our cooperation. <br>
<p>
Of course, there are quite a few problems in the commonwealth. There was a<br>
lot of criticism, frequently fair criticism. I too believe that integration<br>
within our commonwealth could have proceeded more quickly and effectively. I<br>
want to be understood correctly - I never advocated dragging anyone towards<br>
unification by force. No. I am speaking about something quite different - the<br>
development of mutually advantageous relations and joint work, above all in<br>
production, trade, and so forth. There is a tremendous field of activity<br>
here. <br>
<p>
The chief resource is here. But not everything here depends on Russia alone.<br>
We are patiently seeking a balance of interests. <br>
<p>
The CIS has withstood the tests of the most difficult period - that of its<br>
formation. <br>
<p>
The CIS countries took the decision to come closer together freely, of their<br>
own will, without pressure or coercion, because they realized that this was<br>
in their interests. <br>
<p>
I will emphasize that I am talking of cooperation among our countries on an<br>
equal and mutually advantageous basis. There is no alternative to this today,<br>
nor will there be one tomorrow. <br>
<p>
Therefore, I will say this: the CIS is not a return to the past and is not a<br>
truncated version of the former union. This will not be the case. Relations<br>
among our countries will be the way the peoples of the commonwealth want to<br>
see them. We will take into the future everything that has proved valuable<br>
and useful. <br>
<p>
Prospects for closer CIS integration <br>
<p>
[Q] How do you rate the effectiveness of the integration processes within the<br>
CIS? Do you agree with the claim that they are in many ways inferior to the<br>
similar processes in the European Union? What do you see as the reasons for<br>
this lag? <br>
<p>
[A] It is hardly possible to compare the progress of integration in the CIS<br>
and the EU. Our states and the peoples'destinies are too different.<br>
Integration in the EU began several decades ago, virtually from a blank<br>
sheet. The CIS has arisen in the place of a former centralized state. In some<br>
respects integration is proceeding more simply in our case, while in others -<br>
in a more complex way. <br>
<p>
Our cooperation has developed in the course of negotiations, and we have<br>
found the correct tone for relations. At first, even this was not easy.<br>
Solutions have been found to quite a large number of economic and social<br>
problems. The legal treaty base of the CIS has been created, and the<br>
commonwealth's structures are functioning. But today, all of this is no<br>
longer enough. <br>
<p>
I well know the mood of people in our states. They assess integration not by<br>
the number of agreements or joint organizations. The main thing for our<br>
citizens is how integration affects their everyday life and changes it for<br>
the better. I believe that this link can be seen most clearly in the example<br>
of Russia and Belarus. Borders and customs barriers have been removed within<br>
the community of our countries, and people have been afforded equal<br>
opportunities in finding employment, in education, in obtaining medical<br>
services and in acquiring property. Russia and Belarus will have a single<br>
fuel and energy balance. These are the real results of integration. <br>
<p>
Although it cannot be said that our customs officers and border guards do not<br>
have a number of serious questions to put to their Belarusian colleagues.<br>
They must be resolved as quickly as possible. <br>
<p>
On the whole, I look to the future of our commonwealth with optimism. It took<br>
Europe decades to achieve the present level of unification. It will<br>
undoubtedly take us less time. I am convinced of this. <br>
<p>
[Q] Do you think it possible that a closer integration process will spread<br>
within the CIS and that other CIS members will join the treaty of "the four"<br>
before the year 2000? <br>
<p>
[A] Let us not be in a hurry. The treaties of "the two" (between Russia and<br>
Belarus) and "the four" (between Russia, Belarus, Kazakhstan, and Kyrgyzstan)<br>
were signed this year. I have already spoken of the community of Russia and<br>
Belarus. I would now like to point to the special significance of the treaty<br>
of "the four." Interesting cooperation projects are being drawn up among "the<br>
four." These too will soon manifest themselves in practice. If we work well<br>
and the specific benefit of integration becomes obvious, the states and<br>
peoples will draw their own conclusions. Both treaties are open to other CIS<br>
members to join them. <br>
<p>
CIS military cooperation aimed at peace, NATO enlargement to harm Europe <br>
<p>
[Q] Many fears are being expressed in the West in connection with the now<br>
apparent coordination of efforts among the CIS member states in the military<br>
sphere. Is so much really being done here, and is this not affecting the<br>
resolution of the question of NATO's eastward advance? <br>
<p>
[A] As is known, the majority of the commonwealth states joined the<br>
collective security treaty and the collective security concept, and a number<br>
of other documents on deepening military cooperation have been signed. Our<br>
border guards, air-defence services and others cooperate. <br>
<p>
Does the commonwealth need this? I believe that this is necessary and vital.<br>
Above all, in order to ensure the stability and security of the commonwealth<br>
states, to settle conflicts and to prevent new ones. Progress has been made<br>
here, appreciable progress. The armed confrontation in Nagornyy Karabakh, the<br>
Dnestr region, South Osetia and Abkhazia has been halted. The situation in<br>
Tajikistan remains complex, but here too, I am convinced, a peaceful solution<br>
will be found through joint efforts. <br>
<p>
Of course, the development of military cooperation within the CIS has nothing<br>
to do with the plans for NATO expansion. In the commonwealth, everything in<br>
this sphere is organized differently from NATO. I disapprove to the plans for<br>
NATO expansion. I believe that it will harm Europe. I hope that common sense<br>
will still prevail. <br>
<p>
I wish to emphasize that integration for us is a matter of life. We want<br>
closer ties and the restoration of mutually advantageous ties on a new basis<br>
so that a person in Russia or in any other CIS state leads a life that is<br>
calm and well-provided for, and so that contacts among people are as simple<br>
and natural as they have been for centuries. For our countries and peoples<br>
this is normal and necessary . I am sure that our commonwealth will only<br>
benefit from this. <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
