<!-- body="start" -->
1. NeGA [etatist]. Georgia-Abkhazia (Comments on the meeting between Russian<br>
and Georgian Foreign Ministers)<br>
<p>
2. Segodnya [liberal]. Comments on Clinton's new appointments<br>
<p>
3. Zavtra [nationalist]. Miscellania<br>
<p>
******************************************************************<br>
<p>
Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA in Russian 7 Dec 96 p 3<br>
<p>
<p>
   [Report by Mekhman Gafarly:  "Foreign Ministers' Meeting. Spotlight on<br>
Abkhaz Problem"]<br>
<p>
   A meeting was held in the Russian Federation Ministry of Foreign Affairs<br>
yesterday of Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeniy Primakov and the head of the<br>
Georgian foreign political department Irakliy Menagarishvili.  As transpires<br>
from yesterday's press conference of the two ministers held upon the<br>
completion of their behind-closed-doors conversation, this meeting aroused<br>
great interests of journalists.  The Russia-Georgia relations have piled up<br>
many problems the solution of which would require painstaking work.  Among<br>
the questions which arose media interest are those of the Georgia-Abkhazia<br>
conflict, Russia's mediatory role in its settlement, and the Black Sea Fleet<br>
division dispute.  The Georgian and Russian delegations also focussed, of<br>
course, on the questions of settlement of conflicts in the Caucasus region,<br>
including Chechnya, and the presence of Russian military bases in Georgia.<br>
However, both diplomats were reserved in their statements which is rather<br>
natural when discussing the solution of questions which prove to be a<br>
stumbling block in relations between two neighboring states.<br>
   The narrowing of the gap between the positions of Moscow and Tbilisi on<br>
the Abkhaz question is causing clear irritation in Sukhumi.  Sukhumi does<br>
not like of late many things about Russia's stance on the settlement of the<br>
Georgia-Abkhazia conflict, which is primarily attributed to the fact that<br>
Moscow already firmly speaks from the position of preserving the territorial<br>
integrity of states.  Therefore, the Abkhaz authorities have decided to rely<br>
on help from international organizations, including the UN.  For example,<br>
shortly before the Russian-Georgian meeting, the self-proclaimed Republic of<br>
Abkhazia demanded that the UN Security Council should "use its influence<br>
with the Georgian side and take the necessary measures to prevent the<br>
expansion and spread of terrorism."  The statement notes that the Abkhaz<br>
Ministry of Foreign Affairs has facts confirming that Georgia's special<br>
services train bandit groups, infiltrates them into the territory of<br>
Abkhazia and plans wrecking and terrorist operations.<br>
    The fact that the Abkhaz authorities turned, on the eve of the meeting,<br>
to the UN Security Council rather than to the participants in the Moscow<br>
meeting indicates that Sukhumi has actually lost an ally in the shape of<br>
Moscow in solving the Georgia-Abkhazia conflict.  However, such a move may<br>
harm relations between Abkhazia and Russia.  Especially because Tbilisi has<br>
a means to pressure Moscow -- the existence of Russian military bases on the<br>
territory of Georgia categorically objected to by the local opposition.  One<br>
can therefore confidently say that henceforth all compromises reached<br>
between diplomats of Russia and Georgia will not be in favor of Abkhazia.<br>
<p>
&lt;=3D&gt;<br>
 Moscow SEGODNYA in Russian 7 Dec 96 p 1<br>
<p>
<p>
 [Report by Vladimir Abarinov:  "All the President's Men"]<br>
<p>
      The appointment of Madeleine Albright as U.S. secretary of state<br>
creates colossal problems for Moscow which the Russian Foreign Ministry is<br>
simply not ready to handle.  In the Carter administration, Albright was<br>
schooled by Zbegniew Brzezinski, a convinced and consistent fighter against<br>
Communist expansion and Soviet imperialism.  Naturalized Americans,<br>
especially from Eastern Europe, stand out in their rare intolerance of the<br>
slightest manifestations of anti-Americanism, and are extremely sensitive to<br>
any attempts at dictate by Moscow with respect to its former satellites.<br>
Madeleine Albright's unstoppable political temperament, her uncompromising<br>
nature, and her ability to get things done on her terms are widely known.<br>
She never retreats from the positions gained, moving toward her goal firmly,<br>
ingeniously, and assertively.   =20<br>
 There are plenty of examples. =FF20It is enough to recall the sad fate of<br>
Boutros-Ghali.  Moscow for some reason hoped that the United States would<br>
not exercise its power of veto out of the fear of finding itself in<br>
isolation.  The result is well-known:  Washington's lone but decisive vote<br>
forced the general secretary to withdraw his candidacy.  Now Russia should<br>
live up to its promise and block any other aspirant.  Quite obviously it<br>
will not do this -- out of the same fear of isolation that it ascribes the<br>
Americans.  Clinton has warned more than just once:  America will act<br>
together with other countries when this is possible, and will go it alone<br>
when this is necessary for it.=20<br>
 Albright stopped, just as firmly, the attempts to lift the oil embargo on<br>
Iraq, not at all afraid of pitting Washington against Moscow or Paris<br>
against Beijing.  True, there was a moment when the United States was<br>
clearly faced with the danger of not getting enough votes on Iraq.  Albright<br>
made a hasty tour of the countries non-permanent members of the Security<br>
Council, stating at every opportunity that the United States will not let<br>
pass the resolution under any circumstances.  The sanctions remained in<br>
force:  The non-permanent members did not dare to be isolated from America.=<br>
=20<br>
 It noteworthy that under U.S. laws, the secretary of state comes fourth on<br>
the list of officials replacing the president in the event of his<br>
incapacitation, i.e., is the third ranking figure in the administration<br>
after the president and vice president.=20<br>
 Through the appointment of Albright, William Cohen (defense secretary),<br>
Anthony Lake (director of the CIA), and Samuel Berger (national security<br>
adviser) Clinton has forcefully demonstrated how America envisions its place<br>
in the modern world.  These are not simply professionals who have risen to<br>
the upper echelons of power, and not even simply like-minded persons.  This<br>
is indeed a single team in which there is not even a hint at the notorious<br>
"system of checks and balances" for which our internal politics commentators<br>
give Yeltsin a special credit.  Lake served in the Nixon administration<br>
under Henry Kissinger and in the Carter administration under Syrus Vans.<br>
Berger also worked in the Vans' department.  It was Berger who recommended<br>
Lake to Clinton for the post of national security adviser.  Albright, as<br>
said earlier, worked under Carter in the National Security Council.  Cohen,<br>
as congressman and senator, has gained a reputation as an independent,<br>
although he was formally a Republican.  He was one of those Republican<br>
congressmen who voted, in 1974, for the impeachment of the Republican<br>
president.  Under Reagan, as one of the influential members of the armed<br>
forces and intelligence committees, he consistently advocated the building<br>
up of the U.S. might, strongly arguing that this was vital for America at<br>
the end of the Cold War.  In 1970 Lake resigned in protest against the U.S.<br>
invasion of Cambodia.  He threatened resignation to Clinton after the death<br>
of 18 U.S. military servicemen in Somalia -- as is known, in the end the<br>
U.S. troops were pulled out of there.=20<br>
 Such is the team: tough customers.  All this is a direct opposite to the<br>
deplorable Russian circumstances.  Our Foreign Ministry with its euphoria<br>
over the apparent successes in Lisbon will find it not simply difficult:  It<br>
will end up sidelined in international politics.  This inexorable trend is<br>
demonstrated by the absence at the OSCE summit not only of Clinton but also<br>
Christopher.  Next summer will see a real European security summit: a NATO<br>
summit, after which any talk about a multi-polar world will turn into a bad<br>
joke.=20<br>
<p>
&lt;=3D&gt;<br>
 Moscow ZAVTRA in Russian No. 49 Dec 96 (Signed to press 3 Dec 96) p 1<br>
<p>
<p>
   [Unattributed 'field reports by the DEN =AEMDBO=AF=AEMDNM=AFsecurity=<br>
 service']<br>
According to sources in Washington, there are sharpening debates in the<br>
White House and in the Clinton entourage as a whole over Russia's politics<br>
as well as about what line to take in the growing confrontation within the<br>
Russian establishment.  A large number of representatives of special<br>
agencies proposes distancing from the Chernomyrdin group and switching to<br>
full support of the Chubays-Berezovskiy group, which presupposes<br>
recommendations for Yeltsin to issue an edict on Chernomyrdin's resignation<br>
and the dissolution of the State Duma. Meanwhile, groups in the State<br>
Department and other foreign policy departments believe that Chernomyrdin's<br>
line organically fits into the goals of the Chubays group, while Berezovskiy<br>
is a bridge between them -- as Chernomyrdin himself, promoting informal<br>
relations with the CPRF, [Communist Party of the Russian Federation]<br>
effectively nullifies all actions by the opposition.=20<br>
 In the Republican-controlled Congress, an alternative point of view is<br>
spreading whereby the bet should be placed on the tandem of Lebed and<br>
Korzhakov, who, according to military intelligence analysts, are<br>
increasingly articulating the broad socially discontented sections in the<br>
Russian hinterland, gradually squeezing Zyuganov from the opposition.<br>
 These debates sharpened this December when preparations for the adoption of<br>
the 1997 budget by the U.S. Congress entered the final stage.  It is<br>
indicative that the Yeltsin factor is almost fully absent in these<br>
discussions....<br>
 The failure of the State Duma to give an appropriate assessment of the<br>
Chernomyrdin-Maskhadov agreement and its inability to make realistic and<br>
carefully calculated political decisions are seen in analytical circles in<br>
Ankara as a demonstration of the lack of will in the Russian Federation and<br>
a possibility for Turkey to actively expand its zone of influence in the<br>
North Caucasus....<br>
 According to sources at Radio Liberty and Russian TV companies (NTV, ORT,<br>
and others) they received negative comments from centers overseeing these<br>
media organizations in connection with Lukashenka's victory.  These comments<br>
point out their inability to reveal -- in a timely and adequate way -- the<br>
role of Chernomyrdin, who in effect covered Lukashenka by his visit,<br>
preventing the use of force on the part of the nationalist opposition and<br>
the Sharetskiy group (bloodshed in the streets).  In light of this,<br>
according to these sources, Washington directed these media outlets to<br>
continue the "informational onslaught" on Lukashenka, playing him off<br>
against Yeltsin, based on Lukashenka's alleged far-reaching ambitions to<br>
"seize" the Kremlin....<br>
 The events in Belgrade and the U.S.-initiated mass protest against<br>
President Milosevic, according to experts in Russian special departments,<br>
show that concessions over Bosnia and the surrendering of the Krajina Serbs<br>
resulted in the breakoff between the Belgrade authorities and the patriotic<br>
forces, weakening their internal base; as concerns the "weak" opponents, the<br>
United States takes adequate action against them:  They are destroyed.  A<br>
similar situation apparently awaits Russia in the Caucasus, where<br>
concessions to the separatists will in the end bring NATO forces to the<br>
Caucasus region...(end)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
