<title>Groong Network: Armenian News 12/6/96</title>
<h1>Armenian News 12/6/96</h1>
<i>Chavoush@aol.com</i><br>
<i>Fri, 6 Dec 96 15:30:39 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#53">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#53">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#53">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#53">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0054.html">vahe@arminco.com: "Aragil Headlines, 12/07/96"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0052.html">ASBAREZ-ON-LINE: "ASBARZ-ON-LINE [12-06-96]"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Headlines of stories which follow:<br>
<p>
1.  Velayati calls on Armenia, Azerbaijan to resolve dispute for sake of<br>
region <br>
2.  Aliyev terms outcome of Lisbon summit "positive" <br>
3.  Chinese vice president calls for closer relations with Armenia <br>
4.  Armenia received 15m dollars in UN aid since 1992 <br>
5.  Thirty-seven sites named to UNESCO world heritage list <br>
6.  Photographer's Key: Right Place and Time <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Velayati calls on Armenia, Azerbaijan to resolve dispute for sake<br>
of region <br>
SOURCE: IRNA news agency, Tehran, in English 0739 gmt 5 Dec 96 <br>
<p>
Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati in his talks here today with<br>
Armenia's deputy foreign minister, Sergey Manasaryan, hoped that the two<br>
Caucasus neighbours of Armenia and Azerbaijan, would peacefully resolve their<br>
differences and disputes. <br>
<p>
Velayati, emphasizing on regional peace, stability and security, said that<br>
signing a peace accord was not only in the interest of the two nations, but<br>
also in the interest of the whole of the Caucasus region .   He also<br>
expressed hope that soon the effects of the war will be removed and the<br>
displaced Azeri and Armenian people would be able to return to their homes<br>
and hearths. <br>
<p>
He said that the two Caucasus countries can contribute to regional security<br>
and development through cooperation, once they resolve their disputes. <br>
<p>
The deputy Armenian foreign minister, who is Tehran for the quadrilateral<br>
meeting of deputy foreign ministers of Iran, Armenia, Georgia and Greece,<br>
briefed Velayati on the latest political developments in his country. <br>
<p>
He underlined Tehran-Yerevan transportation and telecommunication cooperation<br>
and called on Iran help Armenian companies have a share in the regional<br>
construction projects. <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Aliyev terms outcome of Lisbon summit "positive" <br>
SOURCES: TRT TV, Ankara, in Turkish 1800 gmt 3 Dec 96; NTV, Moscow, in<br>
Russian 1900 gmt 3 Dec 96; ITAR-TASS news agency (World Service) Moscow, in<br>
English 1941 gmt 3 Dec 96 <br>
<p>
Azerbaijani President Heydar Aliyev has described the outcome of the Lisbon<br>
summit of the OSCE, which ended on 3rd December, as positive, Turkish TV<br>
reported. <br>
<p>
In an interview to the television late on the 3rd, Aliyev said that the<br>
summit had served to confirm Azerbaijan's territorial integrity. " The<br>
outcome of the summit is positive. In other words, even though the Lisbon<br>
declaration contains no written statement regarding the Nagornyy Karabakh<br>
problem and the Armenian-Azeri conflict, the OSCE president issued a<br>
declaration on behalf of all the OSCE member countries. <br>
<p>
"This declaration stated that the Armenian-Azeri conflict, the Nagornyy<br>
Karabakh conflict, should be resolved along the lines of the three principles<br>
supported by all the OSCE countries. Armenia is the only country that did not<br>
support these principles," the Azerbaijani president said. <br>
<p>
He also thanked Turkey for its support throughout the summit, the television<br>
added. <br>
<p>
Aliyev, however, did not express the same sentiments towards Russia,<br>
believing that Moscow could have done more in resolving the<br>
Armenian-Azerbaijani conflict. Speaking to journalists after the summit, as<br>
broadcast on Moscow's NTV television, Aliyev said: "Many link Russia to<br>
Armenia very actively so of course Russia could have averted this conflict<br>
and prevented this bloodshed." <br>
<p>
Russian Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin, for his part, appealed to the two<br>
sides to continue working towards a peaceful settlement of the conflict,<br>
ITAR-TASS news agency reported. <br>
<p>
"I hope that Armenian and Azerbaijani leaders will use the Lisbon summit and<br>
continue settlement talks with due account of the opinion of leaders of the<br>
OSCE member-countries," the agency quoted Chernomyrdin as saying before<br>
leaving Lisbon late on the 3rd. <br>
<p>
"Unfortunately, not all the document were adopted at the Lisbon summit as we<br>
would have liked them to because of the different stands of Armenia and<br>
Azerbaijan on Nagornyy Karabakh. But there was a consensus even on that<br>
situation," he added. <br>
<p>
According to the agency, the international mediators agreed to drop all<br>
references to the dispute from the closing document and issued a separate<br>
statement instead which recommended three settlement principles: <br>
<p>
"The territorial integrity of the Azerbaijani Republic and the Republic of<br>
Armenia; a legal status for Nagornyy Karabakh, outlined in an agreement on<br>
the basis of self-determination, which would give Nagornyy Karabakh the<br>
highest decree of self-government within Azerbaijan; guaranteed security for<br>
Nagornyy Karabakh and its whole population, including mutual obligations to<br>
abide by settlement provisions," the agency reported. <br>
<p>
Turkish television quoted "diplomatic sources" as saying that the document<br>
had been "a serious defeat for Armenia" . <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Chinese vice president calls for closer relations with Armenia <br>
SOURCE: Xinhua news agency, Beijing, in English 1239 gmt 3 Dec 96 <br>
<p>
Chinese Vice President Rong Yiren told a visiting Armenian delegation led by<br>
parliament speaker Babken Ararktsyan that parliamentary exchanges would be of<br>
great benefit to the development of Beijing-Yerevan ties, the official<br>
Chinese news agency Xinhua reported on 3rd December. <br>
<p>
"China holds that all countries in the world should treat each other on the<br>
basis of equality and friendship," Rong said, adding that since the<br>
establishment of diplomatic ties between the two countries in 1992,<br>
high-level visits had greatly promoted bilateral cooperation in the fields of<br>
politics, science and technology, and culture. <br>
<p>
Having briefed the Armenian delegation on China's reform policies and its<br>
long-range development plan to the year 2010, Rong said that the sharing of<br>
experiences would be "conducive to the development of both countries, since<br>
they have many things in common" , the agency reported. <br>
<p>
Ararktsyan said that his delegation was very glad to have an opportunity to<br>
become acquainted with China's reform progress. "Both China and Armenia are<br>
carrying out reform and have potential for cooperation," the speaker said,<br>
adding that it was important for Armenia to learn more about China's<br>
development plans. <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Armenia received 15m dollars in UN aid since 1992 <br>
SOURCE: Interfax news agency, Moscow, in English 1200 gmt 3 Dec 96 <br>
<p>
The United Nations has earmarked a total of 15m dollars for Armenia since a<br>
UN mission opened in the country in December 1992. The money has chiefly been<br>
spent on housing construction and social support for refugees, elderly and<br>
disabled people, a UN representative in charge of refugee problems told a<br>
news conference in Yerevan Tuesday [3rd December].   Armenia is now home to<br>
300,000 refugees from Azerbaijan, the UN representative said, adding that<br>
150,000 of them were living in desperate conditions. <br>
<p>
The majority of refugees are living in dormitories, basements, old unrepaired<br>
buildings and homes based in railway cars. Early reports say the United<br>
Nations will give Armenia 5m dollars for handling social problems in 1997. <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Thirty-seven sites named to UNESCO world heritage list <br>
SOURCE:  Agence France Presse December 05, 1996  06:02 GMT<br>
<p>
Thirty-seven new sites, including a dome marking the atomic bombing of<br>
Hiroshima, were named Thursday as world heritage site. <br>
<p>
In addition to the 37 new sites, UNESCO expanded the area in Vicenza and the<br>
Palladian Villas of the Veneto, 16th century country homes created by<br>
architect Andrea Palladio. <br>
<p>
Follows is a (PARTIAL) list of the natural and cultural sites named Thursday.<br>
<p>
<p>
<p>
Armenia Monastery of Haghpat (built in 991 AD)<br>
Georgia Medieval mountain homes of Upper Svaneti <br>
Greece Vergina, the first capital of Macedonia <br>
<p>
(OTHER SITES REMOVED FROM ARTICLE)<br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Photographer's Key: Right Place and Time <br>
SOURCE:  The Moscow Times December 4, 1996 (by Bronwyn McLaren)<br>
<p>
British photographer James Hill claims that he ended up in the cutthroat<br>
business of photojournalism by accident. "I was desperate," he laughs, in an<br>
interview over lunch near the Moscow bureau of The New York Times, where he<br>
is the paper's full-time photographer. "I couldn't decide what I wanted to<br>
do." <br>
<p>
After graduating with a history degree from Oxford University in 1988, Hill<br>
made a half-hearted attempt to become a merchant banker in London before<br>
enrolling in a photojournalism course at the London College of Printing. His<br>
father, although fully supportive, viewed the move as a one-way trip to<br>
complete poverty. <br>
<p>
But in 1991, Hill had an inkling that something momentous was about to happen<br>
in the Soviet Union. When he completed his course, he jumped on a plane to<br>
Kiev, despite the fact he didn't speak a word of Russian. His timing was<br>
perfect. "As a freelancer, you need to be in the right place at the right<br>
time," says Hill, now 30. "That place was the Soviet Union in 1991 and '92". <br>
<p>
According to Hill, who has now spent the last five years in the former Soviet<br>
Union, journalists could travel for next to nothing, and there was an<br>
insatiable demand from the West for stories. They could also take advantage<br>
of the artificially low international phone rates to chat to editors for<br>
hours. "Kiev was a really fun place then," he said. "It was a very close-knit<br>
community. The British Ambassador would take my film back to London for me." <br>
<p>
It was a particularly favorable climate for Hill who claims he ended up being<br>
the only Western photographer in Kiev. "I was the only fish in the pond," he<br>
said modestly. "And I wasn't even a particularly good photographer. I would<br>
just take photos and hope for the best." <br>
<p>
Conflicts in the Caucasus after the collapse of the Soviet Union also<br>
provided Hill with the opportunity to test his photographic skills in the<br>
context of war. In 1992, he found himself lying in a trench in Nagorny<br>
Karabakh while Armenian soldiers calmly tossed mortars at a nearby village.<br>
"When the Azeris arrived with their machine guns I remember lying there in<br>
the trench thinking that this had probably been a bad idea," he said. <br>
<p>
He is therefore relieved that he hasn't had to spend a vast amount of time<br>
covering Chechnya. "I'm a coward," he said. "I only go down there in the off<br>
-season." <br>
<p>
Since relocating to Moscow in Oct. 1995, Hill has worked full-time for The<br>
New York Times as a photographer. Such positions exist in only two other New<br>
York Times bureaus in the world. The tendency of the paper to "invest time<br>
and resources in in-depth feature work" suits Hill down to the ground. "I<br>
like people-based stories" he said. "People wear their souls on their sleeves<br>
here. You can get very close to people like you can't in other societies. It<br>
makes for a good photo." <br>
<p>
At the same time, Hill is continuing to work on a photo feature that takes a<br>
look behind the scenes of a Russian circus. He wants to capture an image of<br>
the circus quite distinct from the bright lights and gaudy costumes. "The<br>
circus is in a bad way" he mused. "The only people left are those who<br>
couldn't get a foreign contract." <br>
<p>
Hill is also quick to dispel the glamourous myth associated with<br>
photojournalism. "Everyone thinks this is a really sexy job, but there are<br>
some incredibly boring points too," he said. One recent feature and<br>
particular low point saw Hill photographing the cyrillic writing on an<br>
uninspiring shampoo bottle for a story on a Western company's arrival in the<br>
Russian market. <br>
<p>
Hill thinks he would like to spend some time in Asia next, probably China,<br>
but adds that he doubts he will remain a photographer all his life. <br>
<p>
"On the whole, I think photojournalism is in bad shape" he said.<br>
"Paradoxically, the quality of the work has never been higher, but the regard<br>
in which it is held has never been lower." <br>
<p>
Television, due to the speed of its publication, is usurping much of the<br>
power of the photograph according to Hill. He describes the now-famous photo<br>
taken by Eddie Adams in 1968: The chief of the Saigon police is holding a<br>
pistol to the head of the Viet Cong's leader. "It shocked the world," he<br>
said. "I wonder if a photograph will ever change history again." <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
