<title>Groong Network: ASBARZ-ON-LINE [12-06-96]</title>
<h1>ASBARZ-ON-LINE [12-06-96]</h1>
ASBAREZ-ON-LINE (<i>76635.2505@CompuServe.COM</i>)<br>
<i>06 Dec 96 17:58:02 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#52">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#52">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#52">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#52">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0053.html">Chavoush@aol.com: "Armenian News 12/6/96"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0051.html">Sassoon Grigorian: "DFAT RESPONDS TO ANC-Australia CONCERNS REGARDING THE 1996 ARMENIAN PRESIDENTIAL ELECTION"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
nASBAREZ ON LINE <br>
12/06/1996<br>
<p>
<p>
1. HUMAN RIGHTS WATCH SAYS GOVERNMENT INTOLERENT OF OPPOSITION<br>
2. ANCA ISSUES STATEMENT ON LISBON SUMMIT<br>
3. KARABAKH FOREIGN MINISTRY CRITICIZES OSCE CHAIRMAN<br>
4. "DRO" VERDICT TO BE ANNOUNCED TUESDAY<br>
5. ARF YOUTH TAKE PART IN ST. PETERSBURG SEMINAR<br>
6. KROUZIAN-ZEKARIAN SCHOOLS RAISES $100,000<br>
<p>
<p>
1. HUMAN RIGHTS WATCH SAYS GOVERNMENT INTOLERENT OF OPPOSITION<br>
<p>
WASHINGTON-Human Rights Watch/Helsinki recently issued its 1997 <br>
World Report in which it severely criticized the authorities in <br>
Armenia for their intolerance toward opposition forces, and <br>
condemned the election irregularities and post-election arrests of <br>
opposition leaders.<br>
	Amnesty International last week also published a report <br>
regarding ill-treatment and torture in Armenian prisons [see <br>
Asbarez 11/29-30/96].<br>
	These two reports are but a few telling examples of <br>
international concern over recent deviation from human rights <br>
practices and should sound an alarm regarding continuing abuses in <br>
Armenia.<br>
	Below is the entire text of the Human Rights Watch World <br>
Report chapter on Armenia:<br>
<p>
Human Rights Developments<br>
	The government crackdown on the political opposition in <br>
September 1996 cast a pall on human rights. Given the 1995 ban on <br>
the Armenian Revolutionary Federation, Armenias largest <br>
opposition party, and fraudulent 1995 parliamentary elections, the <br>
1996 crackdown accentuated the governments intolerance of any <br>
real political opposition. The crackdown followed massive <br>
demonstrations on September 25 protesting election fraud in the <br>
September 22 presidential elections, in which incumbent Levon Ter-<br>
Petrosyan defeated Vazgen Manoukian by nine percentage points. <br>
Demonstrators marched to the Parliament, where the Central <br>
Election Commission (CEC) was housed, and broke through gates to <br>
demand a recount. In the process, they beat Speaker Babken <br>
Ararktsian and Deputy Speaker Ara Sahakian. In response, police <br>
brutally beat demonstrators and later arrested at least twenty-<br>
eight opposition leaders and supporters and CEC staffers. Among <br>
them, according to credible reports, Aghassi Arshakian, Kim <br>
Balayan, David Vartanian, Gagik Mgrtchian, and Aramazd Zakaryan, <br>
were brutally beaten; the latter required hospitalization for a <br>
fractured skull and broken nose and ribs. Attorneys for some of <br>
the detained, notably ARF leader Ruben Hakopian, were not <br>
permitted access to their clients. <br>
	In the wake of these events, police detained about 200 more <br>
individuals believed to have participated in the demonstration, <br>
President Ter-Petrosyan banned public demonstrations and called in <br>
army troops to patrol Yerevan, and the Procurator General <br>
announced his intention to press charges of attempting violently <br>
to overthrow the government against Vazgen Manoukian and seven <br>
other opposition leaders. Police closed the offices of the <br>
National Democratic Union (Vazgen Manoukians party), the National <br>
Self-Determination Union (a tiny opposition party), the Union of <br>
Constitutional Rights (a nationalist party)  and Artsakh-Hayastan <br>
(an organization for the promotion of Karabakh issues). This <br>
crushing of opposition forces bore out Defense Minister Vazgen <br>
Sargsyans September 25 warning that "After [the September 25] <br>
events, even if they win 100 percent of the votes, neither the <br>
Army nor the National Security and Interior Ministry would <br>
recognize such political leaders."<br>
	Credible reports indicate that electoral violations did not <br>
occur in those precincts monitored by international observers; <br>
however, in the majority of districts without international <br>
observers, no local observers were allowed, dead people and minors <br>
miraculously appeared on lists of voters, soldiers were bused in <br>
with orders to vote for Ter-Petrosyan and ballot boxes were <br>
reportedly stuffed. The elections failed to win the approval of <br>
the OSCE/ODIHR Election Observer Mission, which concluded that <br>
"very serious breaches" in the voting raised concern "for the <br>
overall integrity of the election process."<br>
	The ARF remained banned throughout 1996, while the Ministry <br>
of Justice reviewed its request for reinstatement. At the latest <br>
hearing (September 12), the Ministry of Justice rejected the ARFs <br>
registration papers, claiming that they lacked the requisite <br>
minutes of the ARFs founding Congress. As of this writing the <br>
process has not been completed.<br>
	The trial of Vahan Hovanessian, the ARF chair, and thirty <br>
other ARF members (also known as the "Dro" trial, after the name <br>
of an alleged secret armed section within the ARF that is charged <br>
with planning to overthrow the Armenian government) dragged on <br>
and, as of this writing, more than a year after its opening, has <br>
reached no conclusion. In a stunning display of bias, the Supreme <br>
Court judge presiding over the case accused two of the defense <br>
attorneys who had participated in a USAID trip to the US of having <br>
been funded for the trip by the defendants families.<br>
	The Armenian Ministry of Defense continued illegally to <br>
draft refugees from Azerbaijan and Nagorno-Karabakh into the army <br>
and refused to give draft-aged boys obligatory travel passes until <br>
they registered with their local draft board. Local draft boards <br>
on several occasions held hostage the parents of missing soldiers <br>
until the latter returned. In April, the Ministry of Justice <br>
attempted to close Azg, the Ramkavar party daily, claiming that it <br>
needed to re-register under the auspices of the Diaspora Ramkavar <br>
party, which is pro-Ter-Petrosyan. The effort was unsuccessful.<br>
<p>
The Right to Monitor<br>
	The Ministry of Justice refused to register the Committee <br>
for the Defense of Political Prisoners, basing its decision on its <br>
view that since there were no political prisoners in Armenia, such <br>
an organization was unnecessary.<br>
<p>
The Role of the <br>
International Community<br>
<p>
Europe<br>
	In 1996 European institutions sought to include Armenia as <br>
part of an all-Caucasus strategy. In May the Council of Europes <br>
committee of ministers voted in favor of having the Parliamentary <br>
Assembly consider Armenias application for membership. In <br>
response to the September events, the council dispatched a mission <br>
to Armenia in early October. The European Union had been scheduled <br>
to sign an interim agreement underlying a broad trade and <br>
cooperation agreement. It postponed a trip to Yerevan, where the <br>
signature ceremony was to take place, citing "security reasons."<br>
<p>
United States<br>
	The second largest per-capita recipient of US aid, Armenia <br>
received US $95 million for FY 1996 under the Freedom Support Act, <br>
a 100 percent increase in assistance since 1995. The Clinton <br>
Administrations reaction to the September events marked an <br>
abdication of its responsibility towards human rights in a country <br>
in which it has a significant investment. The State Departments <br>
initial weak statement in response to the crackdown, which merely <br>
called on both sides to exercise restraint, demonstrated a feigned <br>
ignorance of government practices, exercised throughout the past <br>
two years, aimed at cutting the opposition out of mainstream <br>
politics. A later statement expressed "concern for the future of <br>
those arrested."<br>
	The Clinton administrations response is even more <br>
inexcusable, given the scrupulous work of the US Embassy staff in <br>
Yerevan, which monitored the "Dro" trial, met with the relatives <br>
of opposition leaders arrested in the wake of the crackdown, and <br>
generally is extremely well informed on human rights violations. <br>
	Two high-level State Department visits were devoted to <br>
regional security and Nagorno Karabakh, and neither had a domestic <br>
politics or human rights component. <br>
	The State Department did, however, acknowledge obvious <br>
cracks in Armenias democracy in its Country Reports on Human <br>
Rights Practices for 1995 and in a July 30 congressional hearing <br>
on the Caucasus. Additionally, on October 22, the Department of <br>
State called on the Armenian government to adhere to OSCE <br>
recommendations concerning the election law, but again failed to <br>
take the government to task for the brutal crackdown.<br>
<p>
<p>
2. ANCA ISSUES STATEMENT ON LISBON SUMMIT<br>
<p>
We welcome the stand in defense of Nagorno-Karabakh adopted by the <br>
Republic of Armenia during the recently concluded Lisbon summit of <br>
the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe.<br>
	Exercising its right to veto language in the final summit <br>
declaration, the Armenian government prevented the ratification, <br>
by the OSCE, of the Azerbaijani position that the Republic of <br>
Nagorno-Karabakh would be subordinate to Azerbaijani sovereignty. <br>
This action was fully consistent with previous decisions adopted <br>
by the Armenian Parliament.<br>
	We share the Armenian governments view that the only <br>
guarantee for the security of Nagorno-Karabakh is its right to <br>
self-determination. Any resolution to the conflict which does not <br>
fully respect this right will lead to increased regional <br>
instability and will place the Armenian population of Karabakh <br>
under the constant threat of genocide.<br>
	In remaining committed to Karabakhs right to self-<br>
determination, the Republic of Armenia resisted heavy pressures <br>
from Western states and the countries of the region. In the wake <br>
of this summit, these pressures will surely increase, fueled by <br>
the short-sighted efforts of the Caspian oil lobby. This fact was <br>
evident in the decidedly unbalanced statement of the Swiss OSCE <br>
Chairman-in-Office, which called for Nagorno-Karabakh to be placed <br>
under Azerbaijani rule.<br>
	We are confident that the collective leadership of the <br>
Armenian nation will rise to meet and overcome these challenges. <br>
Working together, the Armenian government, the government of <br>
Nagorno-Karabakh and the Diaspora are capable of countering the <br>
powerful interests arrayed against the Armenian nation. We, <br>
therefore, call on all Armenian-American organizations to join <br>
together in constructive partnership to advance the commonly held <br>
concerns of all Armenians, and to stand in solidarity with the <br>
people of Nagorno-Karabakh.<br>
<p>
Armenian National <br>
Committee of America<br>
<p>
<p>
3. KARABAKH FOREIGN MINISTRY CRITICIZES OSCE CHAIRMAN<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-The Foreign Ministry of the Nagorno-Karabakh <br>
Republic issued a statement Friday on this weeks two-day Lisbon <br>
Summit of the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe.<br>
	Below is the full text of the statement:<br>
	"The Foreign Ministry of Nagorno-Karabakh was puzzled to <br>
hear the OSCE chairmans statement at the Lisbon Summit concerning <br>
the principles of settlement of the Karabakh conflict, based on <br>
the proposals by the OSCE Minsk Groups co-chairmanship.<br>
	By its content, the statement fully ignores international <br>
legal and historical aspects of the problem, by its form it <br>
contradicts the spirit and letter of the Minsk process, and  by <br>
the way it was adopted it is unacceptable for forums of such <br>
scale. That is why we view it as a defeat of the right, justice <br>
and common sense and a victory of the rude blackmail of <br>
Azerbaijan, which manipulates oil and other interests of some <br>
states.<br>
	In the course of the 20th century, the Armenian people, on <br>
several occasions, became the victim of geopolitical interests of <br>
world powers and experienced the horrors of genocide and <br>
deportation. We view the efforts, aimed at keeping Karabakhs <br>
people within a criminal state, which has been methodically <br>
annihilating this people as the continuation of an already <br>
familiar policy.<br>
	The people of the Nagorno-Karabakh Republic is consistently <br>
and persistently realizing its right to self-determination and <br>
rejects any attempts of arbitrary establishment of a hierarchy <br>
between equal international principles as a base for political and <br>
legal manipulations.<br>
	With this mind, the Foreign Ministry of Nagorno-Karabakh, <br>
confirming Karabakhs resoluteness to maintain the cease-fire and <br>
willingness to settle all disputes peacefully, expresses serious <br>
doubts in the sense of its participation in the process of <br>
negotiation, in which the proposals by the mediating side are <br>
based on an optional attitude toward  international norms and <br>
reflect the stance of only one of three sides to the conflict."<br>
<p>
<p>
4. "DRO" VERDICT TO BE ANNOUNCED TUESDAY<br>
<p>
YEREVAN-Judge Edward Manoukian is expected to announce the verdict <br>
in the so-called "Dro" case Tuesday, Dec. 10, sources close to the <br>
case said on Friday.<br>
	The Armenian Revolutionary Federation Executive Council of <br>
Armenia postponed the ARFs 106th anniversary celebration, <br>
scheduled for that day.<br>
<p>
<p>
5. ARF YOUTH TAKE PART IN ST. PETERSBURG SEMINAR<br>
<p>
ST. PETERSBURG-The Armenian Revolutionary Federation Youth <br>
Organization was among the participants of a St. Petersburg <br>
seminar, co-sponsored by the Union of Young Democrats of Russia <br>
and the Social Democratic Youth of Sweden.<br>
	The ARF-YO was represented by Swedens "Sardarabad" member   <br>
Shahe Khacherian.<br>
	The week-long seminar, which began on Nov. 18, discussed <br>
ways of developing and expanding youth relations.<br>
	During his presentation, Khacherian acquainted participants <br>
with the ARF-YOs structure and activities, focusing on the <br>
present situation in Armenia. He stressed the importance of <br>
establishing inter-youth relations in helping Armenia develop into <br>
a democratic and rule of law society.<br>
	The European Council of Socialist Youth, a member of the <br>
International Union of Socialist Youth, held its annual conference <br>
immediately after the seminar, Nov. 22-24.<br>
	ECOSY general-secretary Philippe Corder chaired the <br>
conference, which included representatives of European socialist <br>
youth organizations, Russian Duma member Sergey Krushchayik, IUSY <br>
general-secretary Alfredo Lazaretti, European Parliament member <br>
Maj. Brit Tiorin and the former general-secretary of NATO, Willy <br>
Klaus. Participants prepared for the upcoming IUSY conference.<br>
	While in St. Petersburg, Khacherian had an opportunity to <br>
meet with representatives of various groups. During his visit with <br>
Lazaretti, Khacherian was informed that the ARF-YOs membership <br>
application to the IUSY was in good standing and progressing very <br>
well.<br>
	In addition, the ARF-YO was invited to attend a seminar in <br>
April 1997 in Germany organized by that countrys socialist youth. <br>
<p>
<p>
6. KROUZIAN-ZEKARIAN SCHOOLS RAISES $100,000<br>
<p>
SAN FRANCISCO-Declaring "it always makes me feel so good when I <br>
write a check out to KZV Armenian School," Hank Torian, along with <br>
his wife Rita and their children, presented a check for $25,000 to <br>
Serpoug Sarkissian of the Krouzian-Zekarian Vasbouragan School <br>
Finance Committee. The occasion was the 16th Annual KZV Banquet <br>
held on the evening of Saturday, November 9. The Colonial Room of <br>
the St. Francis Hotel on Union Square was the elegant setting for <br>
this years banquet and silent auction which raised over $100,000 <br>
for the school, the only Armenian-American day school in Northern <br>
California.<br>
	Currently on a sabbatical in Armenia, retired Pastor of St. <br>
Gregory Armenian Apostolic Church, Rev. Datev Kaloustian, came <br>
especially for the banquet at the request of the Torians. Rev. <br>
Kaloustian praised the Torians for their commitment and unending <br>
generosity to KZV School. A prominent car dealer and Armenian <br>
philanthropist, Hank Torian was hailed as a classic American <br>
success story. A special letter of congratulations to the Torians <br>
was sent by US Representative Anna  G. Eshoo, the only member of <br>
Congress of Armenian descent.<br>
	Speakers for the evening included a member of the first <br>
graduating class of KZV, Garen Nazarian, who since graduating in <br>
1988, attended St. Ignatius College Preparatory, and graduated <br>
last May from the University of California at Berkeley with a BA <br>
in English. The son of Mr. and Mrs. Shahen and Anahid Nazarian, <br>
Garen attributed his academic success to those early years at KZV. <br>
KZV also proudly welcomed the esteemed educator Dr. Dikran <br>
Kouymjian as the honored guest speaker. Presently the William <br>
Saroyan and Krouzian Visiting Professor of Armenian Studies for <br>
the fall semester at UC Berkeley, Dr. Kouymjian is also the Haig <br>
and Isabel Berberian Professor of Armenian Studies and Director of <br>
the Kalfayan Center at Cal State Fresno. He is a well-known <br>
authority on Armenian history, art and literature.<br>
	The annual Banquet was co-chaired by Hildy Sarkissian and <br>
Cindy Krikorian. Hilda Basmajian chaired the Silent Auction which <br>
netted $13,000 and represented the generosity of many individuals <br>
and businesses in the community. Auction items ranged from fine <br>
jewelry, travel, sports memorabilia, fine art, home furnishings <br>
and personal services. Other committee members were Serpoug <br>
Sarkissian and Jack Koujakian of the KZV Finance Committee, Hasmig <br>
Boudaghian, Jeanne Hartunian, Marie Kilijian, Vergine Misserlian <br>
and Talin Kaloustian. Assadour Kevranian served as the Master of <br>
Ceremonies.<br>
<p>
