<p>
PRESS RELEASE<br>
<p>
Contact: Sassoon Grigorian<br>
7 December 1996<br>
<p>
DFAT RESPONDS TO ANC-Australia CONCERNS REGARDING THE 1996 ARMENIAN<br>
PRESIDENTIAL ELECTION<br>
<p>
CANBERRA - The Australian Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade (DFAT) has<br>
responded to the concerns voiced by the ANCA regarding developments<br>
surrounding recent presidential elections in the Republic of Armenia.<br>
<p>
In a letter addressed to the Australian Foreign Minister, the Honourable<br>
Alexander Downer, the ANCA expressed its "profound disquiet" both at the<br>
widespread ballot manipulation which had taken place during the Presidential<br>
election as well as the actions of the current government leadership in<br>
response to the widespread protests by the general populace in the aftermath<br>
of the election.<br>
<p>
Mr J.A. Benson, Assistant Secretary of the Europe and Eurasia Branch,<br>
replying on behalf of the Minister for Foreign Affairs, indicated to the<br>
ANCA that:<br>
<p>
"The (Australian) Government views the conclusions of the OSCE in regard to<br>
the recent election in Armenia with some concern, and is also disquieted by<br>
reports of heavy handed actions by the Armenian authorities in quelling<br>
popular protests in Yerevan in the aftermath of the elections."<br>
<p>
The Assistant Secretary went on further to state:<br>
<p>
"Against this background, we will be monitoring the situation in Armenia,<br>
and will look to opportunities to voice our concerns to the Armenian<br>
Government, and encourage it to ensure that the commitment to the democratic<br>
process in Armenia will be safeguarded."<br>
<p>
