<title>Groong Network: Istanbul Editor Dies</title>
<h1>Istanbul Editor Dies</h1>
Asbed Bedrossian (<i>asbed@skat.usc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 6 Dec 96 12:41:34 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#48">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#48">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#48">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#48">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0049.html">Rose & Alex Pilibos: "Six Rose and Alex Pilibos Alumni Pass the Bar"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0047.html">Asbed Bedrossian: "Vatican Delegation in Istanbul"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
ISTANBUL ("Lraper" 6 December 1996) - The 83 year old editor-in-chief<br>
of the Armenian language Istanbul daily "Jamanak," Ara Kochunian, died<br>
in the Surp Prgitch Armenian Hospital on Tuesday, 4th December, at<br>
18:00 hours. Son of Sarkis Kochunian, who founded "Jamanak" in 1908,<br>
Ara Kochunian edited in the past the "Ahali" and "Arshav" Armenian<br>
weeklies as well. A staunch supporter of Etchmiadzin and a popular<br>
figure in community administration, Ara Kochunian liked to call<br>
"Jamanak" a "people's gazette." He is survived by his wife Mrs Lily<br>
Kochunian, also a writer, his son Sarkis Kochunian and his grandson<br>
Ara Kochunian II, the present editor of "Jamanak."<br>
<p>
A special memorial service was held today at 11:00 hours at the<br>
headquarters of the Journalists' Association of Turkey in<br>
Cagaloglu-Istanbul, where the President of the Association, Mr. Nail<br>
Gureli, delivered a moving speech in memory of the Armenian<br>
editor. The Chancellor of the Armenian Patriarchate, The Revd Dr.<br>
Krikor Damadyan was present.<br>
<p>
The President of the Armenian Academy of Sciences, Mr Fadey Sarkissian, <br>
sent today a message of condolences to His Beatitude Patriarch Karekin <br>
II of Istanbul, expressing the sympath of the intellectuals of Armenia <br>
on the demise of Ara Kochunian.<br>
<p>
The "Jamanak" Armenian daily of Istanbul, with a present tirage of 3,000 <br>
per day is the oldest Armenian paper in the world which has never ceased <br>
since 1908. "Jamanak" is the oldest paper in Turkey as well.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
