<title>Groong Network: CORRECTION: Armenian Church in Turkey</title>
<h1>CORRECTION: Armenian Church in Turkey</h1>
<i>H.TCHILINGIRIAN@lse.ac.uk</i><br>
<i>Fri, 6 Dec 96 12:26:54 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#46">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#46">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#46">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#46">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0047.html">Asbed Bedrossian: "Vatican Delegation in Istanbul"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0045.html">BBulbulian@aol.com: "Panel discussion"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
          [Note: This is the corrected version of an article posted a <br>
          few days ago. Correction in paragraph 11, Abp. Mutafyan's <br>
          quote. Please disregard the previous version].<br>
          <br>
          <br>
          THE ARMENIAN CHURCH IN KAYSERI (GESARIA), TURKEY REOPENED <br>
          FOR WORSHIP  <br>
                <br>
          ISTANBUL ("LRAper" 2/12/96)--Last weekend St. Gregory <br>
          Armenian Church of Kayseri (Gesaria) was officially reopened <br>
          by formal ceremonies presided by Archbishop Mesrob Mutafyan, <br>
          Chairman of the Religious Council of the Armenian <br>
          Patriarchate of Constantinople. For a long time, the church <br>
          was closed due to renovations.<br>
           <br>
          Currently, the St. Gregory Armenian Church serves the <br>
          religious needs of the small Armenian communities spread in <br>
          central and Eastern Anatolia and on the banks of the Black <br>
          Sea. It is the only functioning Armenian Church in the area. <br>
          The church in Kayseri (Cappadocian Ceasarea) already existed <br>
          in 1191. Since the early centuries of Christianity, <br>
          Armenians have been active in this city which was an       <br>
          important commercial center in Asia Minor.<br>
           <br>
          According to Turkish encyclopedias, in 1890 there were <br>
          43,318 Apostolic Armenians in the province of Kayseri, 1,800 <br>
          Armenian Protestants and 1,575 Armenian Catholics.  Today <br>
          only 10 Armenians live in Kayseri. However, St. Gregory <br>
          Church serves as the religious center for about 3,000 <br>
          Armenians living in central Anatolia and the Eastern <br>
          provinces.<br>
           <br>
          On the Way to Kayseri<br>
           <br>
          Renovated in memory of Gesaria-native Hagop Tokerian, the <br>
          reopening of St. Gregory Church was decreed by the Armenian <br>
          Patriarch of Turkey, Archbishop Karekin II Kazanjian.  <br>
                <br>
          On Thursday, November 30, over 400 Armenian pilgrims from <br>
          Istanbul headed to Gesaria on nine buses; they  were later <br>
          joined by another 30 pilgrims who traveled to the region by <br>
          plane. Others came from Ankara, Sepastia, Malatya, Tokat and <br>
          the villages of Yozgat to participate in the opening <br>
          ceremonies. Archbishop Mesrob Mutafyan and his entourage    <br>
          of priests and lay representative arrived on Friday and were <br>
          greeted by the representative of St. Gregory Church, <br>
          Antranik Erkouyoumjian and other officials.<br>
           <br>
          Upon their arrival, the delegation from the Patriarchate <br>
          visited the church and inspected the results of the <br>
          renovations that were carried out and discussed the schedule <br>
          of weekend activities.<br>
           <br>
          On Saturday morning, the delegation, headed by Archbishop <br>
          Mesrob, visited the historic sites of Goreme, Urgupi and the <br>
          famous churches of the region. In the afternoon, an <br>
          elaborate ceremony of "Opening the Doors of the Church" <br>
          (T'rnpatzek) was held in St. Gregory Church in the presence <br>
          of more than 500 Armenian faithful.  Archbishop Mesrob       <br>
          consecrated the three altars of the church and the baptismal <br>
          font. The wood-carved altars and the delicate frescos inside <br>
          the church, which were carefully restored to their original <br>
          brilliance, testify to the fine artistry of Armenian <br>
          masters.<br>
           <br>
          On this occasion, Archbishop Mesrob delivered a sermon <br>
          highlighting the importance of the reopening of the St. <br>
          Gregory Church.  He recounted the historic event when St. <br>
          Gregory the Illuminator, the patron saint of the Armenian <br>
          Church, was consecrated the Head of the Armenian Apostolic <br>
          Church, here in Gesaria in the 4th century, by Leontius, the <br>
          Archbishop of Ceasarea.  As such, Gesaria has a significant <br>
          role in the history of the Armenian Church, especially as    <br>
          we prepare for the celebrations of the 1700th anniversary of<br>
          acceptance of Christianity as state religion in Armenia. <br>
          Based on a passage from the Book of Psalms, Archbishop <br>
          Mesrob then explained the importance of temples build for <br>
          the glory of God and how the faithful, collectively, <br>
          contribute to the edification of a `holy place' where <br>
          pilgrims experience the presence of God.  <br>
          <br>
          The reopening of the church in Kayseri coincided with the <br>
          535th anniversary of the founding of the Armenian <br>
          Patriarchate of Constantinople.  In 1461, Sultan Mehmet II, <br>
          eight years after conquering Constantinople, established the <br>
          Armenian Patriarchate with equal rights and privileges as <br>
          that of the Greek Patriarchate.  The mayor of Kayseri, <br>
          acting in the same spirit as Mehmet II, has not only <br>
          permitted the renovation of the Armenian church, but has <br>
          also allocated financial resources to build a high       <br>
          stone-fence around the Armenian cemetery of Kayseri.<br>
           <br>
          The mayor of Kayseri, Dr. ShukrU Karatepe, was present <br>
          during the consecration ceremonies of the church. After the <br>
          religious services, in the courtyard of the church, the <br>
          mayor welcomed Archbishop Mesrob and greeted the opening of <br>
          the Armenian Church in Kayseri with warm words.  He <br>
          emphasized that it would be wrong to look at this event<br>
          from a "touristic point of view", but rather the importance <br>
          of this event rests in the peaceful coexistence of Christian <br>
          and Moslem peoples. "In the past, we have passed through sad <br>
          events together, but today, the time has come to build <br>
          strong bridges between various communities", said the mayor.<br>
           <br>
          In his response, Archbishop Mesrob, after thanking the <br>
          mayor, said: "There is no formal inter-religious dialogue in <br>
          Turkey between the leaders of various religions, however, we <br>
          notice that there is a dialogue of life among our peoples in <br>
          their day to day relations with each other, which is very<br>
          important for mutual understanding and for future steps <br>
          toward formal dialogue".<br>
           <br>
          Visit to the Armenian Cemetery  <br>
          <br>
          At 3:00 p.m. on the same day, Archbishop Mesrob, in the <br>
          company of the mayor and several hundred Armenian pilgrims, <br>
          visited the Armenian cemetery in Kayseri.  A requiem service <br>
          was conducted for the departed souls of the Armenians of the <br>
          city.  Archbishop Mesrob said that the cemetery looked in <br>
          better condition. Recently, the municipality of Kayseri has <br>
          appointed a full-time custodian for the cemetery.  Mayor<br>
          Karatepe expressed his willingness to enhance the efforts of <br>
          Armenians if they wish to renovate the cemetery and the old <br>
          graves.  After the cemetery visit, Archbishop Mesrob <br>
          returned to Istanbul.  <br>
          <br>
          Divine Liturgy and Blessing of Madagh  <br>
          <br>
          On Sunday, December 1, Divine Liturgy was celebrated in St. <br>
          Gregory Church, presided by Fr. Aram Vartabed Ateshian.  The <br>
          Blessing of Madagh and requiem services followed the <br>
          Liturgy.  <br>
                <br>
          Henceforth, the Armenian Patriarchate will send visiting <br>
          priests to Kayseri on a regular basis to conduct religious <br>
          services and to minister to the needs of the Armenian <br>
          communities in the region.  <br>
          <br>
          By Isahag Bchakjian<br>
          [Translated by ht]<br>
           <br>
          <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
