<title>Groong Network: Turkey cancels SuperCobra deal over U.S. delay</title>
<h1>Turkey cancels SuperCobra deal over U.S. delay</h1>
<i>Chavoush@aol.com</i><br>
<i>Thu, 5 Dec 96 19:14:47 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#43">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#43">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#43">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#43">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0044.html">Asbed Bedrossian: "OMRI Digest 12/06/96"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0042.html">ANCA-DC: "ANCA: Human Rights Watch Issues Report on Armenia"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
HEADLINE: Turkey cancels SuperCobra deal over U.S. delay<br>
SOURCE: The Fort Worth Star-Telegram, December 4, 1996<br>
<p>
The government of Turkey has withdrawn an order for 10 AH-1W SuperCobra<br>
attack helicopters from Bell Helicopter because of a 19-month delay in<br>
getting approval for the sale from the U.S. State Department.<br>
<p>
The State Department has expressed concern about Turkey's treatment of its<br>
Kurdish population, and has not sent the agreement, worth up to $150 million<br>
in sales to Bell, to Congress as required by law.<br>
<p>
State Department spokesman Christopher Bush declined to comment on the<br>
matter, saying "We haven't been given guidance on this matter except to say<br>
that the decision to cancel the sale was by the Turkish military."<br>
<p>
The Turkish Embassy in Washington, D.C., while acknowledging that the country<br>
has some human rights problems, suggested that lobbying by Greek interests<br>
had scuttled the sale. <br>
<p>
"There are always complaints from the Greek interests when the Turkish armed<br>
forces want to make a purchase, and their voices are quite strong in American<br>
politics," said Mehmet Gucuk, politcal counsel in the Turkish Embassy.<br>
<p>
Gucuk noted that Turkey is a member of NATO. It has made several purchases of<br>
American military hardware over the years, including helicopters from Bell.<br>
It has also bought 150 F-16s from Lockheed Martin Corp. The Turkish F-16s are<br>
assembled at a plant in Ankara, and some have been sold to Egypt.<br>
<p>
Bell expressed disappointment with the loss of the sale. Vice President Fred<br>
Hubbard said the decision was "hard to take." <br>
<p>
Hubbard said the lost sale was the result of "U.S. government inaction," and<br>
that it would give Bell's competitors in France and Russia a foothold for<br>
sales to the Turkish army.<br>
<p>
"Bell has enjoyed its long-term relationship with the Turkish Land Command,"<br>
Hubbard said. "The Turkish military operates a preponderance of Bell<br>
helicopters."<br>
<p>
Bell spokesman Terry Arnold said the company doesn't release specific sales<br>
or volume figures to foreign countries. <br>
<p>
Arnold added that because of the present strong backlog of orders, Bell's<br>
6,000-person work force will not be reduced because of the loss of the sale.<br>
Bell recently received an order from the U.S. Marines for the upgrade of 180<br>
SuperCobras, a deal that will be worth around $1 billion and keep Bell's<br>
production lines busy through 2012.<br>
<p>
Bell was unable to proceed with the Turkish sale because the matter was never<br>
referred to Congress by the State Department. Under law, foreign sales must<br>
be referred to Congress, which may turn down a sale by a two-thirds vote of<br>
both houses. No congressional action on a request constitutes approval.<br>
<p>
"Usually, if there has been no disapproval within two weeks, then the sale is<br>
final," said Gucuk. "But it has to be sent to Congress, which never<br>
happened."<br>
<p>
Gucuk said the State Department has expressed concern to Turkey about its<br>
treatment of the Kurds, an ethnic minority in several southeast European and<br>
Middle Eastern states.<br>
<p>
"Every country has human rights problems, and we are trying to resolve our<br>
difficulties through our Parliament and the proper channels," said Gucuk.<br>
"But the issue shouldn't be connected with the purchase of military<br>
equipment. We have the second-largest army in NATO, and we are a member of<br>
several regional security<br>
alliances."<br>
<p>
Gucuk noted that Turkey is within range of missiles from potentially hostile<br>
states, such as Syria, Greece and Armenia. He added that "our military<br>
strategy is based entirely on defense."<br>
<p>
Gucuk left open the question about whether Turkey would be interested in<br>
future purchases from Bell.<br>
<p>
"The problem with the SuperCobra purchase was that we already had waited<br>
almost two years, and would have to wait another two years while the<br>
helicopters were in production," he said. "Meanwhile, the next generation of<br>
Cobras will become available after the turn of the century. So the matter<br>
became a decision about whether the purchase of the 10 SuperCobras would<br>
still be wise."<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
