<title>Groong Network: ASBAREZ-ON-LINE [12-05-96]</title>
<h1>ASBAREZ-ON-LINE [12-05-96]</h1>
ASBAREZ-ON-LINE (<i>76635.2505@CompuServe.COM</i>)<br>
<i>05 Dec 96 19:40:55 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#41">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#41">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#41">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#41">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0042.html">ANCA-DC: "ANCA: Human Rights Watch Issues Report on Armenia"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0040.html">Mher Sassouni: "Turkey/CenAsia Highlights 12/05/96"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
ASBAREZ ON LINE <br>
12/05/1996<br>
<p>
<p>
1. RUSSIAN BORDER PATROL COMMANDER TO VISIT ARMENIA<br>
2. LAWYER, EDITOR DISCUSS VIOLATIONS IN ARMENIA<br>
3. ARMENIA TO TAKE PART IN  BLACK SEA BUSINESS<br>
4. KARABAKH CEC ANNOUNCES FINAL ELECTION RESULTS<br>
5. GEORGIAN CENTRAL BANK DELEGATION ARRIVES IN YEREVAN<br>
6. WORLD BANK FLAGSHIP PROJECT  IMPLEMENTED IN ARMENIA<br>
7. UNHCR OUTLINES ACTIVITIES IN ARMENIA<br>
8. TESTIMONY ELEVATES INCONCISTANCIES<br>
9. IRAN, ARMENIA, GEORGIA, GREECE SIGN AGREEMENT<br>
<p>
<p>
1. RUSSIAN BORDER PATROL COMMANDER TO VISIT ARMENIA<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Itar-Tass)-General Andrey Nikolayev, commander of the <br>
Russian border troops, arrived in Yerevan to discuss the defense <br>
of the Russian Federations borders.<br>
	Nikolayev is expected to meet with Levon Ter-Petrosyan and <br>
commanders of the Armenian border troops to discuss fortification <br>
of the Turkey-Iran-Armenia border.<br>
	Armenias borders are currently defended by Russian frontier <br>
guards. A number of agreements were signed during the past several <br>
years which regulate the status of Russian troops in Armenia.<br>
<p>
<p>
2. LAWYER, EDITOR DISCUSS VIOLATIONS IN ARMENIA<br>
<p>
PARIS-At the invitation of the France-based International <br>
Federation for Human Rights (FIDH), attorney Rouben Sahakian, <br>
founder of Armenias "Avangard" Human Rights Organization, Edward <br>
Mamikonian, also an attorney affiliated with "Avangard," and Golos <br>
Armenii semi-weekly editor Flora Nakhshkarian were in Paris from <br>
Nov. 28 to Dec. 5, where they held meetings with governmental and <br>
non-governmental human rights groups, attorneys and the Armenian <br>
community.<br>
	During their week-long visit, the group met with members of <br>
the French Senate committee on French-Armenian relations, French <br>
Supreme Court representatives, French and Armenian attorneys, <br>
representatives of the European Parliaments Human Rights <br>
Organization, as well as the media.<br>
	Throughout their meetings the group focused attention to <br>
Armenias human rights record of the past five years, particularly <br>
the recent violations of human rights, political persecutions, <br>
obstacles to freedom of expression and the authoritarian regime <br>
currently in place in Armenia.<br>
	The grave human rights violations were also discussed during <br>
a gathering of the Armenian community in Paris on Dec. 4. The <br>
media and representatives of French public-political organizations <br>
also attended the gathering.<br>
	Historian Claire Mouradian presented a brief, yet <br>
comprehensive history of the Armenian people, highlighting the <br>
Armenian Genocide of 1915, the independent Republic of Armenia, <br>
1918-1920, the Karabakh Movement of 1988, and the re-establishment <br>
of Armenias independence in 1991 as a result of the collapse of <br>
the Soviet Union.<br>
	Mouradian also presented the gradual move toward <br>
authoritarian rule in Armenia, pointing to the suspension of the <br>
Armenian Revolutionary Federations activities in Armenia, the <br>
shut down of nearly a dozen newspapers and other publications, and <br>
the crackdown following the Sept. 22 presidential elections, <br>
following which thousands of Armenians demanded the nullification <br>
of the controversial polls and pointed to the OSCE reports casting <br>
doubt on its legitimacy.<br>
	Following Mouradians presentation, attorney Michel <br>
Toubiana, vice-chairperson of the Human Rights League, recalled <br>
his 1995 visit to Armenia where he witnessed prisoners being <br>
denied access to their attorneys and trials that did not meet <br>
international legal standards.<br>
	Toubiana told the gathering that democracy is non-existent <br>
in Armenia and it is not possible to have  rule of law through an <br>
authoritarian regime which suspends political parties, shuts down <br>
newspapers and suppresses freedom of expression through the use of <br>
force.<br>
	Attorney Edward Mamikonian provided a brief background of <br>
the "Avangard" Human Rights Organization, which was established in <br>
1993, but was officially registered by the Armenian government in <br>
1994.<br>
	Mamikonian said that in Armenian today, even the most basic <br>
individual rights are being ignored. "The majority of the <br>
population wants to leave the country, not just for the desperate <br>
economic and social conditions, but because it is difficult to <br>
consider oneself a citizen protected by law," he said.<br>
	"The governing principles in Armenia today are guns and the <br>
use of force," Mamikonian said, pointing to similarities between <br>
events in September 1996 to those of 1993-1994 when armed groups <br>
broke in to homes, conscripting young men into the army without <br>
official draft papers or physical exams. "It happens today and it <br>
happened on Sept. 26.," he added. "Reminiscent of the Stalin era, <br>
the "Yergrabah" armed units [pro-government groups] stormed <br>
private residences, ransacked , beat, kidnapped and pillaged <br>
without sparing even the elderly," Mamikonian told the gathering.<br>
	He concluded by saying "today Armenias Constitution is <br>
under suspicion, there is virtually no parliamentary opposition, <br>
only an oppressed population and an illegitimate president."<br>
	Flora Nakhshkarian, the editor of the semi-weekly, <br>
independent Russian-language newspaper, spoke of the obstacles <br>
faced by Golos Armenii throughout its six-year history and said <br>
that Armenias leadership has attempted to thwart publication by <br>
every means, including shutting off the electricity in the <br>
building for extended periods and harassing and kidnapping several <br>
of its reporters and editors. "But with a clear conscious we <br>
struggled and survived and continue to tell the truth," she said.<br>
	Referring to the harassment and illegal detention of <br>
correspondent Gagik Mkrtchian, Nakhshkarian said that he was <br>
forced out of his apartment by two high-ranking military <br>
personnel, one of whom was the head of Levon Ter-Petrosyans <br>
security team and the other an Interior Ministry official. <br>
"Mkrtchians only wrongdoing was being a Golos Armenii <br>
correspondent," she said.<br>
	Rouben Sahakian, defense attorney in the so-called "Dro" and <br>
"31" cases began his presentation by pointing to a blatant <br>
contradiction between the Armenian Constitution and the status <br>
quo.<br>
	"The very first article of the Constitution declares that <br>
the government of Armenia will be based on democracy and the rule <br>
of law. However, the opposite is true of Armenia today. Not only <br>
is there an absence of democracy and an independent judiciary, the <br>
judicial system is packed with incompetent and inexperienced <br>
judges and personnel that are not familiar with basic judicial <br>
tenets," Sahakian said.<br>
	Sahakian pointed to the massive violations of judicial <br>
procedures in the infamous "Trial of 31" and "Dro" cases, whose <br>
defendants have been baselessly charged with crimes and are <br>
subjected to inhumane prison conditions. "Most of them are the <br>
heads of households and have several children each, which are in <br>
dire financial straits," Sahakian said. "For example, Armen <br>
Shahinian and two others have been in jail for the past two years, <br>
accused of taking part in a gang without informing the <br>
authorities. Their trial is expected to begin in March 1997 and <br>
will last about six months. Based on the charges and according to <br>
the law, they should have been released to await trial a long time <br>
ago. If this is not authoritarian rule, then what would you call <br>
it?" he said.<br>
	Sahakian then detailed the reasons for the death of Ardavazd <br>
Manoukian, who died while in an Interior Ministry detention <br>
facility. "The Prosecutor-General of Armenia is responsible for <br>
Manoukians death, but he has gone unpunished and continues to <br>
occupy himself with the fate of others as long as he remains in <br>
his high and untouchable post," Sahakian said.<br>
	Sahakian pointed to the biased and often distorted reports <br>
of the political trials in Armenia by the state-run media. "The <br>
current leadership is in the hands of Neo-Communists" Sahakian <br>
said, "and nothing has changed from those days."<br>
<p>
<p>
3. ARMENIA TO TAKE PART IN  BLACK SEA BUSINESS<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-Armenia will be among the participants of <br>
the upcoming meeting of small and medium-sized corporations of <br>
Black Sea countries. The meeting will take place on Dec. 19-20 in <br>
Istanbul, Turkey, under the auspices of the Balkan Center.<br>
	The two-day meeting is aimed at developing ties between <br>
Black Sea area businesses.<br>
	Armenia is in the process of compiling a list of local <br>
business leaders that will attend the meeting.<br>
<p>
<p>
4. KARABAKH CEC ANNOUNCES FINAL ELECTION RESULTS<br>
<p>
STEPANAKERT (Noyan Tapan)-The Central Electoral Commission of the <br>
Nagorno-Karabakh Republic announced on Tuesday the final results <br>
of the Nov. 24 presidential elections in the mountainous republic.<br>
	According to the official data, 70,058 (80 percent) eligible <br>
voters participated turned out for Karabakhs first-ever <br>
presidential polls. Robert Kocharian was declared the official <br>
winner of the polls with 88.9 percent of the votes, ahead of Boris <br>
Aroushanians 7.05 percent and Hrand Melkoumians four percent.<br>
<p>
<p>
5. GEORGIAN CENTRAL BANK DELEGATION ARRIVES IN YEREVAN<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-Chief of the Georgian Central Banks <br>
Department for Control, Levan Kistauri, and his deputy, Gotcha <br>
Toutberidze arrived in Yerevan Sunday for a one-day visit.<br>
	They had a number of meetings in Armenias Central Bank to <br>
outline the terms of cooperation between the central financial <br>
institutions of the two countries.<br>
	The Georgian delegation left for Turkmenistans capital of <br>
Ashkhabad Monday.<br>
<p>
<p>
6. WORLD BANK FLAGSHIP PROJECT  IMPLEMENTED IN ARMENIA<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-The World Bank will help in the restoration <br>
of socially important establishments in Armenia.<br>
	This project is one of the twelve World Bank flagship <br>
projects in the world.<br>
	Reconstruction of Russias coal sector and restoration of <br>
Turkeys irrigation system are some of the other World Bank <br>
projects, Director of the Armenian Fund for Social Investments <br>
Gagik Khachatrian said.<br>
	He noted that one of the main tasks is the development of a <br>
partnership on a communal level. Communities cooperate with state <br>
and private sectors, which result in the development of small <br>
businesses and construction of schools and highways. "We should <br>
join this movement and prepare the communities for solving their <br>
problems independently," Khachatrian said.<br>
	Social investment funds, each of which has its own priority <br>
directions, act in different countries. They are mainly working on <br>
projects aimed at solving water supply problems. However, these <br>
kind of projects are of less importance in Armenia. Armenian <br>
citizens first of all wish to solve the educational problems so <br>
the reconstruction of schools is very important to them.<br>
	Presently the construction of socially important <br>
establishments is being made possible by a $2.5 million grant by <br>
the Holland government and $12 million credit by the WB.<br>
<p>
<p>
7. UNHCR OUTLINES ACTIVITIES IN ARMENIA<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-United Nations High Commissioner for <br>
Refugees mission director in Yerevan, Viviane Dawalibi, held a <br>
news conference Tuesday outlining the UNHCRs activities in <br>
Armenia.<br>
	Dawalibi said that $15 million has been spent on the <br>
implementation of programs in Armenia since 1992.<br>
	Dawalibi said that according to the official data, 300,000 <br>
refugees are currently living in the republic, 150,000 of which <br>
need urgent assistance. In addition, 65 percent of the refugees <br>
are women, she noted. The number of unemployed refugees is also <br>
great.<br>
	She also said that the majority of the refugees are still <br>
living in communal centers, damaged buildings, basements and <br>
trailers. The issue of citizenship of the refugees has not been <br>
solved because mechanisms of citizenship acquisition have not been <br>
put in order.<br>
	Dawalibi underlined the necessity of cooperation with <br>
Armenian public organizations dealing with problems of refugees.<br>
<p>
<p>
8. TESTIMONY ELEVATES INCONCISTANCIES<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-Mondays testimony in the so-called "Trial <br>
of 31" raised questions between the official version of the <br>
alleged coup attempt and one defendants testimony of the events <br>
leading up to the death of two police officers in Yerevan.<br>
	All accusations charged against co-defendant Leva Sargssian <br>
are said to be connected to Vardan Manoukian, who is wanted by <br>
police, Judge Davit Avetissian stated after questioning Sargssian <br>
at Mondays court session.<br>
	Avetissian pointed to inconsistencies in the indictment and <br>
testimony. According to the indictment, alleged meetings between <br>
Vahan Hovanessian, Garnik Issagulian, Ashot Avetissian, Gagik <br>
Karapetian and Vardan Manoukian took place at an apartment rented <br>
by a female acquaintance of Sargssian, Ginarpi Simonian, who was <br>
called to the court as a witness.<br>
	Avetissian also pointed to the alleged transportation of <br>
guns in Sargssians car. The weapons were reportedly kept in <br>
Sargssians house, then transferred to Karapet Gazarians home and <br>
later to Ofik Assikians garage-all of whom are defendants in the <br>
case. When the arms were taken to Sourenavan, an incident took <br>
place on the Leningrad highway in Yerevan and two police officers <br>
were killed, according to the court documents.<br>
	Sargssian said that Manoukian called the meetings in <br>
Simonians apartment, and that neither he nor Simonian were <br>
present.<br>
	With regard to the alleged shipment of guns, Sargssian <br>
insisted that he went to a casual meeting in a village near <br>
Hrazdan at the invitation of Manoukian. However, returning from <br>
the village, Manoukian asked him to take the guns to Yerevan <br>
saying that it was perfectly legal because the guns were <br>
designated for Karabakh. Manoukian insisted that the guns remain <br>
at Sargssians house. Several days later, according to Sargssians <br>
testimony, Manoukian took the guns without checking to see if all <br>
the weapons were accounted for.<br>
	According to Sargssian, the majority of his testimony <br>
coincides with those given by other defendants. However, he noted <br>
that the investigators did not take exact notes and based their <br>
investigation on the coup detat version.<br>
	Sargssian stated that he had not heard anything about the <br>
coup from his co-defendants. He also said he could not understand <br>
how his testimony could be used for the confirmation of that <br>
version.<br>
	He said the investigators threatened to arrest his brother, <br>
Edward Sargssian, who was jailed for three days and later <br>
released.<br>
	Leva Sargssian is currently suffering from a heart <br>
condition.<br>
<p>
<p>
9. IRAN, ARMENIA, GEORGIA, GREECE SIGN AGREEMENT<br>
<p>
TEHRAN (Xinhua)-Iran, Armenia, Georgia and Greece set guidelines <br>
for quadrilateral cooperation by setting up five working <br>
committees.<br>
	The four countries finalized three memoranda which will be <br>
signed by foreign ministers of the four countries in Athens in <br>
January.<br>
	The five working committees will include government <br>
officials and experts of the four countries and will explore ways <br>
of cooperation in the fields of transportation, <br>
telecommunications, energy, trade, industry and tourism.<br>
	The representatives of the four countries ruled out the <br>
possibility of launching a military cooperation program among the <br>
four countries, declaring that their cooperation is a purely <br>
economic one and is not against any other countries, clearly <br>
referring to Turkey and Azerbaijan.<br>
	Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati said, "This <br>
economic cooperation serves to bring regional countries closer <br>
together but it is not against any other country."<br>
	Georgian Deputy Foreign Minister Malkhaz Kakabadzadeh said <br>
at a press conference that the intent of this cooperation is quite <br>
peaceful. "We never talked about machine-guns and tanks in this <br>
gathering," he said.<br>
	"We are here to talk about economy and economic cooperation. <br>
Economic cooperation is much better than military cooperation," <br>
Konstantin Gorio of the Greek Foreign Ministry said.<br>
	Observers noted that the close cooperation of the four <br>
countries is politically important.<br>
	The Iranian government, unhappy and worried about the close <br>
ties between Turkey and Israel, is trying to have close relations <br>
with the four countries in a bid to find an alternative route to <br>
Europe.<br>
<p>
<p>
