<title>Groong Network: Turkey/CenAsia Highlights 12/05/96</title>
<h1>Turkey/CenAsia Highlights 12/05/96</h1>
Mher Sassouni (<i>as080@lafn.org</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 5 Dec 96 13:33:25 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#40">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#40">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#40">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#40">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0041.html">ASBAREZ-ON-LINE: "ASBAREZ-ON-LINE [12-05-96]"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0039.html">Mher Sassouni: "Turkey/CenAsia Highlights 12/04/96"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
	+&gt; 315 Iraqi Kurds evacuated to Turkey  <br>
	+&gt; Turkey boycotts IMO meeting on safety  <br>
	+&gt; Turkish report slams prison forces  <br>
	+&gt; Armenian premier visits London  <br>
	+&gt; Turkey to ship spare to Iraq  <br>
                               ======	 <br>
 315 Iraqi Kurds evacuated to Turkey<br>
	A first 315 Iraqi Kurds in a new U.S.-planned evacuation<br>
arrived Wednesday in Turkey from northern Iraq, Turkey's Foreign<br>
Ministry said.  The operation was the third evacuation of Kurds<br>
who worked for U.S.- funded aid agencies in northern Iraq, the<br>
ministry said. The refugees were bused across the southeast<br>
Turkish border, near the border town of Silopi, and will be<br>
flown later in the week to the Pacific island of Guam, a<br>
ministry spokesman told United Press International. U.S. and<br>
Turkish officials plan to evacuate altogether 4,500 Kurdish men,<br>
women and children. The breadwinners in the families had worked<br>
for U.S.- funded humanitarian programs in the Kurdish autonomous<br>
zone of northern Iraq. They have feared for their lives since<br>
Aug. 31, when Iraqi government forces intervened on the side of<br>
one Kurdish faction against another vying for control of the<br>
region. The ministry spokesman said that the United States is<br>
scheduled Friday to start flying the Kurds to Guam and that the<br>
entire evacuation was likely to last 15 days.<br>
	The United States evacuated about 2,000 U.S.-employed<br>
Kurds in mid- September and 700 more a month later. They were<br>
eventually flown to Anderson Air Force Base on Guam.<br>
                               ======<br>
 Turkey boycotts IMO meeting on safety<br>
	LONDON, Dec. 5 (UPI) -- Turkey has walked out of a<br>
meeting of the International Maritime Organization, IMO, because<br>
the agenda included two papers proposing scrutiny of vessel<br>
navigation along the Bosporos, the shipping daily Lloyd's List<br>
reported Thursday. The IMO maritime safety committee's meeting<br>
was held in London Wednesday. The daily said Russia had called<br>
on the London-based IMO to send an international mission to the<br>
Bosporus to assess whether the organization's rules and<br>
regulations on navigation in the waterway were being<br>
observed. However, the Turkish delegation to IMO warned it would<br>
not participate in the meeting if the issue remained as part of<br>
the debate. The Turkish delegation said that proposals by both<br>
the Russian Federation and the Oil Companies' International<br>
Marine Forum were political maneuvering.  The latter had called<br>
for amended rules governing the safety of navigation in the<br>
straits of Istanbul and Canakkale. Turkey said it was IMO's job<br>
to concentrate on purely technical and safety issues.<br>
	The daily said the committee's chairman Giulino<br>
Pattofatto said the committee was obliged to consider operation<br>
of the IMO rules and regulations covering the straits. The<br>
issues would be discussed and a report drawn up by the end of<br>
the week, he said.<br>
                               ======<br>
 Turkish report slams prison forces<br>
	An inquiry has found that 68 security officers who<br>
intervened in a prison riot used excessive force and should be<br>
tried in the deaths of 10 prisoners, a Turkish parliamentarian<br>
said Wednesday. Musa Okcu said the National Assembly's rights<br>
committee said the inquiry found that some of the prisoners in<br>
the Sept. 24 riot at Diyarbakir prison had even been assaulted<br>
on their way to a hospital. The case should be referred to a<br>
civil court away from Diyarbakir, the virtual capital of<br>
southeastern Turkey, to ``unveil the truth, satisfy public<br>
opinion and deter other human rights violators,'' Okcu told<br>
United Press International. Okcu, a parliamentarian from the<br>
ruling Welfare Party, said the four-person inquiry panel pinned<br>
the blame for the 10 prisoners' deaths Tuesday on 30<br>
paramilitary officers and 38 policemen who put down the<br>
riot. The report accused them of ``exceeding the limits set by<br>
the law and killing and injuring inmates,'' Okcu said. It<br>
recommended they be charged with murder, attempted murder and<br>
causing injuries.<br>
                               ======<br>
 Armenian premier visits London<br>
	Armenian Prime Minister Armen Sarkisyan started his<br>
seven-days visit to London, the Russian news agency reported<br>
Thursday. Sarkisyan explained the aim of the visit as presenting<br>
letters of recall of the Armenian ambassador to Britain. He<br>
noted that during his visit he will meet with top officials of<br>
the British Government and hold talks with the leadership of the<br>
European Bank of Reconstruction and Development.  During the<br>
talks the sides will consider a number issues of granting<br>
credits to Armenia, the agency said.<br>
	Sarkisyan occupied this post from 1992 to 1996 when he<br>
headed the Armenian government.<br>
                               ======<br>
 Turkey to ship spare to Iraq<br>
	The United Nations diplomats, in a meeting of sanction<br>
committee on Dec.3, allowed Turkey to ship spare parts and<br>
equipment to Iraq to repair of the Kirkuk-Yumurtalik pipeline,<br>
the Turkish officials reported Thursday. The spare parts and<br>
equipments are to be used to ensure that the pipe line will be<br>
operable to carry Iraqi oil during the first phase of the<br>
UN-Iraq oil -for-food sale. Within the frame work on UN Security<br>
Council Resolution No. 986, the implementation which enables<br>
Iraq to sell oil worth 2 million over a period of six months,<br>
will be underway this month.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
