<title>Groong Network: Turkey/CenAsia Highlights 12/04/96</title>
<h1>Turkey/CenAsia Highlights 12/04/96</h1>
Mher Sassouni (<i>as080@lafn.org</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 5 Dec 96 13:32:40 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#39">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#39">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#39">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#39">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0040.html">Mher Sassouni: "Turkey/CenAsia Highlights 12/05/96"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0038.html">Mher Sassouni: "Turkey/CenAsia Highlights 12/03/96"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
	+&gt; Iran envoy blasts Israel-Turkey accord  <br>
	+&gt; Russia, Iran to boost quake cooperation  <br>
	+&gt; Turks said to kill 105 separatist Kurds  <br>
	+&gt; Iran, Uzbekistan expand scientific ties  <br>
                               ======	 <br>
 Iran envoy blasts Israel-Turkey accord<br>
	Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati concluded<br>
his visit to Syria with fresh criticism of a renewed military<br>
accord between Israel and Turkey, a government-run Syrian<br>
newspaper said Wednesday. ``We strongly oppose any accord<br>
concluded between Muslim countries and the Zionist entity,''<br>
Velayati told the Ath-Thawra daily before leaving Damascus after<br>
a two-day visit. He was referring to a renewal, signed last<br>
week, of a military training accord that had sparked protests<br>
from Turkey's Muslim neighbors, particularly Syria, Iraq and<br>
Iran. ``It is clear that such an accord is not in the interest<br>
of the Muslim world,'' Velayati said. ``We have announced our<br>
protest and rejection of such an accord.'' Velayati met<br>
President Hafez Assad, Foreign Minister Farouk Sharaa and other<br>
high officials during his visit. The talks focused on the Middle<br>
East peace process, growing Syrian-Israeli military tension and<br>
the Kurdish cease-fire in northern Iraq, officials said.<br>
                               ======<br>
 Russia, Iran to boost quake cooperation<br>
	Russia was taking steps Wednesday to improve cooperation<br>
with Iran over earthquake warnings and disaster control, the<br>
government-run news agency Itar-Tass said. Russian Energy<br>
Situations Minister Sergei Shoigu was in Tehran for talks with<br>
Iranian Interior Ministry officials on enhanced cooperation, the<br>
agency said. His talks ran parallel to four days of meetings in<br>
Moscow by the Russian-Iran trade and economic cooperation<br>
commission. It was the first time the commission had met since<br>
the collapse of the Soviet Union in 1991. Shoigu plans to fly<br>
from Tehran, Iran's capital, on Friday to Baghdad, for talks<br>
with Iraqi leaders, the agency said. Also Friday, a Russian<br>
plane is scheduled to deliver 15 tons of medicine and 10 tons of<br>
other humanitarian supplies to the Iraqi capital.<br>
                               ======<br>
 Turks said to kill 105 separatist Kurds<br>
	Turkish troops have killed 105 Kurdish rebels in the<br>
southeast in the last four days, the Anatolian News Agency said<br>
Tuesday. The Emergency Law Governor's Office told the agency<br>
that the clashes had occurred in Diyarbakir and Batman<br>
provinces, about 450 miles (720 km) southeast of Ankara, the<br>
capital. Five soldiers were reported wounded in the clashes, the<br>
agency said. There was no independent confirmation of the<br>
tolls. At least 21,000 people have been killed and many more<br>
wounded since insurgents began their campaign to carve a<br>
separate Kurdistan out of southeastern Turkey in 1984.<br>
                               ======<br>
 Iran, Uzbekistan expand scientific ties<br>
	Iran and Uzbekistan signed an agreement for expansion of<br>
cultural relations, the Iranina news agency reported<br>
Tuesday. The agreement was reached during a meeting between<br>
Uzbek Deputy Minister of Culture, Kozyrev, and visiting Iranian<br>
Deputy Foreign Minister for research- training affairs, Abbas<br>
Maleki. Maleki, who is in Uzbekistan to attend the opening<br>
ceremony of an exhibition of manuscripts and royal edicts<br>
relating to the Tamerlane Period (14th-15th century). He<br>
announced Iran's readiness to contribute to the ceremonies<br>
marking the 2,500th anniversary of the Central Asian cities of<br>
Bukhara and Khiva which are in Modern Uzbekistan. Maleki also<br>
pointed out that Iran is planning to open classes of Uzbek<br>
language at Iranian universities and is ready to help boost<br>
Persian language courses in Uzbek universities.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
