<title>Groong Network: Turkey/CenAsia Highlights 12/03/96</title>
<h1>Turkey/CenAsia Highlights 12/03/96</h1>
Mher Sassouni (<i>as080@lafn.org</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 5 Dec 96 13:30:04 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#38">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#38">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#38">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#38">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0039.html">Mher Sassouni: "Turkey/CenAsia Highlights 12/04/96"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0037.html">Asbed Bedrossian: "AP/Reuters headlines to 12/05/96"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
	+&gt; Heavy fighting flares in Tajikistan  <br>
	+&gt; Libya, Azerbaijan sign education accord  <br>
	+&gt; Aliyev: Karabakh is part of Azerbaijan  <br>
                               ======	 <br>
 Heavy fighting flares in Tajikistan<br>
	Fierce fighting between Tajik government and opposition<br>
forces flared for a second straight day Monday in a region east<br>
of the capital Dushanbe, military sources said. Interior<br>
Ministry troops battled about 200 opposition fighters about 90<br>
miles (150 km) east of Dushanbe on the outskirts of the<br>
administrative district seat of Garm, which the Islamic rebels<br>
seized Sunday after a day of fighting. Casualty figures were not<br>
available Monday, but a governmet official said at least eight<br>
troops were killed Sunday in what the U.N. envoy to Tajikistan,<br>
Gert Dietrich Merrem, called the heaviest fighting in recent<br>
months. The U.N. mission issued a statement condemning the<br>
hostilities as the latest violation of cease-fire agreements and<br>
stating that ``according to unconfirmed reports, there are<br>
numerous victims and serious damage to houses.'' The opposition<br>
representative to a joint commission charged with oversight of<br>
the shattered cease-fire and peace agreement signed in Tehran<br>
last year said opposition forces had taken 100 government troops<br>
hostage.  Tajik Vice Premier Abdurakhmon Azimov said the<br>
opposition attacked government posts in Garm as part of a<br>
continuing effort to seize key towns along the road from<br>
Dushanbe east to the Kyrgyz border. In September, opposition<br>
forces took control of the nearby Dhiagatal and Tajikabad<br>
districts and their seats, east of Garm, and last month they<br>
seized Komsomolabad, west of Garm on the road to<br>
Dushanbe. Azimov condemned the opposition offensive as<br>
``genocide against their own people'' and said the<br>
Afghanistan-based opposition leader, Said Abdullo Nuri, should<br>
be held personally responsible.<br>
                               ======<br>
 Libya, Azerbaijan sign education accord<br>
	Libya and Azerbaijan have signed an agreement in Tripoli<br>
on cooperation in the fields of education and scientific<br>
research, the Libyan news agency Jana said Tuesday. The accord<br>
was signed by a senior official in the Libyan General People's<br>
Committee for Education and Scientific Research and a visiting<br>
Azerbaijani deputy education minister. It provides for an<br>
exchange of expertise and visits and meetings in the areas of<br>
education, scientific research and professional training, the<br>
agency said.<br>
                               ======<br>
 Aliyev: Karabakh is part of Azerbaijan<br>
	Azerbaijani President Heydar Aliyev said, in his speech<br>
to the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe,<br>
OSCE, summit meeting in Lisbon Monday, that independence for the<br>
disputed region of Nagornyy Karabakh is ``unacceptable to<br>
Azerbaijan,'' the Russian Itar- tass news agency said<br>
Tuesday. ``We cannot allow a second Armenian state to be formed<br>
on the territory of Azerbaijan. The Armenian side should finally<br>
recognize that the conflict which it has unleashed,'' Aliyev<br>
said in remarks broadcast on television. Aliyev told Russian<br>
Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin that he was concerned about<br>
Baku and Yerevan's failure to agree the contents of a political<br>
declaration on the status of Nagornyy Karabakh to be adopted by<br>
the Lisbon summit meeting, According to some information<br>
received by ITAR-TASS on the sidelines of the meeting,<br>
Azerbaijan warned that it may block the adoption of the<br>
declaration if no consensus is reached on the Karabakh issue.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
