<title>Groong Network: Noyan Tapan News (December 4)</title>
<h1>Noyan Tapan News (December 4)</h1>
Armen Martirossyan (<i>martiros@scf-fs.usc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 5 Dec 96 11:55:25 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#35">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#35">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#35">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#35">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0036.html">Barlow DerMugrdechian: "ARS Armenian Summer Studies 1997"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0034.html">nt@nt.arminco.com: "Noyan Tapan News (December 4)"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
1. Azerbaijan Lost The War Of Vetoes<br>
------------------------------------<br>
   Lisbon Summit Accepted No Resolution On Gharabagh<br>
<p>
     YEREVAN ("Hayastani Hanrapetutyun" daily), 12/04/96  --  The <br>
Lisbon Summit of OSCE finished yesterday. The  negotiations  were <br>
in an extremely tense atmosphere. <br>
     One of the possible causes of the  failure  of  negotiations <br>
was  Azerbaijan's  position  on  putting  a  veto  on  the  final <br>
declaration of the Lisbon summit. This eight page declaration was <br>
a conclusion of OSCE's two years work. No  coordinated  work  has <br>
been done in preparations  to  the  summit  in  regard  with  the <br>
Gharabagh  conflict,  and  Azerbaijan  unilaterally  stopped  the <br>
negotiation with Armenia. <br>
     In addition to this, Azerbaijan was pressing on OSCE, trying <br>
to  enforce  a  document   affirming   Azerbaijan's   territorial <br>
integrity and mentioning Gharabagh as a part of Azerbaijan.  Note <br>
that the other parts  of  the  declaration  affirmed  territorial <br>
integrity of Russia, Georgia, and Moldova,  therefore  Azerbaijan <br>
has put an enormous effort to  reach  a  similar  result  in  its <br>
regard. <br>
     Chairman of OSCE tried to find a consensus  between  Armenia <br>
and Azerbaijan, stressing that the conflict  should  be  resolved <br>
based on the  guarantees  of  self-determination  of  Mountainous <br>
Gharabagh and the security of its population,  affirming  at  the <br>
same time territorial integrity of Armenia  and  Azerbaijan,  and <br>
stressing that Mountainous Gharabagh should have highest possible <br>
sovereign status as a part of Azerbaijan. <br>
     As long as such formula was not acceptable for Armenia,  our <br>
delegation vetoed the 20th paragraph of the declaration,  whereas <br>
Azerbaijan, in response to  this,  has  put  veto  on  the  whole <br>
declaration. In fact, it failed the  whole  declaration,  reached <br>
through negotiations of the leaders of 55 countries. As a result, <br>
this caused a response pressure  against  the  Azeri  delegation. <br>
Finally, Azerbaijan has lost this war of  vetoes  as  it  had  to <br>
remove its veto, whereas Armenia's veto persisted. <br>
     Chairman, European Union, Russia, and Turkey tried to soften <br>
Azerbaijan's failure, by including  the  vetoed  topic  in  their <br>
declarations. In response  to  this,  Armenia's  President  Levon <br>
Ter-Petrossian made a declaration, stressing the right of nations <br>
for  self-determination  as  the  basic  principle  for  conflict <br>
resolution. <br>
     Finally spoke  Finnish  co-chairman  of  OSCE  Minsk  group, <br>
stressing equality of the principles of the territorial integrity <br>
and the right of nations for self-determination,  and  said  that <br>
the solution should consider all vital interests of the sides  of <br>
conflict. <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
