<title>Groong Network: OSCE Peace-Keeping</title>
<h1>OSCE Peace-Keeping</h1>
Arthur Martirosyan (<i>martiros@hulaw1.harvard.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 4 Dec 1996 20:15:13 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#30">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#30">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#30">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#30">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0031.html">nt-send@nt.arminco.com: "Noyan Tapan News (December 5)"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0029.html">Arthur Martirosyan: "Some details on Lisbon summit statement"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
OSCE peacekeeping: A useful 'harder'option <br>
<p>
edited by Rob Zaagman [1] <br>
<p>
Introduction <br>
<p>
Osce conflict prevention can be considered a `soft' field of activity, since<br>
almost exclusively non-coercive means are employed. Cooperative<br>
implementation of commitments, programmes and measures is the key to the<br>
osce way of doing things. Furthermore, the osce does not make use of military<br>
instruments to achieve its goals. However, the Helsinki Document 1992 does<br>
provide the organisation with the option of fielding peacekeeping operations<br>
(pkos). They are `hard', not in the sense that they are used for coercion<br>
(osce enforcement action is explicitly ruled out in the Helsinki Document),<br>
but in the sense that military forces may be used as an osce instrument. <br>
<p>
The history of the csce/osce shows that the Helsinki process has always been<br>
able to work with only softer options. Nevertheless, there are various<br>
reasons for the osce states to consider exercising `harder' options, in the<br>
first place pkos. <br>
<p>
For one thing, conflict prevention can be necessary at higher levels of the<br>
escalation ladder. Crisis management is also part of the osce's tasks. It is<br>
not defined in osce documents, but can be considered as conflict prevention<br>
in the very last phases of escalation towards violence, i.e. conflict<br>
prevention in a crisis situation. The means to be employed will have to<br>
answer to requirements of urgency and high political investments, perhaps<br>
even more substantial input is needed like emergency aid programmes,<br>
preventive deployment or peacekeeping operations. Osce options for conflict<br>
prevention/peace preservation should therefore encompass the entire range<br>
short of coercive measures to provide the osce with the necessary flexibility. <br>
<p>
For another thing, osce peacekeeping may offer a much more preferable<br>
alternative to bilateral peacekeeping. In general, multilateral peacekeeping<br>
in Europe would be based on osce decisions or undertaken by the osce. (These<br>
remarks are without prejudice to the possible establishment of un<br>
peacekeeping operations in the osce area.) <br>
<p>
A secondary reason is that it will give the osce a higher visibility and<br>
credibility in the eyes of the public which so far perceives the osce as a<br>
weak-bodied talking-shop. <br>
<p>
OSCE PKOs, conflict prevention and crisis management <br>
<p>
In which kinds of pkos should the osce become involved? Proceeding from its<br>
conflict-prevention role, there would seem to be two types of military peace<br>
operations which fit in: preventive deployment like in Macedonia and<br>
post-conflict pkos like (possibly) in Nagorny-Karabakh. (These can be<br>
contrasted with unprofor in Bosnia, which was an example of a pko by the<br>
un taking place during a conflict.) It may be useful to distinguish between<br>
preventive deployment and pre-emptive deployment. Preventive deployment<br>
may take place when there is no acute threat and the situation does not<br>
require quick decisiontaking. Pre-emptive deployment, on the contrary, will<br>
take place when a crisis is imminent and will require speedy decisiontaking. <br>
<p>
For these types of operations, the criteria laid down in the 1992 Helsinki<br>
Document seem useful. The Helsinki Document and the 1993 Rome<br>
Ministerial Council Decisions devote substantial sections to the subject of the<br>
osce and peacekeeping. According to these documents, nato, the Western<br>
European Union (weu) or the Commonwealth of Independent States (cis) may<br>
be requested to provide operational assistance in this field. The principles<br>
and norms elaborated there are, inter alia, the necessary consent of the<br>
parties concerned, impartiality, and the use of force only in self-defence -<br>
the same principles which apply to United Nations pkos with a mandate based<br>
on Chapter vi of the un Charter. <br>
<p>
A move towards more regular osce pkos or a substantial pko capability would<br>
give rise to inter alia the following questions and considerations: <br>
<p>
1) Should the OSCE undertake PKOs itself or should it make use of <br>
<p>
`subcontractors' and if so, which ones? <br>
<p>
To be sure, the osce does not as yet dispose of a regular contingency planning<br>
capability and organisational apparatus to field pkos. The High-Level<br>
Planning Group (hlpg) preparing the Nagorny-Karabakh operation was/is<br>
an ad hoc affair. Osce documents do not offer guidance on these<br>
organisational questions which we think should nevertheless be addressed.<br>
We think that osce peacekeeping is certainly preferable to `bilateral<br>
peacekeeping' (see below). We would have liked to see the Budapest Review<br>
Conference express this preference in a general way. However, the implicit<br>
recognition in the case of Nagorny-Karabakh is also helpful, i.e. the decision,<br>
in principle, on the organisation of a multinational osce peacekeeping force<br>
on the basis of Chapter iii of the Helsinki Document 1992 (Budapest<br>
Document, chapter ii, paragraph 4). <br>
<p>
Conversely, in certain instances the osce could also act as a mandating or<br>
legitimising institution, e.g. on peacekeeping to be implemented by nato, weu<br>
or the Commonwealth of Independent States (cis). Thus, it could cover such<br>
organisations politically with its consensual cloak of impartiality and<br>
legitimacy. This would be one way of dealing with the question of which<br>
international organisation could operate where, i.e. in which region and in<br>
which region not. The osce is impartial (or all-partial) whereas the cis and<br>
nato (or weu or the European Union) are not or are not perceived as such. <br>
<p>
However, such osce blessing would have to be accompanied by certain<br>
preconditions and measures. Note for example that so far Russian so-called<br>
pkos do not answer to the three requirements, in particular consent from the<br>
parties involved. Furthermore, they do not have a formal basis in a cis<br>
decision. Experience shows that such `bilateral peacekeeping' tends to be<br>
coercive, `green' military action more than anything else. As an alternative to<br>
peacekeeping under osce auspices, it cannot be prohibited; perhaps it can be<br>
forestalled, in particular if other states undertake the commitment to<br>
participate in pko operations on the territory of the former Soviet Union. <br>
<p>
At any rate, the osce should insist that in such `bilateral' cases, but also<br>
in multilateral cases under the osce banner, peacekeeping should take place<br>
on the basis of generally accepted principles, including those mentioned<br>
above. In addition, the osce should as a matter of course be permitted to<br>
monitor such operations to check whether they are conducted in accordance<br>
with osce principles and commitments, not just those concerning peacekeeping<br>
but also those pertaining to the human dimension and the politico-military<br>
code of conduct. <br>
<p>
The Rome Council Decisions (chapter ii, paragraph 2) have the following to<br>
say on such monitoring: `The Ministers agreed that the csce could consider,<br>
on a case-by-case basis and under specific conditions, the setting up of csce<br>
co-operative arrangements in order to ensure that the role and functions of a<br>
third party military force in a conflict area are consistent with csce<br>
principles<br>
and objectives' (emphasis added). Paragraph 3 continues the subject: `The<br>
Ministers mandated the cso and the Permanent Committee to further<br>
elaborate conditions and necessary provisions for possible csce arrangements<br>
of this nature. In carrying out this task they will bear in mind the proposals<br>
examined by the cso and be guided inter alia by the following principles and<br>
considerations essential to the csce arrangements as well as the activities<br>
of a third party military force: Respect for sovereignty and territorial<br>
integrity; consent of the parties; impartiality; multinational character;<br>
clear mandate; transparency; integral link to a political process for<br>
conflict resolution; plan for orderly withdrawal'. So far, it has not been<br>
possible to achieve consensus on such arrangements. <br>
<p>
2. Does the OSCE itself need additional legitimacy if it establishes or<br>
mandates a PKO? <br>
<p>
Obviously, if so this blessing would have to come from the un Security<br>
Council (unsc). Formally, no un consent is needed if no enforcement action is<br>
to be undertaken (e.g. the Multilateral Force of Observers (mfo) in Sinai).<br>
Is it then desirable to become dependent on an unsc resolution, like in the<br>
case of the Nagorny-Karabakh pko? An unsc resolution would certainly enhance<br>
the political legitimacy of such an operation, which is an issue separate<br>
from the legal question. Equally, as noted above an osce cloak or umbrella or<br>
legitimisation may politically be necessary, even if formally speaking e.g.<br>
the cis would not need an osce mandate. <br>
<p>
However, there would seem to be a qualitative difference between the osce and<br>
regional organisations or arrangements like the cis (and nato), which we do<br>
not find if we compare the osce with the un, and that is the difference<br>
mentioned under point 1: broad multinationality and (perceived) impartiality.<br>
A un blessing for the osce is therefore politically speaking much less needed,<br>
if at all, than an osce blessing for the cis (or Russia). Therefore, in view<br>
of the<br>
additional obstacles thrown up if the unsc would become involved, in most<br>
cases no un resolution should be sought for an osce pko. (An open question is<br>
whether there are other ways to involve the unsc without the osce and its<br>
operations possibly being hampered or even held hostage by developments in<br>
New York.) <br>
<p>
3. The issue of the composition of a PKO force is in part <br>
<p>
closely connected to the former questions <br>
<p>
The classic un rule is not to have the troops of interested parties included<br>
in a<br>
pko force. Within the osce there is a habit of not including subjects of<br>
neighbouring states in long-term missions in a particular state. One could<br>
even ask whether troops from a state in the same broader region should be<br>
included in a pko in another state in that region. (Specifically, these issues<br>
are acute with regard to the Russian Federation and the `near abroad'.)<br>
However, the converse question arises whether there will be enough states<br>
from outside the region, i.e. without vested interests, willing to<br>
participate in a pko. <br>
<p>
Perhaps the Combined Joint Task Force (cjtf) concept of nato offers a useful<br>
model. In each case of a cjtf mission, the task force will be composed of the<br>
able and willing, who could be nato member-states, states participating in<br>
the Partnership for Peace (including Russia), and neutral states. The Task<br>
Force will make use of elements of nato's integrated structure to which<br>
troops will be attached. Command, logistical and communications procedures<br>
used will be nato's existing ones, which have been tested over decades. <br>
<p>
4. Once the decision to field an operation has been taken, <br>
<p>
the following (and perhaps other) questions arise: <br>
<p>
a) which criteria are needed to determine that the operation will actually go<br>
ahead? <br>
<p>
b) how are military management and control to be organised? <br>
<p>
c) how should political guidance be organised and guaranteed? <br>
<p>
d) could a pko combine military, humanitarian and perhaps other elements? <br>
<p>
With regard to point a, the Helsinki Decisions (chapter iii, paragraph 30)<br>
have the following to offer: `Before the decision to dispatch a mission is<br>
taken,<br>
the following conditions must be fulfilled: - establishment of an effective and<br>
durable cease-fire; - agreement on the necessary Memoranda of<br>
Understanding with the parties concerned, and - provision of guarantees for<br>
the safety at all times of personnel involved'. Paragraph 31 states: `Missions<br>
will be dispatched as soon as possible following such a decision'. In other<br>
words, the criteria of paragraph 30 must be fulfilled before a decision is<br>
taken. Obviously, if the cease-fire would break down (i.e. would prove not to<br>
be durably effective) the mission would not go ahead. <br>
<p>
Point b is answered in paragraphs 39-45 concerning the `Chain of<br>
Command' and the `Head of Mission'. (Of course, the parties concerned could<br>
make their consent dependent on the fulfilment of certain additional criteria.)<br>
In view of recent `lessons learned' in un operations, particular attention will<br>
be devoted to the clarity of the mandate, the unambiguity and unity of<br>
command, the attainability of the objectives and the `robust' quality of the<br>
rules of engagement. <br>
<p>
Political guidance, as mentioned in point c, is dealt with in paragraph 38:<br>
`The Council/cso will regularly review an operation and make any necessary<br>
decision related to its conduct, taking into account political developments and<br>
developments in the field'. <br>
<p>
Helsinki-ii contains a pko model, which so far has not been put into<br>
operational practice. (Planning for an osce-model pko in Nagorny-Karabakh<br>
has been going on for quite some time.) The model could be amended in the<br>
light of future experience; perhaps the lessons which the un is drawing from<br>
its recent experiences could already now be useful. In some instances the<br>
model could certainly do with some elaboration, e.g. with regard to the<br>
financing of operations. <br>
<p>
With regard to the mandate, as raised in point d, the Helsinki Document<br>
states in chapter iii, paragraph 13: `Peacekeeping activities could be used,<br>
inter alia, to supervise and help maintain cease-fires, to monitor troop<br>
withdrawals, to support the maintenance of law and order, to provide<br>
humanitarian and medical aid and to assist refugees." The word `and' in the<br>
last line notwithstanding, the formulation of this paragraph does not make it<br>
entirely clear whether the various elements could be combined in one and the<br>
same mandate. (The words `inter alia' show that this list is non-exhaustive.) <br>
<p>
5. More in general, how can PKOs fit in the overall, <br>
<p>
comprehensive OSCE approach to a certain problem? <br>
<p>
The osce documents do not offer explicit guidance on this issue. Nevertheless,<br>
it is of crucial importance that this question be answered by the participating<br>
states in each and every concrete case in which a peacekeeping operation is<br>
considered. As un experience teaches us, in most cases a pko by itself is an<br>
insufficient response to a problematic situation. The basic assumption<br>
underlying the osce's comprehensive approach, i.e. that a problem has to be<br>
tackled in a coordinated way on many different levels and fields of activity,<br>
reinforces this point. <br>
<p>
The rule of consensus and PKOs <br>
<p>
The question arises whether the osce has the capability to act and to act<br>
quickly enough, in view of the fact that it decides almost all issues by<br>
consensus. One or a few states could effectively block decision-taking. Is there<br>
a way to avoid this? For example, why should a state be allowed to block a<br>
decision on fielding a pko if the parties directly concerned all agree to such<br>
an (osce) operation and if sufficient states are `able and willing' to<br>
contribute<br>
to such an operation? <br>
<p>
Entering into the realm of `hard' options like pkos, we are moving on to<br>
situations in which the consensus rule may stand in the way of timely and<br>
effective decision-making. We do not approach this issue light-heartedly. The<br>
rule of consensus and the principle of sovereign equality of the participating<br>
states guarantee broad political support for decisions taken by the osce. It<br>
avoids a situation in which the osce would be only an instrument of the great<br>
powers, although the Budapest meeting has also shown that without those<br>
powers `nothing goes'. <br>
<p>
At the same time, the rule of consensus turns osce decision-making into a<br>
laborious and slow affair, often leading to watered-down compromises. Except<br>
for the rarest of situations, no sanction other than persuasion and political<br>
pressure is available. The consensus-minus-one rule applies only in<br>
extraordinary cases and so far has been used in only one case. <br>
<p>
In the end, the question is what one would wish to achieve with the osce, and<br>
whether in the light of that ambition the rule of consensus is an advantage or<br>
a drawback. Conflict prevention would not require a change, since in most<br>
cases the cooperation of the states concerned is essential to its success.<br>
(However, sometimes measures can be taken which do not require the<br>
cooperation of the party concerned.) <br>
<p>
One possible nuance, however, could be advantageous, namely the<br>
introduction of the principle of interested states or, better termed perhaps, of<br>
the non-interested states. States which declare themselves to have no interest<br>
in a certain situation or measure or programme would not be bound by the<br>
decisions thus taken and would not participate in the decision-making on<br>
that issue. The risk is that states will withdraw from many osce activities, in<br>
particular when the financial implications are considerable (e.g. in the case<br>
of a pko!). Nevertheless, the possibility of establishing ad hoc groups of<br>
states<br>
as foreseen in the 1992 Helsinki Document points in the same direction. <br>
<p>
It is only if the osce should be able to apply measures against the will of the<br>
state(s) concerned that other decision-making rules could be needed. As far<br>
as decision-taking on pkos is concerned, the following considerations deserve<br>
attention. In the first place, a pko presupposes consent by the parties. The<br>
possibility of a decision on a pko by a qualified majority opens the option for<br>
states to dissociate themselves from a decision without blocking it. States<br>
would then not have to be involved, politically or militarily, in implementing<br>
the pko which would lose credibility and stamina, certainly if it were major<br>
states which would withdraw. <br>
<p>
Furthermore, if `hard options' like pkos could be decided by majority voting,<br>
there would be no reason not to introduce such a procedure in all softer<br>
options as well. Such a development could very well undermine the very<br>
consensual foundations of the osce. Osce decisions would run the risk of not<br>
being implemented at all. (At this point it is useful to realise that such<br>
options<br>
do already exist, e.g. in the framework of the Moscow Mechanism which<br>
provides for the despatch of fact-finding missions even against the will of the<br>
state concerned. However, the existence of this option has never led to the<br>
conclusion or even the argument that such a possibility ought to apply in<br>
other, softer procedures as well.) <br>
<p>
Perhaps the approach through the use of the `able and willing' would be<br>
more fruitful. Before a decision is taken, states would declare their<br>
willingness to participate, a `leading state' being one of them. (These<br>
preconditions apply to every pko.) One example is the Multilateral Force of<br>
Observers (mfo), an ad hoc coalition which was established outside the un<br>
framework because the Soviet Union blocked the formation of a un force for<br>
the purpose of monitoring the post-1967 cease-fire in the Middle East. <br>
<p>
<p>
<p>
Footnotes<br>
<p>
[1]. This report has been produced by an independent working group of the<br>
Netherlands Helsinki Committee as a contribution to the discussions<br>
concerning the security model for the 21st century. The report was written<br>
and edited by Rob Zaagman on the basis of discussions in a working group<br>
consisting of the following persons: Herman Amelink, Arie Bloed, Ige Dekker,<br>
Cees Homan, Jaap de Hoop Scheffer, Wilco de Jonge, Marjanne de<br>
Kwaasteniet, Eimert van Middelkoop, Rob Siekmann, Peter Volten and Rob<br>
Zaagman. <br>
<p>
(end)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
