<title>Groong Network: Some details on Lisbon summit statement</title>
<h1>Some details on Lisbon summit statement</h1>
Arthur Martirosyan (<i>martiros@hulaw1.harvard.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 4 Dec 1996 19:21:34 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#29">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#29">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#29">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#29">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0030.html">Arthur Martirosyan: "OSCE Peace-Keeping"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0028.html">Arthur Martirosyan: "More on Lisbon summit"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
 <br>
Agence France Presse<br>
December 03, 1996<br>
<p>
LISBON, Dec 3 (AFP) - Negotiators at a summit of the pan-European <br>
security body the OSCE failed Tuesday to break a deadlock between <br>
Armenia and Azerbaijan blocking accord on a summit declaration, a <br>
diplomat said. <br>
<p>
Their conclusions were to be presented to the heads of state and <br>
government for their consideration, but it was "unlikely" that they <br>
could agree a final declaration, the source said. <br>
<p>
"It is unlikely we will have this document, the diplomat said, referring <br>
to the final political document of the two-day summit of the <br>
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE). <br>
<p>
Because unanimity is required for the final declaration, the dispute <br>
jeopardizes the overall accord due to be announced at a closing press <br>
conference at 1330 GMT. <br>
<p>
The last OSCE summit in Budapest two years ago collapsed in chaos after <br>
delegates failed to agree a resolution on Bosnia-Hercegovina, in <br>
particular because of Russian disagreement. <br>
<p>
Armenia and Azerbaijan are locked in a dispute over Nagorno-Karabakh, a <br>
predominantly Armenian-populated enclave inside Azerbaijan. <br>
<p>
More than 20,000 people have been killed since inter-ethnic fighting <br>
erupted in 1988. <br>
<p>
US envoy to the summit John Kornblum said shortly before that he still <br>
held out hope for an agreement. <br>
<p>
"As happened in the past in OSCE meetings individual countries with <br>
individual concerns are continuing to want their concerns met before <br>
they approve the documents and this is the situation now," he said. <br>
<p>
"I go into these things presuming success," he said, but added: "It's <br>
impossible to predict what will happen ... great efforts are being <br>
made." <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
