<title>Groong Network: ASBAREZ-ON-LINE [12-04-96]</title>
<h1>ASBAREZ-ON-LINE [12-04-96]</h1>
ASBAREZ-ON-LINE (<i>76635.2505@CompuServe.COM</i>)<br>
<i>04 Dec 96 18:17:55 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#27">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#27">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#27">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#27">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0028.html">Arthur Martirosyan: "More on Lisbon summit"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0026.html">Asbed Bedrossian: "AGBU Intern Program"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
ASBAREZ ON LINE <br>
12/04/1996<br>
<p>
<p>
1. OSCE CHAIRMAN SIDES WITH AZERBAIJAN AFTER SUMMIT<br>
2. KIVIRIAN ENDS HUNGER STRIKE<br>
3. SICU APPLAUDS EUROPARLIAMENT RESOLUTION<br>
4. TEHRAN-ARMENIANS VOICE PROTEST<br>
5. ARMENIAN STUDENTS TURNED BACK AT CONSULATE<br>
<p>
<p>
1. OSCE CHAIRMAN SIDES WITH AZERBAIJAN AFTER SUMMIT<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-The final declaration of the Lisbon Summit <br>
of the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe does <br>
not include the paragraph which deals with the status of Nagorno-<br>
Karabakh.<br>
	"It is widely known that no advance has been registered over <br>
the last two years in the Karabakh problem. I express my regret <br>
that efforts by the Minsk Group co-chairmen to reconcile the <br>
conflicting sides have not been successful," OSCE chairman Flavio <br>
Cotti said in a statement following the two-day summit this week.<br>
	"The territorial integrity of Azerbaijan and Armenia, the <br>
status of autonomy of Nagorno-Karabakh on the territory of <br>
Azerbaijan and guarantees of security of Nagorno-Karabakh should <br>
lie on the basis of the settlement of the Karabakh conflict and <br>
all member states of the Minsk Group believe it so," Molorak <br>
[Planet] newspaper quoted Cotti as saying.<br>
	The proposed paragraph on Nagorno-Karabakh was not accepted <br>
by the Armenian delegation.<br>
	"We achieved what we wanted to, and the final document <br>
adopted at the Lisbon Summit lacked the decision Azerbaijan was <br>
seeking for the past three months," said Deputy Foreign Minister <br>
of Armenia Vartan Oskanian.<br>
	Oskanian noted that the opinion of the international <br>
community on the territorial integrity issue to a certain extent <br>
coincides with that of Azerbaijan. Co-chairmen and members of the <br>
Minsk Group, as well as member states of the OSCE advocated that <br>
viewpoint, but its one thing to express that viewpoint and <br>
another to adopt a resolution during negotiations, Oskanian said.<br>
	The European Union spoke out in support of Azerbaijan. The <br>
EU representative at the summit said his group fully supported the <br>
20th paragraph mentioning the territorial integrity of Azerbaijan. <br>
The Turkish representative voiced support for Azerbaijan as well.<br>
	Russian Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin, standing in for <br>
President Boris Yeltsin, said that the 20th paragraph served as a <br>
solid base for further negotiations.<br>
	Negotiations between Azerbaijan and Armenia over Nagorno-<br>
Karabakh hit a brick wall with no hint of a breakthrough in sight.<br>
	Forced into action by the threat of Azerbaijan vetoing the <br>
entire final summit declaration, international mediators agreed to <br>
drop all reference to the dispute from the closing document and <br>
issued a separate statement on it instead.<br>
	Levon Ter-Petrosyan sat stony-faced at the final session of <br>
the OSCE meeting. Azeri President Gaidar Aliyev, who dropped his <br>
veto threat, hailed his success.<br>
	"I am very satisfied," Aliyev told a news conference.<br>
	Ter-Petrosyan, by contrast, canceled a planned news <br>
conference.<br>
	Azerbaijan wanted its territorial integrity reaffirmed in <br>
the final summit statement. It also sought support for demands to <br>
define Nagorno-Karabakhs legal status clearly, based on the right <br>
to self-determination and guarantees over its security. Armenia <br>
blocked Azerbaijans demands, earning the wrath of other states at <br>
the closing session, including Russia.<br>
	Azerbaijans demands were included in the separate statement <br>
drawn up to the indignation of Ter-Petrosyan.<br>
	He has said "unilateral solutions" must not be imposed over <br>
Karabakh. <br>
	"I would like to express concern in connection with this <br>
statement. In our view it does not reflect the spirit and the <br>
letter of the Minsk Group," Ter-Petrosyan said.<br>
	His comments made clear the leaders left Lisbon as far apart <br>
on Nagorno-Karabakh as when they arrived.<br>
<p>
<p>
2. KIVIRIAN ENDS HUNGER STRIKE<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-Late Tuesday evening, Argishti Kivirian, an <br>
Abkhazian citizen arrested during the post-presidential election <br>
crackdown in Yerevan, ended his 15-day hunger strike.<br>
	According to Vladimir [Vova] Hakhverdian of the National <br>
Democratic Union, Kivirian ended his hunger strike after learning <br>
about his sisters solidarity hunger strike.<br>
	Kivirians health has seriously deteriorated and Armenias <br>
Prosecutor General Artavazd Gevorkian has assured that all <br>
necessary measures to restore his health will be taken, <br>
Hakhverdian said.<br>
	Armenika Kivirian stopped her 6-day-long hunger strike as <br>
well.<br>
	Hakhverdian said the preliminary investigation into the <br>
Sept. 25 events has been delayed by two months.<br>
	Kivirian began  the hunger strike on Nov. 19 from his cell <br>
in the Noubarashen prison.<br>
	His sister who joined the solidarity hunger strike called by <br>
relatives of other detainees, was ordered to be hospitalized after <br>
eight days.<br>
	Armenias Health Minister Ara Babloyan ordered the immediate <br>
hospitalization of Kivirians sister, also a citizen of Abkhazia, <br>
Hakhverdian said.<br>
	Chief warden of the Noubarashen prison falsly reported to <br>
the prosecutor that Kivirian had ended the strike since he was <br>
smoking, Hakhverdian said.<br>
<p>
<p>
3. SICU APPLAUDS EUROPARLIAMENT RESOLUTION<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)- "The presidential and local elections of <br>
1996 marked the end of the formation of illegitimate power in <br>
Armenia which started during the parliamentary elections and the <br>
referendum on the Constitution last year," the Scientific-<br>
Industrial and Civil Union said Tuesday in a statement addressed <br>
to the European Parliament, Council of Europe and member states of <br>
the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe and its <br>
Office of Democratic Institutions and Human Rights.<br>
	The statement criticized the Constitutional Courts handling <br>
of the opposition candidates petitions, saying that the court did <br>
not pay attention to the final report of the OSCE observers, which <br>
had served as the basis for SICU chairman and presidential <br>
candidate Ashot Manucharian's petition.<br>
	The SICU leadership said the court simply organized a formal <br>
scrutiny of only 13 of the 45 precincts mentioned in the OSCE <br>
report, questioned only nine witnesses and did not consider <br>
violations committed before and during the voting. It only <br>
verified the summarized data of the Central Electoral Commission.<br>
	The SICU Council called on the international community to <br>
actively participate in and pay close attention to the <br>
Constitutional Court of Armenia.<br>
	In addition, the SICU called on European institutions to pay <br>
more attention to the crisis of legitimate power in Armenia and <br>
asked for the immediate suspension of financial assistance to the <br>
"illegitimate and corrupted regime."<br>
<p>
<p>
4. TEHRAN-ARMENIANS VOICE PROTEST<br>
<p>
TEHRAN (Alik)-A capacity crowd turned out at "Ararat" stadium <br>
"Sasountsi Davit" hall Friday to hear Armenian Revolutionary <br>
Federation Executive Council of Armenia member and other <br>
academicians who spoke about the ongoing threat to democracy in <br>
Armenia.<br>
	At the conclusion of the gathering, a protest resolution was <br>
adopted calling for new presidential elections in Armenia, the <br>
immediate release of all Armenian political prisoners and an end <br>
to the persecution of opposition leaders.<br>
	The hall was filled to capacity and many were forced to <br>
follow the program standing up or from the outside entryway.<br>
	A representative of the Armenian National Committee of Iran <br>
formally convened the program, saying that the imperative in <br>
Armenia today was the non-existence of leadership and the <br>
continued insistence by a self-proclaimed leader who rejected the <br>
will of the people.<br>
	A brief description of events following the presidential <br>
election and leading to the opposition rallies which were <br>
disbursed by gunfire from troops ordered into the city by the <br>
president and his authorities.<br>
	A videotape was then presented chronicling the events in <br>
Armenia, following which a message to the Iranian-Armenian <br>
community from opposition candidate Vazgen Manoukian was <br>
broadcast.<br>
	Organizers of the rally had called Manoukian earlier that <br>
day and had asked him to convey his thoughts to the Iranian <br>
Armenian-community.<br>
	The ARF Executive Council of Armenia member Vartan <br>
Petrossian then addressed the gathering, describing the current <br>
political climate in Armenia prior and following the presidential <br>
election, outlining the posturing and positions of the opposition.<br>
	Renowned poetess and academician Silva Kapoutikian was <br>
presented and prior to her remarks, poetess Silva Youzbashian <br>
recited several of Kapoutikians timeless works.<br>
	In her remarks, Kapoutikian captivated the audience by <br>
recounting the issues of importance to the Armenian people.<br>
	"Diaspora, with its existence and stability," Kapoutikian <br>
said, is a natural resource replacing the waterways and the oil <br>
which Armenia lacks.<br>
	"The belief is strengthened every time I travel abroad, and <br>
it was once again reinforced in me when I visited your community <br>
center. When I visited your schools, kindergartens I saw in them <br>
your national institutions, and todays gathering is enough for me <br>
to remember for several years to come that we have won, we are <br>
winning and we will win," remarked Kapoutikian.<br>
	At the conclusion of the gathering the protest resolution <br>
was read and approved through thunderous applause.<br>
<p>
<p>
5. ARMENIAN STUDENTS TURNED BACK AT CONSULATE<br>
<p>
BY SEBOUH SIMONIAN<br>
Asbarez Staff Writer<br>
<p>
BEVERLY HILLS-A group of Armenian-American youth arrived at the <br>
Consulate of the Republic of Armenia in Beverly Hills last Tuesday <br>
with intentions of delivering a letter to Consul-General Armen <br>
Baibourtian who was not in the office to accept the letter.<br>
	Baibourtian left for Yerevan Monday and was scheduled to <br>
return Tuesday, according to receptionist Hagop Hovanessian, who <br>
spoke with Meroujan S. Kitsinian and Lilith Davitian of the youth <br>
group.<br>
	[Eds: Baibourtian made an appearance Sunday at St. Marys <br>
Armenian Apostolic Church in Glendale during Mass.]<br>
	Kitsinian, 26, informed the receptionist that the group had <br>
been notified on Monday that Baibourtian would be in the office <br>
when the group arrived the following day.<br>
	Hovanessian suggested to the group to either leave the <br>
letter at the office or return at a later date.<br>
	The letter signed by a group of concerned Armenian-American <br>
youth addressed concerns about the recent presidential elections <br>
in Armenia, mainly criticizing the Constitutional Court. In regard <br>
to the courts rejection of a petition by the opposition to <br>
nullify the results of the recent presidential elections and hold <br>
a new election, the letter stated that the court has been "very <br>
much a part of the entire effort by the administration to, at all <br>
costs, maintain the stranglehold on the Armenian people and <br>
continue the persecution of innocent citizens of Armenia."<br>
	"We are extremely discouraged by the actions of Armenias <br>
current authorities and wish to voice severe discontent for the <br>
violation of human and individual rights which have occurred at <br>
the hands of Levon Ter-Petrosyan and his regime," the letter <br>
stated.<br>
	Davitian, a senior at UCLA, said that "Armenians must not <br>
stay indifferent about what is going in Armenia. Concerned <br>
Armenians need to go out and do their best to help Armenia become <br>
a truly democratic country."<br>
	"The people of America recently experienced a very <br>
democratic election where every citizen freely cast their vote," <br>
Kitsinian said. <br>
	"Armenians in Armenia have been deprived of this basic human <br>
right to elect their own officials. In addition, members of <br>
opposition parties have been subjected to imprisonment and <br>
beatings. We [concerned Armenians] will continue to make demands <br>
because we firmly believe in the democratic process," the letter <br>
read.<br>
<p>
