PRESS RELEASE<br>
<p>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<br>
	November 25, 1996<br>
	Contact:  Talar Sesetyan<br>
<p>
AGBU New York Summer Intern Program<br>
31 W. 52nd Street<br>
New York, NY 10019<br>
(212) 765-8260<br>
(212)765-5414 (fax)<br>
<p>
"This program is one of the most beneficial programs sponsored through th<br>
e AGBU in aiding the future of our people because it is solely aimed at h<br>
elping the educated young prepare for their careers.  It brings together <br>
hand-picked intelligent Armenian students who each stimulate and enhance <br>
each other's knowledge and interests."<br>
		--Gassia Apkarian, AGBU Intern Alumni<br>
<p>
The AGBU New York Summer Intern Program is how accepting applications for<br>
the 1997 summer program.  The AGBU Intern Program is designed to establi<br>
sh professional opportunities for ethnic Armenians living in the United S<br>
tates and abroad.  Now in its 10th year, the AGBU Intern Program combines<br>
summer employment in New York with a full schedule of educational, cultu<br>
ral and social activities.<br>
<p>
Each summer, approximately thirty-five undergraduate and graduate student<br>
s, age 19 to 30, are chosen by the AGBU to participate in this highly sel<br>
ective program.  Although, the majority of participants hail from the Uni<br>
ted States, this program has also hosted Sudan's from Argentina, Armenia,<br>
Australia, Austria, Belgium, Bulgaria, Canada, England, France, Lebanon,<br>
Turkey, and Switzerland.  Students submit academic transcripts, letters <br>
of recommendation, and writing samples for review by an admissions commit<br>
tee.  International applicants are additionally required to demonstrate f<br>
luency in English by oral examination.  applicants are evaluated based on<br>
academic achievement, motivation to pursue a professional career, and a <br>
desire to represent the interests of Armenians in their communities and p<br>
reserve the Armenian heritage.  <br>
<p>
<p>
In addition to conducting an individualized internship search for each pa<br>
rticipant, the AGBU New York Summer Intern Program arranges common housin<br>
g at a new York University dormitory and organizes educational and cultur<br>
al seminars highlighting Armenian topics, social activities, and group to<br>
uring trips in New York exclusively for the interns.  <br>
<p>
<p>
To date, over one hundred different New York companies and institutions h<br>
ave hosted AGBU Interns throughout the program's decade-long history.  So<br>
me of these distinguished establishments are:  Amnesty International, Art<br>
hur Anderson, Edelman Public Relations Worldwide, Fox Television, Hospita<br>
l for Joint Diseases, JP Morgan, Leo Castelli Gallery, Merrill Lynch, Met<br>
ropolitan Museum of Art, Mount Sinai Medical Center, Museum of Modern Art<br>
, New York City Board of Education, New York City Office of Public Affair<br>
s, New York University Medical Center, Nike Communications, Price Waterho<br>
use, Prudential Securities, Salomon Brothers, and The United Nations. <br>
<p>
<p>
Applicants should have completed at least one year of full-time study at <br>
a four-year college, and shooed have a minimum of a  3.0 grade-point-aver<br>
age.  The deadline for applying is February 15th.  For more information o<br>
r to request an application, call Talar Sesetyan at the New York AGBU Off<br>
ice, (212) 765-8260.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
