        THE ARMENIAN COMMUNIST PARTY CONDEMNS THE EUROPEAN<br>
 PARLIAMENT'S RESOLUTION ON ARMENIAN PRESIDENTIAL ELECTIONS<br>
<p>
YEREVAN, DECEMBER 2, ARMENPRESS.<br>
 Recently the "Fact" news agency has published a statement of the<br>
 Central Committee of the Armenian Communists Party regarding the<br>
 European Parliament's resolution on presidential elections in<br>
 Armenia.<br>
 The statement reads, in particular:<br>
 "According to the Central Committee of the Armenian Communist Party,<br>
 the passage of this resolution is based not so much on the concern<br>
 about further democratic development of the country, but on the<br>
 desire to keep the influence of certain political forces in our<br>
 republic.<br>
 It is the first time since the declaration of indepence that our<br>
 society witnesses such a blatant interference with its internal<br>
 affair."<br>
 It also says in the statement that all the processes taking place in<br>
 the region are conditioned by the temporary weakness of Russia and<br>
 the desire of the West to established its influence in the countries<br>
 of the region.<br>
 Remaining a truly opposition party, which does not agree with the<br>
 present authorities of the Republic of Armenia on various important<br>
 principle issues, the Armenian Communist Party stated that using its<br>
 authority and influence, it will not allow for our country to become<br>
 an field for antinational and antidemocratic experiments.<br>
<p>
        BORDER INCIDENT<br>
 YEREVAN, DECEMBER 3, ARMENPRESS.<br>
 Early in the morning of November 30, some unidentifies persons had<br>
 stolen 25 domestic animals from a resident of village Jujevan of<br>
 Tavush province (north-eastern Armenia, near the Azeri border). The<br>
 footprints were pointing toward the Ghazakh region in Azerbaijan.<br>
 Later on, the experts of the Ministry of Internal Affairs and<br>
 National Security of the Republic of Armenia found the animals and an<br>
 armed group of people who stole them. The group was asked to drop<br>
the weapons, but instead they opened fire. The Armenian side had to<br>
 respond. 2 people from that group were killed, 2 escaped.<br>
 The Ministry of Internal Affairs asked the Ministry of Foreign<br>
 Affairs of the Republic of Armenia to sent a note of protest to the<br>
 Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Azerbaijan.<br>
<p>
        "EDIPA" TO HELP ATTRACT FOREIGN INVESTMENTS<br>
 YEREVAN, DECEMBER 3, ARMENPRESS.<br>
 The "Edipa" mediating state agency has developed a strategy of public<br>
 relations for attracting foreign investments.<br>
 According to the agency's director, Mr. Boris Harutyunian, the agency<br>
 has active contacts with Italian, French, Greek, and Lithuanian<br>
 organizations. These contacts are very helpful in finding foreign<br>
 partner for Armenian organizations, as well as for involving foreign<br>
 factories in Armenian economy.<br>
 "Edipa" also offers consulting services and specialist training<br>
 courses.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
