<title>Groong Network: Armenian News 12/4/96</title>
<h1>Armenian News 12/4/96</h1>
<i>Chavoush@aol.com</i><br>
<i>Wed, 4 Dec 96 14:21:57 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#24">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#24">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#24">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#24">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0025.html">Armen Martirossyan: "Armenian News 12/4/96"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0023.html">H.TCHILINGIRIAN@lse.ac.uk: "Armenian Church in Turkey Reopened"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Headlines of stories which follow:<br>
<p>
1.  Final election results give incumbent president nearly 90 per cent <br>
2.  Azeri president rules out independence for Nagornyy Karabakh <br>
3.  Deal saves OSCE accord <br>
4.  vice-president rong meets armenian guests <br>
5.  iran, armenia, georgia, greece seek closer ties <br>
6.  Armenian president warns of genocide - pledges to continue talks <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Final election results give incumbent president nearly 90 per cent <br>
SOURCE: Ekho Moskvy radio, Moscow, in Russian 1600 gmt 30 Nov 96 <br>
<p>
The final results of the presidential elections in the breakaway Azerbaijani<br>
region of Nagornyy Karabakh have been released, giving the incumbent Robert<br>
Kocharyan 88.9 per cent of the vote, Ekho Moskvy radio reported on 30th<br>
November. <br>
<p>
Final figures show that over 70,000 people, or approximately 80 per cent of<br>
eligible voters, took part in the poll, which was held on 24th November, the<br>
radio said. <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Azeri president rules out independence for Nagornyy Karabakh <br>
SOURCE: NTV, Moscow, in Russian 1900 gmt 2 Dec 96 <br>
<p>
Azerbaijani President Heydar Aliyev said in his speech to the Organization<br>
for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) summit meeting in Lisbon on 2nd<br>
December that independence for the disputed region of Nagornyy Karabakh was<br>
unacceptable to Azerbaijan, NTV reported. <br>
<p>
"We cannot allow a second Armenian state to be formed, on the territory of<br>
Azerbaijan.   The Armenian side should finally recognize that the conflict<br>
which it has unleashed, which is in its eighth year now and which has brought<br>
great misfortune and suffering to the people of Azerbaijan, has also made<br>
things difficult for the people of Armenia itself," Aliyev said in remarks<br>
broadcast by the television. <br>
<p>
Aliyev told Russian Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin during their meeting<br>
later on 2nd that he was concerned about Baku and Yerevan's failure to agree<br>
the contents of a political declaration on the status of Nagornyy Karabakh to<br>
be adopted by the Lisbon summit meeting, ITAR-TASS news agency reported on<br>
3rd December. <br>
<p>
"According to some information received by ITAR-TASS on the sidelines of the<br>
meeting, Azerbaijan warned that it may block the adoption of the declaration<br>
if no consensus is reached on the Karabakh issue," the agency said. <br>
<p>
Chernomyrdin instructed members of the Russian delegation "to take measures<br>
to help in a search for a mutually acceptable understanding" , it added. <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Deal saves OSCE accord <br>
SOURCE: Financial Times December 4, 1996<br>
<p>
The 54-nation European security summit agreed yesterday to work towards a new<br>
security system in Europe after a last-minute compromise in a row involving<br>
Armenia and Azerbaijan which threatened to derail the entire meeting. Heads<br>
of government of the Organisation for Security and Co-operation in Europe<br>
<i>&gt;from North America, Europe and the former Soviet Union issued a mildly-worded</i><br>
final statement on the promotion of "security and stability" in Europe which<br>
Azerbaijan had threatened until the last moment to veto. <br>
<p>
The Azeri veto was only lifted after the OSCE's Swiss chairman, Mr Flavio<br>
Cotti, agreed to read out a statement regretting Armenia's refusal to accept<br>
a compromise proposal on the future of the enclave of Nagorno-Karabakh, which<br>
is inside Azerbaijan, but largely populated by Armenians. Bruce Clark, Lisbon<br>
<p>
<p>
HEADLINE: vice-president rong meets armenian guests <br>
SOURCE:  Xinhua News Agency, beijing, december 3<br>
<p>
parliamentary exchanges are of great benefit to the development of bilateral<br>
relations, said chinese vice-president rong yiren when he met here today with<br>
an armenian national assembly delegation headed by its speaker babken<br>
ararktsyan. on behalf of the chinese government, rong extended a warm welcome<br>
to ararktsyan and his delegation on its first china visit since the two<br>
countries forged diplomatic ties in 1992.  china holds that all countries in<br>
the world should treat each other on the basis of equality and friendship,<br>
rong said, adding that since the establishment of diplomatic ties between the<br>
two countries, high-level visits have greatly promoted bilateral cooperation<br>
in the fields of politics, science and technology, and culture.  both china<br>
and armenia are developing countries, shouldering the task of developing<br>
their respective national economies and improving their peoples' livelihoods.<br>
the sharing of experiences is conducive to the development of both countries,<br>
since they have many things in common, rong noted.  rong also briefed the<br>
guests on china's reform and opening-up policies and its long-range<br>
development plan to the year 2010. ararktsyan said that his delegation is<br>
very glad to have an opportunity to become acquainted with china's history<br>
and present conditions as well as its reform progress, adding that he and his<br>
colleagues are particularly interested in the economic and social development<br>
of china.  both china and armenia are carrying out reform and have potential<br>
for co-operation, said the speaker, noting that it is important for armenia<br>
to get to know more about china's development road. <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: iran, armenia, georgia, greece seek closer ties <br>
SOURCE:  Xinhua News Agency, tehran, december 3<br>
<p>
iran, armenia, georgia and greece today held the second quadrilateral meeting<br>
of deputy foreign ministers in a bid to expand cooperation in fields of trade<br>
and transportation.  the four countries have proposed to establish four<br>
committees on telecommunications, tourism, industry, trade, economy and<br>
energy. iranian deputy foreign minister mahmoud vaezi, armenian deputy<br>
foreign minister sergei manasarian, georgian deputy foreign minister malkhaz<br>
kakabadzadeh and greek foreign ministry's secretary-general konstantin gorio<br>
are leading their respective delegations.  observers here noted that<br>
cooperation of the four countries is politically important because armenia<br>
and greece were believed to be historical enemies of turkey.  while iran is<br>
courting friendship of both to find an alternative for its outlet to europe,<br>
it is worried about the close ties between turkey and israel.  however,<br>
iranian deputy foreign minister vaezi made it clear that the economic<br>
cooperation in the region is aimed at more closer ties among the regional<br>
countries and is not detrimental to other countries. addressing the opening<br>
session of the two-day meeting, vaezi said the independence of the central<br>
asian and caucasian republics has provided an opportunity for iran to go on<br>
bilateral and regional cooperation with the republics.  he added that<br>
regional cooperation is an priority in the diplomacy of iran. iran believes<br>
that regional cooperation is an important means for guaranteeing peace and<br>
security in the region and that's why iran is seriously interested in<br>
bilateral, trilateral and quadrilateral cooperation with the regional states.<br>
 "the islamic republic of iran, as an important transit route with abundant<br>
energy sources is ready to develop cooperation using the economic potential<br>
of the countries in the region," he added.  the foreign ministers of iran,<br>
armenia, greece and georgia are expected to hold meeting in athens in<br>
january. <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Armenian president warns of genocide - pledges to continue talks <br>
SOURCE: Deutsche Presse-Agentur December 2, 1996<br>
<p>
Armenian President Levon Ter-Petrosyan Monday told a 54-nation European<br>
security conference that he feared genocide in the disputed Nagorny Karabach<br>
region if proposals for a resolution by Azerbaijan were accepted. <br>
<p>
"Despite any and all assurances that may be given, Azerbaijan is unable to<br>
guarantee the security of the population in Nagorny Karabach," said<br>
Ter-Petrosyan in a speech to leaders from the Organisation for Security and<br>
Cooperation in Europe (OSCE). <br>
<p>
Ter-Petrosyan said if Baku's plan was accepted the people of Nagorny Karabach<br>
would face "genocide or forced deportation". <br>
<p>
Nevertheless, he pledged Armenia would adhere to its ceasefire with<br>
Azerbaijan and continue to negotiate toward "a reasonable and fair<br>
compromise" over the territory. <br>
<p>
Nagorny Karabach is an ethnic Armenian region within Azerbaijan which has<br>
been under control of local and Armenian forces after a military conflict<br>
between Baku and Yerevan ended with a ceasefire in May 1994. <br>
<p>
Ter-Petrosyan was due to meet Azerbaijan's president, Heidar Aliyev, who is<br>
also attending the Lisbon summit. <br>
<p>
Angry over the Nagorny Karabach stalemate Azerbaijan has threatened to<br>
disrupt the summit by blocking approval of three OSCE declarations. <br>
<p>
Baku has demanded an OSCE pledge that any settlement of the Karabach dispute<br>
respect Azerbaijan's territorial integrity. <br>
<p>
Ter-Petrosyan insists that the people of Nagorny Karabach must be granted the<br>
right to self-determination. <br>
<p>
"Armenia refuses to recognise the territorial integrity of Azerbaijan,"<br>
declared Aliyev in a speech to OSCE leaders, adding that he believed Yerevan<br>
planned to keep part of the 20 per cent of his country currently under the<br>
control of Armenian forces. <br>
<p>
But he stressed Baku would also adhere to the ceasefire until a peace treaty<br>
was signed. <br>
<p>
Aliyev said Azerbaijan was prepared to offer Nagorny Karabach a high degree<br>
of autonomy linked to regional security guarantees. <br>
<p>
But Baku would not allow the creation of a second Armenian state within the<br>
territory of Azerbaijan, he said.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
