<title>Groong Network: Armenian Church in Turkey Reopened</title>
<h1>Armenian Church in Turkey Reopened</h1>
<i>H.TCHILINGIRIAN@lse.ac.uk</i><br>
<i>Wed, 4 Dec 96 11:59:07 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#23">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#23">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#23">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#23">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0024.html">Chavoush@aol.com: "Armenian News 12/4/96"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0022.html">Garbis Armen: "WRITING CONTEST: Children's Literature in Armenian"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
     THE ARMENIAN CHURCH IN KAYSERI (GESARIA), TURKEY REOPENED FOR WORSHIP<br>
     <br>
     ISTANBUL ("Larper" 2/12/96)--Last weekend St. Gregory Armenian Church <br>
     of Kayseri (Gesaria) was officially reopened by formal ceremonies <br>
     presided by Archbishop Mesrob Mutafyan, Chairman of the Religious <br>
     Council of the Armenian Patriarchate of Constantinople. For a long <br>
     time, the church was closed due to renovations. <br>
     <br>
     Currently, the St. Gregory Armenian Church serves the religious needs <br>
     of the small Armenian communities spread in central Anatolia and on <br>
     the eastern banks of the Black Sea. It is the only functioning <br>
     Armenian Church in the area.  The church in Kayseri (Cappadocian <br>
     Ceasarea) was built in 1191. Since the early centuries of <br>
     Christianity, Armenians have been active in this city as an important <br>
     commercial center in Asia Minor.<br>
     <br>
     According to Turkish encyclopedias, in 1890 there were 43,318 <br>
     Apostolic Armenians in the province of Kayseri, 1,800 Armenian <br>
     Protestants and 1,575 Armenian Catholics.  Today only 10 Armenians <br>
     live in Kayseri. However, St. Gregory Church serves as the religious <br>
     center for about 3,000 Armenians living in central Anatolia and the <br>
     Eastern provinces.<br>
     <br>
     On the Way to Kayseri<br>
     <br>
     Renovated in memory of Gesaria-native Hagop Tokerian, the reopening of <br>
     St. Gregory Church was decreed by the Armenian Patriarch of Turkey, <br>
     Archbishop Karekin II Kazanjian.<br>
     <br>
     On Thursday, November 30, over 400 Armenian pilgrims from Istanbul <br>
     headed to Gesaria on nine buses; they  were later joined by another 30 <br>
     pilgrims who traveled to the region by plane. Others came from Ankara, <br>
     Sepastia, Malatya, Tokat and the villages of Yozgat to participate in <br>
     the opening ceremonies.  Archbishop Mesrob Mutafyan and his entourage <br>
     of priests and lay representative arrived on Friday and were greeted <br>
     by the representative of St. Gregory Church, Antranik Erkouyoumjian <br>
     and other officials. <br>
     <br>
     Upon their arrival, the delegation from the Patriarchate visited the <br>
     church and inspected the results of the renovations that were carried <br>
     out and discussed the schedule of weekend activities.<br>
     <br>
     On Saturday morning, the delegation, headed by Archbishop Mesrob, <br>
     visited the historic sites of Goreme, Urgupi and the famous churches <br>
     of the region.  In the afternoon, an elaborate ceremony of "Opening <br>
     the Doors of the Church" (T'rnpatzek) was held in St. Gregory Church <br>
     in the presence of more than 500 Armenian faithful.  Archbishop Mesrob <br>
     consecrated the three altars of the church and the baptismal font.  <br>
     The wood-carved altars and the delicate frescos inside the church, <br>
     which were carefully restored to their original brilliance, testify to <br>
     the fine artistry of Armenian masters. <br>
     <br>
     On this occasion, Archbishop Mesrob delivered a sermon highlighting <br>
     the importance of the reopening of the St. Gregory Church.  He <br>
     recounted the historic event when St. Gregory the Illuminator, the <br>
     patron saint of the Armenian Church, was consecrated the Head of the <br>
     Armenian Apostolic Church, here in Gesaria in the 4th century, by <br>
     Leontius, the Archbishop of Ceasarea.  As such, Gesaria has a <br>
     significant role in the history of the Armenian Church, especially as <br>
     we prepare for the celebrations of the 1700th anniversary of <br>
     acceptance of Christianity as state religion in Armenia. Based on a <br>
     passage from the Book of Psalms, Archbishop Mesrob then explained the <br>
     importance of temples build for the glory of God and how the faithful, <br>
     collectively, contribution to the edification of a `holy place' where <br>
     individuals experience the presence of God. <br>
     <br>
     The reopening of the church in Kayseri coincided with the 535 <br>
     anniversary of the founding of the Armenian Patriarchate of <br>
     Constantinople.  In 1462, Sultan Mehmet II, after conquering <br>
     Constantinople, established the Greek and Armenian Patriarchates <br>
     respectively.  The mayor of Kayseri, acting in the same spirit as <br>
     Mehmet II, has not only permitted the renovation of the Armenian <br>
     church, but has also allocated financial resources to build a high <br>
     stone-fence around the Armenian cemetery of Kayseri. <br>
     <br>
     The mayor of Kayseri, Dr. Shukri Karatepe, was present during the <br>
     consecration ceremonies of the church. After the religious services, <br>
     in the courtyard of the church, the mayor welcomed Archbishop Mesrob <br>
     and greeted the opening of the Armenian Church in Kayseri with warm <br>
     words.  He emphasized that it would be wrong to look at this event <br>
     from a "touristic point of view", but rather the importance of this <br>
     event rests in the peaceful coexistence of Christian and Moslem <br>
     peoples.  "In the past, we have passed through sad events together, <br>
     but today, the time has come to build strong bridges between various <br>
     communities", said the mayor. <br>
     <br>
     In his response, Archbishop Mesrob, after thanking the mayor, said: <br>
     "There are no formal inter-religious relations in Turkey between the <br>
     clergymen of various religions, however, we notice that there is a <br>
     dialogue in our daily-life relations with each other, which are very <br>
     important for mutual understanding and for steps toward formal <br>
     rapprochement".  <br>
     <br>
     Visit to the Armenian Cemetery<br>
     <br>
     At 3:00 p.m. on the same day, Archbishop Mesrob, in the company of the <br>
     mayor and several hundred Armenian pilgrims, visited the Armenian <br>
     cemetery in Kayseri.  A requiem service was conducted for the departed <br>
     souls of the Armenians of the city.  Archbishop Mesrob said that the <br>
     cemetery looked in better condition. Recently, the municipality of <br>
     Kayseri has appointed a full-time custodian for the cemetery.  Mayor <br>
     Karatepe expressed his willingness to enhance the efforts of Armenians <br>
     if they wish to renovate the cemetery and the old graves.  After the <br>
     cemetery visit, Archbishop Mesrob returned to Istanbul. <br>
     <br>
     Divine Liturgy and Blessing of Madagh<br>
     <br>
     On Sunday, December 1, Divine Liturgy was celebrated in St. Gregory <br>
     Church, presided by Fr. Aram Vartabed Ateshian.  The Blessing of <br>
     Madagh and requiem services followed the Liturgy. <br>
     <br>
     Henceforth, the Armenian Patriarchate will send visiting priests to <br>
     Kayseri on a regular basis to conduct religious services and to <br>
     minister to the needs of the Armenian communities in the region. <br>
     <br>
     By Isahag Bchakjian<br>
     <br>
     [Translated by ht]<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
