<title>Groong Network: Armenian News 12/3/96</title>
<h1>Armenian News 12/3/96</h1>
<i>Chavoush@aol.com</i><br>
<i>Wed, 4 Dec 96 11:38:09 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#18">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#18">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#18">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#18">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0019.html">Vazgen_Ghoogassian_at_MCMAIL2@ccmail.llumc.edu: "AESA Event"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0017.html">Asbed Bedrossian: "OMRI Daily 12/04/96"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Headlines of stories which follow:<br>
<p>
1.  Guardian Council approves agreements with Armenia, Turkmenistan, Vietnam <br>
2.  Iranian parliamentary delegation chief criticizes Karabakh election <br>
3.  Communists mark anniversary <br>
4.  Sister of imprisoned student begins hunger strike <br>
5.  qiao shi meets armenian national assembly speaker <br>
6.  HIV infection in Armenia likely to spread: official <br>
7.  Islamic organization criticizes Karabakh elections <br>
8.  Armenian court says treaty on Russian military base constitutional <br>
9.  TWR relayed via Armenia on mediumwave <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Guardian Council approves agreements with Armenia, Turkmenistan,<br>
Vietnam <br>
SOURCE: Vision of the Islamic Republic of Iran Network 1, Tehran, in Persian<br>
1030 gmt 27 Nov 96 <br>
<p>
The Guardian Council held a session today, in which it discussed: <br>
<p>
   - amendments to Article 8 of the law on setting up a support fund for<br>
lawyers and advocates of justice departments; <br>
<p>
   - bills on a trade cooperation agreement between the government of the<br>
Islamic Republic of Iran and the government of the Republic of Armenia; <br>
<p>
   - agreements on trade and economic cooperation between the government of<br>
the Islamic Republic of Iran and the Republics of Armenia and Turkmenistan; <br>
<p>
   - an agreement on [giving] mutual support and encouragement to investments<br>
between the governments of the Islamic Republic of Iran and the Republic of<br>
Armenia; <br>
<p>
   - an agreement on cultural, scientific and training cooperation between<br>
the government of the Islamic Republic of Iran and the government of the<br>
Republic of Armenia; <br>
<p>
   - an agreement on cultural cooperation between the government of the<br>
Islamic Republic of Iran and the government of the Socialist Republic of<br>
Vietnam. <br>
<p>
   [The council] considers that these measures do not contravene the norms of<br>
the constitution and shari'ah. <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Iranian parliamentary delegation chief criticizes Karabakh election<br>
<p>
SOURCE: IRNA news agency, Tehran, in English 1947 gmt 28 Nov 96 <br>
<p>
The head of an Iranian parliamentary delegation on a two-day official visit<br>
to Azerbaijan has criticized the 24th November presidential elections held in<br>
the disputed region of Nagornyy Karabakh, the Iranian news agency IRNA<br>
reported on the 28th. <br>
<p>
Seyyed Reza Akrami, a member of the Iranian parliament's foreign affairs<br>
commission, said his country viewed Nagornyy Karabakh as an integral part of<br>
Azerbaijan and therefore believed the holding of presidential elections in<br>
the region was "deplorable" . <br>
<p>
He said Iran was interested in the preservation of Azerbaijan's territorial<br>
integrity and added that his country was ready to offer its expertise to<br>
Azerbaijan. <br>
<p>
Akrami accused "the US and the Zionist regime" of trying to sow discord in<br>
the Caucasus region, and said that "the hands of the US and the Zionist<br>
entity" could be seen behind regional events. <br>
<p>
According to the agency, Hasanov thanked the Iranian parliament for its<br>
effort to promote Tehran-Baku ties and said that President Heyder Aliyev had<br>
given high priority to the expansion of ties with Iran. <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Communists mark anniversary <br>
SOURCE: Interfax news agency, Moscow, in English 1522 gmt 29 Nov 96 <br>
<p>
Armenian communists on Friday [29th November] marked the 76th anniversary of<br>
Bolsheviks rising to power in Armenia.   Some 2,000 people marched down the<br>
central street in Yerevan and laid wreaths on the graves of Armenian<br>
Communist leaders.  <br>
<p>
Armenian Communist Party leader Sergey Badalyan said during a solemn session<br>
of the party that the victory of Soviet power in Armenia had created<br>
preconditions for building a civilized society and moving toward communism.<br>
Badalyan voiced the hope that "the holiday of 29th November will soon become<br>
official" in Armenia. <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Sister of imprisoned student begins hunger strike <br>
SOURCE: Interfax news agency, Moscow, in English 1554 gmt 29 Nov 96 <br>
<p>
The sister of a student detained for his alleged participation in the 25th<br>
September clashes between Armenian opposition supporters and police following<br>
the republic's presidential election has gone on hunger strike, Interfax news<br>
agency reported<br>
on 29th November. <br>
<p>
Twenty-year-old Armenika Kiviryan is holding the protest action outside the<br>
Armenian prosecutor's office in Yerevan.   Her brother, Argishti Kiviryan,<br>
went on hunger strike in prison 10 days ago. "He demanded that all prisoners<br>
of conscience be freed<br>
in Armenia, new presidential elections be held and the ban on the activity of<br>
Armenia' s Dashnaktsutyun party be lifted," the agency said. <br>
<p>
According to a member of the opposition National Democratic Union party,<br>
Kiviryan has been held in prison for two months now without being formally<br>
charged. He is one of about 20 people still in custody after the 25th<br>
September events, the opposition spokesman said. <br>
<p>
"Armenika Kiviryan told Interfax that her only demand was that her brother,<br>
whose life she believes to be in danger, be released," the agency said. <br>
<p>
A senior Armenian investigator, Suren Gezalyan, denied that Argishti Kiviryan<br>
was on hunger strike and said his health was "normal" . "The issue of whether<br>
to bring charges against him or let him go will be finally settled in the<br>
next few days," the investigator said. <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: qiao shi meets armenian national assembly speaker <br>
SOURCE:  xinhua, december 2; ITEM NO: 1202177 <br>
<p>
qiao shi, chairman of the standing committee of the national people's<br>
congress (npc), met here today with an armenian national assembly delegation<br>
headed by its speaker babken ararktsyan.  qiao said that china and armenia<br>
established diplomatic ties immediately after the independence of armenia,<br>
and china believes the bilateral relations of friendship and cooperation in<br>
various fields will be constantly  trengthened on the basis of the principles<br>
stipulated in their joint communique on establishing<br>
diplomatic ties.  a further development of the cooperation between the two<br>
countries in the fields of trade, science, education and culture would lay a<br>
broader foundation for bilateral relations, qiao said, and the development of<br>
bilateral political ties would push forward such cooperation in a positive<br>
way.  the chairman said that the armenian delegation's current visit will<br>
help promote the understanding and friendship between the peoples of the two<br>
countries, and the npc is willing to further develop its friendly cooperation<br>
with the armenian national assembly. ararktsyan said that relations between<br>
armenia and china have developed constantly, and their  cooperation has<br>
expanded since they established diplomatic ties five years ago.<br>
he added that he expects to see closer ties between the parliaments of the<br>
two countries.  the speaker reiterated that armenia recognizes that there is<br>
only one china, and that is the people's republic of china, and it will not<br>
have any official<br>
exchanges with taiwan. <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: HIV infection in Armenia likely to spread: official <br>
SOURCE:  Agence France, Dec 2, 1996<br>
 <br>
Just eight cases of AIDS and 20 carriers have been registered in Armenia in<br>
recent years, but that figure is likely to rise significantly in the near<br>
future, an Armenian health official said Sunday. <br>
<p>
Dr. Lev Zograbian, director of the Armenian AIDS control and Prevention<br>
Center, told Interfax that while Armenia now has just a handful of AIDS<br>
cases, higher HIV rates in neighboring countries like Turkey and Lebanon will<br>
undoubtedly soon affect the former Soviet republic. <br>
<p>
Zograbian said that Armenian health authorities are also hampered by other<br>
problems including the fact that the AIDS centre in Yerevan, which houses 10<br>
patients, lacks running water. <br>
<p>
Armenian officials claim that foreigners brought AIDS into the country and<br>
have proposed legislation which they say would slow the spread of the disease<br>
by requiring the deportation of foreigners who are HIV positive. <br>
<p>
This is similar to a law in Russia which was passed almost a year ago but is<br>
not yet enforced. <br>
<p>
When enforced, the Russian law will require that all foreigners planning to<br>
stay in the country for more that three months be tested for HIV and will<br>
restrict visits by those who test positive. <br>
<p>
Russia currently claims 2,105 HIV carriers and 245 AIDS patients, but medical<br>
experts predict an explosion in the infection rate which will mean at least<br>
100,000 new cases in the country by the end of 1997. <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Islamic organization criticizes Karabakh elections <br>
SOURCE: SPA news agency, Riyad, in Arabic 2015 gmt 28 Nov 96 <br>
<p>
The secretary-general of the Organization of the Islamic Conference (OIC), Dr<br>
Hamed Algabid, has criticized the presidential elections held on 24th<br>
November in the<br>
self-proclaimed Nagornyy Karabakh republic, the Saudi news agency SPA<br>
reported on 28th November. <br>
<p>
The secretary-general said in a statement that the holding of presidential<br>
elections in the disputed region was an encroachment on the sovereignty,<br>
independence and territorial integrity of Azerbaijan and "a political<br>
provocation that would not serve<br>
security and stability in the region" , the agency reported. <br>
<p>
Expressing his "deep concern" about the elections, Algabid described them as<br>
"an attempt to provide some legitimacy to the so-called Nagornyy Karabakh<br>
republic" . <br>
<p>
He urged the international community not to recognize the elections, which<br>
could have a negative effect on diplomatic efforts to settle the Nagornyy<br>
Karabakh conflict, the agency reported. <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: Armenian court says treaty on Russian military base constitutional <br>
SOURCE: Interfax news agency, Moscow, in English 1332 gmt 27 Nov 96 <br>
<p>
The Armenian Constitutional Court has recognized the constitutionality of the<br>
treaty on the deployment of a Russian military base in Armenia. <br>
<p>
The court pronounced its verdict on Wednesday [27th November] after it<br>
considered the case filed by Armenian President Levon Ter-Petrosyan.   The<br>
Armenian Justice Ministry had said some provisions of the treaty did not<br>
comply with the republic's<br>
legislation. <br>
<p>
The Russian-Armenian treaty was signed by the two countries' presidents on<br>
16th March 1995 in Moscow. However, it has not yet been ratified by the<br>
Russian and Armenian legislators. The term of the treaty is 25 years.<br>
Ratification of the treaty will raise interstate relations between Russia and<br>
Armenia to a new level and become an important pledge of peace and stability<br>
in the Caucasus, said Armenian Deputy Defence Minister Vahan Shirkhanyan, who<br>
acted as presidential representative in the<br>
court. The Russian base will promote the establishment and strengthening of<br>
the Armenian armed forces, closer relations between the Russian and Armenian<br>
armies, cooperation in combat training and the creation of joint allied<br>
forces, Shirkhanyan<br>
said. <br>
<p>
The Constitutional Court will also have to rule on seven agreements stemming<br>
<i>&gt;from the treaty, an Interfax correspondent reported from Yerevan. The Russian</i><br>
State Duma plans to consider the treaty's ratification on 6th December,<br>
Maj-Gen. Aleksey<br>
Tretyakov, the chief of the combat management group of Russian troops in<br>
Armenia, told Interfax. <br>
<p>
HEADLINE: TWR relayed via Armenia on mediumwave <br>
SOURCE:    Trans World Radio press release, Cary (USA), in English 18 Nov 96 <br>
<p>
Since 15th November, people in Central Asia and parts of the Middle East who<br>
have had virtually no exposure to the Gospel are now able to hear the good<br>
news of<br>
Christ through Trans World Radio's new broadcast site in Armenia. Programmes<br>
in eight languages are aired from Radio AR Intercontinental by a one million<br>
watt AM [mediumwave] transmitter formerly used for Soviet propaganda. <br>
<p>
Within listening range are more than 60 of the world's least-evangelized<br>
people groups. Traditional missionary work among Muslims in this area is<br>
believed by many to be impossible.  <br>
<p>
According to Werner Kroemer, TWR's regional director for Europe, " Armenia is<br>
probably our most strategic site added in the last decade because of who we<br>
are able to reach." <br>
<p>
Gospel programmes in such languages as Turkish and Farsi [Persian] are<br>
broadcast to the region. This new ministry was made possible through<br>
negotiations, prayer and the delivery and installation of satellite downlink<br>
equipment. It was completed by<br>
TWR engineers hours before the start of Armenia's paralysing snow season. <br>
<p>
[For a report that AWR-Europe had signed an agreement to use the Kamo<br>
transmitter site near Yerevan, see WM/41 1996, page 18.] <br>
