<title>Groong Network: More from Russian press on Lisbon summit</title>
<h1>More from Russian press on Lisbon summit</h1>
Arthur Martirosyan (<i>martiros@hulaw1.harvard.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 4 Dec 1996 11:54:35 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#16">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#16">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#16">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#16">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0017.html">Asbed Bedrossian: "OMRI Daily 12/04/96"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0015.html">nt@nt.arminco.com: "Noyan Tapan News (December 3)"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
KOMMERSANT-DAILY 4 December 1996 page 4<br>
<p>
   Report by Georgiy Bovt:  "Chernomyrdin in One Boat with Lukashenka"<br>
<p>
  The behavior of the CIS leaders at the OSCE summit in Lisbon points to the<br>
conclusion that in their European policy the Commonwealth countries are in<br>
fact not a commonwealth.  Each leader stuck to his guns, stressing<br>
independence from Moscow.  Only two CIS countries were mentioned together in<br>
the summit lobby, as though separated from all others by an invisible<br>
barrier: Russia and Belarus.<br>
   Moscow's strong opposition to NATO expansion found no support among the<br>
CIS member states.  In particular, Leonid Kuchma, in his speech at the<br>
summit, was extremely cautious in choosing his words. But behind that<br>
cautiousness you could discern primarily an aspiration to show the West that<br>
Kiev, unlike Moscow, is not categorically against NATO, but reserves the<br>
right, as it were, to consider options for closer coordination with this<br>
bloc in the future.  Finding no words to condemn the aggressive plans of<br>
Western imperialists, the Ukrainian president observed philosophically that<br>
"of decisive importance for Europe's future will be the consequences of the<br>
expansion and at the same time reformation of the leading institutions: the<br>
EC and NATO as well as the Western European Union."  Moreover, he missed no<br>
opportunity to tease Russian nationalists eyeing Sevastopol, reminding them<br>
of the principle of the inviolability of borders, which, however, did not<br>
stop him from also saying that there are "no serious problems" between<br>
Ukraine and Russia.  But what about the Black Sea Fleet?  The one-on-one<br>
meeting, in Lisbon, between Kuchma and Chernomyrdin passed without any<br>
result:  The time frame for the Russian Federation premier's visit to Kiev<br>
was not determined.  It was only decided that he would go there after<br>
agreement has been reached on the division of the Black Sea Fleet.  The<br>
chances of this happening in the near future, however, appear remote.  On<br>
the other hand, Kiev has no problem with Baku:  The idea of building a<br>
Eurasian transport corridor (the main purpose being "to bypass Russia") is<br>
being translated into life, which, in fact, was duly recorded during<br>
Kuchma's meeting with Geydar Aliyev.<br>
   Two Commonwealth member states -- Armenia and Azerbaijan -- came off at<br>
the summit as enemies.  This provoked speculation whether the adoption of a<br>
final declaration will not be blocked by a veto on the part of either Baku<br>
(if the principle of the country's territorial integrity is not reaffirmed)<br>
or Yerevan (if, quite the contrary, Karabakh's right to self-determination<br>
is not recognized).  Both sides invoked Moscow as a member of the Minsk<br>
group on the Karabakh settlement, which was of no use, considering that<br>
these negotiations have in effect stalled for the past two years. <br>
   As for Nurzultan Nazarbayev, he would not be seen dead wasting his breath<br>
on the subject of NATO.  He has his own pet -- Eurasian -- idea.  The OSCE<br>
is, of course, a unique structure, but now a similar one needs to be created<br>
in Asia.  Failing to support Russia's indignation over NATO expansion, the<br>
Kazakh president hit on a formula that indirectly challenged Russia's<br>
initiatives:  This is the way to read his passage to the effect that the<br>
OSCE should not be turned into a quasi-UN (Moscow is seeking to upgrade the<br>
OSCE's status, finding understanding even in the remote France, but not in a<br>
Commonwealth partner: Ukraine).  President Emomali Rakhmonov of Tajikistan<br>
spoke about what irked him the most: the war in Afghanistan, and intrigue by<br>
drug dealers and the intransigent opposition.  President Petr Luchinskiy of<br>
Moldova, who is considered to be a pro-Moscow politician, said from<br>
Cishinau:  Moldova, in its cooperation with NATO, does not intend to go<br>
outside the Partnership for Peace program, while the problems of "expanding<br>
the alliance and disagreements with Russia should be addressed without<br>
involving Moldova in it." <br>
   Moscow received unreserved support only from Alyaksandr Lukashenka.  He<br>
alone supported its proposal to build a European security system on the<br>
basis of OSCE, not NATO (moreover, NATO should, in effect, answer to OSCE,<br>
which is also in line with the Russian ideas).  Lukashenka spared no words<br>
to condemn NATO and the West which allegedly came down on him for his<br>
loyalty to Russia.  So, Moscow, on the path toward integration into Europe,<br>
has found itself in the same boat with the Belarusian president, whose<br>
authoritarian ways became a regular feature in OSCE discussions.  This,<br>
however, does not bother Moscow whatsoever.  <br>
(end)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
