<!-- body="start" -->
ASBAREZ ON LINE <br>
12/03/1996<br>
<p>
<p>
1. NO DECISION REACHED ON KARABAKH AT LISBON SUMMIT<br>
2. ARF LEADER ADVISED NOT TO TRAVEL TO CANADA<br>
3. CANADIAN DEPUTIES VISIT TORONTO CENTER<br>
4. CHILD DIES IN LAND MINE EXPLOSION, FOUR INJURED<br>
5. TWO AZERI CATTLE RUSTLERS KILLED<br>
6. UNEMPLOYMENT LEVELS GROWING IN ARMENIA<br>
7. HUMANITARIAN AID EXCEEDS $50 MILLION<br>
8. 25,000 TONS OF SEEDS TO BE SHIPPED TO ARMENIA IN 1997-1998<br>
9. CHINESE VICE-PRESIDENT RECEIVES ARMENIAN DELEGATION<br>
10. ERBAKAN SPEAKS OUT ON "STATE GANG" SCANDAL<br>
11. PILIBOS WINS 19 MEDALS AT DECATHLON <br>
<p>
<p>
1. NO DECISION REACHED ON KARABAKH AT LISBON SUMMIT<br>
<p>
LISBON (Reuter)-Bitterness over the Nagorno-Karabakh conflict <br>
almost wrecked the Lisbon security summit Tuesday, forcing <br>
diplomats to revert to an unusual last-minute maneuver to avoid a <br>
major embarrassment.<br>
	Disaster loomed as negotiations between Azerbaijan and <br>
Armenia over Nagorno-Karabakh hit a brick wall with no hint of a <br>
breakthrough in sight.<br>
	Forced into action by the threat of Azerbaijan vetoing the <br>
entire final summit declaration, international mediators agreed to <br>
drop all reference to the dispute from the closing document and <br>
issued a separate statement on it instead.<br>
	Levon Ter-Petrosyan sat stony-faced at the final session of <br>
the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe meeting. <br>
Azeri President Gaidar Aliyev, who dropped his veto threat, hailed <br>
his success.<br>
	"I am very satisfied," Aliyev told a news conference.<br>
	Ter-Petrosyan, by contrast, canceled a planned news <br>
conference.<br>
	The conflict over Nagorno-Karabakh was also seen as a <br>
reminder of the instability and security problems that still haunt <br>
many parts of the former Soviet Union and could threaten European <br>
security.<br>
	Azerbaijan wanted its territorial integrity reaffirmed in <br>
the final summit statement. It also sought support for demands to <br>
define Nagorno-Karabakhs legal status clearly, based on the right <br>
to self-determination, and guarantees over its security. Armenia <br>
blocked Azerbaijans demands, earning the wrath of other states at <br>
the closing session, including Russia.<br>
	"I regret that one delegation could not accept this. These <br>
principles have the support of all other participating states," <br>
said Swiss Foreign Minister Flavio Cotti, chairman in office of <br>
the OSCE.<br>
	Azerbaijans demands were included in the separate statement <br>
drawn up to the indignation of Ter-Petrosyan.<br>
	He rejected Cottis remarks, saying they did not correspond <br>
with the views of a group of 11 countries in the Minsk Group set <br>
up to mediate over Nagorno-Karabakh. He has said "unilateral <br>
solutions" must not be imposed over Karabakh. <br>
	"I would like to express concern in connection with this <br>
statement. In our view it does not reflect the spirit and the <br>
letter of the Minsk Group," Ter-Petrosyan said.<br>
	His comments made clear the leaders left Lisbon as far apart <br>
on Nagorno-Karabakh as when they arrived.<br>
	The OSCE agreed at its last summit, in Budapest in 1994, to <br>
prepare a multinational peacekeeping force for Nagorno-Karabakh <br>
but deployment cannot go ahead until the two sides agree to full <br>
terms for peace.<br>
	"You all know that no progress has been achieved in the last <br>
two years to resolve the Nagorno-Karabakh conflict," Cotti said.<br>
	Matters have been further complicated by tension over an <br>
election in Nagorno-Karabakh last month which Armenia acclaimed <br>
and Azerbaijan condemned.<br>
	Leaders from North America and Europe, however, pledged a <br>
new age of security and peace for all in the 21st century, but the <br>
Lisbon summit was marred by friction over NATO enlargement, <br>
Belarus and Serbia.<br>
	Leaders of the 54-nation OSCE agreed to respect democracy <br>
and human rights, and backed more arms control and an end to <br>
confrontation on the continent where two world wars started. <br>
	"We are determined to learn from the tragedies of the past <br>
and to translate our vision of a cooperative future into reality <br>
by creating a common security space free of dividing lines," the <br>
final summit declaration said.<br>
	The OSCE, sometimes accused of spouting lofty ideals, scored <br>
a notable success at the summit by agreeing to adapt a 1990 arms <br>
reduction pact to reflect a post-Cold War Europe no longer divided <br>
by military alliances.<br>
	Heads of state and government agreed to develop the idea of <br>
a security model for the 21st century, rooted in the principle <br>
that no nations security should be threatened by another. <br>
	"This is a very important document," John Kornblum, US <br>
Assistant Secretary of State for European Affairs, said. "Given <br>
the history of destruction and warfare on this continent over the <br>
past 100 years, ...nations will draw on the tools of solidarity of <br>
others to make sure they are secure," Kornblum told a news <br>
conference.<br>
	But the summit was not free of its diplomatic wrangles. <br>
Russian Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin underscored Moscows <br>
opposition to NATO plans to take in countries such as Poland and <br>
Hungary by the year 2000, raising the specter of new division <br>
lines spreading across Europe.<br>
	President Alexander Lukashenko of Belarus drew open <br>
criticism from several leaders over his autocratic rule.<br>
	Chernomyrdin failed to win support to develop the OSCE into <br>
a more powerful security body to act as a counterweight to NATO. <br>
But one trophy he can carry home is the agreement to update the <br>
Conventional Forces in Europe  treaty, an issue Moscow has been <br>
pushing since the breakup of the Soviet Union in 1991. <br>
	While the final text supported every nations right to <br>
change its security arrangements, Russia will be gratified that <br>
the summit issued no endorsement of NATO enlargement.<br>
	Western diplomats said Russia had insisted the declaration <br>
remove a call for democracy in Serbia, where President Slobodan <br>
Milosevic faces mass protests.<br>
	Many leaders in Lisbon had expressed concern that Milosevic, <br>
now facing an unprecedented challenge to his nine years of <br>
autocratic rule, could use force against protesters now thronging <br>
the streets of Belgrade and calling on him to quit. <br>
	Yugoslavia, comprising Serbia and Montenegro, did not attend <br>
the summit because its OSCE membership has been suspended.<br>
	The last OSCE summit, in Budapest in 1994, collapsed over <br>
differences on the NATO issue and the war in Bosnia.<br>
<p>
<p>
2. ARF LEADER ADVISED NOT TO TRAVEL TO CANADA<br>
<p>
The Armenian Revolutionary Federation Central Committee of Canada <br>
had invited ARF Bureau member Peno Tontian as the main speaker of <br>
the ARF 106th anniversary celebrations in Montreal and Cambridge, <br>
Ontario. <br>
	Following the refusal of entry to ARF Bureau member Garo <br>
Armenian, the Canadian Embassy in Lebanon was contacted regarding <br>
Tontians scheduled visit. The Canadian Embassy suggested that <br>
Tontian not make his trip to Canada, because he too might be <br>
refused entry, even though Tontian had already received a <br>
visitors visa through the same Canadian Embassy.<br>
	Hence, the ARF leaders planned visit is postponed <br>
indefinitely. ARF Bureau member Viken Hovsepian (of Montreal, <br>
Canada) is replacing Tontian as the main speaker at the above-<br>
mentioned functions.<br>
	Three other ARF Bureau members have been refused  entry into <br>
Canada according to sec. 19 of the Immigration Act,  which states <br>
that no person shall be granted admission who is a member of any <br>
of the following classes: persons for  whom there are reasonable <br>
grounds to believe; (...) are or were members of an organization <br>
for which there are reasonable grounds to believe is or was <br>
engaged in (...) terrorism... <br>
	According to the ARF Central Committee, ARF Bureau members <br>
are being refused admission into Canada as part of a campaign by <br>
certain government agencies, to pressure and harass the Armenian <br>
community in the pretext of investigating the 1982 assassination <br>
of a Turkish diplomat in Ottawa and the 1985 raid of the Turkish <br>
Embassy in Ottawa, and in retaliation to legal steps taken by the <br>
community to stop the harassment.<br>
	The declaration further states that "in recent weeks the ARF <br>
Central Committee of Canada has multiplied its efforts with <br>
federal officials, in order  to put an end to these condemnable <br>
pressure tactics."<br>
<p>
<p>
3. CANADIAN DEPUTIES VISIT TORONTO CENTER<br>
<p>
TORONTO-Three members of the Canadian Parliament, Sarkis <br>
Assadourian (Lib. Don Valley North), David Collenette (Lib. Don <br>
Valley East) and Jim Peterson (Lib. Willowdale), through an <br>
invitation of the Armenian National Committee of Toronto, visited <br>
the Armenian Community Center of Toronto on Nov. 21. <br>
	The purpose of the gathering was to  once again familiarize <br>
the community leaders with those who represent them in Parliament.<br>
	Since the new federal electoral ridings are being changed to <br>
increase the total number of ridings from 295 to 301, some changes <br>
will effect the riding in which the Armenian Community Center is <br>
located.  Taking effect on January 8, 1997, the new electoral <br>
riding arrangement will eliminate the riding of Don Valley North, <br>
which will be divided between the Don Valley East and Willowdale <br>
ridings.  <br>
	Since the Armenian Community Center is situated within the <br>
Don Valley North riding, and since Assadourian is its <br>
parliamentarian, he has found it necessary to initiate this <br>
meeting. (Assadourian will be a candidate in another riding.) The <br>
aforementioned issue, as well as the increased cooperation with <br>
the parliamentarians regarding the Armenian Genocide resolution <br>
were among the key issues discussed.<br>
	Following  brief welcoming remarks, the Chairman of the <br>
Toronto ANC, Krikor Shitilian invited Assadourian to address the <br>
more than 60 guests.<br>
	Assadourian briefed the guests on the current concerns of <br>
the Center. He then invited the former Minister of Defense, <br>
Collenette, who stressed his dedication to the Armenian Cause as <br>
well as to the cooperation of the federal government and the <br>
Armenian community at large.<br>
	Peterson, a long time friend of the Armenian Community <br>
Center, detailed his 16-year knowledge of the Armenian Genocide as <br>
well as Armenian issues and reaffirmed his commitment to the <br>
recognition of the Armenian Genocide by the Canadian Government.<br>
	In his closing remarks, Assadourian thanked the two members <br>
of Parliament and all those present, and appealed to the Armenian <br>
community members to continue being demanding on issues concerning <br>
the Armenian Cause, and to strive for the welfare of those living <br>
in Armenia, and for the strengthening of democratic rule there.<br>
<p>
<p>
4. CHILD DIES IN LAND MINE EXPLOSION, FOUR INJURED<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Respublica Armenia, Snark)-A land mine in the village of <br>
Karashen in Goris exploded Friday killing one boy and injuring <br>
four others.<br>
	The explosion occurred while the boys were playing with an <br>
unknown metal object, which turned out to be a land mine, <br>
Armenias Department of Emergency Situations said.<br>
	According to the International Committee of the Red Cross in <br>
Yerevan, some 50,000 mines were installed during the war in <br>
Karabakh. From 1994-95, 24 percent of the injuries were caused by <br>
mines, half of them injuring civilians.<br>
<p>
<p>
5. TWO AZERI CATTLE RUSTLERS KILLED<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-Two Azeri cattle rustlers were killed <br>
Saturday evening as they attempted to steal 25 heads of cattle <br>
from the village of Joujevan in the Tavoush province of Armenia. <br>
Two others escaped.<br>
	Agents of Armenias Interior Ministry and National Security <br>
followed the group to the Kazakh district of Azerbaijan.<br>
	The Azeris opened fire as Armenian officials asked them to <br>
surrender near the Yotnaghpiur border post. <br>
<p>
<p>
6. UNEMPLOYMENT LEVELS GROWING IN ARMENIA<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-The State Statistics Department of Armenia <br>
reported that the unemployment rate for the months of January <br>
through September of 1996 grew from 6.1 percent to 9.2 percent.<br>
	The labor force totaled 153,700 people in September 1996, <br>
which is one percent more when compared to the previous month and <br>
26.5 percent more if compared to September 1995.<br>
	Ninety-eight percent of those out of a job have been <br>
unemployed for a lengthy period. This number has risen by 0.6 <br>
percent since last month and by 27 percent since September 1995.<br>
	Residents of Yerevan, Gumri and Vanadzor make up 55 percent <br>
of the unemployed. Women make up 71.6 percent (109,200 people) of <br>
the total unemployed.<br>
	According to the same source, only 617 unemployed people <br>
were hired in September. Since January 1996, 3,423 people found <br>
jobs through employment services.<br>
	Unemployment benefits were paid to 41,700 people in <br>
September. The unemployment level, calculated as a ratio of <br>
registered unemployed and economically active citizens, was 9.8 <br>
percent in September 1996. It remained unchanged since last month <br>
and grew by 2.2 percent since the same month last year.<br>
<p>
<p>
7. HUMANITARIAN AID EXCEEDS $50 MILLION<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-Between the months of January and August <br>
1996, Armenia received $53,700,000 in humanitarian aid, the <br>
Department of State Statistics reported.<br>
	The aid was donated by 31 countries, mainly the United <br>
States, France, Germany, Switzerland, Denmark, Great Britain, <br>
Belgium and Greece.<br>
<p>
<p>
8. 25,000 TONS OF SEEDS TO BE SHIPPED TO ARMENIA IN 1997-1998<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-The eighth session of the Commonwealth of <br>
Independent States Semena Association took place on Nov. 18-22 in <br>
Yalta, Crimea. <br>
	For the first time the session was attended by <br>
representatives of European countries. Armenia was represented at <br>
the session by First Deputy Minister of Agriculture and Food <br>
Samvel Stepanian, head of the Department of Land Cultivation <br>
Alfred Khachatrian and Director of the Semena firm Roland <br>
Hovakimian.<br>
	From 1997-1998, Armenia will received shipments of seeds <br>
from Russia, Ukraine, and some from Kazakhstan and Kyrgyzstan, <br>
Khachatrian said.<br>
	A total of 25,000 tons of seeds, including 20,000 tons from <br>
Russia, are expected to be shipped to Armenia during the 1997-1998 <br>
period. Under the agreement with Russia, in spring of 1997 Armenia <br>
will be supplied with 500 tons of wheat seeds, 2,000 tons of <br>
barley seeds and 500 tons of oat seeds. If there is a greater <br>
demand, the volume may be increased up to 9,000 tons, Khachatrian <br>
said.<br>
	The agreement also calls for 3,000 tons of winter wheat <br>
seeds, 1,000 tons of barley seeds and 1,000 tons of rye seeds to <br>
be shipped to Armenia in 1997, as well as pea, corn and sunflower <br>
seeds.<br>
	According to Khachatrian, due to the lack of funds, farmers <br>
are unable to purchase seeds which guarantee high yields. He said <br>
that next spring several organizations would allocate money to <br>
farmers for the purchase of high yield seeds.<br>
<p>
<p>
9. CHINESE VICE-PRESIDENT RECEIVES ARMENIAN DELEGATION<br>
<p>
BEIJING (Xinhua)-Parliamentary exchanges are of great benefit to <br>
the development of bilateral relations, Chinas Vice-President <br>
Rong Yiren told an Armenian parliamentary delegation, headed by <br>
Speaker Babken Ararktsian, on Tuesday.<br>
	Yiren welcomed the group on its first visit to China since <br>
the two countries forged diplomatic ties in 1992.<br>
	"China believes that all countries in the world should treat <br>
each other on the basis of equality and friendship," Yiren said, <br>
adding that since the establishment of diplomatic ties between the <br>
two countries, high-level visits have greatly promoted bilateral <br>
cooperation in the fields of politics, science and technology and <br>
culture.<br>
	Both China and Armenia are developing countries shouldering <br>
the task of developing their respective national economies and <br>
improving their peoples livelihoods, the Chinese Vice-President <br>
noted. "The sharing of experiences is conducive to the development <br>
of both countries, since they have many things in common," he <br>
said.<br>
	Yiren briefed the guests on Chinas reforms and policies to <br>
open up the somewhat closed society with long-range development <br>
plans up to the year 2010.<br>
	Ararktsian said that his delegation was very glad to have an <br>
opportunity to become acquainted with Chinas history and present <br>
conditions as well as its reform progress, adding that he and his <br>
colleagues are particularly interested in the economic and social <br>
development of China.<br>
	"Both China and Armenia are carrying out reforms and have <br>
potential for cooperation," Ararktsian said, stressing the <br>
importance of learning more about Chinas road to development.<br>
<p>
<p>
10. ERBAKAN SPEAKS OUT ON "STATE GANG" SCANDAL<br>
<p>
ISTANBUL (Reuter)-Turkeys first Islamist prime minister broke a <br>
prolonged silence to distance himself from a scandal over state-<br>
backed death squads that the Kurdish opposition blamed for <br>
thousands of mystery killings.<br>
	"You cannot have a gang within the state...Nobody can be <br>
allowed to do anything illegal, with no exceptions," Erbakan told <br>
Turkish columnists in an interview widely published on Tuesday.<br>
	Erbakan was speaking in detail for the first time since a <br>
scandal over alleged "state gangs" in the underworld erupted last <br>
month following an accident in which a wanted gangster, Abdullah <br>
Catli, and a top policeman died in the same car.<br>
	A pro-Kurdish opposition party Tuesday blamed state-<br>
sponsored gangs for some 3,500 unsolved murders in southeast <br>
Turkey.<br>
	"We can say these gangs have a direct link with mystery <br>
killings. This is no longer a hypothesis or a guess, this is a <br>
reality acknowledged by officials," Guven Ozata, a senior member <br>
of the Peoples Democracy Party (HADEP), told a news conference.<br>
	"The exact figure cannot be confirmed but, according to the <br>
Human Rights Association, since the middle of the 1980s around <br>
3,500 people have fallen victim to mystery murders," Ozata said in <br>
Ankara.<br>
	Sedat Bucak, a government parliamentarian who heads Turkeys <br>
biggest private Kurdish militia in the fight with the Kurdistan <br>
Workers Party (PKK), was also in the car with Catli but survived <br>
with minor injuries. <br>
	"Nothing, including fighting the PKK, can be an excuse for a <br>
crime. If such things happen, those gangs, whatever their make-up, <br>
will be disbanded," said Erbakan in an apparent rebuff to comments <br>
by his deputy, Tansu Ciller, that anyone fighting for the state <br>
was a hero. Bucak is a deputy for Cillers party. <br>
	Ciller last week defended Catli, saying "those who fire <br>
bullets or suffer their wounds in the name of this country...will <br>
always be respectfully remembered by us." <br>
	Ciller had stressed that Catli had no confirmed convictions <br>
in Turkey. Catli had been on the run since the late 1970s, when he <br>
was accused of killing seven leftists in Ankara. He was also <br>
wanted by Interpol for his alleged role in the 1981 attack on the <br>
Pope and had been jailed-and escaped-in Switzerland for heroin <br>
trafficking.<br>
	Asked directly about Cillers comments, Erbakan said: <br>
"Everyone is entitled to their own view."<br>
	"When he answered this question you could see from his face <br>
that he was not at all pleased by Cillers attitude, but in his <br>
answer he was thinking of the coalition," wrote columnist Fatih <br>
Cekirge in the daily Sabah.<br>
	The scandal has rocked the government and cost Ciller her <br>
hard-line interior minister, Mehmet Agar, who quit following the <br>
crash in the quiet western town of Susurluk amid allegations he <br>
knew of the relationship among the unlikely trio in the car. <br>
	But analysts say Cillers stance during the scandal played <br>
into Erbakans hands and strengthened the coalition, which the <br>
former premier entered amid allegations of corruption against her. <br>
She needs backing from Erbakan-whom she had vowed never to ally <br>
with-to clear her name.<br>
<p>
<p>
11. PILIBOS WINS 19 MEDALS AT DECATHLON <br>
<p>
DUBAI (Reuter)-Iran and Russia agreed to set up a company to look <br>
for oil in the Caspian Sea, the official Iranian news agency IRNA <br>
said Tuesday.<br>
	The agreement was reached during economic cooperation talks <br>
in Moscow late Monday between Irans Minister of Economic Affairs <br>
Morteza Mohammadkhan and Fuel and Energy Minister Pyotr Rodionov.<br>
	It was the joint economic committees first meeting since <br>
the collapse of the Soviet Union in 1991.<br>
	The two countries agreed to set up a company for joint <br>
exploration and exploitation of oil and mineral resources around <br>
the Caspian during a trilateral meeting with Turkmenistan last <br>
month. Russia said Kazakhstan and Azerbaijan were also welcome to <br>
join.<br>
	The Caspian Sea, eighth in the world in terms of discovered <br>
oil reserves, was divided between the Soviet Union and Iran first <br>
in 1921 and again in 1940.<br>
	But since the break-up of the Soviet Union and the birth of <br>
three new states-Azerbaijan, Kazakhstan and Turkmenistan-along the <br>
Caspian shores, the sea has become the subject of an intense <br>
diplomatic and legal battle over its immense reserves of oil and <br>
gas.<br>
	The committee also discussed ways to boost trade links, IRNA <br>
said. Bilateral trade dropped from $1.4 billion in 1991 to $200 <br>
million in 1995 before rising to $350 million this year. <br>
	Russia is helping Iran to build a $1 billion nuclear power <br>
plant at Bushehr.<br>
<p>
<p>
<p>
LOS ANGELES-Rose and Alex Pilibos Armenian School participated for <br>
the first time in the prestigious Academic Decathlon of Southern <br>
California Private Schools on November 16.<br>
	The highly challenging competition drew more than 200 <br>
students from top Southern California private high schools. In the <br>
all-day competition, students are asked rigorous questions in <br>
academic areas including economics, math, world history, <br>
geography, science, literature and fine arts.<br>
	Each school was represented by nine students and three <br>
alternates. Each student competed individually, and an overall <br>
team score was computed to rank the standing of each school.<br>
	Although Alex Pilibos participated in this decathlon for the <br>
first time and competed against schools that have been <br>
participating for many years, the results obtained surprised both <br>
other participants and the organizers of the event. Alex Pilibos <br>
won a total of 19 medals, 10 of which were gold. <br>
	Furthermore, the school ranked fifth among 21 participating <br>
schools on the Super Quiz, the most challenging comprehensive <br>
section of the competition. In addition to these impressive <br>
results, Lusine Danakian, an eleventh grade student at Alex <br>
Pilibos, ranked fourth among over 200 participants. Overall, Alex <br>
Pilibos ranked third in its division.<br>
	"We are astounded by the results achieved by our students," <br>
said Alex Pilibos team coach Jackie Mischler, "We have been told <br>
by the organizers of this event that, as first-time participants, <br>
our students achieved outstanding results. We are very proud of <br>
our students and school."<br>
	"We are not surprised by the brilliant performance of our <br>
students because we witness their abilities on a daily basis in <br>
our classrooms," noted Viken Yacoubian, principal of Alex Pilibos <br>
Armenian School. "However, considering that other teams offer full <br>
semester courses to prepare their students for the Decathlon while <br>
our team studied during their lunch times and after school in only <br>
a four-week period, we are extremely proud of our students. Once <br>
again, it becomes very clear to us that not only are we highly <br>
competitive in comparison to other top private schools in Southern <br>
California, but we are among the best," added Yacoubian.<br>
	Yacoubian announced that the school plans to participate in <br>
the decathlon in the forthcoming years as well.<br>
<p>
