<title>Groong Network: Nagorno-Karabakh row almost wrecks Lisbon summit</title>
<h1>Nagorno-Karabakh row almost wrecks Lisbon summit</h1>
Kevork K. Oskanian (<i>100436.3410@CompuServe.COM</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 3 Dec 96 14:43:48 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#12">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#12">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#12">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#12">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0013.html">Asbed Bedrossian: "OMRI Daily 12/03/96"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0011.html">Kevork K. Oskanian: "VOA/OSCE Summit"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
    By Timothy Heritage<br>
    LISBON, Dec 3 (Reuter) - Bitterness over a conflict in a<br>
remote corner of Europe almost wrecked the Lisbon security<br>
summit on Tuesday, forcing diplomats to revert to an unusual<br>
last-minute manoeuvre to avoid a major embarassment.<br>
    Disaster loomed as negotiations between Azerbaijan and<br>
Armenia over the disputed enclave of Nagorno-Karabakh hit a<br>
brick wall with no hint of a breakthrough in sight.<br>
    Forced into action by the threat of Azerbaijan vetoing the<br>
entire final summit declaration, international mediators agreed<br>
to drop all reference to the dispute from the closing document<br>
and issued a separate statement on it instead.<br>
    Armenian President Levon Ter-Petrosyan sat stony-faced at<br>
the final session of the Organisation for Security and<br>
Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) meeting. Azeri President Heydar<br>
Aliyev, who dropped his veto threat, hailed his success.<br>
    "I am very satisfied," Aliyev told a news conference.<br>
    Ter-Petrosyan, by contrast, cancelled a planned news<br>
conference.<br>
    The conflict over Nagorno-Karabakh, a disputed enclave with<br>
an Armenian majority which is surrounded by Azeri territory,<br>
flared in the Cold War era.<br>
    It is also a reminder of the instability and security<br>
problems that still haunt many parts of the former Soviet Union<br>
and could threaten European security.<br>
    About 10,000 people were killed in fighting which flared in<br>
Nagorno-Karabakh in 1988. The clashes ended under a ceasefire<br>
signed in 1994 but up to one million refugees still live in tent<br>
camps.<br>
    Azerbaijan wanted its territorial integrity reaffirmed in<br>
the final summit statement. It also sought support for demands<br>
to define Nagorno-Karabakh's legal status clearly, based on the<br>
right to self-determination, and guarantees over its security.<br>
    Armenia blocked Azerbaijan's demands, earning the wrath of<br>
other states at the closing session, including Russia.<br>
    "I regret that one delegation could not accept this. These<br>
principles have the support of all other participating states,"<br>
said Swiss Foreign Minister Flavio Cotti, chairman in office of<br>
the OSCE.<br>
    Azerbaijan's demands were included in the separate statement<br>
drawn up to the indignation of Ter-Petrosyan.<br>
    He rejected Cotti's remarks, saying they did not correspond<br>
with the views of a group of 11 countries in the so-called<br>
Minsk Group set up to mediate over Nagorno-Karabakh. He has said<br>
"unilateral solutions" must not be imposed over the enclave.<br>
    "I would like to express concern in connection with this<br>
statement. In our view it does not reflect the spirit and the<br>
letter of the Minsk Group," Ter-Petrosyan said.<br>
    His comments made clear the leaders left Lisbon as far apart<br>
on Nagorno-Karabakh as when they arrived.<br>
    The OSCE agreed at its last summit, in Budapest in 1994, to<br>
prepare a multinational peacekeeping force for Nagorno-Karabakh<br>
but deployment cannot go ahead until the two sides agree full<br>
terms for peace.<br>
    "You all know that no progress has been achieved in the last<br>
two years to resolve the Nagorno-Karabkah conflict," Cotti said.<br>
    Matters have been further complicated by tension over an<br>
election in Nagorno-Karabakh last month which Armenia acclaimed<br>
and Azerbaijan condemned.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
