<title>Groong Network: Russian press on the OSCE Lisbon summit</title>
<h1>Russian press on the OSCE Lisbon summit</h1>
Arthur Martirosyan (<i>martiros@hulaw1.harvard.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 3 Dec 1996 12:24:39 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#9">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#9">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#9">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#9">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0010.html">Armen Martirossyan: "Russian press on the OSCE Lisbon summit"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0008.html">Arthur Martirosyan: "Oil/Chechnya"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
KOMMERSANT-DAILY 3 December 1996 page 4<br>
<p>
   Report by Georgiy Bovt:  "The OSCE Summit in Lisbon.  NATO Will Be Absent<br>
Only from the Final Declaration"<br>
<p>
  On the eve of the opening of the OSCE summit in Lisbon, experts from<br>
various countries were sweating over the text of the final declaration all<br>
night long.  Yet at least on one point, which the Russian delegation regards<br>
as the key one, no consensus seems likely.  Before the summit Moscow<br>
announced its categorical rejection of the idea of NATO expansion, restating<br>
its stance of two years ago, which was made public at the OSCE summit in<br>
Budapest and caused something bordering on scandal there.  The only<br>
difference is that in Lisbon Russia is represented by the premier, not<br>
Yeltsin, and that the range of Moscow's allies narrowed down to just one<br>
man, Lukashenka.<br>
 The suggestions that Moscow might soften its stance, which a majority of<br>
OSCE countries see as inflexible and unpromising, were not borne out.  Boris<br>
Yeltsin said on the eve of the summit:  Russia's attitude to NATO expansion<br>
has remained unchanged.  The premier added that currently Russia would not<br>
agree to join NATO on any terms:  "We are not against NATO as a political<br>
organization, we are ready to cooperate with it.  But let us straighten<br>
matters out without any rush, there are no grounds for making haste."<br>
Chernomyrdin repeated this thought in Lisbon yesterday.  European partners<br>
could have gone into guessing as to whether the word "currently" can be<br>
interpreted as hinting at the possibility of softening its stance later, but<br>
an interview for NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA by Defense Minister Igor Rodionov, who<br>
recently made a number of surprisingly moderate noises on NATO, dotted all<br>
the i's.  As behooves a military minister, he remains "a hawk," threatening<br>
to retarget nuclear missiles to NATO's freshmen in Europe.  He made a<br>
reservation, of course, saying that the missiles would only be retargeted,<br>
if the new members deploy nuclear weapons on their territory.  But even this<br>
reservation is unlikely to make discussions at Lisbon any easier, to say<br>
nothing of the fact that Rodionov's switch to threats will hardly please the<br>
East Europeans, whose dialogue with Russia is already marred by<br>
reminiscences of the Soviet era.<br>
 Just recently analysts indulged in playing the well-known game of "try to<br>
find 10 distinctions," noting that "the Foreign Ministry's line," insofar as<br>
its public statements are concerned, is not identical to "the Defense<br>
Ministry's line" -- some credited the military with greater flexibility and<br>
readiness to adapt itself to inevitable changes -- or "the Security<br>
Council's line" -- Ivan Rybkin suggested that Russia join NATO's political<br>
organization.  Now these exercises have to be abandoned:  "The Foreign<br>
Ministry's line" has clearly gained the upper hand and no deviations from it<br>
can be discerned any longer -- "We are opposed to the expansion.  Period."<br>
It seems that Primakov's ministry will even have to retreat somewhat after<br>
going a bit too far:  Rodionov's zeal with regard to pursuing "the  line of<br>
the Foreign Ministry," with which he was tasked by presidential edict to<br>
"agree on all his foreign policy actions," smacks of the extremes that could<br>
damage relations with the already jittery East Europe.<br>
 Chernomyrdin came to Lisbon essentially with the same baggage Yeltsin<br>
arrived in Budapest with two years ago, namely with the proposal that the<br>
European security system be reformed so that the OSCE, not NATO, will become<br>
its foundation, being a more efficient structure responsible for the<br>
settlement of crises in hot spots.  Two years ago, in the runup to the<br>
Budapest summit Moscow cherished illusions that it could manage to win over<br>
France, which had put forward -- first and foremost in order to spite the<br>
United States -- "the Balladur plan," in whose essence Andrey Kozyrev, the<br>
then head of the Russian Foreign Ministry, discerned many attractive<br>
features.  No fresh Russian-French Entente came into being, however.  (At<br>
this point we can draw interesting parallels between Kozyrev's former<br>
overtures to the French and Chernomyrdin's spectacularly successful visit to<br>
Paris, the only difference being that this time nothing similar to the<br>
"Balladur plan" was even discussed.)  The halt of the war in Bosnia by force<br>
of NATO's weapons -- although with the active involvement of the OSCE and<br>
the European Union -- buried the hopes that the Western European Union's<br>
military organization can be an alternative to NATO'.  In this regard<br>
Moscow's attempts to call into question NATO's leading role in Europe are<br>
doomed to failure and misunderstanding at the summit.  Nonetheless Russia<br>
continues to stick to its guns.  In his yesterday's speech Chernomyrdin<br>
spoke in favor of giving the OSCE the role of coordinator of the efforts of<br>
all European and Euro-Atlantic organizations, although he made it clear that<br>
it is not a matter of giving it "command functions" -- the OSCE should<br>
become "a universal forum to exchange views on acute problems."  In<br>
Chernomyrdin's view, the OSCE should be "the main security organization in<br>
Europe because it can bring us all together."  It is not yet clear, however,<br>
what can bring Russia together with the other summit participants as far as<br>
its criticism of NATO is concerned.  Yet Moscow has not yet proposed<br>
anything constructive -- apart from variations of "no expansion will come to<br>
pass" -- with regard to its new relationship with NATO.<br>
 Only one Russian ally was discernible at the summit -- Alyaksandr<br>
Lukashenka -- but he himself will have a hard time, being exposed to<br>
criticism for his authoritarian manners.  On the eve of the summit the<br>
"troika" of last year's OSCE chairman (Hungary), current chairman<br>
(Switzerland), and future chairman (Denmark) deemed Belarus' recent<br>
referendum to have been illegitimate.  Things went so far that Portuguese<br>
President Jorge Sampayo avoided a purely ceremonial meeting with his<br>
Belarusian counterpart.  The action was agreed upon with the European Union<br>
countries.  In these conditions Moscow would have been wise to keep its<br>
Belarusian friend at arm's length so as not to aggravate its possible<br>
isolation (notably, those same East Europeans, Russia's most difficult<br>
partners, have taken a very harsh stance on the Belarusian question).<br>
Moscow has chosen a different tactic, however.  In particularly, Rybkin<br>
thought it necessary to emphasize:  "Belarus is a sovereign country.  It<br>
held a referendum, passed a constitution on its basis, and formed a<br>
bicameral parliament.  And Belarus has the right to do so."  As if Ivan<br>
Petrovich [Rybkin] were unaware of how the parliament was formed or of the<br>
fact that telling Europe that the area of human rights falls outside the<br>
European community's jurisdiction is very bad manners indeed.<br>
 Maybe, Moscow's harsh stance with regard to NATO is a method of wringing<br>
from its partners concessions on other matters?  For instance, while<br>
reiterating the thesis of a threat coming from NATO, Moscow might have in<br>
mind Western concessions with regard to revising the Paris Treaty on the CFE<br>
[Conventional Forces in Europe], signed in 1990, because it proceeded from a<br>
standoff between NATO and the Warsaw Pact.  Yesterday Chernomyrdin proposed<br>
that "the treaty be adjusted" by limiting the military potential of<br>
military-political alliances and obliging such alliances and individual<br>
countries to refrain from increasing their arsenals from the status as of 17<br>
November 1995.  But one might well suggest that Moscow's persistence in the<br>
question of NATO expansion could cause the West's counter persistence.  This<br>
will not render the talks on the treaty's revision, scheduled to take place<br>
in Vienna next year, any easier.<br>
 In Lisbon, complex discussions of such sensitive subjects as Chechnya and<br>
Karabakh are yet to be held.  According to the results of the discussion of<br>
Chechen problems a decision could be made for the OSCE to monitor Chechen<br>
elections, set for 27 January.  For all the innocuousness of this action, it<br>
promises yet more difficulties in store for Moscow:  If the authoritative<br>
OSCE sees no particular violations, this might give extra trumps to the<br>
newly-elected president of Ichkeria.  And that in a situation where a<br>
separatist is set to win the election!  What will then happen to the<br>
principle of territorial integrity?  Here both Moscow and the OSCE will find<br>
themselves trapped.  This has already happened with regard to<br>
Nagorno-Karabakh.  The Budapest summit decided to send peacekeeping forces<br>
there, but since then talks have stalled.  There will be no breakthrough<br>
this time around either:  Azerbaijan demands that its territorial integrity<br>
be officially confirmed, but all decisions at OSCE forums are made by<br>
consensus and Armenia is bound to veto such a resolution.  It is not yet<br>
clear how would Moscow vote in this case (on the one hand, it has its own<br>
Chechnya; on the other, Armenia lays claim to the role of its strategic ally<br>
in the region).  Nor is it clear how the Russian delegation can disentangle<br>
itself from another triangle of problems -- "Moscow-Tbilisi-Sukhumi."<br>
 The only thing that is known after the expert's all-nighter is that the<br>
summit's final declaration will apparently not mention NATO in its part<br>
proclaiming the European countries' free right to join military-political<br>
alliances.  Nor will it evidently mention Chechnya and Abkhazia.  But even<br>
if they manage to successfully negotiate all the points of friction in the<br>
document, they will not be completely straightened out for that, and the<br>
OSCE will not demonstrate the effectiveness for which Moscow is campaigning.<br>
The usually very reserved and ambiguous in phrasing Yevgeniy Primakov said<br>
yesterday that "difficult talks" were under way at the summit.  Simply<br>
speaking, Russia with its ideas might find itself on the verge of isolation,<br>
which could prompt Chernomyrdin to repeat the words Yeltsin uttered two<br>
years ago:  The Cold War is about to be replaced by a "Cold Peace."<br>
(end)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
