<title>Groong Network: Oil/Chechnya</title>
<h1>Oil/Chechnya</h1>
Arthur Martirosyan (<i>martiros@hulaw1.harvard.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 3 Dec 1996 12:15:38 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#8">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#8">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#8">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#8">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0009.html">Arthur Martirosyan: "Russian press on the OSCE Lisbon summit"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0007.html">Asbed Bedrossian: "!! IMPORTANT GROONG NOTE !!"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt;From Monitor 12/03/96</i><br>
<p>
<p>
CHECHNYA BATTLES OIL BOOTLEGGERS, LOOKS TO SHARE IN PIPELINE PROFITS. "About<br>
3,000 tons of oil are illegally extracted in Chechnya every day. The market<br>
price for our oil is about $80 per ton. So we're losing about $240,000 every<br>
day!" Khodzhakhmed Yarikhanov, president of the Chechen oil monopoly YUNKO,<br>
told the Monitor. Homemade gasoline is sold everywhere in Chechnya. It is<br>
surprisingly easy to make: crude oil is simply distilled in a homemade<br>
still. The quality of the resulting product is low, but serviceable, if a<br>
driver is not finicky about his car. All efforts by the Chechen government<br>
to ban illegal production and trading have so far failed. Yarikhanov says<br>
the authorities intend to redouble the battle against the "oil mafias" but<br>
acknowledges that establishing a state monopoly will not be easy. "Moscow<br>
has not yet handed over a kopeck of the promised compensation. There's no<br>
work in the republic and the underground oil business is the only way many<br>
Chechens can feed their families," he told Monitor.<br>
<p>
The government in Grozny also intends to organize a guard for the Chechen<br>
sector of the pipeline which is projected to transport Azerbaijani oil to<br>
western markets. "In this case, the interests of Russia and Chechnya<br>
coincide, since we too are interested in the 'northern variant' for<br>
transporting Azerbaijani oil," Yarikhanov says. The interim agreement signed<br>
by the Russian and Chechen prime ministers on November 23 called for the<br>
question of the joint transportation of oil to be resolved by December 1,<br>
but Russian government sources now say that agreement will not be reached<br>
before the middle of this month at the earliest. (Trud, November 28) Chechen<br>
leaders will negotiate for some one-seventh or one-eighth of the profits,<br>
arguing that this proportion of the pipeline passes through Chechen territory.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
