<title>Groong Network: ASBAREZ-ON-LINE [12-02-96]</title>
<h1>ASBAREZ-ON-LINE [12-02-96]</h1>
ASBAREZ-ON-LINE (<i>76635.2505@CompuServe.COM</i>)<br>
<i>02 Dec 96 19:51:50 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#5">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#5">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#5">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#5">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0006.html">Asbed Bedrossian: "AP/Reuters headlines to 12/02/96"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0004.html">nt@nt.arminco.com: "Noyan Tapan News (December 2)"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
ASBAREZ ON LINE <br>
12/02/1996<br>
<p>
<p>
1. KARABAKH CONFLICT TAKES CENTER STAGE AT OSCE SUMMIT<br>
2. NATIONAL ALLIANCE PRAISES EUROPARLIAMENT RESOLUTION<br>
3. KARABAKH FOREIGN MINISTRY RESPONDS TO RUSSIA<br>
4. LEBANESE CONSUL-GENERAL VISITS PRELATE<br>
5. CLINTON THANKS ARAM I<br>
6. "DRO" TRIAL ENTERS FINAL STAGE OF TESTIMONY<br>
7. VERDICT PREDETERMINED, SAYS "31" DEFENDANT<br>
8. NEW COMPUTER PROGRAM PROPOSED<br>
9. OSCE ENVOY ATTACKED<br>
10. RELATIVES OF DETAINEES CONTINUE HUNGER STRIKE<br>
11. HUMAN RIGHTS GROUP URGES OSCE TO SUSPEND BELARUS<br>
<p>
<p>
1. KARABAKH CONFLICT TAKES CENTER STAGE AT OSCE SUMMIT<br>
<p>
LISBON (Reuter)-Azeri President Gaidar Aliyev appealed Monday for <br>
a swift agreement on a peace settlement over Nagorno-Karabakh, but <br>
Armenia said the Azeri government was unable to guarantee the <br>
safety of the people in the region. <br>
	The dispute threatened to disrupt efforts to agree to a <br>
final document at the two-day summit of the Organization for <br>
Security and Cooperation in Europe.<br>
	Aliyev told more than 50 OSCE leaders that Armenia was <br>
intent on pursuing independence for Nagorno-Karabakh. <br>
	The president said his framework peace proposal called for <br>
recognition of Azerbaijans territorial integrity, an assurance of <br>
a high degree of autonomy for Nagorno-Karabakh and security <br>
guarantees for all the enclaves population.<br>
	"It is regrettable that the Republic of Armenia refuses to <br>
accept such a formula...It refuses to accept the territorial <br>
integrity of the Azeri republic," Aliyev told the summit. <br>
	"We cannot allow the creation on the territory of Azerbaijan <br>
of a second Armenian state," he said. "We do not want war. We want <br>
peace."<br>
	Azerbaijan wants its territorial integrity to be reaffirmed <br>
in the Lisbon summit final document, similar to a passage in a <br>
draft paper which expresses the OSCEs "utmost support for the <br>
sovereignty and territorial integrity" of Georgia.<br>
	But Armenia is opposed to any reference to Azerbaijans <br>
territorial integrity.<br>
	Levon Ter-Petrosyan said it was because of several "pogroms" <br>
of ethnic Armenians by Azerbaijan since 1988 that he believed only <br>
self-determination of Nagorno-Karabakh would ensure the safety of <br>
its people. <br>
	"Despite any and all assurances that may be given, <br>
Azerbaijan is unable to guarantee the security of the population <br>
of Nagorno-Karabakh," Ter-Petrosyan told the summit.<br>
	"That is why we consider that the only possible way to <br>
prevent further tragedy is to ensure the rights of the people of <br>
Nagorno-Karabakh to self-determination," he added.<br>
	But Ter-Petrosyan repeated a pledge to take part in talks to <br>
try to find a peaceful settlement and cooperate with the 11-nation <br>
Minsk Group, a mediation body set up by the OSCE. <br>
	A fragile cease-fire has existed since May 1994, but both <br>
sides have failed to agree to a peace settlement. Talks in <br>
Helsinki mediated by the Minsk Group broke down last month.<br>
	The OSCE summit in Budapest in 1994 agreed to prepare a <br>
multinational peacekeeping force for Nagorno-Karabakh, but <br>
deployment cannot go ahead until both sides agree to peace.<br>
	OSCE sources said the dispute could disrupt efforts to put <br>
together a final declaration at the Lisbon summit. Azerbaijan <br>
could hinder, or block, a final summit document if it fails to win <br>
affirmation of its territorial integrity.<br>
	Leaders from Europe and North America opened the European <br>
security summit Monday to map out a future blueprint for peace, <br>
but Russias concerns over NATO expansion threatened to dominate <br>
the meeting.<br>
	Heads of state and government from the 54-nation OSCE were <br>
expected to agree a final document that will lay out plans for <br>
European security in the 21st century, launch a new round of arms <br>
control talks and shore up peace in Bosnia.<br>
	"Peace demands trust among peoples," Portuguese Prime <br>
Minister Antonio Guterres told the opening session of the two-day <br>
summit. "We, political leaders, must be the builders of that <br>
trust."<br>
	Russian Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin, standing in for <br>
President Boris Yeltsin who is recovering from heart surgery, was <br>
due to speak early in the Monday session.<br>
	Russia has wasted no time in underscoring Moscows <br>
opposition to NATO plans to take in former members of the now-<br>
defunct Warsaw Pact.<br>
	Speaking on the eve of the summit, Chernomyrdin repeated the <br>
tough line adopted by Russian leaders last week against the <br>
Western alliances eastward expansion, which Moscow says would <br>
threaten Russias security.<br>
	"Russia is categorically against NATO expanding eastwards," <br>
he told reporters. "There is no need to rush. The fact that Europe <br>
is now without blocs is very important. We must work together. We <br>
must develop this, strengthen this." <br>
	Western diplomats say they would prefer the Lisbon summit, <br>
which brings together the United States and Canada with European <br>
states, to avoid the debate on NATO enlargement.<br>
	The last OSCE summit two years ago in Budapest was wrecked <br>
by a row over the same issue and by differences over Bosnia. <br>
	The leaders will also hold a series of bilateral meetings on <br>
the fringes of the summit-more than 170 in total. Chernomyrdin was <br>
scheduled to meet Vice President Al Gore, German Chancellor Helmut <br>
Kohl and French President Jacques Chirac.<br>
	Representatives from Algeria, Egypt, Morocco, Tunisia, Japan <br>
and South Korea are attending the summit as observers, as well as <br>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.<br>
	Russia has little chance of winning support at the summit <br>
for its proposals to give the OSCE a more powerful role in <br>
European security and act as a counterbalance to NATO.<br>
	But by taking a hard-line on NATO enlargement, Moscow may <br>
win concessions in talks on other issues at the summit, including <br>
adapting a 1990 treaty on conventional arms control. <br>
	The United States, represented by Gore who arrived Monday, <br>
and most NATO states have indicated they will accept new talks <br>
next year on adapting and modernizing the Conventional Forces in <br>
Europe treaty.<br>
	Despite concerns over a possible NATO row, some diplomats <br>
said they were more worried over hard-line positions being taken <br>
by Azerbaijan over Nagorno-Karabakh.<br>
<p>
<p>
2. NATIONAL ALLIANCE PRAISES EUROPARLIAMENT RESOLUTION<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-The national alliance caucus issued a <br>
statement Friday welcoming the European Parliaments Nov. 14 <br>
resolution on the presidential elections in Armenia adopted.<br>
	The statement said that new and fair National Assembly <br>
elections are necessary for the establishment of democracy and <br>
rule of law in Armenia.<br>
	Below is the text of the statement.<br>
	"Being committed to our aspiration for membership in the <br>
European Council, which is a support for the democracy and rule of <br>
law, we, as a united opposition, since 1995 have been struggling <br>
for the establishment of democratic order in Armenia. Our first <br>
joint initiative in this direction was related to the <br>
parliamentary elections in Armenia held on July 5, 1995.<br>
	Because of the pressure exerted by the authorities, the 1995 <br>
elections were not successful. International observers claim they <br>
were unfair. The National Assembly has become a state structure, <br>
which prepared grounds for the present unfair elections. The <br>
demand of the European Council to observe equal representation in <br>
electoral commissions was ignored in the Law on Presidential <br>
Elections. This led to the fact that the pro-government forces in <br>
all organizing and controlling electoral commissions retained more <br>
than 2/3 of votes and were able to rig the vote.<br>
	We express our deep satisfaction with the tough position of <br>
the European Parliament on the issue of human rights and we hope <br>
for further cooperation in the process of establishing a <br>
democratic power in Armenia."<br>
<p>
<p>
3. KARABAKH FOREIGN MINISTRY RESPONDS TO RUSSIA<br>
<p>
STEPANAKERT (Noyan Tapan)-The Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the <br>
Nagorno-Karabagh Republic issued a response Thursday to an earlier <br>
statement by the Russian Foreign Ministry regarding the November <br>
22 presidential elections.<br>
<p>
The following statement was read by a ministry spokesperson.<br>
<p>
	"The statement issued by the representative of the Ministry <br>
of Foreign Affairs of the Russian Federation on November 26, 1996, <br>
on the subject of the presidential elections in the Nagorno-<br>
Karabakh Republic has caused utter bewilderment in the Nagorno-<br>
Karabakh Republic. Their calling the elections an independent <br>
action is at the least strange because elections in the civilized <br>
world are not initiated from without, but are held by the <br>
authorities of the given state. As for the legitimacy of the <br>
elections, which is doubted in the statement, it is confirmed by <br>
the results of the free expression of the peoples will. This was <br>
also confirmed by international observers, representing a number <br>
of countries and international organizations, including a group of <br>
deputies of the State Duma of the Russian Federation.<br>
	It is not understandable how the elections of the President <br>
of the Nagorno-Karabakh Republic contradict the universally <br>
accepted human rights principles. It is well known that it is the <br>
free elections that are the most clear expression of civil <br>
freedoms and human rights. It is also known that the vast majority <br>
of the citizens of the Nagorno-Karabakh Republic now lives in the <br>
Nagorno-Karabakh Republic and participated in the elections.<br>
	The position of forcing a model of its future status to <br>
Nagorno-Karabakh is also surprising because the  status issue <br>
should be settled in the process of negotiations and during the <br>
Minsk Conference of the OSCE [Organization for Security and <br>
Cooperation in Europe], and not in the lobbies of the diplomatic <br>
organizations of third party countries.<br>
	It is puzzling how the authors of the statement see the <br>
continuation of mediating efforts, while ignoring the will of the <br>
whole nation. The Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Nagorno-<br>
Karabagh Republic hopes that another, more informed representative <br>
of the Russian Ministry of Foreign Affairs will clarify who is <br>
supposed to be the contact in the Nagorno-Karabakh Republic for <br>
the quick resolution of the Karabakh conflict. "<br>
<p>
<p>
4. LEBANESE CONSUL-GENERAL VISITS PRELATE<br>
<p>
LOS ANGELES-Lebanese Consul General Gibran Soufan met with Western <br>
Prelate Right Rev. Moushegh Mardirossian during a visit to the <br>
Prelacy Friday morning, reported the Prelacy.<br>
	Soufan thanked the Prelate and the Prelacy Executive Council <br>
for honoring his invitation and attending a special banquet <br>
organized by the Lebanese Consulate celebrating Lebanons <br>
independence.<br>
	During his pre-holiday visit to the Prelacy, Soufan <br>
personally invited the Prelate and the Prelacy Executive Council <br>
to take part in activities for the upcoming visit of Lebanese <br>
President Rafik al-Hariri to Los Angeles.<br>
	During the meeting the two leaders also discussed continuing <br>
and expanding cooperation both in Lebanon and the US.<br>
	At the conclusion of the meeting, Prelate Mardirossian <br>
thanked the Consul General and wished him success in all his <br>
endeavors.<br>
<p>
<p>
5. CLINTON THANKS ARAM I<br>
<p>
ANTELIAS, Lebanon-The US ambassador to Lebanon visited His <br>
Holiness Aram I, Catholicos of the Holy See of Cilicia Sunday and <br>
delivered a thank you letter from President Clinton who expressed <br>
his gratitude for His Holiness congratulatory note on  his <br>
election to a second-term.<br>
	In his letter Clinton also emphasized the importance of His <br>
Holiness friendship and cooperation to his presidency.<br>
<p>
<p>
6. "DRO" TRIAL ENTERS FINAL STAGE OF TESTIMONY<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-Armenak Mnjoyan, co-defendant in the so-<br>
called "Dro" case pointed to a different version of events leading <br>
to the murder of Ashot Nersessian and his wife Nouneh Maroukian.<br>
	Mnjoyan drew the courts attention to a number of unclear <br>
pieces of evidence. According to Mnjoyan, multiple injuries were <br>
revealed on the body of Nouneh Maroukian, suggesting that she had <br>
been raped.<br>
	The investigation had failed to reveal whether the semen <br>
sample matched that of Mnjoyan, Armenak Zakarian or Armenak <br>
Grigorian, who following the indictment reportedly took part in <br>
the murder of Nersessian.<br>
	He also noted that investigators had found fingerprints at <br>
Nersessians apartment, but had not been identified. Fingerprints <br>
of the defendants, however, were never found at the apartment, <br>
Mnjoyan said.<br>
	He linked the murder of Gagik Sahakian to Ashot Nersessian. <br>
He said that Sahakian, who was responsible for arm shipments to <br>
Karabakh, was connected with Nersessian. Nersessian carried out <br>
those transactions, Mnjoyan said.<br>
	According to documents submitted in the case, the so-called <br>
"Dro" group ordered the assassination of Sahakian. If Nersessians <br>
murder is excluded from the case, then the murder of Sahakian <br>
automatically falls out of the case as well, Mnjoyan said.<br>
	According to relatives of the defendants as well as <br>
attorneys attending the court session, Mnjoyans account was <br>
"absolutely new for them."<br>
	According to Nouneh Maroukians mother,  her daughters body <br>
was mutilated and even the bones were broken. The documents <br>
submitted in the case lack forensic expertise, she said.<br>
	Speaking on behalf of Arsen Ardzrouni, Armenak Zakarian and <br>
Armen Grigorian, all sentenced to death, Mnjoyan said that if the <br>
court assumes responsibility and convicts them without having <br>
evidence of their guilt, they will refuse and instead request the <br>
court to follow the orders of the president of Armenia, who <br>
demanded to "severely punish the culprits."<br>
<p>
<p>
7. VERDICT PREDETERMINED, SAYS "31" DEFENDANT<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-Armen Roustamian, one of the defendants in <br>
the "Trial of 31" said that he and his fellow defendants were <br>
presumed guilty before the trial even started.<br>
	"I have been forced to defend myself against the indictment <br>
because in Armenia there is a presumption of guilt instead of  the <br>
presumption of innocence. According to this principle, you remain <br>
guilty until you prove you are not," Roustamian said.<br>
	Pointing to statements by the Armenian Security Council-July <br>
30, 1995-and the National Security Ministry-August 4, 1995 <br>
Roustamian said, "These documents are no doubt a political order <br>
and pursue political goals. Their main goal is to stop the <br>
activity of the Armenian Revolutionary Federation and to eliminate <br>
that party in Armenia."<br>
	Roustamian said the investigators interpreted the <br>
defendants testimonies in their own way, leading to charges that <br>
each apartment was a place for secret meetings and each friendly <br>
talk was a preparation of a coup or recruitment.<br>
	The co-defendant in the prolonged trial said that the <br>
verdict was predetermined and had no hope for acquittal of even <br>
one of the defendants. He said that the statements of the Security <br>
Council and the  National Security Ministry, as well as the <br>
documents from the Yerevan regional department of the Ministry of <br>
Interior be attached to the case.<br>
	Roustamian said that during the preliminary investigation, <br>
the majority of the defendants were called to the court as <br>
witnesses unless they had been testifying in accordance with the <br>
investigators scheme. Investigators forced the witnesses to give <br>
self-incriminating testimonies so that later, when necessary, a <br>
witness could turn into a defendant, Roustamian said.<br>
	He denied that arms found at his apartment during the search <br>
belonged to him.<br>
	Roustamian also denied allegations by some investigators <br>
that he was involved in espionage abroad. He said that in May 1993 <br>
he was in France conducting scientific research.<br>
<p>
<p>
8. NEW COMPUTER PROGRAM PROPOSED<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-The National Academy of Sciences and the <br>
Engineering Academy of Armenia proposed a program Friday for the <br>
development of new technology for the creation of "sixth <br>
generation" computers.<br>
	The proposed program will be submitted to the Armenian <br>
government for consideration.<br>
	The president of the Armenian National Academy of Sciences, <br>
Fadey Sargssian said that the integration of the Republics <br>
scientific potential and appropriate financing were needed for <br>
that purpose.<br>
	If the program receives financial support, it would then be <br>
possible to assimilate such hi-tech productions in Armenia as <br>
computer assembly or computer manufacturing networks  such as <br>
"electronic nose" used to detect drugs.<br>
	All this will make it possible to create computers of the <br>
sixth generation which are mainly being used in defense and space <br>
industries.<br>
<p>
<p>
9. OSCE ENVOY ATTACKED<br>
<p>
STEPANAKERT (Noyan Tapan)-Tibor Lakatti, an envoy of the chairman <br>
of the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe, was <br>
attacked while in Azerbaijan monitoring the militarized zone <br>
between the Azeri and Karabakh forces near Agdam.<br>
	According to a Nagorno-Karabakh Foreign Ministry <br>
spokesperson, it was pure luck that the Hungarian Lakatti escaped <br>
unscathed.<br>
	Similar provocations by Azerbaijan occur quite often, the <br>
spokesperson said. "In the month of April, representatives of  the <br>
OSCE High Level Planning Group Mission were attacked in a <br>
neighboring front-line section, according to the same source.<br>
	From a distance of 300 meters, it would be impossible to <br>
distinguish peacemakers, who wear yellow berets from servicemen of <br>
the Karabakh Army, a Foreign Ministry statement said.<br>
<p>
<p>
10. RELATIVES OF DETAINEES CONTINUE HUNGER STRIKE<br>
<p>
YEREVAN (Noyan Tapan)-Relatives of those arrested following the <br>
Sept. 25 events in Yerevan continued their solidarity hunger <br>
strike in front of the Armenian Prosecutor-Generals Office.<br>
	The group was  joined by the sister of detainee Argishti <br>
Kivirian who demanded the release of her brother.<br>
	Kivirian started the hunger strike on Nov. 19 from his jail <br>
cell.<br>
	"I hope that justice will prevail and human rights will be <br>
observed in Armenia," Arminka Kivirian said.<br>
	According to National Democratic Union member Vladimir <br>
[Vova] Hakhverdian, the chief warden of the Noubarashen prison <br>
where Kivirian is being held violated the law by falsely reporting <br>
to the Prosecutors Office that Kivirian was not on a hunger <br>
strike because he was smoking. According to Hakhverdian, <br>
Kivirians health is deteriorating.<br>
<p>
<p>
11. HUMAN RIGHTS GROUP URGES OSCE TO SUSPEND BELARUS<br>
<p>
VIENNA (Reuter)-An international human rights group urged Europes <br>
top security body on Monday to suspend Belarus from membership <br>
following a controversial referendum last month that significantly <br>
increased the powers of its president.<br>
	"We take this step...based upon our analysis of recent <br>
political and human rights developments in the country," the <br>
Vienna-based Helsinki Federation for Human Rights said in a letter <br>
addressed to the Organization for Security and Cooperation in <br>
Europe chairman, Flavio Cotti. <br>
	"Belarus should...be suspended from membership in the OSCE <br>
pending its tangible re-commitment to democratic principles, human <br>
rights and the rule of law," said the letter, a copy of which was <br>
made available to Reuters.<br>
	Belarussian President Alexander Lukashenko has come under <br>
strong criticism from the West which has accused him of building <br>
dictatorial powers.<br>
	Cotti, chairing the OSCEs two-day summit now under way in <br>
Lisbon, rapped Lukashenko in his opening speech on Monday, telling <br>
him the growing crisis in his country should be resolved through <br>
dialogue and that he was "deeply concerned" by developments in <br>
Belarus.<br>
	Western leaders lined up on Monday to attack Belarus <br>
President Alexander Lukashenkos record on democracy at a European <br>
security summit, but he hit back by warning the rest of the world <br>
to mind its own business.<br>
	"It would be counterproductive to try to exert pressure on <br>
us or try to interfere in our internal affairs," Lukashenko <br>
bluntly told the Lisbon OSCE meeting.<br>
	Lukashenko, said by his foes to have dictatorial tendencies, <br>
attended the two-day meeting of more than 54 nations despite <br>
growing criticism that a referendum on November 24 which gave him <br>
sweeping powers was neither free nor fair.<br>
	Vice President Al Gore, British Prime Minister John Major <br>
and President John Bruton of Ireland, which holds the European <br>
Unions rotating presidency, also joined the attack. <br>
	"The European Union remains profoundly concerned at the <br>
constitutional referendum in Belarus and the resulting <br>
developments there," Bruton said.<br>
	"We call upon Belarus to respect its commitment to OSCE <br>
norms and democratic principles.<br>
	Leaders of Poland, Ukraine and Lithuania expressed concern <br>
after meeting in Lisbon on Sunday to discuss the situation in <br>
their neighboring state.<br>
	Completely unruffled, Lukashenko denied there was a <br>
political crisis in Belarus, accused the United States of double <br>
standards, blasted NATO plans to expand eastwards and told <br>
Washington, the OSCE and neighboring states not to meddle. <br>
	"The United States is, of course, a great power but this <br>
does not give it the right to interfere in the affairs of another <br>
state," Lukashenko told a news conference.<br>
	He said he was flattered by the attention of the leaders of <br>
Ukraine, Lithuania and Poland, but added sarcastically: "I think <br>
there are enough problems in their own countries to deal with."<br>
	Lukashenko said the much-criticized referendum had been <br>
completely legitimate and democratic, and defended his handling of <br>
a crisis in which his opponents in parliament had threatened to <br>
try to impeach him.<br>
	"The recent referendum held in Belarus was held in full <br>
compliance with the constitution and legislation of our country. <br>
Any attempt to represent the results as not legitimate are <br>
completely without foundation," Lukashenko said.<br>
	"I emphasize strongly that we do not have a political crisis <br>
and there is no hint of a division in our society, despite what <br>
our internal opposition would have you believe." <br>
	Belarus only remaining major ally is Russia, with which the <br>
economically struggling country of 10 million is seeking closer <br>
integration five years after the Soviet Unions collapse. <br>
	In remarks likely to add to the wrath of the rest of Europe, <br>
Lukashenko joined Russian Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin in <br>
condemning NATOs plans to take in other countries of eastern and <br>
central Europe.<br>
	"When the military machine comes closer to Russia, it will <br>
pass through Belarus on the way. Belarus will find itself on the <br>
border of two blocs," he told the news conference.<br>
<p>
