<title>Groong Network: FROM THE&lt;ATHENS NEWS&gt;GREEK NEWS PAPER IN ENGLISH</title>
<h1>FROM THE&lt;ATHENS NEWS&gt;GREEK NEWS PAPER IN ENGLISH</h1>
Armen Martirossyan (<i>martiros@scf-fs.usc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 2 Dec 96 12:32:31 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#3">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#3">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#3">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#3">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0004.html">nt@nt.arminco.com: "Noyan Tapan News (December 2)"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0002.html">KEVORK: "FROM THE&lt;ATHENS NEWS&gt;GREEK NEWS PAPER IN ENGLISH"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
        ASSOCIATION OF BANKING LAWYERS ESTABLISHED IN ARMENIA<br>
<p>
 YEREVAN, DECEMBER 2, ARMENPRESS.<br>
 The Central Bank of the Republic of Armenia and a group of commercial<br>
 banking lawyers established the "Association of Banking Lawyers of<br>
 Armenia." The founding meeting of the association took place in<br>
 Yerevan last Sunday.<br>
 The goal of the association will be to increase the professionalism<br>
 of banking lawyers in Armenia. It is planned to establish a center of<br>
 banking law studies. Another area of the association's activities<br>
 will be to introduce various banking problems in simple language to<br>
the<br>
 general public.<br>
<p>
        PRIME MINISTER ARMEN SARGISSIAN PROPOSED TO ORGANIZE ARMENIAN<br>
        AND EGYPTIAN CULTURAL FESTIVALS<br>
<p>
 YEREVAN, DECEMBER 2, ARMENPRESS.<br>
 On November 29, the Prime Minister of the Republic of Armenia Armen<br>
 Sargissian received the Charge d'Affaires of the Arab Republic of<br>
 Egypt in Armenia Ahmad Fuad Raslan. The Charge d'Affaires<br>
 congratulated the Prime Minister on his recent appointment.<br>
 The Prime Minister proposed to organize Armenian and Egyptian<br>
 cultural festivals in Egypt and Armenia respectively, which will<br>
 promote further development of Armenian-Egyptian relations.<br>
<p>
        UN ACTIVITIES IN 1997 IN ARMENIA<br>
<p>
 YEREVAN, DECEMBER 2, ARMENPRESS.<br>
 Since December 1992, the UN has allocated 15 million dollars to<br>
 Armenia. Most of this money is spent of contruction of residential<br>
 areas and improving the living conditions of refugees, elderly and<br>
 disabled people. This was announced by the UN official responsible<br>
 for refugee women and children issues Vivien Davalibi during a press<br>
 conference.<br>
 It was announed during that press conference that there are now 300<br>
 thousand refugees in Armenia, of which 150 thousand are in poverty.<br>
 65 percent of them are women. Many refugees still live in hostels,<br>
 basements, and trailers.<br>
 It was also announced that in 1997, the UN activities in Armenia will<br>
 concentrate on 5 main areas: defense of the rights of refugee women,<br>
 family, healthcare, education, and employment. The expenses for the<br>
 next year are not specified yet, but, according to preliminary data,<br>
 the UN will spend about 5 million dollars in 1997 in Armenia.<br>
<p>
        COMMUNISTS CELEBRATE THE 76TH ANNIVERSARY OF ESTABLISHING<br>
        SOVIET POWERS IN ARMENIA<br>
<p>
 YEREVAN, DECEMBER 2, ARMENPRESS.<br>
 On November 29, armenian communists celebrated the 76th anniversary<br>
 of establishing Soviet powers in Armenia. A session of the Central<br>
 Committee and the Yerevan City Committee of the Armenian Communist<br>
 Party took place in Yerevan on that occasion.<br>
 Presided the First Secretary of the Communist Party Sergey Badalian.<br>
 Special festivities on took place in Gyumri and Vanadzor as well.<br>
<p>
<p>
        NEW GOVERNMENT'S PROGRAM APPROVED BY THE NATIONAL ASSEMBLY<br>
<p>
 YEREVAN, DECEMBER 2, ARMENPRESS.<br>
 On November 29, the National Assembly of the Republic of Armenia<br>
 continued the discussion of the program of the new Government of the<br>
 Republic of Armenia.<br>
 The President of the National Assembly Babken Ararktsian informed the<br>
 deputies that none of the parliament's factions has submitted any<br>
 resolutions about a vote of no confidence to the new Government.<br>
 According to the Constitution of the Republic of Armenia, if no such<br>
 resolutions are submitted within 24 hours after the presentation of<br>
 the program, then the program is considered approved by the National<br>
 Assembly.<br>
 Thus, the National Assembly of the Republic of Armenia approved the<br>
 program of activities of the country's new Government.<br>
<p>
        PRIME MINISTER SARGISSIAN VISITS GYUMRI<br>
<p>
 YEREVAN, DECEMBER 2, ARMENPRESS.<br>
 On November 30, the Prime Minister of the Republic of Armenia visited<br>
 Gyumri (second largest city in Armenia, badly damaged in the 1988<br>
 earthquake).<br>
 The purpose of the visit was to get acquainted with the current<br>
 situation in the region and the process of reconstruction of the<br>
 earthquake region.<br>
 Following is an overview of the main problems of the region and the<br>
 reconstruction programs which have already been implemented.<br>
 The main issue in the region today is the construction of residential<br>
 space (apartment buildings) which is taking place slowly. It is<br>
 planned to build 3000 apartments in Mush district. However, according<br>
 to the builders, only 1000 apartments will be completed by the end of<br>
 this year. Today, more than 10 buildings are completed, they have<br>
 electricity supply and communications. However, only 140 families<br>
 live there. The district is far from the city and there are no<br>
 schools, kindergartens and roads. These buildings were built with the<br>
 money provided by the World Bank, and the communications - with the<br>
 means of the state budget. Not a penny was allocated to the<br>
 construction of other conveniences in the district. As a result,<br>
 people prefer to live in the city instead of in these otherwise<br>
 convenient apartments.<br>
 In general, none of the programs implemented in the region allows to<br>
 resolve fully any problem. The only units which were fully equipped<br>
 and completed in a short time were the units constructed by foreign<br>
 firms.<br>
 According to Sirekan Ohanian, Head of the Urban Planning and<br>
 Earthquake zone reconstruction of the Government of the Republic of<br>
 Armenia, all the resources invested in the reconstruction of the<br>
 earthquake zone have not had the expected results. According to him,<br>
 the reconstruction programs should focus on separate districts. It<br>
 has to do not only with the availability of economic resources, but<br>
 also with the regulation of the moral state of the people. It is<br>
 necessary to achieve a state when people don't have to live in close<br>
 neighborhood with rubble, the presence of which constantly reminds of<br>
 the horrible earthquake. Today, the reconstruction works are<br>
 financed by the Government of the Republic of Armenia, the World<br>
 Bank, the Eurobank, the Armenian Relief Fund, and the "Hayastan"<br>
 Fund. Some coordination between these organizations will not hurt.<br>
 There should be a single organization which should coordinate the<br>
 efforts of reconstruction, prioritize the tasks, and address other<br>
 similar issues. Otherwise, we will have the same situation where<br>
 different things are constructed in different parts of the city, and<br>
 as a result, not a single district is completed.<br>
 Mr. Ohanian informed that the Armenian government has developed a<br>
 list of programs related to the earthquake zone reconstruction.<br>
 First of all, a central committee and a working group will be<br>
 created. They will examine all the work performed in 1988-1996, and<br>
 based on the results of the examination, they will develop the list<br>
 of tasks for the future. A reconstruction program should be developed<br>
 which will allow to fully finish the reconstruction of the earthquake<br>
 zone by the year 2001.<br>
 The visit of the Prime Minister coinsided with the last day of<br>
 autumn. Some regions in Gyumri already have heating for this winter.<br>
 This year, more regions will receive heating than last year.<br>
 According to the Minister of Social Welfare of the Republic of<br>
 Armenia Ms. Hranush Hakobian, many people in the earthquake zone will<br>
 receive kerosene distributed by the "Paros" program. Cards for<br>
 250-300 kw of free electricity will also be distributed.<br>
<p>
        PRESIDENT OF THE NATIONAL ASSEMBLY BABKEN ARARKTSIAN VISITS<br>
        CHINA AND INDIA<br>
<p>
 YEREVAN, DECEMBER 2, ARMENPRESS.<br>
 On November 29, the President of the National Assembly of the<br>
 Republic of Armenia Babken Ararktsian left for China and India on the<br>
 invitations of the parliament leaders of those countries.<br>
 Mr. Ararktsian is planning to meet with high ranking government<br>
 officials of both countries and will deliever speeches in the<br>
 parliaments of China and India.<br>
<p>
        A CANADIAN NGO TO WORK IN ARMENIA<br>
<p>
 YEREVAN, DECEMBER 2, ARMENPRESS.<br>
 On November 29 a press conference was held in Yerevan to introduce<br>
 the activities of the Canadian Center of Experimental Organizations.<br>
 This non-governmental organization has been operating for more than<br>
 30 years in 70 countries around the world.<br>
 The activities of the organization in Armenia will focus on the<br>
 areas of reconstruction of the banking system, food processing,<br>
 packaging, storing and export, development of tourism, manufacturing<br>
 of building materials, energy, and machine-tool manufacturing.<br>
 Special attention will be paid to establishing joint ventures with<br>
 foreign companies.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
