<title>OMRI and Other Excerpts for Azerbaijan: Interfax Jan0597 Red Cross says POWs still held in Karabakh</title>
<h1>Interfax Jan0597 Red Cross says POWs still held in Karabakh</h1>
<i>ctroy@mail.sorosny.org</i><br>
<i>Wed, 08 Jan 97 16:42:13 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#67">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#67">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#67">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#67">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0068.html">eurasia@sorosny.org: "OMRI - 9JAN97 - ALIEV ON GEORGIA"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0066.html">eurasia@sorosny.org: "OMRI - 8JAN97 - RUSSO-AZERBAIJANI TALKS "USEFUL AND CONSTRUC"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
               RED CROSS SAYS POWs SEIZED IN KARABAKH STILL TO BE FREED<br>
     <br>
                    YEREVAN, Jan 5 (Interfax) - Many of the POWs and hostages<br>
               seized during  the armed conflict in Nagorno Karabakh have not<br>
               been  freed  yet  and  are  currently  kept  in  Karabakh  and<br>
               Azerbaijan, Zoran  Jovanovic, the  leader of the International<br>
               Red Cross delegation in Armenia, told Interfax Sunday.<br>
                    He said, however, that the sides had promised to free all<br>
               prisoners. In  1996, he  said, the  Armenian  and  Azerbaijani<br>
               sides freed a total of about 110 POWs.<br>
                    The International Committee of Red Cross Organizations in<br>
               1996 spent  $4.2 million  on  the  implementation  of  various<br>
               humanitarian programs  for Armenia,  he continued.  Next year,<br>
               the International  Red Cross  is to  increase the  sum to $5.5<br>
               million. He  said that  the  International  Red  Cross  should<br>
               continue its humanitarian activity in Nagorno Karabakh until a<br>
               political solution has been found.<br>
                    Ten foreign  and 70  local Red Cross staff currently work<br>
               in Armenia and Nagorno Karabakh. The Red Cross personnel is to<br>
               be increased  next year.  Proper conditions  have been created<br>
               for the  Red Cross staff and nothing threatens them in Armenia<br>
               and Nagorno Karabakh, said Jovanovic.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
