<title>OMRI and Other Excerpts for Azerbaijan: Interfax,12/09 For. Investing in Azerbaijan to rise in '97</title>
<h1>Interfax,12/09 For. Investing in Azerbaijan to rise in '97</h1>
<i>fsu@mail.sorosny.org</i><br>
<i>Fri, 13 Dec 96 13:45:06 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#55">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#55">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#55">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#55">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0056.html">fsu@mail.sorosny.org: "OMRI - 16DEC96 - AZERBAIJAN SIGNS ANOTHER OIL CONTRACT"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0054.html">fsu@mail.sorosny.org: "Interfax, 12/12 NAGORNO-KARABAKH MAY OPT OUT OF PEACE TALKS"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
                    FOREIGN INVESTMENT IN AZERBAIJAN COULD DOUBLE IN 1997<br>
     <br>
                    BAKU,  Dec  9  (Interfax-PIA)  -  Foreign  investment  in<br>
               Azerbaijan could nearly double next year compared with 1996 to<br>
               $872 million,  and command a 71.3% share of overall investment<br>
               in  the   country,  Oktai   Akhverdiyev,  deputy   Azerbaijani<br>
               economics minister, told a press conference in Baku Friday.<br>
                    Akhverdiyev said  $758 million  of  the  total  would  be<br>
               pumped into  oil projects:  the Azerbaijani  International Oil<br>
               Company, which is coordinating a project to develop the Azeri,<br>
               Chirag and  Gyuneshli offshore  oilfields, stands  to  receive<br>
               $723 million;  and other  projects to develop the Karabakh and<br>
               Shakh Deniz  oil fields should get $20 million and $15 million<br>
               respectively.<br>
                    Investment by  international financial  organizations  is<br>
               also anticipated.  The World Bank should open a credit line to<br>
               improve the  country's gas sector ($5 million), water supplies<br>
               ($5 million)  and land  melioration ($0.6  million); while the<br>
               European Bank  for Reconstruction  and Development  (EBRD)  is<br>
               expected to  set aside  $23.2 million for the construction and<br>
               reconstruction of hydroelectric power plants.<br>
                    Turkey's ExIm  Bank will  release $10  million of  a $250<br>
               million export  credit to build an air terminal at Baku's Bina<br>
               airport ($6  million) and to upgrade local telephone exchanges<br>
               ($4 million).  And the  Islamic Development Bank has agreed to<br>
               finance two  $2 million  projects, one  to build the Mil-Mugan<br>
               collector, and  the other  to reconstruct  the Samur  Apsheron<br>
               canal.<br>
                    Akhveriyev said  also that  Azerbaijan's export potential<br>
               was on  the up, despite a continuing foreign trade deficit. He<br>
               said total  foreign trade  next year  could be as high as $1.8<br>
               billion, compared  with $1.6  billion this  year.  The  figure<br>
               would include  $800 million  in exports  (compared  with  $675<br>
                million in 1996) and $1 billion in imports ($950 million).  <br>
                The main export  commodities, he  said, would  be oil       <br>
                products and cotton.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
