<title>OMRI and Other Excerpts for Azerbaijan: Interfax -- 24 November, Nagorno-Karabakh elections decried</title>
<h1>Interfax -- 24 November, Nagorno-Karabakh elections decried</h1>
<i>fsu@mail.sorosny.org</i><br>
<i>Tue, 26 Nov 96 18:34:19 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#46">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#46">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#46">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#46">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0047.html">arichter@sorosny.org: "OMRI 26Nov96 Rasi-Zade Confirmed as Azeri Prime Minister"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0045.html">eurasia@sorosny.org: "OMRI - 21Nov96 - Azerbaijani Foreign Minister on Nagorno-Kar"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
     BAKU SAYS KARABAKH ELECTION ATTEMPT TO "PRESSURE" AZERBAIJAN<br>
     <br>
     BAKU, Nov  24 (Interfax)  <br>
        - A senior Azerbaijani official<br>
     on Sunday called the current elections in Nagorno-Karabakh for the <br>
     post  of president  of the  enclave "a  new attempt to put pressure on <br>
     Azerbaijan."<br>
        "It  is  putting  pressure  on  Azerbaijan  and  not  the<br>
     legitimization of  the self-declared separatist regime that is the <br>
     main goal of the so-called election," State Counselor Vafa Guluzade <br>
     told  Interfax. "They  want to tell us directly: look who is able to <br>
     influence Karabakh."<br>
        He  quoted   U.S.  political  scientists  as  saying  the<br>
     separatist movements  in  Nagorno-Karabakh  and  in  Georgia's regions <br>
     of  Abkhazia and  South Ossetia  were "controlled from the same <br>
     center."<br>
        He said  raised tension in Karabakh served the purpose of<br>
     those who  are  seeking  "to  regain  their  foothold  in  the <br>
     region."<br>
        Meanwhile, Baku  residents and  refugees from Armenia and<br>
     Karabakh held rallies on Sunday in the Azerbaijani capital and its <br>
     suburbs,  condemning the election as an attempt to torpedo the current <br>
     truce between Azerbaijan and Armenia.<br>
        Each  rally  on  average  brought  together  about  5,000<br>
     people.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
