<title>OMRI and Other Excerpts for Azerbaijan: OMRI--28 August 96--AZERBAIJAN CREATES ANTI-NARCOTICS COMMIS</title>
<h1>OMRI--28 August 96--AZERBAIJAN CREATES ANTI-NARCOTICS COMMIS</h1>
<i>tlankina@sorosny.org</i><br>
<i>Wed, 28 Aug 96 12:10:44 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#5">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#5">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#5">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#5">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0006.html">eurasia@mail.sorosny.org: "OMRI--30 August 1996--CONFUSION OVER GERMAN STANCE"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0004.html">tlankina@sorosny.org: "OMRI--28 August 96--AZERBAIJAN'S FOREIGN MINISTER IN TEHRAN"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
     AZERBAIJAN CREATES ANTI-NARCOTICS COMMISSION. Deputy Prime Minister <br>
     Iziat Orudzhev has been named to head a state commission on fighting <br>
     drug abuse and trafficking, ITAR-TASS reported on 28 August. The <br>
     commission was established just before a conference was convened in <br>
     Baku, attended by senior UN International Drug Control Program (UNDCP) <br>
     officials, devoted to these same issues. Azerbaijani officials <br>
     participating in the 27 August conference pointed to skyrocketing <br>
     figures for drug-related crimes, the cultivation of narcotic plants, <br>
     and drug seizures in the country. President Heidar Aliev told the <br>
     conference that the fight against the spread of drug addiction is one <br>
     of the country's priorities; the UNDCP will reportedly provide Baku <br>
     with $500,000 to help in the fight. -- Lowell Bezanis<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0006.html">eurasia@mail.sorosny.org: "OMRI--30 August 1996--CONFUSION OVER GERMAN STANCE"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0004.html">tlankina@sorosny.org: "OMRI--28 August 96--AZERBAIJAN'S FOREIGN MINISTER IN TEHRAN"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
