<title>OMRI and Other Excerpts for Azerbaijan: OMRI--21 August 96--FBI IN TRANSCAUCASUS AND CENTRAL ASIA</title>
<h1>OMRI--21 August 96--FBI IN TRANSCAUCASUS AND CENTRAL ASIA</h1>
<i>tlankina@sorosny.org</i><br>
<i>Wed, 21 Aug 96 10:01:29 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#3">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#3">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#3">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#3">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0004.html">tlankina@sorosny.org: "OMRI--28 August 96--AZERBAIJAN'S FOREIGN MINISTER IN TEHRAN"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0002.html">tlankina@sorosny.org: "OMRI--15 August 96--AZERBAIJANI STATE OIL COMPANY REASSURES"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
     FBI IN TRANSCAUCASUS AND CENTRAL ASIA. The U.S. Federal Bureau of <br>
     Investigation plans to double it overseas offices from 23 to 46 over a <br>
     four-year period, AFP reported on 20 August. Among other countries, <br>
     the agency plans to establish a presence in Kazakhstan, Uzbekistan, <br>
     and Georgia in 1998. This is part of the FBI's effort to create a <br>
     "first line of defense" or early warning system to cope with what it <br>
     considers to be the growing internationalization of crime and crime <br>
     threats to the U.S. The report detailing these plans stressed that the <br>
     agency, whose mission has been confined to domestic law enforcement <br>
     and counter-intelligence, would not be engaged in espionage but would <br>
     liaise with its foreign counterparts. -- Lowell Bezanis<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0004.html">tlankina@sorosny.org: "OMRI--28 August 96--AZERBAIJAN'S FOREIGN MINISTER IN TEHRAN"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0002.html">tlankina@sorosny.org: "OMRI--15 August 96--AZERBAIJANI STATE OIL COMPANY REASSURES"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
