<title>Human Rights Center of Azerbaijan: Political persecutions in Azerbaijan</title>
<h1>Political persecutions in Azerbaijan</h1>
<i>agalietti@sorosny.org</i><br>
<i>Thu, 15 Aug 96 16:55:43 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#3">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#3">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#3">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#3">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0004.html">agalietti@sorosny.org: "General information about HRCA"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0002.html">agalietti@sorosny.org: "Deaths of political prisoners in Azerbaijan"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
     <br>
 <br>
  INFORMATION CENTER OF SOCIAL-DEMOCRATIC PARTY OF AZERBAIJAN   <br>
  Phone +994-12-933378, fax 986454, e-mail osdma@ipca.baku.az   <br>
         3-11, 28th May, Baku 370014, Azerbaijan / CIS          <br>
                     = December 6, 1995 =                       <br>
<br>
     <br>
        POLITICAL PERSECUTIONS IN POST-SOVIET AZERBAIJAN <br>
        ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~<br>
                     Background information<br>
                     ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~<br>
     Azerbaijan is   the   former  Soviet  republic,  biggest  in<br>
Transcaucasia with the  territory  of  86.6  hundreds  sq.km  and <br>
population of 7.5 million people.<br>
     Azerbaijan declared the independence first time  on  28  May<br>
1918,   and  second  time  in  August  1991.  It  was  recognized <br>
internationally following the demise of the Soviet Union  at  the <br>
end  of  December 1991.  The republic was admitted to the CSCE in <br>
January 1992, and to the United Nations on March 1992.<br>
     Under strong pressing  of  Russia,  the  republic  joint  in<br>
Autumn 1993  to the Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS).  It <br>
was the direct result of armed conflict  with  neighbour  Armenia <br>
for  the  territory of Nagorno-Karabakh in Azerbaijan.  In Spring <br>
1992 the   war   unsuccessful   for   Azerbaijan  spread  without <br>
Nagorno-Karabakh and to day more than 20%  of  the  territory  of <br>
Azerbaijan   (it   is   3   time   more  than  the  territory  of <br>
Nagorno-Karabakh  itself).  Now  in  Azerbaijan  are  about   200 <br>
thousands  refugees  from  Armenia  and Middle Asia and about 650 <br>
thousands of  internally  displaced  population.  Reportedly,  18 <br>
thousands were killed,  50 thousands were wounded and about 4.600 <br>
people missed in the operations.<br>
     Azerbaijan has a state-controlled economy rich in oil,  gas,<br>
and cotton.  It continues to deteriorate because of the war  over <br>
Nagorno-Karabakh.  In the result of economical crisis about 76.5% <br>
of population live under the level of poverty.  For the  present, <br>
the minimal monthly salary and social benefits are about $1.2 and <br>
average salary is $15.<br>
     The permanent  war  and  total poverty are the background of<br>
political life of the country.<br>
     <br>
                       Political situation<br>
                       ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~<br>
     Azerbaijan is  a  republic  with  a  presidential  form   of<br>
government. Excluding  the period of March 1992 - June 1993,  the <br>
Presidents were former Communist leaders.<br>
     Since 1988,  the country lives in the situation of permanent<br>
political struggles,  mainly  between  radical  nationalists  and <br>
(former) communists.   It  was  the  reason  for  the  states  of <br>
emergency which was declared 5 times,  and  4  successful  and  2 <br>
failed attempts of coup d'etat.<br>
     Heydar Aliyev,  a  former  First  Secretary  of  Azerbaijani<br>
Communist  Party,  assumed  presidential  powers  after  the 1993 <br>
overthrow of his predecessor,  Abulfaz Elchibey,  and was elected <br>
President in   October   1993.   The  supporters  of  overthrowed <br>
Presidents Ayaz Mutallibov and Abulfaz Elchibey are a  main  part <br>
of opposition movement.<br>
     On November  12'95,  in  Azerbaijan  was  elected  the   new<br>
Parliament, Milli Medjlis  (National  Assembly).  The  local  and <br>
international observers  informed  about  the rough violations on <br>
democratic norms and  electoral  procedures.  As  a  result,  the <br>
Presidental Party of "Yeni Azerbaycan" ("New Azerbaijan") got the <br>
majority in Milli Medjlis that guarrants the legislative  support <br>
of President.  Opposition has only 6 from 125 deputies, less than <br>
in the old Parliament.<br>
     The political  struggles  are  still  accompanied   by   the<br>
permanent human  rights abuses increasing since Azerbaijan became <br>
independent.<br>
     <br>
             Violation of human rights and freedoms <br>
             ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~<br>
     Both old (1978) and new (1995) Constitutions  of  Azerbaijan<br>
declare the  basic human rights and freedoms.  The State is party <br>
of International Covenant on Economic, Social and Cultural Rights <br>
(ICESCR) and International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights <br>
(ICCPR). On June 12-14'94 Azerbaijan presented to UN first report <br>
about  implementation  of ICCPR, which was met critically.<br>
     Peaceful demonstrations  and  meetings  are  suppressed   by<br>
the police.  The  National TV and print-houses are managed by the <br>
Presidental  Staff  that  facilitates  the  governmental   policy <br>
against opposition   mass   media.   The   strong  and  arbitrary <br>
censorship exists though the state of emergency was abolished.<br>
     The attacks against opposition were more active  before  the<br>
Parliamentary elections.  According  the new electorial law,  the <br>
public unions were deprived a right to propose their  members  as <br>
candidates. The Ministry of Justice abolished the registration of <br>
range of political  Parties.  The  Central  Electoral  Commission <br>
restricted to some other Parties the possibility of participation <br>
by various ways, including arrests of their activists.<br>
     The arrests on the political accusations indicate truly  the<br>
progress of  the  government in the human rights area.  After the <br>
change of  Azerbaijan  leadership  in  June  1993  the  political <br>
prisoners  of old regime were released and began the new waves of <br>
arrests.  Reportedly,  to day in Azerbaijan are from 873  to  894 <br>
prisoners  arrested by the cases related with political struggles <br>
and terrorist activity.  Among  them,  at  least  7  people  were <br>
reportedly arrested for the political crimes made in 1992,  70-84 <br>
people - in 1993, 270-282 - of 1994 and 510-513 people - in 1995.<br>
     Azerbaijan is not  joint  to  the  international  Convention<br>
against Tortures and Other Cruel, Inhuman, or Degrading Treatment <br>
or Punishment.  That liberates it from the necessity of reporting <br>
about the situation in this field.  The local human rights groups <br>
and International  Committee  of  the  Red  Cross (ICRC) does not <br>
monitor the conditions of political prisoners,  but supporters of <br>
the   opposition   inform   that   policemen  beat  the  arrested <br>
oppositioners.  The Ministry of Internal Affairs  built  in  1995 <br>
twelf new prisons,  but the detencion centers are now overcrowded <br>
in 2-3 times and have not adequate provision for medical care.<br>
     The opposition   concerns  specially  about  the  deaths  of<br>
political prisoners became more often in this year. On July 15'93 <br>
in  the  prison  died well-known oppositioner and field commander <br>
Yaqub Rzayev.  On May 15'94 died Natiq Qurbanov, the bodyguard of <br>
former  Minister of Defense Rahim Gaziyev,  now one of opposition <br>
leaders in exile.  On February 2'95,  during the trial  died  the <br>
arrested activist  of  Popular  Front  Novruz Novruzov.  On March <br>
29'95 died one of the leaders of PFA,  MP Shahsultan Jafarov, who <br>
had been  wounded  by  police  and  deprived the adequate medical <br>
care. On July 10'95, six weeks later his extradiction from Russia <br>
died also  one of the organizers of attempt of coup d'etat Nusret <br>
Budaqov. On November 19'95 died MP Seyfal  Babayev,  arrested  on <br>
the charge  of  organizing  the  political  killing of H.Aliyev's <br>
supporter. On  November   25'95   died   the   Vice-Chairman   of <br>
Social-democratic Party  Aypara  Aliyev arrested on the same case <br>
as N.Budaqov.  At least two unsuccessful attempts  of  poinsoning <br>
the political  prisoners  were  registered  by local human rights <br>
activists in 1994.<br>
     These cases are not investigated by the authorities, and the<br>
appeals and requests of Amnesty International, Human Rights Watch <br>
and other organizations are ignored.<br>
     <br>
             Suppression of Social-democratic Party <br>
             ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~<br>
     SDPA was  created  on  December 1989 as the reaction of some<br>
democratic orientated  members  of Popular Front of Azerbaijan on <br>
the pressure of anti-democratic tendency  in  this  organization; <br>
the establishment  of internal terror against non-radical members <br>
ruled PFA;  the  protest  against  the  forced  methods  in   the <br>
political struggle.<br>
     In June   27'90   it   was  the  first  non-communist  party<br>
registered officially  as  the  public  association.  Because  of <br>
strong opposition of Ministry of Justice,  SDPA was registered as <br>
political Party only on September 1'95 under pressing of requests <br>
of big powers' Ambassadors.<br>
     SDPA as   the   Party   stating   always   for   the   civic<br>
reconciliation, dialogue  and compromises is permanently attacked <br>
by the radicals of both sides.  There are mainly used such "soft" <br>
means as   censorship   of   Party's   newspaper   of  "Istiqlal" <br>
("Independence"), slander in the media,  or obstacles in election <br>
campaigns.  Well-known is the case of beating the Editor-in-Chief <br>
of "Istiqlal" Z.Alizade by the Minister of  Internal  Affairs  in <br>
1993, mentioned in the reports of big human rights organizations.<br>
     The Chairman of SDPA,  MP Araz  Alizade  objected  to  armed<br>
overthrowing  of  President  was  in 1992 in the short-term exile <br>
because of several attempts  for  his  life.  He  was  under  the <br>
investigation in  1991,  1993  and  1995 for the critics of three <br>
Presidents.<br>
     Less known are the cases of arrests of SDPA members. So, two<br>
activists   of   Party   were   detained  in  1990-1991  for  the <br>
anticommunist activities.   About   30   social-democrats    were <br>
short-termly arrested in late 1992 for the peaceful demonstration <br>
afront Parliament against nationalist tendention of  governmental <br>
policy. Vice-Chairwoman  of  SDPA,  a  winner of Olof Palme Prize <br>
Arzu Abdullayeva was arrested twice in  1992  and  1993  for  her <br>
activity for the peace dialogue in the front area.  Two activists <br>
were repeatedly  arrested  in  1993-1995  for  the  advocacy   of <br>
minority rights.<br>
     At last,   the  Vice-Chairman  of  SDPA  Aypara  Aliyev  was<br>
arrested in October 1994 for the treason of Mother-land, the main <br>
political accusation from the Soviet period.  Soon, the health of <br>
this man was worsened in the prison,  and it was a reason of some <br>
appeals of  Socialist  International  to  the  authorities of the <br>
country. Before the law-suit,  he fell into  the  coma  and  died <br>
on November  25'95 without adequate medical care.  His corpse was <br>
burried without  any  official  investigation.  So,   the   false <br>
accusations  against  famous  SDPA leader in Parliament and media <br>
were not refuted in the court.<br>
     In the  statement  of  SDPA  leadership  the death of Aypara<br>
Aliyev was called as the crime against Azerbaijani democracy  and <br>
social-democracy, particularly.<br>
     <br>
     <br>
     <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
