<title>Human Rights Center of Azerbaijan: Written Statement to the CIS Conf. on Migration</title>
<h1>Written Statement to the CIS Conf. on Migration</h1>
<i>agalietti@sorosny.org</i><br>
<i>Thu, 15 Aug 96 17:02:33 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#10">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#10">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#10">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#10">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0011.html">agalietti@sorosny.org: "Refugees and IDP in Azerbaijan"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0009.html">agalietti@sorosny.org: "Statistics on IDP"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
 <br>
              HUMAN RIGHTS CENTER OF AZERBAIJAN                 <br>
    150-9, Bashir Safaroglu Street, 370000 Baku, Azerbaijan     <br>
 Tel+994-12-947550, fax 942471, e-mail: eldar@hrcenter.baku.az  <br>
                      = May 30, 1996 =                          <br>
<br>
     <br>
                   Dear Ladies and Gentlemen,<br>
     <br>
     I represent  here a small non-governmental organization from<br>
Azerbaijan, the  Human  Rights  Center  of  Azerbaijan.  It   was <br>
established in  April  1993  and  deal with monitoring of general <br>
human rights situation, including the forced migration issues.<br>
     Azerbaijan  is  a  typical  post-Soviet  republic  with  the<br>
old economy structures and social conciousness. Disintegration of <br>
USSR and  enter to the world community was painful.  As a result, <br>
appear a  forced  migration,  when  the  citizens  of  Azerbaijan <br>
escaped   from   war,   economic  stagnation,  ethnical  tension, <br>
political repressions.<br>
     Of course, since 1988, a main problem in this sphere are the<br>
refugees and  internally  displaced  persons.  I  would  like  to <br>
attract  your attention to several points only.  The first one is <br>
an absense of comprehensive migration service.  Its functions are <br>
divided between  State Committee on Refugees and Forced Settlers, <br>
Ministry of  Labour  and  Social  Maintenance,  State  Statistics <br>
Committee, and so on.<br>
     As a result,  there is not an unified  policy  and  reliable<br>
registration of  displaced population.  To October 1995,  only 60 <br>
thousands people,  or 7% from total had a sertification of refuge <br>
or IDP [1]. There are several total figures, and no one is right. <br>
When in February 1996,  the Executive Power of Baku city finished <br>
the  registration  of  IDP,  there  was get a total number in 118 <br>
thousands instead of 200 thousands [2]. The revision of the State <br>
Committee for  Refugees  and  IDP  in March 1995 showd,  that the <br>
official number of refugees was more to 119,229 people  than  the <br>
real number [3].<br>
     Simple accounting shows that it permits an  embezzlement  of<br>
humanitarian aids in many millions dollars. It is a main cause of <br>
absense of Migration Service and registration even after 8  years <br>
of Karabakhi  war  and  2  years of cease-fire.  It is better for <br>
donor states to help in the  establishment  of  these  structures <br>
than lose regularly a big part of humanitarian aid.<br>
     There is also the forgotten problem of Meskhetians  deported<br>
from Georgia  in  1944.  After  the  ethnical disorders in Soviet <br>
Middle Asia in 1989 they became  also  the  refugees.  The  total <br>
number of Meskhetians is 260 to 280 thousands [4],  but they have <br>
not such international attention as, for example, Crimean Tatars. <br>
About 60 thousands Meskhetians live now in Azerbaijan near to the <br>
mother-land,  but only several hundreds were repatriated.  United <br>
nations could deal with this problem,  concerns many republics of <br>
CIS. I appreciate highly that the representative  of  Meskhetians <br>
was invited and supported by UNHCR.<br>
     Painful is also a problem of political migrants, both to and<br>
from country.  In  Azerbaijan  live  to day about 7,000 apatrids, <br>
mainly from Iran.  Since Azerbaijan became independent, they lost <br>
their privileges.  As  apatrids,  they  have not a possibility to <br>
work in the state structures.  They are not a refugees and do not <br>
get an humanitarian aid.  Parliament discussed the law "About the <br>
legal status of foreigners and apatrids",  where is  this  right, <br>
but there   was  passed  only  first  draft.  Many  of  political <br>
emigrants are apatrids and have not the appropriate documents for <br>
going abroad, only temporary residence permit.<br>
     Some emigrants complaint to our Center that are harrassed by<br>
Iranian agents,  and there is the confirmation.  For example, Ali <br>
Tavassoli, an Iranian national, was reportedly abducted from Baku <br>
on 27 September 1995 and taken to Iran. Some Iranian families are <br>
threatened by phone.  Accounting the recent events in the Iranian <br>
Azerbaijan, where   police  persecuted  and  executed  the  Azeri <br>
opposition, and the  practice  of  Iranian  secret  service,  the <br>
emigrants would  like to change the permanent address.  But their <br>
appeals to Azerbaijan authorities and especially to UNHCR  office <br>
are without  adequate response.  What evidences are necessary for <br>
UNHCR for to save the migrants' rights?  Killing or disappearance <br>
of family members? But it could be also explained as accident.<br>
     Other group of political migrants are  opposition  political<br>
figures who  left  Azerbaijan  because  of  real danger for their <br>
health and  lives.  Practically  all  of  them  prefer  to   live <br>
illegally or  half-legally  in neighboring states than appeal for <br>
an asylum. No wonder that they do not appeal, because it needs to <br>
make known their address. Secret services of CIS countries abduct <br>
the oppositioners, and it is well-known for the Russian colleagues.<br>
     The mutual  agreements about the legal assistance are in CIS<br>
a tool for the extradition of  political  emigrants  without  any <br>
fair procedures.   For  example,  ex-Minister  of  Defense  Rahim <br>
Qasiyev escaped from Azerbaijan and sentenced to  the  death  was <br>
extradited  from Russia on April 16 only because of this sentense <br>
passed in absentia [5].  Whole extradition procedure took 2  days <br>
only. Only  special  resolution  of  Russian  Duma saved from the <br>
immediate extradition a  former  President  of  Azerbaijan,  Ayaz <br>
Mutallibov  [6].  As  many human rights organizations considered, <br>
there are a violations of Convention Relating to  the  status  of <br>
refugees  (1951).  In  February,  former State Adviser and former <br>
member of Parliament,  Adil Hajiyev,  who is accused in the  high <br>
treason  and  can  be  sentenced  to death,  was arrested without <br>
preliminary permission of Parliament and extradited  in  10  days <br>
[7]. Group  of  Azeri  agents  attempted  two  weeks ago abduct a <br>
former member of Parliament Araz Alizade who is  accused  in  the <br>
insult of  President and escaped to Moscow.  Nusret Budaqov,  who <br>
had been extradited in May 1995,  died in Baku  prison  in  seven <br>
weeks, although he was healthy [8].<br>
     Totally, in  1995  were extradited to Azerbaijan at least 13<br>
people: 4 people from Russia,  4 from Ukraine, 5 from Georgia. In <br>
1996 were extradited at least 8 oppositioners:  7 from Russia and <br>
1 from Ukraine.<br>
     I am  glad  that the draft of Programme of Action provides a<br>
way for deciding the situations I described.  It is a  result  of <br>
big work  of  many  partners,  including  both  governmental  and <br>
non-governmental organizations.  I hope that the  Programme  will <br>
stregthen their further cooperation.<br>
     Thanks for your attention!<br>
     <br>
     Eldar E. Zeynalov,<br>
     Director<br>
     Human Rights Center of Azerbaijan<br>
     <br>
     <br>
Reference:<br>
~~~~~~~~~~<br>
1. "Azerbaycan", 13.03.96, "Ayna", 16.03.96 <br>
2. "Yeni Musavat", 23.02.96<br>
3. "Azerbaycan", 17.05.95<br>
4. Narushenie   prav   vynuzhdennykh   migrantov  i  etnicheskaya<br>
   diskriminatsiya v Krasnodarskom krae. Polozhenie meskhetinskikh <br>
   turok.- Moscow: "Memorial", 1996<br>
5. "Amnesty International", 15.04.96; Human Rights Watch/Helsinki,<br>
   17 and 18.04.96<br>
6. "Zerkalo", 20.04.96<br>
7. "Azadliq", "7 Gun", 24.02.96<br>
8. "Azerbaycan", 21.07.95<br>
     <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
