 <br>
              HUMAN RIGHTS CENTER OF AZERBAIJAN                 <br>
    150-9, Bashir Safaroglu Street, 370000 Baku, Azerbaijan     <br>
 Tel+994-12-947550, fax 987555, e-mail: eldar@hrcenter.baku.az  <br>
                      = March 01, 1996 =                        <br>
<br>
       Information for the participants of Network Meeting <br>
       Forced Migrations Projects, Open Society Institute<br>
                         March 5-6, 1996<br>
     <br>
     General situation of forced migration in Azerbaijan in 1995 <br>
     ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~ <br>
     The operations  in Nagorno-Karabakhi region did not restored<br>
since the cease-fire  agreement  of  May  12'94.  Simultaneously, <br>
there  were  not  the  certain  results  of  the  permanent peace <br>
negotiations in the framework of  OSCE  Minsk Group  and  shuttle <br>
visiting the region by the high diplomats of Russia.<br>
     Therefore, in Azerbaijan was  not  any  changes  in  neither<br>
number of  forcedly displaced people (FDP) nor situation of their <br>
repatriation.<br>
     There was  the  conference  on  problems  displaced  people,<br>
repatriants and migrants in Tbilisi on July 9-11'95. The heads of <br>
Armenian and  Azerbaijanian  delegations  had  signed  there  two <br>
protocols of intention about  the  information  exchange  on  the <br>
refugees and   harm   compensations,   but   it   had   not  real <br>
consequences.<br>
     In 1995  was  continued  the  Western  humanitarian  aid  to<br>
Azerbaijan in the total volume more than 100 Millions USD.<br>
     <br>
                     Changes of legislation<br>
                     ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~<br>
     In the   main,   the  national  legislation  on  the  forced<br>
migration and humanitarian aid had not been changed. However, the <br>
new Constitution   of  Azerbaijan  acting  since  December  27'95 <br>
content new significant items of political asylum right.<br>
     According to  the  Constitution of 1977,  the foreigners and<br>
apatrids have the asylum right,  if they are persecuted  for  the <br>
"protecting  of  workers  interests  and peace,  participating in <br>
revolutionary and  national  liberation  activities,  progressive <br>
social and political, scientist and other creative activity." The <br>
Constitution of 1995 gives the raight to the political asylum  to <br>
the foreigners  and  apatrids who "are being persecuted for their <br>
political believes and the actions, which are  not considered  as <br>
criminal in Azerbaijan Republic."<br>
     For the  privileges  to  FDP,  on  May 16'95 were passed the<br>
ammendments of 2 articles of Crime Code concerning the violations <br>
of passport regime. Now, FDP are not punished for that.<br>
     Some  new  laws  facilited  the  activity  the  humanitarian<br>
organizations in  the  country.  For  example,  in  January  1996 <br>
fifteen foreign humanitarian organizations were released from the <br>
registration tax   $2,000  for  opening  the  local  offices.  On <br>
February 8,  there was signed the protocol  about  special  legal <br>
status of IFRC in Azerbaijan.<br>
     In April 1995,  Milli Mejlis (National Assembly) refused  to<br>
pass the  agreement  "About Help to Refugees and Forced Settlers" <br>
signed by CIS leaders.  Reportedly, the reason was that according <br>
this agreement,  the  harm  compensations to internally displaced <br>
people from the territories occupied  by  Armenians  are  in  the <br>
responsibility of Azerbaijan itself.<br>
     <br>
                           Statistics<br>
                           ~~~~~~~~~~<br>
     State Committee for Statistics informed that to January 1'96<br>
in Azerbaijan were 918,622 FDP or 202,918  families.  Among  them <br>
are  233,682  people (49,149 families) are refugees,  and 684,980 <br>
people (153,763 families) are internally displaced persons. There <br>
are  330,000  displaced children:  144,500 are in the age under 5 <br>
years, and 185,500 are from 5 to 16 years old.<br>
     The number of employable people is 395,829,  and only 93,271<br>
are employed. There are also 90 thousands pensioners.<br>
     It is possible that total figures are inflated, as it was in<br>
the past  (the  previous  official  fugure of 1993-1994 and early <br>
1995 was 1.030.000 people).<br>
     For example,  in  May  1995  the revision of activity of the<br>
State Committe  on  the  Work  with  Refugees and Forced Settlers <br>
discovered that total figure of FDP only in the  main  places  of <br>
their compact living was inflated to 199,229 people. According to <br>
information  of  Baku  City   Administration   for   Population's <br>
Employement,  to  September  1'95 in Baku lived 192,560 FDP.  But <br>
latest information (February 1996) proved that in city are living <br>
only  118 thousands FDP,  because some people were simultaneously <br>
registered in two addresses.<br>
     The problem  of  official  registration  is not decided yet.<br>
According to State Committe on the Work with Refugees and  Forced <br>
Settlers,   during  last  5  years  24,971  refugees  and  35,785 <br>
internally  displaced  persons  got  the  certain  statuses.  The <br>
establishment  the  card file of FDP living in Baku needed half a <br>
year.<br>
     It is correctly when a head of local representation of  IFRC<br>
Torsten Wegner  stated  that  official statistics "is our biggest <br>
difficulties," because of "governmental data is  not  reliable... <br>
there are several figures."<br>
     To October  1995,  in  Azerbaijan  were   registered   3,962<br>
apatrids, including  1,897  political  emigrants and persons with <br>
the equal status.  Together their  families  members,  the  total <br>
fugure is  about  14 thousands people. Azerbaijan takes the first <br>
place in  former  USSR  on  the  number  of  political  emigrants <br>
(registered officially).<br>
     According to the result of opinion poll,  the monthly income<br>
of 38%  FDP was in 1995 from $1 to $2 for one person,  19% - from <br>
$2 to $4,  5%  - more than $4,  16%  - less than  $1.2  (official <br>
minimum), 21% couldnot say the amount of their income.<br>
     <br>
                   Placement and repatriation<br>
                   ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~<br>
     In 1995,  the significant part of FDP (about 50,000  people)<br>
lived in the tent camps.<br>
     There was continuing the building  of  standard  settlements<br>
from the  prefabricated  houses by EC in both front-line area and <br>
regions far from the front-line.  However,  the revision in March <br>
1995 showed that from 4,389 built flats 112 were given to persons <br>
who was not FDP.  According to preliminary information,  also 136 <br>
houses and 1,173 flats were given to the unidentified persons.<br>
     Sociologists consider that  only  7%  FDP  do  not  want  to<br>
return, 40%  FDP  want to return unconditionally,  12%  FDP would <br>
return if the state would warranty their security,  and 41% FDP - <br>
if the state would warranty their security and give the financial <br>
means for restoring their households.<br>
     For example,  after  the  establishment of the settlement in<br>
the unoccupied  part  of  Agdam  region  there  were  voluntarily <br>
repatriated some thousands of FDP.<br>
     State Committee  on  the  Work  with  Refugees  and   Forced<br>
Settlers informed   that   the   draft   version  of  Program  of <br>
Repatiation of Refugees and  Forced  Settlers  was  presented  to <br>
Ministers' Cabinet already.  However, it was neither published in <br>
the press nor discussed in the Parliament.<br>
     Although the  authorities  do  not  recognize the problem of<br>
Azerbaijan emigration from the Eastern  Georgia,  they  facilited <br>
the  repatriation  of persons who escaped from Georgia because of <br>
the rise in crime.  For example,  the executive power of Dmanissi <br>
region  had  decreed  in  1995  the abolishment the rewjection of <br>
passport registration of returning  people.  As  a  result,  tens <br>
families returned and was quickly registered again. The change of <br>
national policy in Georgia resulted in the election 4  Azeris  to <br>
the  Georgian  Parliament  (in  the  previous one was nobody from <br>
Azeris).<br>
     <br>
                        Humanitarian aid<br>
                        ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~<br>
     From January 23 to  29,  1995,  the  representatives  of  UN<br>
humanitarian organizations  visited Azerbaijan for collecting the <br>
documents on the needs of FDP.<br>
     Then, UN  decided to give Azerbaijan the UN humanitarian aid<br>
from April 1'95 to March 31'96 in the amount $34,536,620. It will <br>
be made through UN structure (UNHCR, UNESCO, WFP, etc.). Besides, <br>
without  the  framework  of  UN  programs  will   be   made   the <br>
humanitarian aid for $77,437,219.<br>
     The necessity of visit of UN officials was probably grounded<br>
by  the difference in the governmental data and information about <br>
the embezzlement of humanitarian aid that is  confirmend  by  the <br>
authorities, too.<br>
     For the struggle against these abuses,  President decreed on<br>
January  15'95  the establishment of Republican Commission on the <br>
International  Humanitarian  and  Technical  Aid  with  Chairman, <br>
Deputy Prime-Minister Izzet Rustamov.  The Commission established <br>
on April 26'93 was practically stopped its activity a  long  time <br>
before   this   decree,  and  control  for  the  distribution  of <br>
humanitarian aid was lost.<br>
     Totally, in  Azerbaijan  to  December  1'95  were  active 38<br>
international   humanitarian   organizations,   among   them   35 <br>
registered officially.<br>
     In the  contrary  to  the  official  statements  about   the<br>
governmental control  for  the  distribution of humanitarian aid, <br>
even the  few revisions  in  1995  resulted  scandaleously.<br>
     The revision  of the activity of State Committee on the Work<br>
with Refugees  and  Forced  Settlers  in  March  1995  discovered <br>
119,229  inflated  FDP,  embezzlements  of  tens tons foodstuffs, <br>
rough abuses in the distribution of housing and fees. In December <br>
1995  were  published the results of checking the activity of the <br>
Azerbaijan Society of Red Crescent (ASRC).  There were discovered <br>
the disappearance of about 440 ton foodstuffs,  using the form of <br>
humanitarian aid for the transport of  tens  tons  of  commercial <br>
stuffs,  big  difference  in  the  amounts of given food parcels, <br>
distribution of humanitarian aid to the died  or  false  persons. <br>
Finally, there was discovered the correspondence of ASRC with the <br>
Head of Executive Power of Baku city about permitting to sell the <br>
humanitarian  aid  in  the  Baku  markets (early,  a Deputy Prime <br>
Minister had denied this information).<br>
     Since January  1995  the railway and sea communications with<br>
Russia were aborted by it because of Chechenian war.  It had been <br>
violated   the  schedule  and  amounts  of  humanitarian  aid  to <br>
Azerbaijan, which was  transported  with   difficulties   through <br>
Georgia, Iran  and  Turkmenia.  The cargo transport was partially <br>
restored only in January 1996.<br>
     Beside that,  in  1995  the  donor countries were interested<br>
more for not Karabakhian, but Abkhazian and Chechenian conflicts. <br>
Other factor complexing the humanitarian situation was the acting <br>
ammendment #907 to the US Freedom Support Act,  which relates the <br>
direct  humanitarian and technical aids of USA to Azerbaijan with <br>
the deblockade of Armenia by Azerbaijan. It practically postpones <br>
these  aids  till  the  peace  agreement  between two conflicting <br>
states.  (This ammendment was softened a little on January 26'96, <br>
when   the   President   Clinton   signed  the  decree  about  US <br>
governmental humanitarian aid  to  Azerbaijan  if  the  President <br>
would  consider  that  aid providing through NGOs was not covered <br>
the refugees' needs. The decree will valid till September 30'96).<br>
     <br>
                 Activity of HRCA in the Network<br>
                 ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~<br>
     In 1995,  the experts of  HRCA  took part  in  the  regional<br>
meeting in   Tbilisi   and   international   meeting  in  Warsaw, <br>
concerning the preparation to the UN Conference on the  migration <br>
in CIS.<br>
     There were sent to OSI 54 newsletters on the  general  human<br>
rights situation in Azerbaijan,  including refugees,  minorities, <br>
peace-making, etc.  issues.  Also were made 4 special reports for <br>
the Forced Migration Projects.<br>
     <br>
     <br>
     Eldar Zeynalov,<br>
     <br>
     Director,<br>
     Human Rights Center of Azerbaijan<br>
     <br>
